"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Where Do We Stand?<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
</CENTER>
<P><HR><B>As Gov. Tom Ridge Approaches the Midpoint of His <BR>
Four-Year Term,Ridge's Commerce Secretary - Erie Native Thomas B. Hagen
- Reflects <BR>
on the Ridge Administration's Efforts to Improve Pennsylvania's Business
Climate<BR>
<BR>
An ER Extra<BR>
</B><HR><BR>
Al Monzo's Palace Inn in Monroeville seems like an unlikely place to keep
an appointment with Pennsylvania's Secretary of Commerce. But Tom Hagen,
in Pittsburgh to meet with a group promoting tourism, just wanted to find
a place to sit down and get to work.<BR>
 <BR>
In 1994, capitalizing on economic stagnation, low job growth and dismal
export activity, Gov. Tom Ridge wooed the business community. Long dissatisfied
with many elements of doing business in Pennsylvania, business supported
Ridge in his bid for the capitol. <BR>
<BR>
Once there, he appointed Thomas B. Hagen secretary of commerce to spearhead
this all-important area. Hagen, long Ridge's friend and political supporter,
also calls Erie home. Former chairman and CEO of Erie Insurance Group, Hagen
knows about doing business in Pennsylvania - he's been doing it for 40 years.
<BR>
<BR>
In this career incarnation, Hagen flies here and there, home and abroad,
promoting Pennsylvania's positives and strategizing against its negatives.
Lydia Strohl talked to Hagen about his strategy for economic growth.<BR>
<BR>
Executive Report: What are the strengths and weaknesses of the Pennsylvania
business climate?<BR>
Thomas Hagen: First of all, our workforce. The workforce in Pennsyl-vania
has great work ethic and high productivity. Our costs might be a little
high in comparison to some states, but the productivity more than makes
up for it. We also have a great strength in the quality of life in this
state.<BR>
<BR>
Our weaknesses from the business point of view have been two-fold. One is
the cost of doing business, through taxation and related costs like workers'
compensation. And the other has been attitude of state government. Namely,
the attitude and regulation in the old Department of Environmental Re-sources,
which was really extremely negative to creating a good business climate.
I think we've made some strides starting to turn that around.<BR>
 <BR>
ER: Statistics rank Pennsylvania quite low in a lot of business-related
growth areas, like new business formation, export potential, etc. Do you
think these figures are justified?<BR>
<BR>
TH: I think the figures are justified and they should be considered. But
we shouldn't make judgements totally on those figures without knowing some
things about the whole picture. <BR>
 For example, new business formation. We are not in a high-tech    area,
although we have a growing population of high-tech companies, particularly
here in the southwest and in the southeast. But it's not like California,
which has a lot of high-tech companies spinning off constantly. We're going
to be at a disadvantage comparing new business startups to a climate like
that.<BR>
While, yes, we've got weaknesses, we should be doing a better job of promoting
our strengths. Because if we're going to promote our weaknesses, then others
will pick up on that.  There's one [relocation consultant] I can think of
who doesn't even bother to mention Pennsylvania to his clients because he's
been so turned off by the attitude of Pennsylvania state government.<BR>
<BR>
ER: Are there any areas of business that you really think can drive growth
for the state?<BR>
<BR>
TH: We have a very diverse state, so it really depends on what part of the
state you're talking about. Here in the southwest we've had a lot of bio-tech
firms. We have the same in the southeast, particularly in the pharmaceutical
area. In the northwest we have the plastics capital, the powdered metals
industry in the north central part of the state. I'm not necessarily going
to promote one over the other. <BR>
<BR>
We're just taking a step in our current budget by eliminating the sales
tax on computer service companies, companies that do data processing. That
tax, put on several years ago, is really counterproductive if you want to
have that kind of operation grow in your state.<BR>
<BR>
ER: Does this diversity make your job easier or more difficult?<BR>
<BR>
TH: It makes it more interesting. Yesterday I was working on some things
involving the Philadelphia naval shipyard, and today I'm here working on
tourism. And a few days ago I was talking with the secretary of agriculture
about some things we're working on together - agriculture is our No. 1 industry.<BR>
 <BR>
ER: What's your strategy to capitalize on the strengths of our business
climate?<BR>
<BR>
TH: First of all, we have to do some things to make the business community
aware that we mean business about pumping that business climate. Last year
we started out by proposing a $286 million business tax reduction, the third-largest
business tax reduction in the United States in the last 10 years. We followed
up on that this year with another $60 million in business tax reduction.
In two years that's roughly $350 million - we're putting our action where
our mouths are. <BR>
<BR>
Now what I would hope for is that the leaders in the business community
and others in business would tell their friends - in trade meetings, on
the golf course or wherever - that Pennsylvania has a whole new attitude.<BR>
<BR>
To help us in that regard, the state appointed two new advertising agencies.
One, for travel and tourism promotion, is Poppe Tyson WCP, and that's here
in Pittsburgh. And on the economic development side, Ketchum. These are
two outstanding firms, creative firms, that we believe will be very helpful
to us in getting the word out to the world that Pennsylvania is a good place
to vacation in, Pennsylvania is a good place to work in, Pennsylvania is
a good place to do business in.<BR>
<BR>
ER: Do you think that Commerce got what it needs in the new budget to do
all this work?<BR>
<BR>
TH: The new budget is an extremely tight budget. It's the first time in
a quarter-century that a governor has proposed a budget less than the year
before. It's about $30 million less than the budget last year overall.<BR>
<BR>
In Commerce, our programs are at the same level as last year. We were still
able to rearrange so that we have some good new initiatives, but when it
comes to the total at the bottom of the sheet, we're equal with last year.
<BR>
<BR>
The reason for this very tight budget is a slow economy forecast over next
year and the prospect of about $600 million less in federal aid.<BR>
<BR>
ER: It's early, but are there any results from this new business climate
you say exists in the state?<BR>
<BR>
TH: It takes a little while for the word to filter out that Pennsylvania
is getting more competitive and wants to have new businesses here. I know
of one in my home county, Erie County, that came from Jamestown, N.Y., Bush
Industries. They said very candidly that if it were not for the attitude
of the Ridge administration toward creating a good business climate that
they would not have located that plant. It's eventually going to be 1,000
jobs. Using Pennsylvania wood products, the furniture that's going to be
made in this new state-of-the-art plant is mostly for the export market,
mostly cabinets and tables for computer equipment.<BR>
<BR>
ER: Obviously it's hard to concentrate on all the elements - geographically,
by industry - how will you prioritize?<BR>
<BR>
TH: It's not too hard to prioritize.  The business climate is created through
a reasonable and competitive tax structure, workers' comp structure, regulatory
structure. We've already started to work on that. <BR>
<BR>
At the same time, we've been working on strengthening our international
development. We have four offices now, in Brussels, Frankfurt, Toronto and
Tokyo, staffed by independent contractors, natives, they know the culture.
But we're looking at East Asia, South America, and increasing our presence
in Central and Eastern Europe.  Our goal is to increase export trade by
40 percent over the four years of this term, which will equate to about
100,000 new jobs. And we believe we're right on track with the increase
that we're seeing in trade.<BR>
<BR>
A tangential area is quality education. We need to have that if we're going
to compete in the world economy. The governor feels very strongly about
his voucher plan for education.<BR>
The other thing we are trying to do is have better coordination in government.
We came in and found that the information systems were not only archaic,
but chaotic. The Department of Administration has been undergoing an exhaustive
study of our information technology and how we can better utilize the technology
of today. We've been engaging in a conscious effort to help departments
and agencies to work together for a common goal. I was just here for a regional
meeting regarding tourism, we've had several throughout the state. It's
not just the Commerce Department, other elements of state government are
involved: the Pennsylvania Historic and Museum Commission, the Department
of Transportation with their welcome centers, the Turnpike Commission with
their rest stops along the turnpike, the Department of Conservation and
Natural Resources - all these agencies need to be involved so that we have
a total effort toward promoting. <BR>
<BR>
ER: How do you keep it lean when you're getting all these entities involved?<BR>
<BR>
TH: It's lean because we're keeping down our employment growth. Actually,
if you have better coordination, maybe you can do it with less people and
fewer costs in the long run and have a better result.<BR>
<BR>
ER: That's your business background talking  there. How hard will it be
to work smart in a governmental structure?<BR>
<BR>
TH: It comes in really handy. Quite frankly, this administration has been
able to attract really first-rate people. Our new director of the Office
of International Trade is a lawyer that has negotiated international contracts,
has spent 30 years in international business with several companies, the
last 12 years of his career as president of Hershey International. He has
lived all over the world, Japan, Berlin, Paris, speaks five languages -
to be able to attract someone with that kind of talent to government is
unusual.<BR>
<BR>
I won't say he's typical, but we've been able to attract people with equal
credentials in their respective areas. <BR>
<BR>
ER: How were you personally chosen for the position to which you were appointed?<BR>
<BR>
TH: I've been friends with Governor Ridge a long time, going back to the
days when he was a young practicing attorney in Erie. I was involved in
every one of his congressional races and was very active in his campaign.<BR>
<BR>
I also was at a point where after 40 years of business I was looking for
a last assignment, you might say. So when he asked me, this was a challenge
I was eager to take on.<BR>
<BR>
I think I can bring experience in the business world, a knowledge of the
political system, because I've been involved in one form or another of it
for a long time. Particularly, I'm aware of the international aspects of
things, because I have had that experience. <BR>
<BR>
ER: We've seen a reduction in the corporate net income tax - will there
be another?<BR>
<BR>
TH: We only have so much available to us - I mentioned the job creation
tax credit and the elimination of the so-called computer tax [in the current
budget]. And we felt we had to have some reduction in the capital stock
franchise tax, which is an archaic tax that this state has and has depended
on, one that I'd eventually like to eliminate all together. It's a question
of what's available and what the priorities are. We certainly hope to reduce
the CNI some more. It would be nice to get it to 8.5 percent if we can do
it, it's now 9.99 percent.<BR>
<BR>
ER: What's your reaction to allegations that the restructuring of the DER
and loosening of certain environmental regulations has actually been detrimental
to the health of the general public?<BR>
<BR>
TH: Secretary Seif would be better suited to answer this question but I'll
say this: It's a balancing act. <BR>
What we are trying to get away from are the punitive aspects of the previous
regulatory environment. We want to have strict regulatory standards and
if people violate those standards then they should be punished. But we don't
want to go out and, where people have an environmental problem, and admit
they have an environmental problem, hit them over the head with regulations
and fines and jail terms and those sorts of things. It's much better to
work with people that have environmental problems and help them solve them.
<BR>
<BR>
ER: What governmental priority is attending to the needs of small and mid-sized
businesses? <BR>
<BR>
TH: It's an extremely high priority. In fact, we have totally reorganized
our small business operation in our department, that had become pretty ineffective.
We have now an office of Entrepreneurial Assistance, that will be more proactive
with small businesses, with minority-owned businesses and women-owned businesses.<BR>
<BR>
As you know, we're working out the merger between the Department of Commerce
and the Department of Community Affairs. We think it will have a positive
impact.<BR>
<BR>
ER: How does Pennsylvania rank right now?<BR>
<BR>
TH: Pennsylvania is the fifth largest state, but ranks 11th in export trade.
So we think we can do a lot better. But it will take time to get that ranking
down closer to our population, because as we grow, other states are growing.
So we've got to grow at a greater rate to overtake them. <BR>
But it isn't as competitive overseas as it is domestically for location
of new plants or businesses. It is quite cut  throat right now, with all
of the states around us attracting businesses or retaining businesses in
the state. New Jersey, quite frankly, is out to eat our lunch. <BR>
