ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>We Need Everyone </FONT></B><BR>
<BR>
<I>By Rebecca Fenoglietto</I></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>A Majority of American Employers Aren't Covered by the Family
and Medical Leave Act; Some of These Smaller Employers Try to Mirror the
FMLA, While Others Can't Afford To</B><BR>
<HR>When Doris Dyen needed to have surgery last summer, her coworkers at
the Steel Industry Heritage Corp. picked up the slack. Dyen's position as
director of cultural conservation requires her to handle cultural planning
and programs and supply documents and archiving work. She had completed
most of her major work before the absence, but the small staff of four full-time
employees and three part-time staffers had to keep Dyen's projects going
during her recovery. <BR>
<BR>
The trick was to plan carefully for Dyen's six-week absence.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There's never a good time [to take an extended leave],&quot; says
Dyen. &quot;But if you know beforehand, you can plan it around big events.
As it happened, our major project wasn't completely finished, but there
was substantial work done. It wasn't a crisis.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Mainly, because Dyen and her employer worked together. For some smaller
employers, the situation might have turned into a crisis. Unlike larger
employers that are now bound by the relatively new Family and Medical Leave
Act, companies with less than 50 employees are not bound by FMLA and must
develop leave policies that serve the needs of both the company and the
employee. According to the U.S. Small Business Administration, 95 percent
of U.S. employers employ less than 50 people and are not bound by FMLA.<BR>
<BR>
So how do these employers handle leave requests? Oftentimes, smaller employers
don't develop a policy until a situation - such as the one Dyen was in -
presents itself.<BR>
<BR>
In Dyen's case, the smooth extended leave could be credited to good cooperation
between employer and employees, and to the fact that she's not easily replaceable.
But had she needed more time, there's no legal mandate that Dyen's job be
waiting for her when she was ready to return. <BR>
<BR>
The only employers required to preserve a job for someone like Dyen are
those that employ 50 or more employees, according to FMLA final regulations
promulgated by the U.S. Department of Labor a little over one year ago.
Covered employees must have been with the company for a year or have worked
1,250 hours in the previous 12 months. Covered employees can request leave
for birth or adoption of a child, or treatment of a serious health condition
or the serious health condition of an immediate family member. FMLA allows
an employee to take up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave for qualifying circumstances.
(See sidebar for the mechanics of FMLA.)<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Smaller Companies</B><BR>
<BR>
At the Steel Industry Heritage Corp., the formal, written leave policy gives
a certain amount of vacation time, sick days and personal days, which can
accrue and can be used for emergencies. Dyen used her three weeks of vacation
and most of her accrued sick days to cover her six-week absence without
having to take any unpaid leave. She was able to return when the time came.
 <BR>
Augie Carlino, executive director of the Steel Industry Heritage Corp.,
says his group's policy regarding paid leave, i.e., vacation, sick and personal
days, is set by the board of directors and depends on the employee's position.
If Dyen had required more time, says Carlino, the two of them would have
negotiated it. But that's an issue the group is presently reviewing. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;At the present time, we look at each situation on an independent basis,&quot;
says Carlino. &quot;We'd probably have continued to pay her even if she
had to be gone longer, but it would have to be reviewed by the board. We're
now looking at our total benefits package because we realize we need to
be more competitive in order to attract quality employees. We'd like to
enact some kind of short-term disability policy.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Like Steel Industry, Print Tech, a printing business that employs slightly
more than 30 employees in its four locations, also does not fall under the
FMLA. Print Tech employees are required to use their vacation and sick days
when faced with extended leave. Unlike Steel Heritage, however, Print Tech
does have a formal policy to deal with extended leave. President Bob Weingard
says Print Tech's policy allows employees to apply for a 30-day unpaid leave.
If more time is needed, employees need to reapply. However, he says, there
is no guarantee that the employee will come back to the same position, although
it's never happened so far.<BR>
<BR>
In developing this policy, Weingard looked to both human resource consultants
and legal experts. In effect for five years, he says &quot;there have been
no real problems.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
A 1994 survey of 300 small companies by the Kessler Exchange, a research
company in Northridge, Calif., showed that 60 percent of the companies with
fewer than 50 employes had leave policies in place. <BR>
<BR>
Those policies, however, in most cases do not mirror the FMLA guidelines,
says John Kirkwood, president of Kirkwood Consulting Associates, a human
resources consulting firm. Additionally, there are no other laws covering
an extended sick leave that give direction to smaller companies. Situations
like pregnancy, age and sex discrimination, and sexual harassment while
on the job are covered by other laws, but nothing mirrors some of the situations
covered by FMLA.<BR>
<BR>
Small companies, Kirkwood says, are aware of FMLA, but must respond to the
circumstances of their own businesses. &quot;Certainly, employees are better
off with the protection of family leave, but many smaller companies simply
can't afford to let their employees leave for extended periods of time,&quot;
he says.<BR>
<BR>
The resulting policies that are not as generous as FMLA are not based on
any mean-spiritedness, but rather are &quot;solely a function of what [the
employer] can afford to do.&quot; If forced to comply, small companies would
be faced with either having to find some way to temporarily replace an employee,
or find another way to get the job done, such as asking the remaining employees
to work overtime.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There'd be a loss of productivity, especially in smaller companies
where each employee is valuable,&quot; Kirkwood says. &quot;It's tough to
bring in a temporary employee and ask him or her to be      up to speed.
A larger company is in a better position because there are    more people
who can take over an absent employee's duties or move up temporarily.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
A study recently released by the Department of Labor stated that 85 percent
of employers surveyed indi-cated that the law had no noticeable effect on
productivity; 93 percent reported no change in profitability.  But  larger
companies bound by FMLA cite common complaints, among them:
<UL>
  <LI>	The burden of recruiting, selecting, placing and training temporary
workers to fill clerical and labor vacancies at a much lower rate of efficiency.
  <LI>	The fact that managerial employees can't be replaced by temporary
workers. 
  <LI>	Without citing statistics that support their position, employers
argue that temporary workers have more accidents, adding to workers' compensation
costs.
</UL>
<BR>
Print Tech's Weingard doubts that his company could comply with FMLA.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It would be a big problem,&quot; he admits. &quot;With four locations,
we have a minimum of staff at each, so even if one person calls in sick
for one day, it's a problem - we've lost 25 percent of our workers for that
day. If we're understaffed, we lose customers. We need everyone.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Weingard says that even a six-week absence would be difficult. &quot;We
can't use temporary placement agencies, because we have all skilled workers.
We can't hire a trained person for six weeks, and then ask them to leave.
We'd have to hire someone permanently and when our original worker came
back, hope we had work for him or fire the replacement.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, more regulation may be on the way, especially if Democrats
are able to regain control of Congress. Some fear currently mandated unpaid
leave may eventually turn into paid leave. Others expect smaller businesses
eventually will be bound by FMLA.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Many companies are writing polices that come into compliance with
the act in anticipation that they'll be required to do so in the future,&quot;
says Ronald Andrykovitch, an employment law attorney with Cohen &amp; Grigsby
in Pittsburgh. &quot;They think it's fair.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kirkwood, however, doubts that the majority of small companies could meet
FMLA, because of business necessities. Statistics support his theory.<BR>
<BR>
A study conducted by the      Small Business Administration in 1990 titled
Leave Policies in           Small Business, estimated the cost     of six
weeks of unpaid maternity     and infant care leave to be $612 million,
nationally, a year. The        amount for 12 weeks of leave, as  mandated
by he FMLA, would           be double.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;An employer can't always       find someone to fill in if a worker
      is gone for an extended period            of time,&quot; Kirkwood
says. &quot;They    might be required to if the employee is part of a union,
or if there's an employment contract, but if not,  they can only do so much.
Employers must be responsible to both    employee needs and the needs of
the business.&quot;<BR>
But for Steel Heritage's Carlino, meeting employees' needs makes      for
good business, be it granting extended leave for medical reasons,  or letting
employees work less         one day if they worked more the      day before.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Because we have so many late-night meetings and travel time that we
don't track, we have an unwritten policy that allows us to be flexible when
employees need extra time off. When you ask people to put in extra time,
you're taking away their private time with their families, and they should
be compensated for that.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You need to treat people with respect and dignity. You can't make
your employees feel that they're expendable commodities. If you treat them
like that, there's no incentive for them to go the extra mile.&quot;   
               <BR>
<H3>An Employer's Guide to  Family and Medical Leave Act</H3>
<BR>
The Family and Medical Leave Act was signed into law in 1993, and the final
regulations were released by the U.S. Department of Labor about one year
ago. It covers employers who hire at least 50 workers. Employees must have
worked for that company for at least 12 months, but not necessarily consecutively,
or at least for 1,250 hours during the last year. Employees may not be covered
if they work at a site with less than 50 employees within 75 miles. Further,
part-time employees are usually covered if they work approximately 20 hours
per week.<BR>
<BR>
Employees can take up to 12 weeks for several reasons: to care for a newborn
or adopted child; if the employee is suffering from a serious health condition
(mental or physical), or if an immediate family member (spouse, child or
parent) is suffering from such a serious health condition.<BR>
Under &quot;serious health condition&quot; are afflictions that could come
as a surprise to employers. For example, morning sickness, asthma and migraines
are all covered under FMLA. Abuses are more prevalent when employees take
intermittent leave for these kind of chronic illnesses (with the exception
of morning sickness, which does ultimately end). This happens, according
to attorney Ronald Andrykovitch of Pittsburgh's Cohen &amp; Grigsby, because
the law's definition of serious medical illness is very broad. Employees
don't need to be hospital inpatients. Rather, leave can be for chronic conditions
like those mentioned above. Additionally, an employee needs to provide only
the initial medical certification for chronic illnesses. He or she does
not have to provide certification every time a condition flares up, although
updates can be required. Because of this, says Andrykovitch, abuses are
difficult to police.<BR>
<BR>
If the 12 weeks are used and the condition still exists, as is often the
case in recurring illnesses, then employers may be required to provide more
leave under other laws such as the Americans with Disabilities Act. Alternately,
if the employee's situation is not covered under another law, or under a
union contract or company employment policy, the employer's legal obligation
could end.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Many employers think that the 12 weeks are a ceiling. It's not. It's
more of a floor,&quot; Andrykovitch says. &quot;Once the 12 weeks are up,
more time might be required. It's very complicated and unclear.&quot;<BR>
In fact, Andrykovitch says family leave is usually taken because of serious
illness - not the maternity leave that so many people associate with the
law. Rarely will a situation be limited solely to FMLA. Instead, there usually
is interaction with ADA, workers' compensation laws or unemployment laws.
Human resource professionals need to have an integrated approach to leave
policies because of this, he says.<BR>
<BR>
Generally, an employee's job is protected during this 12-week leave. The
exception, says Andrykovitch, is for highly compensated employees. <BR>
<BR>
According to Andrykovitch, paid leave such as vacation or sick days can't
be added on to FMLA leave, which is unpaid. Employees take either their
accrued paid leave or unpaid leave under FMLA.<BR>
The trick for employers, says Andrykovitch, is designating such leave as
FMLA. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;This law has a strange twist in that employees need not request that
their leave be designated as family leave. Lawmakers did not place the responsibilities
of knowing the act's intricacies on the employees, but rather on the employers.
As long as [the employees] give notice to the employer and it's for a FMLA-protected
reason, an employer can't terminate them.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Employers need to be aware that it's up to them to designate leave
as FMLA leave - including giving the employee notice -  so the employee's
'bank' of leave is used. Employers must be proactive when it comes to family
leave.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It's especially important to label FMLA leave as such if there's an attendance
problem, he says. FMLA is sometimes used as a defense by employees who feel
they were wrongly fired for discipline problems.                       
                              <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
