"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H4Editor.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Managed Care </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Patient Care Must Remain<BR>
the Industry's Top Priority</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR>The story goes something like this: Johnny wipes out on his bicycle.
He's stained in blood from head to toe. As Dad's rushing him to the emergency
room, Mom's punching buttons on the cellular phone, calling the HMO to obtain
the required approval for an emergency room visit.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Is he unconscious?&quot; the voice on the other end of the telephone
asks.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;No, but he's very bloody,&quot; retorts worried Mom.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Well, why don't you just bring him into the office tomorrow.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That's the wrong answer, at least from Mom's perspective.<BR>
<BR>
But like it or not, managed care and its cost-containment strategies are
upon us. At midyear, about three-quarters of the Pittsburgh area's commercially
insured population was enrolled in managed care, according to a study by
Towers Perrin, a benefits consulting firm, and the Pittsburgh Business Group
on Health, a group of 33 employers in the region.<BR>
<BR>
In Pittsburgh, not suprisingly, the most popular forms of managed care are
those affording consumers most leeway in their healthcare. Just how long
employers can continue to offer these products, which are more costly than
more restrictive ones, remains to be seen. We've been lucky so far: the
region's dominant health insurer, Blue Cross, has exercised the decision-making
power it retains in managed care responsibly, as have the smaller players.
<BR>
<BR>
Elsewhere, it's been a different story. Just ask Joyce Cerep of Scranton.
Her husband died on the bathroom floor of their home while a doctor serving
as an HMO gatekeeper refused to give permission to call an ambulance. The
Geisinger Health Plan and the Scranton doctor are the defendants in - you
guessed it - her lawsuit.<BR>
<BR>
About a year before his death, Jim Cerep suffered a seizure and was involved
in a minor car accident. An ambulance took him to Community Medical Center
in Scranton for tests. Because the hospital was not a Geisinger facility,
the HMO refused to pay nearly $2,800 in medical bills, according to the
lawsuit.<BR>
 <BR>
The Cerep's family physician - assigned to the Cereps by Geisinger - warned
the family to contact him in the event of any future seizures before seeking
medical care. <BR>
  <BR>
In May 1994, Joyce Cerep heard her husband collapse in the bathroom. She
called the primary care physician, who told her that the situation was not
an emergency. She called back three minutes later and pleaded for permission
to call an ambulance.<BR>
<BR>
The woman called again 14 minutes later, when she could no longer hear her
husband breathing. The doctor was unavailable, so Joyce Cerep finally called
the ambulance.<BR>
<BR>
Paramedics found her 33-year-old husband dead. He had suffocated. <BR>
   <BR>
Don't get me wrong. This column isn't a knock on managed care. This column
is about priorities. By early August, four of the country's largest HMOs
predicted disappointing second-quarter earnings, accelerating a deep plunge
in HMO stocks to levels not seen in almost a year. The situation could hurt
patients if HMOs cut expenses too deeply - just to restore their bottom
lines to please Wall Street.<BR>
    <BR>
I don't want a doctor or a hospital whose bottom-line concern is the bottom
line. I want a physician whose bottom-line concern is the patient's health.<BR>
<BR>
Managed care decision-makers must not lose sight of their primary goal:
providing the best healthcare possible for the patients who need it. That's
priority No. 1.<BR>
When healthcare decisions come down to dollars and cents, patients are in
trouble.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
