<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H3Publish.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.GuestEditorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> </CENTER>
<P><B><IMG SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Leaving Chautauqua</FONT SIZE> <FONT size=+1> </B>The Western
New York Educational Institution<BR>
Keeps its Incredible Wealth Within its Gates<B></FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher <BR clear=all></I></B><HR>The end
of the last century saw a period of social unrest not unlike that which
we see today. Turbulence, engendered by the Civil War and marked by a deep
chasm between North and South and black and white, gorged the nation's psyche.
Concurrently, the shift from an agrarian to an industrial economy made even
our bread and butter uncertain.<BR>
<BR>
Out of this turmoil, a peaceful place, reserved exclusively for quiet reflection
and dedicated to the dissemination of knowledge, emerged on the serene banks
of Lake Chautauqua, New York. Initially founded in 1874 as a summer school
for Sunday school teachers, its educational mission expanded rapidly. Today,
Chautauqua attracts over 15,000 individuals seeking knowledge to conquer
the challenges confronting mankind, in an environment providing refuge from
the harshness of the world.<BR>
<BR>
An easy three-hour drive from downtown Pittsburgh, Chautauqua is a citadel
of culture, education and religion. From the moment one enters the  gates,
which limit access to the 1 1/2- square-mile grounds, one senses this place
is markedly different. People genuinely respect each other here. Aside from
the somewhat onerous gate fees, the price of entry is the willingness to
shelve behavior patterns mandated by today's uncivil society. In their place,
Chautauquans adopt a behavior code founded in politeness.<BR>
<BR>
In some ways, Chautauqua is a microcosm of Pittsburgh. The over-65 crowd
clearly dominates. Cultural activities are the foundation upon which the
community is built. And Chautauqua, like Pittsburgh, holds a vise-like grip
on its past. <BR>
  <BR>
Pittsburgh could learn from Chautauqua. As we move from an industrial to
an information-based economy, the Chautauqua concept is especially valuable.
<BR>
<BR>
But the distinguished lecturers who feed Chautauquans a steady diet of provocative
insights into the world's most enigmatic dilemmas go largely untapped, their
ideas evaporating when the next lecture begins. In 1881, Chautauqua spawned
the nation's first correspondence program, spreading education to the common
man, even beyond its geographic boundaries. Now the birthplace of distance
learning needs to extend itself once again. Pittsburghers who flock to Chau-tauqua
in droves fail to harness the energy and seize its powerful ideas. Chautauqua
itself needs to examine the reality of the world in which we live, and let
its lofty ideals out of its gates. Chautauqua should be a departure point,
not a destination. Ideas should not go there to die.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
