<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H5Guest.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Repeat Offenders</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Employers Beset by Repeated Workplace Accidents <BR>
Should Take a Long Look at</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1> Themselves</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Bill D. Hager</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P>While there are no formal statistics on accident repeaters in the workplace,
many companies report that a small percentage of employees account for a
large percentage of lost-time injuries.<BR>
<BR>
One safety director believes that 30 percent of accidents at his company
are caused by 3 percent of the workers. For many organizations, dismissing
repeaters runs them afoul of union contracts, provisions of the Americans
With Disabilities Act or leaves them ripe for an expensive wrongful termination
or discrimination lawsuit.<BR>
<BR>
What then to do? First, we need to confront a misconception. Both studies
and experience show that accident repeaters are much more than disturbed
employees and, in fact, are not always the same people. Rather, while some
workers have a chain of accidents for a period of time, they seem to end
the pattern, only to be replaced by yet new repeaters.<BR>
<BR>
True, there are some employees who take advantage of the workers' compensation
system, looking for a way out. But on closer examination, some companies
have been surprised to find that these escapists are only a small percentage
of the repeater problem. The bulk of repeaters, it turns out, don't want
to get hurt, feel embarrassed by their injury history and would like nothing
better than to regain control.<BR>
<BR>
If we correctly assume that attitude affects safety, it is critical not
to label people as &quot;accident repeaters.&quot; This term coldly implies
that all fault lies with the worker.<BR>
To break the habit of accident repeaters, we first need to distinguish between
four sources of accident      repetition:
<UL>
  <LI>Exposure: Acknowledge that some people work at tasks that have relatively
high risks. This includes anyone who does heavy manual materials handling,
drives a truck or works outdoors in extreme environments.
  <LI>Cumulative: Realize that some employees experience wear-down from
cumulative trauma. Often physical job stresses lead to progressive illnesses,
each of which may be reported as separate incidents. But they may really
have one problem that never healed.
  <LI>Reinjury: Recognize that after an injury, sometimes a weak spot is
created, leading to future problems in that same area.
  <LI>Referred injury: Know that injury in one part of the body can lead
to problems in another area. For example, a foot problem can affect how
people walk, which in turn can lead to potential knee pain.
</UL>
<BR>
These sources can affect even previously strong workers. They may      
 be too proud or think of themselves     as too tough to report minor pains,
until these build into major, ongoing problems. <BR>
While it's easy to fault people for their own injuries, in every example
mentioned here, unrealistic management expectations or poor safety communication
may be hidden contributing factors in accident repetition.<BR>
<BR>
The bottom line is that &quot;frequent flyers&quot; - as one manufacturer
labels repeaters - can be reset onto the safety track. But companies need
to act strategically to help break the chain of multiple incidents.<BR>
First, they need to determine which contributing factors propelled the accident
series. Interview those who have had repeat incidents             and solicit
their expertise. Talk to supervisors, managers and line workers, and seek
their opinions on causes and solutions.<BR>
<BR>
Next, a strong safety training program is most likely to help end a chain
of repeat accidents. What should this training include? For starters, practical
methods of attitude control, balanced body mechanics and stress management,
as well as a strategic understanding of the multiple contributing factors
in accidents.<BR>
<BR>
Then develop positive accident investigations that are prevention - not
blame-oriented. Supervisors can be trained to see early warning signs and
to better listen to safety concerns.<BR>
<BR>
And keep it alive. Safety intervention has to be more than a one-time  event.
                                                   <BR>
<I>Bill D. Hager is president of  the National Council on Compensation Insurance
Inc., the nation's largest information company serving the voluntary and
involuntary workers compensation and healthcare marketplaces. The corporation
provides database products, software, publications and consultation services
to state funds, self-insureds, independent bureaus, agents, regulatory authorities,
legislatures, consultant and more than 700 insurance companies.</I><BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
&copy; Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
