<DOCNO>WT10-B34-6</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA061-000343-B038-339</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0996.Chronicles.html 192.204.56.67 19970115120905 text/html 7751
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 12:14:16 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:50:34 GMT
Content-length: 7575
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.GuestEditorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>
<H4>A Bright Idea</H4>
Look up. How's the lighting situation in your office? Odds are you've never
considered how much it costs to bathe your desk in orangey-pink fluorescent
glow, let alone whether it could be done better or cheaper. How would you
like the federal or state government to step in and tell you how to improve
your efficiency - or else?<BR>
<BR>
Commercial (and residential) lighting systems have grown vastly more efficient
and affordable over the last couple of years, so much so that proponents
say businesses upgrading antiquated systems can save 30 percent and up on
their overall energy bills. New bulbs and electronic ballasts are cooler
as well as more energy-efficient, creating savings on air-conditioning bills
in the bargain.<BR>
<BR>
Naturally, lighting manufacturers and distributors are high on the new products.
Large corporations can spend tens of thousands of dollars installing systems
which, they say, will pay for themselves inside of three years and provide
savings eternally after. <BR>
<BR>
But there's shedding light on an idea, and there's overexposing it. One
lighting company, Northern Light &amp; Supply Co., went so far as to pose
this question: Should either Pennsylvania's Public Utility Commission or
the state legislature mandate installation of highly energy-efficient systems?<BR>
<BR>
The EPA has already addressed the issue with its five-year-old Green Lights
program (mentioned in last month's story on Green Design). The goal is to
get businesses to voluntarily pledge to revamp their lighting systems while
providing technical information <BR>
and contacts. It's gotten results.<BR>
<BR>
Nationally, the EPA estimates a savings on electric bills of $200 million
for participating businesses, with an average internal rate of return of
30 percent per business. That also comes to an air pollution reduction of
3.5 billion pounds per year - less electricity production means less combustion.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;As a voluntary program, Green Lights has worked well,&quot; says Carol
Febbo of EPA's Green Lights program, Region III. &quot;In our region, as
of March, we'd signed on 426 partners of all kinds, large and small, public
and      private. They've committed to upgrading 880 million square feet
over the next five years.&quot; Nationally, she says, the total square footage
is equivalent to  one out of every 14 buildings around the country.<BR>
<BR>
She does add to the EPA's wish list some kind of partnership with the Pennsylvania
Public Utility Commis-sion and utilities - so far this program has gone
on without them - but adds that no one has thought about mandating business
participation in conservation programs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Things go smoother when we tell them that it's a voluntary program,&quot;
she says. &quot;People open up.&quot; And Green Lights is only one of a
slate of volunteer conservation programs. Next on the list for the region
will be the EnergyStar building program - helping businesses design and
redesign for HVAC savings.<BR>
<BR>
Jay Latterman, president of Northern Light, says even more incentives for
conservation are possible. Many businesses across the country receive credits
and rebates from power companies to convert their lighting. He suggests
that the western Pennsylvania area take an aggressive look at forming an
energy-saving policy.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There's nothing really that says, 'People, go look at it,' &quot;
he says. &quot;The utilities aren't pushing it, because they're trying to
sell electricity.&quot; He points out that energy costs in Allegheny County
are very high,  10 1/2 cents per kilowatt as opposed to around 8 cents outside
of Duquesne Light territory. Latterman believes that some sort of state-sponsored
forum for education for small business and residential consumers is in order.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When this country is trimming back, this is a plus-plus way to cut
costs that won't hurt anybody,&quot; says Latterman. &quot;What I am suggesting
is that we take a look at the policy we presently have - which is no policy
-and look aggressively into getting one. It requires that we look at the
energy efficiency overall of products being sold here and that we try to
improve them. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I don't want to get on the Green bandwagon too dramatically. But we
waste a hell of a lot of electricity unnecessarily. There's no one out there
at this point that's saying we should look at ourselves.&quot;<BR>
		                  
<H4>A Wild Ride</H4>
The Pittsburgh Zoo has had one wild and woolly summer. Flocks of visitors
shattered all previous attendance records in July, with over 145,000 snaking
through the gates. The previous record was around 124,000. On July 5, the
zoo topped its one-day attendance record (9,066, set in July 1995) as 9,081
people came to &quot;do the zoo.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're getting around 4,000 visitors most weekdays, as opposed to 1,000
or 2,000 a couple of years ago,&quot; says Public Relations and Marketing
Director Saul Markowitz. &quot;They don't just wait for special events or
sunny days.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Pittsburghers are becoming aware that the zoo is a wonderful family
day,&quot; says Assistant Marketing Director Kitty Julian. &quot;The Kids
Kingdom has brought people back to the zoo and helped regain everyone's
trust that it's a great place.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The education program is also attracting herds of kids, with 2,000 attending
Zoo Camp, well over the 1,400 of last year. <BR>
<BR>
This fall promises a whole slate of &quot;emu-sements&quot; - ZooBoo, a
Halloween celebration including a parade and haunted house, and     free
kids' month through all of November. New animals like a baby mandrill born
in May and the expected arrival of rare black rhinos in the late summer
or early fall add  to the zoo's attractions.                       <HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
