<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Ann Devlin</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Directory Inassistance</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Fed Up With Phone Menus?<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>OK, I am going to keep this very simple. When I make a phone call,
I want a human being to answer. And I want that human being to be in Pittsburgh.
<BR>
<BR>
Yes, I have exited from my e-mail and let my calls go to my voice mail,
just to share this radical definition of customer service with you. I'll
offer in     my defense that I am an entrepreneur in the middle of a small,
high-tech start-up. Now, corporate Pittsburgh, what's your excuse?<BR>
<BR>
I write that good-naturedly ... but make no mistake, like many of your other
customers, I am at my limit. All together now, let's take a field trip back
in time and find out how we got here.<BR>
<BR>
It all started innocently enough, with that sadistic little exercise we
can almost now recall with affection. You remember - the runaround. <BR>
<BR>
That was when businesses allowed human beings to make things difficult.
We called with a question, concern or complaint, and a customer service
  representative who'd heard it all before assumed the posture of corporate
   protector. <BR>
<BR>
If evasive action was necessary, we were transferred ... and transferred
... and transferred. No problem in getting someone to pick up the phone,
but we seldom got what we needed. <BR>
<BR>
By the time that suspicion was confirmed, we had already been transferred
into oblivion  or disconnected. Oh, we always had a fall-back position.
We could call back. Or we could call KDKA's Wayne Van Dine.<BR>
<BR>
Then, slowly, we started hearing what we thought just might be our big chance
for some high-tech revenge. Every now and then, we might get a machine on
the other end of the line. Automated phone answering systems were novel,
efficient and, yes, just a little bit of fun. <BR>
<BR>
Our fingers could control our fate. If we pressed the buttons in an orderly
and fast enough fashion, we could eliminate human incompetence and get exactly
what we wanted. <BR>
<BR>
Finally getting a human on the phone was like winning the grand prize.<BR>
<BR>
This was sport - phone recreation. What we didn't expect was that this was
about to become the business equivalent of a medal event.<BR>
<BR>
Suddenly, automated answering systems were everywhere. So were menus. And
then, an even uglier reality set in. Sometimes those menus never even gave
us the option of talking to a human being. <BR>
<BR>
If we didn't know the extension, if we didn't have a name, if we didn't
have a correct spelling, we didn't have a chance. We thought, This can't
get worse. Surprise.<BR>
<BR>
We dialed a sure thing: Directory Assistance. And got a recording.<BR>
<BR>
News reports labeled this &quot;progress&quot; - and revealed that callers
would have to sound totally helpless, pathetic or both before a listening,
but not speaking operator would actually make a sound on the other end of
the line.<BR>
<BR>
We were not amused. We mumbled or concocted other subversive strategies
to make operators speak. We didn't want to, but we learned we could play
this game, too.<BR>
<BR>
That's when they moved the playing field altogether. We dialed local, our
calls were answered long distance.<BR>
  <BR>
Which brings us to today, when we ring a Pittsburgh business ... and get
a pick-up in Indiana. And if we ever do get a real live human being, that's
where they are, too. Just for sport, ask for directions or ask them to deviate
from their automated menus and tell you what is on the seventh floor. Try
to get them to find employees who have changed job descriptions, or names,
or are away from their desks. Ask them about changes in cafeteria hours.<BR>
<BR>
I myself keep asking questions until they finally disclose their location.
And then, after I tell them that I'm sure they are a very lovely person,
I tell them that I wish someone in Pittsburgh had their job. <BR>
<BR>
Here's a question to top managers who decided customers could be handled
by remote control: Since when did telephone operators and customer service
representatives take such a huge bite out of your bottom line that you've
had to automate them, centralize them and alienate all the rest of us? The
next time you're going fishing for some new gee-whiz customer service technique
to employ ... why not try common sense?<BR>
<BR>
When we call your business, let us speak to a human being, and let that
human being be right here in this place where they can help us and where
you are making money: Pittsburgh. <BR>
<BR>
If you want a refresher course in the payoff for all this, call Carol here
at Executive Report. She'll listen to you and point you to whomever best
can answer your query. The moment you hear her voice, your day is going
to get much better. And my argument is going to get much stronger.     
            <BR>
<BR>
