<HEAD>
    <TITLE>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Diner.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Working With Reality</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>The Pennsylvania Manufacturers Association<BR>
Strives to Keep Jobs in the Area</FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>In a state whose factories were the forge of the nation, a decline in
manufacturing jobs marks what could be seen as a cultural change. After
all, from the mills of the Mon Valley came the beams that built the country's
skyscrapers, the bridges that spanned rivers and the armaments that helped
America win world wars. The blue- collar hardhat who carried a lunchbox
in the plant gate and hoisted an Iron City after quitting time became an
American icon.<BR>
<BR>
But like much of the country, Pennsylvania has seen a drop in its number
of manufacturing jobs as employment climbed in the service sector. In fact,
the state's decline was much sharper than the rest of the nation, according
to recently released figures from the Pennsylvania State Data Center, the
state's official source of population and economic statistics. From 1980
to 1990, the center says, manufacturing jobs in Pennsylvania plummeted by
23.5 percent; the comparable number nationwide for the same period was a
drop of 6.6 percent.<BR>
<BR>
And the decline has continued;  from 1991 until last year, Pennsylvania
lost more than 43,000 manufacturing  jobs, according to the center.<BR>
<BR>
By comparison, jobs in construction rose from 1980 to 1990 by 37.9 percent,
the state data center says. Financial jobs increased by almost as much,
at 36.9 percent, and professional services jobs rose by 32.6 percent.<BR>
	<BR>
The shift to other types of jobs as elements of heavy industry disappear
is something state officials and representatives of manufacturing industries
recognize. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Obviously, we're concerned,&quot; says Dick Shurilla, a Harrisburg
spokesman for the Pennsylvania Manufacturers Association. &quot;Our position
is one of working with this reality.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A variety of broad economic development efforts could help state government
have an impact on stemming the loss of manufacturing jobs. <BR>
<BR>
The state has pushed a program of job creation and job retention, using
a variety of methods to boost employment. In an undertaking not limited
to any business sector, the Ridge administration pushed for and won lower
business taxes and reforms in the workers' compensation system and began
a review of regulatory policies. The state has looked for new markets for
Pennsylvania's products, both around the country and especially overseas.<BR>
<BR>
Of more direct benefit to the attempt to keep heavy industry at home in
Pennsylvania is a law passed last year that encourages companies to clean
up and reuse abandoned industrial sites. The program is being used cooperatively
by the Department of Environmental Protection, which is responsible for
overseeing clean ups, and by the Department of Community and Economic Development
- the former Commerce Department - which provides loans and other assistance.
They have strong PMA backing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I can't think of anything the Ridge administration is doing that we
don't support,&quot; Shurilla says. <BR>
But the PMA also has its own take on how to approach the problems its members
face and to look for solutions. The organization, which represents manufacturers
in matters relating to state government, sees its mission as that of a foundation
more than a lobbying group, Shurilla says. The PMA is more interested in
building coalitions on issues than in button-holing lawmakers and officials.<BR>
<BR>
A recent thrust and a key priority for PMA President Murray Dickman is education
improvements, Shurilla says, on the theory that a better educated work force
helps business. &quot;The schools aren't giving us the workers we need to
meet the demands of manufacturers,&quot; according to Shurilla. The need
is seen in secondary and higher education, as well as in vocational and
technical training, he says.<BR>
<BR>
Other issues tie in to the effort to improve conditions for manufacturing.
Though they don't seem to have an apparent link, PMA supports both a proposed
gas tax increase and competition in the electric business. While higher
gas taxes would hit businesses that rely on trucking, the improvements to
roads would outweigh that cost, Shurilla says. And electric competition
would be good for customers, if it can be phased in to keep utilities afloat
in the meantime, he adds. In the end, it all goes back to one goal.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Our policy is to do what we can to promote job creation,&quot; Shurilla
says<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
