<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.People.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Creative Native</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Another Young, Innovative Chef Returns and is Now Starring<BR>
at the Iron Butterfly, a New Cultural District Eatery</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>Despite the fact that their wine menu is blazoned with &quot;In A
Gadda Da Vino,&quot; the Cultural District's newest restaurant, The Iron
Butterfly, isn't named for the '70s rock group famous for recording the
longest song in rock history. <BR>
<BR>
Rather, the name is a sort of metaphor for culture emerging from the gritty
industry that was foundation to Pittsburgh's fortunes. Barbara Hughes, 
formerly the manager of Bravo Franco, and one of several partners in the
new venture, says the basis of the restaurant will be its interaction with
the events in the Cultural District. Others involved are Nathaniel Wilcox,
owner of the Sewickley Hotel, chef Stephen Malfatti and Kathleen Master,
former bar manager at Rico's.  &quot;For instance, if there's a cabaret,
we might have a 'cabaret of cabernets' wine tasting.' &quot;<BR>
<BR>
But it will take more than clever promos to overcome what can be a dearth
of downtown business; Wilcox says nights with no theater performances sometimes
see just two diners. And for that, the restaurant's shooting for an old-fashioned
solution:  just darn good food and drink.<BR>
<BR>
Malfatti, 34, a Pittsburgh native and graduate of the Culinary Institute
of America, cut his teeth at the London Hilton as well as in New York's
superior Le Cirque and Tavern on the Green. The eclectic influence is clear.<BR>
<BR>
On a recent evening, we had a roasted calamari and saffron risotto and the
barbecued duck and portobella mushroom quesadilla with spicy mango salsa.
The risotto was creamy and smooth, but the saffron taste was a little too
overpowering. The quesadilla was at once piquant and sweet, held together
with melted cheese. The barbecued duck was piquant - not too oily, with
a thick, rich barbecue tang, grilled to perfection. The mango salsa was
sweet, a thick, guacamole-textured topping adding a surprising dimension
to the already inventive dish. The salads are uninspired - I'd suggest choosing
some other tempting item, like the tian of crabmeat and avocado, sauce gazpacho,
or the seared foie gras on poached figs with a currant demi-glace.<BR>
<BR>
The English influence shows in Malfatti's use of rich reductions, flavored
with fruit or port - but the accommodations he creates for them are uniquely
contemporary. We tried medallions of veal tenderloin in a port wine shallot
demi-glace; the sauce was well-balanced and deep, the veal perfectly cooked.
But the hit at the table was Napoleon of red snapper: a finely sauteed fillet
of snapper layered with scallops, crayfish and asparagus, then another fillet.
The innovative port wine lobster sauce was delicately flavored but quite
rich; unfortunately, the entree was sitting in a pool of it, which overpowered
the other wonderful tastes.<BR>
<BR>
The Iron Butterfly's lunch menu is not just a thin echo of dinner. For starters,
we tried the roasted yellow bell pepper soup infused with basil, a light
cream soup with a fantastic sweet taste. The fried herb polenta was smooth,
perfectly complementing a thick link of sweet sausage and a marinara of
which even our picky Italian taster approved. Sandwiches include the usual
Reuben - but we were impressed with the hand-hewn prosciutto and gorgonzola
on foccacio, served with fire roasted pimento chutney. Lunch entrees run
the gamut: we tried lobster and shrimp ravioli - wonderful, but again sitting
in a pool of herbed olive oil. Bites mixed with a bit of the accompanying
sun-dried tomato were heavenly, however. Another winner was roasted breast
of chicken with portobella Madeira demi-glace and saffron risotto - the
risotto was mellower than when tried before,   the chicken moist and finely
sauced with an earthily rich glaze.<BR>
<BR>
The dessert menu is not as inspired as the rest of the creations. A light
Marscapone cheesecake was fluffy, not too sweet. The raspberry chocolate
torte is thick and rich with chocolate. But go back to the office for coffee
-even a freshly brewed pot was mediocre.<BR>
<BR>
The wine list currently presents a short, but admirable selection - from
an Opus I Meritage ($95.00) to an Italian Gavi di Gavi ($22.00). Happy hour
in the bar, which is a beautiful slab of viridian marble, perfectly complimenting
the celery walls and simple white table-clothed rounds, looks like a restful
alternative to Dingbats.<BR>
<BR>
FYI, &quot;In A Gadda Da Vino&quot; is an allusion to the Iron Butterfly's
(the group's) drunken pronunciation of 'In the Garden of Eden.' <BR>
<BR>
With a little more consistency, this Iron Butterfly might just emerge as
one of downtown's hits.<BR>
<BR>
The Iron Butterfly<BR>
212 Sixth Street<BR>
Downtown<BR>
434-4766<BR>
<BR>
Hours: <BR>
Mon. - Thurs.: 11 a.m. - 11 p.m.<BR>
Fri. - Sat.: 11 a.m. - 11:30 p.m.<BR>
Closed Certain Sundays<BR>
<BR>
Appetizers and Salads: $4.95-$10.95 <BR>
Entrees: $9.95 - $18.95<BR>
