BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Law.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Secking Ablak</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: <I>Secking Ablak</I><BR>
Occupation: Vice President, Pizza Outlet<BR>
Age: 30<BR>
Personal: Lives in the South Hills with his wife<BR>
Maria and daughter Anna<BR>
Education: BS., University of Pittsburgh, 1988<BR>
Last Book Read: &quot;The One-Minute Manager&quot; by Kenneth Blanchard
<BR>
Last Vacation: Orlando last spring<BR>
</B><HR>You've probably seen the Strip Tease - a clever ad campaign touting
the freshness of Pizza Outlet's ingredients. With 53 stores open since 1988
and counting, banking on quality seems to be working for the company. A
$30,000 initial investment into one store in Mt. Lebanon has grown into
a company recording $20 million to 30 million in sales company-wide, doubling
sales each year since 1994. Varol Ablak, his brother Seckin (pronounced
&quot;Sedgekin&quot;) and their father head the company's quick expansion,
and have goals of opening store 1,000 by the year 2005. But they're running
out of room in Pittsburgh, so Seckin is heading down to conquer northern
Virginia and spread pizza to the D.C. market. He's expecting to open the
first store there by September, and have 10 open by next year. Lydia Strohl
talked to him about the fast-moving company in their South Hills office.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Executive Report:</B> When did the first Pizza Outlet open?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Seckin Ablak:</B> January 30, 1988. My brother and father started the
business; I was finishing my last term at school and helping out whenever
I could. They had some experience. My brother went to Louisiana to open
a store with some friends and they didn't have success there. My father
is a mining engineer, a deep mine specialist and he went down there, too.
When the [oil] industry started to go bad he decided that he might want
to do something like [a restaurant] too - but that was when the economy
started to go bad because oil prices went down. They were big restaurants
- Sicily's Pizza, dine-in, buffets, plus deliveries. So they had a lot of
overhead. They did have a few stores that were delivery, and it seemed those
stores were a lot more profitable. Just because of the low overhead. I mean,
Pizza Hut now has gone into delivery. They're getting away from the restaurants,
not totally, but they seem to be opening more of the delco - delivery and
carry out - than red roof dine-in facilities. <BR>
<BR>
There's a lot of places that do the restaurant very well, but there are
few places that deliver pizza very well. It's difficult. You've got to find
the drivers. When they decided to come back to Pittsburgh - we had a lot
of friends and this was where we wanted to be -[my brother] sold his interest
and invested it in the first store here.<BR>
<BR>
The first store in Mt. Lebanon was just a small delivery/carry out store.
We don't have other financing. There have been other partners that have
come in, but basically it's just through the stores that we've been able
to grow. <BR>
<BR>
It's so tough to find people to work. With the training that we do we feel
that we have very good people working for us. We have 25 people who work
out of the office, including supervisors. Everyone in the office also assists
in the stores. Ever since we started eight years ago we've put in a tremendous
number of hours.<BR>
<BR>
We've almost overextended ourselves at times. We had an opportunity to take
over a lot of [Domino's]stores, and it wasn't a very good time for us financially
to do it, but we didn't feel we had another opportunity like this. We jumped
and we really had to buckle down and make sure it worked for us. And it
has. Overall, I think we have about six stores that were Domino's. We have
about four stores that were Four Star Pizza. Until recently, all the stores
we opened were previously owned by someone else, and were, obviously, unsuccessful.
We've gone in and streamlined the operation, made it more efficient and
increased sales. But recent stores have been built from scratch. <BR>
<B>ER:</B> What was the initial capital investment?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> I believe it was about $30,000. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How did the growth track from the first opening?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> By the end of 1988 there were two stores. By the end of '89 there
were six stores. At the end of '90 there were seven - then it starts getting
gray. But in 1996, by the end of July, we will have opened 13 stores. And
that's not including two temporary locations that were open in the Olympics.
We also had a location at the Regatta, selling personal pizzas; we had a
wave runner delivering pizzas to boats.<BR>
<BR>
There are a lot of people involved in the company, and we respect everyone's
ideas. We have the final say, of course, both in the franchise and the corporate
stores, but you know, you learn every day. And if you're just so straight
that you think you know everything, you lose the opportunity to grow, to
try different things. We in no way feel we're above anyone else. We work
just as hard as we expect everyone else to work.<BR>
<BR>
My father watches over the maintenance department, and a lot of times he's
up on the last rung of the ladder painting something because no one else
will go up there. He does what it takes to finish the job. Sometimes I'll
drop by a store and if they're behind, I'll grab a broom, you know. I don't
want to be there 'til one in the morning, so I do what it takes. I feel
that they see us working this hard, they know what it takes. They're going
to work this hard for us. And they do.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How many employees do you have now?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA: </B>Between corporate and franchise I believe we employ about 1,300.
We have 25 corporate stores and 28 franchise stores. We just had a store
open in Kittanning. We continue to grow. After college, I went to New Orleans
for a year and worked on the offshore oil rigs. I wasn't very happy with
my job and planned on coming up to Pittsburgh, helping out a little, passing
out resumes. I believe it was May of 1989. I didn't send one resume out.
I just got involved in the business and it just took off. My brother Varol
has engineered a lot of the deals that we've come across. He's very experienced
in lease negotiations and business opportunities. He's the president and
the one that really pushed for the expansion. He's struck the deals for
the locations - to be able to go in with less capital and strike up the
best deal.<BR>
<BR>
He's in Turkey right now. There are some people interested in opening stores
in Turkey. We're Turkish. And there are other people that are interested
in foreign markets. There's so much growth potential in foreign markets,
it's really amazing. Friends that we have that have gone to Turkey have
seen, in popular beach towns for example, a three-story Burger King that
has 300 or 400 people there 24 hours a day eating. It's constantly packed.
So we feel our expansion could be beneficial for us and whoever gets involved.
It's amazing how they look at American investors, and American companies.
It's very positive. I believe one of the busiest McDonalds in the world
is in Moscow. I've seen sales figures for companies that have opened in
foreign markets and they are two and three times what American stores are
doing. I know the Domino's that have opened in Japan are maybe four times
the sales of the U.S. stores, but they could also be charging more because
they pay more for rent or labor. But generally all you hear is success stories
as far as expanding. <BR>
<BR>
There are also areas we're looking to expand to in the U.S. As I said, we
opened some stores in the Olympics.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How did that happen?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> We have some people interested in opening some stores in the
South, in Florida, in Texas, and they're from At-lanta. One of the stores
that we opened this year is in Atlanta - the owner had some friends that
invest with us in Pittsburgh, and he thought it would be great to develop
there. So my brother went down to see him and he had some friends that had
space at the Olympics. He looked into it, and we assisted them in getting
the equipment and in the management end of it. We have someone down there
now supervising the whole operation. It was basically word of mouth.<BR>
I've met with various franchise companies, and one of the things that one
company asked was 'What type of advertising do you do?' I thought he meant
to sell our product - he meant advertising to sell a franchise. I said,
'Well, we haven't.' He said, 'What do you credit your growth towards?' I
said, 'Every person that has opened a franchise store has either been family,
friend or employee.' Even the store in Atlanta is an employee who used to
work for us - he was a driver for us while he was going to school. Then
he moved to Atlanta and he felt that our product was better than anything
he could get there, so we helped him open a store down there. A franchise
store opened in Laguna Hills, that's near Los Angeles. There are two brothers,
and when we opened the first store in Mt. Lebanon one used to work for us.
Once again they call us and say, 'Can you guys get us a steak hoagie out
here? We haven't had a steak hoagie like you guys make.' They're business
people and they sold interests in other investments to open a store out
there. They're very successful and are looking to open a second store.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What kind of investment is it to open a store?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> To get into a franchise is about $83,000. The initial investment
in the delivery end is a lot less than you would have to pay in a lot of
the big restaurants - Olive Garden, Italian Oven, even Boston Market, the
investment is well above $300,000. I think the Italian Oven is half a million.
With us, you can open at least five stores for the same amount of money.
We require that the managing partner have a certain ownership percentage.
Unless someone has money invested, people switch jobs. The only way we could
assure that store would be run properly is by having a partner that's going
to run it. Now, we have a lot of managers in our stores that run better
stores than some of our franchisees. But we're the managing owner, so we
guarantee those stores are going to be run right.<BR>
<BR>
A few of the people that we've had have gone on to open a second store,
a third store - what they do is get a general manager in their store, and
supervise it. But that owner is trained to run that store, if the manager
leaves. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>Opening a pizza franchise in Pittsburgh sounds like taking sand
to the Gobi - and yet, you've had phenomenal success. What are the keys?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> First of all, we set up a game plan. And one of the most important
things was - well, there's a lot of things. Quality. We use nothing but
quality products since we've opened our stores, even the first store. My
brother was doing research and he came across my father-in-law, who had
a food supply company. They talked about what were the best products out
there for pizza. Since then, my father-in-law has gone on to work with Pennsylvania
Macaroni Co., and we feel they supply the best Italian products in the market.
<BR>
<BR>
Second thing is service. We've all strived to make sure we had good people,
we had clean stores, we had good service. That's not an easy thing to ask
people - because you can't just have 10 or 15 people in a store cleaning.
So you also have to run it in the most efficient way. It's budgeting your
time, scheduling properly, expecting more from people and constantly checking
on things, making sure the people do what they need to do before they leave.
Sunday, my father and I went to the driving range, and we were supposed
to meet that night for dinner. We got done around 12:00, and he said he
was going to check on a few stores. When I met him that night, he told me
which ones he went to, and what he saw. We want to check on our stores,
and if there's anything that might not be right, correct the problem. We
have checklists to make sure the drivers know what they're supposed to do
during peak times and during slow times. A lot of the people that we deal
with are parttime employees, so it's real important to train them right.
You can't constantly tell people what to do, they have to know. So if you
spend the time to train people, it might initially take a little longer,
but once you do it right the store runs a lot more efficiently.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How does the training run?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> The general manager handles it at each store. He has a checklist
and goes right down the list. Cooks are the same way. Especially with new
stores, it's very difficult, because we hire about 30 or 40 people, and
you need to train all those people by the time the store opens. What you
do is isolate a person to one particular area, and work with them until
they know that area. Everyone's cross-trained, so if a driver comes in and
the phone is ringing, he grabs the phone. If a cook is making pizzas and
a hoagie needs to be made, he does it. If it's a busy night and someone
gets behind, he tells the general manager, who assigns a backup. <BR>
<BR>
We're in the process of getting computers. We use Pizza Fast. Each customer
has a separate file, which is accessed through their phone number. It would
automatically pop up their name and address, a history of what they've ordered,
and it gives us a mailing list so we can send coupons. It gives us other
information automatically like how many orders an hour, at the end of the
week, what's the average delivery time, each day - it allows us to take
care of things if need be. We have a director of operations in the office,
and underneath him are five supervisors. They each watch over five stores,
and each store has a general manager. The general manager watches over day-to-day
operations, and he's the one person we talk to. We have meetings in the
office to go over various things - it's the supervisors' job to get the
message to the managers. It's maybe a little top heavy, but it's worked
very well for us.<BR>
<BR>
The franchise department is quite similar. We have a director of operations
for the franchise stores. He has two assistants under him and we visit each
franchise store once a month. We do a visit sheet to make sure they are
following all the specs. We check on the image of the store and other various
things. If there's something they need to address, they take care of it
that month. If they don't, then we can take action - we've never had to
in the past. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What type of control do you retain?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> We have the ability to pull the name from the store if it's necessary.
It may never be necessary, but there's a lot of people that have their total
lives invested in our company. Us, for example, but just to give you an
idea - say we have an owner in Dormont that isn't doing a very good job.
That affects Mt. Lebanon. It's up to us to make sure that doesn't happen,
because someone has their whole life savings tied up in that store. This
is a map of the whole Pittsburgh area, and you can see that all the delivery
areas come right up to each other. Pretty much all of Pittsburgh is covered
- we're looking to open a store in Carnegie. There are certain areas we
don't deliver to, and that's why we say limited delivery area. For example,
Rte. 19 and Rte. 8 are maybe six miles apart, and we try to do about a 2.5
mile radius, so there's an area there that's not covered. But you really
need to be on Rte. 19 or on Rte. 8 - and there's really not enough in the
middle to put a store there.<BR>
<BR>
We're starting to move into areas farther out - Morgantown, Charleroi, Ellwood
City, St. Clairsville, Ohio.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What do you look for in locating an Outlet?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA</B>: We check demographics, automobile count - it's real difficult
to come up with a minimum. Do you know where Valencia is? It's real spread
out, but Valencia is one of our best stores. It's very interesting. And
a franchise store in Sarver is one of our most successful franchises. You're
talking in a three- or four-mile radius only having 3,000 households. There
is competition - three or four stores have opened and closed since we've
been there. It's the management. We've created a system where, if you follow
the system, there's no reason it shouldn't be successful.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How will the minimum wage hike affect your business?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> We're going to have to adjust our prices. It's not bad for us.
We have a lot of very dedicated people. It's going to be difficult, but
we'll do what we need to do.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Restaurants traditionally have narrow profit margins. Is that
true in your business?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> We've had stores that have had a 25 percent profit in a month,
and we've had stores that have lost money. We've closed two stores. We closed
one store downtown, on Fifth Avenue - it was a dangerous area. Not that
we ever had a problem with it, but you just needed the right person in there.
There were break-ins - it was just difficult. The other was a store in Carnegie,
and the owner was building another store and didn't want to pay our royalty
fees. He just switched the name - he's running a very successful business
right now.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER</B>: Is the royalty based on a percentage?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA</B>: Yes, three percent is our fee. Initial franchise fee is $8,000.
They get trained, and even if they haven't run a business before, we show
them how to look at the numbers, we show them how to train people. We have
a four-week training program that we put people through and they learn every
aspect of the business. We also assist them in opening the store. We have
a crew of people that go up there, since you're talking about 30 to 40 people
coming in at once. We're there for the first full week, open to closing,
making sure the stores run properly. Their second store is less, as there's
no training involved, it's $5,000. And employees of ours, even if there
is some training involved, we'll give it to them for $5,000, just because
they've worked with us and they know much of the business. We cut them a
break.<BR>
<BR>
It's not like we're profiting $8,000 - we have a training manager and a
whole crew of people that we pay for to work in that store. We have a guy
involved in national development, who assists in every aspect of opening
the store - hiring a general contractor, putting together a floor plan,
purchasing the equipment - all that. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How do you increase sales in a market? Which company do you consider
your toughest competition?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> In general, when we go into a market, we like to open right next
to Pizza Hut, to Domino's, because we feel we have a better product and
we can compete with them. There's plenty of business for both of us - and
if they open in our area, they'll take a little bit from us. People have
different tastes.<BR>
<BR>
They're very successful: but they don't have what we have. What we stress
is quality. A lot of those companies will have their vegetables sliced and
vacuum packed, delivered out of the back of an 18-wheeler. We slice the
vegetables we need that day. We make the dough fresh daily. We have proprietary
items - like our own pizza sauce, pepperoni and fresh cheese.  We tell the
companies what kind of specs we need on the food. They're all top quality
companies. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Can the franchises outside of Pittsburgh get the same ingredients?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA: </B>We don't ship ourselves, but these companies that are working
with us in the local area are making enough money that we expect them to
service a place like California, or Atlanta. We pick companies that are
already being serviced by our suppliers - so to put an extra pallet of pizza
sauce up until our store there needs it is no problem. So a pizza in California
is the same as here, Atlanta the same thing.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What about Turkey?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA: </B>Turkey, it might be a similar menu, but there's going to be some
differences. A lot of the products we work with are pork products, and Turkey
is a Muslim nation - they don't eat pork. We'll have to find what the tastes
are. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>Which marketing strategies do you find most effective?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SA:</B> For local areas, these last two openings, Kittanning and St.
Clairs-ville, we've done more sales than any of the other areas. This is
outside of the Pittsburgh market. And what we attribute that to is radio
ads, television - I'm sure St. Clairsville catches a few of our ads. But
they must've heard about us somehow - from coming up to Pittsburgh, maybe
seeing our billboards. But it's not like we did a tremendous amount of advertising
to warrant that amount of sales. The ones opening in Georgia and California
have started out slower, and we expected that. It takes time. There's not
the momentum.<BR>
<BR>
We do various things when we open. There was a live remote from the Kittanning
store, so a lot of people heard we were opening that day. We send flyers
out to local businesses with coupons on them. We go from house to house
hanging menus on doors. We try to cover the whole area before we open. We
always open on Wednesday.<BR>
<BR>
There's a certain percentage that we do out of the office, like a co-op
program. We have an advertising agency, Carroll Advertising, they come up
with ads. Last year's ad was the 'Strip Tease,' a play on words, basically,
because all of our products are delivered fresh from the Strip district.
The radio ad won first place in the Pittsburgh area, and in the national
awards, I think we came in third. It was tremendous for us. <BR>
<BR>
There were a few people that did complain, that didn't appreciate the whole
concept, we tried to handle them as delicately as possible. <BR>
<BR>
Basically, we give [the advertising agency] a budget, we say we want to
spend this much. In general, it's roughly $700 per store - with 45 stores
in the Pittsburgh market, we say you have $31,500, that much to spend. When
a new store comes on, instead of taking that and splitting it up one more
way, we just add to it. We request that the franchises spend 6.5 percent
of sales, the $700 is included in that, and whatever's left we ask them
to spend on local markets, from putting ads in the paper, to local yearbooks,
to sponsoring local teams. <BR>
<BR>
The best form of advertising is door hanging, flying coupons and menus on
the door in the afternoon; when they come home they're more likely to order.
The same with businesses - if you stop in before lunch when everyone's hungry
you get more response.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
