"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Sexual Harassment</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Don't Think it Will Go Away;<BR>
Investigate it and Eradicate it<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When six former employees of Astra USA sued the pharmaceuticals giant
last spring, their charges were simple and to the point: Top management
sexually harassed young, female members of the Astra sales force, and middle
managers who tried to put a stop to the harassment were forced out of the
company, the complaint charged.<BR>
<BR>
Astra, which calls the lawsuit &quot;outrageous,&quot; nonetheless has suspended
CEO Lars Bildman and two other top executives amid allegations that they
were among the worst offenders, preying on young, female sales trainees
at meetings the company held near its headquarters in Boston.<BR>
<BR>
In a nutshell, the sexual harassment scandal has been a public relations
nightmare for Astra, which is finding out how quickly word gets around.
Some female physicians who got wind of the scandal have stopped writing
Astra products - including popular allergy drug Rhinocort - in silent protest.
And prospective employees now view Astra as an employer that tolerates sexual
harassment in the workplace.<BR>
<BR>
No employer wants that kind of reputation. The Astra case shows the importance
of investigating sexual harassment when allegations surface and eliminating
harassment if it does indeed exist in the workplace. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sexual harassment in the workplace is a problem,&quot; says attorney
Robert McTiernan of Tucker Erensberg in Pittsburgh. &quot;It is not something
that has been blown out of proportion. It is there. You just cannot readily
dismiss something as being without justification. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Usually, you will not find some kind of behavior that is not appropriate,&quot;
says McTiernan.<BR>
The problem is this: Some companies, especially smaller businesses that
don't have human resources professionals on staff, think the problem will
resolve itself. Those companies, by ignoring the harassment, are risking
litigation and the kind of negative publicity that Astra is still experiencing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You cannot put your head in the sand,&quot; says Sidney Zohn, an attorney
with Buchanan Ingersoll in Pittsburgh who handles many sexual harassment
cases. &quot;There is an affirmative obligation to address the situation.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sometimes an employee who may have been the victim of sexual harassment
tells the employer but doesn't want anything done,&quot; adds attorney Vicki
Beatty of Pittsburgh's Meyer Darragh Buckler Bebenek &amp; Eck. &quot;The
employee just wants the employer to know. Even though the employee may not
want anything done about it, the employer has an obligation to investigate.
They are making a big mistake if they don't.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Sexual Harassment Types<BR>
</B><BR>
The courts recognize sexual harassment claims under two primary theories:
quid pro quo sexual harassment and hostile environment sexual harassment.<BR>
<BR>
Quid pro quo sexual harassment occurs when a superior demands sexual favors
in return for economic or job benefits, or when the superior punishes the
subordinate employee for refusing to comply with the sexual request. Quid
pro quo harassment also has a subcategory called reverse quid pro quo harassment:
If an employee is coerced into submitting to unwelcome sexual advances in
return for a job benefit, other employees who were qualified but denied
the benefit can establish that sex was a condition for denying the benefit.
<BR>
<BR>
The courts usually follow a five-part test to decide whether the plaintiff
has a quid pro quo case. The victim must show they are a member of a protected
group, such as females; the sexual advances were unwelcome; the harassment
was sexually or gender motivated; the individual's reaction to the advances
affected a tangible aspect of employment such as compensation or advancement;
and, the offender is a superior.<BR>
<BR>
The other type of harassment, hostile environment, exists when sexual or
gender-related conduct unreasonably interferes with an individual's performance
or creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive environment. Employers
often fear this kind of sexual harassment complaint because it is likely
the harassment occurred without the employer's knowledge. The sexual harassment
claim need not be based on conduct that is solely sexual in nature, since
intimidation and hostility toward gender can result from conduct other than
explicit sexual advances.<BR>
<BR>
<B>It Gets Tricky</B><BR>
<BR>
Any personnel investigation is complicated, whether the employer suspects
theft, drug abuse or sexual harassment. But investigations especially get
tricky when the subject is sexual harassment.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A lot of these types of situations don't occur when there are a number
of other witnesses standing around,&quot; says Meyer Darragh's Beatty. &quot;Often-
times, that type of harassment -  propositions and threats - takes place
behind closed doors.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So it comes down to the purported victim's word against the purported offender's
word, and credibility is the issue.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The employer must walk that balancing act,&quot; adds Buchanan Ingersoll's
Zohn. &quot;Are you going to destroy the career of someone who has done
nothing wrong? Are you going to take no action when there might be something
there?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Most attorneys agree that it's best to take a detailed statement from the
victim, perhaps allowing the victim to write out the statement and sign
it. The employer then must get a response from the suspected offender, and
from there move to corroborate information via other sources.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It so often boils down to one person's word against another and a
determination of credibility,&quot; says Tucker Erensberg's McTiernan. &quot;The
employer has to make a credibility determination based on all the points.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;To me, in my experience, the person handling the investigation usually
has a pretty good sense of who is telling the truth.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, there will be instances in which the evidence is inconclusive.
In that case, the employer should inform all parties that the investigation
was inconclusive, but sternly remind them that sexual harassment is not
tolerated.<BR>
<BR>
There have been many instances in which an employee who was in jeopardy
of losing his or her job came forth with sexual harassment allegations with
hope of securing their job. On the other hand, there have been cases in
which poor employees who were in jeopardy of losing their jobs also had
valid harassment claims.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are no guarantees,&quot; says Meyer Darragh's Beatty. &quot;You
have to go with what you believe to be the truth.&quot;<BR>
