<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Law.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Uniform Changes</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Teams Generate Money by Changing Uniforms: <BR>
The Pirates and Steelers are Next <BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>The Pirates 1996 season comes to a merciful conclusion at the end
of this month and after a season like this one, fans expect changes.<BR>
<BR>
And, shortly after the World Series, the Pirates will respond to that demand
and announce major changes, designed to alter the club's bottom line.<BR>
<BR>
Free-agent signings? Trades? Front-office shakeup? Naw, that's old hat,
and old hats don't cut it in the '90s. Which could explain why the Pirates
have decided to change their hats - along with their uniforms and logo.<BR>
<BR>
For the 1997 season, the Pirates will have three different caps they will
wear in games, three different uniforms, new warmup jackets and a new official
logo. Most importantly for the team, the moves figure to be anything but
cosmetic.<BR>
<BR>
The Pirates were so serious about making these changes that they test-marketed
the designs on focus groups most likely to be interested in the new look:
kids ages 6 to 19.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We saw what they liked and what they didn't like,&quot; says Steve
Greenberg, the Pirates' vice president for marketing and operations. &quot;If
the team shows significant improvement, what we propose to do can create
an incredible demand for Pirates clothing.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Pirates, of course, are not alone in changing uniforms or logos to increase
income. It's something that has been done by a number of teams in recent
years, albeit with mixed results. In Houston, for instance, the NBA Rockets
figured after winning two championships, the time was ripe for a new look.
But the new look, coupled with a less-than-championship season, resulted
in disappointing sales in 1996.<BR>
<BR>
A more successful fashion statement was made by the Penguins, who added
a third jersey to their home/away wardrobe and not only pleased fans with
the new look, but translated the jerseys into playoff success. Until reaching
the Stanley Cup semifinals, the Pens were undefeated in their new jerseys,
which made the shirts even more popular.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The third jersey was our best-selling item all year,&quot; says Mark
Willand, director of marketing for Prime Sports, which handles Penguins'
marketing. &quot;As soon as we introduced it, it was extremely successful.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Penguins, in fact, sold out an initial order of 300 jerseys - at $110
each - on the first night they were offered to fans on TV. That's right:
$110 for a night shirt.<BR>
<BR>
Like all professional sports teams, the Penguins have to share some of the
proceeds from merchandise sales with the rest of the league. But the Penguins,
Pirates and Steelers can benefit from the sales of their own merchandise
by becoming part of the retailing process, as all three have done.<BR>
<BR>
Even the Steelers have planned a uniform change - albeit a modest one -
for 1997. Joe Gordon, the Steelers' marketing director, says the sale of
merchandise only accounts for a small percentage of the $65 million in revenue
the club annually produces. Yet he considers this revenue &quot;critical.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Any revenue a team can generate on its own is very important,&quot;
says Gordon. &quot;It's an additional revenue source, which didn't exist
three years ago. It's important as a way of helping us continue to compete.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Gordon says sports fans are more willing to accept design changes in this
era, but the Steelers - conservative as ever - will &quot;not do anything
radical.&quot; The new &quot;streamlined, contemporary look&quot; is largely
the result of the uniforms being produced by Nike in 1997 rather than Starter.<BR>
<BR>
The Pirates and Penguins have always been willing to make more radical changes,
and the moves have paid off. Willand says in the past decade merchandise
marketing has gone from producing revenue in the low six-     figure range
- $150,000 to $200,000 - to seven figures.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It can have a big impact if done sensibly,&quot; Willand says. &quot;You
can't be overly commercial, because people will see through it. But anytime
you make a sensible addition, it can make a significant difference.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
For the Pirates, who generate seven-figure revenue from shared national
money, plus additional money they get from their own &quot;clubhouse stores,&quot;
the new uniforms and hats are designed to be more than just cash cows. &quot;It's
a marketing tool,&quot; says Greenberg. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If a lot of people are walking around in our new jerseys,&quot; says
Greenberg, &quot;it's advertising.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
