<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Education.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Pension Plan</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Setting One Up Is Not as  <BR>
Difficult or Costly as Some Think<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Ryan Krischke, owner of data communications firm Network Resources,
has always offered his employees a good benefits package, but he wanted
to take it a step further by setting up a pension plan. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've always done everything we could. We saw this as the last major
benefit,&quot; he says. &quot;It's worked out fairly well because we can
tie it directly to the profits of the company.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Sound like a major undertaking for a small business? In reality it's not.
Thinking that pension plans are difficult for small businesses to set up
is a common misconception, says Joseph P. Nicola Jr., a senior tax manager
with  Pittsburgh's Alpern, Rosenthal Co. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The Department of Labor and the IRS have both made it very easy for
small businesses to set up retirement plans,&quot; says Nicola. &quot;And
the reason is because the IRS in particular has a procedure by which they
will bless a plan well in advance.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So what keeps many small businesses from establishing a pension plan? &quot;My
guess is fear, more than anything else,&quot; says Nicola. &quot;There are
quite a few employers out there who are concerned about fiduciary liability
and responsibility. Now that's a rather fallacious fear only in the sense
that all pension plans are required to carry what are known as fidelity
bonds, which is basically insurance. That's what essentially protects the
employer from any kind of liability.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Granted, there are certain costs associated with setting up and administering
a pension plan. A company can have a tax attorney or accountant draw up
a customized plan to submit to the IRS for approval, costing $2,000 or more.
An alternative is a prototype plan, which costs a business next to nothing.
Administrative requirements include annual filing requirements with the
IRS and the labor department.<BR>
<BR>
There are also costs associated with meeting the testing requirements of
the IRS for pension plans. For qualified retirement plans, such as 401(k)s
and profit-sharing plans, the government attempts to maintain a ratio of
the money that is going into a plan for two separate groups within a company:
highly compensated employees and non-highly compensated employees. <BR>
<BR>
Criteria used to distinguish highly compensated employees includes income
levels and whether the employee is a stockholder. The government totals
up all of the income in each group and how much money went into the plan
for each group, not only contributed by the employee, but also by the employer.
<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;What happens is that you then get a certain ratio of income to the
amount contributed for each group,&quot; explains Don McDade, an associate
general manager for AllAmerica Financial. &quot;And let's just say that
for the non-highly compensated group, that percentage came out to five percent
of income. Then what the government says is that the highly compensated
group cannot contribute more than five percent of their total income.  There's
a two percent spread between the two.&quot;  The government calls this test
a nondiscrimination test. &quot;What the government says is that if we allow
the highly compensated group to contribute a lot more money than the non-highly
compensated group, then that would be an unfair advantage.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What can happen is that the plan over time can become pretty expensive
to administer because of these regulations and the testing that has to go
on,&quot; says McDade. &quot;The employer generally can't do it, it's too
complicated.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Although a broker or insurance agent can perform this work, it is still
an extra cost for a small business.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, says McDade, &quot;The main reason that small business owners
do not set up qualified retirement plans is because a small business owner
does not want to be locked into having to commit to putting a certain amount
of money into a qualified retirement plan every year. With a lot of plans,
they could be locked into putting in a fair amount of money. &quot;<BR>
<BR>
When small businesses do bite the bullet and set up a plan, chances are
they are doing it as a benefit for employees, not as a tax deduction for
the company. &quot;I would say that 80 to 90 percent of business owners
out there are very aware of the fact that they need to save money for retirement,
that they want something that they can contribute to and work with, and
they want their employees to be able to have something,&quot; says McDade.<BR>
<BR>
That is the reason, despite the testing and administration costs, why Network
Resources set up a 401(k) and a profit-sharing plan. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've been around - it will be nine years this year - and it's something
we've always wanted to do,&quot; says Krischke. &quot;Historically it's
always been very difficult in terms of the paperwork and reporting requirements.
I really wanted to get it done simply as a corporate benefit. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The company's been very solid and profitable over the last few years
and we really wanted a way to provide a benefit to the employees that would
also give everyone a tax break.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
&copy; Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
