<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H17Education.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>Teaching Leaders</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1>Leadership Can Be Taught in the Classroom;<BR>
Corporate America Thinks So, Anyway<BR>
</FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Conventional wisdom tells us great leaders are born, not made. But
some students at Pittsburgh colleges and universities would argue against
that notion. They are enrolled in programs and classes that teach leadership.<BR>
<BR>
These classes attempt to teach the subtle, but critical, skills that separate
a &quot;leader&quot; from just a boss.<BR>
&quot;Some of the very best, brightest individuals aren't necessarily the
best leaders,&quot; maintains PNC Bank training specialist Larry Pickett,
who considers a good leader as one who can give direction to, coach and
support his or her employees, as well as delegate tasks.<BR>
<BR>
And you won't always find that person at the top of the organization. Pickett
should know: He's among 50 or so graduate students at Duquesne University
who spend their Saturdays working toward their  Master of Arts in Leadership
and Liberal Studies, or MLLS.<BR>
<BR>
The 36-credit program is designed to develop a person's leadership capabilities
as well as increase his or her understanding of the world in which modern
leaders must function.<BR>
<BR>
According to Benjamin Hodes, Duquesne's dean of continuing education, the
need for leadership education has never been greater, particularly as more
and more organizations remove layers of management.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Having technical skills isn't enough to understand how to cope with
change and challenge,&quot; says Hodes, who defines leadership as the ability
to influence others. &quot;Especially when people are much more responsible
for managing themselves and their work.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Still, can leadership be taught to a natural-born follower? Absolutely,
says Marie Cini, assistant professor of leadership studies at Duquesne.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Leadership is a journey,&quot; Cini says. &quot;It involves constantly
recognizing your weaknesses and building upon your strengths.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In the corporate world, Pickett says the learning process is by &quot;trial
and error, and we can't afford that. When you let good people slip out the
door [because of poor leadership], there's an intangible cost to the bottom
line.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Corporate America obviously agrees that leadership education outside the
organization is a viable pursuit: 75 percent of students are reimbursed
for tuition by their employers.<BR>
<BR>
Carnegie Mellon University requires students in its Graduate School of Industrial
Administration to take at least two courses in leadership as part of the
curriculum.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We think we have something serious to add to what you might accidentally
pick up on the job,&quot; says instructor Thomas Kerr, former assistant
general counsel to Westinghouse.<BR>
<BR>
Course work includes case studies of actual situations students or others
in the industry have dealt with, either successfully or not. Students, for
example, may be asked to prepare a female employee for a tour in a foreign
country that disapproves of women in management positions.<BR>
<BR>
That hands-on approach also is paramount in CMU's course on crisis management
and leadership. In addition to giving students the benefit of his own experience,
instructor Gerald Meyers, former chairman of American Motors and a crisis-management
expert, invites a different chief executive officer to class each week for
a question-and-answer session.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;I bring them in and say, 'Here's the guy, ask him any question you've
got, see what you can learn from him,' &quot; says Meyers.<BR>
 <BR>
Beforehand, students research the industry and prepare a paper describing
the executive's qualities. They also role-play a crisis with the actual
executive in attendance.<BR>
<BR>
The experience, says Meyers, is one where  &quot;a whole lot of heat happens
 and sometimes some light.&quot; Especially since the executive himself
later comes on stage to tell the class &quot;what went right and wrong.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;That's how we study leadership,&quot; says Meyers. &quot;We see what
made this person great, his attributes, as well as his shortcomings.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
CMU, like other schools, also offers one- to four-week courses in leadership
for working executives, often on individualized topics, through its Executive
Education Center.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sometimes an executive gets so embedded in what he's doing day to
day, he needs to step back and say, 'Is this the most objective or productive
way to manage this?' &quot; says program director Clark Jordan.<BR>
<BR>
Leadership studies aren't always tied to business: Robert Morris College
offers a program for teachers and professional trainers, the Master of Science
in Instructional Leadership.<BR>
<BR>
The degree, intended for educators who want to take a greater role within
their schools in the area of curriculum development and design, includes
courses in leadership, decision-making and written and oral communication.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Leadership is the ability to influence others,&quot; says Edward Nicholson,
president of Robert Morris, who likens learning how to lead to mastering
golf or a musical instrument.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You can watch it on TV, but it usually won't improve your skills,&quot;
he says. What's needed, he says, is good instruction, constructive feedback
- and lots of practice.<BR>
<BR>
Leadership training isn't restricted to the graduate level; at least two
local colleges offer either classes or entire programs in leadership for
undergrads.<BR>
<BR>
At Robert Morris, for example, undergraduate business majors must take at
least two courses that emphasize the development of leadership skills -
that is, learning how to communicate well one-on-one and in small groups,
how to organize and motivate others, and how to formulate visions and develop
strategies.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, every undergraduate must take a series of five courses in oral
and written communication during freshman and sophomore years.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Leadership is essentially the ability to influence others,&quot; explains
Nicholson, &quot;and to a large extent, that's through the communication
process.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
At Chatham College, a women's college in Oakland, all students are encouraged
to participate in Chatham LEADS, a non-degree program that aims to develop
leadership skills and provide true practice in leading.<BR>
<BR>
The four-year program consists of workshops and seminars focusing on self-awareness
and leadership skill development as well as mentoring and internship opportunities
with local and national women leaders. Last year, for instance, a group
of students traveled to Ireland to study with Irish leaders. And this fall,
Chatham launched the Pennsylvania Center for Women in Public Leadership,
through which students will study leadership positions.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My premise is, you lead if you're expected to lead,&quot; says Chatham
President Esther Barazzone, &quot;but a lot of women aren't expected to
lead.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Women need to become aware early on of their potential, says Barazzone,
or they may not develop that expectation. They also need to become conscious
of barriers they face.<BR>
 <BR>
Leadership training is particular- ly important for women, notes Barazzone,
because it helps them learn how to deal with what she sees as &quot;public
resistance to women in leadership positions.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;An openly strong woman is not always welcomed as that,&quot; she says.
&quot;Leadership training is a way of keeping their confidence high and
strengthening their effectiveness.&quot;<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
