<HEAD>
    <TITLE>HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Education.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H15Health.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>EMoney Back Guarantees<BR>
</FONT></I><FONT size =+1>IEmployers Find Ways to Make Insurers<BR>
Put Their Money Where Their Mouth Is<BR>
</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Employers shopping the managed care market for a healthcare provider
have encountered a problem: With competition so fierce, insurers are jumping
all over themselves promising to meet the healthcare needs of corporations
and their employees.<BR>
<BR>
That doesn't sound like such a bad problem - but in the fervor of the sell,
managed care companies may promise more than they can deliver. In healthcare,
that can be downright dangerous. Enter, the performance guarantee.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Employers need to ensure that [the managed care company] is not buying
their business,&quot; says Maureen Londino, a principal with Buck Consultants.
&quot;They have a better chance if they can put the appropriate protocols
in place and build some kind of performance guarantees. They have to define
all this up front, and then hold them accountable.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The first thing to question is whether the managed care company has the
network of providers in place to service your employees. Employers must
check that the network has the right geographic placement of doctors, hospitals
and other providers. They should also make sure the doctors are taking on
new patients, so that employees are assured access to them.<BR>
<BR>
If the proper network isn't in place, however, don't immediately discount
that insurer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sometimes the network will agree to expand access and will negotiate
with the provider,&quot; says Londino. &quot;In fact, some may even put
dollars at risk, for example, $100,000, if the networks aren't in place
by a specific date.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
According to Londino, networks now cover most of the region. But that's
not always been the case. &quot;Two years ago, there was a problem with
access in West Virginia, but corporations negotiated with managed care companies,
who built the networks.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Other often-negotiated elements revolve around financial arrangements, according
to Towers Perrin consultant David Lagnese.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The old days where everything is fully insured are long gone,&quot;
says Lagnese. &quot;There's a lot of variation in plan design among employers.&quot;
Banks, for instance, might want to delay payment, whereas a utility might
want more predictability in their billing scheme. Negotiating points often
include the capitation arrangements with providers, as well as how various
bonuses are paid to providers. Another area for big employers to explore
is whether or not they will share in volume discounts with suppliers, such
as pharmacy charges.<BR>
<BR>
Also popular are performance guarantees that put some part of the administrative
fee (generally in the range of 50 to 100 percent) at risk if the managed
care company doesn't meet targets set in the areas of claims, customer service
and response. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The managed care company comes in and projects what the covered claims
cost will be - and it generally should be 5 percent either way,&quot; says
Londino. &quot;But they can put the numbers on and then not manage the business
and have a 25 percent difference.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Other areas in which standards are often set are in claims turnaround -
Londino says it should be under 10 days, &quot;or there's a problem.&quot;
Some contracts establish how out-of-network claims will be responded to,
as well.<BR>
<BR>
Member services is another area of concern. The rule of thumb is that a
hotline call be answered in 30 seconds. And look at that carefully, says
Londino, because some companies may use answering machines to maintain the
answering time in heavy calling periods. A 15 percent abandonment rate -
when the phone isn't answered so the caller hangs up - is often a contractual
point.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The benefits may be richer, so there's some concern on the part of
employers that they're giving away savings. Managed care is supposed to
be more efficient and these arrangements ensure that,&quot; says Lagnese.
<BR>
<BR>
While these guarantees are generally written as multiyear agreements (two
to four years) that allow for some kind of settling up at the end of the
specified period, Londino recommends asking for monthly administrative reports,
and having quarterly meetings with the insurer to make sure problems are
being addressed. Once a year, invite an outside auditor in to make sure
the contract is being honored. Londino says some companies don't monitor
or recapture these savings, which can be up to 20 percent of healthcare
costs.<BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, these negotiations seem to be reserved for large employers.
Small companies, insuring under 1,000 lives, generally buy an off-the-shelf
managed care product, so have less leeway. Still, it's good business to
monitor and partner with the insurer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;To some extent, employers need to be realistic - if they push too
hard the company may say they can do something when they really can't, so
the plan is poorly administered and the employer is unhappy,&quot; says
Londino. &quot;If they work in partnership, they have a more successful
long-term relationship. And on the flip side, if a managed care company
does better than the targets, the employer may want to build in performance
incentives, and split the gain.&quot; <BR>
<H4><CENTER>Comparing the Big Three HMOs<BR>
</CENTER>
</H4>
The following is a breakdown of basic coverage by HMOs. Some group plans
may differ at the employer's request:<BR>
<BR>
<B>Keystone Health Plan West</B><BR>
<BR>
Parent: Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania/Pennsylvania Blue Shield<BR>
<BR>
<B>HMO: </B>KeystoneBlue, licensed since August 1986. Primary care centers
are located in Harmar, Robinson, Green Tree, Monroeville, McCandless, West
Mifflin, Squirrel Hill and Moon Township.<BR>
Medical Care: The covered medical care includes immunizations, mammograms,
allergy testing and treatment, home care, physician services including surgery
and anesthesia, hospital care including drugs, maternity care and emergency
care worldwide. Some group plans may require a copayment for health assessments
or new baby and child care.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Gynecological Care: </B>Covers 100 percent of routine gynecological care,
including a pelvic exam, clinical breast exam and PAP test administered
by the primary care physician or any Keystone participating  gynecologist.
No referral required.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Prescription Drugs:</B> Most plans cover drugs, including prenatal vitamins,
when filled through participating pharmacies. Copayments apply.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Eye Care:</B> Vision screening for diagnostic proceedures is covered
when provided by the primary care physician; routine exams for glasses are
not.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Dental Care: </B>Not covered.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Mental Health:</B> Up to 20 outpatient mental health visits covered in
each calendar year with a $25 copay per visit (some group plans may vary).
Inpatient mental health care covered for up to 30 days in a 12-month period.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency Services:</B> The first course of outpatient treatment
is covered in full.<BR>
 <BR>
Subsequent courses of outpatient treatment are subject to a $25 copay or
50 percent of allowable charges, whichever is less. Inpatient rehab covered
for up to 30 days in any 12-month period, with total lifetime coverage not
to exceed 90 days.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Infertility Testing/Counseling:</B> Copay is a maximum of $200 per course
of treatment or 50 percent of charges, whichever is less.<BR>
<BR>
<B>What's Not Covered:</B> Services by nonparticipating providers (except
during emergencies), reversal of voluntary sterilization, cosmetic surgery,
dental care and drugs prescribed for nicotine cessation or weight reduction.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Other Blue Cross Plans:</B><BR>
<BR>
SelectBlue, a point-of-service program that combines the managed care features
of an HMO with the freedom of choice of traditional healthcare plans. The
patient may utilize a primary care physician arrangement common to an HMO
or self-refer to a physician in or out of the SelectBlue network. Self-referrals
are subject to an annual deductible.<BR>
<BR>
PreferredBlue, a preferred pro-vider organization, also allows subscribers
to go outside the Blue Cross network. There are no primary care physicians,
but those who stay within the network pay less than those who go outside
the network.<BR>
<BR>
<B>HealthAmerica<BR>
Parent: Coventry<BR>
<BR>
HMO: HealthAmerica</B>, licensed since 1975. Primary care centers are located
in Wexford, Upper St. Clair, Oakland, Penn Hills, Monroeville, Green Tree,
West Mifflin, Cranberry and Moon Township.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Medical Care: </B>The covered      medical care includes periodical 
   physicals, immunizations, mam-mograms, cholesterol screenings,    allergy
testing, home care, physician services including surgery and anesthesia,
hospital care, maternity care including Lamaze training and emergency care.
Some group plans may require a copay of $25 for emergency room visits.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Gynecological Care:</B> Routine    services, including pelvic examination,
PAP test and any follow-up care are covered 100 percent when performed by
the primary care physician, a HealthAmerica gynecologist or a  gynecologist
to whom the patient  is referred by the primary care physician. The patient
may select a gynecologist of her choice without  a referral, with HealthAmerica
paying up to $100 toward the annual checkup if the physician is outside
of the   network.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Prescription Drug:</B> Most plans cover drugs, including prenatal vitamins,
when filled through participating pharmacies. Some copays apply.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Eye Care:</B> Eye care is included as an optional benefit in some group
plans. Most HealthAmerica medical offices have optometrists on staff to
perform routine examinations, diagnose eye disease and write prescriptions
for eyeglasses.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Dental Care:</B> Participating dentists will provide an oral examination,
routine cleaning and two bite-wing X-rays for $18 every six months. Discounts
are available, in some instances, on other dental care.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Mental Health:</B> Inpatient mental health treatment is covered 100 percent
for up to 30 days per year, except in some group plans that may require
a $25 copay for each of the first five days. Up to 20 outpatient visits
are covered annually, each subject to a $20 copay  per visit. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency Services:</B> Inpatient alcohol and chemical detoxification
treatment is covered 100 percent for up to 30 days per year, except in some
group plans that include a copay. Inpatient care is limited to 90 days lifetime.
Up to 60 outpatient visits covered annually, with a cap of 120  lifetime.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Infertility Testing/Counseling:</B> Counseling may require some copay.<BR>
<BR>
<B>What's Not Covered:</B> Serum       for allergy treatment, services by
   nonparticipating providers (except during emergencies), reversal of 
     voluntary sterilization, cosmetic surgery.<BR>
Other HealthAmerica Plans:<BR>
<BR>
HealthAssurance, a preferred pro-vider organization, gives patients the
option of remaining in the Health-America network at less expense      
  or using physicians outside the network, with care subject to an annual
deductible. <BR>
<BR>
<B>U.S. Healthcare<BR>
Parent: Aetna Inc.<BR>
<BR>
Medical Care:</B> Coverage includes well care; physicals; routine allergy
shots, illnesses or injuries; well-baby visits and immunizations; vision
care and home healthcare. Hospital care covered includes surgical expenses,
medications, consultations and diagnostics, and emergency care worldwide.
Outpatient surgery is also covered.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Maternity Care:</B> Includes prenatal care, delivery and postnatal care,
discounts through outside vendors on baby products, and a high-risk pregnancy
program which pairs a U.S. Healthcare member with a nurse case manager who
coordinates access to specialists (perinatologists) in order to bring the
pregnancy as close to term as possible. Length of hospitalization for mother
and newborn is based on medical necessity.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Gynecological Care:</B> U.S. Healthcare members are eligible for one
routine exam per year without a referral from the primary care doctor. This
includes coverage for all office-based services. Additional visits with
the Ob/Gyn require a referral from the primary care doctor.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Prescription Drugs:</B> Covered   with a purchased prescription rider.
   In addition, U.S. Healthcare's Medi-care plan offers prescription cover-
  age with a $1,000 annual maximum and a $10 copayment in the Pittsburgh
area.<BR>
 <BR>
<B>Eye Care:</B> Eye examinations are covered under most plans. Some plans
reimburse for the cost of prescription eyeglasses or contact lenses every
two years.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Dental Care:</B> Covered for pediatric preventive dental services. Additional
dental care covered with purchased dental rider.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Mental Health:</B> Baseline benefit is set by state mandates. Some employers
purchase additional coverage.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Chemical Dependency:</B> Baseline benefit is set by state mandates. 
    Some employers purchase additional coverage.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Infertility Testing/Counseling: </B>U.S. Healthcare offers an expanded
infertility program. This includes one cycle of Assisted Reproductive Technology
(ART), and the implantation of eggs.<BR>
<BR>
<B>What's Not Covered:</B> Non-referred specialist care (except in the point-
   of-service plans, where care by a physician outside the network is subject
     to coinsurance and deductibles),     cosmetic surgery, provision of
blood,           custodial care, immunizations for work or travel, treament
of mental retardation (no medical treatment available), reversal of voluntary
      sterilization.                                            <BR>
