<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+>A Regular Guy<BR>
</FONT SIZE><BR>
<B>By Catherine Dressler</B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Cut From a Different Mold Than His Predecessors, New    University
of Pittsburgh Chancellor Mark Nordenberg Referees Swim Meets, Shops for
Groceries and Picks Up the Family Laundry;<BR>
Many Think He's the Right Man for Pitt<BR>
</B><BR>
<BR>
Mark Nordenberg celebrated with friends the day he got the biggest break
of his 23-year career, the day &quot;interim&quot; was dropped from his
title as chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh. But he didn't toast
his good fortune at a fancy restaurant or a swanky club. Not even at the
corner bar. <BR>
<BR>
Instead, at the end of that fine June day, he did what he does countless
summer nights: He acted as a referee for his 13-year-old son's swim meet.
At the end of the meet, another parent unexpectedly pulled out a magnum
of champagne and the grown-ups toasted Nordenberg with plastic cups and
joked around.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;People feel like they're part of Mark's success,&quot; says Nordenberg's
 wife Nikki. &quot;It's a very Pittsburgh thing.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Now so is Nordenberg, head of a university that in recent years was stung
by charges that the chancellor's office had become rife with cronyism and
arrogance. That's hardly the case with Nordenberg, a 48-year-old,      boyish-looking
chief executive who     many describe as a regular guy. He's a law professor
whose true love is teaching. A committed husband and father who juggles
the demands of a dual-career family and teenage kids.<BR>
<BR>
This is a guy who picks up the laundry, shops for groceries and hand-writes
notes in his Christmas cards - hundreds of them. A guy so regular that some
of the perks of the job - like living in the chancellor's sprawling residence
just off the Oakland campus - seem a bit too much for him.<BR>
&quot;I like to be in a place where you naturally run into your kids on
the way to the bathroom,&quot; <BR>
Nordenberg says in what he calls his &quot;drawn-out Midwest-ern drawl.&quot;
He picked that up in Duluth, Minn., where he was born and spent most of
his childhood, in a tight-knit family from Swedish roots.<BR>
<BR>
Growing up in Duluth, Nordenberg cheered on the St. Louis Cardinals because
- simply put - his father did. &quot;I was a typical oldest child,&quot;
he says. &quot;What my dad liked, I liked.&quot; <BR>
His mother was a high school English teacher, and he was a serious student
who regularly made the honor roll and ran cross-country track. He was forced
to leave his hometown the summer before his senior year in high school when
his father, a U.S. Steel Corp. executive, was transferred to Pittsburgh.<BR>
 <BR>
The family loved Pittsburgh and the move drew them closer, so much so that
when Nordenberg graduated from North Allegheny High School, he chose to
attend Thiel College in Greenville to be near them. Ironically, his father
was transferred to Chicago two years after the family came to Pittsburgh.
Nordenberg's teachers encouraged him to stick with science, so he majored
in math at Thiel. But after a couple of years he began contemplating the
career in law that later landed him back in Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
His father, Alan, was not pleased to hear of his interest in law, and told
Nordenberg to think twice about it. &quot;He looked at me and said, 'I hope
you thought carefully about all the opportunities you are leaving behind
in science,' &quot; Nordenberg recalls. <BR>
<BR>
About that time, Nordenberg met Nikki Pirillo on a bug-collecting biology
field trip at Thiel. She was a 17-year-old freshman. He was a more seasoned
man, a 19-year-old sophomore. The two married in 1970, the year both graduated,
Nikki six months early. <BR>
<BR>
After graduating with honors from the University of Wisconsin Law School,
Nordenberg joined a firm in Minneapolis in 1973. He was offered a position
in the Watergate prosecution but turned it down, largely because he did
not want to move at that time. The decision left him pondering &quot;the
power of personal inertia,&quot; the lure of the familiar that could keep
one from growing and trying new things in the course of a career. So after
just two years of practicing law, he decided to try teaching. &quot;I really
thought I should see if this form of life would be more rewarding,&quot;
he says. <BR>
<BR>
He joined the faculty of the Capital University Law School in Columbus,
Ohio, in 1975. Two years later, he returned to Pittsburgh - hired by a Pitt
law dean named John E. Murray Jr. - and never left. He's Pitt's 17th chancellor.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Trusted and Respected</B><BR>
<BR>
Libby Jacaszek worked under seven deans as an administrative assistant at
Pitt's law school before retiring last spring. Nordenberg's strong work
ethic still stands out in her mind. One Saturday morning when he needed
her help sending out a Federal Express package, he tracked her down by calling
her cousin.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;He's a person of determination,&quot; she says. <BR>
<BR>
Others agree. In fact, Nordenberg's enthusiasm for teaching earned him the
nickname &quot;Sparky Nordenberg&quot; among his students in the early 1980s.
Murray, now president of Duquesne University, gave Nordenberg a job as a
visiting assistant law professor at Pitt in 1977. At the time, Murray periodically
watched professors in the classroom and critiqued their teaching. He will
never forget the first time he watched Nordenberg.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;After that hour, he came into my office and said, 'What do you think?'
and I said, 'I never really want to see you teach again because you are
an excellent teacher.' Some people are born to teach, and Mark is one of
them.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Nordenberg began teaching specialty civil procedure, the rules that govern
how cases move through civil court. In 1983, he was named a full professor.
A year later, law students voted to give him the Excellence-in-Teaching
Award. The next year, he received the Chancellor's Distin-guished Teaching
Award.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;He was almost intellectually intimidating,&quot; recalls Brian Himmel,
a 1992 magna cum laude graduate of Pitt's law school who was in Norden-berg's
civil procedure class in 1990. <BR>
&quot;It wasn't because he put on airs or anything,&quot; Himmel says. &quot;You
could just tell how much he knew.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Some law professors humiliate students using the Socratic method of teaching,
embarrassing them in front of their peers if they can't break down a case.
But the tone in Nordenberg's class was more friendly, and he never seemed
to deliberately belittle anyone, Himmel says. In fact, he would patiently
try to explain an answer if a student didn't seem to understand.<BR>
 <BR>
Nordenberg did, however, keep the students on their toes by posing long,
detailed questions - often rocking slightly as he recited the background
- capped off by the name of the student he was addressing. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;He wouldn't say your name until the end,&quot;  Himmel says. &quot;When
you heard your name, you would feel this pain go through your body.&quot;
When Himmel graduated, he was shocked when, as Nordenberg handed him his
diploma, Nordenberg commented on how well Himmel had done in tax courses.
&quot;That he knew about that and realized it was me surprised me,&quot;
Himmel says.<BR>
<BR>
Nordenberg's affection for people lies at the heart of his love for teaching.
&quot;There probably is nothing more noble than being involved in the development
of human potential, which is at the heart of teaching at any level,&quot;
the chancellor says. He treasures the moments when former students return
or bump into him and tell him how much they learned in his classes, &quot;how
someone might have grown over the course of a semester or year.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But there is a pattern to Nor-   denberg's career at Pitt. Every time he
got comfortable in the classroom, someone asked him to take on an administrative
job. In 1985, he was named associate dean for academic affairs and then
interim dean of the law school. Two years later, he became dean on a permanent
basis, a post he held until 1993. He then turned his attention to teaching
again and, a few weeks later, was asked to take on another interim job,
this time as provost. He had returned to teaching yet again when former
Chancellor J. Dennis O'Connor announced plans to step down under fire and
board of trustees Chairman J. Wray Connolly approached Nordenberg in the
summer of 1995 about taking on the role of acting chancellor.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I was minding my own business and putting my faculty life back in
order,&quot; Nordenberg says. But those days are over for now. Nordenberg
will be lucky to fit guest lecturing around his new priorities, which include
growing Pitt's endowment, cultivating alumni, convincing state legislators
to fund the school at an adequate level and maintaining enrollment levels.<BR>
<BR>
His track record as dean of the Pitt law school lays a good foundation.
At the law school, Nordenberg built alliances with law alumni and the community.
He attended the annual Bench-Bar Conference at Seven Springs Resort, a weekend
of schmoozing that academic types usually avoid. He gave speeches to law
firms and corporate legal departments and served on countless committees
and commissions, some of which revised civil court rules.<BR>
<BR>
Pat Sorek, a 1984 Pitt law graduate who is a clerk for U.S. District Judge
Robert Cindrich, was working for the U.S. Justice Department in Washing-ton,
D.C., when he met Nordenberg at alumni receptions held in the capital. &quot;He
was just great, the way he could talk to people and work the crowd,&quot;
Sorek says. &quot;He was your prototypical ambassador.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Nordenberg also developed an alumni giving program that was extremely successful,
says Marvin Lieber, a '58 Pitt law graduate and partner with Lieber, Lieber
and Tarantine in Pittsburgh. &quot;His outreach is very important because
it gave him the opportunity to listen to a number of constituencies that
aren't the faculty alone,&quot; Lieber says. &quot;He continues to do that
type of outreach.&quot;<BR>
One incident that caused controversy during Nordenberg's tenure as dean
involved S. Candice Hoke, a professor who sued the university in federal
court after she was denied tenure. The sex discrimination lawsuit charges
that some senior male faculty members in the law school consistently voted
against the tenure of feminists they viewed as outspoken. The suit says
Nordenberg &quot;seriously misrepresented'' Hoke's qualifications in a letter
to the provost and that Nordenberg later wrote to recent law school graduates
who supported Hoke's decision to sue and threatened &quot;not to certify
them as morally fit to be admitted into the state bar.'' Nordenberg was
not named as a defendant.<BR>
<BR>
The university says the decision to deny Hoke tenure was based on weaknesses
in Hoke's professional performances, not gender. Pitt says in the spring
of 1992 - when Hoke says her tenure was denied due to gender - two of the
three law faculty members who received tenure were women. <BR>
Nordenberg's friends, meanwhile, say his concern for others and an ability
to listen carefully, analyze information and present a reasoned solution
make him a trusted adviser.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When it was time to make important decisions in my career, I always
talked to him,&quot; says Ken Gormley, now a law professor at Duquesne who
started teaching at Pitt in 1982. Nordenberg became a friend and colleague
who was always willing to stop by and help out.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You just knew that when you sat down and talked to him, he was listening
and whatever he said was going to be his honest opinion,&quot; Gormley says.<BR>
<BR>
Link Christin, a 1979 Pitt law graduate, says, &quot;He has a sort of a
judicial quality about him, a wisdom that is older than his years.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Even current Pitt students find Nordenberg appealing. Senior Andrew Wuertele
had only met Nordenberg once when he saw him walking out of the student
bookstore last year. Wuertele explained he was considering running for the
president of Pitt's student government and would like to talk about it.
&quot;He said, 'Yes, come along, walk along with me. Tell me what's on your
mind,' &quot; says Wuertele, who later ran for the office and won. &quot;It
showed so much respect for me as a student.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>His Father's Influence</B><BR>
<BR>
Since his father died of cancer three years ago at the age of 73, Nordenberg
has realized the power of his example. Like Nordenberg, his father worked
hard - he was usually the first to arrive at the office in the morning -
and honored institutional loyalty. &quot;He was a person who I think placed
an extremely high value on treating people with respect, recognizing and
rewarding their contributions and attempting to work with people to improve
performance,&quot; Nordenberg says. &quot;I do think all those things are
also very important to me.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Some have noticed that at Pitt, where Nordenberg is known for sending handwritten
notes to colleagues. H.J. &quot;Jerry&quot; Zoffer, who recently stepped
down as dean of Pitt's Joseph M. Katz Graduate School of Business, says
he got about three notes from Nordenberg in a single month. <BR>
&quot;It's not the kind of thing you expect from someone as busy as him,&quot;
Zoffer says. &quot;You feel he has nothing else to do but concern himself
with those kinds of acts of kindness.&quot;<BR>
 <BR>
Another faculty member who has never met Nordenberg was pleasantly surprised
when she got a note from him after reading about her involvement in a workshop.<BR>
<BR>
Yet Nordenberg finds the time, just as his father did. Ironically, all three
of the senior Nordenberg's children went into law.<BR>
<BR>
Nordenberg's sister, Lynn Crenney, who is a year younger, is a partner at
Wilder Mahood and Crenney in Pittsburgh. His brother, Jon, who is five years
younger, is an attorney in Madison, Wis.  <BR>
Today Nordenberg's family re-mains as important to him as anything.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Nothing in life has been more satisfying than being a father,&quot;
he says. &quot;I probably would give up everything if that was the price
required to maintain our relationship as a family.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The couple's 22-year-old daughter, Erin, recently graduated from Kenyon
College in Ohio. Carl, 16, attends Central Catholic High School, and Michael,
13, attends the Falk School at Pitt. Nikki is a partner in a career counseling
and consulting business. Most of her work involves counseling members of
the Allegheny County Bar Association about work issues, sometimes a desire
to leave law. <BR>
<BR>
As Nordenberg settled into the new job, the family was wistful about leaving
their five-bedroom home in Regent Square, which they are renting out to
a visiting faculty member, and moving into the chancellor's residence on
Devonshire Street.<BR>
<BR>
The imposing mansion has four floors, including the basement, and is easily
three times bigger than the house the Nordenbergs lived in for the past
13 years. Sure, Sophie, the family's mixed-breed dog, and Snake, a 5-foot-long
king snake, will be there, but as Nordenberg puts it, &quot;major areas
of the house are more suitable for professional entertaining than roughhousing
with my sons.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Still, Nikki is committed to making the new house a home. The Ping-Pong
table she got Nordenberg for his birthday goes in the basement rec room.
The kids will no longer be allowed to keep televisions in their rooms for
fear they will never be seen again. The Nordenbergs hope putting the television
in a second-floor living room will force togetherness, a challenge in any
family with teenagers. <BR>
  <BR>
The family usually eats dinner together, though some nights are reserved
for the children's activities. The Nordenbergs have volunteered at Michael's
swim meets for several years. Nordenberg has coached several of Carl's soccer
and baseball teams. He and Carl have played Rotisserie League baseball together
for years despite consistently finishing in the bottom half.<BR>
<BR>
The family has adjusted fairly easily to Nordenberg's new job, Nikki says.
After all, Nordenberg has been working seven days a week for years. On weekdays,
he's usually at his desk at around 6 a.m. and home by about 7 p.m. On the
weekends, he slacks off a little, getting into the office at about 6:30
a.m. and home by lunch.<BR>
<BR>
Nordenberg laments that the university is too often viewed in impersonal
terms as a big, complex place. The chancellor's cavernous office, Room 107
at the end of a dimly lit catacomb-like hallway in the Cathedral of Learning,
still has its charms, though. Nordenberg knocks on a wood panel and laughs,
saying his son is convinced there must be a secret compartment somewhere.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In fact, the university is home to tens of thousands of wonderful
human beings, faculty, staff and students who make important contributions
on a daily basis and who are individually good citizens and neighbors,''
Nordenberg says. &quot;I would like more of that to show through and be
 appreciated.&quot; <BR>
He will, no doubt, try to do his part. Sending out notes and remembering
faces and names. Pulling into his parking spot in the predawn darkness.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;He knows this university,&quot; says Edward Sell, a member of Pitt's
faculty since 1947 and the dean of Pitt's law school from 1966 to 1977.
&quot;If anybody can pull this off, he has the capability  to do it.&quot;<BR>
<H3><CENTER>Meanwhile, at Duquesne, Murray Settles In<BR>
-Deanna Gentile Marra</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
Duquesne University's board of trustees recently broke a 118-year-old tradition.
The university normally renews its president's contract annually. But this
summer, the board offered a five-year contract to President John E. Murray
Jr. who, since 1988, has had his contract renewed on a year-to-year basis.<BR>
<BR>
Why the sudden change of heart? In large part because of Murray's fund-raising
prowess and how it has allowed him to transform Duquesne into a top institution.
You may remember that ER featured Murray as the cover story one year ago
this month. But Duquesne's board of trustees noticed his success long before
ER did.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The board could not be more pleased with the leadership of President
Murray over the last eight years,&quot; says Richard L. White, chairman
of Duquesne's board of trustees. &quot;It is an amazing effort that has
brought Duquesne national and international acclaim as one of the leading
Catholic universities in America and the world.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Murray is often thought of as the man who saved Duquesne from serious enrollment,
financial and morale problems. During his tenure, Duquesne's enrollment
has increased by 46 percent, the curriculum has expanded to include 80 new
academic programs, and the campus has been rebuilt to make Duquesne one
of the top universities in terms of computerization, multi-media and distance
learning. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think it was basically the concept of stability and continuity,
and a continuation of all the foundations we have been building over the
last eight years,&quot; Murray says of his five-year extension. &quot;Another
piece of this is that our capital campaign will finish in 1999 and, therefore,
it would be appropriate to finish that capital campaign before leaving as
president.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Murray made his mark as a fund-raiser extraordinaire in 1988, when he revitalized
a dead capital campaign that had a goal of $25 million. At that campaign's
completion, a total of $74 million was raised. <BR>
<BR>
The latest capital campaign has a goal of $100 million. So far, more than
$84 million has rolled in.<BR>
&quot;The most important ingredient in the entire capital campaign is scholarships,&quot;
says Murray. &quot;If we want to remain on the cutting edge of computerization
- multi-media, distance learning - the state-of-the-art equipment that you
buy today becomes primitive within three years, so you have to keep replacing
that. We need support for the technology we have integrated into the campus
and will continue to advance with over the next five years. On top of that,
we need support for the kind of research that goes on in a typical university.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Murray's plan for the next five years focuses primarily on making major
advancements in distance learning. &quot;Everybody now is a perpetual student
no matter what the discipline. Everybody has to continue to go to school,
and it's a lot easier if you're in Erie or Tokyo to go to school where you
are and be taught by highly qualified people in a place like Pittsburgh.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
For example, distance learning has allowed Duquesne to offer a chemistry
course to students both at Duquesne and the University of Kansas simultaneously.
Earlier this summer, Murray taught a two-day seminar to approximately 65
executives here in Pittsburgh and at the same time to a group of executives
who tuned in from Houston. <BR>
<BR>
   Murray sees distance learning not only as the key to expanding both continuing
education programs and corporate education  programs well into the next
century, but also as a way of establishing branch campuses via cyberspace
through partnerships with other schools. <BR>
     What happens after the five-year contract expires? The 63-year-old
Murray says he has no plans to retire any time soon. <BR>
<BR>
     &quot;I don't think I'll ever retire,&quot; he says. &quot;I will continue
to teach as I will even next year in the school of law as a professor of
law, and I will continue to write my books and my articles.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
   With a chuckle he adds, &quot;I used <BR>
to say that I would like to be found dead in the library, slumped over books.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Now I've changed that a little bit. Either that or slumped over a
computer screen.&quot;<BR>
<H3><CENTER>CMU's New GSIA DeanMixes a Corporate  Background With<BR>
Academic Experience<BR>
- Jim Urban</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
Some of the more popular elective courses at Carnegie Mellon's Graduate
School of Industrial Administration are those that drill students in entrepreneurial
strategies. In simplest terms, the students learn how to start and build
their own businesses.<BR>
<BR>
Now, the new GSIA dean - former AT&amp;T Vice President Douglas M. Dunn
- says he's ready to take entrepreneurial education a step further at GSIA.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;How can we begin to bring the kind of material offered in these entrepreneurship
courses into our core material?&quot; Dunn asked rhetorically during an
interview in late July, shortly after he moved into his new office on CMU's
Oakland campus.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I don't want to treat entrepreneurship as a separate discipline, but
rather part of the core curriculum,&quot; Dunn says. &quot;We can help people,
as their careers develop and grow, have the ability to start a business
on their own and make intelligent decisions.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Dunn, a Canadian-born 53-year-old, knows firsthand what entrepreneurial
thinking can do for a regional economy, having spent a number of years in
entrepreneurial hotbed Atlanta. He earned bachelor's and master's degrees
from Georgia Tech and taught there for two years. During a later stint in
Atlanta, he headed external relations for AT&amp;T's southern region, shaking
new hands every Monday at the Rotary Club luncheon.<BR>
<BR>
Can Pittsburgh follow Atlanta's lead? Dunn admits that one of the first
stories he heard about Pittsburgh was the &quot;brain drain&quot; - the
flight of young talent to other regions of the country. He says GSIA plays
a role in attempting to stem the tide.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My model is to support local businesses and local business opportunity,&quot;
Dunn says. &quot;I think that will be the magnet for not only stopping the
brain drain to the extent that it exists, but also serving as a point of
attraction for people coming in.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'd also like to do more good research into entrepreneurship. We want
to understand what business models are successful and why businesses succeed
or fail. These are good research subjects for our faculty. I'd like to see
more of that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
CMU's appointment of Dunn is in line with a national trend in which some
MBA schools are looking for deans outside of academia. Duquesne University
has former Westinghouse Electric executive and deputy U.S. Commerce Secretary
Thomas Murrin as dean of its A.J. Palumbo School of Business. Elsewhere,
the University of Maryland hired a one-time Wall Street heavyweight, former
First Boston CEO William Mayer to head its MBA program. Other schools, meanwhile,
including some top programs, have resisted the move to the corporate world
and remained within academia. An example is Harvard's appointment last year
of world-renowned manufacturing management professor Kim Bryce Clark as
dean of its business school.<BR>
In GSIA's case, CMU President Robert Mehrabian says Dunn has a unique mix
of both corporate and academic experience, which makes him a good fit for
GSIA. Dunn spent 26 years at AT&amp;T, his most recent position being vice
president of visual communications and multimedia strategy. And he has a
Ph.D. in business statistics from the University of Michigan, where he studied
quantitative methods under noted professor W. Allen Spivey.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Communication is one of his strongest characteristics,&quot; Spivey
says of Dunn. &quot;That's refreshing for someone who has a technical background.
People with technical backgrounds sometimes tend to speak in technical terms
and for many years thought they could stay off in their own domain talking
to each other. And what happens is that they tend to be dealt out of the
big hands.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Doug is free of that,&quot; Spivey says.<BR>
<BR>
Adds CMU President Robert Mehrabian: &quot;His knowledge of the business
world and his understanding of how universities can serve the needs of the
corporate world make him an excellent choice to head our world-class business
school.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<H3><CENTER>Kalamazoo's Cook Takes Over at Allegheny<BR>
- Cynthia Bent</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
&quot;What attracted me to Allegheny College was the quality of the people,&quot;
says Richard Cook, who began his term as the new president of Allegheny
College in August. &quot;It's a very open and supportive environment. It
struck me so clearly that it seemed very much like the place that I wanted
to be.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Cook says he wants to continue the focus on the quality of the student experience,
capitalizing on the excellence of the staff and faculty at the Meadville
school while improving facilities. Following a $45 million capital campaign,
Allegheny is building a $15 million science center, with a   $12 million
sports and recreation center soon to come.<BR>
 <BR>
As far as academic direction, Cook wants to push for an integrated learning
experience, meshing academics with real life. He brings to Allegheny a background
of administering off-campus internship and international studies programs
for which Kalamazoo College of Michigan, his previous employer, was well-known.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Internships may play some part in that, some sort of service may play
an increasing role, and we need to carefully and deliberately look at increasing
international opportunities,&quot; says Cook. &quot;I don't intend to impose
any kind of blueprint on a   different place. But I think there        
are things from my past experience that I can bring to Allegheny that  
   will help increase the effectiveness of the program.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
He also emphasizes that the Pittsburgh area plays a major role in the life
of Allegheny College. Some 25 to 30 percent of the student body is recruited
from Greater Pittsburgh, and thousands of alumni populate the Pittsburgh
business community. Over a quarter of the board of trustees hails from Pittsburgh,
as well.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'm enthusiastic about increasing the ties between Pittsburgh and
Allegheny,&quot; he says. &quot;I've already been to the city a couple of
times. I was very impressed - the people were personable and warm, and I
saw a lot of pride about the city. I'm looking forward to getting to know
Pittsburgh.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Cook leaves the position of provost at Kalamazoo College. He had been with
the school for 23 years, having risen through the chemistry department.
<BR>
<BR>
As provost there, he worked with the president to revamp the entire curriculum
and academic calendar. He also revamped the school's prominent study-abroad
program and recruited and hired more than 40 percent of the Kalamazoo faculty.
 <BR>
<BR>
Hunting for the Right Graduate Program? Here's a Sampling of Some Unique
Degrees<BR>
<BR>
While we are on the topic of education, here's a sampling of unique degrees
offered by the region's four-year colleges and universities. Some of the
programs have been around for years, while others are brand-new. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Among them:<BR>
<BR>
<B>CMU's Winning Pair</B><BR>
<BR>
At the top of the list are two programs offered at Carnegie Mellon University:
the Master of Science in Industrial Administration, or MSIA, and the Master
of Science in Public Policy and Management, or MS.<BR>
<BR>
The MSIA, offered at CMU's Graduate School of Industrial Admin-istration
(see the story about new GSIA Dean Douglas Dunn on page 22), is similar
to an MBA, only CMU adds a few twists.<BR>
The core curriculum covers quantitative managerial decision-making techniques;
business communication skills; tools for managing human resources and dealing
with organizational issues; and an overview of how the economic, political
and legal environments interface with business. <BR>
The GSIA faculty members have won wide acclaim - and three Nobel Prizes
- for ground-breaking research in organizational theory, artificial  intelligence,
operations research and corporate finance.<BR>
<BR>
The MS is offered at CMU's Heinz School, which traditionally leads     
professional programs in the             integration of analytic skills,
management competency  and technological sophistication. <BR>
Students develop broad-based, analytically rigorous, marketable and transferable
skills regardless of their particular substantive areas of interest.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Katz MBA</B><BR>
<BR>
A mile away from CMU, full-time MBA students at the University of Pittsburgh's
Katz School earn their degree in 11 months. That's only a year off from
work. <BR>
<BR>
About 40 percent of the 52.5 credits are electives, so the student can pretty
much choose to concentrate on one area or acquire a variety of skills.<BR>
<BR>
The student learns teamwork by going through the entire program as a member
of a group called a Learning Organization, or LO. Each LO sets its own rules,
forms smaller teams for projects and self-governs - just as a corporation
functions.<BR>
<BR>
Pitt also offers the MBA to part-time students, who usually finish in about
three years and do not have to quit their full-time job.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Duquesne and Bayer<BR>
</B><BR>
Further down Forbes Avenue is the Bayer School at Duquesne University, where
graduate students in the Environmental Science and Management program study
ever-developing environmental issues.<BR>
<BR>
The 42-credit curriculum emphasizes environmental sciences, but also includes
the necessary training in business and behavioral science and touches on
law and public policy. Practice in writing and related communication skills
is integrated throughout the program. Two internships - one in  industry
and the other in a regulatory agency - provide valuable practical experience.<BR>
<BR>
Qualified students who do not wish to pursue the degree may still seek enrollment
in particular classes that interest them.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Penn State</B><BR>
<BR>
Penn State is combining business education with science, too, offering a
new five-year, dual degree program in which students can earn a Ph.D. in
pharmacology while they also earn their MBA. Students conduct their Ph.D.
research during the day at Penn State's Milton S. Hershey Medical Center
in Hershey. They take their MBA classes at night and on weekends at Penn
State's <BR>
Harrisburg campus.<BR>
<BR>
The program is geared toward people who plan to work for small to mid-sized
biotechnology firms.<BR>
&quot;[Scientists] find themselves managing labs rather than working in
them,&quot; says Mel Billingsley, professor of pharmacology in the college
of medicine at the Hershey Medical Center. &quot;And as soon as they step
away from that design bench, they are immersed in very different kinds of
activities - scheduling, managing personnel, budgeting and coordinating
programs.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Point Park's IMBA</B><BR>
<BR>
Point Park College offers an International MBA that moves beyond the traditional
MBA by integrating the international dimension of modern business into the
program.<BR>
<BR>
One of the core courses is Cross-cultural Business Management, in which
students learn cross-cultural skills that help them function effectively
in multinational enterprises. <BR>
<BR>
The electives include International Advertising, International Accounting
Concepts and Multinational Human Resource Management.<BR>
<BR>
Working professionals can pursue the degree on a part-time basis. Students
need 39 credits to graduate.<BR>
<BR>
<B>La Roche's HR Program</B><BR>
<BR>
La Roche College offers a master's degree in human resources management,
combining  business administration with psychology, sociology, economics
and the law. The degree consists of 14 three-credit classes, with part-time
students usually finishing in under three years. The classes are held in
the evenings and on Saturdays.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Chatham</B><BR>
<BR>
A new addition to the curriculum at Chatham College is the Master of Liberal
Arts. The MLA program examines major works and ideas that express humankind's
continual efforts to understand the self, the family, the community, the
natural world and the universe.<BR>
<BR>
One course offered in the program this fall, entitled Seminar on Labor Issues,
includes an economic analysis of labor issues along with discussion of the
gender gap in the work force and the decline in union membership.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Geneva's MSOL</B><BR>
<BR>
Geneva College just added a Master of Science in Organizational Leadership
program after spending about three years developing the       curriculum.
The school interviewed scholars in leadership studies as well as corporate
leaders in developing the program.<BR>
<BR>
In 20 months, students can complete their master's degree, meeting one night
each week from 6 p.m. to 10 p.m. at assorted class locations throughout
the Greater Pittsburgh area.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Other Good Ones</B><BR>
<BR>
At Waynesburg College, the 36-credit MBA program is designed to accommodate
both the part-time and full-time student.  Students in the MBA program may
elect to specialize in the criminal justice area. The MBA/Criminal Justice
option emphasizes the real world, real problems and real solutions for those
students concerned with crime and justice. The program also delivers managerial
and organizational skills essential to justice agency operations.<BR>
<BR>
Seton Hill College in Greensburg offers a graduate program in art therapy,
the process of putting what one feels into something one can see. For example,
an adult in a treatment program may keep to himself and seem lost in his
own thoughts. The art therapist helps the client express those thoughts
and communicate through art.<BR>
<BR>
Program director Josie Abbenante built the program from scratch. She came
to Seton Hill from the University of New Mexico, where she developed a similar
program that now is among the top five in the country.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The State Universities</B><BR>
<BR>
What the universities in the state system of higher education bring to the
table is quality graduate programs usually at less expense than the private
universities.<BR>
<BR>
<B>At Indiana University of Pennsylvania</B>, the MBA can be taken on either
a full-time or part-time basis, with day and evening classes available,
including a full schedule of course offerings in the summer. The program
has a strategic and international focus in its curriculum. The faculty members
have extensive academic, industrial and consulting experience and bring
a strong, real-world flavor to the IUP classrooms.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Executive Track of IUP's MBA, </B>located in the Pittsburgh and Johnstown
areas, is designed for experienced managers from industrial, financial,
nonprofit and small businesses as well as the public sector. A Saturday-only
class format allows participants to complete the degree in two years. <BR>
<BR>
<B>At California University of Pennsylvania,</B> meanwhile, full-time students
complete the MBA program in a little over one year, with part-time students
finishing is just over two years. California's MBA program takes the student
through advanced managerial skill development in the areas that significantly
affect modern business enterprises.<BR>
<BR>
<B>At Slippery Rock University, </B>a notable graduate offering is the Master
of Public Administration degree, available full- and part-time to students
wishing to advance through the public sector. The program probes administrative
problems and practices in the public sector, pushes for improvement in the
students' communications skills and drills them in quantitative and qualitative
research and analysis.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Undergraduate Options</B><BR>
<BR>
Are you trying to convince some of your employees to complete their undergraduate
degree? Carlow College offers the Carlow Accelerated Program. CAP features
intensive eight-week sessions (five sessions per year) of evening courses
leading to a Bachelor of Science degree in business management, health science
management or information management, among other degrees.<BR>
<BR>
It is possible for students to complete a degree in 18 months if they take
courses throughout the year.<BR>
<BR>
What about your children as they head into higher education? Allegheny College
in Meadville (see the story about Allegheny's new president on page 23)
offers an environmental management program in which undergrads spend their
first three years at the Meadville campus, followed by two years at Duke
University in Durham, N.C.  The student finishes with a bachelor's degree
from Allegheny and a master's from Duke. <BR>
<BR>
Westminster College in New Wilmington offers a bachelor's degree in international
business. The curriculum addresses the international aspects of business
while also focusing on foreign language and foreign culture. <BR>
<BR>
 While very few entry-level positions exist in international business, the
program is excellent preparation for aspiring MBAs and for employment opportunities
that may come five to 10 years down the line.<BR>
<BR>
At Robert Morris College, undergraduate business majors must display a proficiency
in communications  skills, including writing, speaking and cross-cultural
communication. The nine required communications courses were added to the
curriculum one year ago. The college had surveyed business leaders in the
region, who told the college that today's graduates lack writing, verbal
and critical thinking skills.<BR>
<BR>
At St. Vincent College in Latrobe, students at the Center for Northern Appalachian
Studies document the heritage of the multifaceted region of northern Appalachia
using the tools provided by a variety of disciplines and community-oriented
projects.<BR>
<BR>
Students learn across the whole spectrum of human experience through interdisciplinary
study and participation in fieldwork. Simul-taneously, members of the off-campus
community collaborate with students in collecting, preserving, relating
and interpreting their pasts and experiences. St. Vincent's center was the
first of its kind to specifically identify itself with northern Appalachia.
         <BR>
