    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Psst... We Want to Manage Your Money </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Pennsylvania Capital Bank Showed There is a Market for
Private Banks; Almost Seven Years Later, Larger Banks Have Jumped Into the
Old European-Style Banking That Caters to the Wealthy<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Christopher L:awton</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Meet Barb, a midlevel manager for a large manufacturing company.
She makes a better-than-average income of about $60,000 per year. Her husband,
John, makes his living as an elementary school teacher in one of Pittsburgh's
local school districts. He also makes a good income, about $38,000 per year.
The private banking industry, traditionally a staple of the very wealthy,
wants their business.<BR>
<BR>
Surprised? You shouldn't be. Many couples today who earn two incomes and
approach $100,000 in combined yearly income are prime candidates for private
banking, a growing niche in the banking industry. Private banking supplements
the basic services offered in consumer banking with services such as sophisticated
investment counseling and trust and estate planning.<BR>
<BR>
Private banking emerged in the late 1980s out of the less traditional trust
services that many banks provided for the extremely wealthy. It became the
best way for most banks to rebound from enormous losses suffered from pursuing
large corporate clients and institutional investors. With the recession
of the '80s, the banks faced falling interest rates and competition for
corporate loans from alternative investment sources such as investment bankers
and insurance companies. That forced the banks to attract a new segment
of customers.<BR>
<BR>
So Barb and John ... come on in.<BR>
<BR>
According to most experts in the industry, affluent customers are those
who make at least $100,000 in income as a family or on an individual basis.
Some are the extremely wealthy families of Pittsburgh's elite. But most
private banking customers come from other market segments. Many are entrepreneurs
- individuals who have recently started or have inherited the family business.
Others are attorneys, physicians and mid- and senior-level corporate executives.
Those customers who have recently received payments from 401(k) retirement
plans or who need estate and retirement planning help round out the list
of potential private banking customers.<BR>
<BR>
In addition to managing money and providing business banking services, private
banking facilitates the applications for jumbo mortgages - those exceeding
$250,000.<BR>
<BR>
Private banking has become a viable way for the banks to attract the wealth
of these customers - who still need traditional banking services as well.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Pittsburgh's Growth</B><BR>
<BR>
The private banking industry quickly became such a viable market nationwide
that banks such as Pittsburgh's Pennsylvania Capital Bank were founded for
the sole purpose of providing private banking services for an affluent customer
base. <BR>
<BR>
Pennsylvania Capital opened its doors in the Times Building on Fourth Avenue
downtown in September 1990. The bigger regional banks jumped into the fray
later.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We established Pennsylvania Capital Bank in Pittsburgh because of
the region's excellent small business market and affluent customer base,&quot;
says Donald Nolan, president of Pennsylvania Capital. &quot;Many of our
customers are the young business entrepreneurs, in their mid-30s to mid-50s,
who need help with lending, investing and business planning.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Nolan argues that he feels Pennsylvania Capital Bank is better suited to
fulfill the needs of private banking customers than many of its larger competitors.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We specialize in private banking products and services, period,&quot;
Nolan says. &quot;Other banks that sell traditional services aren't as focused.
They're more like generalists who can offer a diverse product to a wider
array of customers.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The bigger banks say, &quot;Not so fast.&quot; Their size, larger banks
say, provides resources that smaller banks can't tap when it comes to serving
the private banking market.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We bring all of the bank's cultures together for the benefit of our
private banking customers,&quot; says Joseph Guyaux, senior vice president
and manager of PNC Private Bank. &quot;We bring the management of investment
performance, traditional banking needs, and matters of trust and estate
planning together under one roof. The private banking customer then has
these services coordinated by a private banker who directly oversees the
client's financial goals.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
PNC and other banks such as Mellon and National City also have an exceptional
breadth of investment experience and capital assets to offer. PNC has been
managing money for its customers for 178 years and is the 19th-largest investment
manager in the nation. Mellon Bank has also been a long-standing lending
institution and a major bank holding company with over $30 million in assets.
<BR>
<BR>
In the last two years, Mellon made two key acquisitions: The Boston Co.,
currently Mellon's premier mortgage provider, and Dreyfus Financial, which
handles mutual funds and nonbanking investments. &quot;All of these services
give our private banking customers the widest array of competitive products,&quot;
says David Kutch, senior vice president of Mellon's Private Bank. <BR>
<BR>
The latest entry into private banking is National City-Pennsylvania. Following
the acquisition of Integra, National City moved quickly to bring private
banking to western Pennsylvania. Steve Hartle, executive vice president
for National City's Private Bank, has the responsibility for initiating
National City's private banking push through the end of this year.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our goal is to bring banking services to traditional trust services,&quot;
says Hartle. &quot;This mixture broadens and deepens the relationship we
have with our private banking customers.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
 Hartle feels that private banking customers want and demand a high degree
of responsiveness, and he's right. Some say that is what private banking
is all about.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our customers want to work with a knowledgeable professional who understands
their needs, and they appreciate having a primary contact at the bank who
provides quality products and superior service,&quot; Hartle says.<BR>
<BR>
Private banking customers require more sophisticated types of products than
their traditional banking counterparts. And, unlike convenience banking
customers, private banking customers want to deal with a person, not just
an institution. In other words, they perform a lot of their banking in the
bank.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;We get to know our customers on a personal level, so that we can make
the best choices for them in terms of the products and services we offer,&quot;
says Pennsylvania Capital's Nolan.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Pennsylvania Capital</B><BR>
<BR>
The mere existence and growth of Pennsylvania Capital shows there is a market
for private banking in Pittsburgh. It had been 15 years since a bank in
Pittsburgh had started from scratch when Pennsylvania Capital began operations
in 1990. With $110 million in assets and 1995 posted earnings of $1 million,
Pennsylvania Capital has demonstrated in a short period of time that it
is a player.<BR>
<BR>
And although Pennsylvania Capital doesn't have the lengthy history or combination
of traditional services that many of the larger banks in town have, it boasts
an impressive asset ratio and diverse products, many of which mirror those
offered by larger banks.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Most of the larger banks gear their cash management services to large
Fortune 500 companies,&quot; says Judy R. Murtha, a vice president who oversees
the cash management services at Pennsylvania Capital. &quot;We offer these
services to middle-market companies who quite often are amazed that we're
willing to help them.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Pennsylvania Capital Bank's  Capital Cash Service gives customers detail
or summary balance information on all activity occuring in their account
the previous business day, with up to 60 days of history.  It can also provide
information on accounts maintained at other institutions. The information
can be accessed by personal computer or telephone. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our cash management services enable Pennsylvania Capital to provide
an in-depth financial analysis of a business and/or an individual,&quot;
says Murtha, adding that for those who prefer to deal directly with their
local bank, Cash Concentration Service allows daily consolidation of all
of an individual's accounts into one concentration account at Pennsylvania
Capital Bank.  <BR>
<BR>
&quot;This service gives our customer added flexibility by consolidating
their funds quickly and easily,&quot; says Murtha. &quot;And with our Electronic
Debit/Credit Service, customers can pay bills, perform direct payroll deposits
or collect member dues.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
Pennsylvania Capital matches the larger banks by offering sweep accounts,
which enable companies to automatically invest any excess collected checking
account balances into several different investment vehicles, including a
tax-free money market fund, a regular money market fund, a money market
trust, a treasury obligations fund or a prime obligations fund.<BR>
<BR>
Pennsylvania Capital also allows companies to borrow up to 97 percent of
their receivables, eliminating or narrowing cash-flow problems.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When the majority of our customers hear about this service, they think
that it's too good to be true,&quot; says William E. Koeberlein, another
Pennsylvania Capital vice president. &quot;But they quickly see how lucrative
it is for them, and Pittsburgh has proved to be one of the best markets.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Private banking is one of the highest growth services in the banking industry
today. Some scoff that it is a service just for the wealthy, but those same
individuals may be surprised to know that they're already a part of the
growing segment of affluent private banking customers. Or potential candidates
in the near future.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
