    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0996.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0996.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0996.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Aggressive Outsiders </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>A Developer Partnering With the Rooneys is From Connecticut, an
Indication of How Aggressive Some Outside Developers are Being in the Pittsburgh
Market; But What <BR>
About the Local Developers?<BR>
<BR>
By Vince Gagetta<BR>
</B><HR>Alex Conroy, owner of the Conroy Cos. of Greenwich, Conn., can credit
his skills as a salesman as much as his reputation of being a heavy hitter
in real estate development for winning the coveted contract to develop the
area near Three Rivers Stadium for the Rooney family. <BR>
<BR>
Why was Conroy selected for the job?  Because, Art Rooney II says, he did
what all good salesmen do: He asked for the order. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Frankly, we didn't seek him out, he approached us,&quot; says Rooney,
a Pittsburgh attorney and the Steelers' vice president.<BR>
<BR>
The fact is, Conroy approached the Rooneys regarding another project, not
even in Pittsburgh, which the Steelers' owners were not interested in pursuing.
But they were - and had been for some time - more interested in doing something
about turning the barren wastelands and dreary warehouses near the stadium
into something more appealing and commercially viable. As long as Conroy
- presumably with very impressive resume in hand - was in town and pitching,
why not run the North Side project up the flagpole? <BR>
 <BR>
Why not, indeed? And so a choice local commercial development plum got plucked
by an out-of-town firm while some of Pittsburgh's biggest, best and brightest
developers watched with, in many cases, undisguised envy. <BR>
<BR>
It's not that Pittsburgh companies will be shut out of the proposed $600
million project to construct a multi-use sports, retail and entertainment
complex on land west of the stadium. As Rooney notes: &quot;I don't think
the decision to use Conroy as the developer on the project eliminates the
possibility of involving local developers at some point. The potential is
there, and there are a lot of very fine local companies that could play
key roles in the project. They have the capabilities to participate, certainly.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But Conroy will be lead developer.<BR>
 <BR>
Calling in big guns from out of town to handle very large, very public and
very prestigious Pittsburgh area projects is nothing new. It has happened
often enough throughout the various Pittsburgh renaissances to give some
locals the modest beginnings of inferiority complexes.<BR>
It is likely to continue. Even the largest local firms maintain a regional
focus and few have even ventured on to the national scene. Conroy's company,
on the other hand, has had extensive national experience and currently is
involved in similar projects in Rhode Island and Virginia. <BR>
The Connecticut developer also impressed the Rooneys by bringing something
more to the party than his development skills: the Nordstroms. Conroy had
already worked with the Seattle, Wash.,  family - owners of what is reputed
to be the finest, most customer-sensitive and most sought-after retail store
chain in the nation.  Both Conroy's Rhode Island and Virginia projects include
Nordstrom stores, and his involvement in the Three Rivers Stadium project
was seen as the key to convincing the Nordstroms that there was no finer
place in the land for their next store than Pittsburgh's North Side - the
wishes of Mayor Tom Murphy and the Pittsburgh Downtown Partnership notwithstanding.<BR>
<BR>
Although the Rooneys and the Nordstroms have known each other for years
- Steelers' President Dan Rooney was chairman of the NFL's Expansion Committee
in 1974, the year the Seattle Seahawks, of which the Nordstroms were then
majority owners, joined the league. Since then, the Rooneys on numerous
occasions have tried to convince their friends the Nordstroms to expand
their 80-plus-store chain by building one  near Three Rivers Stadium. But
it was not until Conroy entered the picture that the Seattle family realized
what a smart move it would be. Art Rooney II credits Conroy with being the
principal reason that Nordstrom agreed to participate in the local undertaking.
<BR>
<B>Connections Count<BR>
</B><BR>
The formal announcement of the Three Rivers project was made on July 17,
one day after Mine Safety Appliances Co. announced it intended to develop
the property it owns in Cranberry, Butler County, into an office park. The
company plans to subdivide the property, sell parcels and construct buildings
suitable to the buyers' needs. <BR>
<BR>
MSA - like the Rooney family, long and very positively identified with Pittsburgh
- did not immediately announce the developer of the project. But a company
spokesperson emphasizes that MSA is looking for a prominent developer with
national connections as a joint-venture partner. And several people closely
associated with local commercial development activities say they think the
&quot;national connections&quot; requirement will eliminate many Pittsburgh
developers from realistic consideration.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It looks like another invitation for the big guns to come in and show
the locals how things are done,&quot; one observes.<BR>
<BR>
There are those who claim that Pittsburgh developers tend to be too narrowly
focused, too conservative and perhaps too set in their ways to keep national
firms from walking off with the most profitable local projects or from venturing
further afield  themselves.<BR>
<BR>
There are good reasons why local developers have become so conservative.
Everyone acknowledges that the Pittsburgh area is not a prime development
area. Most of the choice, reasonably level sites, especially those in close
proximity to the city, disappeared from the market decades ago. There is
hardly any property available here where a developer can put up a building
or two without either demolishing existing structures or going through the
considerable expense of leveling hills.<BR>
 <BR>
That, says Tony Dunn, president of the Kossman Realty Co. unit of Kossman
Development Co., could be too great a challenge for some local developers.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is a tendency around here for us to look at a typical piece
of Pittsburgh land and see a big hill that makes the site unacceptable for
development, while some more adventuresome developers apparently see an
opportunity to bulldoze away the hill to create a valuable and desirable
building site,&quot; Dunn says.<BR>
<BR>
The adventurers, Dunn thinks, tend to be from out of town. At a recent meeting
in Las Vegas of the International Council of Shopping Centers, a group that
includes developers, property owners and retailers, Dunn was surprised to
see a developer promoting potential sites in the Pittsburgh market.<BR>
The developer, a Texas company, has tied down properties in the northern,
southern and western suburbs that - according to the company's brochure
- are ripe for development. &quot;Apparently, that company sees something
in our own backyard that most of the rest of us have not seen or have chosen
to ignore,&quot; Dunn says. <BR>
<BR>
That speaks to the vision - or lack thereof - of many long-established local
development firms, Dunn says, adding,&quot;Local developers here are very
conservative, even the biggest ones. We don't seem to have the energy or
the vision any longer to pursue many projects, particularly the more challenging
ones. We're focusing on our own properties, trying to keep them filled,
and not taking on new projects.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kossman Development, like all other local developers Dunn knows, will no
longer build an office or commercial building on speculation as they would
just a few years ago. &quot;We won't even think of breaking ground unless
we have a very firm commitment - and by that I mean a long-term commitment
in the form of a lease of at least 15 years from someone who will occupy
most of the building,&quot; he says. &quot;And the committed tenant must
have an impeccable credit rating. That's the way - the only way - we do
business in the 1990s.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Playing With Fire<BR>
</B><BR>
The reasons for such an approach are readily apparent. Banks, insurance
companies and other lenders have adopted extremely cautious - some say negative
- attitudes about lending money for commercial real estate development projects,
having been hit severely during the 1980s hell-bent-for-leather development
years. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They're saying 'no' and asking questions later,&quot; remarks the
head of one small local development company, who asked not to be identified
because he does not want to appear to be criticizing anyone he might approach
for a loan anytime soon. &quot;They're asking themselves, 'What would the
people who ran Westinghouse Credit do with this loan application?' and then
doing the opposite. And who can blame them?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Tight financing, along with labor and other operating costs that continue
to be high in comparison with surrounding areas and nearby states, has made
Pittsburgh &quot;a market that hasn't got growth built into it, it seems,&quot;
Kossman's Dunn says. &quot;Most people around here are taking a wait-and-see
attitude.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That is certainly the case when it comes to the development of new downtown
office space. Not only are locally based conservative developers shying
away from such projects, but the supposedly more adventuresome and wealthy
national firms are taking a pass on them as well. That is hardly likely
to change anytime soon, everyone contacted for this article agrees, and
certainly not before there is some vigorous upward movement in Class A rental
rates.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Given the current high construction and financing costs, any new Class
A space downtown would have to go for around $30 a square foot,&quot; says
Warren Kimball, president of Kimball Properties Inc. &quot;That is well
over the current market, which is at about the mid-20s. I don't see it happening
anytime soon. And that has nothing to do with being conservative. It's just
the reality.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
David Matter, president of Oxford Development Co., agrees. His company needs
that type of rental-rate breakthrough before it can proceed with the long-awaited
construction of Two Oxford Centre downtown, in what is now a parking lot
between One Oxford Centre and the City-County Building. <BR>
&quot;Nothing will happen until we begin to approach the $30 mark,&quot;
Matter says. <BR>
<BR>
Oxford and other local developers have several nonoffice commercial projects
underway or about to begin downtown, so things are far from being dead in
the water. But city development is downright sluggish compared to the suburbs.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The suburbs is where the action is,&quot; says Jim Scalo, president
of Burns &amp; Scalo Real Estate Group in Bridgeville. &quot;And local developers
are getting a big part of that action because we know the suburban markets.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The real growth potential for this region is in technology-driven
industries. They typically don't need to be in downtown Pittsburgh or downtown
anywhere. They don't want to be downtown. They want the campus-type settings
that we can offer in the suburbs. The people who work in these companies
are more interested in, say, playing Frisbee at lunchtime than going to
some fancy restaurant. And that's not only in this area but all across the
country.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Scalo says he does not worry   about big out-of-town firms coming   in and
picking up choice projects.      His biggest concern - and the     biggest
threat to local development efforts throughout the Pittsburgh region - is
about local conditions which have been allowed to deteriorate for years,
he says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What we have to address is our terrible infrastructure situation and
the civil wars being fought among groups and political forces over new road
construction. Some people are actually working to delay needed road- building
projects for politically selfish reasons, and that is an abomination.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;And we don't have a marketing plan for the entire nine-county region.
We have development agencies, which are supposed to be working to attract
businesses to the region, competing with each other rather than cooperating
and doing what's best for the entire region, not just one small segment
of it,&quot; he adds.<BR>
<BR>
The region is too fragmented politically to achieve reasonable    development
goals, Scalo says.       Some areas seem to have a definite anti-development
bias - and no clue as to what's needed to attract and   keep businesses.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Fortunately, there are pockets of the region where you can still get
things done,&quot; Scalo says. &quot;Washington County, for example, has
very proactive commissioners and a development authority that is very receptive
to new ideas and approaches. When we have that kind of atmosphere, we usually
end up being too busy working and developing projects to worry about out-of-towners
coming in and stealing jobs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Will local forces have the foresight to collaborate in a manner that has
the potential to strengthen themselves along with the region? <BR>
<BR>
Let's just say that for the present, hello Nordstrom and hello Alex Conroy.
		                     <BR>
