<B><FONT size=+2>The YWCA Kicks Off its Capital Campaign<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>From its beginning 129 years ago, the YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh
has focused on creating opportunities for women's growth and leadership.
The annals of the YWCA overflow with success stories of women it has helped
- women who have given back a hundred fold to their families and their communities.<BR>
<BR>
But the challenges facing today's YWCA and the women it serves are very
different than those of a century,  half-century, or even a decade ago.
Today's YWCA is addressing these changes as well as anticipating tomorrow's
challenges with energy and vitality - understanding that in change, there
is growth and opportunity.<BR>
<BR>
The YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh has forged a path of leadership, advocacy,
courage, compassion, action and results for the women of this community.
From counseling to child care, housing to job training, teen clubs to health
advocacy, the YWCA reinforces individual values and encourages women to
actively resolve their problems by setting and achieving goals.<BR>
<BR>
Today's YWCA serves tens of thousands of tots, teens, young women, baby-boomers
and seniors through a broad spectrum of diverse human services and educational,
social and recreational programs. The girls and women it serves are representative
of the diverse needs and cultures found in the urban mix that is Pittsburgh
and Allegheny County.<BR>
<BR>
The YWCA's commitment is simple, yet profound - &quot;To strive to create
opportunities for women's growth, leadership and power in order to eliminate
racism, and to facilitate a common vision: peace, justice, freedom and dignity
for all people.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Its success is clearly and forcibly demonstrated by all statistical measurement.
It is perhaps best calculated, however, by the number of women whose lives
have been changed forever because of today's YWCA.<BR>
<BR>
Today, the YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh's ability to continue to grow to meet
the changing needs of women faces some serious challenges. In response,
the YWCA has, for the first time in more than three decades, turned to the
community to support its efforts. The YWCA currently is conducting an $8.75
million capital      campaign - and is happy to report that almost 60 percent
of the goal already has been reached due to the generosity of Pittsburgh's
corporations, foundations and individuals who have consistently supported
the YWCA's programs.<BR>
<BR>
We sincerely hope that you will take the opportunity to learn more about
the YWCA and the campaign in the pages that follow. Above all, we hope you
will join those generous contributors in supporting this effort to assure
that one of Greater Pittsburgh's greatest and most vital assets remains
strong.<BR>
<BR>
Meeting today's challenges and strengthening the YWCA's people, programs
and facilities for the challenges we face in the future is what this campaign
is all about.<BR>
Thanks in advance for your generous support.<BR>
<BR>
	Florence Johnson                        	  <BR>
        Jane Roesch <BR>
Sandra J. McLaughlin <BR>
