<BR>
YWCA- The YWCA: For Today's Women <BR>
A Message from CEO Margaret Tyndall<BR>
<BR>
The need for a vibrant, dynamic organization that creates opportunities
for women's growth and leadership is as strong today as it was 129 years
ago when the YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh was started.<BR>
<BR>
Back then, the YWCA served young women flocking to the city for jobs. Those
were grueling times for women. Demeaning working conditions and low pay
devalued their lives. Through the YWCA they found a safe, nurturing place
to live. The YWCA educated those young women, cultivated moral values and
improved their lives as well as the fabric of their community.<BR>
<BR>
Today, the center of the YWCA's mission is empowerment. And while some of
the issues may have changed, the need for an organization like the YWCA
has not. Take a look at the world around us: the disparity between women's
income and men's income, racism scarring the lives of young people, violence
casting a dark shadow on their futures.<BR>
<BR>
The YWCA is deeply committed to meeting the needs of women, girls and their
families. More importantly, the YWCA recognized very early on that providing
services was not enough. We knew we had to attack the root causes of the
social problems that created the demand for our services. The YWCA's mission
is a rare blend of service to women and advocacy on issues affecting their
lives and futures.<BR>
<BR>
Our Bridge Housing, job training and child care programs address the most
urgent needs of women: a secure place to live, learning skills that lead
to productive employment at a decent wage, and providing support for mothers
trying to make their way in the world while raising a family. These programs
make a direct impact on the lives of young women.<BR>
<BR>
On a broader scale, the YWCA is a moral compass for the community, speaking
out firmly on the social ills that have created the need for our     services.
Foremost among these ills        is racism. It is a blight on our community.
It consumes so much energy      that could be channeled to more productive
uses. As women, we have experienced oppression and discrimination. This
experience helps us understand how racism dehumanizes both its victims and
its perpetrators. It has given us the firm resolve to eradicate racism wherever
it exists, by any means necessary.<BR>
<BR>
Our voter registration drive is another reflection of the YWCA's advocacy.
We are helping people, particularly those who historically have been disenfranchised,
to understand their responsibilities as citizens. The YWCA is empowering
these women to seize control of their own lives, to raise their voices on
pressing issues affecting their lives and the lives of their families.<BR>
<BR>
Today's YWCA, like the fledgling association that nourished young women
129 years ago, remains committed to giving women the tools and moral fiber
they need to lead productive lives This is our mission. It is reflected
in everything we do and say.                      <BR>
<BR>
Training, Inc. <BR>
and the Journey <BR>
to Self-Sufficiency<BR>
<BR>
Twenty-five year-old Tricia Wojtasiak was a welfare-dependent, single mother
of a five-year old daughter until she decided to break the cycle of dependency
that had ruled her life.<BR>
<BR>
That's when she enrolled in the YWCA's Training, Inc. program.<BR>
<BR>
The 22-week program gives unemployed or under-employed people a chance to
support themselves by training them for office careers. The training is
done at the downtown headquarters of the YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My mother was on welfare; I grew up on welfare. I didn't want my daughter
to grow up on welfare like I did,&quot; said Wojtasiak, who completed training
in April and was hired as a receptionist at the downtown law firm of Jones
Gregg Creehan and Gerace. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I love my job. It's great getting a paycheck. I've earned it - it's
not a handout. And I am glad to get off welfare,&quot; Wojtasiak said.<BR>
 <BR>
Wojtasiak was hired when another Training, Inc., graduate moved up the career
ladder. Peg Krainc, a 1988 graduate, left the firm in March after eight
years as a receptionist to work as judicial secretary for Judge Cynthia
Baldwin. Before leaving, she recommended that her replacement come from
Training, Inc.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I have good memories of Training, Inc., and how they help people get
on their feet. And, I knew they wouldn't recommend someone who was not qualified.
It was a way of paying them back - a way to say thanks,&quot; Krainc said.<BR>
<BR>
Krainc, now 42, used Training, Inc., as a springboard to the professional
world from the blue collar world she had known. She had grown bored with
the monotony of her letter-sorting job and worried about her future. She
wanted a better paying office job but lacked computer skills. Through Training,
Inc., she got &quot;a taste of everything&quot; from word processing to
data entry, mock interviews and dress codes.<BR>
<BR>
Krainc was one of the first         graduates of Training, Inc., which began
here in 1988. As a program of the YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh, Training,
Inc. is primarily funded through the Pittsburgh Partnership of the City
of Pittsburgh. In the eight years of the program, 76 percent of those graduating
have been placed in jobs and 83 percent are still working after one year.<BR>
<BR>
Shirley Mueller, manager of Training, Inc., said the program's long-term
success is due to the fact that it reshapes participants' lives.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's not just a training program. Our graduates are still working
because our program changes lives. If they lose their job, they don't go
back to their old ways. They get another job,&quot; Mueller said.<BR>
During the 22 weeks, trainees gain hands-on experience in a simulated office
setting. They get practical experience with office equipment and software
used in Pittsburgh's business community and learn business and management
skills through operating a fictitious corporation. Training includes typing,
word processing, data entry, filing, spreadsheets, customer service, business
communication, business ethics, career planning and goal setting skills.<BR>
<BR>
Most importantly, trainees develop confidence and self-sufficiency through
a positive attitude that includes rewards for every achievement, no matter
how small. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;When a person has been on welfare more than six months, they lose
their sense of self-worth and self-esteem. They don't see themselves as
making a positive contribution to society. They feel trapped and they are
trapped,&quot; Mueller said.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Through daily achievement and recognition of that achievement, they
come to believe in themselves. They renew their belief in themselves,&quot;
she said.<BR>
<BR>
Judith Burton, now 50, was at the lowest point in life when she turned to
Training, Inc. in 1992. Burton was forced to go on welfare in 1986 when
her husband of 16 years left her with three children and no child support.
Despite her extensive work experience in an office and as a supervisor,
Burton felt the job market had passed her by since she had quit working
to raise her family.<BR>
<BR>
Her life continued its downward spiral for the next six years.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Things changed so much in a few short years. Welfare kept us alive,
but to me it meant failure,&quot; Burton said. &quot;I had no confidence,
no self-esteem. I had nothing.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Training, Inc. proved to be Burton's lifeline. She learned new computer
skills and improved her typing. More importantly, Burton rediscovered herself.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They (Training, Inc. instructors) gave me back my life. They give
you a chance to improve everything about yourself and your life. My self-esteem
and confidence came back,&quot; Burton said.<BR>
The Training, Inc. staff continued to support Burton during her job search.
They helped her prepare a resume, taught her interviewing techniques and
provided moral support. After 162 applications and 75 second interviews,
Burton's determination paid off with a job with Allegheny County. Today
she is supervisor of inventory control and assistant to the deputy director.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's hard work, but it's heaven. You are in control of your own life
and your own destiny. And when you cash a check, it's not a handout - you've
earned it,&quot; Burton said.<BR>
<BR>
Thirty-five year-old Jane Davis also used Training, Inc. to get out of the
&quot;welfare trap.&quot; She was on welfare for two years when she enrolled
in the program in 1994. Her goal: to get off welfare and earn a good living
for herself and her son, now 11.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My goal was to get off welfare and stay off it for good. Welfare is
a trap. You get on and you have to make more than minimum wage to get off.
Without an education and skills, you get trapped. Training, Inc. gives you
credibility in writing that you have the skills,&quot; Davis said.<BR>
<BR>
Davis, who now works for a major Pittsburgh corporation, said Training,
Inc. changed her life for the better.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Work can be stressful, but it's a good stress. It feels good to be
working. Even if I won the lottery, I'd still work. And I know I'll never
go back on welfare,&quot; she said.                                    
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Something for Everyone<BR>
</B><BR>
Women striving for growth in their personal lives can look to the YWCA of
Greater Pittsburgh for a broad range of support and services. At the YWCA,
attention is focused on improving the economic condition and quality of
life of those served. YWCA programs and services give women greater self-confidence,
enabling them to take control of their lives.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Teen Programs<BR>
</B><BR>
Working with young women is the YWCA's highest priority. In 1995, more than
8,000 teenagers took part in   classes addressing dating, sexuality,   values
and setting limits. Over 500 teenage girls participated in after-school
teen clubs that helped them develop self-confidence and realize their assets.<BR>
 <BR>
Force, a new initiative launched in 1994, tackles the tough issue of gang
violence. The Fe-male OutReach Collaborative Effort provides outreach, case
management, information, referral, support and follow-up for young women
be-tween the ages of 10 and 25 who are involved in gang activities, violent
or self-destructive behavior.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Counseling Services<BR>
</B><BR>
The YWCA's Coun-seling Services help women address such problems as depression,
emotional abuse and addiction. Legal Resources for Women provides information,
referral and consultation services to women facing legal problems often
related to divorce, child custody, credit or sexual harassment.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Health Promotion<BR>
</B><BR>
The YWCA continues to offer affordable, accessible exercise programs for
women of all ages and their families. Encore Plus is a new program aimed
at the early detection of breast and cervical cancer. The YWCA also offers
post-mastectomy physical rehabilitation and psychological support services.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Employment Training<BR>
</B><BR>
Through YWCA employment services, women achieve economic independence by
increasing their employment opportunities. These programs serve women who
primarily are educationally disadvantaged, lacking work experience and who
are often long-term welfare dependent. The employment services provide basic
skills training and help build self-confidence, enabling participants to
enter the world of work. Additionally, parenting classes and quality child
care are provided for young mothers. These job training programs have a
75 percent placement rate for women completing the curriculum.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Child Care Services<BR>
</B><BR>
Another way the YWCA enables women and their families to achieve self-sufficiency
is by providing quality, affordable, accessible child care. The YWCA offers
a variety of day care    programs for children up to age 12, including pre-school,
before and     after school care, holiday care and  summer day camp. Child
Care Partnerships' resource and referral division provides a variety of
              services to help families obtain child care - including a
database with information on more than 700 licensed and registered child
care providers in 26 counties in Western Pennsylvania. The YWCA also manages
approximately 2,900 child care subsidies at any given time. Partners in
Caring offers training and support for child care providers, particularly
those offering care in their homes. And the YWCA offers technical assistance
to employers seeking to provide employee child care services. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Housing Services<BR>
</B><BR>
The YWCA's Bridge Housing provides shelter and support services to women
and children who are homeless as a result of domestic violence, drug abuse
or economic setbacks. The assistance they receive through counseling, parenting
education and referrals helps them achieve economic and emotional independence.
                                   <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Campaign for the YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh<BR>
</B><BR>
The YWCA's $8.75 million capital campaign will raise critically needed funds
to build a new Homewood-Brushton center, renovate its aging downtown facility
and expand programs for youth and job training.<BR>
<BR>
According to YWCA Chief Executive Officer Margaret Tyndall, Ph.D., the fundraising
initiative marks the organization's first capital campaign in over 30 years.
Nearly 60 percent of the goal has been raised to date.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh has reached a critical juncture in
its history. This fundraising effort is vital if we are to continue to respond
effectively to the challenge of change in the 21st century,&quot; Tyndall
says.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Homewood-Brushton Center: $2 Million</B><BR>
<BR>
The YWCA's Homewood Brush-ton Center serves a predominately African-American
community with a median household income just over $13,000. More than a
third of the population has not finished high school and 70 percent of the
households are headed by single women. The rate of teen pregnancy in the
area is among the highest in the country.<BR>
<BR>
The YWCA plans to build a two-story, 17,000 square-foot facility - four
times larger than the current center - on the same site at Frankstown Avenue
and East View Street. The new facility will allow the creation of a full-service
women's and family center, including: 
<UL>
  <LI>larger space and new technologies to improve job training and child
care capabilities and capacity; 
  <LI>the addition of new state-of-the-art computer technology for classrooms;
  <LI>well-designed and adequate recreational space for youth; and 
  <LI>accessibility for people with disabilities.
</UL>
<BR>
The new structure will increase by 50 percent the YWCA's ability to serve
area women and children through job training and child care. The expanded
facility also will allow the YWCA to offer a more comprehensive program
of counseling, information and referral, parent resource center, and teen
services to the girls and women of this area. It is this comprehensive approach
of today's YWCA which makes a difference in the live of those it serves.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Renovation of Downtown Flagship Program Center: $4.5 Million </B><BR>
<BR>
The capital campaign includes the first major alterations to the YWCA's
Wood Street headquarters since it opened in 1962. About 100,000 people -
slightly under 10 percent of the population of the Greater Pittsburgh area
- use the YWCA's downtown facility each year. The building was designed
to serve both as an administrative center for the five centers in Allegheny
County and as an activity center for the Pittsburgh community.<BR>
<BR>
Modernization and renovations will allow for enhanced services and programs.
The renovations also will allow the YWCA to incorporate the new technologies
now available to ensure modern delivery of services. Programatic needs to
be addressed include:
<UL>
  <LI>A Child Care Resource Center housing a library of materials for both
child care providers and parents. Today, the YWCA serves family daycare
providers, child care center staffs and more than 10,000 parents. Expansion
of the program will allow the YWCA to impact the lives of 15,000 children.
  <LI>Personal Counseling Center to provide private space for interaction
between staff and clients. The YWCA conducts more than 2,000 legal and personal
counseling sessions annually. About 75 percent of the women served in counseling
have annual incomes under $17,000.
  <LI>YWCA Teen Programs reach out to almost 10,000 adolescents annually.
The downtown facility's Teen Service Program Center will serve as a hub
for the YWCA's adolescent programming.
  <LI>Health Promotion Services always have been an important element of
the YWCA's mission. The health and fitness program, which for many is the
only affordable program in the area, is used thousands of times each month.
Improvements must be made to the facility's recreational and exercise programs.
Space reconfiguration also will allow expansion of the highly regarded breast
surgery survivor program, Encore, and Encore Plus, a new program aimed at
early detection of breast and cervical cancer.
  <LI>A Center for Collaboration will provide space for other women's organizations
- enabling the YWCA to work with them to promote services for women and
families. The YWCA has worked closely with these organizations, often acting
as an incubator for new programs.
</UL>
<BR>
<B>Widening the Doors of Opportunity: $2.25 Million</B><BR>
<BR>
Youth programs are among the most demanding, yet essential,      activities
of the YWCA. The YWCA's programs focus on enhancing          self-esteem,
building character and developing leadership skills among girls ages 10
to 15. Increased funding for this program will allow much needed growth.<BR>
<BR>
Job training programs are at       the very core of efforts to bring training-disadvantaged
women into the workforce. The YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh currently serves
155 women per year in its programs, but there is overwhelming demand   
       for expansion. Welfare reform will   create the need to move thousands
of women into work activities. The YWCA is committed to assisting with that
transition.      <BR>
