<A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H4Editor.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Congressional Power </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>The Debate Should Not Be How Much,<BR>
But Rather How it is Used</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR>When Alfonso Lopez Jr. carried a .38-caliber revolver and five bullets
into his Texas high school in 1992, I'm sure he never dreamed that he was
about to set in motion a debate over how much power Congress should wield.<BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, Alfonso did just that. Caught with the gun, the teenager appropriately
was charged by San Antonio authorities with a firearms violation. The state
charges were dropped the next day, when federal prosecutors took over the
case, charging Alfonso with violating a relatively new federal law: the
Gun-Free School Zones Act.<BR>
<BR>
Lopez was convicted, but won a reprieve last year when a deeply divided
Supreme Court reviewed his case and in a 5-4 decision struck down the Gun-Free
School Zones Act as being unconstitutional. The majority's reasoning was
simple: Congress - whose power to regulate is limited by the constitution
- had overstepped its bounds.<BR>
<BR>
Congressional power to regulate, in part, rests in the commerce clause of
the constitution, which simply states that Congress can regulate commerce
among the states. From the 1930s until Alfonso Lopez's case, that power
for the most part had been absolute. If Congress wanted to regulate something,
it regulated it, citing the link to interstate commerce. Some examples of
commerce clause-based legislation: Congress criminalized carjacking, domestic
violence, arson and the failure to pay child support, all of which already
had been criminalized by many of the individual states. Some businesses
also felt the reach of Congress when it used the commerce clause to prohibit
wetlands destruction.<BR>
<BR>
I have no problem with a federal law punishing those who bring a gun into
a school or steal a car at gunpoint, except for the fact that many states
already have similar laws enacted. That begs the question: When Congress
passed the Gun-Free School Zones Act or the carjacking law, was the intent
to get guns out of schools or protect drivers? Or was it to allow the politicians
who supported the law to position themselves as being tough on crime?<BR>
<BR>
It's most likely the latter. And who loses? We do.<BR>
<BR>
All those civil lawsuits pending in federal court are pushed back a few
more months because the federal judiciary must give priority to the Alfonso
Lopezes of the world who are dragged into the federal system by our &quot;tough-on-crime&quot;
Congress. After all, the same constitution that gives Congress the power
to regulate interstate commerce also gives criminal defendants like Lopez
the right to a speedy trial. Civil cases get pushed back.<BR>
<BR>
And that brings me to my point: Perhaps this debate Alfonso Lopez triggered
should not be over the extent of Congressional power and the Supreme Court's
interpretation of that power. Rather, the public should instead keep one
eye on how Congress uses its power. <BR>
<BR>
Right now, Congress is using its commerce clause power to push through tort
reform, which from a business standpoint is good. Give Congress credit for
seizing on that power to remedy a problem. Every business benefits from
tort reform.<BR>
<BR>
But let's not be misled the next time Congress pushes through duplicative
legislation like the Gun-Free School Zones Act. It amounts to political
grandstanding and good sound bytes at election time. It's not an effective
use of the power our constitutional drafters bestowed upon Congress.<BR>
<BR>
It's an abuse of power, and we should recognize it for what it is.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
