<P><B><IMG SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Quiet Courage<BR>
Our Pages Reflect Her Dedication</FONT SIZE> <FONT size=+1></FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher <br clear=all></I></B><HR>For decades,
business defined model employees as devoted and proficient individuals who
consistently exceed expectations, setting the pace for others to follow.
These employees are generally reliable to a fault and pursue excellence
with a vengeance.  Customer service and independent problem-solving come
instinctively to them. They are as rare and as precious as the historical
artifacts housed in the splendid new Senator John Heinz Pittsburgh Regional
History Center.<BR>
<BR>
Over the years, the intense demands of burgeoning global competition expanded
the definition of &quot;model employee.&quot; Today, such employees generally
also are technologically proficient individuals. Experts in communications,
they've refined relationship-building to an art form.<BR>
<BR>
At Executive Report, I recently adopted a more succinct definition. To all
of our staff, the name Jackie Priddy is synonymous with model employee.<BR>
<BR>
Jackie brought all of the characteristics of the exemplary employee to her
job and more. She juggled billing, collections, phone answering and typing,
while masterminding the magazine's circulation system. And, she cheerfully
handled these multiple priorities gracefully and flawlessly.<BR>
<BR>
April 16, 1996, was a ferociously sad day at Executive Report. This was
the day that Jackie lost her two-year battle with cancer. This was also
the day that the magazine lost part of its soul.<BR>
<BR>
Jackie's infectious can-do attitude was the infrastructure upon which Executive
Report built its successes. Serving as the gateway to the magazine, she
greeted all with aplomb. The sparkle in her voice and in her work energized
our organization daily. Jackie's invincible spirit permeated the company,
inspiring everyone to reach for broader horizons.<BR>
<BR>
Most truly great individuals never grace the pages of a history book. Instead,
they persevere only to claim their place in anonymity.<BR>
<BR>
Although Jackie's hard work and dedication won't feature prominently in
history textbooks, the pages of Executive Report will always reflect her.
By elevating the standards of performance at the magazine, Jackie made an
indelible mark in the magazine's annals.<BR>
<BR>
She added quiet courage to our definition of model employee, and she will
continue to inspire us to realize our fullest potential. That's the modern-day
version of exemplary.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
