<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H5Guest.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Seniority Rules</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>It's Time We Recognize Our Large</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Elderly Population as a Resource, Not a Liability</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Michael C. Hendrickson</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P>Yhere was a story on a local television station a few months ago that
dealt with the progress being made in the treatment and possible cure of
Alzheimer's disease.<BR>
 <BR>
Towards the end of the segment the newscaster solemnly informed the audience
that &quot;Allegheny County now has the second-highest number of residents
over the age of 65, trailing only Dade County, Fla.,&quot; the implication
seeming to be that our region is in danger of being overrun with forgetful,
disoriented, wheezing elderly men and women.<BR>
<BR>
There are magic numbers and milestones in all our lives.  Age 30 - time
to settle down, raise a family. Forty - time to slow down a little and enjoy
life, then 50 - half a century! <BR>
<BR>
The age of 65 has in many cases signaled the end of one's professional life
in the way of employment. There is a pervasive theory in society today that
being productive is synonymous with being gainfully employed and if you're
not gainfully employed, then you must be poor and/or a drain on our resources.
<BR>
<BR>
Gerontologists and sociologists have coined the term &quot;ageism&quot;
to connote a negative stereotyping of older adults and aging in general,
with 65 being a general barometer of being &quot;old.&quot; This approach
to aging is not only unfortunate, it's also inaccurate in light of some
basic facts.  <BR>
<BR>
Allegheny County is proof there is successful aging in this country - less
than 5 percent of our residents over the age of 65 are in nursing home settings.
Nationally, more than two-thirds of those over 65 are independent, as is
half the population over 85. Locally, 75 to 80 percent are moderate to middle
income spenders and have nearly twice the disposable income of those aged
20 to 35, making them a very strong consumer force.  <BR>
<BR>
But the fact is, this age group brings more to our quality of life than
can be determined in dollars and cents. How can we begin to measure the
   benefits provided by thousands of    volunteers - most over 65 - in 
  organizations such as the United Way and Meals on Wheels, not to mention
a plethora of libraries, churches, hospitals, nursing homes, foundations
and other social support agencies? <BR>
<BR>
Western Pennsylvania's broad-based volunteerism allows society to extend
certain benefits to the less fortunate. Not to mention the level of satisfaction,
well-being and quality of life that can only be described by someone who
has been a volunteer. <BR>
<BR>
Some demographic experts have even suggested that Pittsburgh's relatively
low crime rate is partially due to our large contingency of elderly residents.
<BR>
  <BR>
There are many areas where age isn't an issue. Seniors have been recognized
for their inspiration, creativity and leadership in fields such as the arts,
literature, music, healthcare, education, scientific study and sports. In
our region, contributions made by Pittsburghers in their later years are
too numerous to list. <BR>
     <BR>
And there is still tremendous room for growth for additional opportunities
to utilize the skills and talents of those aged 65 and over. Those of us
in progressive geriatric healthcare systems have suggested this population
could perhaps be utilized to solve some of our society's more pressing problems,
such as day care and illiteracy. Many geriatric systems have developed mentoring
programs with local schools to help bridge generational gaps. <BR>
<BR>
The concept of reintegrating older adults into the societal framework to
share their vast wisdom, experience and knowledge with younger individuals
benefits society at large and can begin to dispel some of the misguided
myths of aging. <BR>
<BR>
Seniors today continue to have opportunities to be pioneers in all walks
of life. They have had many life experiences - good and bad - that we can
draw from. All they need in many instances is an avenue to share their time
and talents, which might be the role of a volunteer, consultant, coach -
or just a friend.<BR>
<BR>
Perhaps those who view our elderly population as a necessary inevitability
do so because they have realized their own life is temporal, it is finite,
there will be an end some day. But those who have reached this age are repositories
of important information about how to live as well as age successfully.<BR>
<BR>
As such, they are extremely well-equipped to be role models and mentors
to a growing number of young people who are desperately trying to find leaders
to emulate.                          <BR>
                                <BR>
Michael C. Hendrickson is president and chief executive officer of Lutheran
Affiliated Services in Cranberry Township.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
