"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><BR>
<B>LAUGHING MATTERS</B><BR>
<BR>
Got problems? Employees disgruntled? Production down? Stress levels rising?
Here's an idea: lighten up and laugh a little.<BR>
<BR>
That's advice from Ron Cichowicz and Ken Service, a pair who could be called
the &quot;chuckling communicators.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Cichowicz, who for years handled public relations for the Catholic Diocese
of Pittsburgh, and Service, director of communications for the University
of Pittsburgh, have devoted years of study to the benefits of a little laughter.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My personal belief, both as a writer and just as a person, is that
humor is critical in our lives,&quot; says Cichowicz. &quot;I've got research
that shows that two-thirds of illnesses in people under the age of 65 are
stress-related. Ten minutes of laughter can produce two hours of restful
sleep that night.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The two have been friends for 20 years and enjoy collaborating on projects
like speaking engagements for organizations. The International Association
of Business Communicators sponsored the two for a talk May 7 about how frivolity
can improve life. Both are dedicated humorists in their own rights; Cichowicz
writes a regular humor column for Hospital News and has written two books
of witticisms, while Service pens a humor column in a new monthly publication,
Higher Education News.<BR>
<BR>
Cichowicz collects research on the topic of humor as it relates both to
personal life and to organizations like corporations. Study after study,
he says, demonstrates the benefits <BR>
of applying humor to the workplace as well as the home. <BR>
<BR>
Cichowicz says that beyond the physical benefits to individuals (less stress,
less illness, even burned calories), humor can help companies by improving
teamwork, creativity and morale, diffusing tension and creating communication.
The direct results are impressive.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Digital Equipment Company in Colorado Springs incorporated a humor
program at their office. Productivity rose 15 percent, and sick days were
cut in half,&quot; he says. It may be as simple as employees posting cartoons
on their doors or in interoffice memos. One company kept a set of foam rubber
balls in the conference room to be thrown at cynics in meetings. CEOs can
set the tone for their company by injecting a little humor into speeches
and internal newsletters. <BR>
<BR>
Service says the key is taking a sideways look at life, stepping back for
a little light-hearted <BR>
reflection on the inconsistencies of the world. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Self-effacing humor is good,&quot; he says, &quot;and doesn't risk
offending others or descending into tastelessness.&quot; Looking at the
funny side of things, he says, might even help find serious solutions. <BR>
<BR>
There's even help for the comically impaired: It is actually possible to
teach someone to be humorous. Cichowicz says with practice, one can develop
a knack for organizational humor.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you've ever laughed at anything since you became an adult, you've
got a sense of humor,&quot; he says.                      <BR>
<BR>
<B>ZOO LOOKS TO YOU FOR NEW REVENUE<BR>
</B><BR>
The Pittsburgh Zoo is at it again. In April's issue, ER detailed the zoo's
rise from the ashes of governmental stagnation by privatization. Now the
zoo has joined forces to create the Pennsylvania Zoological Council and
produce the council's first brainchild, the &quot;Save Wild Animals&quot;
license plate.<BR>
The Zoological Council was formed to market, lobby and raise funds for Pennsylvania's
four American Zoological Society accredited parks, including Pittsburgh's
zoo, the Philadelphia Zoo, the Erie Zoo and the National Aviary here in
Pittsburgh. On the council are the directors of the four institutions: Barbara
Baker of Pittsburgh, Pete Hoskins from Philadelphia, Jim Rhea of Erie and
Dayton Baker from the National Aviary. It was Dayton Baker (also Pittsburgh
Zoo director Barbara Baker's husband) who dreamed up the plates and pushed
the project from design through Harrisburg's approval. <BR>
<BR>
It took back and forth negotiations between the council and PennDot to finalize
the project. But the final slogan and the image, a tiger and her cub, were
judged to be the most instantly recognizable and emotionally appealing from
among the designs submitted.  The plates went into production in April.
<BR>
<BR>
Each attention-grabbing $35 plate will garner $3.75 for the Pittsburgh Zoo.
Pennsylvania vehicle registration renewal packets will contain applications
for the plate; the Pittsburgh Zoo also has applications, and AABCO Notary
Service on Frankstown Road can issue a plate on the spot.<BR>
<BR>
The Pittsburgh Zoo will use the revenue to partly fund the Kids Kingdom's
Discovery Pavilion, set to open in May 1997. The Aviary plans on putting
its share to work in its conservation projects, including both care of rare
birds here and research and planning projects worldwide.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SPENDING RETIREMENT DOLLARS ... ON THE GRANDKIDS<BR>
<BR>
</B><BR>
If you think our region's large (300,000 plus) elderly population is a drawback,
talk to Leslie Hughan. She'll set you straight.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'd say of the very elaborate cruises, to the Far East and so on,
90 percent are for the 60 and over market,&quot; says Hughan, an Ambassador
Travel Service agent. &quot;They can afford it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Doug Mato of Around the World Travel in Greentree says there's lots of money
in the &quot;mature&quot; market, and it's only going to get better as the
senior population grows.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They do more getaways, they've got the time and the money,&quot; he
says. Many of their older customers take several vacations each year. Even
though there are travel groups that cater extensively to seniors, he thinks,
&quot;It's really an untapped market.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Retirement used to be just a prelude to death, but now we live 20-plus
years after. People ought to think of their later years in terms of how
they want to be productive,&quot; says Jim Denova. As director of Vintage,
a senior citizens' center in East Liberty, he advocates looking at senior
citizens as an asset ... and an opportunity.<BR>
<BR>
Ken Dychtwald, president of Age Wave Inc., has been researching &quot;social
gerontology&quot; for years with amazing results. Senior citizens nationwide
command some 70 percent our nation's net worth, and contrary to popular
belief, they aren't afraid to spend it.  In fact, they account for 40 percent
of total consumer demand. Seniors (over age 50), for example, are the No.
1 spenders on children's retail clothing. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Grandparents are always in here shopping,&quot; says Jacque Stuckert,
manager of Gap Kids clothing in Shadyside. &quot;They always come in and
buy and have us send out the clothes to their grandkids. They like the convenience.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Seniors also purchase 80 percent of all luxury travel, 37 percent of spa
memberships, and watch more television than any other age group.<BR>
<BR>
Considering this state of affairs, Denova believes Pittsburgh may well be
sitting on a Methuselan gold mine. He says few businesses in the area effectively
cater to one of its largest markets because of misconceptions about senior
citizens' financial situations. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Baby boomers are turning 50 this year, and they're going to push the
threshold of aging up. Fifty doesn't mean 'Senior Club,' &quot; says Denova.
&quot;They don't see themselves that way.&quot; Combine the boomer attitudes
with their sheer numbers and the assets they command, he says, and our nation's
concept of senior citizens is going to change very soon. <BR>
<BR>
He suggests a couple of industries that could benefit substantially from
the &quot;maturity bloom.&quot; Health clubs, for one. Insurance companies
are taking advantage of the increased amount of time people are healthy
and active, realizing their business will benefit from encouraging seniors
to be active.<BR>
 <BR>
    Modern Maturity offers some specific tips on marketing to the older
set in a special report, &quot;Mature America in the 1990s.&quot; The report
outlines preferences among the &quot;50-plus&quot; for almost every consumer
category - what they think about the environment, their health, what kinds
of cars they buy, and the marketing they respond to. They even publish a
small booklet entitled &quot;How to Advertise to Maturity.&quot; Some tidbits
of advice: <BR>
<BR>
 Furnish evidence like studies, ingredients and warranties. Older adults
take time to analyze their purchases. Samples and trial periods are good
strategies for the same reason.<BR>
<BR>
 Depict them with a whole range of people, not just in groups of elderly.<BR>
<BR>
 Acknowledge the fact that retirement means more time for leisure and romance,
not the end of life.<BR>
Other sources of information include the AARP Research Infor-mation Center,
American Demo-graphics magazine, and Age Wave in Emeryville, Calif.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>MANAGED CARE FOR THE MASSES</B><BR>
<BR>
Managed care's going mainstream - and that means a whole new lingo to learn.
Here are some terms you may need to learn to play (see our cover story:
Managing Managed Care  on page 18): <BR>
 <BR>
Capitation: A method of paying for medical services on a per-person rather
than a per-procedure basis. Under capitation, an HMO pays a participating
doctor a fixed amount per month for every HMO member he or she takes care
of, regardless of how much or how little care the member receives.<BR>
<BR>
Copayment: A fixed payment the member pays (usually in the $5 to $25 range)
each time he or she visits a clinician or receives a covered service.<BR>
<BR>
Deductible: In traditional insurance and POS plans, a fixed amount the patient
pays each year before the insurer will begin covering the cost of care.<BR>
<BR>
Health Maintenance Organization (HMO): An organization providing healthcare
in return for pre-set monthly payments. Most HMOs provide care through a
network of doctors, hospitals and other medical professionals that their
members must use in order to be covered for that care.<BR>
<BR>
HMO Model Types: HMOs generally come in two different &quot;models&quot;:<BR>
<BR>
1. Staff Model HMO: A type of HMO in  which doctors and other medical professionals
are salaried employees of the HMO, and work in clinics or health centers
owned by the HMO.<BR>
<BR>
2. Group Model HMO: An HMO made up of one or more physician group practices
not owned by the HMO, but operating as independent partnerships or professional
corporations. The HMO pays the groups at a negotiated rate, and each group
is responsible for paying its doctors, other staff, hospital care and care
from outside specialists.<BR>
<BR>
Independent Practice Association (IPA): IPAs generally include large numbers
of individual private practice physicians who are paid either a fee or a
fixed amount per patient to take care of the IPA's members.<BR>
<BR>
Mixed-Model HMO: A health plan that includes more than one form of HMO within
a single plan. For instance, a staff model HMO might also contract with
independent physician groups or individual private practice physicians.<BR>
<BR>
Managed Care Organization: An umbrella term for HMOs and all health plans
that provide health care in return for pre-set monthly payments and coordinate
care through a defined network of primary care physicians and hospitals.<BR>
<BR>
Network: The doctors, clinics, health centers, medical group practices,
hospitals and other providers that an HMO, PPO or other managed care plan
selects and contracts with to care for its members.<BR>
Out-of-Network: Not in the HMO's network of selected and approved doctors
and hospitals. HMO members who get care out-of-network (sometimes called
out-of-area) without getting permission from the HMO to do so may have to
pay for all or most of that care themselves. Exceptions are usually made
for extreme emergencies or urgent care needed when traveling away from home.<BR>
Point-of-Service (POS) Plan: A type of HMO coverage that allows members
to choose to receive services either from participating HMO providers, or
from providers outside the HMO's network. In-network care is more likely
to be fully covered; for out-of-network care, members pay deductibles and
a percentage of the cost of care, much like traditional health insurance
coverage.<BR>
Practice Guidelines: Carefully developed information on diagnosing and treating
specific medical conditions. Practice guidelines, usually based on clinical
literature and expert consensus, are designed to help physicians and patients
make decisions, and to help a health plan evaluate appropriateness and medical
necessity of care.<BR>
<BR>
Preferred Provider Organization (PPO): A network of doctors and hospitals
that provides care at a lower cost than traditional insurance. PPO members
get better benefits (more coverage) when they use the PPO's network, and
pay higher out-of-pocket costs when they receive care outside the PPO network.<BR>
<BR>
Preventive care: Care designed to prevent disease altogether, to detect
and treat it early, or to manage its course most effectively. Examples of
preventive care include immunizations and regular screenings like Pap smears
or cholesterol checks.<BR>
<BR>
Primary Care: Preventive health care and routine medical care that is typically
provided by a doctor trained in internal medicine, pediatrics or family
practice, or by a nurse, nurse practitioner or physician's assistant.<BR>
<BR>
Primary Care Physician: A physician, usually an internist, pediatrician
or family physician, devoted to general medical care of patients. Most HMOs
require members to choose a primary care physician, who is then expected
to provide or authorize all care for that patient.<BR>
<BR>
Referral: A formal process that authorizes an HMO member to get care from
a specialist or hospital. To ensure coverage, an HMO patient generally must
get a referral from his or her primary care physician before seeing a specialist.<BR>
<BR>
Specialist: A doctor or other health professional whose training and expertise
are in a specific area of medicine, like cardiology or dermatology. Most
HMOs require members to get a referral from their primary care physician
before seeing a specialist.<BR>
<BR>
Treatment Protocols: Practice guidelines for treating specific medical conditions.<BR>
<BR>
Glossary adapted from the National Committee on Quality Assurance Guide
for Consumers.<BR>
	                                 <BR>
