<HEAD>
    <TITLE>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.People.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Numbers Game</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>The Democrats Bash Ridge for Job Losses,<BR>
But Whose Story Can You Really Believe? </FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>Not too many images spell more trouble for politicians than laid-off
workers walking out the gates of a plant slated for shutdown. Lost jobs,
whether due to companies' laying workers off or  deciding to expand elsewhere,
don't help anyone trying to foster economic growth.<BR>
<BR>
And while building the excitement over the prospect of new jobs often is
left to press secretaries  - usually new plants and expanded businesses
are still intangibles when announced - the disappointment at the opposite
is generally public domain. The faces of blue-collar workers losing their
jobs make great TV, and the newly unemployed often provide stinging quotes.<BR>
<BR>
Gov. Tom Ridge, who made job creation a part of his economic program for
the state, has had his share of well-noticed job departures from Pennsylvania
in the first 18 months of his term.<BR>
<BR>
 Economic bad news, when it hits in different parts of the state, compounds
the black eyes Ridge suffered for signing off on a legislative pay raise
last year and calling for an increased gasoline tax earlier this year.<BR>
<BR>
This spring, Caterpillar Inc. announced it would close a parts plant in
York, eliminating 1,100 jobs. That closing gave Democrats in Harrisburg
the cue to tally the lost jobs they attribute to Ridge. They counted almost
25,000.<BR>
<BR>
The Democrats include in  their  tally 1,500 banking jobs at Integra following
its acquisition by National City and 225 Westinghouse Electric jobs cut
in restructuring. A <BR>
Keystone Coal mine closing in Armstrong County added 350 jobs to the list.
And Democrats say a strike at Industrial Ceramics Inc. in Westmore-land
County cost 219 jobs.<BR>
<BR>
The total includes jobs lost for a wide range of reasons - factors as diverse
as restructuring, downsizing, acquisitions and military base closings. 
Two of the largest hits the Democrats pointed out were jobs lost because
of Pentagon cuts - 1,700 jobs lost at a Boeing helicopter plant in Delaware
County and 2,100 jobs lost when the Philadelphia Naval Shipyard closed -
both decisions of the federal government. It may be a stretch to blame Ridge
for the lost Navy jobs, but they're on the list anyway.<BR>
<BR>
Those kinds of calculations anger Ridge's staff. Spokesman Tim Reeves says
the Democrats shouldn't count job losses that Ridge had no control over
and should count the jobs that have been created with his help. Reeves points
to 1,200 PNC Bank jobs, for instance, that were close to going to New Jersey
but remain in Philadelphia. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In an economy the size of Pennsylvania's, in the healthiest, most
robust times, there are companies that close and companies that relocate,&quot;
Reeves says. &quot;The key is the net effect.&quot;<BR>
Reeves says unemployment figures showed a gain of about 28,000 jobs in roughly
the governor's first 12 months in office and a jobless rate at its lowest
point in the state since 1991.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is not picking and choosing the facts,&quot; he says. &quot;This
is the barometer we have always used.&quot;<BR>
PNC Bank regional economist Paul Flora says both Ridge and the Democrats
seem to be reading too much into the events of the last year. Not a lot
of what happens in the economy under a particular political administration
can be traced to its actions, he says. More often, events were set in motion
years earlier.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, factors under the control of the federal government - such
as fiscal and monetary policy - have a much larger impact on state economies,
Flora says. Typical initiatives of state governments, chiefly tax and regulatory
incentives, take more time to produce effects.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In general, I guess I've disagreed with both the sitting governor
and his Democratic opponents,&quot; Flora says.&quot;He can neither take
credit nor be blamed.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Flora's figures, which measure job growth from December 1994 - just before
Ridge took office - to the following December, show an increase of about
10,000 jobs. The numbers showed national job creation for the year proceeding
at a slightly lower rate. <BR>
<BR>
To the Ridge administration, the criticism from Democrats amounts to the
product of a &quot;bad news magnet,&quot; Reeves says. The number of new
jobs created tell the true story, he said.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If one is an incident and two is a trend,&quot; he says, &quot;we're
way past a trend here.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
