<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H10People.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>James Treher</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: James Treher<BR>
Age: 67<BR>
Personal: Married, he and wife Barbara live in the South Hills.<BR>
Daughter Adrienne works with CII; son James Jr. is a <BR>
Pittsburgh based FBI agent.<BR>
Education: BA, Political Science, Duquesne University, 1952<BR>
Public Administration/Psychology<BR>
Last Book Read: Code Name Downfall, The Secret Plan to<BR>
Invade Japan, by Thomas Allen <BR>
</B><HR>The FBI? Scotland Yard? Criminal intelligence? How does this impact
my business? Ask Jim Treher. Sixteen years ago, Treher retired from the
FBI after 25 years of service. But he got bored and - tired of being in
his wife's way - started Corporate Investigations Inc. with a fellow former
FBI employee (guess they just can't sit still). The advent of multimillion-dollar
negligent hiring settlements made their timing perfect. <BR>
<BR>
The now 10-year-old company practices its own brand of corporate preventive
care, screening potential employees for corporate clients the world over.
Treher deploys his considerable knowledge to do everything from a simple
department of motor vehicles check to thorough background investigations,
making sure that the candidate has given the company the correct information
about his or her situation.<BR>
 <BR>
It's amazing (and a little frightening) just how much information can be
gleaned legally - if you know where to look. Well, Jim Treher does. Lydia
Strohl talked to him in his Scott Township office.<BR>
 <BR>
Executive Report: Tell us about Corporate Investigations Inc.<BR>
<BR>
Jim Treher: I retired from 25 years in the FBI 16 years ago, as an agent.
I was in San Francisco, Detroit, New Orleans, Pittsburgh, in [former FBI
Director J. Edgar] Hoover's office, and was a staff instructor at the FBI
academy. I came back to Pittsburgh and retired and directed the county police
department for three years.<BR>
<BR>
Ten years ago I started this business with one employee and an office half
the size of this one. In 10 years, we've grown to 25 employees and are probably
one of the leading companies in spite of our size. We're now on our third
generation of computer operation - we have a lot of innovative ideas. <BR>
<BR>
We're up against some giants, like Burns and Pinkerton, and others, but
their piece of the corporate pie that is background investigation is not
much bigger. It's a highly competitive field. <BR>
<BR>
We now have a service called Corp Net, everything that's found is immediately
entered into the computer.  Clients can check via their computer.<BR>
<BR>
The other thing that we have that is unique is that I still have all the
old FBI contacts all over the world. We also have a division of linguistics,
people who can speak and write Russian, German, French, Spanish. We do a
lot in the West Indies and South America, the former USSR, China, Canada,
Israel, all over Europe.<BR>
<BR>
Ninety-nine percent of the work is background investigations -  do one thing
and do it well, and you can do it better than anybody else.<BR>
<BR>
ER: How big is the background investigation industry?<BR>
<BR>
JT: I can't answer that, but it's growing daily. Ten years ago, there were
only a handful of companies doing it, and then the legal profession discovered
what they term 'negligent hiring.' <BR>
<BR>
I'll give you a good example: A transportation firm in Texas, they provide
taxicabs, buses for the disabled. They hired a driver and didn't do any
kind of background investigation at all. He wasn't there six months before
he had brutally raped a woman, in front of her sub-teenage daughters. This
guy had a string of sex crimes as long as your arm. The victim sued the
company for negligent hiring, and they were found guilty. The judge leveled
a penalty of $2.7 million in actual damages. Then he added another $1 million
in punitive damages for what he called deliberate neglect.<BR>
So companies can't afford not to do this, like you can't afford not to have
liability insurance. And the fact is, for an entry level job, let's say
$20,000, it costs one-half of one percent for a background investigation.
When you consider all the jeopardy: You're going to bring someone in, they're
going to know the company's competitors, resources, procedures. What if
this guy is capable of selling out? What if you've got a gambler, a heavy
drinker? You can't go on what people say on their resumes. If you hire someone
who says 'Yes, I have all the qualifications,' or 'I have a master's degree,'
and it takes you a lot of money to recruit them, then to go through the
hiring process, then you put them on the job for six months before they
find their way around, and you find this person's grievously unprepared,
they can't do the job. Now you've got to start that all over. Where for
$200 you could have had the whole thing.<BR>
<BR>
ER: What do you look at?<BR>
<BR>
JT: We have three levels. The lowest level we suggest is rudimentary - criminal
and credit and past employment, DMV for a driver, or if you pay them mileage
for their automobile, you would be held liable. That would be for  a basic
laborer in the shop or the office. For people in positions that are more
critical, we would want to check or confirm the degree or certification
and the level. Then we would want to talk to references, and more importantly,
developed references, because obviously, everyone gives their best friend
for a reference. We have a whole list of questions. One of which is does
he have any debilitating habits, how much does he drink, is it a problem?
And the outsider is more apt to answer those questions.<BR>
<BR>
We develop references generally by asking. If they're just out of school,
we'll ask the department head if he had any close friends. Or the reference,
by asking, who else did you play ball with? But one thing that I am absolutely
a bug on is we don't ask one applicant one set of questions and another
one a different set. I would not want to go into an adversarial situation
in court and the judge say, 'How come you have three pages of information
on this person and only one on this person?' I have applied all the structures
and tried-and-true procedures that we used in the FBI. Remember, we're dealing
with people's lives, and if we come up with something wrong, and they don't
get a job, we've affected them. <BR>
<BR>
We may want to look into bankruptcy or their general business ability. Some
people say, 'I don't care whether they pay their bills or not - why should
I do a credit check on some guy that's out there moving boxes around?' Well
the reason is that a credit profile is a pretty good profile of an individual's
maturity and dependability. If they can't pay their bills, if it's a consistent
pattern, they're not the kind of person I'd like to have working for me.
Plus the person that can't pay their bills may be a gambler, may be sniffing
nose candy or may be just a compulsive drinker who spends too much money.<BR>
<BR>
One of our clients is the biggest pharmaceutical company in the world. They
built a research facility down in the southern states a few years back.
 They produce pharmaceuticals that you could literally put under your tongue
or down your shoe that have a street value of $500 or $600. Because of the
cost and the susceptibility of what they manufacture to theft, they projected
that they would have a 12 percent theft loss rate. <BR>
<BR>
When 1,400 people were to be hired, we did background investigations on
everybody. We had about a 22 or 23 percent question rate. And that means
serious questions - bad credit, criminal conviction background, bad driving,
bad employment record. The first quarter of the operation they had a zero
loss rate. They were delighted, and I said, 'Well, we got rid of a quarter
of the people that would have been problems - drinkers, thieves, the poor
credit risks.'<BR>
<BR>
That's another one of the reasons for the necessity of a background investigation.
Retail credit theft, for instance, runs about 40 percent of their loss.
They think it's the shoplifters. Shoplifters don't take nearly as much as
their own employees. They have the opportunity; they know how to do it.
<BR>
One thing that bothers me is we haven't been able to make any inroads in
the health profession. And there is absolutely no enterprise that I can
think of where there is more opportunity for grief than hospitals. They
say they can't afford it: If you hire someone with no background investigation,
they have access to hospital narcotics, they're in the rooms of people who
are susceptible to assault of all kinds, they can steal the patients' and
visitors' stuff. Another one is the airlines. What the airlines lose in
theft of baggage is just incredible. They just fire people and shut up about
it. <BR>
<BR>
ER: What's the most intense check that you would do?<BR>
<BR>
JT: That would be level three. The basic things, and then some. We go into
Nexis/Lexis, to see what kind of publicity there might have been. We're
going to check every company they've worked for to make sure that the company
really exists and they really worked there. Another thing a lot of people
have misapprehension about is if there is no state record. But they could
have been involved in a kidnapping, or bank robbery; those federal crimes
are not in state records. So we check the federal criminal docket and the
civil docket. We're going to check on the county level. We're going to check
net worth - how many homes or boats or airplanes. Even that is seldom more
than about $500, for a cradle to grave search.<BR>
<BR>
ER: How do you find out what people own?<BR>
<BR>
JT: It's all a matter of tax records. There are data banks. You can find
out a lot about a person legally and properly. A lot of the civil libertarians
worry about that, but I don't. If people are too concerned about what other
people can find out about them, they probably have something to hide.<BR>
<BR>
ER: What percentage of investigations turn something up that causes a candidate
not to get a job?<BR>
<BR>
JT: Between 20 and 25 percent. And these are serious contradictions or questions.
We don't make any recommendations - all we say is that we find no problem
or it's questionable. You make your decision. It's a judgment call. If someone's
been convicted of a felony, and you can't count arrest - legally you can
only go back seven years - you've paid your fine or your time and they haven't
done anything since. They're getting on with their life. But that's up to
company policy.<BR>
<BR>
ER: What do you feel your FBI background brings to the company ?<BR>
<BR>
JT: I think the experience of having been in an adversarial situation in
court, in front of a judge and a jury and attorneys. You only have to get
caught a couple of times not having a real good answer. I put the worst
case scenario on every one. <BR>
<BR>
I'll give you a for instance. We go to a university and say, 'Confirm this
person's degree.' They look in the computer and can't find it. We then ask
them to do a hand search, because things can fall through the cracks. If
they still can't find it, if it's been within seven years, we'll go to the
department head. Last thing we'll do is go to the alumni association and
ask them. All four. That's the thing that I learned from the FBI. <BR>
<BR>
Make sure your sources are ethical. Don't take just one, particularly if
it's a negative. It takes you a lifetime to make your reputation - you can
lose it overnight by some dumb thing. <BR>
<BR>
We've had some close calls. Talk about double jeopardy - this was a black
female who'd applied for a pretty responsible job with a big company.  We
went through the four phases, she didn't get the degree. We checked the
four things again, no degree. They said, 'She just handed me the diploma.'
<BR>
<BR>
So I asked them to fax me a copy; I faxed it to the university. They quit
using those diplomas five years before she claimed she'd graduated.<BR>
<BR>
Another pair of gals, twins, both used the initials B.J. Did the university
check and they came back and said 'B.J. got a degree, but her social security
number is one digit off what you have.' The next thing was to check references,
and one of the developed references said, 'Tell Betty Jane I said hello.'
'Who?' 'Betty Jane, B.J.' Turns out they were twins, one was going on the
other.<BR>
<BR>
It's like a doctor - you've got a swollen knee and the first thing he does
is look down your throat, to know the totality of the situation.<BR>
<BR>
One time, doing one of the things that the client hadn't asked us to do
- they didn't want the criminal check done anywhere else but where this
woman lived, even though she had lived in two or three other states - we
found out that this woman had murdered her husband and cut him up into little
pieces.<BR>
 	<BR>
You know, even when we go to the state with a release from the employee,
22 states will not let us into their criminal records. So on the one hand
we have the court saying to the employer, you are responsible for doing
a background investigation, and then you go to this state and they say no,
you can't see the records - you talk about a catch-22. Now there are some
of my competitors who claim, and this is just a lie, that they can get a
national criminal check. You cannot get a national criminal check. There's
only one national crime repository, and that is only available to the criminal
justice system. Some firms keep databases, they're inaccurate, inadequate.<BR>
<BR>
We do a state-wide if we can, and if they won't let us we go to the counties.
But you can walk from here to six counties - Pennsylvania is a state that
allows us to get the whole thing. I don't think everyone should be able
to get it on their neighbor or friend, but if you have a release, you should
be able to.<BR>
<BR>
ER: In all these steps do you have the employee's consent?<BR>
<BR>
JT: Oh, absolutely. I spent a great deal of money getting a lot of legal
advice and creating a compliance manual that made absolutely certain that
we were in compliance with the Consumer Protection Act, the Fair Trade Reporting
Act, the OEO and the OEA and all the rest of them. <BR>
<BR>
ER: Where do your FBI contacts come into play?<BR>
<BR>
JT: For instance, I have a correspondent in London who I met in my FBI career
who was in criminal intelligence with Scotland Yard. He does things for
me in the UK and Europe. We are getting more German and Russian and Chinese
and French technical people. For instance, it's very hard to get information
from India. So I'll look in my directory of former FBI agents and find someone
who is there or has contacts there. If I didn't call them, I'd probably
have to go to the embassy, and it'd take six weeks. Having people on the
spot who know what you want, and how to do it legally and professionally
 is an enormous advantage.<BR>
<BR>
Not only is it the FBI directory -also the FBI National Academy. We bring
in police from all over the world and train them for 12 weeks at the FBI
Academy in Quantico. Their directory has contacts in every state in the
union, every city, and every country in the world. Pago Pago, Bangladesh,
Guam, each one of these is an individual who speaks English, and whose connection
with the FBI they honor and value. I was an instructor and sometimes one
of these guys was in my class. That's worth a million bucks right there.<BR>
<BR>
ER: So you hire them like you would an independent contractor?<BR>
<BR>
JT: Yes, only in some cases they are forbidden to accept it and will do
it just as a matter of international cooperation. Going to someone who knows
and saying 'Do you have our equivalent of a credit check? Do you know of
a company doing business as so-and-so and where are they located?' It's
an enormous advantage.<BR>
<BR>
ER: What's been your most astonishing discovery?<BR>
<BR>
JT: The lady who cut up her husband, that was one of them. But there was
another one - one of the biggest chemical technical companies in the country
hired a guy for a cleanup of a hazardous materials site, Superfund. They
hired him for about $100,000 based on his master's degree in chemical engineering,
his experience as a CEO - he had a marvelous resume. He dressed in Brooks
Brothers clothing and he could drink two or three martinis and still not
put the lampshade on. He handled his silver very well and he was a perfect
gentlemen. Well, they did not have him around long, and first thing you
know he'd gone out and gotten himself a Cadillac on the company plastic.
He was running up enormous bills and taking trips to places that never heard
of chemical spills, and pushing people around. So finally I got the case,
and determined he was a liar and a blackguard that had been cited by the
DEA a number of times and started companies that went bankrupt. He'd picked
up a few words here and there and was an avid reader and he was a big faker,
that's all. What happened was there was a class-action suit against the
company for this hazardous materials site he was hired to clean up. Well,
the company was not lily white, and he knew it all. After he figured he
was going to get it anyway, some attorney came to him and wanted to know
whether or not he'd cooperate with them, and he said, 'If I had a couple
bucks I could tell you.' And he did. He cost that company a mint, a lot
of legal grief. For $200, I could have had that faker out before they even
brought him in. He cost them hundreds of thousands of dollars.<BR>
<BR>
ER: So everything you check out by computer and telephone is legal - do
you do surveillance and whatnot as well?<BR>
<BR>
JT: No, I do not. I don't have anybody on the street. What people do call
and ask is about counterelectronic measures. And I tell them look, there
are about 13 or 14 different ways to intercept a conversation. They have
what they call parabolic mikes - you can sit right there, over in that building,
aim it  like a camera. It reads the vibrations off the window from our conversation
and they can reconstruct our conversation. <BR>
<BR>
Everybody's watched too much television. I get something every day advertising
you can listen to your neighbors' conversation three blocks away - that
stuff doesn't work.<BR>
 <BR>
On the other hand, everything here is shredded. I take defensive tactics.
I don't want anyone to know my clients.<BR>
<BR>
Now there's the most productive, cheapest, easiest surveillance in the world
- trash cover. People throw things in the can - and you pay some guy $5
a day to go through it. You can't believe the stuff you can find out. You
can find out what kind of medicine they're taking, whether they've got a
girlfriend, if they're taking trips, or own stock. <BR>
                                                   <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
