<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Diner.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Shoot the Messenger </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Can We Hold Economists<BR>
Hostage for our Economic Woes?</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>He is Anonymous Economist. And he is ready to talk. I open with a
gentle inquiry: &quot;So why do people hate you guys?&quot; Long pause and
then, &quot;I think economists have become the butt of jokes...&quot;, Anonymous
Economist begins his attempt to explain why his colleagues, to a one, proved
to be some of the most inflammatory talk show guests I ever interviewed.
The conversations always started safely enough, with concise observations
on emerging trends. But then I'd take that first listener phone call and,
yes, Houston, we had ignition.<BR>
<BR>
It seems there were a lot of temple-throbbing folks out there just burning
to get even with one of society's officially sanctioned soothsayers. Get
even for all those forecasts that torpedoed their well-intentioned investments.
Get even for those defeating interest rate fluctuations that forced them
to forego the luxury car ... or the big step-up home. Get even for every
insecurity, real or imagined, in their corporate futures. Rage mattered.
Facts did not.<BR>
<BR>
Anonymous Economist has some thoughts on taking the heat. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Economists have allowed themselves to be viewed as forecasters. And
anyone who does [forecasting] is bound to be wrong, like weather forecasters.
The ability to forecast is very limited. Possibly, in the past, economists
have claimed too much for their       profession.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And history shows just how easily that can happen. The '60s delivered a
Masters of the Universe decade for economists. Just about everyone, it seems,
decided that it was their good judgment and right-on-target forecasting
that delivered all that prosperity. <BR>
<BR>
And yet, Anonymous Economist notes, there were a few other factors going
their way. The economy had emerged unscathed from war and American goods
dominated the world market. Add to that, he says, cheap energy, liberalized
trade and the commercial exploitation of technological developments that
date back to the 1930s: jet aircraft, rocket propulsion technology, a host
of other inventions and, yes, even television.<BR>
 <BR>
It all brought about &quot;a sense of optimism and confidence,&quot; Anony-mous
Economist explains, &quot;a sense the economists knew how to manage or fine-tune
the economy. And that was reflected in an overconfidence about the economists'
ability to forecast and prescribe the right medicine.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But time, as it will, rudely advanced. The 1970s brought high inflation
rates, high interest rates  and a lack of growth in real incomes.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;All of the positives turned slightly negative,&quot; Anonymous Economist
remembers. &quot;The technology cycle was slightly on the downside. World
trade grew at a much slower rate, with many countries turning to protectionism.
There was an eight-fold increase in energy. Bad harvests drove up the price
of food. And all of that was compounded by the bad economic policy of the
Nixon administration.&quot; <BR>
Yes, it was time, the public decided (and maybe some public officials too)
to blame the economists.<BR>
And we've been at it ever since. &quot;That's absurd. People want to lash
out at somebody,&quot; Anonymous Economist says. But then the conversation
turns to the other kind of criticism: corporate. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The point is, many economists failed to address the needs of their
companies. Becoming blinded by the forecasting of the gross domestic product,
they started playing games,&quot; Anonymous Economist asserts, as he looks
back on all those honors given to the most accurate of his colleagues. <BR>
&quot;Instead of forecasting for profits, they were forecasting for prizes,&quot;
and that, he says, is how some economists found themselves out of a job.
Companies, especially industrial ones, now find it all too easy to rely
instead on economic intelligence and forecasts widely available by computer.<BR>
<BR>
Ah, yes, the '90s. Economists can find themselves victims of one of their
own trend projections: outsourcing.<BR>
<BR>
But, the No. 1 reason we don't like economists may come down to this: They
are no fun. We want to believe all things are possible. Economists, however,
never fail to remind us all things come at a price.<BR>
<BR>
And the  price of ending our conversation, I told Anonymous Economist, was
proof that he and his colleagues had a sense of humor to get them through
these difficult times. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;So,&quot; he asked me, &quot;do you know the definition of a male
economist? <BR>
<BR>
&quot;A man who knows 50 different ways to have sex, but he doesn't know
any women,&quot; he answered himself.<BR>
<BR>
P.S. - Anonymous Economist decided during our conversation to decline the
title I offered him. While that didn't stop me from using it, it now gives
me great pleasure to reveal that Anonymous Economist is, in truth, Norman
Robertson, Economic Consultant and Adjunct Professor at Carnegie Mellon
University.                <BR>
<BR>
Ann Devlin's column will appear monthly in Executive Report. <BR>
