<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Antonini's</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Just off the Coast<BR>
of the South Side</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><BR>
From the outside, Antonini's, at 27th and Jane Street in the South Side,
seems a definite drive-by. Housed in a rather rundown brick building, with
a low paneled addition, the exterior features a large weathered sign with
an arrow pointing to parking and a few faded flags. It may look like a miss,
but hit the brakes and follow the arrow.<BR>
<BR>
The interior hasn't fared much better than the exterior - the addition has
aspirations of being an indoor courtyard, complete with a fountain. An adjoining
room and bar have been repapered and are rather dark. Everything's mauve,
except the little white Christmas lights which grace the  greenery. <BR>
So far, you might think the only thing this joint's got going for it is
that it's a South Side restaurant with a parking lot. Withhold judgment
please, until your mouth is full.<BR>
<BR>
There's Italian in the very foundation of the South Side, but until about
three years ago, there were no Italian restaurants here, excluding pizza
shops. Now they abound, and Antonini's takes top marks. <BR>
<BR>
The menu, graced with a sepia photo of the Italian coast, is where the artistry
of this ristorante begins. The menu is manageably small, yet has a substantial
selection of pastas, meats, poultry and seafood. Items range from traditional
(veal parmesan, $15.25) to unusual (macaroni with lobster and roasted peppers
in a tarragon scented cream sauce, $18.50).<BR>
<BR>
Appetizers, too, give choice to both timid and the adventurous. There are
clams steamed in seasoned oil and garlic ($6.95) or panino fritto, fried
bread dusted with garlic and parmesan ($2.95). We tried calamari, pan-fried
in garlic and oil with fresh plum tomatoes and fresh clipped parsley. It
was wonderful to have a calamari offering that wasn't fried. This was cooked
so lightly and subtly, just softening the squid. A frequent Antonini's specialty
is the sauteed portobella mushrooms - these were two of the largest I'd
ever seen, with stems like ping-pong balls full of fleshy meat. The mushrooms
themselves were cooked to tender perfection and bathed in a rich reduction.
Along with them came grilled Italian bread dotted with partially melted
square of fresh mozzarella. <BR>
<BR>
Without asking, your waitress will bring an antipasto to the table. The
offerings vary, but each time we dined included spicy homemade Italian sausage,
marinated roasted red and green peppers, wedges of polenta and marinated
red potatoes. One night, the  plate hosted a wealth of grilled vegetables
as well; another night, some crisp and marinated green beans.<BR>
<BR>
Next comes a family salad, simple fresh greens and vinaigrette. A bowl of
fresh parmesan and cruet of herbed olive oil accompany Italian bread, which
is unfortunately unexciting.<BR>
<BR>
I admit, on more than one occasion I've just stopped there. The service
here is friendly, down to earth and busy - they don't hassle or hurry you.
In fact, they almost ignore you. As with  the decor, no airs or attitudes
here.<BR>
<BR>
But the food is fresh and luscious. We sampled from both the pasta and the
entree menu. Tempted by the macaroni with artichokes, black olives and sundried
tomatoes in garlic and olive oil ($12.95), I instead dove into the linguine
with lobster, shrimp and scallops in a spicy diablo sauce ($18.95). And
I mean dove. There had to have been six lobster claws, a half a dozen each
large scallops and shrimp. The sauce was a little thin, but rich-tasting
and spicy indeed. By contrast, a scallopini of veal with roasted sweet and
hot peppers, ($15.95) - chosen with difficulty over the chicken stuffed
with ground mushroom stuffing ($14.95) - was sauteed with a rich brown reduction,
subtle and tender. <BR>
The wine list, too, is simple but substantial. A good Pinot Grigio can be
procured for $16, and there are more pricey alternatives as well.<BR>
<BR>
We finished with the smoothest  Tiramisu in my personal experience. Even
the weak coffee couldn't dull Antonini's shine.<BR>
<BR>
			    <BR>
Antonini's Ristorante<BR>
2700 Jane Street, South Side<BR>
381-9901 <BR>
Hours: <BR>
Mon. - Fri.: 11 a.m. - midnight<BR>
Sat.: 5 p.m. - midnight<BR>
Sun.: 3 p.m. - 9 p.m. <BR>
Appetizers and Salads: $2.95 - $6.95<BR>
Entrees: $11.50 -$24.95<BR>
<HR><BR>
