<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Education.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Staffing Solutions</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Don't Be Left Short When Vacations Start<BR>
Some Firms Use Interns, Others Use Temps<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>At International Sports Marketing, summer is the busiest time of
the year. But it's also the time when employees take the family to the beach
for a week. And when you factor in sick days or long weekends, it's tough
to maintain adequate staffing. For a small business, that can be crippling.<BR>
ISM's solution, in part, has been simple and inexpensive: It uses interns,
lots of them.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We use interns year-round, but we have more use for them in the summer,&quot;
says Kevin Saundry, ISM's director of account services and internship coordinator.
&quot;Unfortunately our calender of events, while it's spread out throughout
the year, is heavily based around the summer. So for us, the ideal intern
would start around March and end in July or August. We'll have one to two
interns a semester, except for the summer, when we utilize up to six.&quot;
 <BR>
<BR>
Robert Perkoski, director of  placement at the University of Pittsburgh,
says both interns and employers benefit from internships. The employers
benefit because they get a good look at someone who upon graduation may
be considered for a full-time position.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;[The company] can get an idea of what the candidate will be like in
the workplace. And for the candidate it's a good opportunity for them because
they also get experience and they get the opportunity to use some of their
academic skills in the workplace,&quot; Perkoski says. &quot;It's a win-win
situation for a lot of companies, and I think students in particular find
it a great opportunity.<BR>
&quot;In the Pittsburgh market we can have PR, advertising firms, those
kinds of companies. And then students will get the opportunity to go in
and work sometimes 10, 20, even 40 hours a week in the summer. In lots of
cases they'll get the real life experiences as it would be working as a
full-time employee.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Although most internship programs pay very little, Perkoski stresses the
importance of work experience for students that internships provide. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In some fields it's almost absolutely critical,&quot; he says. &quot;If
you're looking at public relations, advertising, radio, television, lots
of those fields, it's almost an absolute requirement.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In other fields, it helps tremendously. In a survey that was done
last year of employers and companies by one of the professional associations,
one of the highest ranked criteria for selecting candidates was previous
work experience in the field.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You can get a chance to prove your talents right there and sometimes
you can just come right on board afterwards and get an offer from the company.&quot;
<BR>
 <BR>
The internship program for all companies, according to Perkoski, is above
and beyond the current staffing that a company has, and there are laws to
ensure that businesses keep it that way.  &quot;So they're really looking
at more of a partnership,&quot; he says, &quot;not to cover a position that's
been let go or something like that.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
ISM's internships are unpaid for the most part, but interns the company
feels have shown some potential will have a chance to represent the firm
by going on the road to execute events. These interns are paid a small stipend
and all their business expenses are taken care of. Other firms will compensate
interns, usually an hourly wage.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;We're very flexible with working with them,&quot; says Saundry. &quot;We're
willing to work with students that need to earn money to either pay for
an apartment, if they're from out of town, or just to make money for the
summer.  We don't stand in their way.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Employers can solicit interns from just one school, perhaps the company
president's alma mater, or they may solicit from many different schools
to attract a larger pool of candidates. This year, ISM broadened the base
of schools from which is solicits internship applicants.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;In the past we traditionally really only utilized interns from a
couple of sources,&quot; says Saundry, &quot;one being Robert Morris College,
which has been our primary feeder, if you will, of interns. We've had a
relationship with them for over four years, and I am a product of that internship
program. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;And we have three other full-time employees who are products of internships
through our company as well. Part of our refocus this year was to say 'Okay,
let's expand our internship pool and go after interns from varied backgrounds.'
Our needs have somewhat changed focus, and we look at ourselves as more
of a sales-oriented-type agency, so therefore we wanted to come at schools
like Pitt, Duquesne, Slippery Rock, all the local schools, to find the most
qualified candidates with a little bit of a sales background, a little bit
more of a marketing background, than what we had seen in the past.&quot;
 <BR>
<BR>
The other staffing option is the use of temporary employees. According to
Antoinette Grady, general manager for Allegheny Personnel Services, the
peak season for hiring temporaries has traditionally been the summer. <BR>
 <BR>
However, she says, &quot;we've been noticing a constant, more steady flow
throughout the year.&quot;<BR>
Like internships, a temp agency may provide an eventual employee.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I believe a lot of people realize now that the temporaries services
are a very viable source for recruiting,&quot; says Grady.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
