<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H17Education.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Sports.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>Mastering the Possibilities</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1>The Wide Array of Local MBA Offerings Allows<BR>
Students to Tailor a Program To Their Own Career</FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>During the '80s, you couldn't walk the halls of corporate America
without bumping into an MBA grad.<BR>
<BR>
Ten years later, little has changed: In fact, the Master's of Business Administration
degree is as popular as ever, with more than 800 business schools across
the U.S. offering some 1,300 programs.<BR>
<BR>
That should ben no surprise. William Presutti, associate dean and director
of graduate studies at Duquesne University, says an advanced business degree
is almost mandatory  to climb the corporate ladder. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;With corporate downsizing, there are fewer career tracks. People are
looking for ways to differentiate themselves,&quot; he says, noting that
the credential has become so prevalent it may work against you not to have
it. <BR>
 <BR>
But today's MBA programs bear little resemblance to those of a decade ago.
For one, students are older, more likely to have work experience or be going
to school part-time.<BR>
<BR>
And thanks to the globalization of the U.S. economy, the '90s MBA programs
have more emphasis on the international. And increasing numbers of international
students deepen the understanding of cultural, social and political differences
among peoples.<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne, which offers the traditional MBA as well as a Master of Science
in Information Systems Management (MS/MIS), has reshaped its curriculum
to require courses in communications, computers and quantitative and qualitative
problem solving. Both programs also integrate four major themes into all
of their courses: ethics, the globalization of business, total quality management
and the management of technology (computer literacy).<BR>
<BR>
And Duquesne has replaced the &quot;case method&quot; of learning business
with a more &quot;hands-on&quot; approach where real business people come
in to present actual issues or problems. The University of Pittsburgh's
Katz School of Business takes a similar tack.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We demand it,&quot; says associate dean Daniel Fogel. Pitt students
team up with area businesses for class projects. &quot;There's no secondary
research, just real problems and real solutions.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Teamwork, too, is a priority. Every student goes through the entire MBA
program as a member of a &quot;learning organization.&quot; These students
acquire team-based skills, and learn how work gets done in a real corporation,
says Fogel, where people with different  viewpoints must reach consensus.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Businesses want students to understand that the world doesn't work
as neatly as in a computer program,&quot; he says. &quot;They have to be
able to deal with uncertainties...to develop interpersonal skills so they
can deal with other people.&quot;<BR>
 <BR>
Pitt offers traditional two-year MBA and MS/MIS programs, as well as the
FLEX-MBA, where students earn their degree electronically via fax, E-mail
and videotape. Students can also choose between an 11-month MBA, two 2-year
dual degrees and three international dual degrees.<BR>
Bill Donley, a Koppers vice president, says the FLEX-MBA program expands
his own business experience. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I've been with Koppers for seventeen years, so I don't have a great
perspective on how other companies are run,&quot; he says. Through the degree,
he'll discover how things happen both in Pittsburgh and around the world.<BR>
<BR>
Point Park College emphasizes global markets, too, and is the only school
in the area to offer an international MBA. The program echoes the traditional
MBA but goes one step further by integrating international dimensions into
each class. In addition to electives in international accounting, advertising
and marketing, students gain an overview of management practices and government
policies in Europe, the Middle East, Latin America and East Asia.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We can't isolate an economy anymore,&quot; says program director Dimitris
Kraniou. &quot;The name of the game is global competition. American executives
know they have to deal with international business forces.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Looking to specialize? In addition to the traditional MBA, business students
at Robert Morris College can opt for the MBA or Master of Science (M.S.)
with a concentration in accounting, computer and information systems, finance,
health services management, marketing or sports management. Those with enough
undergraduate business courses can also choose the one-day-a-week MBA, which
takes two years to complete.<BR>
<BR>
How's the job market for MBAs in the Pittsburgh area? Still good, says Joan
Craig, director of placement and career services at Pitt. Those with the
dual MBA/MS-MIS do especially well, she adds, as the need for more technically
oriented graduates increases.  MBAs with some relevant work experience can
earn an average of $51,000; new grads command from $37,000 to $40,000 a
year.<BR>
<BR>
Craig admits, though, that an increasing number of graduates must leave
the city for employment. Most jobs here are in service industries.<BR>
<BR>
The bottom line, she says, is that the MBA is still a very marketable degree.<BR>
 &quot;Employers are always looking for bright young people,&quot; she says.
The MBA, she says, is the degree of choice.<BR>
