<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Education.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Law.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Walking the Line</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>College Athletic Departments Struggle to Comply With<BR>
a Federal Law That Calls for Gender Equality<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>College athletics has always been about great rivalries. Army-Navy
in football, Duke-North Carolina in basketball, Harvard-Yale in crew.<BR>
<BR>
In recent years, however, new rivalries have sprouted up and, unlike their
predecessors, they produce very few winners. In fact, it's hard to even
know how to keep score when you pit men's gymnastics against women's tennis
or men's wrestling against women's soccer.<BR>
<BR>
But those kind of matchups are becoming increasingly commonplace in colleges
and universities as athletic departments struggle with ways to equalize
opportunities in sports for both men and women.<BR>
<BR>
The struggle is not motivated entirely by a search for equality. A legal
mandate -  Title IX of the Education Act of 1972, which bars sex discrimination
in schools that receive federal funding - hangs over the entire enterprise.
Living with Title IX is sometimes difficult, sometimes costly and often
perplexing for college administrators striving to do the right thing.<BR>
<BR>
Consider, for instance, Pitt. In 1995, Athletic Director Oval Jaynes had
to do something lots of corporations have done in the '90s - downsize. He
eliminated the men's gymnastics program and the men's tennis program and
added women's soccer as a varsity sport. The two-steps-back-one-step-forward
approach was Pitt's latest attempt to satisfy one of the demands of Title
IX; namely, if your school is 50 percent female, then approximately 50 percent
of your athletes should be female as well.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;With a Division I football program that has 108 athletes on it,&quot;
Jaynes says, &quot;and with the largest female team having only 27 women,
this becomes a very, very difficult thing to reach.&quot;<BR>
But the effort must be made. In 1993, in a landmark case involving Indiana
University of Pennsylvania, IUP was ordered to reinstate two women's sports
teams that had been dropped for budgetary reasons. The judge ruled that
lack of money was no excuse when opportunities for female athletes are involved.
Around the nation, more than a half dozen colleges have been sued over potential
Title IX inequities.<BR>
<BR>
Jaynes realizes that while decreasing opportunities for male athletes is
not the ideal way to make things work, it is a quick and efficient way.
Decisions are based on expenses, a survey of student interests and the amount
of participation, Jaynes says.<BR>
<BR>
Pitt will start the 1996-97 school year with nine male sports and nine female
sports. Traditionally at most Division I schools, sports are paid for by
revenues generated by the top money-makers - football and men's basketball.
<BR>
<BR>
Supporters of Title IX claim that schools like Pitt that cut men's teams
to reach equity figures are using the legal mandate as a scapegoat. &quot;An
excuse is what it is,&quot; says Arthur Bryant of the Trial Lawyers for
Public Justice, a Washington public-interest law firm that has handled most
Title IX lawsuits, including the IUP case.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's an equality law. The way Title IX is interpreted doesn't mean
you have to eliminate men's sports.&quot; To Bryant, the issue is financial.
Schools are facing difficult economic times, but are nonetheless reluctant
to trim the fat from the main revenue sports - football and men's basketball.
He cites one common Division I practice - having the football team spend
the night before a home game at a local hotel - as a wasteful practice.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The cost of that alone could pay for a minor sport for a year,&quot;
Bryant says. Still, it is hard for athletic directors to cut corners in
the major sports. For one, being frugal could hurt recruiting and give opponents
a competitive advantage. Two, most ADs are evaluated on the major sports'
success. <BR>
So it is sometimes more politically expedient to drop a men's sport with
little student support - such as gymnastics, swimming, water polo and wrestling
- rather than trim the football budget. <BR>
According to Bob Bubb, former wrestling coach at Clarion University and
executive director of the National Wrestling Coaches Association, over 60
Division I schools have dropped wrestling in the past five years.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It makes you angry,&quot; says Bubb, who thinks the matter needs to
be resolved by Congress. &quot;It's not the law that's bad, it's the interpretation
of <BR>
the law.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The important thing,&quot; says Jaynes, &quot;is to make the decisions
for the right reasons. I care about the student athletes at Pitt, male and
female, and that drives every decision I make.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
