<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Double Jeopardy</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Employers Face Legal Obstacles On<BR>
Both Ends of Employee Reference Checks<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Jim Treher conducts background checks for a living, and oh, can he
tell some stories. There's the woman who used her twin sister's college
degree to get a job offer. There's the would-be MBA graduate who actually
only completed a few credits toward the degree. There's the corporate executive
whose professional experience wasn't what he said it was.<BR>
<BR>
And those were the cases in which no one really got hurt, outside of a little
wasted time and money. This past spring, the stakes were higher: A meter
reader was arrested and charged with raping a woman inside her Westmoreland
County home. The employee, who worked for a subcontractor that Peoples Gas
Co. had hired to read meters, had a criminal history of burglary, theft,
auto theft and criminal mischief. No one checked.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The best reason to do a background check is because the employers
are absolutely responsible for seeing that the people they hire are not
dangerous,&quot; says Treher, a retired FBI agent and president of Pittsburgh-based
Corporate Investigations Inc. (for more on Treher and his work, see People
Making News on page 10).<BR>
<BR>
But finding out information about prospective employees is not always easy,
even when a veteran investigator like Treher is doing the digging.<BR>
 <BR>
One problem: Former employers - fearing legal action if they give a negative
reference - often will only confirm the dates of employment, the job title
and salary.<BR>
<BR>
Another problem: only 40 percent of the states - fortunately Pennsylvania
is one - will release a criminal's rap sheet to the public.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Neutral References</B><BR>
<BR>
Pennsylvania courts have held that employers have a conditional privilege
to communicate defamatory information when asked by a prospective employer
to evaluate the employee's performance. Yet employers, often at the prodding
of legal counsel, limit the information they disclose about a former employee
- even if that employee was exemplary. <BR>
<BR>
In a recent Robert Half International poll of 200 executives from the country's
1,000 largest companies, 68 percent said that it was hard to obtain reference
information about a prospective employee. And another survey of human resource
professionals showed 41 percent worked at companies with policies against
providing any outside references for former employees.<BR>
<BR>
But this blanket &quot;no comment&quot; practice, as it's known in some
legal circles, is not as foolproof as once thought. It actually has spawned
a new line of lawsuits in which former employers have been sued for not
disclosing information about an employee's questionable past. In other words,
even saying nothing can come back to haunt the former employer.<BR>
<BR>
In Florida, for example, the families of several people killed in a workplace
shooting sued the gunman's previous employer for not disclosing the gunman's
&quot;dangerous propensities.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Specifically, the families charged that the former employer witnessed the
man threaten coworkers with guns, espouse belief in aliens and worship the
devil. Yet, this same man - later a murderer - had a letter of reference
from the former employer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You've got walk a thin line there,&quot; says attorney Theresa Wasser
of Doepken Keevican &amp; Weiss in Pittsburgh. &quot;If you know this person
has the propensity to do something criminal, you absolutely have to disclose
that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Some good advise: Have departing employees sign a release in which the employees
consent to disclosure of information relevant to work history. When a reference
query comes in, it's best to speak honestly and avoid puffery. Don't disclose
information related to the employee's physical or mental health. The employee
may later accuse you of firing him or her because of a physical or mental
disability.<BR>
<BR>
On the other side of the hiring process, employers should have prospective
employees sign a release authorizing former employers to provide work history
information. Check with multiple references to draw a more complete picture
of the applicant, and be attentive to what the references don't say. What
they don't discuss may be a red flag. <BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
