"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Birth of an Industry<BR>
</FONT></I><FONT size =+1>In the Footsteps of Yet Another National Trend,<BR>
Women Choose Mid wifery Over Medicine</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When Kelli Huss had her first baby, all eyes were on her ... 20 in
all. Crowded into the birthing suite with her were husband Mark, mother
Jan, sister-in-law Darlene, cousin Lynette, mother-in-law Charlene, Aunt
Carol, Mark's Aunt Kay, even Kelli's 10-year-old sister Leanne. All of them
fit, and there still was room for two certified nurse midwives from Family
Nurse Midwife Associates. <BR>
In a traditional hospital setup, Huss's choice of company would have been
impossible - husbands only. But the midwives gave the power of decision
to Huss and her husband.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Everything was exactly the way I wanted,&quot; she says. &quot;They
have a special connection with my daughter now.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Certified nurse midwives are not really new. Midwives in one form or another
have been around for as long as women have given birth. But more and more
women in the western Pennsylvania area are choosing midwives over obstetricians,
reflecting a trend that's already overtaken most of the rest of the country.
<BR>
<BR>
Midwives offer more personal attention, more empowerment to the family,
less traumatic births and a cheaper bill. Numerous studies, including one
by the Institute of Medicine in Washington, D.C., and one by the United
States Congress, Office of Technology Assessment, show that certified nurse
midwives are safe, cost-effective and educated practitioners. Far from the
traditional image of a lay woman with a bonnet and a bucket of hot water,
modern nurse midwives are formally educated and rigorously certified. They're
backed up by obstetricians, insured and operate mostly in hospitals or specialized
birth centers. Family Nurse Midwife Associates, for instance, is based in
Westmoreland County at Jeannette Hospital. <BR>
<BR>
The midwife philosophy is that birth is a normal process. &quot;Low-tech,
high-touch&quot; is an oft-used  catch phrase.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;We believe that childbirth is a normal event that happens in a family's
life, rather than a potential medical disaster,&quot; says Nancy Ritenour
of Family Nurse Midwife Associates.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're alert to problems, but we attend to normalcy.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Not that midwives stint on attention to their patients. Intensive prenatal
care is a cornerstone of practice. Midwives universally take at least half-hour-long
appointments. They take pride in their consideration of the whole family,
using appointment time for education about diet, emotional issues and family
adjustment.<BR>
<BR>
Midwives educate and counsel, but urge mothers to take control of their
pregnancies. The family draws up a birth plan saying exactly what they want
- who will be there, how much monitoring they want, yea or nay to an episiotomy.
When labor actually starts, the midwife stays with the woman from the moment
she checks in. Use of fetal monitors and IV drugs is minimal. Birth is seen
as normal and natural unless something happens to suggest otherwise.  The
mother does whatever she wants to - walk, take a hot bath, sip tea, sit
in a rocking chair, take any position she chooses, and nature takes her
course relatively unassisted. In case of complications, backup doctors are
there in the hospital (at stand-alone centers, the patient is transported
to the nearby affiliated hospital). But while Caesarean sections are performed
in 25 percent of traditional births, they are used in just 4 percent of
midwife-assisted births.<BR>
<BR>
Yet some women do not feel midwifery is for them, despite the safety nets.
Critics charge that midwives in some centers urge women who request drugs
to &quot;tough it out,&quot; and some centers have no-epidurals policies.
Though early discharge policies (some as early as 12 hours) are unsettling
to some, most women are ready to go, and are visited by a nurse within 72
hours. <BR>
<BR>
At BirthPlace, the only stand-alone birthing center in the region, women
who find they must have some relief during labor can have Stedol, a synthetic
narcotic, at the center or be transported, accompanied by the midwife, to
affiliated West Penn Hospital.  The center itself is in a Victorian house
on Baum Boulevard, one half mile away. It boasts five midwives and  two
birthing suites, outfitted like Holly Hobby's bedroom, with lacy curtains
and bedspreads, pink and blue wallpaper, even straw hats on the walls. A
bathroom with a jacuzzi-jet tub and a complete kitchen round out the comfort
 zone.<BR>
<BR>
But beneath the homeyness, each bedroom can transform instantly to a hospital
unit. Cabinets hold cotton, antiseptics, sharps; an oxygen tank lurks in
a corner under a pillowcase, and the hat hanger over the bed doubles as
an IV hook.<BR>
<BR>
The result of all this extra care, ironically enough, is a lower bill. Excluding
treatments and procedures most women don't need, preventing cesarean sections,
and providing early discharges add up to less. The average bill for a hospital
birth can range anywhere from $7,000 to $10,000; the national average is
$4,000 for a birth center.<BR>
<BR>
But  western Pennsylvania has not quite caught up. This is surprising, since
midwives' cost-effectiveness makes nurse-midwifery attractive to insurers
and HMOs. Nurse midwife services are covered by almost all insurance plans;
BirthPlace is an alternative with all the HMOs and carriers in the area,
and is covered by Medicaid, though not always by Medicare.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our perspective is that nurse midwives who are licensed to practice
in Pennsylvania are considered safe practitioners and that they provide
a good service for our members,&quot; says Dr. Carey Vinson, regional medical
director for Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania. All the safeguards taken
by midwives mean they have no problem finding malpractice insurance, either.
BirthPlace pays the same rates as  obstetricians attached to West Penn.<BR>
<BR>
So why hasn't nurse midwifery boomed here? Nearby Philadelphia has 20-plus
midwives, to Pittsburgh's handful.<BR>
<BR>
One reason is lack of advertising. Most people have never heard of the option.
Midwives also face stiff competition from the large local population of
obstetricians. But nurse midwives put the onus on the consumer. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;There's not much proactiveness here on the part of women,&quot; says
Jane Butler, a nurse midwife from the San Francisco area.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;It's not as if hospitals in California said, 'OK, we're going to
change things and make everything nice for you.' The women said, 'Look,
we don't want it like this anymore.' &quot;         <BR>
