<A HREF="../zine/0696.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+>Managing Managed Care<BR>
</FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I> </CENTER>
<P><HR>Hannah Rose Nickeson was born eight weeks premature. At first there
seemed to be no undue threat to her health: Hannah, though tiny, had only
some typical liver problems. But at three months, an extremely high temperature
prompted her parents to rush her to the ER.<BR>
<BR>
In fact, she had a septic kidney infection. Doctors found that her ureters,
which conduct the flow from the kidney to the bladder, had developed at
the wrong angle; urine backup was causing the infection. A 10-day course
of antibiotics treated the infection, but doctors found mysterious calcium
deposits in her kidneys. High levels of calcium were also found in her urine.
When the infection returned three months later, an operation was scheduled
to correct the ureters. And the calcium conditions (called nephrocalcinosis
and hypercalcuria) led to years of doctors, pills and tests for the small
child, as experts tried to advise the family on how to manage these conditions
and prevent the calcium buildup from leading to blockage.<BR>
<BR>
That's easier said than done. Hannah's condition is baffling. Usually, problems
such as she experiences (and they are not common) are manifestations of
syndromes which are also accompanied by mental or physical retardation.
The early infections arrested the growth of her left kidney, but Hannah
shows no sign of developmental problems - now almost 5, she's smart, creative,
adventurous and incredibly cute. She loves bugs and ropes - just your typical
kid.<BR>
If it seems a miracle that a child with such a mysterious and potentially
dangerous condition is so healthy now, consider this: At the time she was
born, Hannah's family belonged to a managed care plan, and they still do.
Despite the horror stories that abound about the difficulty and limitations
of managed care, the Nickesons were able to secure the best care they knew
about for her. Granted, both parents work in the healthcare field, and neither
is a pushover. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;You have to be willing to work with and shop within the system,&quot;
says Ellie Nickeson, Hannah's mom, a social worker in the Ventilator Assisted
Children/Home Program of Western Pennsylvania. <BR>
&quot;You have to understand your limitations and look for and get other
things. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;But you also have to be willing to accept the limitations,&quot; she
adds. &quot;We've gone outside the system. We've paid for things we feel
we need that aren't covered.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
At this stage, developmental problems are no longer a threat. Hannah continues
to have high levels of calcium in her urine, but at last check had no further
deposits in her kidneys. Her left kidney has begun to grow again. It's a
mystery where the calcium comes from, or why she has the condition in the
first place. Generally, problems of this sort are genetic, but in her case
that doesn't seem so. One Chicago specialist calls her condition the Hannah
Nickeson Syndrome - because he has never seen anything like it before. Now
managed by medication, there seems little threat to her future health.<BR>
As Pittsburgh moves toward managed care, more and more people like the Nickesons
will have to advocate for themselves in the healthcare system. In the managed
care framework, no longer is it acceptable to go for care where you see
fit - and expect insurance to cover it. Rules and regulations born of cost
containment are limiting care in all manner of ways. To achieve their desired
result - a happy, healthy daughter - the Nickesons have researched, appealed
and discussed their hearts out during the last five years. Perhaps you don't
think it should be necessary to do so, but don't waste too much time bemoaning
that state of affairs. The fact is, you might have to, too.<BR>
<BR>
Executive Report's two-part series entitled Managing Managed Care will detail
the choices necessary to make a smooth transition to managed care. This
month, choosing a plan. In the July issue, using it to get proper care.<BR>
<BR>
Choosing a Plan<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Managed care&quot; means just that. To control costs, managed care
plans limit the care to which their subscribers have access. While that
does not mean a patient cannot get treatment for a health condition, it
does mean that they must follow certain guidelines in pursuing their care,
typically within networks of providers that the insurers contract with in
large volume. In an HMO, or health maintenance organization, the member
is only covered for services from providers in the network. The more popular
POS, or point-of-service programs, allow members to use providers outside
of the network at a higher cost (for definitions of common managed-care
terms, see Chronicles on page 8). Theoretically, the tighter the controls,
the more costs can be cut out of the system.<BR>
Though managed care is relatively new to western Pennsylvania, the market
is already burgeoning. Experts surmise that over 50 percent of the private
health insurance market is insured under managed care, up from just 7 percent
in 1990, as more and more employers turn to managed care to help control
skyrocketing benefit costs. Sometimes employees have a choice of plans and
sometimes they do not; Blue Cross, for example, cuts out competition by
giving tempting rates to employers who offer only their products, which
limits employees' choices. Locally, Blue Cross, with Keystone Health Plan,
its HMO, and Select Blue, a POS option, is estimated to dominate with over
50 percent of the managed care market; U.S. Healthcare, HealthAmerica and
Advantage Health Plan also provide managed care here. All offer an array
of managed care products, each with varying degrees of freedom for the consumer.<BR>
<BR>
Employees confronting a choice of managed care plans usually have an ace
in the hole: their corporate human resources personnel. They've probably
done a lot of research on the plans being offered and will share it. <BR>
<BR>
The plans, too, are good sources of information. They do regular member
satisfaction surveys, and keep records of complaints and re-enrollment rates
for both doctors and members. And if they're unresponsive in giving information
to you, it may be indicative of their customer service. Make sure you ask
about that too: Find out the hours they have real people on the line to
talk about your concerns. Better yet, ask around. People you know who use
these plans are the best sources.<BR>
There are outside organizations that monitor and accredit these healthcare
plans. At the national level, the National Committee on Quality Assurance
has standardized measures for quality, called HEDIS data, which are the
basis for plan &quot;report cards.&quot; They also provide comparative information
useful in benchmarking a plan's effectiveness in these areas. NCQA has a
voluntary accreditation process, in which plans are reviewed under 50 standards
in the areas of quality improvement, physician credentials, members' rights
and responsibilities, preventive health services, utilization management
and medical records. Only 37 percent of plans actually have full accreditation,
and the information is available on the World Wide Web at http://www.ncqa.org,
or by calling NCQA at 202/955-3515.<BR>
Another national organization, the Center for the Study of Services, has
also published plan-by-plan ratings, gleaned from a survey of 150,000 HMO
members nationwide. Advantage Health Plan and HealthAmerica are the only
two Pittsburgh HMOs represented; the ratings cover access, quality and choice
($12; call 800/475-7283).<BR>
<BR>
At the state level, HMOs and PPOs must be licensed by the department of
insurance; industry insiders say Pennsylvania has some of the best standards
in place of any state. But while information about the plans is compiled
by the state, they have yet to make this information available to consumers.<BR>
<BR>
Locally, however, the Pittsburgh Business Group on Health has also done
some benchmarking of plans. Their information is available on three local
plans, HealthAmerica, Keystone Health Plan and U.S. Healthcare. It compiles
findings on the physicians and hospitals in the networks, along with member
satisfaction rankings, such as ease of making appointments and whether members
would recommend the plan. The information has been published in their publication,
Health Pages, which periodically runs information on other aspects of the
local healthcare industry as well (for subscription info call 212/505-0103).<BR>
<BR>
To further assess the health of the organization, Angela Walker of Johnson
and Higgins recommends checking its financial stability. &quot;Especially
with some of the smaller companies - you want to be sure they'll be around
in a couple of years, and be sure the company can pay their bills,&quot;
says Walker. One source is Best's Insurance Reports. To secure a copy, call
800-424-BEST.<BR>
Another financial factor that can affect the quality of care is the method
managed care companies use to compensate doctors and hospitals. Traditional
indemnity plans paid for services on an as-used basis. But as managed care
networks buy or partner with physician groups to streamline their services,
more and more doctors in the area are on the staff of managed care plans
and receive a salary. One way managed care motivates providers they contract
with for services to be judicious caregivers is by paying them a capitated
fee: one lump sum per member per month, regardless of the services performed.
Capitation rates for primary care range from $7 to $24 per month, depending
on factors like age and level of illness; physicians sometimes also receive
bonuses or withholds based on their patterns of referral and usage of ancillary
services. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;At present, most of these are based on utilization - experience, referrals
and the number of other services they use, and not on other aspects of performance,&quot;
says Marvin Gaynor, a professor at CMU's Heinz School of Public Policy.
Theoretically, these policies could cause doctors to be too conservative
doling out services. &quot;Although that is changing. It might be hard to
find out how doctors are compensated from the HMO, because they do not have
a single uniform contract with physicians.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Gaynor recommends asking your physician how he is compensated, and how that
level compares to true expenditures, to gauge these issues.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
What's Up, Doc?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Accreditation status, all these things are useful, but they're of
little value to the consumer,&quot; asserts Robert Achenbach, deputy secretary
for quality assurance and health planning in the Pennsylvania Department
of Insurance's Bureau of healthcare financing, which is responsible for
monitoring managed care plans.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;People make the choice by providers, doctors and hospitals,&quot;
he says.<BR>
<BR>
In managed care plans, patients are generally monitored by their primary
care physician, who becomes their &quot;gatekeeper&quot; to care. All care,
except in the case of extreme emergency, must be coordinated by the primary
care physician, who may be a family practitioner, internal medicine physician
or pediatrician, depending on the needs of the patient. <BR>
<BR>
The gatekeeper concept is meant to ensure that the patient is not making
treatment decisions that are unnecessary or inefficient, thus taking cost
out of the system. It also ensures that the patient will make decisions
with the help of someone who not only knows the healthcare system, but who
has access to all th patient's records and knows the patient's history,
which can figure prominently in treatment decisions. In the past, cases
in which a patient might have gone to the more expensive care of a specialist
might have been just as competently handled by the primary care physician.<BR>
<BR>
And, in this world of increasing rules and regulations from healthcare insurers,
the primary care physician should become a patient advocate, helping them
through a now-confusing system of referrals, authorizations and limitations
on service.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's essential for the consumer to understand when they join a managed
care plan that they are putting their faith in the hands of a primary care
physician medical manager,&quot; says Tom Chepel, who works with Achenbach
in the bureau of healthcare financing. &quot;An essential provision consumers
should look for is whether your primary care physician is in the plan.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
If you have a doctor you trust, check the networks that are offered through
the various plans to see if he or she is involved. Do the same with specialists
and hospitals you prefer and trust. The HMOs all have lists of providers
they contract with for care.<BR>
<BR>
If you do need to choose a new primary care physician, look at the list
of providers and determine what kind of service you need - pediatric, for
young kids and teens; family or internal medicine, for older folks. Then
look at where the doctors are geographically, or call your local hospital,
describe your needs and ask them to refer a doctor. <BR>
<BR>
Last but not least, call the physician's office. Find out where they were
educated, and whether they have board certification. If the physician has
teaching responsibilities at an area school or hospital, that's also a plus.
Make sure that they're taking new patients (many primary care physicians,
particularly in rural areas, have become overrun with the new structure
of managed care) and ask how long it takes to get an appointment.<BR>
<BR>
The relationship that your doctor has with the managed care company is also
important. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Find out if the doctor knows and wants to participate in managed care,
or has to do it to survive,&quot; says Dr. Richard Harris, president of
the Allegheny County Medical Society. &quot;Ask about the procedures for
referrals and emergencies, because the booklets are very misleading. They
may say the ER is covered, but you may have to go through your doctor and
have other restrictions.&quot;<BR>
Conflicts between doctors and plans usually arise from the plans' requirements
for making referrals and using ancillary services, like blood tests and
x-rays. Dr. Marc Schneiderman calls it the &quot;hassle factor.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The playing field is even - if the patient needs an x-ray, every insurance
company will give it to them. It's where you want that care, and how much
you're willing to pay for that,&quot; says Schneiderman, a primary care
physician with Fifth Avenue Medical Associates in Coraopolis. Though they
have the capability of doing both x-rays and blood work in the office, some
of the HMOs they contract with will only pay for these services to be done
at certain labs. &quot;So they have to go to the hospital, park, go to the
lab, check in -that's an hour and a half right there.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Schneiderman also suggests asking your doctor's office about the HMO's guidelines.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The HMO will tell you if the doctor chooses to do it in the office
he can - but they don't tell you they won't pay for that. Our office will
tell you what we will do depending on the coverage you have.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The same thing goes, he says, for referrals to other physicians.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A lot of HMOs are advertising coverage for chiropractic services.
If you call the HMO and ask if you can go they'll say, 'Yes, if your primary
care physician refers you.' But they don't say, 'We have restrictions on
the doctor,' &quot; says Schneiderman. &quot;To refer to a chiropractor,
it has to be an acute problem, less than 10 days old, not recurring, and
the patient has to have finished a course of physical therapy and seen an
orthopedic surgeon to say the problem is not curable by surgery.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Then I look like a schmuck. It's the hassle factor that HMOs build
in that saves them money.&quot;<BR>
Harris recommends checking other aspects of a doctor's involvement with
the plan, too.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Ask how long they've been in managed care - if it's more than two
years, their offices will be better at dealing with it. It's a function
of learning the system and being reasonably good at it,&quot; says Harris.
<BR>
&quot;Also, how much of their practice is managed care? It's got to be a
significant portion, so they're set up to deal with it. Ten percent is not
enough, but 70 percent is too much, because you don't care. My office at
40 percent is almost impossible.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Because managed care requires authorization for almost every step of treatment,
doctors have had to add staff to handle the extra load both the insurers
and the patients demand. Physicians spend a lot of time on the phone with
the insurers too - often explaining their course of treatment to a paper
pusher.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I have to explain to a person who doesn't understand what I'm going
to do. When an office has over 50 percent of patients in managed care, they
just can't do all that fighting, so they don't go to bat for their patient,&quot;
says Harris. &quot;Also, with managed care, the number of visits is higher,
because the co-pays are low; they come to the office with a hangnail. There's
a lot more to do to take care of them the way you need to.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>All Plans are not Equal</B><BR>
<BR>
The bulk of grievances and complaints lodged by consumers of managed care,
according to the state bureau of healthcare licensing, are benefit-related.
HMOs are contractually obligated to cover you according to the benefits
and limitations of your specific package - not to cure you as you see fit.
Review the coverage available to you carefully, because there is no one-size-fits-all
plan - every company negotiates their own package of benefits.<BR>
 <BR>
Only you know what kind of coverage you need. If you or someone in your
family has special needs, look to see that those services are covered, and
to what extent. Really probe: Check the number of allowable visits, the
use of diagnostics, the HMO's attitude on experimental treatment.<BR>
Fortunately or unfortunately, however, many consumers are making decisions
about their care when they're healthy - so they don't know specifically
what they need. One important aspect if you are healthy is preventive services.
Though that's a charge to managed care, they don't always fulfill it. Check
what kinds of services are actually included: Checkups, immunizations, lifestyle
modification programs and even co-pays on health club memberships are among
the offerings. Also look at the coverage of any non-disease-oriented health
services you may need, like birth control, optical benefits, even infertility
treatments. <BR>
<BR>
The key is not to think just in the short run. Make sure the plan has the
depth of service you would like to have when you're sick - the right numbers
and locations of well-respected specialists and hospitals, continuity of
care options like mental health benefits. Remember, though, that it is largely
your own doctor who will determine your hospital - so find out the affiliations
of the doctors you will use. Also check into policies on allowed lengths
of hospital stays. More is not always better - but make sure the managed
care company will cover a continuity of care, such as a rehabilitation facility
or home nursing if you don't have someone at home to take care of you.<BR>
<BR>
Another important difference is pharmaceuticals - many HMOs have formularies,
specific lists of drugs they cover. HMOs save money by having doctors stick
to the formulary, because they can buy those medicines in volume. Trouble
is, those drugs aren't always the most effective for treatment, so patients
may end up with the choice of paying more or getting less. <BR>
<BR>
Check with your doctor to see how much freedom he has in these issues; also
ask about treatment protocols. &quot;Find out what leeway there is in treatment;
there may be protocols for physicians,&quot; says CMU's Gaynor. (Protocol
is a roadmap for treating an illness.) &quot;Who's approving those on the
other end? Is it an administrator? A nurse? And how much flexibility does
the doctor have in following their protocol?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Emergency service is another stickler - because care must be routed through
the primary care physician, HMOs routinely turn down bills for service enrollees
deemed &quot;emergency.&quot; <BR>
It's policies like these that can make dealing with HMOs difficult - so
find out the restrictions before you run smack into them.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The only thing you can be guided by is a knowledge of yourself and
the predictors your lifestyle has for illness,&quot; says Dr. Sean McLinden,
executive director of the Pittsburgh Health Research Institute at Duquesne
University. &quot;You can identify needs based on certain lifestyle choices
- like prenatal care. And if I drive fast and reckless, I ought to pay attention
to my trauma coverage. <BR>
&quot;If you have a point of service plan, you can go outside the network,
but may receive no compensation. Usually, for a specialty illness, the plan
doesn't cover it. And you can do very little under the current system, because
you're locked in for a contract year.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Knowing the system, and having your doctor as an advocate, can help. But
not always, so check on your re-enrollment options - generally, subscribers
may only switch plans once a year.  But if you voluntarily move to another
plan and have a pre-existing condition, it may not be covered.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Almighty Dollar</B><BR>
<BR>
At the root of managed care is cost, and the dollar savings on the surface
of the plan may look tempting. But take the time to sit down and actually
figure out, to the best of your ability, what a year with either plan will
cost you. Figure in everything that's covered and not covered. If a service
is not covered, call and find out what it will actually cost you to pay
for it out of the network. Figure in the cost of premiums, which are fixed
monthly contributions; co-pays, which are amounts you must contribute for
services or prescriptions; deductibles, if any, and the amounts you will
pay before insurance kicks in. Some plans cover preventive necessities,
like checkups and  immunizations, others don't. Factor in your own needs.One
important element is what insurance companies call benefit maximums. Some
plans will have lifetime maximums putting a dollar amount on care you may
receive in a lifetime. This may be ridiculous if a family member has a critical
illness. Other plans may have limits on the amount you are allowed to spend
out of network.<BR>
Once you come up with a true measure of what the cost of the plan will be
to you and your family, think about the hassle factor. Weigh the savings
against the extra you'll have to do if services you or your family need
are all the way across town.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There's a big difference between what people say they want and what
they will insist on,&quot; says McLinden. &quot;If you ask patients, they'll
say restriction is a big issue - but if the cost of the plan increases more
than $120 a year, they will give up choice.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In traditional fee-for-service plans, it wasn't so necessary to think ahead.
Now, in the managed care climate, it's beneficial to look as far ahead as
you possibly can. <BR>
<BR>
Of course, there are no guarantees - but if you ensure your family a certain
depth of coverage, and learn the system, that's one for you. <BR>
<BR>
Next month, we'll help you work the system you've chosen.              
          <BR>
<BR>
