<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Tax Reform </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Business Has Yet to Recover What it<BR>
Lost Back in 1991</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>It was the Top 10 list on which nobody wanted to be, but the cities
of Philadelphia and Pittsburgh were right at the top. <BR>
<BR>
Vertex Inc., an eastern Pennsylvania software development firm, outlined
in a detailed study the tax burden on businesses in 25 metropolitan cities.
And the message the study gave about Pennsylvania was loud and clear: We're
No. 1.<BR>
<BR>
Philadelphia and Pittsburgh were actually Nos. 1 and 2 respectively in tax
burden, both well ahead of New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and other cities.
No one should have been surprised.<BR>
<BR>
It all dated back to 1991, when the legislature and then-Gov. Robert Casey
resolved a budget impasse largely by raising taxes impacting business. The
1991 budget pushed the corporate net income tax from 8.5 percent to a national
high of 12.25 percent. On top of that they piled an increase in the capital
stock and franchise tax on corporate assets.<BR>
<BR>
And it gets worse. That year, the state eliminated the net-operating loss
carry-forward and initiated a 6 percent sales tax on a variety of computer
services, including data processing services such as those that prepare
payroll checks, as well as software writing and system design. Accountants
all around the state complained that no other state had such a tax.<BR>
<BR>
The message to business: Steer clear of  Pennsylvania.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;State taxation is a problem,&quot; Carl Johnson, chairman of Saxonburg-based
II-VI Inc. told fellow CEOs during an April panel discussion featuring the
region's high-growth companies.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;I've seen companies relocate to Ohio because of taxation, along with
workers' compensation,&quot; added another participant, First Western Bancorp
CEO Thomas P. O'Shane.<BR>
<BR>
In the final installment of Executive Report's six-month series entitled
Resuscitating the Region, ER looks at how tax reform offers an opportunity
to spur regional growth. In previous months, the magazine talked about the
importance of entrepreneurship, exporting, education, transportation and
tourism.<BR>
<BR>
This month: Tax reform.<BR>
<BR>
Looking Back<BR>
<BR>
The Vertex study that rated Philadelphia and Pittsburgh so poorly was conducted
in 1993, which was probably Pennsylvania's worst in terms of the tax burden
it levied upon businesses. Since then, business taxes in Pennsylvania have
been rolled back a bit. Nevertheless, many say there remains room, and need,
for further decreases.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You gave business a significant kick in the pants in 1991,&quot; says
Lance Shaeffer, executive director of the Greater Pittsburgh Chamber of
Commerce. &quot;We are only halfway home on that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It helps to first understand the landscape in 1991. It was then legislators
reluctantly approved, and Gov. Casey signed, a $14 billion state budget
to end a 35-day impasse. The stalemate had left the state unable to pay
its bills or its employees.<BR>
 <BR>
It was ugly. At one point in the game, legislators got into a shoving match
on the House floor in Harrisburg. When the budget passed (following an all-night
session), many unshaven and bleary-eyed lawmakers broke into applause.<BR>
<BR>
The state's 501 school districts clapped too, since their funding was about
to collectively jump by about $200 million.<BR>
<BR>
Casey signed the budget into law at 11 o'clock that night, and quickly moved
to save face before hopping into bed at the governor's mansion.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;The best we can say . . .  is that this budget restores Pennsylvania
with sound financial and fiscal footing,&quot; Casey said that night. &quot;I'm
not happy with the size of the increase or the mix of taxes found in this
bill.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
If he wasn't happy, just think how business felt.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Business Barometer<BR>
<BR>
Business wasn't happy at all. In fact, business was ready to bail out ...
of Pennsylvania, that is.<BR>
In that same year, 1991, accounting firm Coopers &amp; Lybrand partnered
with the Pennsylvania Chamber of Business and Industry to conduct what has
become an annual survey of Pennsylvania business leaders. Taken each of
the five years since then, the survey consistently has shown that more than
a third of the businesses would relocate to another state if they could.<BR>
<BR>
In the most recent survey released last September, for instance, 43 percent
of the 665 business leaders who responded said they would move to another
state if possible. <BR>
<BR>
In that same 1995 survey, more than 75 percent of respondents rated the
state's business climate as fair to poor. The 76.6 percent figure was better
than the 90.4 percent who responded the same way in 1993 and the 87 percent
who responded that way in 1994, but nevertheless it was still very high.
And in each of the surveys, taxes were rated as one of the top two concerns,
along with workers' compensation.<BR>
<BR>
So why was business force-fed the tax increases in 1991, with such backlash
practically inevitable?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Businesses don't vote,&quot; says accountant Jeffrey Wlahofsky of
Schneider Downs in Pittsburgh. &quot;Individuals vote.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
By the time Casey left office in 1994, the corporate net income tax had
been cut to 10.9 percent, but was still considered high in comparison with
 other states. Casey's successor, Gov. Tom Ridge, took it one step further
in his 1995 budget by trimming the rate to 9.9 percent, retroactive to Jan.
1 of that year. Ridge's first budget also allowed businesses to deduct the
first $100,000 in assets from the capital stock and franchise tax, an increase
from $75,000.<BR>
<BR>
Ridge also reinstated the net-operating loss carry-forward measure - eliminated
in 1991 - allowing businesses a tax credit for net-operating losses from
previous years. Until Ridge restored the net operating loss carry-forward,
Pennsylvania was the only state in the nation to assess a corporate net
income tax but not offer a net-operating loss provision. It made doing business
in Pennsylvania much more risky than in any other state. The measure still
lacks in that the loss from one year may only be carried forward for up
to three years.  In neighboring Ohio,  for example, the carry-forward is
allowed for 14 years.<BR>
<BR>
Additionally, the capital stock and franchise tax is still considered to
be high despite Ridge's increase of the deduction to the first $100,000.<BR>
<BR>
Looking Ahead<BR>
<BR>
The most recent state budget does not include the high profile cuts of 1995
- the corporate net income tax rate remains 9.9 percent - but Ridge maintains
there is relief.<BR>
<BR>
Most notably, the ridiculous computer sales tax that was created during
the 1991 budget crunch is history for businesses in manufacturing, processing
and agriculture, as well as for public utilities.<BR>
Ridge also offered tax credits for companies that created new jobs - $1,000
per employee after 25 are hired. So when an employer creates 26 new jobs,
the employer gets $26,000 in tax credits. While critics say that measure
won't do much for small businesses, Ridge maintains it's still relief that
business can seize.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Last year, we cut taxes by $286 million,&quot; the governor says.
&quot;We did it to send a signal that Pennsylvania is job-friendly. We did
it so everyone will know we are more committed than ever to retaining the
jobs we have and creating new ones. This budget continues that trend.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
There's action on other fronts, too. Jim Stalder, managing partner of Price
Waterhouse in Pittsburgh, is heading the Pennsylvania Tax Blueprint Project,
an independent, nonpartisan analysis of state tax policy that was endorsed
by the governor. The Tax Blueprint Project will develop computer-based impact
models that can be used to evaluate tax reform policies. Early findings
of benchmarking against 12 other states were due for disclosure shortly
after this article went to press.<BR>
<BR>
Longer term, any proposed tax reform can be tested to determine revenue
estimates and economic impact.<BR>
<BR>
In the end, legislators and the governor will be armed with information
enabling them to enact meaningful long-term measures that will foster economic
growth.<BR>
<BR>
As Ridge puts it: &quot;Tax cuts are an important part of our economic development
strategy.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
