<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Exclusive Publishers Report </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>The South: Boomtowns Turned Zoomtowns</FONT> </B><I>By
Lind A Dickerson</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Greenville was a sleepy southern city 30 years ago. Today, Greenville
and the county that surrounds it are the economic development meccas of
the South, boasting      9 percent population growth over the past five
years while consistently holding unemployment rates well below 3 percent.
The last available numbers put Greenville's unemployment at 1.3 percent,
and much of South Carolina brags a similar track record.<BR>
<BR>
Sound like winning numbers? It gets better.<BR>
<BR>
Capital investments in South Carolina reached a state record $5.4 billion
in 1995 - the first year of Gov. David Beasley's administration - and new
jobs created neared 24,000. Michelin and Nucor each invested about $500
million, while Nan Ya Plastics and Amoco each invested $300 million. International
firms accounted for $1.8 billion of the $5.4 billion in new investment enabling
the state to stake its claim as a truly globalized region.<BR>
<BR>
The unassailable barometer of a vibrant economy, however, is always the
degree to which existing enterprises are growing in the economy. Here South
Carolina outperforms most other economies as well: Existing industry was
responsible for 84 percent of the state's total incremental capital investment.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When you win, it's fun,&quot; says Robert V. Royal, a retired banker
who currently is South Carolina's Secretary of Commerce. Royal says Beasley
effectively leveraged his cabinet to proactively encourage business and
the state legislature to locate and grow new investments within the state.
But government is not alone in its efforts to grow the economy. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's a good partnership between local and state government, and in
most cases, the private sector,&quot; Royal says. &quot;It takes both to
make it happen.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Why Greenville?<BR>
<BR>
A prominently displayed brochure in the lobby of the Greenville Chamber
of Commerce poses the following question: &quot;With an entire continent
to choose from, where in the world did Michelin put their North American
headquarters?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The answer, of course, is Greenville. And why not? Greenville is in many
ways the Camelot of the Carolinas.<BR>
<BR>
In addition to the symbiosis between business and government, Greenville
boasts a strong work ethic, a high quality of life and a less than  2 percent
rate of unionization, factors Royal believes stimulate South Carolina's
unmatched ability to grow companies.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Nowhere in the world had [Michelin] seen people with a stronger work
ethic,&quot; the commerce secretary says. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The people were the single biggest reason that this region developed,&quot;
adds long-time Greenville resident Buck Mickel. &quot; We believe in a partnership
between business, government and the people.<BR>
Tom Wyche, a prominent Green-ville attorney and a pillar in the community,
asserts that Greenville's growth hinges on its environmental appeal and
its concomitant high quality of life. Admitting that historically the low
cost of land and labor were always factors, Wyche attributes the community's
most recent expansion to its tremendous appeal as a great place to live.<BR>
Less than an hour from the Blue Ridge Mountains and surrounded by beautiful
lakes, Greenville is gorgeous. And its consistently warm climate is also
one of its biggest assets. At 320,127 residents, Greenville is South Carolina's
most populous county. It's no wonder. People are flocking to the area to
take advantage of the burgeoning employment opportunities and the beautiful
surroundings.<BR>
Each of the 21 attorneys practicing at Wyche's firm, Wyche Burgess Herman
&amp; Parham, is a graduate of a top law school. Over 90 percent carry sheepskins
from Harvard, Yale or the University of Virginia. Wyche contends that Greenville's
outstanding cultural amenities and unmatched natural beauty enable his firm
to recruit the nation's best and brightest. And when you ask these Greenville
recruits how they like it there, they give you a resounding &quot;We love
it.&quot;<BR>
Wyche is not alone in his assessment. Thomas Barton, the founder and 34-year-veteran
president of Greenville Technical College, describes the region that spawned
his stalwart institution as &quot;a combination of companies and counties.&quot;
A long-time observer of Greenville's rags to riches development, Barton
contends, &quot;There's a new spirit here over the past decade. It's just
like a new city springing up.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Foreign Investment<BR>
<BR>
Greenville's growth is anchored in direct foreign investment. More than
231 international firms from 18 nations selected the upstate (Greenville
and surrounding areas) as their U.S. home, placing this region among the
highest per capita for foreign investment of any metropolitan statistical
area in the country.<BR>
<BR>
Renowned Harvard scholar Rosabeth Moss Kanter chose Greenville and nearby
Spartanburg as one of only five regions in the nation to feature in her
newly released book &quot;World Class.&quot; Kanter categorizes the Greenville/Spartanburg
area as a &quot;maker,&quot; which she defines as those regions that &quot;attract
world manufacturing because of their competence, and are thus magnets for
foreign investment.&quot;  Together, Greenville and Spartanburg have the
highest per capita diversified foreign investment in the United States.<BR>
<BR>
Perhaps the most celebrated international recruit is BMW, which opened production
at its Spartanburg plant in 1994. BMW's total investment in the upstate
region is expected to top $750 million, and projections indicate that over
8,000 peripheral jobs will be created because of BMW.<BR>
Then there is international player Michelin, a 20-year veteran of the upstate.
Michelin's investment began with a tire manufacturing facility in 1973.
By 1985, the Michelin Group of France decided to locate its North American
corporate headquarters in Greenville.<BR>
<BR>
Unlike Charleston, S.C., which has in its port an inherent connection to
the outside world, Greenville's integration with the world stems from the
business community's conscious decision to build their economy on direct
foreign investment.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Business Leads<BR>
<BR>
Max Hellar, who led the development charge first as mayor of Greenville
and then from the South Carolina Department of Commerce, says business was
proactive in triggering regional growth. Himself a highly successful textile
manufacturer early in his career, Hellar asserts, &quot;We [government]
tried to be the spark plug. Business was the engine.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One of the most coveted community leadership positions that one can hold
is to be a member of the chamber's esteemed Headquarters Recruitment Committee.
Prospects are afforded the utmost in southern hospitality when they visit
Greenville, but recruitment doesn't stop there. Four to five times annually,
the recruitment committee hits the road looking for prospects.<BR>
<BR>
When offered a tour of Pittsburgh, FOCUS Management Development Inc. President
Richard Harpum said wryly, &quot;You don't want us in Pittsburgh. We steal
companies.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
And when the companies come, finding skilled labor is not a problem. Harpum
says the area's quality of life enables it to attract people from outside
the region. As a result, they view their labor pool as the rest of the universe.
Since the supply of labor worldwide would never exceed Greenville's demand
for labor, Greenvillians think their cost of labor is stable over the long-term.<BR>
<BR>
Charleston Port<BR>
<BR>
What Greenville lacks, Charleston has in a deep water port that provides
a natural link to the rest of the globe. The second largest port facility
in the East, the Port of Charleston is the key driver of Charleston's economy
and is the connection to the rest of the globe for much of South Carolina.
<BR>
A recent economic impact study conducted by the South Carolina State Ports
Authority indicates that the ports generate $1.5 billion in personal income
annually. This study also credits the ports with creating 66,000 jobs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're an opportunity even for those not ready to use us yet,&quot;
says Anne Mose, director of public relations for the South Carolina State
Ports Authority. &quot;We've gotten to the point where success breeds success.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Because South Carolina built its economy on an international base, the Charleston
Port anchors much of the state's development efforts. From 200 miles east,
Greenville uses the Charleston Port as a critical component of its foreign
investment-based growth strategies. Serving as the nation's sixth largest
containment port, the Charleston Port handled 10.6 million tons of cargo
last year.<BR>
The Port moves cargo an average of two days faster than other ports, providing
South Carolina yet another advantage in luring firms doing business in international
markets. Easy interstate highway access and cost-effective rail transportation
add value to the Port, which in turn builds the state's capacity to attract
new industry. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Other Factors<BR>
<BR>
Some believe that South Carolina gives away the store to attract new industry
within its borders. It does give incentives, but how much weight those incentives
carry is a matter of debate.<BR>
&quot;Incentives are not the No. 1 thing you look for,&quot; says A.J. Batia,
vice president and general plant manager for Bayer Corp.'s Bush Park Plant
in Charleston.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I don't believe that incentives are the end-all,&quot; adds Ben Cole,
executive director of the Charleston Regional Development Alliance.<BR>
<BR>
Just look at South Carolina's strong education foundation, thanks in part
to the work of Greenville Technical School's Barton, who led the charge
in creating an ambitious program three decades ago to provide globally competitive
work forces to existing companies as well as corporations exploring relocation
in the South. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In order to attract industry, you have to have something to bring
them here,&quot; Barton says. &quot;We don't care what you tell us that
you need. Whatever you need to make you competitive - worldwide machinery,
engineering, text books, teaching - we'll provide it.&quot; South Carolina's
Special Schools Program uses community colleges and technical schools throughout
the state to train work forces to meet existing or incoming industry needs.
Industry pays nothing for this training, which is frequently delivered on
site.<BR>
<BR>
Art Cann II, plant manager of Global Manufacturing Inc., credits the Special
Schools program as a key variable in Global's decision to locate a manufacturing
site in Charleston. At Global, the company establishes the curriculum, while
the state supplies - at taxpayer expense - the manuals and instructors.<BR>
<BR>
Southern Hospitality<BR>
<BR>
Ronald Hubner, president of Hubner Manufacturing Corp., says his reception
in Mt. Pleasant, S.C., was so special it swayed his decision to locate his
business there. Recruitment southern style involved dinner invitations to
local political leaders' houses. When NISE EAST arrived on the scene in
Charleston, the three counties surrounding Charleston jointly sponsored
a barbecue for all NISE EAST employees who were relocating there. In addition
to the 1,400 people NISE EAST will add to the area's employment rosters,
this consolidated naval engineering center will also serve as a strong magnet
for high tech firms  subcontracting to the Navy. <BR>
<BR>
On the other side of the state in Greenville, stories of generous entertainment
budgets and full-time recruiters abound. Visitors are treated as royalty.
Business people join economic development professionals to wine and dine
myriad individuals from around the world.<BR>
<BR>
Boomtowns and Zoomtowns<BR>
<BR>
After several pro-business state governments, all of South Carolina has
coalesced around economic development, and virtually everyone out to make
a buck is an economic development agent. The state's impressive track record
in meeting the needs of both domestic and international companies alike
stems from a variety of strengths. An appealing climate, a strong work ethic,
a reasonable cost of living, a business-friendly political environment and
relatively low corporate taxes number among the factors compelling businesses
worldwide to take note of the Palmetto State.<BR>
<BR>
The term &quot;gone south&quot; is no longer equated with a &quot;turn for
the worse.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The South is booming, with exponential growth rates the norm rather than
the exception. Greenville and Charleston became boomtowns by riding the
southern growth wave. However, both communities became zoomtowns because
of their burning desire to assume their rightful place in the world. This
intense southern pride, coupled with good old-fashioned southern hospitality,
created forces with which the world must reckon. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
