    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Special Supplement : United Way </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>Building a Better Community Together</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Linda A Dickerson</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When it comes to fiscal accountability, strategic direction, customer
satisfaction and return on investment, which local business segments come
to mind? Our banking community? Manufacturing? Our burgeoning high technology
industry? Or how about the ever-increasing cadre of entre-preneurial ventures?<BR>
<BR>
How about our local United Way?<BR>
<BR>
For each of the past several years, United Way of Southwestern Pennsyl-vania
has raised $35 million for area health and human service programs. Through
a thoughtful allocations <BR>
process, United Way gifts are distributed to a network of nearly 300 effective
human service programs that counsel and protect battered women, reunite
and strengthen families, protect our youth from violence, care for our elderly
and provide other critical services. <BR>
<BR>
United Way also connects more than 20,000 local people each year with the
counseling, protection from abuse and violence, food, clothing, shelter
and other vital resources they need. And it engages thousands of local people
in volunteer service to their neighbors.<BR>
<BR>
United Way does all of this - and more - at a cost of under 13 cents per
dollar.<BR>
<BR>
Yet another key lesson we in the business community can learn from United
Way is the importance and effectiveness of partnering - of pooling resources
and addressing an issue on a united front rather than in isolation. United
Way is in a unique position: it cuts across all boundaries - real or imagined
- between service providers, funders, the business community and other groups,
and brings them to the table to address our community's most critical problems.
And no other organization has such a kaleidoscopic view of our community's
health and human services - a view of the &quot;big picture&quot; rather
than one agency or one issue.<BR>
<BR>
This Executive Report supplement highlights a few of the partnerships our
community has asked United Way to become involved in just because of these
attributes. I hope you enjoy reading this supplement. More important, I
hope you join Executive Report in supporting our United Way as it continues
its unique role in helping to improve the quality of life for all of us.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Collaboration key to turning<BR>
addiction into hope</B><BR>
<BR>
Each morning brings a rush of decisions: which suit to wear to work, which
alternate road to use to avoid Parkway traffic, what to eat for breakfast,
whether or not to reschedule a meeting to free up some time. The list goes
on. <BR>
<BR>
For Sandra, a young woman trying to raise a 1-year-old with another baby
on the way, morning decisions amounted to deciding whether to buy milk for
the baby or drugs for herself. <BR>
<BR>
Because of a series of setbacks culminating in the death of her grandmother
who raised her, Sandra had become addicted to crack cocaine. But she wanted
out. She wanted her own house. A healthy baby. A good job. And, most importantly,
she wanted to reunite her family, which included a son living with a relative.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I planned to stop using drugs and get my life together,&quot; she
remembers. &quot;But each time my money would come, the drug man would come,
too.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That was two years ago. Since then, Sandra's not touched drugs. She moved
out of a housing community and into a beautifully furnished home in Oakland.
She has a job as a nursing assistant. She bought a new car. And she has
her family back together again - all because of the Homewood/ Brushton Community
Collaborative, one of three unique partnerships of human service nonprofits
serving substance abusing women and their children. Others are helping change
lives in the Hill District and McKeesport.<BR>
<BR>
The Community Collaboratives were begun by United Way with the support of
local foundations nearly four years ago. Their aim was to introduce the
concept of collaboration to the human service industry, which had never
before cooperated, communicated and coordinated services to people in need
to the extent that the present Collaboratives do. Each of the Collaboratives
developed action plans to coordinate existing services, identify service
gaps and design initiatives to assure substance abusing women and their
children a &quot;continuum&quot; of care.<BR>
<BR>
Without the Collaborative, women like Sandra literally would have run all
over the area, hoping bus connections would get them to medical treatment
for their addiction, to help with housing needs, to marital and family counseling,
to job skills training and employment counseling, to legal advice, to healthcare,
and to parenting support groups. The partnership among United Way, local
foundations, governmental agencies and nonprofit providers participating
in the Collaboratives has created a single, one-stop source of help and
support. This, in turn, has strengthened more than 1,200 families by helping
mothers regain their self-sufficiency.<BR>
<B><BR>
Joining forces to make summer <BR>
productive for teens</B><BR>
<BR>
Last summer, Kenneth Johnson, an 18-year-old who lives in Pittsburgh's Hill
District, and Tina Martin, an 18-year-old Manchester resident, both worked
for the City, he in the General Services area helping to maintain the fleet
of vehicles, she in a project that installed heating and air conditioning
in renovated homes. And 19-year-old Gareth Davis II worked in the day care
center at the Wilkinsburg YWCA.<BR>
<BR>
Based on a report of the Employ-ment Policies Institute, these three local
youth will do significantly better and make more money out in the &quot;real
world&quot; than their non-working contemporaries.<BR>
That's one of the reasons a group of local companies and organizations,
including United Way, come together for YouthWorks '96, the Youth Employment
Initiative to develop summer jobs for local youth. Chairing the initiative
are Fred Thieman, U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania
and chair of the Youth Violence Prevention Council; David Brewton, executive
director, Breach-menders, Inc., and Dianna Green, senior vice president,
Customer Operations, Duquesne Light Company. <BR>
<BR>
Green points to the employment initiative's benefits for local businesses.
&quot;Research shows employers reap dividends when they invest in human
capital - their productivity increases, which in turn benefits economic
development,&quot; Green adds.<BR>
<BR>
The Youth Employment Initiative is working to develop 1,800 jobs from the
public and private sectors. Key to the project is the preparation of youth
for their work roles and the participation of Olsten Staffing Services which
is helping to make sure the match between employers and youth are suitable
for both.<BR>
<BR>
The results? Look at more statistics from the Employment Policies Institute:
People who didn't work in high school were almost twice as likely to be
unemployed after 12 years, and kids who worked when in school earned $1,300
to $1,600 a year more than those with no early work experience.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Be a good neighbor... volunteer</B><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Buoyed by positive volunteer experiences with United Way Day of Caring and
other community service projects, Bayer Corporation wanted to develop a
formal way to engage employees in regular volunteer activities. But how?<BR>
<BR>
United Way Leadership contributor, Dan Grealish, president of Henderson
Brothers Inc., wanted to mobilize his fellow insurance industry professionals
in a day of volunteering: United Way Day of Caring with the Insurance Industry.
Where could he go for assistance?<BR>
<BR>
Nate Bodin, a junior at Upper St. Clair High School, is a leader when it
comes to organizing volunteer projects for his fellow students. But where
can he find information on projects that address the community issues he
and his fellow students are interested in?<BR>
<BR>
City Theatre wanted to improve the way it recruits and uses volunteers -
volunteers who can help not just with day-to-day tasks like designing sets
but volunteers who can lend their professional expertise in areas such as
marketing. But who is the local expert in such topics?<BR>
Good Neighbors, a partnership between United Way and the local foundation
and business community, can help people and groups like these. A service
of United Way, Good Neighbors is our community's newest and most comprehensive
resource for those who want to volunteer.<BR>
Good Neighbors quickly and efficiently matches people and companies with
volunteer experiences through a database of thousands of volunteer opportunities.
Potential volunteers can find tasks suited precisely to their expertise,
interest, schedule and location. <BR>
<BR>
And the volunteer opportunities aren't limited solely to human services.
Rather they include those in education, arts and culture, religion, government,
business and other public and private sector initiatives. Good Neighbors
also provides an array of support services including training and technical
assistance, recruitment, and recognition. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Volunteers can lend their expertise, new ideas and cost-efficiency
benefits to the community,&quot; notes Jane Burger, executive director of
the Grable Foundation. &quot;And with Good Neigh-bors, we can build on the
capacity of nonprofits to use volunteer resources which is critical in this
time of shifting dollars.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Is your company interested in helping the community and building teamwork
and morale with a volunteer program? Call Good Neighbors at 394-5380.<BR>
<BR>
<B>United Way, WTAE team up to support children, families</B><BR>
<BR>
Two-year-old Missy looks forward to the day care center her parents drop
her off at each morning on their way to work at a downtown bank. At the
center, Missy enjoys a safe, nurturing environment offering her a variety
of educational, cultural and social activities. She's learned to count to
10 and recite the alphabet, except she still has trouble with her Fs and
Rs.<BR>
Jeremy, another 2-year-old, lives with his grandmother because his mother,
a single parent without a job, tries to overcome a substance abuse problem.
Jeremy's grandmother cares for him most of the time, except when she cleans
homes to make money for the family. Then, he is shuffled off to one of the
neighbors' houses where he watches TV most of the day, not all of it aimed
at children.<BR>
Which child has the better chance of growing up to be productive, responsible
and happy? Statistics tip the odds in favor of Missy, who is receiving the
nurturing and stimulation needed in children her age. For example, &quot;The
Challenge to Achieve,&quot; a report of the Allegheny County Policy Council,
notes that children who enter school unprepared are often doomed to school
failure and that children who begin behind generally stay behind.<BR>
<BR>
Another partnership involving United Way is helping to create greater awareness
of the needs of our children and their families: SUCCESS BY 6. WTAE-TV invited
United Way to join in this two-year public service program. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;SUCCESS BY 6 is the next logical step following our FamilyWorks! campaign
to bring even greater focus to those issues that impact the well-being of
our children,&quot; notes WTAE-TV Vice President and General Manager Jim
Hefner. &quot;We are honored to be joined by such community leaders as United
Way. Together, we hope to make a significant contribution to the cause of
children.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The public service program includes SUCCESS BY 6 spots, each featuring a
different topic related to early childhood development and family support.
In addition, special programming such as &quot;Our Children: A Crying Shame,&quot;
are featured in WTAE-TV's prime-time line-up. Many of these specials feature
a phone bank to offer viewers the United Way HelpLine number to call for
more information on community resources - and for volunteer opportunities
that enable local people to help our community's children and families.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, WTAE-TV and United Way are developing community outreach projects
that will bring SUCCESS BY 6 to local neighborhoods.<BR>
<BR>
