<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0696.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0596.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0696.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Summer Construction </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>Union vs. Nonunion Contractors</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Christopher Lawton</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Several years ago, a Macy's Department store was scheduled to be
built at one of the nation's largest shopping malls near Philadelphia. The
200,000 square-foot project occupied three levels of retail space and included
several ornate German escalators, which were preassembled in Germany and
shipped up the Delaware River. All workers had to do was install them at
the store, but that's where things got complicated.<BR>
<BR>
Because the escalators came preassembled, one union realized that there
would be a loss of work for its members. Construction was immediately halted
as workers for the elevator subcontractor called a strike against the entire
mall project. To end the strike, a deal was ultimately negotiated with the
union whereby the workers would be paid to disassemble the escalators, then
reassemble them for inclusion in the mall. <BR>
<BR>
This delay of work and subsequent disassemble and reassemble cost several
months of work and hundreds of thousands of dollars in cost increases.<BR>
<BR>
Sound all too familiar? Stories like these have haunted union contractors
in the past. But more recently, these same contractors are pointing to their
share of fairy tale endings. Most notably, the $1 billion Midfield Terminal
project at Pittsburgh International Airport &shyp; a union job &shyp; came
to completion on time without any work stoppages. &quot;Old perceptions
generally aren't true anymore about the unions,&quot; says Jack Ramage,
secretary of the Master Builders' Association, an umbrella group consisting
of union contractors. &quot;The unions have become more flexible and competitive
in order to progress with their nonunion counterparts.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Union and nonunion contractors could debate for hours. Most nonunion, or
open-shop contractors, will tell you that union construction is more costly
because union wages are higher. On the other hand, most union contractor's
will counter that union construction may be more costly, but the quality
of workmanship is higher because union workers are better skilled and receive
ongoing safety training.<BR>
<BR>
In reality, there is truth in what both have to say.  <BR>
<BR>
The Union Contractors<BR>
<BR>
The Master Builders' Association has chapters all over the United States
and in Pittsburgh is made up of over 100 different member companies associated
with union construction. All of Pittsburgh's larger construction companies
are represented, as well as, general contractors, law firms and insurance
companies. <BR>
<BR>
Originally formed to negotiate with the unions over labor issues, in the
last 10 years the MBA has formed more of a partnership with the unions.
Ramage says this change came about because of the influx of the open-shop
competition.<BR>
<BR>
The MBA still finds itself negotiating collective bargaining agreements
with the four main trade unions, including the carpenters, laborers, cement
masons and operating engineers. But in addition, the MBA also provides ongoing
training to union workers, which Ramage says results in better quality and
explains the higher labor costs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A portion of the union worker's wage, whether they're a carpenter
or a general laborer, is paid to the MBA to provide [the worker] with ongoing
education in their trade,&quot; Ramage says.<BR>
<BR>
Then there's worksite safety, where the MBA says it also holds an edge by
providing some 500 on-site safety consultations and safety training seminars
during the year with the various contractors.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our safety representative goes to the site and performs a mock OSHA
inspection, to let the job-site superintendent know where he's weak,&quot;
says Ramage. The safety department of the MBA will also represent individual
contractors if they in fact are cited by OSHA for any job-site violations.<BR>
<BR>
Douglas Dick, the Dick Corp. president who holds the same title with the
MBA, gets right to the point.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I've driven by a number of the larger nonunion job sites and most
of them are using unsafe work practices,&quot; Dick says. &quot;The nonunion
contractors are simply unable, because of cost, to provide an adequate safety
training program for their workers. In some cases the contractors themselves
haven't been educated about job safety issues.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Is Price a Priority?<BR>
<BR>
Jack Mascaro, president of union contractor Mascaro Inc., says he usually
declines when his company is asked by a developer to bid against a nonunion
contractor.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;By and large it's difficult to beat a nonunion contractor if the owner
is only buying on price,&quot; Mascaro says.<BR>
<BR>
This is because in many cases the nonunion contractor can and will underbid
the union contractor's asking price.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But,&quot; says Mascaro, &quot;if the owner is more interested in
best value, consisting of price, quality performance and service, then we
can compete.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
How often does that happen? In today's construction economy, most builders
are concerned with union constructions cost. &quot;Any nonunion contractor
can be cheaper if they want to. Unfortunately, many clients have a tendency
to only look at the bottom line on bid day. What they don't anticipate is
that often with nonunion work, there's going to be a change in work orders,
as well as situations throughout the job that will make costs go up,&quot;
says Ramage. <BR>
<BR>
So when it's all said and done, Ramage says, union contractors may do it
just as cheaply as their nonunion competitors with more attention to skill
and safety. <BR>
<BR>
Rich DeYoung, chief operating officer of the architectural firm Williams
Trebilcock Whitehead, says his firm has worked with both union and nonunion
contractors and had great success with both of them. DeYoung agrees with
the union contractors' position that they offer more in terms of quality
labor.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Some of the primary differences are that the union trades have an
apprenticeship program, a way to formally train the craftspeople, and they
also have a skilled labor pool available at all times,&quot; says DeYoung.<BR>
<BR>
Nonunion construction, on the other hand, is usually made up of out-of-work
union-construction workers, workers just out of trade schools or people
who are beginning a second career.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;While theirs is not as formal a kind of training as their union counterparts,
the larger contractors generally work with the same people and therefore
provide a more informal type of training for them,&quot; adds DeYoung. <BR>
<BR>
The only real disadvantage DeYoung sees with union construction is in the
area of work rules. If you're from a particular trade on a union job site,
you can't perform another trade's work. So a carpenter can't unload a truck,
they must let someone from the trucking company do it for them. Construction
companies in this position often aren't able to use their work force in
the most efficient manner because of union rules. However, DeYoung notes
that even this rule is changing today.<BR>
&quot;Unions and construction companies are beginning to work together because
they know, bottom line, that this is affecting overall cost and job effectiveness,&quot;
says DeYoung. &quot;Unions today realize that they're bidding for work against
nonunion contractors, so while there might have been a significant division
between the unions and nonunions 10 years ago in terms of cost, the unions
are working to decrease that gap.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They're much more cooperative with union contractors, allowing them
to do things more efficiently at the job-site.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In the Pittsburgh construction market there is a trend toward job-site cooperation
between union and nonunion contractors. Many projects use both types of
contractors to complete building contracts. <BR>
<BR>
Other markets are not so lucky. This is due mainly because of a shortage
of a skilled union labor force in other markets. Pittsburgh has not felt
this shortage due to the sheer number of contractors &shyp; 1,000 or so
independent nonunion contractors operating within the metropolitan area.<BR>
<BR>
DeYoung does cite some nonunion contractors, such as Bridges &amp; Company,
that perform high quality work. However, he's quick to point out that, by
and large, there are many more qualified union contractors than there are
nonunion counterparts.<BR>
<BR>
The FMS Network Inc. is a company that represents and finds for its clients
various types of contractors to perform labor and service tasks. At times,
they represent both union and nonunion laborers, and as company President
David W. Buckley states, &quot;You find good and bad work practices with
both types.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In a region such as Pittsburgh, many of the skilled laborers are swallowed
up by the union contractors because the industry is busy. &quot;However,
since the closing of the steel mills in the 1980s, there are more skilled
ex-union laborers in the market who are working for themselves, performing
the same tasks that they did when they were union,&quot; says Buckley. Buckley
sees this shift as one of the primary reasons there are more quality construction
choices in this market, and many of those are nonunion.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The quality of union or nonunion work depends upon the work ethics
of the owners and senior management. If they have a high work ethic, it's
often relayed to the workers, and if so the job runs smoothly and within
budget. If they don't have a high work ethic, things obviously don't run
smoothly and there is a lot of waste on the job site in terms of building
costs. The latter is an example of contractors I won't work with if I suspect
or know these things in advance,&quot; says Buckley.<BR>
<BR>
 Buckley points out that whether or not someone chooses a union or nonunion
contractor, they should thoroughly inspect their work habits on past job
sites and get a feeling from the contractor that they are legitimate and
honest.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I would check their references and find out as much information about
them before they set foot on the job site. This is what we do for our customers
to ensure a proper match of labor to the task.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In this way, the job is implemented successfully and within their
budget,&quot; says Buckley.<BR>
The bottom line: whether or not a developer decides to use one or the other
type of contractors is unimportant. What is important is that they choose
the contractor who is going to give them the best value for their money.
The highest attention to detail with a minimum of waste and a maximum of
value.	<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
