BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>A Gamble </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Labor is Spending Big Bucks in Support of<BR>
Clinton and Congressional Democrats</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR><BR>
The questioner wanted to know why the Republicans were doing such a lousy
job of getting their message out in advance of the presidential election.
And how were the Democrats doing such a good job of getting their message
out?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When people ask me that,&quot; Republican U.S. Sen. Rick Santorum
replied, &quot;I ask them how long it's been since they have written out
a check to the Republican party.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That wasn't the answer the questioner - in this case a small business owner
from Pittsburgh - wanted to hear. Nevertheless, Santorum hit the nail on
the head.<BR>
<BR>
While unfortunate, it appears that President Clinton could win another term
thanks to financial clout of special interest groups such as organized labor,
which will spend about $35 million supporting Clinton and congressional
Democrats with advertising in advance of this November's election.<BR>
And don't think Republican leaders aren't a little worried. That question
posed to Santorum was also posed by Newt Gingrich during a spring meeting
with Republican National Committee Chairman Haley Barbour and other party
operatives. Gingrich told party leaders that something needed to be done
to offset the media blitz by Democrats and organized labor. And everyone
at the GOP meeting, including advisers to Republican nominee Robert Dole,
agreed that the advertisements were taking their toll.<BR>
<BR>
This election is coming down to money, and the Republicans may not have
enough of it.<BR>
<BR>
The Democrats began their hard-edged television blitz - at the rate of $1
million in paid advertising per week - a year ago. The campaign began with
a barrage of ads designed to shore up Clinton's stand on crime. Later, the
Democrats slammed Republicans' proposed Medicare cuts and GOP lawmakers'
efforts to limit the increase in spending for environmental protection.
Labor mixed in its own spots.<BR>
<BR>
The ads were precisely targeted, running in states that can turn a presidential
election, including Pennsylvania, Michigan, Ohio, Illinois and Wisconsin.
<BR>
<BR>
I find labor's role in all of this quite interesting. I guess if you belong
to a union, consider the heavy financial support for Democrats as your dues
money at work. All this despite exit polls from the 1994 elections - when
Republicans won a Congressional majority - showing that 40 percent of self-identified
union members voted for Republican candidates.<BR>
<BR>
To me, it looks like this: Labor is gambling with its money. In the 1990s,
unions saw their base decline to 15 percent of the work force and only 10.4
percent of the private sector. What growth there was occurred mainly in
public employee unions. <BR>
<BR>
If labor puts Clinton back in for a second term and swings the Congressional
majority back to the Democrats, it has re-established itself as a formidable
political operation and a powerful voice within the Democratic Party. <BR>
<BR>
If the Republicans win the White House - and if you haven't guessed, I hope
they do - organized labor will have sealed its own fate as a nonfactor in
American politics. And you can bet labor will feel the Republican wrath.
<BR>
<BR>
During the GOP's brief hold on the majority, Republicans have threatened
to ease penalties for work place safety law violations, repeal the Davis-Bacon
Act propping up construction workers wages and hold down growth in Medicare
and Medicaid spending. They also fought the minimum wage increase. <BR>
<BR>
More will come, with labor paying a heavy price. It's quite a gamble, one
that may not pay off.                              <BR>
