<P><B><IMG SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Thinking Ahead<BR>
A Few ounces of Prevention Now Will<BR>
Pay Dividends Latewr for Impoverished Youth</FONT SIZE> <FONT size=+1></FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher <BR clear=all>
</I></B><HR>The choice between prevention and intervention should be a simple
decision. Prevention generally costs less - much less - and it takes care
of problems before they occur.  <BR>
<BR>
Yet, society continues to rely on intervention strategies to mitigate its
problems. Why? <BR>
United Way's Early Childhood Initiative offers Allegheny County's low-income
preschool children true hope for a promising future and is an example of
prevention. Research shows that children born into poverty often struggle
to succeed in school and sometimes engage in violent behavior later in life.
<BR>
<BR>
Through the Early Childhood Initiative, United Way hopes to provide an escape
route for impoverished youngsters. The initiative will deliver high-quality,
affordable early education to low-income preschoolers in Allegheny County.<BR>
<BR>
The Allegheny Policy Council's &quot;Challenge to Achieve&quot; report asserts,
&quot;Children who begin behind, generally stay behind.&quot; The costs
to this community of children &quot;staying behind&quot; are immense. Allegheny
County's annual expenditures for child welfare, juvenile detention, juvenile
probation and principal alternative juvenile probation programs total $131
million.<BR>
<BR>
Despite these burgeoning costs, only 7,800 of Allegheny County's 18,000
preschoolers living in poverty currently receive comprehensive family support,
subsidized child care or publicly funded early education. <BR>
<BR>
The positive correlation between poverty and seriously substandard performance
in school and between poverty and violent behavior is irrefutable. Poor
performers and high- school dropouts swell the welfare rolls, exacting a
hefty investment from society. Similarly, incarceration for violent offenders
costs Allegheny County taxpayers approximately $44,000 per jailed individual.<BR>
<BR>
The Early Childhoo Initiative is asking this community to invest approximately
$3,500 per low-income child in early education programs. It's a pay now
or pay more - much more - later decision. The $3,500 investment is a prudent
one.<BR>
<BR>
Poverty need not sentence children to a life on welfare row or death row.
Society knows that early education significantly enhances a young person's
opportunity to succeed. <BR>
<BR>
Prevention at an early age is an investment. Intervention at a later age
is a cost.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
