<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H5Guest.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Sexual Harrasment</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>It's Not Only Against the Law,</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>It's Wrong and Can Hurt Your Business</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By James B. Brown</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P> surge in sexual harassment complaints in Pennsylvania over the past
few years should compel employers to seek to eradicate any  such problems
in their own workplaces. For besides being against the law,  it's wrong
and it's bad for business.<BR>
<BR>
Many attribute the increase in sexual harassment complaints to the Anita
Hill-Clarence Thomas sexual harassment hearings in 1991, which thrust the
issue into the national spotlight and raised public awareness about unacceptable
behavior in the workplace in Pennsylvania and nationwide.<BR>
<BR>
In 1990-91 there were 191 sexual harassment complaints filed with the Pennsylvania
Human Relations Commission. By 1993-94, the number increased precipitously,
to 738 complaints. <BR>
<BR>
The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission recognizes two kinds of sexual
harassment. &quot;Quid pro quo&quot; harassment occurs when an individual
is subject to sexual advances, when conduct of a sexual nature is used as
a basis for employer decisions affecting the individual, or when the individual
is subject to such conduct as a term or condition of employment. &quot;Hostile
environment&quot; harassment occurs when unwelcome sexual conduct interferes
with an individual's job performance or creates a hostile, intimidating
or offensive work environment even if it does not result in tangible or
economic job consequences. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Bad for Business<BR>
</B><BR>
All employers must take proactive steps to prohibit sexual harassment in
the workplace and clearly communicate their sexual harassment policy to
employees.  Defending against a sexual harassment lawsuit can have a devastating
cost in money, employee morale and public image. <BR>
 <BR>
While most complaints typically have come from women working in blue-collar,
traditionally male-dominated work environments, there are a growing number
of lawsuits in white collar companies. The Wall Street brokerage firm of
Smith Barney Inc., for example, is currently battling a lawsuit where the
plaintiffs charge that the firm routinely discriminates against female employees
and has retaliated against women who complain about sexual harassment. 
Baker &amp; McKenzie, the world's largest law firm, had to pay $3.5 million
in punitive damages to a female secretary who sued the firm for sexual harassment.<BR>
<BR>
A 1995 report, &quot;Sexual Harassment in the Federal Workplace,&quot; found
that nearly half of all incidents against workers at federal work sites
go unreported and only 6 percent of workers file official complaints. Experts
say these statistics also apply to the private sector.<BR>
<BR>
The actual number of sexual harassment incidents is likely much larger than
that because many companies resolve sexual harassment complaints with employees
on their own. And some employees are reluctant to lodge a formal complaint,
and do so only as a last resort. <BR>
<BR>
In most sexual harassment lawsuits, the harassed employee does not sue the
harasser but rather the employer, the one with the deep pockets.<BR>
<BR>
Juries are doling out increasingly harsh penalties to employers whose employees
convince them that the employer condoned or failed to eradicate a hostile
work environment.  Verdicts with draconian punitive damage awards hit large
employers hard and can wipe out smaller companies. In Kimzey v. Wal-Mart
Stores, Inc., for example, the employer had to pay  $50 million in punitive
damages for not doing enough to prevent harassment in the workplace. In
Rush v. Scott Specialty Gases Inc., a federal court jury penalized the employer
by awarding a former employee 10 percent of the company's assets: That's
$4.2 million plus attorneys fees. <BR>
 <BR>
Every company needs a well-publicized policy against sexual harassment that
contains easily followed procedures for employees to file sexual harassment
complaints. The policy also must ensure that potential victims of workplace
harassment have protection from retaliation, enabling victims to come forward
as soon as an incident occurs.  Most importantly, there should be zero tolerance
for sexual harassment and the policy must be enforced 100 percent of the
time.<BR>
<BR>
Sexual harassment is wrong. The law says so, and juries have and continue
to penalize irresponsible employers accordingly.<BR>
                                           <BR>
James B. Brown is an attorney with Cohen &amp; Grigsby in Pittsburgh who
 concentrates his practice in defending employers in discrimination and
other employment litigation matters.<BR>
<HR><BR>
