<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.GuestEditorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Olympic Tickets: Check Out This Price Markup</B><BR>
<BR>
Publisher Linda Dickerson tells the story of Atlanta's success as a hotbed
of entrepreneurial activity, beginning on page 27.<BR>
<BR>
But here's another Atlanta story, compliments of ER staffer Cynthia Bent,
a fencing enthusiast who is headed south this month to the Olympics:<BR>
<BR>
Prices charged by the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games for tickets
to the men's and women's fencing at this month's games: $11 for preliminaries,
$35 for finals.<BR>
<BR>
Prices charged by Aarons Worldwide Tickets of Bala Cynwyd, Pa., for tickets
to the exact same events: $75 and $125.<BR>
<BR>
That's quite a markup. <BR>
<BR>
Add to that the fact that the Atlanta Committee is supposed to be the only
source of tickets to the Olympics. And as of June 1, no fencing tickets
are available from the Atlanta Committee - the event is sold out. <BR>
<BR>
But don't tell that to Aarons  Worldwide, which told ER it had &quot;plenty.&quot;
And Aarons  isn't the only ticket seller with fencing seats. The story is
the same for many of the smaller events like archery, handball or cycling.
Just look in your local Yellow Pages, under &quot;Tickets.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The source of private agencies' tickets depends on whom you ask. Aarons
 says it played the lottery, just like any other &quot;civilian.&quot; Top
Centre Ticket Service in Washington, D.C.,  says it bought tickets from
individuals who didn't want the second- and third-choice tickets they received
through the lottery. Diamond State, a local Pitts-burgh ticket agency, has
no comment.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;You're asking all the wrong questions,&quot; said the man who answered
the telephone there. &quot;Who put you up to this call, girlie?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Ticket distribution goes like this: The Atlanta Committee first made tickets
available to special parties like national Olympic committees (the USOC,
the French Olympic Com-  mittee, etc.) and sponsors (Coca-Cola, Kodak, etc.).
Then, on May 1, 1995, sales began to the general public through a mail order
lottery, and on February 10, 1996, through first-come, first-serve telephone
orders. The Atlanta Committee reports that 71 percent of the 555 event sessions
were sold out by the end of the mail order lottery. No tickets were distributed
until      June 8; until then, agencies were selling promises, no actual
tickets.<BR>
<BR>
A likely scenario is that sponsors and NOCs (national Olympic committees)
were reselling large blocks of seats they didn't want, but were forced to
buy by ACOG. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sponsors have a large appetite for tickets,&quot; says Laurie Olsen,
communications director for Olympic programs and ceremonies.<BR>
<BR>
To keep popular tickets available for the general public, sponsors and NOCs
were: 
<UL>
  <LI>Limited in how many tickets they could buy; and
  <LI>Required to buy at least one low-demand ticket  (to events like fencing
or archery) for every high-demand ticket (like basketball or gymnastics).
Olsen says this is the only way to keep popular events open to the public.
</UL>
In the past, this has resulted in empty stands on the day of competition,
because no one in the sponsor's party was really interested in the fencing
and archery tickets in the first place. Another result: scalping. Some sponsors
and NOCs are presumably turning around and selling their unwanted inventories
to ticket agencies, despite the fact that these sales invalidate their contract
with ACOG.<BR>
<BR>
To remedy these problems, ACOG has added a high-tech touch to the process.
Large-block ticket recipients can scan unwanted tickets back into ACOG's
ticket database. Those tickets will then be immediately available through
box offices and via the World Wide Web and telephone order. If the ticket
is sold, the sponsor gets a rebate on the ticket<BR>
<BR>
Despite this more than generous offer, ACOG already has found at least two
agencies selling tickets and filed lawsuits against them. One agent agreed
to stop selling tickets; the other, according to Olsen, filed Chapter 11
bankruptcy shortly after the lawsuit was filed.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've been taking the responsibility to protect the public's rights
and our commodity very seriously,&quot; says Olsen, &quot;and communicating
to all of the sponsors and all of the NOCs, we will not deliver tickets
to them if we find out that they are reselling them to scalpers. That's
the kind of activity that frustrates the public.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It even frustrates the athletes. Fencer Suzanne Paxton, a member of the
women's foil squad, will be issued only two tickets - far from enough. Her
entire family wants to attend, but they can't find tickets anywhere but
the overpriced agencies. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I don't know if my family can come,&quot; she says. &quot;It's very
unsettling not to have tickets in hand.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Gone Rowing<BR>
</B><BR>
On a balmy morning at the Three Rivers Rowing Association, it's not unusual
to see executives ducking out of the locker room suited up for work.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We go down shortly after 6 a.m., very early in the morning, when the
rivers are empty and there are no waterskiers or windsurfers,&quot; says
Ken Stiles, a Pittsburgh lawyer. &quot;We're back at 7:15, and by 7:30 we're
on our way.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Stiles is a member of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater's crew, which was established
in 1993. Stiles, at the time, was a PBT board member.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I can't stress enough what being on the river is like,&quot; says
Ed West, property master at the Ballet and one of the team's founders. &quot;Going
out on the Allegheny, feeling this is one boat, one heart - it's a very
rewarding feeling.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The PBT crew is part of a corporate rowing program started by TRRA Executive
Director Michael Lambert. With a half dozen or so teams, it's not thriving
- but the benefits are greatly appreciated by those who are involved.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You're working with people in corporate or other levels that you don't
usually work with,&quot; says West.<BR>
<BR>
Jennifer Fagan, 25, a food technologist at Heinz, agrees. She's been with
the Heinz crew for three years; the team's been together for five.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It's a great way to meet people from other departments - there are
other members, like from sales, that I would never have dealt with otherwise,&quot;
says Fagan. Heinz supports the team, paying the $240 dues per person, supplying
crew jackets with Heinz emblazoned across the back, and allowing leeway
for the lunchtime practice sessions. <BR>
<BR>
Corporations have the chance to compete against each other in Monday night
races, plus in the Lottie McAlice Regatta and the Head of the Ohio. And
they take it quite seriously.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We won the corporate championship two years in a row,&quot; says Stiles,
&quot;but were outrageously robbed last year.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But despite the enthusiasm of participants, TRRA has had a problem gaining
ground among corporations. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;As hard as we've worked at corporate rowing, we can't drum up other
corporations. It seems to be hard to maintain a crew, between the competition
for equipment, the early hours and the financial aspects,&quot; says West.
Members of the nonprofit PBT's crew  pay their own dues.<BR>
<BR>
The eight-person Heinz crew is raising money for their own boat - a $13,000
to $15,000 expenditure. That's a lot of bake sales. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's too bad there aren't more corporations that want to do it, because
we want more competition,&quot; says Fagan. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Mind Your Ps and Qs ... and Watch Out for Bear-Hugging Russians<BR>
<BR>
</B>This month's cover story talks about H.J. Heinz Co.'s push in Russia
and includes details of cultural differences Heinz officials encountered
there as they built a manufacturing facility.<BR>
<BR>
One Heinz vice president suffered two broken ribs when he was bear-hugged
by a Russian bureaucrat (see Hold the Pickles, Hold the Ketchup on page
22). Should American executives  run when they see a Russian headed their
way with arms extended?<BR>
<BR>
Author John Mole explores cultural differences in Europe in his new book
entitled &quot;Mind Your Manners, Managing Business Cultures in Europe&quot;
(Nicholas Brealey Publishing, $17.95 paperback).<BR>
<BR>
The book explores the nuances of interpersonal relationships and tries to
explain the miscommunications that arise between different cultures with
different priorities. Mole, an Englishman, gained his cross-cultural wisdom
through a 15-year stint in American banking that took him around the world.
His summations of the character of American executives  can seem a little
smug - there's no one like a Brit for &quot;putting things in a nutshell&quot;
- but generally observations hold at least a grain of truth to them. <BR>
<BR>
Russia earns a chapter of its own. Mole says:
<UL>
  <LI> The Russian organization tends to be very autocratic, with all decisions
stemming from a central boss. Lower managers shuttle information back and
forth, with little power themselves. 
  <LI>The spoken word carries more weight than in America, with many agreements
sealed on the telephone. Papers like contracts may be open to later negotiation
and usually clarify situations rather than confirm.
  <LI> In the current climate of chaos, laws and regulations change as fast
as flags, and corruption is at least as widespread as under communism. The
Western executive is warned that commercial law is untested and unfamiliar
to most Russians.
  <LI>For Russians, smiling is not respectful on formal occasions. &quot;Smiling
for no reason is a sign of idiocy not geniality,&quot; Mole declares.
</UL>
One drawback: the book didn't mention bear hugs. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
