<HEAD>
    <TITLE>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.People.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>A Dime Short</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>Actually, Western Pennsylvania Needs About<BR>
$500 Million to Complete Necessary Road Work</FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>Anyone who's ever pulled up to a turnpike booth and been a few coins
short of the toll knows how Bob Kochanowski feels.<BR>
<BR>
Except in his case, it's not a matter of a handful of change making up the
difference. As executive director of the Southwest Pennsylvania Regional
Planning Commission, Kochanowski's transportation concerns are much broader
than that. He sees the area's road projects falling short by about $5 billion
over the coming 20 years.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We really have a crisis in transportation funding,&quot; Kochanowski
says, adding that short-term plans are being reworked after the transportation
department scaled back its commitment to highway projects this year.<BR>
<BR>
And that crisis, as Kochanowski sees it, is a big yellow caution sign for
the region's economy. Without additional highways and road improvements,
regional growth will slow in the years ahead. Legislators in Harrisburg
know the problem, but say there is no easy solution around the bend.<BR>
&quot;Bob has every reason to be upset,&quot; says Paul Parsells, the top
Democratic staffer on the House Transportation Committee and an aide to
Rep. Ron Gamble of Oakdale. &quot;Western Penn- sylvania really got whacked.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
PennDOT's commitment to the region over the next four years dropped in February
from $1.3 billion to $850 million. That means revising the plans and eliminating
work.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The projects missing from PennDOT's proposal hurt our region badly,&quot;
Kochanowski says. &quot;We had expectations that these projects would soon
be completed.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Just two years ago, the SPRPC drafted a forecast of the transportation needs
of Allegheny, Armstrong, Beaver, Butler, Washington and Westmoreland counties
through 2015. By that time, the SPRPC anticipates, population will have
grown by 17 percent to about 2.7 million people and employment will have
increased 28 percent to more than 1.5 million jobs.<BR>
<BR>
To meet future needs, planners sketched out more than 50 projects. But with
the reduction in available funding, those plans have been scaled back.<BR>
<BR>
Two projects generally seen as the most important - the Mon-Fayette Expressway
and the Southern Beltway - remain priorities. These new toll roads would
complete a highway loop around the congestion of Pittsburgh, solving a long-standing
transportation problem.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Pittsburgh is one of the few areas that lacks a good circumference
beltway. We've always just shoved everything through the city,&quot; says
Sen. Barry Stout of Eighty-Four, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Transportation
Committee.<BR>
<BR>
When the region thrived on &quot;smokestack industries&quot; like steelmaking
and coal-mining, companies used rails and rivers to move their goods. As
those businesses were replaced by lighter industry and the kinds of businesses
that relied on &quot;just-in-time&quot; delivery provided by trucks, roads
took on greater economic value.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;For us to be competitive, we need to get the raw materials in and
the finished products out,&quot; Stout says.<BR>
<BR>
Which is tough for a company to do if its trucks spend a lot of time sitting
in traffic on Route 51 - today's best alternative to the Mon-Fayette Expressway.<BR>
<BR>
A beltway system would not only speed transportation and products around
the urban center, it also would provide prime ocations for new or expanded
businesses, Stout argues. <BR>
<BR>
But it all takes money. And since the state reduced its commitment, other
alternatives have been discussed, including a hike in the gas tax suggested
by Gov. Tom Ridge as a way to repair roads damaged by the winter storms.
The idea was an example of terrible timing - it came in an election year
and just as gas prices began climbing.<BR>
<BR>
Also put on the table for consideration - by Democratic Rep. Harry Readshaw
of Pleasant Hills - was a plan to increase vehicle registration fees. Charging
tolls on more roads, particularly Interstate 80, was another alternative
presented.<BR>
<BR>
Without some kind of financial boost, and given the number of hills and
bridges in the area and its terrain, Kochanowski says the available money
will allow only basic maintenance of current roads.<BR>
&quot;It really is a circumstance where we can only just run in place.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
