<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H10People.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Margaret J. Forbes  </FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: Margaret J. Forbes  <BR>
Age: 44<BR>
Personal: he and husband Stephen Spear and daughters Alice, 12, and Kaitlin,
15, live in Regent Square<BR>
Education: BA, Literature, Kirkland College, Clinton, NY, 1973<BR>
Last Book Read: Minnie, by Annie M.G. Schmidt<BR>
Last Vacation: New Hampshire, annually each summer<BR>
</B><HR>Entering the North Side's tree-lined Allegheny Square, you might
almost be in Europe - shady stone walks are lined with monumental yet intimately
scaled buildings. One of these, Pittsburgh's old Post Office building, now
houses the Pittsburgh Children's Museum. Thirteen years ago, the museum
opened in 5,000 square feet in the basement. It now occupies all three floors,
not to mention the sky-reaching rotunda. With a 22-foot  high climber, interactive
exhibits, a mural made of 30,000 gum balls and a puppet collection that
includes favorites from Mr. Rogers and Jim Henson, the museum is a child's
dream. Parents love it, too, for beneath the exciting exhibits is a mission
attributable to Executive Director Maggie Forbes that goes beyond fun and
games. Just this summer, the museum is debuting an exhibit called Safety
Street, which is geared to saving lives by teaching traffic safety - an
 important message in a city that recently lost two children to school bus
accidents. ER's Lydia Strohl talked to Forbes.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Executive Report</B>: Talk, if you will, about the early years of the
museum.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Maggie Forbes</B>: The museum opened in 1983. It was started by the Junior
League of Pittsburgh. The myth is that the idea was spawned on a rainy summer
Monday when a couple of women had nothing to do with their kids. They started
to look at how much there was geared toward their kids. They did three or
four years of research to make sure they weren't duplicating services. Certainly
we're not the first children's museum - there are well over 300 children's
museums in the country, and I get calls all the time from people looking
to start one. I think the reason is you don't go to the Metropolitan Museum
of Art and say, 'Oh, let's start one of those.' But you can come to a children's
museum and say, 'Look how wonderful. We could do something like this at
home.'<BR>
When we opened, and Buhl was next door, I think that gave us a focus. A
lot of children's museums open as sort of a junior science center, and for
us, that didn't make a lot of sense. I do get militant sometimes that children's
museums are the only ones that get their start in 5,000 square feet in the
basement, just to see how they do.<BR>
<BR>
One of the exciting things in the last 10 years is that some children's
museums are actually starting in buildings built just for them. But that's
not the norm. I love my old unsuitable building, but there are not bathrooms
on every floor. There are absolutely no amenities - no classrooms, no place
to eat, all those things that are very important to a museum.<BR>
 <BR>
And still I'd say that Pittsburgh has one of the real jewels of children's
museums. It's the right size: It's big enough that you walk in and say,
'Oh wow,' yet small enough that you can flit around and see everything,
then come back and do what you really want to do. It's very intimate, but
not the sort of place that 10-year-olds will walk into and think, 'Oh this
is a baby place.' For all our lack of funding, this place is very forgiving;
it has a richness and a luster that doesn't look shabby.<BR>
I think one of the things that we struggle with as a young organization
is that this region is so multigenerational. Western Pennsylvania parents
do with their kids what their parents did with them. That leaves us out.
We've had to struggle to introduce ourselves.<BR>
<BR>
For the first couple years I would watch them line up to see the trains
[at Buhl]. Eventually they got brave enough to come over. And then we were
bursting at the seams. We're still recovering from the congestion and the
crowds. For years I heard, 'I haven't been here since you expanded.' Well,
they weren't in a hurry to come back, to wait in line and not be able to
get in. But when we lost Buhl - it was awful. Our visitation was climbing
steadily; it hit 125,000 in 1991. I forget when the science center opened,
but it took a long time to really affect us. I swear just last year somebody
came back to see the trains. But it fell off precipitously. Things added
up - the 8-month newspaper strike, it seemed to all come at once. Advertising
is a good thing, but as a nonprofit you don't spend money you don't have,
so we didn't spend a dime on advertising. But what we did do, we concentrated
on building relationships with schools and community groups. And as hard
as it is to get to them, once you're working with them they know who you
are. And that's where this incredibly strong outreach came from. We learned
that they wanted us to come to them, because of busing problems, because
of distance.<BR>
<BR>
We're a little schizophrenic about that, because I really do believe that
the cities and museums are things we share. You're rubbing shoulders with
people you don't know. There are consequences of urban flight, of not sharing
with people. That is one of the real outcomes of a children's museum experience
- role-playing, kids interacting with other kids - it's as much about the
socialization as the content of the exhibits.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What's the philosophy focusing the museum?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MF:</B> Our mission is to enrich children's lives. Children with their
family, schools and community groups. That makes it very inclusive. Children
do not come to us on their own. <BR>
<BR>
Those early childhood years, birth to three, are the most critical ones.
And it doesn't just drop off - you have to begin at the beginning, and then
move forward. You can't take those quantum leaps. If you don't begin at
the beginning and build - anyone who knows young kids knows how every day
they are learning things that are formative - so that is to say, let us
do everything we possibly can for our youngest kids.<BR>
<BR>
My husband's a professor at Carnegie Mellon, he's head of the Ph.D. Economics
program at GSIA, and in a recent class of his, there were 20-some candidates,
and 2 or 3 were American born. We have the finest schools in the world -
for other people. You can't fail kids in preschool, or kindergarten, and
expect them to do well at Carnegie Mellon University. The phrase higher
education offends me. My husband says I'm picking on academia, but they're
not the most exalted. It's full circle; it has to begin at the beginning.
Education is ostensibly for our youth, yet the younger you are the less
you matter. Certainly, financially, there's no question, but even in terms
of outlook - if you tell someone you are a preschool teacher, their eyes
glaze over. Yet the impact that those people have on children's lives, and
particularly on children that are at risk, is incalculable. Early childhood
experience is so important. At an early age, my kids were part of a group,
where they made choices, in a day care. And I think they have yet to find
that again. You learned to be part of the group, but you didn't have to
fit the mold.<BR>
<BR>
When my younger daughter was in kindergarten, she had a hard time adjusting.
She said, 'Mommy, we never have time to play.' I hit the roof. The teacher
said, 'They have 20 minutes for lunch and once they get used to this, they
eat more quickly and play on the playground.' The principal said, 'It's
not state law in Pennsylvania that children have recess.' But if you stop
and think about what you learn on the playground - for many of us, kindergarten
and first grade is the first social experience. And you're not getting it
if all you do is sit at a desk. You're not working things out. You're not
learning the consequences of not agreeing with the group or they won't play
with you any more. If you don't have those opportunities, that social aspect
of being part of a group is lost.<BR>
<BR>
If I could change the world, I would make it state law that there be no
more than 15 kids in the class. We know all the economic and social disparities
that exist - but we should really pay attention to the developmental disparities.
It's perfectly ok to learn to ride a two-wheeler anytime between 4 and 8
years old, and you're not weird or abnormal. Even more, you still want to
learn, because your friends do.<BR>
<BR>
But you're supposed to learn to read by second semester first grade, or
already you're a loser. When you think about all the things that contribute
to that, but our schools don't allow for those differences. <BR>
<BR>
I feel when kids come to the Children's Museum, they succeed. It doesn't
mean you don't have to learn to read; it's not to say you don't have to
learn mathematics. There are natural points, and some people will be ready
sooner. We shouldn't try to fit all those kids into the same pegs.<BR>
I also think that everybody is so busy blaming somebody else - parents say
it's the school's fault, teachers say it's the parents - that we aren't
focusing on what we can do to help our kids. Quality early childhood education
should be available to everyone.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How does the Children's Museum incorporate elements that make
early childhood education successful?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MF: </B>We know that there are a lot of things that make children want
to learn, but failure doesn't make them want to learn. Project-oriented
things should be so much a part of the early childhood education. <BR>
<BR>
Yesterday we had a group of sixth graders from Greensburg Salem that did
a puppet show here.<BR>
 These kids had been given three months - this project was of cooperation.
There were kids who had built the puppets, or the set, or written it - they
had to research it, go find out about it, present your story and then share
it with people. Talk about a curriculum model. And I know all of the kids
on the project were not of all the same academic level. I don't know how
we've come away from recognizing how important all these things are. The
product wasn't half bad. But the process was extraordinary.<BR>
<BR>
There are ways that you can help kids want to learn, and many teachers are
doing a fine job. My daughter Alice is hugely competitive. We got a call
a few weeks ago from her new clarinet teacher saying she hadn't been to
a clarinet lesson in six weeks - totally unbeknownst to us. Well, this new
teacher came in and said that if you practice 100 minutes a week, there
will be a pizza party. Alice has never not been eligible for a pizza party.
That's not exactly the best educational model, but it's what works for her.
And I think that what works for these 10 kids may not work for that 11th
kid - but that does not mean that kid is a loser. <BR>
<BR>
There are kids that aren't bright, but they still can be good citizens.
But we still have a school system that pretty much awards academics or athletics.
Maybe you don't get excited if you're being handed a certificate - but just
think how you feel if you're not being handed that certificate. <BR>
<BR>
I remember a day when there were kids from Fox Chapel Country Day School,
and another day having kids from Northview Heights. And other than the color
of their skin and the lack of uniforms, the experience at the museum wasn't
different. The kids from Fox Chapel didn't do better at the Children's Museum
than the kids from Northview Heights. It worked for all of them. And I think
we have to come up with educational models like that.<BR>
<BR>
Another thing is, when you talk about educational reform, they always have
to have a revolution. Once again, begin at the beginning. If you have a
new model, introduce it in kindergarten, refine it, tweak it, take it up
to first grade. <BR>
<BR>
We've done it that way just because of resources. Sometimes we have no money,
but we try it. Then we can go out and get funding, because we know it works.
That learn by doing model, it is a process.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> When the museum opened, in the basement here, this exhibit, Riverscape,
was among the original offerings. Why has it remained viable?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MF:</B> Riverscape is the classic children's museum exhibit, the role-playing
we all do in kindergarten. Plus, it is about Pittsburgh in the past. These
pictures wouldn't exist simultaneously, but that wasn't our purpose, it
was to create a flavor of Pittsburgh in the past. While our first mission
is to our children, to be fun and engaging, we also want to be true to our
subject matter. This is a gritty, strong city, so the black and white photos,
the real scale, the ship's wheel, take the subject matter seriously. The
only thing we have redone is the floor. This is the exhibit where most adults
say, 'I wish they had something like this when I was growing up.' It's like
theater or literature that has an honest voice - anybody can read it.<BR>
<BR>
I really do feel that a children's museum exhibit should tell you right
away what you should do there.<BR>
 <BR>
<B>ER:</B> How long did it take for the museum to gain momentum to get out
of the basement.<BR>
<BR>
<B>MF:</B> Actually, it happened quite fast. Basically the museum went from
the basement to the second floor - we got a fabulous puppetry exhibit. But
the main rotunda space hadn't been developed. We have far more cubic footage
than square footage - it's one of our greatest challenges. Your strengths
are your weaknesses, whether you're a person, a city or an institution.
Then we got a grant and commissioned the climber, commissioned this wonderful
sculpture. There's Pisces the fish, diving into a gold lame cloud.<BR>
 <BR>
We first opened the puppet exhibit in 1985. Margot Lovelace, who ran the
longest continuing puppet theater in the country in Shadyside, donated a
big part of her collection. When we first opened it, the kids came up from
the basement all hot and sweaty and went 'Wow.' Hands-on is one thing, but
minds-on is another. This is completely visual. And they're not going to
spend as much time as they will loading up vegetables in the basement, but
it's important in that moment.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What's your annual budget?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MF:</B> The budget is around $1million, it's a little more than that
this year because of Safety Street. They call it 'earned' and unearned -
which I think is funny, the unearned stuff we work damn hard for, sometimes
harder. The same audience development issues existed with corporate and
foundation Pittsburgh, so it's getting better. But not any easier. We're
not defined by our collection, we're defined by our audience - and we are
not by any means the only organization in town that deals with children.
These are all things that people can take with them - the teacher that did
that puppet show took a class as puppetry as a teaching tool at the museum.
And look what it turned into. I think that relationship building is something
that is being recognized as being very important.<BR>
<BR>
This Safety Street that we are building with Allegheny General Hospital
is an example of this, it's a co-production. The idea came from a pediatric
trauma surgeon. When I first met Dr. Michael Hirsh I was showing him around
and saying, 'Inner being, self-esteem, well-being, they're all part of the
same spectrum,' and he said, 'Maggie, how would you like to save kids' lives.'
'Of course.' And this exhibit that teaches car and bus traffic safety is
about how children begin to take responsibility for their own safety. Learning
those things has to be the precursor to driver's education. When they're
15, they're rebelling, they're immortal. The safety message is so much better
taught as the responsibility of being a pedestrian when you're seven years
old. <BR>
<BR>
Also, parents are so fearful - and fear is not a positive motivator. It
makes us keep our kids apart - thinking, what are people going to do to
them. These are things we have very little control over. You can't put your
kids away in a box like Rapunzel. But these injuries that are happening
are preventable. Kids can be taught to make safer choices. This program
ties into a lot of others. I see this exhibit as a beacon for making safer
choices - how do we as a community take better care of them and teach them
to take better care of themselves. I feel very strongly about working together,
not being balkanized, not being so angry about what's going on that we don't
work together to find solutions. It's a scary time right now. The government
shuts down. That's a model for chaos right there, that the people who are
in government can't work together. And I think we see that trickle-down
effect. Our children should be something that unites us - that's something
we need to do and should be doing.<BR>
<BR>
On a feminist front, I believe that for the longest time no one paid attention
to our children for so long because it was the mother's job. The world has
changed around us and it's not just single parents, or working mothers,
but when you look at our schools, we aren't as much involved. That real
PTA involvement with schools - there was a whole segment of our population
that for so many generations was a part of the schools. The answer is not
just [for women] to stay home, you can't just worry about yours and live
alone.<BR>
<BR>
Safety Street is patterned after a program in Holland that has reduced traumatic
injury by 50 percent. This was not easy. We thought we had something everybody
was going to jump on - but we had to wrestle. When we first talked about
this, one of my board said, 'You know, Maggie, it doesn't put any fire in
my belly.' Then unfortunately, this winter, a five-year-old and a 15-year-old,
within five days, were killed in school bus accidents. The last thing that
mother told her son was, 'Don't miss the bus.' He chased the bus. These
are things that shouldn't happen. There was a 12-year-old killed by an ambulance
- he was riding his bike. I've never read an obituary for a 12-year-old.
<BR>
<BR>
This has been two or three years in the making. It's close to a $200,000
project. We're working with the communications department of Allegheny General
Hospital. They've donated $100,000, plus their expertise. IKM donated the
design of the exhibit; Laidlaw donated and refurbished the school bus; the
city gave the street lights. There's been major coalition building, curriculum
building. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>How much of your budget do you raise yourself?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MF:</B> It's 55 percent - so I guess if you compare us to the Carnegie,
or the Symphony, we're doing pretty well.<BR>
<BR>
We've sold Stuffee, our health exhibit, to over 60 museums around the world.
He's just picking up his international market. I just got a royalty check
for one that was sold to Brazil. You unzip him, pull out his insides, and
talk about how the body works. We also have a giant lunchbox - so we talk
about what happens to the turkey sandwich after you chew it up and swallow
it down. You can pitch it to the age of the audience you're talking to.
You can say, 'What's this?' And the 7th grader can tell you - though you
find that the parents' knowledge of the anatomy is rusty at best.<BR>
<BR>
One of the things I am surprised by is that even the tiniest child might
say, 'Yuk.' I've said, 'Do you think the things inside you are disgusting?'
You talk about self-esteem, but also respect for your body, whether you're
talking about drugs or alcohol or your diet - that whole your-body-is-your-temple.
<BR>
<BR>
I say, 'These are wonderful things. Just say yes to who you are and what
you are.' Fostering respect and responsibility, making choices - I really
do think understanding makes a real big difference in this.            
                           <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
