"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.People.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <A HREF="../zine/0796.Diner.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Coaching Employees</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Try Some of This Philosophy From a Guy Who<BR>
Knows How to Motivate: Steelers Coach Bill Cowher</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>So , I was reading about this business that does consulting for,
well, business. They are offering the answer to a number of corporate problems,
everything from building team spirit to keeping chins up when downsizing
begins. And they do all this by delivering just one fellow to a company's
doorstep: the Coach. Yes, for a significant fee, an honest-to-God NFL coach
can call the plays for your employees. And, yes, it seems this idea is really
taking off with managers who sideline themselves, so a coach can tackle
the most difficult plays.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think there's a great parallel between coaching [employees] and
running a football team,&quot; says Steelers coach Bill Cowher, who has
delivered speeches on the subject to corporate managers. &quot;You're bringing
together a group of people striving for a particular goal. You are trying
to get people to work with one another, understand the rules, be motivated
and work as one.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Cowher says managers have lots of questions. They want  to know how to maximize
an employee's time and effort, while building pride and dedication. This
coach emphatically states that priority No. 1 for any organization must
be communication. Every manager knows business, on a good day, can be an
obstacle course. But Cowher points out that when good communication puts
all employees on the same page, internal hurdles can often be eliminated
and goals achieved even faster.<BR>
 &quot;I think it's making sure people feel comfortable with one another.
Make sure they clearly understand what you expect from them. And I think
[you] need to give feedback ... on a regular basis ... and not just the
things they need to do better. Tell them when they are doing good.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
These downsizing days of drastic corporate realignments, though, add a whole
new dimension to the business of keeping employees productive and motivated
in the midst of their fears. Cowher sees the parallel to professional football,
where the triple threat of superior talent, trades and injuries constantly
calls into question every player's fate and/or fortune. And Cowher sees
the way to motivate right through that problem: &quot;I think it is a case
of people feeling good about themselves. Whether or not the opportunity
exists with this company, or this football team, they can't control that.
So why worry about it? <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Why not have confidence in [your] own abilities ... in [your] own
skills ... and say, 'Hey, I'm going to do what you are asking of me now,'
and recognize that if I do it to the best of my abilities, it's going to
do nothing but open up opportunity for me.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There always remain the employees, though, that even a coach couldn't motivate.
To them, the Cowher Power of Communication Rule still applies: &quot;Take
the people who are constantly testing the system, the people constantly
working on the edge, and you have to let them know what is expected of them.
Then, when it comes time to make a tough decision and say, 'Listen, you
are no longer going to be acceptable in this environment,' you can feel
good about yourself, that you have given that person every opportunity to
respond.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And what about the latitude a coach has to show, in a saliva-flying way,
his distinct displeasure when someone or something goes very wrong? Cowher
admits his profession affords him a certain license not broadly held by
America's corporate managers. Yet, under calmer circumstances, the coach
is struck by how similar the roles can be.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'm a weight-balance. When we're winning, I've got to bring them down.
When we're losing, I've got to bring them up ... It's just like with a corporation.
When you're doing well, it's a good time to get on the employees, to make
sure that complacency doesn't set in. And at the same time, when things
aren't going well, it's your responsibility as a leader, to create the incentive
- to create othe reasoning for coming in and working a little bit harder.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Cowher philosophy will confront a fresh test in just a few weeks, when
training camp opens and the ghost of a Super Bowl Past might linger. No
problem.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I make sure you look at the big picture,&quot; Cowher says. &quot;Don't
look at one game or one situation and say because of that, forget about
the rest of the year. As long as you prepared, as long as you have gone
in there and done the very best that you can do,  you have got to accept
the fact that it isn't always going to work out ... For us after the Super
Bowl, the most important thing I wanted our team to do was remember what
we had done for that year and recognize that hey, we did everything we could
do. We put ourselves in a position to win and we played it toe-to-toe. We
went in there as an underdog and you could walk away from the 1995 season
with your head held high. And for us, that's going to be some of the fuel
that is going to spark this football team for next year.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
