<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>El Compesino</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Try Some Good Mexican Cooking<BR>
Just East of the Border ... City Border</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>amuel Aquirra came to the U.S. in 1987 from Guadalajara, Mexico.
His parents owned a small restaurant in the city; the family also worked
a farm just outside its limits. When he and his brothers - Ezekiel and Joel
- came here, they did what they knew. They started opening Mexican restaurants,
the first in Atlanta, Ga., in 1988. <BR>
<BR>
The three brothers now have five restaurants: three in Ohio, in Massilon,
Mansfield and Lima; one in Kokomo, Ind., and one just east of Pittsburgh,
in Monroeville. Why these distinctly undistinct locations? No magic to their
method, Aquirra says: &quot;We were just driving around, and we liked them.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Pittsburgh was a tip from a customer at a restaurant Aquirra owned (and
has since sold) in Indianapolis,  who said there was nothing in this town
like it. And while that's not exactly right (the Fajita Grill, near Century
III Mall, also specializes in Mexican homecooking), El Campesino does fill
a niche for those not interested in Route 51, Chi-Chi's or Taco Bell.<BR>
<BR>
Which are, coincidently, both across the street from Aquirra's Jonnet Plaza
location. But his food is worlds away from their offerings.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our food is no different from the food in my mother and father's restaurant
in Mexico,&quot; he says. &quot;We use the same seasonings, the same spices.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One recent weekend, we sat at a booth in the brightly lighted El Campesino
- there's no disguising it's in a strip mall, no matter how many sombreros
and maracas are hung on the wall - and ordered up a storm. The menu is huge
and confusing -combinations of enchiladas, burritos, tamales, flautas, tacos,
chili rellenos and chalupas dominate the right-hand side, in platters No.
1 through No. 25. If you tire of deciphering what goes with what (there
is a handy glossary on the back of the menu, for those who do want to wade
through it), you can order a la carte. There are also dinners, like the
grilled cazuelada and the chimichanga, and El Campesino special combinations,
under which are featured local favorites like carnitas and pollo loco.<BR>
<BR>
The food is fresh and cheap and hot and plenty, that's for sure. Hot, handmade
chips and salsa come to the table immediately - some of the best I've ever
had, so crispy they almost tasted roasted, and not oily. We started with
a quesadilla, which was overloaded with cheese and grilled chicken, nicely
spiced. The guacamole dip was smooth and refreshing, not bland as they tend
to be in restaurants.<BR>
<BR>
The entrees came all looking alike - the combinations are smothered in a
thick, cheesy red sauce, which Aquirra says is thickened with mole. The
tamale is a thick cornmeal casing stuffed with barbecued pork - delicious.
 The fried chimichanga was also a treat - crispy but again not oily, with
great flavors and tender chicken that cooled just perfectly with fresh lettuce
and tomato.<BR>
<BR>
But the combinations were a bit of a disappointment - the enchiladas, burritos
and chalupas, in particular, were a little on the flavorless side. The chili
relleno had a good stuffing of ground meat, but was smothered in a strong
cheese sauce that was far too overpowering for the rest of the dish. The
chili poblano one night was so hot we turned purple upon ingestion - but
a couple days later was as tame as just-lain eggs. The chicken fajitas had
the good spices we were yearning for in the other dishes, but the chicken
that day was tough and chewy.<BR>
<BR>
It's hard, but save room for dessert. Fried ice cream - yes, it's true,
and it sure saves having to put it in the microwave - is a soft and tasty
treat, served in a taco shell with whipped cream and chocolate sauce. For
the true aficionados, the sopapillas - fried flour tortillas with cinnamon
and honey - are a delectable morsel. The flan, while rich and soft, was
almost too perfect to add much to the category. Skip coffee, unless you
want to be reminded of the office.<BR>
<BR>
Despite the campy atmosphere and some unzippy dishes (by my second visit,
I had caught on to using the bottles of El Yucetuco hot sauce on each table
- but not liberally), El Campesino is worth every penny (try as we might,
we could never spend even $10 a person). Plus, the waiters have beautiful
manners, soft accented voices and serve their customers thoughtfully and
adroitly. A large smile from the man who took our bill revealed a silver-rimmed
tooth - precious metal indeed, these days.     <BR>
<BR>
El Campesino<BR>
4063 Wm. Penn Hwy.<BR>
Jonnet Plaza, Monroeville<BR>
373-1772<BR>
<BR>
Hours: <BR>
Mon. - Thurs.: 11:30 a.m. - 10 p.m.<BR>
Fri. - Sat.: 11:30 a.m. - 10:30 p.m.<BR>
Sun.: 12 p.m. - 9 p.m. <BR>
<BR>
Appetizers and Sides: 15&#162; - $5.95<BR>
Entrees: $3.75 - $8.00                          <BR>
