<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Sharing Spaces</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Here's How to get High-End Space<BR>
When You Want Low Overhead<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>when attorney Alex Parrish decided to go it alone, he needed an office.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I looked around and thought about getting a space and a secretary
and all those things, and that's a huge overhead,&quot; he remembers. &quot;And
a big problem if anything goes wrong.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So instead of committing to a long-term lease in a location he could afford
but was far from his clients, Parrish found a home of sorts at HQ Business
Centers. HQ is one of a number of businesses in the Pittsburgh area offering
shared office space, secretarial services and the use of a wide range of
office equipment to small businesses.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;For me it's worked out perfectly,&quot; says Parrish. &quot;It gives
me a mailing  address at One Oxford Centre, right across from the courthouse
where all the lawyers are. And it's also a quality address. For a sole practitioner
or any small business, that's critical to give you some credibility.&quot;
<BR>
 <BR>
Parrish chose HQ's &quot;Business Identity&quot; package, which lets him
use an office or conference room when he needs to, as well as a full-time
  receptionist. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The thing I use all the time is the phone system. I have my own phone
number. When it rings, a confident, professional secretary answers it every
time within a couple rings, the way I would ask my own full-time secretary
to answer it, and then does whatever I've asked with the call. I can be
working at home and they'll send it home. It'll ring there; the secretary
will tell me who called, and then I talk to the person. It's great,&quot;
says Parrish.  <BR>
<BR>
The HQ Business Centers franchise includes Pittsburgh, as well as Cleveland
and Columbus. There are  three locations locally.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are two customer bases that drive the business,&quot; says HQ
President Calvin Hunter. &quot;The first customer base is large firms which
need to set up branch operations in another city but don't want to commit
to a fully staffed and equipped office. The second base is the local entrepreneur,
the small business professional.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Hunter thinks the most important feature that shared-office facilities like
his offer clients is telephone related.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They don't have to have any contact with Bell Atlantic. We provide
a complete telephone package - a phone number, phone lines, the instrument,
long distance service and 800 number service if they want it. Plus, we answer
their phones,&quot; says Hunter. Other office services include fax, copying,
mail and a range of computer-based services like word processing, desktop
publishing and presentation and proposal preparation. <BR>
 <BR>
In some instances, shared-office setups have been a stepping stone for the
growth of small businesses. HQ's Hunter recalls one investment management
firm in Cleveland that started using the business identity service close
to five years ago.  <BR>
<BR>
&quot;He ran that business out of his home until it became a two- or three-
person business,&quot; says Hunter. &quot;And then he grew into our facility.
I think he started with three offices, and it grew to six.  After about
three years of that, they just outgrew us there. So he took a traditional
space.&quot;<BR>
The concept works for a number of service-based industries.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is like incubator space for the white collar worker,&quot; says
Steve Arcivolo, a commercial real estate developer who rents office space
at the HQ facility in One Oxford Centre. Arcivolo is a virtually self-sufficient
solo practitioner, with occasional support from the HQ staff.  <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I have a dedicated fax line in my office, so I use my own fax, which
doubles as a photocopy machine. I have my own computer with a printer so
I can type my own letters. I would say I operate 90 to 95 percent self-sufficiently,&quot;
says Arcivolo. &quot;But if there's something I need them to do, they do
it for me. It's nice to know that it's there if I need it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Arcivolo has found the HQ setup ideal for a small, one person operation.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I could really just get established immediately, without having to
buy furniture or a lot of equipment, without hiring a secretary or even
looking for office space,&quot; says Arcivolo. &quot;They have a ready-made
receptionist/secretarial staff, office equipment, furniture. I have a conference
room if I want it, when I want it.  And I like the location.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is going to come a point in time, probably, when I'm going to
need my own office, I'm going to need my own secretary,&quot; he says. 
&quot;I'll have to try and judge when I'm ready for that.  But until you
build up that head of steam, this is a good place to be.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
