<HEAD>
    <TITLE>HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H15Health.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Law.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Corporate Fitness<BR>
</FONT></I><FONT size =+1>Can Companies Save on Healthcare<BR>
by Motivating Employees to Exercise?</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Surprise, surprise. Healthy, active employees are better for a corporation
than sedentary ones. Studies consistently prove that introducing some form
of corporate fitness benefit improves productivity and morale while decreasing
healthcare costs, turnover and absenteeism.<BR>
<BR>
For instance: medical claims for corporate fitness program participants
at Steelcase were 55 percent lower - $478.61 for participants vs. $869.98
for nonparticipants - over a six year period. Dupont saw absenteeism reduced
47.5 percent over six-years among   participants in their fitness program.
Eighty percent of Union Pacific Railroad employees involved in corporate
fitness reported increases in productivity; 75 percent thought it increased
levels of relaxation and concentration at work. The Canadian Life Assurance
Company found job turnover among fitness program participants was 31.4 percent
lower over a seven-year period than nonparticipants. And in the first year
of its fitness program, the Scoular Grain Co. re-duced healthcare costs
by over $1 million - that's $1,500 per employee.<BR>
<BR>
Call the evidence anecdotal if you will. But in an area like healthcare,
where good fiscal news is infrequent, you'd think any economic cheer would
be embraced like a frosty beverage on a summer day. Yet in a Towers Perrin
survey, just 21 percent of mid- to large-size western Pennsylvania employers
reported supporting corporate fitness. Nationwide, that figure is a bit
larger - anywhere from 29 to 50 percent, depending on to whom you speak.
<BR>
<BR>
Hello, Corporate America. Anyone home?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think corporations understand that couch potatoes are expensive,&quot;
says Cindy Mendolia, director of marketing/membership for the Downtown YMCA.
&quot;But it takes money to save money, and they have to invest in their
employees. They've downsized, but they're not really taking care of the
employees who are left. Employees are putting in more time, but there's
no decompression.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A lot of managers are in tune, but they don't want to spend the bucks,&quot;
says Mendolia, quoting the Y's corporate subsidized membership at a low
    2 percent of its 2,100 members. &quot;The company spends more for employee
assistance programs - to handle issues that arise from stress.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
By then it's too late for prevention, in either health or spending. Locally,
GNC attributes healthcare claims by its employees that are 15 percent below
normative data to a combination fitness/wellness program instituted in the
early '90s. In addition to a fitness facility that's available free-of-charge
to employees at GNC's downtown headquarters, it has annual screenings for
cholesterol, blood pressure and weight. If employees pass normative standards
they are awarded $100 - an improvement can garner up to $50. Cash disincentives
are also used - smokers can pay as much as $65 a year more for healthcare.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Because the nature of our business is self care we have a strong corporate
philosophy that our employees should have healthy lives,&quot; says Eileen
Scott, vice president of human resources at GNC. <BR>
<BR>
The numbers of employees who use the fitness center is relatively low -
75 to 100 out of 500 employees at the site - but about 350 employees use
the screening mechanism. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've had people with very serious cholesterol problems they didn't
know about change their lifestyle and stave off heart attacks,&quot; says
Scott. &quot;And they like having the fitness center even if they don't
use it - it gives them a good feeling about the company.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Others, too, tout fitness benefits as an attraction and retention tool.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We attract applicants of higher energy levels, competitive and disciplined,&quot;
says Terry Kelly, vice president of human resources for Federated, which
pays half of the $67 monthly dues at the DoubleTree fitness center for its
managers who want to work out there. About one-third of them do. &quot;We
thought it would be a good thing to do - management works hard and we are
always looking for benefits to enhance our package - but we didn't know
how well it would be received.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kelly herself takes advantage of the membership, working out three times
a week on the treadmill with her husband, also a Federated manager.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It affords us the opportunity to exercise together and that means
a lot. When I leave work I have to kind of force myself to go over there
- but then I leave feeling better about my day,&quot; she says. &quot;The
benefits are hard to quantify, but we probably do have increased productivity
and greater morale. And camaraderie - people from different departments
meet each other working out together.&quot;<BR>
Chris Gibson, manager of the DoubleTree fitness center, says Federated's
location in the adjacent Liberty Center is key. Employees from Edgar Snyder's
law practice, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and accounting firm Schneider
Downs have corporate perks there as well.<BR>
<BR>
Fitness benefits can be as easy as hiring an aerobics instructor to come
in a few times a week after work, says KaDee Lewis, a local corporate fitness
consultant who does a similar program for a PNC Bank branch. She's also
in the process of setting up an in-house gym for Tomko Plumbing and Heating
in the South Hills. But both Lewis and Gibson are disappointed with corporate
interest here.<BR>
&quot;Companies are myopic,&quot; Gibson says. &quot;They're not assessing
the long-term behavior of their employees and the impact of that. They think
[a corporate fitness program] will encourage the people who already do it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've only looked at it informally,&quot; says John Kozar, manager
of  insured benefits at Aristech Chemical Corp. &quot;I'm sure bosses think,
'People can go home and jog.' It's something where you need a health fan
at the top. Pittsburgh in general has old line management; they don't get
into this stuff.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think it's a good benefit - anything you can do in terms of education
is good. In general, only the healthiest people will participate - but they're
setting an example.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
What can't be overlooked in all this is that even in the corporations that
do offer fitness benefits - whether through an in-house fitness center or
by subsidizing all or part of an employee's health club membership - participation
isn't the rage. 84 Lumber Company built a fully equipped fitness center
for employees in their 84 office in 1987. In 1989 they opened the center
to the public. Today, just 156 of the 1,100 members are company employees;
350 are eligible.<BR>
<BR>
Edgar Snyder's looking at a similar ratio: Just about half of the staff
in his Pittsburgh law office take advantage of a corporate fitness policy
which provides reimbursement up to $40 a month on health club membership
or other fitness/life-style memberships.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The motivation is simple,&quot; says Snyder. &quot;I work out every
day and believe that has helped me in my career. Working in a trial law
firm today creates tension - for me, this is an outlet.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;And,&quot; Snyder adds, &quot;I believe that people who keep themselves
in good shape are more productive - and for me, productivity goes right
to the  bottom line.&quot;                                             <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
