<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Education.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Employee Evaluations</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Either Do Them Right<BR>
Or Don't Do Them At All<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Attorney Robert L. McTiernan has seen a few employee perfor- mance
evaluations that came back to haunt the employer. So has attorney Thomas
S. Giotto. <BR>
<BR>
It's common: The employee is dismissed for a legitimate reason, but has
a handful of evaluations dating back several years that portray that employee
as dedicated, effective, productive or hard-working - the list can go on.
So if the evaluations were truthful, why was that employee even terminated
in the first place? And what will a civil-court jury hearing a wrongful
termination case think?<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;The problem with evaluations, if they're not done properly, is that
they will contradict a supervisor's point of view,&quot; says McTiernan,
an employment law attorney with Tucker Arensberg in Pittsburgh. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;You get to the point where you discharge someone, and the evaluations
conflict with why you are discharging them.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I really haven't had many lawsuits where the performance appraisals
helped the employer,&quot; adds Giotto, a labor and employment law attorney
with Klett Lieber Rooney &amp; Schorling in Pittsburgh. &quot;Usually, they
harm the employer.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And both McTiernan and Giotto agree: If you don't do performance appraisals
right, don't do them. Period.<BR>
<BR>
That said, statistics show that an estimated 70 million employees receive
performance appraisals annually in the United States. The employees often
crave the feedback, believing any pay raise or promotion possibilities for
them will turn on how favorable their evaluation is. So employers large
and small engage in the annual process of taking time to evaluate the people
who work for them, many times bestowing undeserved praise on employees.
It's human nature.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Supervisors don't like to say negative things about employees,&quot;
Giotto says. &quot;It's not motivation. It's hard to do. The supervisors
usually overrate everyone.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And that's were problems can start.<BR>
<BR>
Take, for instance, one federal lawsuit in which a female employee charged
sex discrimination after being terminated by her employer,  a television
station. The station said the woman's termination was based on poor performance,
yet the jury was shown performance appraisals that contained complimentary
language and rated the woman's performance as satisfactory. The jury eventually
awarded damages to the woman.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Evaluation Options</B><BR>
<BR>
There are four common methods of employee evaluation, each of which has
strengths and weaknesses:
<UL>
  <LI>	In the weighted responsibility method, employees are rated on how
effectively they carry out the position's responsibilities, which the employer
usually lays out for the employee. This method is particularly useful for
employees subject to merit-based pay, but also requires a time investment
that many supervisors won't make.
  <LI>	The weighted trait method utilizes standardized rating forms that
list qualities or &quot;traits&quot; of employee performance, such as &quot;Employee
works well with co-workers.&quot; This method is easily administered, but
tends to be general and focused more to personality instead of performance.
  <LI>	With the management by objective method, the employee and supervisor
agree on performance objectives for a set time period, monitor progression
toward the goals and ultimately base the evaluation on whether the goals
were achieved. This method includes no surprises, but is subject to the
limitations of forecasting. In other words, an unforeseen occurrence might
make it impossible for the employee to reach his or her goals. Then, how
do you evaluate?
  <LI>       The narrative evaluation method is just that, a written rundown
of the employee's performance, with no set formula. This tends to be the
most descriptive and informative for the employee, but also can be hampered
by a supervisor who lacks writing ability or does not have the time to invest
in the evaluation. If the supervisor spends 15 minutes writing an evaluation
that should take one hour, trouble is looming.
</UL>
<BR>
&quot;Unless you really train supervisors and oversee the system, the evaluations
tend to not be a useful tool,&quot; McTiernan says, &quot;either because
the supervisors give too favorable a review or they do not give an accurate
account.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The bottom line: Do evaluations right or don't do them.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's better not to do them at  all than to do them improperly,&quot;
McTiernan says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you are not good at putting things into writing, then don't put
them in writing,&quot; Giotto adds. &quot;If you are not capable of doing
performance appraisals properly, then don't do them.&quot;             
                                     <BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
&copy; Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
