<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Law.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H17Education.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Sports.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>Evolving SAT Scores</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1>College Admissions Counselors Say the Standardized Test<BR>
Scores Still Carry Weight, Just  Not as Much as Before</FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Ask any college-bound high school junior what he's losing the most
sleep over, and chances are, he'll mention the Scholastic Aptitude Test,
or SAT.<BR>
<BR>
Those fears are well founded: SAT scores are required by virtually every
college and university for admission, and have become so important that
students spend hundreds of dollars on prep courses to bone up for the test.
In fact, more than 1 million students in the class of 1995 took the dreaded
exam last year, scoring an average of 428 out of 750 points on the verbal
section and 482 on the math.<BR>
<BR>
 Yet prospective collegiates waiting for those scores can relax - a bit.
Though SAT scores are often a good determinant of which students will be
admitted into a particular college, they're only one piece of the application
puzzle.<BR>
<BR>
In fact, most institutions consider SAT scores as just one in a whole laundry
list of admission requirements. Just as important are grades, class rank
and extracurricular activities, as well as college prep-type curriculum,
such as honors courses in English, natural sciences, history and mathematics.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;SAT scores do carry weight,&quot; acknowledges Kevin Altomari, executive
associate director of admissions at the University of Pittsburgh, &quot;because
it continues to be the one benchmark consistent for all students.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
However, he continues, colleges are less likely to rely on them as blindly
as they have in the past, especially since the test scores have been &quot;recentered&quot;
so the national average on each section will be boosted back to 500 next
year.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's a tool to help us better understand an applicant, but we don't
put the scores into a computer and spit out who to accept,&quot; says Altomari.
Rather, an admissions committee meets each day to individually review the
more than 10,000 applications Pitt receives each year.<BR>
<BR>
At Pitt, grades are most important, followed by standardized test scores
and class rank. The school won't publish SAT averages for its incoming freshman
classes because then applicants would &quot;put too much weight on that
piece of the pie,&quot; says Altomari.<BR>
<BR>
Chatham College is more forthcoming - its students average 1050 and above.
But it, too, considers SAT marks as only part of the story.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Scores can be deceiving,&quot; says Annette Giovengo, dean of enrollment
management. &quot;Someone may not test well but have excellent academic
preparation.&quot; Conversely, a student may test well but have a transcript
that reveals she's not ready for college work, she says.<BR>
<BR>
As at Pitt, good grades are of significance, but Giovengo says they take
a &quot;good hard look&quot; at what those grade point averages tell them.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We look for commitment to academic achievement,&quot; Giovengo says,
noting some students struggle in the early years, pulling their GPA down.
&quot;We don't believe in penalizing a student for a bad experience she
may have had - such as a death in the family.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Extracurricular activities, too, are a big piece of the puzzle, as is community
service and leadership skills because they paint a picture of a student
who will contribute to a campus as well as enhance the educational product.<BR>
<BR>
To give prospective students a chance to sell themselves, Chatham recommends
that applicants complete one of five essays on what it takes to be a successful
student (for example, &quot;I have a lifelong dream or goal&quot; or &quot;I
am an independent thinker&quot;). In addition, Chatham encourages students
to submit portfolios, resumes, graded writing samples - anything that gives
a better picture of their background and goals.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We try to get as complete a picture of that student as possible so
we can make the best judgment we can about her,&quot; says Giovengo. <BR>
<BR>
At Seton Hill College, the number one criterion for admission is a successful
marriage of school grades and curriculum.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;We would prefer to have someone take calculus and earn a 'B' than
stop at algebra 2 and get an 'A', &quot; says Peter Egan, director of admissions.<BR>
<BR>
Seton Hill also looks for extracurricular activities such as sports, band,
clubs and student council, as well as community service because, as Egan
reasons, students who are involved in high school tend to be those who are
more involved in college.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;All activities are student-run,&quot; he says, &quot;so we're looking
for students who will contribute.&quot;<BR>
An essay, too, is suggested for those students who want to explain a circumstance
where they might need extra help, or would like to tell what they   hope
to accomplish at Seton Hill.       <BR>
<BR>
<B>What Admissions Counselors Consider<BR>
<BR>
1.	Grades and courses taken in high school<BR>
2.	SAT scores<BR>
3.	Class rank<BR>
4.	Essays included with the admissions application<BR>
5.	Extracurricular activities<BR>
6.	Leadership qualities</B><BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
&copy; Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
