"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Believe It</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Here's a Professional Athlete Who Shunned<BR>
Free Agency's Big Bucks to Stay in Pittsburgh<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>To his agent, it's a feel-good, &quot;dog-bites-man&quot; story that
never gets the publicity it deserves. To his general manager, it is simply
a case of someone looking at the &quot;total package&quot; and finding value
someplace other than the bottom line.<BR>
<BR>
Even Jeff King feels the need to remind people every once in a while: &quot;I
did not take a pay cut.&quot;<BR>
Indeed, he did not. In fact, since he stands to make $5 million for two
years work with the Pirates, he certainly qualifies as one of the highest-paid
residents of western Pennsylvania.<BR>
<BR>
In this era, that's not unusual for baseball players, especially for those
who have proven to be as productive and versatile as King, the Pirates first
baseman. What makes King unusual is that he could have made more - maybe
a lot more - but he chose not to explore the possibility. <BR>
<BR>
At the end of the 1995 season, with baseball in Pittsburgh in a state of
uncertainty, King showed his faith in  the Pirates. Rather than choose to
become an unrestricted free agent, which he was entitled to do, he instructed
his agent to make a deal that would keep him in Pittsburgh. <BR>
<BR>
In essence, he told his agent to make a deal without really knowing how
much he was worth. <BR>
And as someone capable of playing all four infield positions who has shown
steady improvement in power and production in his seven-year career, he
was likely to find he was worth plenty. In a Sports Illustrated poll of
Major League players, managers and general managers, King was selected among
the five most underrated players in the National League. In other words,
the fans don't necessarily know how good King is, but the rest of the league
does.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Possibly, I could have gotten him $1 million more and probably $400,000
to $500,000 more a year,&quot; says Alan Hendricks, King's agent. &quot;This
is a wonderful story about loyalty. We all have images of athletes chasing
the almighty dollar. This is the reverse of that story.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
For the 31-year-old King, there were other concerns beyond money. A year-round
resident of Wexford, he enjoys the North Hills, as does his wife, Laura,
and his four children. He likes the Christian school that his children attend
and he very much likes his church, the Christian &amp; Missionary Alliance
Church of Allegheny Center.<BR>
 <BR>
He also likes the Pirates organization because of the way it's treated him.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The Pirates have always treated me well,&quot; says King, who had
a career-high 18 home runs in 1995. <BR>
&quot;They supported and stuck by me when I hurt my back in 1991. I appreciate
that.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
He also appreciates his manager, Jim Leyland, and the fact that the Pirates
told him he could play first base full-time in 1996. As a free agent, he
likely would have generated most interest as a third baseman. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;He had a preference to play first, not third,&quot; says Hendricks.
<BR>
<BR>
Even the things that have previously hurt the Pirates in attempts to sign
and/or hold onto other free agents were positives for King. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Pittsburgh is the greatest place to play,&quot; King says. &quot;I
like the small-time atmosphere. I like the fact that there's not a big media
presence here. In New York or L.A., the media can break a player, but that
doesn't happen here.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Pirates General Manager Cam Bonifay says for many free agents, &quot;the
money aspect is not always the thing that determines where players go.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Bonifay believes players - especially the more mature ones - look at the
total package, which includes the manager, the organization and the city,
as well as family concerns. He thinks the Pirates can attract some free
agent talent in the coming years by pushing the new ownership and the city's
commitment to a new ballpark.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I suppose you're always curious about how much you're worth on the
open market,&quot; says King. &quot;But it was no secret I wanted to stay
here. The deal we made was good for me and good for them. I got to stay
where I wanted. I didn't feel like uprooting my family. To me it was not
worth it to go to a situation that might not be as comfortable for me.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
His agent has another theory. &quot;I think he didn't want to be tempted,&quot;
says Hendricks of King's decision not be a free agent. &quot;He's a nice
man and I think he was afraid the offer would come back $4 million a year
instead of $2.5 million.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
King, however, is not easily tempted.  He looks at it this way: &quot;Sometimes
getting every last dollar is not the most important thing.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
