<A HREF="../zine/0796.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Feature.2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Hold the Pickles,<BR>
Hold the Ketchup<BR></B>
</FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Richard Bierck</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>The Chernozem region of southern Russia is a farmer's dream, with
black, fertile soil extending more than 12 feet deep into the earth. Here,
about 1,000 miles from Moscow, the growing season runs about the same duration
as western Pennsylvania's growing season, but that's where the comparison
stops. Few, if any, agricultural regions in the world compare to the Chernozem.
It's that black, mineral-rich earth. Crops thrive in it.<BR>
<BR>
This year, many farmers in the Chernozem are growing buckwheat for H.J.
Heinz Co., the Pittsburgh-based multinational company that's more famous
for products from tomatoes and cucumbers - ketchup and pickles - than products
from buckwheat.<BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, the Chernozem farmers, with that black earth imbedded under
their fingernails, will harvest their buckwheat this fall and haul it down
the country roads of rural Russia to an H.J. Heinz Co. plant in Georgievsk,
in Russia's Stavropol region.<BR>
<BR>
For at Heinz's Russian facility, it's not pickles or ketchup rolling off
the plant floor, but baby cereal. The company is hoping that mothers who
feed their children Heinz baby cereal now will develop brand loyalty - eventually
feeding their families Heinz soups or condiments as the company expands
in this huge market. They think it's a good bet.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The one way consumers are the same in Russia and the United States
is when it comes to babies,&quot; says Brian E. Falck, area director for
Heinz operations in Russia.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Parents are very cautious about the brands they buy and are willing
to spend money on those brands. That's money that they would never spend
on themselves. Even if it means sacrificing for the rest of the family,
infant feeding has to have a level of trust,&quot; Falck says.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Open Door<BR>
</B><BR>
Companies like Heinz began looking closely at Russia after December 1988,
when the Soviet Union passed a law allowing foreign majority holding in
businesses. This prompted a slew of U.S. companies to jump into Russia.
Many, like Heinz, had already sold some products there, but now manufacture
there, too.<BR>
 <BR>
Take Pepsi, the cola then-Soviet Premier Nikita Kruschev was photographed
drinking in 1959. It has long held a market edge over rival Coke in Russia
and is investing $550 million over five years to expand manufacturing and
distribution reach in central, northwestern and eastern Russia.<BR>
<BR>
And Wm. Wrigley Jr. Co., which supplies Russia with chewing gum made at
its plant in France, is spending $25 million to build a chewing gum plant
in St. Petersburg.<BR>
<BR>
For Heinz, the idea was to locate production near the raw materials - the
grains of the Chernozem - because the dry baby cereal could be shipped more
economically than the raw materials. Since Stavropol is a Russian tourist
attraction because of its inland springs, it has excellent rail and air
travel connections.<BR>
<BR>
And business-wise, a majority partnership in Russia was desirable to Heinz,
which   is resistant to releasing its trademark unless it controls the enterprise.
At the same time, however, Heinz executives say they prefer not to own 100
percent of a foreign partnership because they prefer a substantial local
commitment. Thus they echo the philosophy of CEO Anthony J.F. O'Reilly,
as he wrote in the Columbia Journal of World Business in the spring of 1988:
&quot;Above all other requirements for offshore joint ventures is our imperative
of majority interest. ... The key to our strategy has been to use the joint
venture as our entree to a region. A joint venture offers the twin advantages
of familiarity and facilities.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But there are disadvantages to working this closely as well - especially
between two cultures with a history like that of Russia and the U.S. Heinz
executives began the on-again, off-again project while communism still reigned,
and for six years navigated the regime's collapse and tumultuous aftermath
to achieve its fruition.<BR>
 <BR>
Today, about 180 Russians cover two daily shifts at the Heinz plant in Georgievsk,
producing box upon box of dry baby cereal in two flavors: buckwheat and
buckwheat with apple.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Genesis<BR>
</B><BR>
It was early July 1989, in Stavrapol,  the heart of the Chernozem. The scene
was the office of Alexander Gaevou. Several telephones, a status symbol
in the Soviet bureaucracy, adorned his otherwise stark desk, proving Gaevou
a figure of some authority.<BR>
<BR>
 Gaevou was director of the area's kombinat, a combination of farms and
factories established by the region's former governor, Mikhail Gorbachev,
as an incubator for agro-industrial reform. The Soviet government had pointed
to Gaevou when Heinz executives asked whom to contact concerning a partnership
in Stavrapol; this meeting followed several with other leaders, who had
seemed uninspired.<BR>
<BR>
Extending from Gaevou's desk was a long conference table that bore bottles
of mineral water (a Communist tradition since Stalin) and a jar of candy.
Sitting around the table were Englishman Michael J.B. Smither, operations
director for Heinz in eastern Europe; Tom MacMurray, a Scotsman who preceded
Falck as the company's area director for central and eastern Europe; Gaevou;
local government officials; and assorted bureaucrats, some of whom had traveled
1,000 miles south from Moscow.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They were deputies this and deputies that; they had obviously been
sent to watch us dangerous foreigners,&quot; Smither recalls.<BR>
<BR>
Why shouldn't they? The Berlin Wall wouldn't come down until the following
year; the Soviet Union was not dissolved until December 1991. And though
the Soviet Union was already embarking on the wrenching transition from
totalitarianism to the first vestiges of a free-market economy, old habits
- and hatreds - die hard. <BR>
<BR>
Heinz executives used this initial meeting to size up Gaevou, too. &quot;It
was exploratory,&quot; says Smither, a former attache in the British embassy
in Moscow who speaks fluent Russian.<BR>
&quot;We were feeling them out and they were feeling us out. The Cold War
wasn't officially dead yet,&quot; Smither says.<BR>
<BR>
After proceeding for about an hour, the meeting became mobile as Gaevou
proudly squired the Heinz people around state farms and processing factories.
The tours and meetings continued for weeks, often centering around a rustic,
wood-toned hotel. Many times, the entourage didn't sit down to dinner until
late in the evening.<BR>
<BR>
As MacMurray tells it, this was just as well, for dinner invariably involved
a good deal of toasting, with native vodka that was glycerine-slick from
freezer storage. &quot;Every time they toasted, they drank a glass of vodka
- and they toasted a lot,&quot; MacMurray recalls. &quot;The secret was
to take a small sip when someone else is toasting and to keep your own toasts
to a minimum.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But the quintessentially Russian Gaevou didn't subscribe to this minimalist
school of toasting. To the contrary, as he grew to trust his American partners-to-be,
his toasts evolved into bear hugs - one so exuberant it broke two ribs of
Paul Corddry, then a Heinz senior vice president. &quot;Paul's eyes practically
popped out of their sockets,&quot; says Smither. &quot;When a Russian gives
you a bear hug after a few glasses of vodka, you know you've been hugged.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But even as Gaevou hugged his new partners, another squeeze was in the offing
- that of old-line Soviet bureaucracy on the strange new culture of open-market
capitalism.<BR>
<BR>
From 1989 to 1993, the fate of the project was directly in the hands of
the Russian government. Beyond the challenge of dealing with a bureaucracy
 designed to operate a state-regulated economic system, Heinz had to overcome
the obstacle of being pegged an outsider with an alien commercial  mindset.
Russian economics is different than American economics.<BR>
<BR>
Bruce Bowden, chair of Buchanan Ingersoll's international practice group,
has experienced the difference first-hand during trips to the Ukraine. &quot;They're
able to do the math,&quot; Bowden says. &quot;But they don't approach it
the same way.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Specifically, the Russians want to know how much finished product they'll
get, not how much money they'll make. Heinz found that out.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The biggest sticking point in the whole thing was that the Russian
economy was material-based, in which they think of the output of a factory
as so many things, whereas we tend to think of it in terms of a value,&quot;
Smither explains. &quot;So the concept of them receiving their share of
a business in money - in dividends - was foreign to them. If they had 15
percent of the business, for example, they thought they were going to get
15 percent of the product that the factory produced.&quot;<BR>
Could this cultural chasm be spanned by speaking in terms of rubles and
dollars? Hardly easy, considering that under the former communist system,
virtually all rubles ultimately belonged to the government.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They didn't instinctively understand that dollars and rubles are tools
in business and that you need to use those tools ... they knew the theory,
but it doesn't work that way,&quot; says Smither. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;[For a long time,]Russian industry didn't have any means of counting
work in progress. It just measured what came in and what went out. So you
can have a very efficient business with a high turnover, but there could
have been tens of millions of dollars tied up in work in progress that was
bankrupting the enterprise.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Other Cultural Gaps<BR>
</B><BR>
In the Soviet Union, building a new factory was naturally approached in
its societal totality. The project was viewed as the nexus of a new community
that would spring up around it - a community that, like the factory, would
be built by the state. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Historically, if the Russians built a factory on a greenfield site,
they would automatically include as part of that factory the costs of providing
accommodations for the workers: transportation, schools, medical and dental
care,&quot; says Smither. &quot;They would build a mini-city around the
factory, which means their critical mass of factories had to be pretty large
to make it worth doing. In a horizontally integrated economy, you build
a factory to do one thing only - manufacture products. But if you wanted
to have the permits to operate a factory [in the Soviet Union], people would
come along and say, 'Where is your hospital? Where is your fire station?
Where is your kindergarten? Where is your nursery school?' &quot;<BR>
<BR>
Though that expectation was, in reality, suspended with communism's fall,
the mindset remained. Tethered to Gaevou, Heinz executives trudged through
the moraine left by a glacier of Soviet-era bureaucracy. To make matters
worse, the deal was still not cemented when Soviet tanks rolled into Latvia
and Lithuania in the Baltic crackdown in 1991. Heinz's straightforward business
development suddenly assumed political connotations. A clean getaway was
even in doubt, because the ruble wasn't then convertible to dollars. Heinz
executives grew antsy about whether they'd be able to pull out their stake
if they decided to.<BR>
<BR>
And after this threat passed, another potential deal-breaker came when the
Soviets disbanded the kombinats. Suddenly, Heinz officially had no Russian
partners.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Then they went through the legal process of taking the rights to someone
else,&quot; says Smither, a process during which many previously resolved
issues were put back on the table. &quot;All that seemed to take about three
years.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It was 1993, nearly two years after the USSR no longer existed, before the
Russian government gave the Russo-American partnership permission to proceed
with plans to build the factory. <BR>
And the fun was just beginning.<BR>
<BR>
Heinz secured a promise for  $3 million in grant money from the federal
Agency for International Development. The agency's interest was for Heinz
to transfer western technology in the form of construction methods and agricultural
techniques, and thus benefit Russian society. <BR>
 According to MacMurray, the grant money, $2 million of which was actually
used, was useful in defraying the cost of teaching basic construction methods
in a culture where quality was only consistent in prerevolution structures.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Most Russian buildings aren't built very well. When they build a building
and take the scaffolding down, it looks about 20 years old,&quot; says MacMurray.<BR>
<BR>
Design commenced immediately, and the foundation was laid in late 1994.
 But Heinz's contractors had to begin at ground zero to get the right materials.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We decided to use western construction companies to teach the locals,&quot;
says MacMurray. &quot;One thing they were taught is how to make bricks.
We were rejecting about 70 percent of the bricks coming to the site. Then
they taught the brickies [masons] how to build walls; they had never used
plumb lines.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
All this took time, especially considering the language barrier. Though
the different companies involved had some bilingual people on board, a new
way of doing something - once understood - had to be related to monolingual
co-workers. &quot;It takes twice or three times as long that way,&quot;
MacMurray says.<BR>
<BR>
The factory was finished as designed in 1995, but delays continued to bedevil
the project. Though free market ventures were getting the go- ahead from
the Russian government, the process was still replete with bureaucracy lingering
from the Soviet era. Add to this the new, strange animal of a Russo-American
partnership, and the result was mounds of red tape for even the most routine
items.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Just getting safety certificates for simple thing like boilers would
take two or three months,&quot; MacMurray recalls. &quot;Electrical installation,
pipe work, sewers, drains - everything had to be inspected and it all took
two or three months longer than expected.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The farmers were another concern - obviously,  without buckwheat, there's
no cereal. Heinz executives have labored to consistently obtain quality
raw materials at the right price. The buckwheat must be of a precise grade
and be milled to the correct specifications. Also in demand is the right
kind of apple puree. &quot;You have to find out who's doing it [the best]
and then go work with them,&quot; Smither says.<BR>
<BR>
Shepherded by such hands-on effort, though, the crops are coming in as ordered,
and production is proceeding as planned. Heinz is now sending the dried
baby food initially to Moscow and St. Petersburg. The cereal sits beside
the Heinz baby food that is shipped in from other European     facilities.<BR>
<BR>
<B>A Homegrown Strategy</B><BR>
<BR>
The decision to produce pre-cooked baby food from and on Russian soil hinged,
for the most part, on the culture's ubiquitous cooking tool - the samovar,
which boils water used to make tea.<BR>
&quot;Baby food was their crying need in Russia, but we had to make baby
food safely and successfully using local ingredients and local processing
and yet still have an advanced recipe that met the needs of the society,&quot;
Smither says. &quot;The samovar doesn't make tea. It boils water. Because
of the samovar, boiled water is almost universally available across the
whole of the former USSR, whether in a tent on the steppes or in a railway
waiting room in Murmansk. So if you've got a mother with a baby and give
her a product to add boiling water to, she's got a precooked, ready meal
that's hygienic.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Neat, clean, efficient. But would the mothers buy it? In the Russian culture,
where time isn't so precious, would they care that the baby food was instant?
In America? They would. But this was not America, so that's where marketing
came in.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The convenience part won't appeal to all Russians because, unlike
the West, there are still many stay-at-home moms. Just as important, there
are still many grandparents living with the family. [The convenience] is
really our prime education job. The consumer has got to understand the convenience,&quot;
says Falck. &quot;But it's an opportunity, too.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Heinz will buy some print advertising and hand out samples. It also will
try to educate the healthcare professionals who staff birth houses, the
Russian version of maternity wards.<BR>
<BR>
Who wins from this project? Both Russia and Heinz.<BR>
<BR>
In the country, some 1,200 Russians, apart from factory employees, received
the training that AID envisioned in trades such as masonry.<BR>
<BR>
Heinz, meanwhile, is building a new clientele in a vast market.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The name recognition Heinz has right now in Russia is principally
a result of baby food,&quot; Falck says. &quot;The consumer could continue
to grow up with other products, ketchup and soups. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;What better way to engender awareness and trust than with baby food.&quot;
                                                <BR>
<BR>
