"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Atlanta's On Fire<BR>
</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Linda A. Dickerson</I><BR>
<HR><B>Atlanta is More Than the Town Hosting the 1996 <BR>
Summer Olympics; This Town is a Hotbed of <BR>
Entrepreneurial Activity and is Growing Younger Daily<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>Don't confuse metropolitan Atlanta with Pittsburgh. Atlanta leads the
nation for the last four years in job creation, immigration, housing starts
and building permits issued. It's a city where well-educated twenty or thirty-somethings
go to launch their successful careers. It's a city that exudes an energy
and vitality antithetical to its sleepy southern heritage.<BR>
<BR>
Growth exacted an exorbitant price, however. Atlanta boasts one of the country's
highest metropolitan crime rates, while Pittsburgh proudly proclaims the
nation's lowest crime rate. And despite a six-to-eight lane bypass around
the city's core, traffic regularly chokes Atlanta, whose suburban sprawl
is unmatched. As Atlanta's burgeoning boundaries continue to  test its city
limits, Pittsburgh's topography keeps it relatively constrained.<BR>
<BR>
High growth versus low growth. Young versus old. Unsafe versus safe.  Expansive
versus contained. The differences between Atlanta and Pittsburgh are significant.
Yet, the most striking dichotomy between the cities is less apparent and
difficult to quantify. <BR>
<BR>
<B>It is attitude.</B><BR>
<BR>
The granddaddy of all entre-preneurs, Ted Turner, who brought CNN to the
world, describes Atlanta as &quot;having one of the most can-do attitudes
on the planet.&quot; A past riddled with social anguish and destruction
instilled a resiliency within Atlantans that manifests itself today in this
hallmark can-do temperament. Sherman reduced the city to ashes but failed
to defeat Atlanta's indomitable spirit.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Atlanta thinks that it can conquer the world,&quot; says Keith Melton,
vice president of development at the Atlanta Economic Development Corp.
&quot;This is a very opportunistic environment. We're opportunistic about
building wealth here.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
This &quot;opportunistic&quot; environment makes Atlanta the lightning rod
for international investment. In 1994, the Association of Foreign Real Estate
Investors dubbed Atlanta the most viable city for investment. Over 1,400
foreign businesses representing 35 nations operate in Georgia. Metro Atlanta
is home to most of these enterprises.  Thirty-two foreign banks have a presence
in Atlanta, fueling this burgeoning international economy. <BR>
 <BR>
Because the nation will rivet its attention on Atlanta during this month's
Olympics, the city will secure its long-term position as a major player
in the game of global economics. The Olympics is the ultimate affirmation
that the city has come of age, adding $5.1 billion dollars to the Atlanta
coffers, creating 80,000 new jobs and attracting 2 million visitors.<BR>
<BR>
Behind it all is Billy Payne, an attorney-turned-community leader who lit
the Olympic torch for Atlanta. Payne mortgaged his home to raise the seed
capital to pitch Atlanta as the best location for the 1996 Summer Olympics.
Epitomizing the city's can-do attitude, entrepreneurial types like Payne
 abound.<BR>
<BR>
In its October 1994 issue, Entrepreneur magazine ranked Atlanta as the best
U.S. city in which to own a business. Fortune magazine validated Entrepreneur's
assessment when in both 1994 and 1995 it included Atlanta among the world's
top 10 cities in which to do business.<BR>
<BR>
As a testament to these rankings, more than 700 of the combined service
and industrial Fortune 1,000 companies have operations in Atlanta.  Melton
says that Atlanta is a new player on the world business stage.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Growth<BR>
</B><BR>
The confluence of many contributing factors spurred Atlanta's unbridled
growth. Aside from its upbeat approaches to development, the linchpin of
its success is Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport. Attracting Delta to Atlanta
was a capstone event that altered the city's destiny.<BR>
<BR>
Since its auspicious beginnings in 1842, Atlanta anchored its growth strategies
in transportation. From a city whose original raison d'&ecirc;tre was the
convergence of two railroads, the emphasis that present-day leaders place
on transportation is not surprising.<BR>
<BR>
Boasting the nation's largest international terminal, Hartsfield is also
one of the world's busiest airports. Roy B. Cooper, vice president of economic
development at the Atlanta Chamber of Commerce, says &quot;the airport is
undoubtedly our number one economic asset.&quot; Cooper cites superb transportation
as one of the top four reasons a company would locate in Atlanta. A modest
cost of doing business, the region's friendliness and a high quality of
life are among the other factors he says motivated over 1,500 companies
to relocate or expand within Atlanta during the past decade. <BR>
Hartsfield consistently ranks as the nation's premier airport and is pivotal
to Atlanta's extraordinary growth. Interestingly, on most rankings, Pittsburgh
International Airport rates a close second. <BR>
<BR>
However, Hartsfield's world-class air cargo capacity distinguishes it from
Pittsburgh. Hartsfield currently ships the nation's sixth largest tonnage
of air cargo and has the nation's only U.S. Customs model inland port and
the newest all perishable cargo facility. By contrast, Pittsburgh's air
cargo capacity is limited at best and is clearly not cost competitive with
other sites.<BR>
<BR>
Its aspirations to become the nation's port of entry for air cargo, and
the convergence of three major interstate highways in downtown, make Atlanta
a distribution powerhouse.  But transportation alone didn't produce Atlanta's
remarkable growth. Sweat equity also helped.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Atlanta businesspeople still think that they're on a frontier - that
there are opportunities here,&quot; says Sam Williams of Central Atlanta
Progress. He's right. Atlanta is a panacea for young entrepreneurs with
fire in their bellies to build a business. The city is growing younger,
while Pittsburgh grows older.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We have such a strong, growing economy. People with ideas can get
them going here,&quot; says the Atlanta Chamber's Cooper.  &quot;From the
Atlanta Chamber's perspective,&quot; he adds, &quot;we would very seldom
have Pittsburgh as a competitor.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
Why? Lots of reasons, but the most accurate and succinct reason is Atlanta's
reputation. &quot;People - especially young people - have heard that they
can get ahead in Atlanta, so they come here,&quot; says Melton, the economist.<BR>
<BR>
The centerpiece of incubator facilities, Georgia Tech's Advanced Technology
Development Center, is one of many magnets enticing the world's best and
brightest to launch their new business enterprises in Atlanta.  At least
70 percent of the companies hatched in Georgia Tech's incubator survive
the five year mark, garnering national respect. Companies launched at the
technology development center reportedly generated      $24 million in tax
revenues last year.  <BR>
<BR>
<B>Continued Growth<BR>
</B><BR>
Williams, of the Central Atlanta Progress, says,  &quot;Atlantans believe
that tomorrow will be better than today.&quot;  And, based upon the city's
recent results, they're probably right.<BR>
CAP is a private association representing business and downtown organizations'
interests. It works to make Atlanta safe, to develop market-rate housing
downtown, to capitalize on the economic development opportunities that the
Olympics present and to increase the number of jobs downtown.<BR>
CAP brings local and state government officials together on issues shaping
downtown development, promoting the downtown core in an environment where
no natural boundaries contain suburban sprawl.  &quot;This sprawl thing
- we just open a new upscale community every week,&quot; explains Carolyn
Boyd Hatcher, president and CEO of the Georgia Conservatory.<BR>
<BR>
Where suburban expansion becomes suburban explosion, solidifying a strong
and vibrant downtown becomes critical. Central Atlanta Progress and its
spin-off, the Atlanta Downtown Partnership, emerged as the ultimate champion
of the downtown's interests.<BR>
<BR>
Describing her organization as a cheerleader for downtown, Atlanta Downtown
Partnership head Ronnie French sadly comments, &quot;Without us [CAP and
ADP], there'd be nobody here to say 'Locate your business downtown, and
here's why.' &quot; <BR>
 <BR>
Endemic to its culture, Atlanta's boosterism is a legacy from the city's
past. In her famed work, &quot;Gone With the Wind,&quot; Margaret Mitchell
asserts, &quot;The people who settled the town were a pushy people. Restless,
energetic people  came with enthusiasm.  They were proud of the place, proud
of th.   growth, proud of themselves for making it grow.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Lauded years ago by the editor of City Builder as Atlanta Spirit, the city's
celebrated boosterism is its most salient quality. A prominent display at
the Atlanta History Center defines &quot;Atlanta Spirit&quot; as &quot;What
is good for business is good for Atlanta, and what is good for Atlanta is
good for all citizens.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Rated last year by Fortune as the seventh best place in the world to do
business, Atlanta beat the odds to hit the world's radar screen. From its
largely agrarian background, Atlanta emerged as an industrial and entrepreneurial
powerhouse. One hundred years ago, Georgia was the Cotton State, and Atlanta
was a railroad stop.  Period. Nothing else.<BR>
<BR>
Today, the world looks to Atlanta to set the pace.  How did the city metamorphose?
&quot;The confidence of Atlanta's leadership that it can do anything it
wants to&quot; is the key reason that the city sprinted onto the world business
scene according to Sam Williams.  At the Atlanta Chamber, Roy Cooper summarizes
the city's success similarly.  He says, &quot;Leadership is the key. A great
climate won't do any good if you don't have any leadership.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
With the fierce determination that typifies Atlanta, Cooper adds, &quot;We
don't let the [corporate] leadership 'not do' something; we get them involved.&quot;
 Williams adds, &quot;You really can't be a CEO in Atlanta and not have
a high level of community service. It's demanded.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
From a region that spawned &quot;the real thing,&quot; disingenuous leadership
is not tolerated. Describing his hometown as having &quot;a sense of soul,&quot;
Williams also acknowledges the role that committed government leaders played
in shaping the city's stellar success. During the tempestuous '50s and '60s,
a progressive mayor, Ivan Allen  put Atlanta 20 years ahead of itself according
to Williams.<BR>
Cooper freely recounts stories of governors who regularly recruit overseas.
Regarding Atlanta's impressive track record in growing its economy, he comments,
&quot;Over a prolonged period of time, government has been pro-business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
For Atlanta's sake, thank goodness that the state drives most of its economic
development activities. The stories of local government in Atlanta sound
curiously like stories from the 'Burgh. The city and the county are constantly
at odds. The mayor and his 18 member council don't generally agree. And
a City Charter Review Committee is recommending changes in an outmoded government
structure.  Doesn't this sound familiar?<BR>
<BR>
However, in Atlanta, the business community coalesced to work in concert
with state government. AEDC's Keith Melton characterizes the cooperation
between state government and business as &quot;superb.&quot; He asserts,
&quot;Government has incredible respect for the can-do attitude of private
business.&quot; With a governor who Melton refers to as &quot;the best governor
in the history of economic development,&quot; early reports of 100,000 new
jobs created in 1995 alone seem not only feasible, but expected.<BR>
<BR>
By Atlanta's standards, the Pittsburgh region's job growth goals are diminutive.<BR>
 <BR>
The Working Together Consortium, an offshoot of the Allegheny Conference
on Community Development, last year established a job creation goal of 100,000
new jobs in this region over the next six years.<BR>
<BR>
The difference between Atlanta's results and Pittsburgh's expectations is
attitude. Atlanta not only thinks it can - it knows it can.<BR>
<BR>
Locked out of her office, Ronnie French exemplified the Atlanta attitude.
Of course she could interview sans her office.  But she burst into a neighbor's
conference room, taking over with great finesse. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Part of our success is that we never give up,&quot; she says.<BR>
<BR>
