BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Battle of the Banks </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>Rival Banks Feel They Can Lure Away  Customers of the
<BR>
Former Integra Bank; National City With <BR>
About $50 Billion in Assets Says, Not So Fast </FONT> </B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Surely, it must rank as some sort of Pittsburgh first.<BR>
<BR>
A heretofore fiercely local enterprise is being invaded by an outsider and
the least important aspect of the enterprise - the least important part,
by far - is that the invader is from Cleveland.<BR>
<BR>
Not to belittle the longstanding Rust Belt rivalry, but it really does not
matter that National City Bank - the bank that acquired Integra Bank for
$2.3 billion in stock and renamed it National City of Pennsylvania on June
1 - is headquartered in Cleveland. <BR>
<BR>
Of far greater consequence is how Pittsburgh's parochial banking industry
will react to this new player and how western Pennsylvania customers -both
corporate and individual - will take to the newcomer. <BR>
<BR>
It's not that Pittsburgh's banking community is unfamiliar with acquisitions.
PNC Bank and Mellon have been spreading themselves into other markets for
years now. Those acquisitions helped place both banks among the top 20 largest
banks in the country at the end of 1995. <BR>
<BR>
Integra's acquisition by National City moves it to No. 17, making it a more
formidable force to be reckoned with in the marketplace. That is it should
be, assuming the Pittsburgh marketplace is open to outsiders.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In this marketplace,&quot; says Sy Holzer, executive vice president
of PNC Bank, &quot;the clients, we believe, much prefer to deal with a Pittsburgh-based
company.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We think the Pittsburgh market is unique and being a Pittsburgh bank
is a large advantage.&quot;<BR>
Certainly, that has been the conventional wisdom. But if there is one thing
National City's acquisition of Integra should definitely do, it is to either
prove or explode this long-held myth. Is the fact that until now the bank
acquisition movement has avoided Pittsburgh proof of the city's resistance
to outsiders, or just another example of how western Pennsylvania is always
late - but never entirely left out - when it comes to national trends? After
all, it may have taken a decade or so, but even Howard Stern eventually
entered the Pittsburgh market.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is a continuing trend. Pittsburgh's just catching up with the
rest of the country,&quot; says Joseph Duwan, a banking analyst for Keefe,
Bruyette and Woods in New York. <BR>
<BR>
If that is so, the Integra takeover is proof that it has caught up in a
big way. National City, a $35 billion diversified financial services company
based in Cleveland, purchased Integra, a $14 billion bank holding company,
effective May 31. With assets of $50 billion, National City compares favorably
with its new rivals, PNC ($61 billion) and Mellon ($42 billion).<BR>
<BR>
The merger made big news in terms of employment as well. Takeovers of this
kind are designed to streamline productivity, eliminate duplication of effort
and, essentially, save money as well as make money.<BR>
<BR>
 That generally means layoffs - as was certainly the case here, an area
feeling the effects of corporate downsizing longer than most of the country.
 Initial reports had the merger eliminating 1,500 jobs in western Pennsylvania.
The negative news fallout - the only negatives that have surrounded this
deal - caused National City to scramble and revise that figure to 1,200.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;That's just a result of any consolidation,&quot; says Thomas Golonski,
the former president of Integra, now president of National City Bank of
Pennsylvania. &quot;As the bank grows, those numbers can change. I see positive
hope for employment.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Certainly, most other signs are positive. The main idea behind the acquisition
was that Integra's strengths - retail banking and dealing with small business
customers - be maintained while its weaknesses are offset by National City.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Integra was good with companies that have sales up to $10 million,&quot;
David Daberko, chairman and chief executive of National City Corp., told
Dow Jones International News. &quot;They were very minor players beyond
that. It happens to be a business we're very good at in all of our other
markets.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Despite National City's desire not to appear an outsider, there is also
an interest in stressing the fact that the new entity will not just be Integra
with a new name. To that end a longstanding company policy - a $15 million
in-house  lending limit - has been lifted, according to Golonski. The new
 &quot;to start&quot; limit will be $25 million.<BR>
 <BR>
Golonski says that while Integra was five to six years away from achieving
goals such as being No. 1 or No. 2 in this market, joining National City
will shorten the time span. &quot;With National City, we'll provide first-class
competition for the upper-end market.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What I see happening is intensified competition in an already competitive
lending market,&quot; says Henry S. Pool, an attorney with Tucker Arensberg
of Pittsburgh who specializes in representing financial institutions. &quot;The
battle for the small to middle market customer - up to $100 million in sales
- will be strong, and PNC and National City will go head to head.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Historically, Integra and Union National were not aggressive in that
area.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Expanding into western Penn-  sylvania is a move that is consistent with
what Golonski calls National City's &quot;concentric&quot; growth pattern.
Prior to the Pittsburgh move, National City had gone into central Ohio,
northern Kentucky and Indiana.<BR>
<BR>
In keeping with that strategy, Pool sees National City as using western
Pennsylvania as an entry into a richer market farther east. &quot;National
City will try to move east incrementally,&quot; Pool says. &quot;Western
Pennsylvania is a particularly difficult lending market right now. The businesses
that are headquartered here - small and middle market companies - are very
cautious about going into debt.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Both National City on the corporate level and Golonski, in a personal sense,
understand how acquisitions work, or should work. One of the first things
National City did was to put Pennsylvania in the new name, and stress that
major decisions in the marketplace will be made by local officials.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;National City is careful,&quot; says Duwan, the industry analyst.
&quot;They have a lot of experience with acquisitions. They've obviously
learned a lot over the years and have a strong history of completing larger
transactions.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They're quite careful to focus on business generation on the business
side and at the same time achieve cost savings in the back shop. Most of
the savings they will achieve will be invisible from the customer standpoint.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Golonski contends that most customers - even in a relatively stable market
such as Pittsburgh - have grown used to bank mergers and acquisitions. A
former president of Seneca Bank, Golonski has worked for banks that have
been acquired three times in his 33-year career. He maintains that changing
times and the concept of local autonomy will negate any &quot;outsider&quot;
image. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think the reason the National City transition is as smooth as it
has been is that we didn't change any rules or any of the lending authorities,&quot;
he says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I remember when Integra took over Seneca, there was concern from our
opponents that Integra was getting too big to still be a community bank.
We went through some soul-searching, we formed industry groups and kept
our affiliates autonomous in the communities.<BR>
&quot;Since this merger has been announced, we've been growing. Western
Pennsylvania has the highest percentage of loan growth of all National City's
affiliates.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One area of unquestioned growth will come in marketing and advertising.
First, National City must educate its new customers with a large ad campaign.
And, while that's going on, its competitors realize this could be a good
time to remind customers that they've been here all along.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is a very exciting time if you're a marketer,&quot; says Joseph
B. Smith, senior vice president of marketing for Dollar Bank. Dollar Bank,
the second-largest savings and loan in Pennsylvania with $2.4 billion in
assets, is looking to cut into Integra's old retail business. And while
Dollar Bank isn't billing itself as the third-largest &quot;Pittsburgh&quot;
bank quite yet, it  is stressing historical themes in its advertising.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We feel well positioned to compete,&quot; says Smith. &quot;There's
a lot of unrest in this market. And anytime there's unrest, it presents
a good opportunity.&quot; Smith says Dollar Bank's advertising will emphasize
its 1855 founding and reassert its claim as &quot;the oldest bank in Pittsburgh.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Smith also understands that while the public is aware of the move to bank
consolidations all across the country, there could be strength in familiarity.
That's why Dollar Bank plans to be more aggressive this summer in marketing
its checking product. &quot;We're in a unique position in Pittsburgh,&quot;
Smith says. &quot;We're not going to be acquired.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But the main competition for National City will come from Mellon and PNC
Bank. Mellon declined to be interviewed for this story, citing the company's
policy of not commenting on its competitors or its own strategies.<BR>
<BR>
If PNC is worried, it is not showing it. &quot;Frankly, it doesn't change
anything for me personally,&quot; says Holzer. &quot;We're a bank that is
able to compete nationally with other out-of-town banks. We have the dominant
share of the market.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Holzer cites his company's status as the No. 1 underwriter of munici-  pal
bonds in Pennsylvania in 1995 - $660 million - as indicative of how size
and strength can produce local results.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We have the product capability and service to match the requirements
of any client.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;They will be a good competitor ... but their being in Pittsburgh 
doesn't change what we do here.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Even before the merger was complete, National City showed it was serious
about competing by luring former loan officers from both Mellon and PNC
to the new bank. <BR>
<BR>
Because National City poses more of a threat to Mellon and PNC for big customers,
its existence could bring about big deals in which two of the banks join
forces to the exclusion of the third. That, in turn, could lead to further
consolidation of banking interests in Pittsburgh. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The unanswered question is, 'Who is the next merger partner for National
City?' &quot; says Pool, who does not see the bank as an &quot;ultimate
survivor&quot; in the market.  &quot;By the year 2000 to 2005, there will
be 12 to 20 super regional banks and 5,000 to 8,000 community banks. There
will only be one or two Pittsburgh banks. Two banks will merge one more
time or they'll be bought.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But in the short term, everyone tends to agree with Duwan of Keefe, Bruyette
and Woods. <BR>
&quot;I expect change to be gradual,&quot;    he says. &quot;Pittsburgh
is quite a concentrated market to begin with. Its  top three banks have
the highest  percentage of the business of any major market.<BR>
<BR>
According to Duwan, in 1993, Mellon, PNC and Integra had 71 percent of the
lending business. Compar-atively, Philadelphia's top three banks had only
43 percent and St. Louis' only 39 percent. <BR>
Golonski says the new bank's immediate goals will be to use National City's
extensive corporate banking capacity and its cash management expertise to
grow the corporate side of the business, while maintaining Integra's market
share in retail.<BR>
<BR>
On the retail side, the biggest  question Golonski has is: &quot;How do
  you prevent disintermediation of the depositor?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
National City's answer is to provide securities underwriting and other investment
banking services not offered by Integra. National City also has what Golonski
says are &quot;better  technical-oriented capabilities.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But perhaps the most important thing that National City has is a sense of
reality. With National City, there's  a &quot;been there, done that&quot;
attitude that  is reassuring.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Being acquired is very traumatic,&quot; Daberko told American Banker,
&quot;and that carries over to customers because if employees are uncertain,
customers are going to be uncertain.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Golonski agrees totally. &quot;Acqui-sitions can be traumatic.&quot; But
he believes because the practices of National City are compatible with Integra,
this transition will be smooth.<BR>
<BR>
As for whether this can work in such a unique market, Golonski thinks he
understands that, too, as a result of his  personal history.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think Pittsburgh is unique. I think Cleveland is unique. I think
Erie is unique. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The winners in the long run deal with that uniqueness.  Pittsburgh
is definitely unique. Time will tell.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One thing is certain. The invader from Cleveland, as Pool says, &quot;spells
competition in an already tight marketplace.&quot;<BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Should Banks Be Selling Insurance? The Debate </B></CENTER>
<P>You already let them hold or invest your money. You turn to them when
you need to borrow money to pay for your home. Would you want banks to handle
your life insurance, too?<BR>
<BR>
Many of the banks are pushing for such privileges.<BR>
<BR>
And it may happen someday, although as this issue went to press, the outlook
for a bill to expand banks' powers to sell insurance and stocks was thrown
in doubt. In Washington, two senior Republicans joined Democrats and the
Clinton administration in opposing the major overhaul to current banking
regulations.<BR>
<BR>
The proposal, sponsored by House Banking Chairman Jim Leach - a Republican
from Iowa - was attacked as the committee opened what was expected to be
a lengthy and tense debate. <BR>
Leach's bill would repeal a key Depression-era law that separates banks
from Wall Street firms and insurance companies.<BR>
<BR>
A Republican opposing the measure, U.S. Rep. Doug Bereauter of Nebraska,
argues that the bill should be tied with other important banking issues,
such as Bereauter's bill to cut red tape for the banking industry as well
as a package to rescue the deposit insurance fund for the nation's troubled
savings and loans.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We cannot deal with these issues individually, in isolation,'' says
Bereauter, one of the committee's  ranking Republicans.<BR>
<BR>
The other Republican opposing Leach's proposed reform is U.S. Rep. Bill
McCollum of Florida. McCollum is instead pushing an amendment that would
permit banks and insurance companies to affiliate, despite state law to
the contrary.<BR>
<BR>
Leach, meanwhile, was pushing on without their support, calling his bill
&quot;the most significant financial services modernization approach of
the century.''<BR>
<BR>
The Leach bill has had a turbulent history. The full committee in May 1995
approved a bill to repeal key parts of the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act so that
banks could underwrite and deal in securities through separate affiliates.<BR>
<BR>
In June 1995, the panel passed a Bereauter's bill to reduce many regulations
for banks, including controversial revisions to laws that provide consumers
with consistent information about interest rates on savings accounts. <BR>
<BR>
But neither bill made it to the House floor because of intense fighting
between the bank and insurance lobbyists, who don't want bankers for  competition.<BR>
<BR>
According to Leach, the bill currently under consideration is &quot;in philosophic
harmony'' with the two measures approved by the committee last year, although
with major revisions to the insurance language.<BR>
<BR>
The Clinton administration sent a letter to Leach opposing the bill in its
current form, saying it would create &quot;needless regulatory burdens,''
hinder innovation and draw capital out of banks.                       
                  <BR>
<BR>
