    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Pennsylvania Environmental Council and Duquesne Light Company
Honor Local Environmental Achievements<BR>
 </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>Third Annual Three Rivers Environmental Awards Program
<BR>
Recognizes 29 Individuals and Organizations <BR>
Dedicated to Enhancing Western Pennsylvania's Environment</FONT> </B></CENTER>
<P><HR>The landscape of Western Pennsylvania was not always as clear and
clean as it is today. Before Pittsburgh's environmental renaissance, thick
black soot lined the streets and clouded the skies. However, thanks to the
efforts of many who started the environmental movement here, Western Pennsylvania
has become a cleaner, safer, and healthier place to live and work. <BR>
<BR>
These efforts were led by well-known local figures such as Richard King
Mellon, Mayor David L. Lawrence, and Henry J. Heinz. But a number of lesser-known
Pittsburghers played an equally important role in cleaning up the city and
surrounding areas - work that has led to substantial advancements in air
and water quality, as well as land conservation. <BR>
<BR>
Today, our friends, neighbors, and colleagues  are also playing an important
role in enhancing and     protecting our region's environment. Through their
 efforts in recycling, conservation, environmental management, and technology
development, today's  environmental stewards are helping to make Western
Pennsylvania one of America's most successful  environmental comeback stories.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Three Rivers Environmental Awards</B><BR>
<BR>
As a means of honoring the local individuals and     organizations who have
demonstrated their commitment to enhancing our region's environment, the
Pennsylvania Environmental Council and Duquesne Light Company established
the Three Rivers Environmental Awards    program in 1993. Recipients of
the Three Rivers Environmental Award have demonstrated a commitment to environmental
excellence, leadership, and accomplishment.<BR>
<BR>
The 1996 Three Rivers Environmental Awards Dinner was held on Tuesday, May
28, at the Pittsburgh Hilton and Towers. More than 600 business, civic,
and environmental leaders gathered to honor  29 award finalists, as they
competed  for top honors in 10 categories. These   29 finalists were chosen
from more than 100 nominations received. <BR>
<BR>
Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge was also on hand to deliver     the keynote
address at this year's awards dinner.<BR>
<BR>
The Three Rivers Environmental Awards are co-sponsored by the Pennsylvania
Environmental Council and Duquesne Light Company. Chairpersons for the event
were Joanne Denworth,   president of the Pennsylvania Environmental Council,
and Wes von Schack, chairman and chief executive   officer of Duquesne Light.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our goal in creating this program was to make   others aware of some
of Western Pennsylvania's most successful environmental efforts,&quot; said
Denworth. &quot;We hope to encourage others to emulate the achievements
of the finalists and winners - and improve the    quality of life in Western
Pennsylvania.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Those honored in the 1996 Three Rivers Environ-mental Awards are individuals
and organizations who have joined in accepting responsibility for the environment
- and their local communities,&quot; said Duquesne Light's von Schack. &quot;We
believe this commitment to environmental responsibility and stewardship
is very important, and we are proud to help recognize the accomplishments
of all our finalists.&quot;<BR>
In addition to the multimedia presentation honoring each finalist, the event
featured a video called There Once Was a Time, hosted by veteran CBS News
 correspondent Charles Osgood and produced     especially for the Three
Rivers Environmental Awards. The video chronicles the history of the regional
environmental movement throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, and complimentary
copies will be distributed to secondary schools throughout Western Pennsylvania.<BR>
<BR>
The 1996 Three Rivers Environmental   Awards program was open to individuals
<BR>
and organizations throughout Western Pennsylvania. Applications were evaluated
by an independent panel of judges based  on environmental need, environmental
impact, and evidence of impact, as well as planning and innovation.<BR>
<BR>
In addition to receiving an award, each winner was given a check for $1,000,
to  be donated to the local nonprofit environmental organization of his
or her choice.<BR>
<BR>
The efforts of the 10 recipients of the 1996 Three Rivers Environmental
Awards are described in the following pages. Finalists for each category
are also listed (in alphabetical order).<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>COMMUNITY -<BR>
Social Organizations</B><BR>
Winner:	
<BLOCKQUOTE>Green Harvest Program,<BR>
Greater Pittsburgh<BR>
Community Food Bank</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
The Greater Pittsburgh Community Food Bank's &quot;Green Harvest Program&quot;
provides a renewable source of fresh, organically grown produce for low-income
families in Western Pennsylvania, making it one of the most novel food bank
programs in the United States. Using crops from its 20-acre Longview Food
Bank Farm in McKeesport, the Green Harvest Program distributed more than
32,000 pounds of fresh vegetables to the hungry in 1995 alone - nearly half
of it harvested by community volunteers. Equally important are the environmental
education activities which take place at Longview Farm and several community
gardens supported by the Food Bank. Together, these programs have quickly
become an important source of fresh food for those in need, as well as a
dynamic environmental classroom.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:	<BR>
James W. Johnson<BR>
Oakmont's Boulevard Project, Garden Club of Oakmont<BR>
<BR>
<B>COMMUNITY -<BR>
Environmental Organizations</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Winner:	Loyalhanna Watershed Association</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
For a quarter of a century, the Loyalhanna Watershed Association, based
in Ligonier, has brought together a wide range of volunteers to protect
and enhance the natural beauty of eastern Westmoreland County and western
Somerset County. Farmers, teachers, businesspeople, and legislators work
together to promote conservation, recycling, and environmental enhancement
- through hands-on efforts, as well as community education. Initiatives
include the beautification of the Route 30 corridor, the development of
a 37-mile bike trail in the Laurel Highlands, efforts to reduce acid mine
drainage in Loyalhanna Creek, and a recycling program which has diverted
more than a million pounds of materials from landfills. In addition, day
trips, seminars, a youth conservation corps, and other outreach efforts
demonstrate the Association's commitment to involve the community in protecting
the environment.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:	<BR>
Recycling Committee<BR>
of the Borough of East Washington<BR>
Slippery Rock Watershed Coalition<BR>
<BR>
<B>GOVERNMENT</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Winner:	Erie City Water Authority</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Presque Isle Bay is significantly cleaner than it has been in many years,
thanks to the environmental stewardship initiatives of the Erie City Water
Authority. In response to growing public concerns about water quality in
the Bay, the Erie City Water Authority last year     elected to voluntarily
cut its wastewater emissions from 1.3 million gallons per day to zero! The
Authority moved quickly to install the necessary equipment at its two water
treatment facilities and, within months, had completely eliminated its permitted
wastewater discharges. As a result of this action, tons of suspended solids
- including aluminum, iron, and manganese - are no longer released into
the Bay. This effort has been cited as an excellent example of a municipality
going beyond federal standards to protect an important environmental asset.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:	<BR>
Charles J. Goetz<BR>
Westmoreland Conservation District<BR>
<BR>
<B>PUBLIC AWARENESS</B><BR>
Winner:	
<BLOCKQUOTE>Pittsburgh's Picking Up!<BR>
Pittsburgh Downtown Partnership</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Downtown Pittsburgh businesses are confirming that clean streets and sidewalks
can be good for business, thanks to the efforts of the Pittsburgh Downtown
Partnership's &quot;Pittsburgh's Picking Up!&quot; program. Since 1994,
the Partnership has been educating property owners and tenants about their
responsibilities to keep streets and sidewalks clean, as well as to enforce
city ordinances. Many property owners were concerned about the effect of
sidewalk trash on their businesses, so Partnership sidewalk cleaning crews
have literally been walking the streets picking up litter, adding new trash
containers, and helping to enhance the quality of life Downtown. Thanks
to the efforts of the &quot;Pittsburgh's Picking Up!&quot; campaign, more
than 600 pounds of trash and litter are removed from Downtown sidewalks
each week!<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:	<BR>
Don Hopey, Pittsburgh       Post-Gazette<BR>
Tarentum Energy Efficiency and Economic Initiative<BR>
<BR>
<B>BUSINESS - Environmental Products or Services</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Winner:	Recmix of PA, Inc.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
In stainless steel manufacturing, it is important to recover and      recycle
as much stainless material as possible from the residual slag. However,
conventional stainless steel slag recycling processes are inefficient, leaving
large quantities of useful stainless steel mixed with refuse material which
is discarded in slag piles. Fortunately, Recmix of PA has solved this problem
- with a highly efficient recycling  process that recovers far more stainless
steel than other methods. This process uses no chemicals, and yields a marketable
byproduct that has proven to be an effective alternative to lime as a buffer
in surface mine reclamation, and is also effective in reducing acid mine
drainage. To date, about one million tons of stainless steel have been removed
from Western Pennsylvania slag piles using this process.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists: <BR>
Kipin Industries, Inc.<BR>
Waste Management of Southwestern Pennsylvania<BR>
<BR>
<B>BUSINESS - Environmental Stewardship</B><BR>
Winner:	
<BLOCKQUOTE>Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. and <BR>
American Iron Oxide Company</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Each year, the steel industry uses millions of gallons of hydro-       chloric
acid solution as a cleaning agent during processing. In the past, this hazardous
waste was treated and then disposed of in landfills or deep wells - at great
cost to both the steel producer and the environment. In response, Wheeling-Pittsburgh
Steel Corporation, in partnership with the American Iron Oxide Company (AMROX),
constructed an on-site facility to separate pure hydrochloric acid for 
    re-use as a steel cleaning solvent. A byproduct of this innovative 
 process is high-quality iron oxide, used to manufacture washing machines,
televisions, and other consumer products. The AMROX facility safely regenerates
more than 21 million gallons of acid     solution each year - the equivalent
of nearly 200 million pounds of hazardous material that would otherwise
go into lready crowded landfills or wells.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:	<BR>
Clairton Works,<BR>
US Steel Group<BR>
Scrubgrass <BR>
Generating Plant<BR>
<BR>
<B>PLANNING, DESIGN, AND DEVELOPMENT</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Winner:	Techniflo Systems </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Acid mine drainage is a widespread environmental concern   throughout Western
Pennsylvania, but Wexford-based Techniflo Systems has commercialized new
technology to help address the problem. Based on technical research conducted
by the US Bureau of Mines, Techniflo products achieve more effective and
reliable large-scale treatment of acidic water than conventional systems
- at a fraction of the cost. In addition, this system produces less solid
waste than competing products. Through this technology, Techniflo has enabled
coal companies to afford the water treatment operations they need to comply
with environmental standards and reduce the amount of disposable solid waste
material produced - a major step forward in the battle to clean up mine-contaminated
waterways across the United States.<BR>
<BR>
Finalist:	<BR>
RPS, Inc. <BR>
<BR>
<B>EDUCATION - Primary or Secondary Education</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Winner:	Pittsburgh Voyager</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Pittsburgh Voyager provides local students in grades five through     12
with hands-on lessons in the ecology of Pittsburgh's three rivers. The centerpiece
of this program is the Voyager - an 80-foot, 70-ton retired Navy boat that
has become a floating laboratory for young environmental scientists. The
Pittsburgh Voyager staff provides    training for teachers at participating
schools, as well as classroom tools such as wet chemistry kits and river
charts. Students receive classroom lessons in water quality, aquatic life,
nautical science,   and related topics - then they embark on a one-day river
cruise       to apply what they've learned. In addition to biology and other
life sciences, student voyagers learn valuable lessons in environmental
stewardship - and see firsthand how pollution can affect humans, as well
as river plants and animals. <BR>
<BR>
Finalists: <BR>
Neighbors &amp; <BR>
Schools Gardening Together, The Pittsburgh Civic Garden Center<BR>
James G. Rutkowski,     Strong Vincent High School<BR>
<BR>
<B>EDUCATION - Higher Education</B><BR>
Winner:	
<BLOCKQUOTE>Center for Building Performance and <BR>
Diagnostics, Dept. of Architecture, 			<BR>
Carnegie Mellon University</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
The Center for Building Performance and Diagnostics at Carnegie Mellon University
is the only graduate architectural program of its kind in the US. The Department
of Architecture founded the program in 1981 to address environmental problems
associated with modern building construction - such as excessive energy
consumption - and to offer solutions aimed at sustainable development, design,
and construction. At the Center, faculty and graduate students work together
to overcome such challenges as poor air quality, inefficient use of energy,
and high operating costs. A key initiative is the &quot;Intelligent Workplace,&quot;
a 7000-square-foot facility under construction on the roof of an existing
campus building. This innovative facility will allow for real-world environmental
teaching and research - and encourage future architects to use environmentally
responsible practices in their own work.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:<BR>
Francis Clay McMichael, Ph.D., Dept. of Civil and Environmental Engineering,
Carnegie Mellon University<BR>
Western Pa. Section, Air and Waste Management Assoc.<BR>
<BR>
EDUCATION - Community or Continuing Education<BR>
Winner:	
<BLOCKQUOTE>Schoolground Teacher Workshops,<BR>
Audubon Society of Western Pa.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
For years, the Audubon Society of Western Pennsylvania has  conducted educational
programs for local elementary schools at Beechwood Farms Nature Reserve.
With environmental education now mandated by the Commonwealth, demand for
these programs is growing - while budgets for field trips are shrinking.
In response, the Audubon Society has developed a continuing education curriculum
that prepares elementary school teachers to conduct environmental lessons
at their own schools - teaching students about the natural environment of
their playgrounds. At participating schools, Audubon Society professionals
conduct Schoolground Teacher Workshops that introduce teachers, parents,
and administrators to natural resources, as well as instructional resources
that can help students learn about their environment. To date, nearly 350
teachers have participated in             30 workshops - and thousands of
students Ehave benefitted from this innovative program.<BR>
<BR>
Finalists:	Local Government Academy<BR>
Jane Madsen, Ph.D., and Harold Mitzel, Ph.D.<BR>
<BR>
