<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement5.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Getting Inside the Employee's Head </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>Hiring a New Employee is a Costly Investment; Can You
Tell in Advance Whether an Employee Will Steal or Act Violently in the Workplace?
Some Employers are Subjecting Prospects to a Battery of Tests</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>I thought he was the best thing since sliced bread,&quot; says Marty
Marra of a candidate who once applied to him for a managerial position.
Just as a formality, Marra gave the man a psychological profiling test his
company, Amarraca supermarket, administers to all managerial applicants.
But the test's results said the man was &quot;posturing,&quot; psycho-speak
for someone who tries to pretend he's something he's not.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;So I called one of his previous employers I happened to know, and
this guy told me, 'Marty, stay away from him. He's the biggest BS'er I've
ever met.' I said, 'Holy cow, these tests really work.' &quot;<BR>
Or do they?<BR>
<BR>
Stephen Whitlock, a young Briton, was well along in an interviewing process
with a small documentary production company until he was asked to go through
testing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I don't know about Americans, but the British are simply not used
to pouring their hearts out to people they don't know. I found the whole
process excruciating,&quot; he says. He found the psychologist to be &quot;completely
without a personality,&quot; the tests to be invasive and irrelevant, and
as a result, he clammed up. His testers told his employer that Whitlock
was arrogant and a cold fish.<BR>
&quot;They asked me if I would enjoy a vacation in Las Vegas,&quot; he says
scornfully. &quot;It was daft. I thought, the owner should have just taken
me out for a chat, I'd have been perfectly happy to talk to him.&quot; Because
of the bad taste in his mouth, Whitlock refused the company's subsequent
job offer.<BR>
To test, or not to test is a sticky question for many employers. Most people
have no idea what psychological testing is all about as it relates to employment.
And the myriad of testing options can be confusing. But with a little self-examination,
employers can easily decide what type of program to use or whether to test
at all.<BR>
<BR>
Good hiring practices, as any manager knows, can be critical because of
the heavy training investments in the new hire. An obvious clue to whether
employers can benefit from testing is whether or not they are satisfied
with their current hiring formula. Employers suffering from rapid turnover,
theft, excessive training costs, tension or inadequacies in large portions
of the work force may want to investigate testing. Otherwise, it may be
best not to upset a successful formula.<BR>
Psychological testing for the workplace can take many forms. Prospective
and current employees can be skill-tested for everything from math and verbal
skills to sales knowledge or customer service aptitude. &quot;Integrity
tests&quot; screen employees for traits such as honesty and likelihood to
abuse substances, even predict violent behavior. Other psychological profiles
attempt to measure applicants' job-related personality traits such as self-reliance
or organizational skills, or to try to determine an individual's fit with
the company offering the job.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are costs associated with psychological testing, including the
employer's time and the costs of the test itself. But tests which measure
some personality traits, like conscientiousness and extroversion, do have
validity, and these traits tend to correlate with job performance,&quot;
says Dr. Susan Straus, a psychologist with the Graduate School of Industrial
Administration at Carnegie Mellon.<BR>
<BR>
Garry Hughes of PCI, a division of Performance Management Resources, Inc.,
says all businesses can benefit from using an industrial psychologist.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;For small businesses, hiring is a critical issue because each new
person is a significant addition to the firm, and a good personal fit is
essential. And big companies just don't have the time to evaluate the way
I can,&quot; Hughes says.<BR>
<BR>
The first step in the process is to nail down exactly what the position
in question entails. Beyond the specific skills needed - math ability for
a cashier, typing or computer knowledge for a data entry clerk - industrial
psychologists help a client decide what skills are necessary.<BR>
<BR>
Does this position demand creativity? A great problem solver who thinks
systematically might not fit in. Is the office structured around teams working
for collective goals, or are employees asked to be self-motivated and independent?
Different types of organizational skills, ability to work in groups, or
with or without supervision will then be critical. A good testing company
will be able to tell employers what traits they haven't considered.<BR>
<BR>
Testing levels range from simple pencil and paper tests for entry-level
retail or clerical positions to hours of paper testing and interviews with
psychologists. Costs can range from $7 for a self-scoring test to $1,500
for intensive profiling of upper-level hires.<BR>
<BR>
Paper and pencil tests are used to scale applicants in a number of areas
by establishing a pattern of responses to simulations or statements. One
question will not &quot;knock someone out.&quot; Scales are drawn based
on the responses of productive employees to the same questions. All also
use a combination of evaluators, not just one test, for each trait or characteristic
they're testing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;These are well-established tests in the personality area, used nationally,
hundreds of thousands of times,&quot; says Hughes. &quot;Our database has
about 30,000 to 40,000 cases so we can be pretty sure. It's not a guess,
not a gut feeling.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Much entry-level testing stops with pencil and paper tests. For more advanced
positions or for an especially thorough process, the personal interview
allows for more flexible questions. The interviewer might ask the candidate
to describe their favorite previous work experience, or even to solve a
problem with a team of other interviewees. They might describe certain characteristics
of the position - this job pays on commission rather than steadily - and
ask the applicant's preferences in this area.<BR>
<BR>
Industrial psychologists say the benefit of their interviews is the experienced
hand they lend to the process. They emphasize that each psychologist has
professional training in just this field, and does hundreds of interviews
per year, while the average personnel manager may do 10.<BR>
In the end the psychologist will go over the battery of results and explain
what they mean for the client. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I usually try to give my clients an idea of the consequences associated
with their decision,&quot; says Hughes. For example, &quot;If they go with
person A, they're going to get someone who's ready to do a good job right
now, but they may not have any potential for developing five years from
now into more. Person B [is inexperienced and might need more] developmental
time, but they've got a great deal of potential.&quot; Giving clients more
information on which to base decisions, rather than picking or eliminating
candidates, is the name of the game.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Measuring Integrity<BR>
Can a test tell if you're honest?</B><BR>
<BR>
Integrity testing, despite changes in methods and design, is still surrounded
by controversy. <BR>
In general, research done for this article found that the only parties who
recommend integrity testing were those who sold the tests; others warned
about invalidity and legal problems.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;From a practical standpoint, these tests produce many false hits,
predicting too many people would not meet standards, and people are screened
out for the wrong reasons,&quot; says Bill Jackson, vice president of selection
and assessment services at Development Dimensions International, a human
relations firm based in Bridgeville.<BR>
<BR>
Other prickly issues include possible legal problems. Integrity tests are
currently restricted or banned in Massachusetts and Rhode Island, and challenges
rise in other states, including Pennsylvania.<BR>
Jack Jones, vice president of research and service with McGraw Hill London
House, which publishes integrity tests along with other screening instruments,
says many misunderstandings fuel the controversy. He says many industries
suffer heavily from theft and other losses because of employee behavior
like drug abuse, aggression (especially towards customers) or time theft.
He points to a supermarket industry survey conducted by London House, which
found that an average 150-store company may lose $1.6 million per year to
employee theft.<BR>
<BR>
What integrity instruments predict, he says, is a whole potpourri of counterproductive
behavior, not just attitudes towards theft. Integrity tests measure the
responses of individuals to attitudinal studies - about stress response,
how to deal with others who steal on the job, etc., and then create scales
based on which of those actually steal or use drugs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But in a literal sense you're not measuring but predicting based on
social conformity,&quot; points out Jackson. &quot;So if you are less uniform
than most people, you're not going to look good. Some of the neatest, most
productive employees are screened out.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Jackson, Hughes and others think the estimate that 30 percent of the population
steal (given by Jones and other integrity testers) is way too high. Their
estimate is around 2 to 3 percent. They also point out that &quot;theft&quot;
could refer to taking a pencil home and &quot;time theft&quot; could mean
lurking around the water cooler for five minutes longer than the model office
worker. If your company is losing money to theft, they say, it's a management
problem.<BR>
<BR>
Jones' response is that if you're talking about a hamburger and coke, well,
those add up into thousands of dollars over a year, billions for the industry.
Independent research on the issue found that losses to all businesses due
to &quot;theft,&quot; which could be defined as anything from pens or long
coffee-breaks to embezzlement, run anywhere from $5 billion to $40 billion
per year.<BR>
<BR>
The claim that testing can predict and therefore prevent workplace violence
is also disputed. Jones says research shows well-designed testing can predict
whether a candidate is disposed toward disruption, based on whether that
person handles stress well, is likely to use drugs, or so on. Hughes says
the only reliable predictor of future behavior is past behavior, and that
if he had a method that reliably predicted violent behavior, he'd be rich
beyond his wildest dreams.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Violence is hard to predict because there aren't enough occurrences
to measure factors accurately,&quot; adds CMU's Straus.<BR>
<BR>
The whole controversy is further fueled by a 1990 General Accounting Office
report concluding, in a nutshell, that &quot;research on integrity tests
has not yet produced data that supports or dismisses the assertion that
these tests can predict dishonest behavior.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That report sparked the American Psychological Association to do its own
study, which concluded that there is a demonstrated business need for the
tests, and that they have demonstrated predictive value. Other independent
studies have shown that integrity tests can have reliability and validity.<BR>
The APA also noted no test is perfect, and that such tests should only be
used as a supplement to other sources of information such as reference checks
and interviews. Jones, Jackson and Hughes also firmly recommended use of
more than just one test for any selection purposes. 
<H3><CENTER>To Test or Not?</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
Employers considering psychological testing services should consider the
following: 
<UL>
  <LI>Tightly define the position before you look for a testing service,
including a description of duties and qualities your company wants in that
employee. 
  <LI>Define your goals for the testing service - such as saving time, preventing
theft, finding employees who make a better fit with your business. Look
for a tester who gives you extra information, not one who makes the decision
for you. 
  <LI>Look for credentialed operations, affiliated with the APA. Look at
the stability of the company, and ask for references from other businesses
who use their services. Make sure the tests they recommend can be shown
to have no impact on protected minority groups and have documented effectiveness.
  <LI>Always use all available information, and evaluate candidates on your
own. Avoid using the service as your only evaluator. Keep in mind the reactions
of some people to taking such tests, especially people from other cultures.
If a test result is surprising, back it up with reference checks or other
validation. 
  <LI>Take the tests yourself, so you know what you're asking of your candidates.
Do you think this test is something you would resent taking? 
  <LI>Use the tests not only to make selections, but as an aid for the employee's
advancement, training in weak areas and utilizing strong points. 
  <LI>Evaluate the effectiveness of the testing program regularly - are
the new hires more productive? Has the testing service met the goals you've
set out to accomplish? 
</UL>
<BR>
One guide to setting up selection services is Jones' book, &quot;Personnel
Testing, A Manager's Guide.&quot; Jones outlines several specific steps
in choosing a service, including worksheets. Good testing services will
sit down with you and go over these steps themselves, ensuring you know
what you're looking for. <BR>
