ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement6.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Best Deals</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1>A Handful of Aces</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>The task before Kevin McClatchy last summer was crystal clear: Come
up with $90 million dollars ... within two weeks. If he failed, he'd have
to take his dream of owning a Major League Baseball franchise and head back
to California empty handed.<BR>
<BR>
Today, McClatchy's hands are full, juggling management of the Pirates and
a schedule loaded with public appearances in his role as the managing partner
of the Pirates ownership group he assembled for the purchase.<BR>
<BR>
For the most part, McClatchy's quest to buy the Pirates gained steam in
that two-week period shortly after Major League Baseball rejected the bid
of cable magnate John Rigas, the original frontrunner to purchase the team.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I was in California waiting to hear what the Rigas situation was,&quot;
McClatchy recalls. &quot;We were never told we were the group. I think initially
there were four or five groups. The idea was that we would come in and have
a two-week window to raise a huge amount of equity.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And once two weeks were up, the next player would step to the plate. But
McClatchy never gave anyone else a chance in the batter's box. He methodically
worked the deal for six months, finally scoring big this past spring when
the city, the team's former owners and Major League Baseball all signed
off on his bid to purchase the team.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In the end, we were able to raise, in a short amount of time, a substantial
amount of capital. We also brought in some good local partners, such as
Chip Ganassi and Tony O'Reilly, which I think helped us in the mayor's eyes,&quot;
McClatchy says today.<BR>
<BR>
The Pirates purchase leads the lineup of Best Deals of 1995 that are being
honored by Executive Report and Price Waterhouse as part of an annual program
recognizing deals that have a positive impact on western Pennsylvania. The
program also recognizes the dealmakers behind the deals.<BR>
<BR>
The Pirates deal wins this year under the category Best Quality of Life,
joining that category's previous winners including Carnegie Science Center
and the Pittsburgh Zoo. For the judges (see sidebar list) and outsiders,
McClatchy's purchase was a no-brainer since the presence of the Pirates
in Pittsburgh serves as a source of entertainment, tourism dollars, job
creation and regional promotion. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It's a deal that's good for baseball and the city of Pittsburgh,&quot;
Mayor Tom Murphy says of the McClatchy group's purchase. &quot;We kept our
team, and we did it in a way that makes sense.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Adds Gov. Tom Ridge: &quot;Pittsburgh is a national landmark for our national
pastime, and the Pirates could play baseball nowhere else - just as the
Golden Gate Bridge could span no other waters, and the Empire State Building
could rise from no other city.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It was June 1995 when electronics giant Sony joined Corning Inc. and Asahi
Glass America Inc. in a partnership to operate a television glass manufacturing
plant on the site of Sony's Pittsburgh Manufacturing Center in Mount Pleasant,
Westmoreland County. <BR>
<BR>
Today, the venture is known as the American Video Glass Co. and is being
honored for Best Regional Impact, joining previous winners Pittsburgh International
Airport, Union Switch &amp; Signal and the Pittsburgh Supplier Training
Center.<BR>
<BR>
The American Video Glass facility will employ about 500 people after production
begins at the plant next year. Representatives of the three companies broke
ground last fall after overcoming one key obstacle: the Clean Air Act and
its requirement that Penn-   sylvania manufacturers purchase emission credits.<BR>
<BR>
Sony spent about a year researching the availability of emission credits
before spending millions to actually secure the credits. Some credits were
purchased at a bankruptcy auction.<BR>
<BR>
Sony Electronic's Pittsburgh Manufacturing Center currently produces rear
projection televisions and is the company's world headquarters for the design
and engineering of that product. The facility, which opened in 1991, also
produces seven-inch cathode ray tubes for use in the rear projection sets
and has begun manufacturing aperture grilles used in Trinitron direct view
televisions. That plant employs approximately 700 people, across the street
from where the glass facility is being constructed. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sony, Corning and Asahi have growing operations in Pennsylvania, and
American Video will be a valuable asset to the three companies and the state,&quot;
says Donald Dicken, president of American Video.<BR>
<BR>
After a decade of planning, fund-raising, design and construction, the Historical
Society of Western Pennsylvania opened its new home, the Senator John Heinz
Pittsburgh Regional History Center, in late April.<BR>
<BR>
The 160,000-square-foot history center on Smallman Street in the Strip District
occupies the seven-story former Chautauqua Lake Ice Company warehouse and
two smaller attached buildings. <BR>
&quot;It's a great privilege to spend a decade of one's life building a
facility which represents so many positive things to a city and a region,&quot;
says John Herbst, executive director. &quot;We have had quite a team to
pull this off.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A team indeed, as virtually every corporation in the region anteed up funding
for the history center. David McCullough, the Pulitzer Prize-winning author/historian,
served as honorary chairman of the capital campaign, which has raised over
$30 million of the center's $36 million projected cost. Mellon Bank Chairman
Frank Cahouet headed the capital campaign.<BR>
<BR>
The history center comprises a first floor Great Hall, 50,000 square feet
of gallery space, library and archives, children's Discovery Place, museum
shop, cafe and the historical society offices. The permanent exhibit, &quot;Points
in Time: Building a Life in Western Pennsylvania, 1750-Today,&quot; occupies
the second floor.<BR>
 <BR>
Previous winners for Best Community Impact include St. Francis Health System,
the United Way of Allegheny County and the Blue Cross Caring Program.<BR>
<BR>
The actual papers were signed thousands of miles away, but the effect was
felt in a West Mifflin plant. Zurich-based ABB Asea Brown Boveri, a world
leader in electrical engineering, merged its railway activities with those
of transportation systems giant Daimler-Benz AG.<BR>
<BR>
The result is ADtranz, with North American headquarters in Pittsburgh and
continued operation of a West Mifflin plant that at presstime employed about
1,000. The facility formerly operated under the name AEG Transpor-tation
Systems Inc., which was part of Daimler-Benz prior to the merger.<BR>
Previous winners for Best Merger/ Joint Venture include Federated Depart-ment
Stores, Mellon Bank and Michael Baker Corp. <BR>
<BR>
ADtranz executives say their merger creates the world's most complete provider
of railway systems, with a portfolio including electric and diesel locomotives,
high-speed trains, inter-city and regional trains, trams and underground
trains, people-movers, signal and traffic control systems and infrastructure
installations, as well as servicing and maintenance.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;With our product range, capabilities and the strong backup of the
parent companies, ADtranz is a strong and powerful railway supplier able
to meet all requirements of our global customer base,&quot; says Kaare Vagner,
president and chief executive of ADtranz.<BR>
<BR>
Just before presstime, Singapore awarded ADtranz a $202.1 million contract
to build Singapore's first light-rail commuter line, opening the door to
a possible $850 million in further business. The light rail cars will be
built at the West Mifflin facility.<BR>
<BR>
It probably didn't look like much of a &quot;gift&quot; at first, but the
Urban Redevelopment Authority, the Pittsburgh Economic and Industrial Development
Corp. and a company named GalvTech were able to look beyond the surface.
And inside the former Hays Ammunition plant, all three groups found opportunity.<BR>
<BR>
The plant was idled in 1970 and was the subject of little activity until
1993, when the U.S. Army donated the facility on Mifflin Road in Pittsburgh
to the URA. The URA moved quickly, selling it to the Economic and Industrial
Development Corp., which is renovating the facility and will lease it to
GalvTech, this year's winner for Most Innovative. Previous winners include
Taylor Development Group, the former Joseph Horne Co. and Duquesne Light
Co.<BR>
<BR>
GalvTech is a manufacturer of hot dip galvanized steel for the construction,
appliance, heating ventilation and air conditioning, and service center
industries. After about a $37 million investment in renovations, equipment
and infrastructure improvements, GalvTech eventually will employ about 80
people at the site.<BR>
<BR>
GalvTech's sister company is MetalTech, which renovated an abandoned mill
in 1984 at a site adjacent to the Pittsburgh Technology Center. It now employs
about 90 people there. Another sister company is NexTech, located in Turtle
Creek, which employs about 60.<BR>
<BR>
Some call it Silicon Alley, the section of Oakland near Carnegie Mellon
University that has become a hotbed of technology-based companies. It's
here that you find four companies the Best Deals judges feel are primed
for growth:  GALT Technologies, Internet Securities, the EnviroLink Network
and OnTV. Previous winners in the  Best Prospects for Growth category include
FORE Systems, Medrad and Respironics.<BR>
<BR>
 GALT is best known for NETworth, its popular Internet site that provides
investors with current mutual fund information, including prospectuses and
performance figures. A weekly investors' market outlook and an interactive
question-and-answer forum with industry professionals are also available,
and NETworth gives registered users the ability to track their investments
through a personalized on-line portfolio manager. <BR>
<BR>
 GALT's story is interesting in that it already has been acquired by California-based
Intuit, perhaps best known as the developer of Quicken and TurboTax software.
 GALT's NETworth will enhance Intuit's Quicken Financial Network, an Internet-based
financial services forum. Intuit plans to increase GALT's operations in
Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
OnTV is a Pittsburgh-based company that produces sites for the World Wide
Web and provides Web presence to clients. What makes OnTV different is that
it is the world's first digital broadcaster of the World Wide Web.<BR>
<BR>
OnTV also is involved in custom software development aimed at making the
Internet more user-friendly. It developed MetroMap, which displays the location
of any street address, or the relative positions of up to three locations
in the Pittsburgh area. Other software, Webfetcher, allows users to download
web information on a schedule they choose. <BR>
<BR>
The future includes a strategic alliance with Transphone, a unique Internet
appliance that allows one-button access to the World Wide Web. The transphone
looks like a normal lap-top computer, but also includes an integrated telephone,
answering machine, fax, speaker phone and color monitor. OnTV will market
the devices in the U.S. and build and distribute servers used to support
the system.<BR>
<BR>
Internet Securities is an on-line information service that provides financial,
political and economic information on emerging markets. Through agreements
with a wide range of local and international sources - including newspapers,
news bureaus, government agencies, stock exchanges and analysts - Internet
Securities  provides comprehensive, up-to-date information on markets including
Poland, Russia, the Ukraine, the Czech republics, Hungary, the Baltic states
and China.<BR>
<BR>
The EnviroLink Network differs from the other three Silicon Alley winners
in that EnviroLink is a nonprofit organization. It provides 3.4 million
users worldwide rapid access to environmental information, experts, activists,
educators and environmentally conscious businesses. It also provides nonprofit
environmental organizations with on-line presence and Web development.<BR>
<BR>
The EnviroLink Network is probably the most powerful, useful and easy-to-navigate
source of environmental information. Anyone with a modest computer setup
can find any kind of environmental information with a few keystrokes or
clicks of a mouse.<BR>
<BR>
One is built, the other is well on its way.<BR>
<BR>
The judges selected the headquarters projects of Roadway Package System
and FORE Systems as winners for Best Real Estate Development. RPS and FORE
join previous winners Southpointe, Edgewood Towne Centre and Keystone Commons.<BR>
<BR>
Both facilities demonstrate each company's long-term commitment to the region.<BR>
The RPS headquarters facility, which opened last September, sits high atop
a hill on a 115-acre site in the Parkway West corridor. The 350,000- square-foot
facility includes three atriums, a 125-seat auditorium, a 300-seat cafeteria,
media studio, conference center and physical fitness center.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We feel,&quot; says RPS President Ivan T. Hofmann, &quot;that the
close proximity of our headquarters to the airport and the exceptional labor
pool available in this area have played and will continue to play a pivotal
role in our growth and profitability. RPS is committed to remaining in the
Pittsburgh area.&quot;<BR>
FORE broke ground last Halloween in Marshall Township for its three-building
headquarters, slated for initial occupancy this December.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The buildings will be like none that exist in the area,&quot; says
William Bates, director of facilities for FORE. &quot;We believe the unique
new headquarters will contribute to the growing visibility of FORE, while
improving recruitment and creating a sense of identity for employees.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
FORE is a repeat winner in Best Deals, having won last year for Fastest
Growing Company. <BR>
Price Waterhouse and Executive Report added a new category to Best Deals
this year: the Spirit of Pittsburgh Award. The category will honor groups
or individuals who have gone the extra mile for the economic good of the
region.<BR>
<BR>
The inaugural winner, the Working Together Consortium, is a broad-based
volunteer collaboration of civic leaders who have agreed to monitor and
review the implementation of the action recommendations in the 1994 report
entitled The Greater Pittsburgh Region: Working Together to Compete Globally.<BR>
<BR>
The consortium's genesis dates back to 1993, when the Allegheny Conference
on Community Develop-ment commissioned an analysis of the region's competitiveness
by a committee headed by Carnegie Mellon University President Robert Mehrabian.
<BR>
<BR>
The resulting findings touched on both the region's strengths and weaknesses
and led to the first community-wide strategic planning process for western
Pennsylvania, known as the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative.<BR>
<BR>
RERI recommended establishment of the Working Together Consortium itself,
along with implementation of the following regional strategies the consortium
oversees:
<UL>
  <LI>	Build on the strengths that hold the key to future job growth;
  <LI>	Invest in wealth- and 
  <LI>	job-creation assets;
  <LI>	Revive our entrepreneurial vitality;
  <LI>	Make greater Pittsburgh a leading destination for world visitors;
  <LI>	Create an economic climate for the 	21st century;
  <LI>	Establish a new spirit of teamwork in economic development;
  <LI>	Connect workers and students to the jobs of the future; and,
  <LI>	Build one economy
</UL>
<BR>
&quot;In benchmarking other regions, one fact becomes clear: In successful
regions, everyone understands  the region's goals, and everyone works together
to make those goals happen,&quot; says Allegheny Ludlum Chairman Richard
P. Simmons, who also is chair of the Working Together Consortium.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If our region is to be successful, we have to adopt an attitude of
cooperation among ourselves, a can-do attitude,&quot; Simmons says.  <BR>
