<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0796.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement5.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>This is Where It's Happening</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size =+1></FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>They say the heaviest traffic is on Sunday mornings, when people
venture from their homes to go to church or buy a newspaper. The cars might
be lined up four or five deep at a stoplight - a downright inconvenience
by local standards.<BR>
<BR>
So you know that typical 10-minute trip down Route 30? Well, you better
allot yourself an extra minute or two to get through that congestion at
the stoplight near Westmoreland Mall<BR>
<BR>
Welcome to Westmoreland County: small towns, country setting, relaxed atmosphere,
low crime rate, but a big-league player when it comes to economic development
in western Pennsylvania. That's right. Amid the forests and rolling fields
- which cover about 70 percent of Westmoreland County - are businesses large
and small that have created more than 2,500 jobs in the past two years<BR>
&quot;This,&quot; says long-time County Commissioner Terry Marolt, &quot;is
where it's happening.&quot;<BR>
Indeed, it is. Here's a sampling:
<UL>
  <LI>	Kennametal, the Latrobe-based manufacturer of industrial tools and
tooling systems, is moving its North American metalworking operations from
Raleigh, N.C., to Westmoreland County, including about 300 jobs.
  <LI>	Sony continues expansion of its Technology Center in East Huntingdon
Township. It already employs about 1,200 people, with another 500 to start
next year when the American Video Glass Co. plant comes on-line across the
street from the existing Sony facility.
  <LI>	Robicon, a maker of power conversion equipment, stayed in the region
last year after outgrowing its 30-year site in Plum Borough, Allegheny County.
The company moved its operations and 400 jobs across the county line to
a new $7.7 million facility near the Alcoa Technical Center in Upper Burrell
Township.
</UL>
<BR>
And those are only the big hitters. While Westmoreland County has shown
a knack to lure those bigger employers, it also is convincing its smaller
but growing firms to sit tight instead of looking elsewhere. These companies
add five jobs here, 10 jobs there - they add up after a while.<BR>
<BR>
 Meanwhile, the existing jobs of these growth companies - an estimated 2,500
positions - have been secured by keeping the companies at home.  <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've attracted new companies,&quot; says Larry Larese, the county
planning director, &quot;but we've also been able to keep the ones who were
already here and are expanding. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Keeping the existing companies,&quot; Larese says, &quot;is just as
important when you talk about economic growth.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
What's Westmoreland's secret? A combination of things, according to planning
officials and the business people who deal with them. Collectively, they
provide insight into the county's fast-paced economic growth.<BR>
<B><BR>
The Pitch<BR>
</B><BR>
It starts with the bait, then comes the hook. The bait brings prospective
businesses in for a look, and here's a sampling of what they hear:<BR>
<BR>
Westmoreland economic development managers are quick to note the county's
proximity to Pittsburgh, but in the same breath will quietly point out what
differentiates Westmoreland County from greater Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
Take the cost of electricity. West Penn Power, which services Westmore-land
and all or parts of 22 other counties, boasts an industrial utility rate
of 4.54 cents per kilowatt hour, below both the national average of 4.96
cents and Duquesne Light's rate of 5.94 cents. The figures are based on
data about 200 utilities report to the Edison Electric Institute, a Washington,
D.C.-based association of shareholder-owned electric companies.<BR>
<BR>
Sony has cited the low power costs as one of several reasons it located
in Westmoreland County. In Robicon's case, electricity rates played a role,
too. Robicon's new plant uses about 20 percent more electricity than the
old facility in Plum Borough, yet its costs are unchanged since it now is
serviced by less expensive West Penn.<BR>
<BR>
West Penn credits its low cost to a decision the utility made over two decades
ago. When other electric utilities were investing in nuclear power, West
Penn remained loyal to coal and to this day still fires its power generation
plants with coal.<BR>
<BR>
Another piece of bait: the small town atmosphere only a 45-minute ride from
the big city. Of the 10 Pennsylvania counties with populations in excess
of 300,000, Westmore-land - with a population of about 390,000 - has the
lowest rate of crime, according to FBI statistics. The crime index of 1,593
incidents per 100,000 inhabitants is less than half of Alle-gheny County's
rate of 3,582 incidents.<BR>
Prospects like the low energy costs and high quality of life, so they visit
Westmoreland for a closer look. Now comes the hook: Westmoreland's ability
to sweep prospects off their feet by presenting a complete package: land,
facility, infrastructure, permits and financing, all on a silver platter.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They buy the land, put the utilities in place, lay out the parcels
and sell them at really good prices,&quot; Robert Bryan, a real estate consultant
in Westmoreland County, says of the county's development team. &quot;They
put the financing in place. They go to someone, they really have a package
for them. You can build a building and set up shop pretty quickly.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Strategically, they've done a really good job,&quot; Bryan says. &quot;It's
been a good effort. I can't personally say enough.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The county's development arm - the Westmoreland County Industrial Development
Corp. - even ventured into the railroad business by purchasing and rehabilitating
rail lines previously owned by Conrail, PennDot and CSX. Prospective businesses
see the rail system - consisting of about 38 miles of track - as a plus
because of its use in receiving parts and shipping a finished product. It
was a key in landing the American Video Glass plant at the Sony Technology
Center.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;I like to think we are one of the leaders as far as providing available
sites that are ready for prospects,&quot; says Joseph Sisley, marketing
director for the WCIDC. &quot;We do the infrastructure, permitting and utilities.
The wetlands issues and archeological studies have all been taken care of.
<BR>
&quot;We also have a very good working relationship with various agencies
that put financial packages together. Often times, when we meet with prospects,
we pull in all these key people to not only answer questions on available
sites, but also financing available for the project.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Advanced Manufacturing Tech-nologies, for instance, worked with the county's
development team in securing a $263,380 state loan so it could build a 11,520-square-foot
building at the Westmoreland Industrial Park III in Penn Township, one of
seven county-run industrial parks. Advanced Manu-facturing, an expanding
company, manufactures electronic assemblies such as cables for televisions
and employs 25.<BR>
<BR>
At the same park, vinyl graphics manufacturer Endagraph Inc. used a $312,888
state loan to finance its expansion. The company employs 25, but hopes to
add another 40.<BR>
<BR>
All seven Westmoreland County industrial parks consist exclusively of greenfield
sites, meaning there is no environmental remediation necessary. At presstime,
three of the parks were full, including the previously mentioned Penn Township
park, whose last parcel was optioned to developer A. Richard Kacin and will
likely be occupied by a security firm. The park is home to 19 businesses
involved in manufacturing and distribution.<BR>
<BR>
Many of the smaller companies take more land than they initially need, allowing
them to easily expand as growth occurs. It also prevents them from looking
for another location.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Bigger Fish<BR>
</B><BR>
Sony has been everything Westmoreland hoped for and more. The electronics
giant and its partner, Corning Asahi Video Products, swallowed several million
dollars in Clean Air Act costs when they decided to build the glass plant
at the Technology Center (For more on the Sony glass venture, see the Best
Deals winners on page 46). In addition to the glass plant, the Sony Technology
Center also has spawned Sony Chemical Co., which manufactures thermal transfer
tape coatings and employs about 100 in nearby Hempfield Township.<BR>
<BR>
Fred Ishii, vice president of American Video Glass, confidently shrugged
off the Clean Air Act costs when questioned about them at a groundbreaking
for the glass plant last fall. The utility costs were low, Ishii says, and
there were other positives that outweighed any negatives.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We liked this location because of the skilled work force available
and the infrastructure,&quot; he says.<BR>
<BR>
The Sony Technology Center is about a five-minute ride from the junction
of the Pennsylvania Turnpike and Interstate 70 in New Stanton. Parts manufactured
in Southeast Asia are flown into Columbus, Ohio, and trucked to Sony. While
that's an indictment of Pittsburgh International Airport's freight-handling
capabilities, it's also an endorsement of the infrastructure Sony touts
at the Westmoreland site.<BR>
<BR>
Kennametal's activity is about 15 miles to the east of Sony, near Latrobe.
The company is spending about $20 million on construction of a new corporate
headquarters building and improvements on two existing structures along
Route 981. Once complete, Kennametal's three-building headquarters complex
will total approximately 380,000 square feet of space, house approximately
700 employees and allow the company to become more efficient and competitive.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;For Kennametal, this is a wise decision,&quot; says CEO Robert McGeehan.
&quot;We always have been headquartered in Latrobe. We have deep roots in
western Pennsylvania, but today we are a different company and are competing
in a different world. This consolidation will make us even stronger and
better than we are today.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Residential Growth<BR>
</B><BR>
With economic growth comes population growth. At the next census, Westmoreland
County planners expect the county's population to exceed 400,000, and many
of the big growth areas are communities with close proximity to Allegheny
County, such as Murrysville, Penn Township and North Huntingdon. One indicator
of the growth: Voter registration for the most recent primary election showed
jumps of several thousand in all three areas since the previous presidential
primary in 1992, county officials say.<BR>
<BR>
Many newcomers to western Westmoreland work in Pittsburgh and make the daily
commute on the Parkway East.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Lower property taxes are really a big incentive, plus utilities are
generally lower when you compare Westmore-land to Allegheny,&quot; says
Terry Ruta, a Coldwell Banker agent based in Murrysville. &quot;A lot of
people also like the small town atmosphere.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Deerfield Estates in Penn Township, with homes starting at $170,000, is
now in Phase III of construction, according to Ruta.<BR>
<BR>
Homebuilding also continues further east in the heart of Westmoreland. In
Youngwood, for example, Millstein Industries Inc. is entering Phase II of
its Cherry Creek development near Westmoreland County Community College.
Homes starting at $170,000 surround a 4,500-yard, 18-hole golf course. In
addition to 162 single-family units, the development will also include 138
multifamily units.<BR>
<BR>
n Hempfield Township, Logan Dickerson, father of Executive Report publisher
Linda A. Dickerson, is subdividing and developing 304 acres at the Lindwood
Farm. Phase I includes 22 homes starting at $285,000. Eventually, the development
will include 205 upscale single-family homes, plus 60 upscale condominiums.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's about 13 to 15 minutes from Murrysville, and the setting is upscale
rural,&quot; says Bryan, who consulted on the Lindwood project. &quot;The
attempt there was to make a statement to the people who live in Westmoreland
now and are ready to move up.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It's also an attempt to get people who work in Pittsburgh and are
willing to go as far as Murrysville. Maybe we can get them to come another
15    minutes,&quot; says Bryan.<BR>
<BR>
Not far away, Samaritan Health-Care Inc., a subsidiary of Lutheran Affiliated
Services, is building a retirement community that initially will feature
104 senior condominiums and a 98-unit assisted living facility. The community,
known as Crown Point, is one of four Samaritan is building in western Pennsylvania,
with the others in Cran-berry Township, Sewickley and the South Hills of
Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
Eventually, the Samaritan site will include a 120-bed skilled nursing facility
for acute care and Alzheimer's care.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When it's all said and done, we expect to have about 400 folks living
on our campus,&quot; says Samaritan President William Pratt. &quot;Westmoreland
County is a strategic location in our master plan.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Future<BR>
</B><BR>
With growth comes growing pains, but Westmoreland is taking steps to limit
those. It already has in place the Amos K. Hutchison Bypass, a tollroad
linking New Stanton to Delmont. And commissioners continue to lobby for
construction of the Laurel Valley Expressway, a limited access highway that
would link New Stanton to Latrobe.<BR>
<BR>
In May, the county also floated bonds to finance expansion of the county
airport in Latrobe, not far from Kennametal's campus. Airport Manager Gene
Lakin says the $4.75 million project will double the public areas of the
airport terminal and likely attract another major carrier.<BR>
<BR>
Currently, USAir Express provides daily commuter service to Pittsburgh International
Airport, with eight roundtrip flights each weekday. Lakin says a new carrier
may establish direct commuter service to another hub or direct service to
another city, such as Philadelphia.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We see great potential with this,&quot; Lakin says. &quot;With the
space we have now, we really are limited to one commercial carrier in there.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This project really opens it up,&quot; Lakin says.<BR>
<BR>
Meanwhile, the aggressive recruitment of business continues, with many companies
listening intently.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The tax structure is more favorable, the utilities are less expensive.
And some of these properties the county develops - they are put on the market
at really competitive prices, sometimes half of what the private sector
would sell them for,&quot; says Jeffrey Ferris, a vice president for Kacin.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;These are the deciding factors for a lot of businesses.&quot;<BR>
