<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Supplement5.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>The First Step
</font><BR>
<font size=+1> Many are Embracing Proposed Changes,<br> and That's Good Sign for this Region 
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<P>
<hr>

We weren't proclaiming the death of Pittsburgh when we placed a tombstone on our January cover, but we were offering this hint: If this region doesn't get its act together, its residents  are facing a grim future.<P>Some readers chastised the magazine for kicking the region when it was down. Others told us we were courageous to package the message the way we did: on the face of a tombstone.<P>Our goal throughout the Resuscitating the Region series has been to point out in what areas our region is lacking, while identifying windows of opportunity through which we can help ourselves.<P>This month, we discuss the importance of highway infrastructure (see page 14), most notably how other regions have benefited from building a beltway and the feasibility of circling Pittsburgh with our own beltway.<P>As 1996 has progressed, other parties have offered their own opinions or recommendations on how this region can become - as a whole - more competitive. Executive Report Publisher Linda Dickerson toured southern cities during the month of January, interrogating 107 people from Greenville, S.C., to Jacksonville, Fla., about how their regions have gained an edge. You'll read her findings next month.<P>The Committee to Prepare Allegheny County for the 21st Century culminated a year of benchmarking with recommendations of far-reaching changes to the way Allegheny County government operates. Among the recommended changes was a call for consolidation of suburban municipalities.<P>The biggest surprise of this all? The response from the public, which seems to be embracing the recommended changes.<P>When Linda Dickerson invited 50 community and business leaders to hear her and Carnegie Mellon University economist Don Smith discuss her southern trip, 85 people showed up. That's right: 85 people.<P>As for the ComPAC 21 report? The Republican commissioners slowly have warmed up to the report, and the reception in the suburbs was better than expected.<P>Jim Turner, who coordinated the study and the compilation of its findings, says he feared suburban communities would protect their turf and resist the ComPAC 21 committee's call for suburban consolidation. Instead, Turner says the early response from suburban leaders has been, "How can we get moving on this?"<P>Let's hope it continues, because there indeed is reason to think this region can land on its feet. Milwaukee - a Rust Belt city against which the ComPAC 21 committee benchmarked Pittsburgh - sure has.<P>Since 1987, Milwaukee has edged steadily upward in job growth and remains among the nation's top 20. The unemployment rate, once more than 13 percent, was at just 3.5 percent by the early part of this decade. Yet the industrial heritagee remains in Milwaukee, a city whose skyline, beyond a smallish downtown area, is mostly smokestacks and church steeples.<P>Naysayers may claim we can't compare Pittsburgh to southern boomtowns because of the climate difference. As Turner says, that excuse doesn't work when comparing Pittsburgh to Milwaukee. Same climate. Same Rust Belt history. Milwaukee just has a different way of doing things.<P>I mentioned the suburban consolidation. Milwaukee leaders think they have too many municipalities in Milwaukee County. They have 19, to our 130. <P>Enough said.<P>Let's not fear change. Let's continue to embrace it.  We all will benefit in the long run.                                                <P>


<hr>

