<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><IMG border=0 align=left SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><BR>
<BR><FONT SIZE=+2>The Right Time<BR>Good Leaders - Like Robert Mehrabian -<BR>Know When it's Time to Move On 
</FONT SIZE>
<font size=+1></font><BR>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b>
<hr>


Late last year, in his office overlooking the construction site of the University Center, a hallmark of his presidency at Carnegie Mellon, Robert Mehrabian reflected on the characteristics of great leaders.  Accustomed as I am to receiving Robert's sagacious counsel, somehow I sensed that this conversation was different. First, his back was to me.<P>Robert is a captivating conversationalist who never fails to make eye contact. But his penetrating looks were directed at the campus, not at me, as he spoke on this early December day.<P>The words he uttered were deliberate.  "Linda," he said, "the job of a university president is tough." <P>He was silent. I was uncomfortable, sensing that this dialogue between friends was a departure from the many that preceded it.  After what felt like an interminable wait, Robert continued.<P>As if to prepare me for his decision to leave CMU, he began reciting a litany of the qualities unique to strong leaders. Tucked obscurely among the list he recounted was the leader's ability to recognize when to turn the reins over to another. An important dimension of leadership is, after all, planned succession. <P>Yet many good leaders miss the opportunity to become great leaders because they linger too long. To themselves and to many others, these  leaders become indispensable. But in today's world, sustained leadership can easily stifle organizations.<P>As we all know by now, Robert Mehrabian will not fall prey to this fate. <P>Who's to say how long is too long?  Only the great leader knows the answer to this question. And only a great leader has the conviction to leave at the pinnacle of his or her success. When no one else thinks a leader should resign is precisely the time that the most extraordinary depart. Leaving on an upswing affords a successor the       optimal opportunity to succeed. True leaders recognize that perpetuating    the organization's success supersedes amassing individual success.<P>If the time is right, the temptation to stay and enjoy the fruits of one's labor does not dissuade a true leader. This impeccable sense of timing seems to many almost an uncanny ability to see the future.<P>At a university where presidents' tenures regularly exceed a decade, Robert's imminent departure seems premature. But his announced resignation is nothing more and nothing less than a testament to his tremendous leadership capacity.<P>Some may view "leaving for personal reasons" as placing self before institution. In Robert Mehrabian's case, the opposite is true.<P>


<hr><BR><BR><BR>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

