<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>It's a Start
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>Current Brownfields Act Still Needs Work
</font><br>
<font size=+1>to Really Help the Economy</FONT><br>
 <i>By Laura Schleich Irwin
</b></i>

<HR>


Recent issues of this magazine have questioned the economic viability of the greater Pittsburgh region, and  painted a dreary outlook for western Pennsylvania. <P>A better view would be one that focuses on the positive aspects of this region and recent developments that  look forward, not back.<P>One example is the Land Recycling and Environmental Remediation Standards Act, known to many as Brownfields legislation. This law is not only a means to improving our region economically, but also shows that government and business can join forces to make the region a competitor for new businesses. <P>Enacted by Pennsylvania's legislature last summer under the strong guidance of Gov. Tom Ridge, the Brownfields legislation facilitates recycling abandoned industrial sites by linking site remediation to the risk connected with its intended use. In other words, the long-overdue act finally recognizes that former industrial sites intended to house another industrial operation do not require cleanup to the same extent that, say, a day care center would require. <P>Other provisions of the legislation provide lending institutions with protection from environmental claims for contaminated property in which they own a security interest. It also offers the new owners limited release from liability for historic contamination.<P>Abandoned sites, formerly home to businesses ranging from steel making to chemical manufacturing, are typically contaminated with materials considered harmful to human health, such as metals and coal derivatives, that remain in the soil and often the groundwater for years. Traditionally, state and federal environmental agencies imposed onerous cleanup standards for these sites, often requiring cleanup  to "background" levels.<P>For you and me, "background" level means we could picnic on the site without fear of contaminating our lunch. To property owners, however, achieving this standard meant no economic gain reselling these sites. Abandoning them became common, and in some instances the only wise and viable option for businesses.<P>Logically, prospective buyers and developers weren't interested in these  contaminated sites. As we can see up and down the three rivers of Pittsburgh and elsewhere, redevelopment of these sites rarely occurred. Instead, companies looked to pristine properties for industrial development. Urban blight, a declining tax base and a sense of doom for our region - once an economic powerhouse - followed.<P>Advocates and critics alike point out shortcomings of the Brownfields legislation. Chief among these are that that the legislation does not provide prospective developers with three crucial commodities: time, money or a full release from liability for historic contamination. These points are well taken and require attention from legislators.<P>Although the act includes a limited release from liability for historical contamination, the release provision may not insulate an owner from actions by third parties or by all enforcement agencies. For prospective buyers and sellers to be comfortable signing on the dotted line, state lawmakers must revisit this provision.<P>Time is also a significant concern for prospective buyers. The current act does not alter the administrative details of seeking and obtaining approval to investigate and remediate an abandoned site. This process, which can be tedious, costly and sometimes frustrating, must be amended to provide priority treatment by state agencies.<P>Likewise, money is an ever-present consideration. This Brownfields act provides no financial incentive to tip the balance in favor of an abandoned site. At a minimum, abandoned sites will require an initial capital outlay to conduct an investigation and cleanup of the site and negotiate releases from historical contamination. To bridge the gap, an investment tax credit, tax abatement plan or other financial incentives should be considered by the legislature.<P>In short, lawmakers must remember that the developer's choice often is between a virgin site and an abandoned site. Given the excellent location of many Brownfields sites, legislative action to rein in these negative aspects of the Brownfields legislation can tip the balance in favor of abandoned sites.<P>Pennsylvania has emerged as a leader in the move to redevelop abandoned industrial sites. While the Brownfields legislation is not a panacea for our region's complex economic and social problems, it is a start. Indeed, it demonstrates that things are looking up in western Pennsylvania.  n<P>Laura Schleich Irwin is an associate with the law firm Babst Calland Clements and Zomnir in Pittsburgh.<P><P>

<hr>


<P>


