<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>
</i></b>

<HR>

<H2>Giving Business What it Wants</h2>Carla Brownell draws a simple pear in 3-D, rotates it and does a drive-by, which makes you feel like you're in a plane flying low over it. Then, with a click of the mouse hooked to the Silicon Graphic workstation, she shades it blue. Brownell used to be an art student, used to be a computer programmer. Now, she's both, as the graduate assistant to John Shepherd, head of Duquesne University's new multi-media master's program.<P>"USA Today ranked computer animation as one of the top jobs for the year 2000," says Shepherd, looking over Brownell's shoulder, delighted with the computer program. "Computer animators starting out make $60,000."<P>It just so happened that Duquesne President John E. Murray Jr. heard that multi-media - the use of interactive audio, video and computerized graphic techniques - was the way of the future. He asked John Shepherd, a professor in the school of health sciences, known among his colleagues for his multi-media enthusiasm, to investigate starting such a program. <P>Shepherd looked to the business community.<P>"I called the people I knew doing this stuff in Pittsburgh, and asked them who else did it," says Shepherd. He ended up with an advisory board, which he uses to shape curriculum and, because the field is so new, to actually teach. He's also hoping they'll be a boon to graduating students.<P>The program, now a master's, is shaping a certificate program at the encouragement of Mellon Bank, which sent six of its training designers over to take classes this semester.<P>"Students have to shoot and edit video, shoot 35mm, record audio - they learn all the basics, then integrate them by designing a home page on the World Wide Web," says Shepherd, showing off a student's design for the local Warner Bros. cable channel. <P><P>Others have done home pages for the Steelers and the Tribune-Review.<P>But the real draw are classes like the one Brownell's demonstrating: Computer Animation 101. <P>"It was a big decision to buy these really expensive Silicon Valley workstations, which are the computers they used to dothe animation for 'Jurassic Park'," says Shepherd. "Because they gave us such a huge break, we could buy two, and the <P>software." <P>The classes are double the enrollment he expected, and Shepherd says he needs a third, and possibly even a fourth workstation. <P>Shepherd hopes to train not only artists, but technicians, to make the programs run, and authors, to design programs for training and education. He's even incorporating an elective in computer game design. And he's planning for the future.<P>"Seems like one of the emerging areas is virtual reality, creating 3-D animation for use on the Internet," says Shepherd. It's already made the short list of tentative electives.                       <P>- Lydia Strohl<H2>Corporate Shootout at Diamond Run</H2><P>Executive Report, Coldwell Banker and Diamond Run Golf Club are teaming up to host the first annual         Corporate Team Shootout golf        tournament July 1 at Diamond Run's Gary Player signature course in the North Hills.<P>Thirty teams from businesses in southwestern Pennsylvania will square off in a shotgun-start, best ball tournament followed by a sudden-death shootout among the top finishing teams to determine the champion.<P>"We've always covered golf, because it was and remains a critical part of doing business," Executive <P>Report Editor-in-Chief Jim Urban says. "We are glad to hold an event like this at Diamond Run, one of westernPennsylvania's most challenging golf courses."<P>The event is open to four-person teams comprised of players with <P>current USGA handicaps who are <P>affiliated with the company they are representing. <P>Look for further details about the Corporate Shootout in next month's issue of Executive Report. <H2>Is the Pittsburgh Marathon<br>Running Out of Steam?</H2>Like the spring weather, the Pittsburgh Marathon has been buffeted by the winds of change since its inception in 1985. Some of the changes have been pretty stormy, including the takeover of the marathon by the city in 1991 and drops in attendance since then.<P>This year, a kinder breeze may blow on the event; Larry Kuzmanko, founder of the race, has been asked back on the planning board, presumably to work the same magic that brought the marathon to its summit as an Olympic Trial event in 1988.<P>Runner's World called it the best first-year marathon in the country. The first year attracted 2,510 runners, followed by 3,000 the second year, 1987. <P>"There was a time when what we did here actually influenced Boston," remembers Kuzmanko. "We had Ray Flynn, the mayor of Boston, come here and run one year, and the next year, Boston put forth prize money. We were able to show this city off in terms of our people, the neighborhoods, the creativity, in a light that was comparable to Boston, New York, and I think that that's one of the reasons why the marathon is good."<P>Part of his magic was his ability to recruit people like Allan Steinfeld, director of the New York City Marathon, one of the premier running events in the world. Kuzmanko coaxed Steinfeld into playing the role of technical coordinator during the early years here, and the expertise Steinfeld lent the Pittsburgh Marathon played a great role in the event's success in the 1980s. <P>"Larry knew how to take care of people," says Steinfeld. "You have to make the top athletes feel like they're being catered to." That "caring touch" was part of what fell apart when Kuzmanko left. Many sponsors left with Kuzmanko.<P>The city, by most accounts, simply never got along with Kuzmanko's flamboyant style and outspoken character. From long, flowing hair and jeans with suit jackets to tactics like giving kegs of beer to pubs to recruit crowds along the routes - none of that sat well with the powers that were.<P>"From the get-go with the marathon, it wasn't just the last year, I had difficulties with the bureaucracy. And I just don't think that we shared the same vision," says Kuzmanko. "When Mayor Caliguiri died, it was very difficult because, in effect, I lost the person who could share a vision." <P>The Masloff administration decided it would run the event, and pushed Kuzmanko out. "My dilemma was, do I just continue to butt heads with the city and make it impossible to have an event, or do I let it go, and the event survives. Although it didn't continue to flourish the way it did, it still continued, and that's important, because no one likes to see something that they start ruined."<P>Whether the Marathon was "ruined" or not depends on who you talk to. It is the case that before 1991 Pittsburgh attracted some of the top runners in the world; now, it does not. The top attendance in 1990 was 4,385; last year, that number was 2,700.<P>"It's nice to have a director like Larry who's fair and takes care of the athletes. That was the reason I enjoyed it," says elite runner Maureen Custy-Roben. "I was going to come back in 1992, but the guy who was [athlete coordinator] at that point promised things and then went back on them. Then no one else went, either."<P>    Today, she says, the Pittsburgh Marathon doesn't have the prestige is once held among the sport's elite athletes. <P>     "There's a working chemistry [at a successful event] that nobody wants to upset, or you can lose it all," adds Steinfeld. "I think that's what happened in Pittsburgh's case. The political people who got involved brought it down."<P>  This year, University of Pittsburgh Medical Center gurus Dr. Freddie Fu and Larry Grollman, himself a former disciple of Kuzmanko, head up the marathon board in yet another changing of the board. Kuzmanko says that formula is promising. This year's organizers hope to attract 5,000 runners to the May 5 event.<P>The race will be held entirely downtown, <P>which some feel slights the neighborhoods that made the race in years past. The board hopes to attract more people by making it easier to see both the start and finish. Also featured will be a relay race, allowing groups to run the marathon in shifts. <P>Steinfeld thinks it may be possible for the Pittsburgh Marathon to regain its former glory if it is properly promoted. He says the sponsors should campaign to get the backing of the local running community. He says that it's good Kuzmanko is back on the board.<P>Kuzmanko's take on the matter?<P>"I'd take a polygraph on Grant Street that the city was 100 percent wrong with the way they handled things, but the issue is not one of the past, the issue is one of the future - that the event continues to enhance Pittsburgh, that the event is still good for Pittsburgh.<P>"If you care about something, you want to see it succeed and continue to do good things. The problem is, how much bureaucracy and how much government can I take? There are some people who can drink it in glasses - I have to take it in little teaspoonfuls. Whether I'm the problem or they're the problem, I don't know. Let's say it's me."                              n<P>- Cynthia Bent<P>



