<HEAD>
<TITLE> EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Abandon Ship?</b> 
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Riverboat Gambling Legislation<BR>Is Taking on Water in Harrisburg                

</font><BR>
<i>By Jim Strader
</i>

<HR>

<P>
Early last year, supporters of riverboat gambling felt their ship had come in. Gov. Robert P. Casey, a longtime opponent of the idea of casinos floating on Pennsylvania waterways, had left office and had been replaced by Tom Ridge. The new Republican governor was not an avid advocate of riverboat gambling, but, with his business-friendly attitude, had given signs during the campaign that he would not stand in the way.<P>Developers responded to the potential change by buying up riverfront tracts along the Monongahela, Allegheny and Ohio rivers in Pittsburgh, as well as property in Philadelphia and Harrisburg. Prices for land along the riverbanks shot up.<P>But now, more than a year after Ridge took office, hopes for riverboat gambling seem to be dead in the water, at least for now.<P>The supporters of legalized riverboat gambling pointed to a potentially huge windfall for the state and host communities. Detractors warned of criminal influences and other woes often associated with gambling. Those concerns were countered with proposals - backed by Mayor Tom Murphy in Pittsburgh and Mayor Ed Rendell in Philadelphia - that the casino developments would have to anchor larger improvements along the rivers.   <P>The first sign of rough sailing for gambling proponents came when <P>Ridge stated flat out that he favored a statewide referendum before riverboat gambling would be legalized.  The  governor said <P>he would veto any bill that passed without such a provision. <P>Legislation sponsored by Rep. Frank Gigliotti, a Democrat from Brookline, was introduced in the House of Representatives last year. It didn't reach the House floor for a vote before lawmakers broke for the summer, and was slow to get back into play in the fall. Though the proposal never got to the point where a vote was called, it seemed that the bill might have played a part in Ridge's effort to get education reforms passed.<P>The governor was having trouble amassing enough votes for his education package - rooted in a tuition voucher plan - and the word heard around the Capitol was that Ridge was trying to enlist the support of those eager for riverboat gambling. Both initiatives fell short by year's end.<P>Parliamentary politics played a big part in keeping the idea from gaining much steam. Republican leaders in the House - like Ridge, having other priorities - sent the riverboat gambling proposals to a committee chaired by Rep. Paul Clymer, a gambling foe from Bucks County who ensured the demise of the bills. He was content to take minimal action.<P>Clymer did hold two days of hearings on riverboat gambling in Philadelphia, with a field trip of sorts to Atlantic City to see casino operations there. Clymer indicated that his goal was to air the issue publicly, taking in all points of view. But he never wavered from his point of view, leaving no hope that any of the proposals would make it through his committee.  They haven't. Gigliotti thinks the hearings were a farce, and refused to testify or take part.<P>Early this year, other issues dominated the attention of the governor and lawmakers. Snowstorms and flooding hit much of the state in January. The annual budget process began in February, focusing the work of the legislators and the Ridge administration on spending priorities for the coming fiscal year. As for riverboat gambling? It remained low on the priority list. <P>The governor renewed his position that the state's votersshould ultimately decide the issue, but did not push to get the gambling question on the November ballot, when the presidential election is likely to draw a large turnout. Ridge indicated that legislators seemed to have had their own referendum on the matter by not bringing the bills to a vote.<P>Meanwhile, some developers in western Pennsylvania gave up waiting for their lucky number to hit in Harrisburg. Parcels of riverfront land once staked out for access to floating casinos are being turned to other uses.<P>"The land was just sitting there and it was prime land," says Wade Fox, data services manager of the Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Planning Commission. "They wanted to get something out of it and decided it's best to move on."<P>




<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

