<a href="../zine/0496.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>No Love Lost
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>A Bust at Fist Bite, Valentino<BR>Antes Up for Lunch
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<p>

<hr>
Many restaurants have come to the third floor of Walnut Street's Hartwell Building - and gone just as quickly. The newest is Valentino, which opened there in January.<P>Fashioned as an Italian bistro, the restaurant, faux-painted to resemble a courtyard, is trendy and relaxing. As you come up the stairs, an array of beautifully laid out dishes greets you. <P>Unfortunately, Valentino is as inconsistent as the human heart.<P>Though the menu looks creative, on closer examination it is astonishingly devoid of details. On our first visit, our waitress knew nothing. She did offer her opinion, when we asked - but we should have known her tastes differed from ours when she indicated pleasure with the sun-dried tomato pate, which she brought, along with a white bean pate, to accompany a small crusty loaf of bread. The bread was unremarkable and the pates bland - the tomato tasted like tomato paste direct from the can.<P>We bit when she recommended an appetizer of grilled shrimp on the half shell, with marinated peppers and artichokes. But they were grilled to a crisp. By the time we pried off the skins, there was precious little left. <P>We also tried the angel hair frittata with seafood, a house specialty. It was a big, dry omelette, with the angel hair pasta and other ingredients in the middle. The menu touted shrimp, crabmeat, peppers, scallions and shittake mushrooms in the middle, but there was little of anything. Perhaps, we thought, we just don't like breakfast before dinner. We ordered a glass of wine from the wine list, which is nice (but go for the bottle, because the glasses are small and pricey). And we waited for the entrees.<P>Again, in vain. The Pappardelle pesto chicken pasta sounded wonderful - but because I don't like heavy cream sauces, I asked how much cream was in the pesto cream sauce. Our waitress said not much. She lied. It was laden with cream. The doughy overdone squares of pasta (since changed to a different noodle, according to executive chef George Harris III) all stuck together, taking on the shape of the plate. The grilled chicken was good.  <P>What we had been waiting for were the crab cakes served with asparagus in a red pepper sauce. They looked beautiful, but they were also laden with egg, perhaps for frying, which had been done incompletely.  <P>We didn't eat much. So naturally, we eyed the dessert tray ravenously - and decided to splurge on a chocolate decadent called chocolate windmill. It was wonderfully rich, creamy and smooth. The cappuccino was frothy, though the espresso might have been filtered with dishwater. <P>Lunch, a week later, was better. The ribolita soup, which a different, more knowledgeable waitress described as minestrone in nature, was thin but passable.<P>We ordered sandwiches this round, which are not on the dinner menu. The chicken pesto sandwich involved no cream; the grilled chicken was topped with herby pesto, asparagus, portabella mushrooms and asiago cheese. The grilled portabella sandwich featured plump stripsof portabella, marinated and grilled, topped with wide planks of roasted red peppers and asiago cheese. In each dish, the assemblage of tastes melded together perfectly. Both were served on wonderful, chewy and crusty in all the right places Chibata bread. The sandwiches were accompanied by homemade chili pepper penne, mixed with regular penne in a light vinaigrette, al dente, but tasty and unique.<P>Again, the food was beautifully presented. A jug of water, topped with a whole lemon, is a nice touch. But the menu and the consistency need some work. Chef Harris, formerly of Diamond Run Golf Club, says he's made staff changes and increased his time there to try to evolve the young restaurant. But everything is a la carte; dinner for two with wine was $80. So try it for lunch first.<P>


<hr><P>


