<center>

<B><font size=+2>Location Vs. Savings</font><br><font size=+1>Does a Prime Location Justify the Added <br>Expense That Accompanies Being Downtown?<br>
</font></B><i>By Henry Lipput</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>
After paying steep rent in downtown Pittsburgh for five years, Frank Marmion moved his advertising agency to the Southside, purchasing the building in which he now conducts business.<P>What a difference, financially speaking.<P>"I only have seven employees, but I was picking up parking for five of them, so parking was costing me $1,000 a month, plus my rent," says Marmion, president of Marmion Advertising. "My [current] monthly outlay is the same as it would have been in town for rent plus parking.<P>"From a financial standpoint it just made a great deal of sense to me,"  says Marmion, one of many small business owners who have found it lucrative to locate outside the central business district.  <P>Marmion says he doesn't worry about his clients having to leave the city to come and see him. <P>"They don't come to me as much as I go to them," he says. "I didn't need to be in town, although I do need access to town. And that was another thing that appealed to me about the Southside.  A lot of my suppliers are in town, and a lot of the art houses and the production houses that I use are in town."<P>Al Thompson, a retired PPG executive and volunteer for the Service Corps of Retired Executives, says one of the most important things a small business must consider in choosing a location is its target market. <P>"You look at the area and whether it produces the demographics and other dimensions that [you] need to market your service or products," he says. "Then you start getting into specific site selections. And then you ask: Does the site provide the type of amenities and benefits that you're looking for? Adequate parking? Ease of access? Those sorts of things. You would probably want to - from a customer's standpoint - consider making it accessible to a major thruway."<P>Beyond the fringe markets like the Strip District, North Side and Southside, some suburban communities are marketing themselves as good business locations. Carnegie, for example, buys and resells buildings to businesses that locate there.<P>"We're the only small town between Pittsburgh and the airport on the Parkway," says Allen Turske, Executive Director of Chartiers Valley Area Community Development Inc.  "[Our charter is] basically to promote Carnegie and to develop Carnegie by various means, including purchasing properties so that we can offer them for development and give incentives, for example, on the the price of the land or the way it would be paid back. Also, to foster development through advertising or any other way that we can do it.  But our primary thrust is to get Carnegie redeveloped, if you will, renovated, renewed.   <P>"There are advantages to being here in Carnegie because of its location and also because of the prices of real estate," says Turske.  <P>Solutions 21, a training and organizational development company, is located in Carnegie. Buddy Holbart, the firm's President, loves the convenience.<P>"Carnegie is 15 to 20 minutes from the airport, [and that's important] because our business is national and international. In off-hour traffic, we're 15 minutes from downtown.  I couldn't beat the location from that standpoint." He had thought about establishing his company downtown, "but I live out west and the reality is Greentree Hill every morning.  And the base of my business isn't in town."  <P>Another reason for his selection, according to Holbart, was the availability of old homes that had been converted into office space. "Carnegie brought a whole different flavor, if you will, to my office," he says, "because I was able to put it in a building that has a great deal of character. So it's not an office environment, it's in an old Victorian home. Training participants who are coming here - when they take a break and walk out and have a cigarette or just to stretch their legs - they walk out onto a wrap-around porch and not into some lobby somewhere."<P>Holbart is not concerned about asking city-dwelling clients and their employees to visit him. "I have had absolutely zero problem getting people to schedule appointments in my office," he says. "There's certainly not a parking issue." <P>But consider if Holbart was located downtown.<P>"Say I'm doing a training class for your company and you're sending five  employees here, and I'm in downtown Pittsburgh. Each one of those five  employees is paying $10 to $12 a day to park," Holbart says. "So your business now has a $60 expense, because they'll expense that to your business. But sending them here avoids all that."<P>


<hr>

