<HEAD>
<TITLE> Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Sports.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Purchasing Problems</font><br><font size=+1>When the Purchase Order Conflicts<br>with the Sales Acknowledgement, Who Wins?<br>
</font></B><i>By Jim Urban</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>

When a carpet retailer started receiving complaints about the quality of rugs it was selling to the public, the retailer did some investigating and discovered the rugs shipped by one of its suppliers were made of low quality fiber.<P>Weeks later, Carpet Mart went to court, suing the supplier for $450,000 in compensatory and punitive damages. It looked like a simple breach of contract case - the rugs were not up to the quality the two parties had agreed upon - but in reality, the case was anything but simple.<P>The supplier pulled out the acknowledgment form it sent in response to the purchase order initially sent by Carpet Mart. On the back of the acknowledgment, in plain English, was a clause stating that any disputes between the supplier and its buyers would be settled in arbitration. In other words, Carpet Mart had waived its right to sue, and the supplier did not have to defend against the lawsuit.<P>The dispute would be settled in arbitration.<P>The case represents a common predicament for businesses large and small. When buying from another business, the standard practice is to cut a purchase order and send a copy to the supplier, who responds with the acknowledgment form confirming the order.<P>The reason such preprinted forms are used is simple: It's not efficient to negotiate, draft and sign a contract for each transaction between merchants.<P>But here's the problem with the preprinted forms: Buyers' purchase orders often include terms that expressly protect warranty rights or the right to sue - just as Carpet Mart wanted to do - when a dispute arises. The sellers, on the other hand, build in terms in their acknowledgment forms that severely limit warranties and damages or mandate arbitration.<P>So when these forms are exchanged - as is standard practice among American businesses - who wins when a dispute arises?<P>"I talk to purchasing managers from major corporations, and many of them don't know about this problem," says Duquesne University President John E. Murray Jr., a nationally recognized expert in contract law who also writes a monthly column for Purchasing magazine.<P>"These purchasing managers for major corporations leave me saying, 'This is one more thing I now have to worry about,'" Murray says.<P>In transactions between merchants, the buyer's purchase order often operates as an offer to which acceptance is expressly limited to its terms. So when the seller responds with an acknowledgment form with different terms, it operates as a counteroffer and no contract is formed under contract law.<P>"This is a common occurrence," Murray says. "The parties think they have entered into a contract, when in actuality they have not."<P>What complicates matters is that the seller then ships the goods to the buyer, who accepts them. So although no contract was formed, both parties have acted as though they are under contract. <P>The solution lies in the Uniform Commercial Code, which keeps the dickered terms the two parties agree upon - price, description and quantity for example - but excises the conflicting terms such as warranty or damages provisions. Those gaps are then filled in with UCC terms that in most cases favor the buyer.<P>For instance, the UCC's implied warranty of merchantibility covers goods for four years in most states, compared to most sellers' preprinted acknowledgment forms that limit the warranty to 90 days.<P>In Carpet Mart's case, it could proceed with the lawsuit against its supplier even though the supplier's acknowledgment form mandated that disputes be resolved via arbitration.<P>Lawyers refer to the purchasing predicament as the "Battle of the Forms."<P>There are other variations of the scenario, and the UCC addresses most of them in favor of the buyer. Revisions to the UCC are due in 1997, when Murray hopes resolving the battle of the forms will be simplified.<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

