<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Law.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>March Madness</font><br><font size=+1>The NCAA Tournament Comes Here Next Year and<br>Brings With it Plenty of Ouside Dollars<br>
</font></B><i>By Bill Modoono</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>

With little more than a third of 1996 passed, the biggest sporting event of the year in Pittsburgh has already taken place. Super Bowl XXX had the hype, the drama and the local TV ratings to make it a mega-event in western Pennsylvania and overcome its only real drawback: It was not actually held in western Pennsylvania.<P>But then Pittsburghers are used to having major events involving their local teams decided in locales far away. They have no problem accepting that. Here's something that might not go down so easily: The early leader in the race for Pittsburgh's top sports event of 1997 figures to be one with no - count them, none - local teams or athletes involved.<P>Two first-round games from the 1997 NCAA basketball tournament (aka "March Madness") are scheduled for the Civic Arena on March 14 and 16. The price is steep - $105 for three separate admissions to see six games, and you have to buy all three - but no one expects any of the 17,500 seats to go unsold.<P>This is precisely the kind of event that Pittsburgh almost never gets, despite its tendency to congratulate itself for being a great sports city. Apart from the once-a-decade appearance of the U.S. Open at Oakmont - an event that has more to do with the historical and competitive significance of the course than with western Pennsylvania's passion for golf - and the once-every-two-decades appearances of baseball and/or hockey all-star games, Pittsburgh is seemingly never viewed as a potential venue for events with national cachet.<P>But that was not the way Brian Colleary saw things. "The NCAA tournament is probably the top event in college athletics and I thought Pittsburgh was a great site for it," says Colleary, the athletic director at Duquesne who will serve as tournament director for the games at the Civic Arena. "It will put Pittsburgh and Duquesne in the public eye." <P>Colleary backed his belief in Pittsburgh by nominating the city two times unsuccessfully before finally winning NCAA approval on his third try.<P>Eight teams will play six games that weekend next March - four on Friday in a day/night doubleheader and two on Sunday. The winners advance to the regional finals and then to the Final Four, more prestigious events that the city could conceivably bid for in the near future.<P>What makes Pittsburgh such a strong site is not only a sizable arena and a vast number of hotel rooms in the area, but the number of hotels in close proximity to the site of the game. "The farthest any team will be from the Arena is eight miles," says Colleary.<P>Pittsburgh is such a good site it's a wonder it has never hosted this event before. According to local legend, the city's infamous 10 percent amusement tax was a deterrent, but Colleary says the tax (now at 5 percent) was "never a topic of conversation."<P>Joseph McGrath, president of the Greater Pittsburgh Convention and Visitors Bureau and a member of the board of directors of the Pittsburgh Sports and Festival Federation, says the amusement tax was never the "real reason" the NCAA did not come before, just one of several reasons. Among the factors he cites was a lack of interest from previous owners of the Penguins, previous managers of the Arena, and the athletic departments of Pitt and Duquesne. <P>"What you have now is a jelling of personalities and desires and agendas. All involved feel this will be beneficial to them," McGrath says.<P>McGrath likes to point out the economic advantages of events such as these that draw large numbers from outside the immediate area. While big events in general can add to a city's amorphous sense of "vitality," big events can bring concrete, short-term financial gain. Big-spending sports fans can spend as much as $200 a day for food and lodging and assorted souvenirs, McGrath estimates.<P>One other advantage is that an event like this, where upwards of two-thirds of those attending will likely be from out of the area, "can bring with it a significant amount of money," McGrath says. Big events that draw mostly locals compete with existing local attractions and do not add to the local economy. <P>"This is exactly the kind of event that creates tourism and adds vitality," says Louis B. Kushner, chairman of the Sports and Festival Federation, which was formed to attract events of this kind. "It's an excellent event for Pittsburgh."<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

