<HEAD>
<TITLE> HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Sports.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H15Health.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>Out of the Locker Room<br>
</font></I></B>

<b><font size =+1>Sports Medicine is No Longer<br>Just for the Athletes</b></font><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
</center><P>


<HR>
Last fall, Rose Ravasio had anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction just days before Steeler Rod Woodson did. But unlike Woodson, she was not hoping to play in the Super Bowl against Dallas. Her goal? To be able to walk a little bit, and someday to do low impact aerobics. <P>So did she need the assistance of Dr. Patrick DeMeo, director of sports medicine at Allegheny General Hospital? Absolutely, according to DeMeo.<P>"The goal of sports medicine is to keep people athletically viable whether they're 7 or 70, because we know that inactivity is deleterious to the quality and the length of life," says DeMeo. "That ligament wasn't going to kill her, but she couldn't do everything she wanted to."<P>Sports medicine brings cutting edge techniques, developed to get top athletes back to play, out of the locker room. It's not just for sports-related injuries anymore.<P>"Even if they're going to sit behind a desk the rest of their life," agrees Steelers' athletic trainer John Norwig. "Especially if they're a young person - they could end up with arthritis."<P>"Sports medicine is basically the practice of medicine in motion - looking at the whole human being and the demands and needs of individuals who are dynamic," says Dr. Doug McKeag, director of primary care sports medicine at UPMC. "Our diagnoses are enhanced because we see more sports-related injuries, and better understand biomechanics. The ancillary diagnostic tools we use are better, so we don't ill use resources. It eliminates the need to shot gun therapies, and we have an unbiased view because we're not surgeons."<P>Sports medicine practitioners also tout its comprehensive care; most clinics have consulting primary care physicians, orthopedic surgeons, physical therapists, athletic trainers, chiropractors and nutritionists.<P>In all of these arenas, what makes sports medicine different from traditional health care is the goal of the injured patient. Some clinics, such as St. Margaret's, define sports medicine patients as those who have been injured while engaged in athletic activity, or who have aspirations to return to a high level of activity. But others have a more lenient yardstick. <P>"We're a very active society," says Dr. Paul Michael Hoover of AGH's Back Institute. "We're not just passive observers, thus injuries become more significant. Traditional medicine is geared towards maintaining activities of everyday living. Sports medicine far surpasses that - to run or to throw or to make contact requires greater strength and agility, so our rehabilitation techniques have to go beyond."<P>"We have to be a lot more aggressive and a lot more creative," agrees John Duffy, district director of Health Trax Rehabilitation Services, overseeing nine regional clinics. "There's a lot more problem solving because the forces at work are much more dynamic and powerful. Why does a guy who runs 20 miles with no problem start to feel pain when he runs 22 miles? It's a lot easier to figure out why a guy who never ran, then ran five miles, hurts. We try to get to 100 percent strength and 100 percent range of motion - but we need to find out what the patient's goals are. If all they're going to do is walk around, clean house, if that's their 100 percent, then maybe they don't need to be paying for a session."<P>Sports medicine uses both traditional and innovative treatment protocols, personalizing the program to the patient. Take Woodson and Ravasio, both with ACL reconstruction. After surgery, Woodson's job was to heal: He devoted himself to recovery, working one-on-one with an athletic trainer two or three hours a day. Ravasio, who works in PR for Duquesne University, attended physical therapy three hours a week. Woodson had superior strength and agility to start with. Ravasio had a history of knee problems. <P>Different treatment for different goals? You saw it. In January, Woodson played in the Super Bowl. Ravasio still limps some days. <P>"The actual treatment varies minimally," says Greg Campbell, coordinator of sports medicine at St. Margaret's Hospital. "But when it comes time to functionally progress them, they may not have the time or the resources. If your HMO only pays for six visits, what can your goal be?"<P>Not everyone needs sports medicine - and for some its techniques may be damaging. So buyer beware - for along with the vagueness of the term, sports medicine also suffers from its popularity. "Sports medicine" has turned up in clinic names and ads with increasing regularity - but there are as yet no mechanisms in place to regulate their veracity.<P>"There is no specialty in sports medicine. Other specialties, like internal medicine, family practitioners, pediatrics, have a certificate of added qualification [in sports medicine], and there is an orthopedic fellowship in sports medicine," says UPMC's McKeag. "But it's not well regulated - many of these people who hang out shingles don't have these qualifications."<P>And that's bad news for consumers, because it doesn't stop practitioners from throwing the term sports medicine into an ad as a sexy way to sell physical therapy. The consequences can be dire.<P>"If you use bad sports medicine, as with any charlatan type of care, you can have greater dysfunction," says Hoover.<P>So far, say the experts, Pittsburgh's sports medicine market doesn't have a lot of imposters, but they do recommend checking qualifications and the actual activities of a clinic to assess its capabilities. Many local clinics have contracts with high school sports teams to provide training and rehab services. Local colleges and universities have clinics for their own teams which also service the public. Many hospitals are developing programs too.<P>Physical therapists may have a certificate in sports medicine, or be certified athletic trainers. <P>But in this fledgling field, title isn't always indicative.<P>"If someone spends four years here learning under me, they will definitely learn sports medicine," says AGH's DeMeo. "Knowledge passes boundaries, and it doesn't mean they're not in tune if they're not a sports medicine specialist.<P>"What we're doing in sports medicine today will benefit the general population tomorrow."<P>
<P>

<hr>

