<HEAD>
<TITLE> Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H17Education.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<center><b><font size =+2>
No Joking</font></B><br>
<B><I><font size=+1>A Law Degree Is a Marketable Asset Even If You<br>Don't Become a Lawyer
</font></I></B><br>
<i>By Paul Nutcher</i></center>

<HR>

<P>
When Carol Loncar decided on a graduate degree as a way to improve her future employment prospects, she decided on a law degree even though she didn't necessarily plan to become a lawyer.<P>"I felt it was one of the most skill-oriented types of degrees you could get.  It was a great professional choice," says Loncar, currently dean of admissions at Point Park College.<P>So while working as a school administrator during the day, Loncar also attended law school at Duquesne University in the evening. It was a grind: Classes were often five nights a week. At best, she'd have Friday evening free, and that was it.<P>Loncar made it through the four-year program and today credits the law degree with making her more marketable. In many cases, a law degree can lead to improvements in salary and job security, she says. There's also the added knowledge: The study of law includes topics like corporate structure, environmental issues, basic contract principles, the tax code, immigration and property law, all of which are applicable in today's global economy.<P>"On a whole, it's nice to know the law," Loncar says. <P>Both Duquesne and the University of Pittsburgh offer flexible law degree programs for working people. Pitt has a reduced credit-load daytime program; Duquesne's program is geared toward the evening student.<P>"I leave my residence at about 7:30 a.m. and return around 9:30 p.m.," says Luigi DiIanni, a U.S. Steel environmental engineer and second-year evening student at Duquesne. "It can be a long day, and it's tough because I have to perform on all cylinders while I am at work, then face the same expectations at school at night."<P>But, DiIanni adds in the same breath, without an evening program many would not be able to go to law school in the first place.<P>Pitt does not offer an evening program, but allows students in its flex program to reduce their credit load and take up to five years to finish, according to Fredi Miller, dean of admissions, adding that no one has ever taken longer than four years. The program has attracted physicians, business owners and parents who cannot leave their kids alone in the evenings but can squeeze in classes during the day.<P>"Students say, 'Had it not been for the flex program, they would not have been able to go through law school,' " Miller says.<P>In addition to time, the law school commitment is also financial, as much as $40,000 over the four years. Some companies, like U.S. Steel, will pick up all or part of the cost for their employees as part of their benefit package. Most students have to foot the bill themselves. And facing those loan payments motivates one to enter the field of law.<P>Those who do go on to practice can be very marketable provided that they held a position of substance as they attended law school. At Duquesne, many evening students are over the age of 30 and have life experience that may give them an edge while searching for jobs in the tight Pittsburgh market, according to Professor Ronald Ricci, dean of admissions at Duquesne's law school.<P>"They tend to have experience that helps them to gather contacts," Ricci says. <P>From the law firms' perspective, many seek individuals who have the poise to sit down with clients right away. Joe Vater, managing partner of the Pittsburgh law firm Meyer Unkovic & Scott, says that experience in the working world is a plus, but don't forget good grades.<P>"Someone who works 40 hours a week with high grades shows they are able to balance a lot of things well," Vater says.<P>Vater is often asked about what he looks for in a hire, but says he doesn't have a cookie cutter mold.<P>"If you were good in law school and doing 40 hours a week in an executive position, that person is going to get a serious look," Vater says. "I'm constantly impressed with people who can hold down a job, family and finish after four years with a law degree."<P>


<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

