<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>Reign Man</B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+>Bayer Corp. Chief Executive Helge Wehmeier is <br>Executive Report's CEO Communicator of the Year
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>


<P>
It was the first working day of 1994, and Helge Wehmeier was on his way to Minneapolis to schmooze a customer. Heavy snow closed Pittsburgh International Airport, so Wehmeier - the president and chief executive officer of what then was known as Miles Inc. - suddenly had some time on his hands and was wondering how he would spend it.<P>Then it came to him, maybe from the sight of employee cars lined up in the snowy parking lot. Wehmeier set off through the campus, walking department to department, desk to desk, pumping hands like a politician in an election year.<P>"I wanted to shake hands with all the people who struggled through the snow drifts to get to work and take the orders from our customers," Wehmeier says, looking back. <P>An isolated incident? Hardly. There he was again this past January, shaking many of the same hands in what has become an annual tradition for Wehmeier on the first working day of each year.<P>The main differences: the weather wasn't nearly as bad this year, and Miles now calls itself Bayer, the name to which it reacquired U.S. rights last spring.<P>Because of the importance Wehmeier places on employee communication, and  the effective way his corporation handled its name change from Miles to Bayer, Executive Report selected Wehmeier as its CEO Communicator of the Year.<P>The magazine annually honors a chief executive who not only personally excels in communication, but also pushes the company to display communications excellence. The award ispresented in conjunction with the Renaissance Awards sponsored by the Pittsburgh chapter of the Public Relations Society of America. Previous winners of the CEO award include Duquesne University President John E. Murray Jr., PNC Bank CEO Thomas O'Brien, DQE CEO Wesley W. von Schack and the late Blue Cross CEO Eugene Barone.<P>And while the list of the previous winners is impressive, few, if any, can say they've faced the type of communications challenge Wehmeier and the employees at Bayer faced one year ago this month.<P>The Name Change<P>The reason Miles changed its name to Bayer dates back to World War I. At the end of the war in 1918, the U.S. government confiscated the Bayer name and U.S. assets as enemy property, eventually auctioning off the name to Sterling Winthrop, which held the rights until late last year.<P>So for 76 years, Miles' parent firm Germany-based Bayer AG used the Bayer name everywhere else in the world except the U.S.<P>In January 1994, Sterling finally sold its over-the-counter medicine business - including the Bayer rights - to British pharmaceutical giant SmithKline Beecham, which turned around and sold the Sterling business to Miles for $1 billion two weeks later.<P>And on last April 3, 1995, Wehmeier and Bayer AG chairman Manfred Schneider flipped a six-foot high switch, illuminating the new Bayer sign that sits on the edge of Mount Washington in Pittsburgh.<P>Miles was forever gone.<P>"All of a sudden, all the Bayer entities that had been under wraps, so to speak, in North America, all came out in the open," Wehmeier says. "All was revealed about what really we are doing and what our plans were in the United States."<P>And it sure didn't hurt that the lesser-known Miles name was being replaced by one with which most Americans had grown up. Even though  Tylenol and other nonaspirin pain relievers had crept into medicine cabinets throughout North America, Bayer remained a name most people easily recognized.<P>"What we acquired with the name Bayer, was not a corporate name but a product name: Bayer aspirin," Wehmeier says. "Our challenge was to continue to strengthen the brand name Bayer, which will always be ourflagship brand, but also to strengthen the corporate name Bayer."<P>Bayer pulled out all the stops, heralding the name change in television, radio, print and direct-mail advertising a few weeks before Wehmeier and Schneider threw the switch on Mount Washington. A Chicago-based ad agency, Foote, Cone & Belding Communications, came up with a catchy slogan: "We cure more headaches than you think." <P>The ads employed the well-known Bayer cross, which shows the Bayer name spelled horizontally and vertically and appears on each aspirin tablet. <P>One print ad included the headline, "After all these years, we think it's time you called us by our first name." <P>As effective as the advertising was, Wehmeier says a big key to pulling off the change wasinternal communications. After all, this company is undergoing its second name change in a decade:  A few years earlier, Bayer AG replaced the name Mobay with Miles.<P>First Mobay? Then Miles? Now Bayer? Employees had to be wondering what was going on, right? Not so, says Wehmeier. The Bayer management team knew employees would have to buy into the change. Once they did, customers would follow.<P>"We did it in the right way," Wehmeier says. "We said, 'We cannot hope to convince our customers that this name change is good for our customers if we do not have our employees on board.' So the bulk of the communication was not on the customers, but was initially focused on the employees. We knew that only if we captured the hearts and minds of our employees would we be able toconvince our customers that this is the right thing to do.<P>"It was very well executed, in part because we already [changed names] once, but also because we focused it properly. Our employees saw this and appreciated that they were the target and focus of management. They did not learn things from the newspaper. They learned things directly from management."<P>The employees bought into it.<P>"To the great credit of our employees, they are pragmatists," Wehmeier says. "They have wonderful attitudes even though we asked a lot from them. We asked them to change their identity from Mobay to Miles, and then from Miles to Bayer. That's asking a lot.<P>"The upside was that we had practice. We had changed namesbefore and done it effectively. "<P><P>The Personal Side<P>Wehmeier knows a little bit about communicating. Born in Goettingen, Germany, in 1943, he joined Bayer AG in 1965 at the age of 22 and spent his early years with the company marketing products. During one stint in New York City from 1969 until 1974, Wehmeier was responsible for the marketing of synthetic fibers in the United States and Can-ada. He later managed the marketing division of the Fibers Division for Scandinavia and the British Isles from 1974 until 1978.<P> So perhaps em-ployees shouldn't have been surprised when the snowbound Wehmeier showed up at their desk in January 1994. Wehmeier knows how to communicate, whether it be in the workplaceor in public. And being a CEO has taught him how to work a crowd. It's part of the job he had to work at, Wehmeier says.<P>"It did not come naturally to me," Wehmeier says. "I had to get going on this ... I am not the type of person who walks around with an outstretched arm. But again, this comes with responsibility. I am the standard bearer for Bayer, so I have to reach out, especially coming into a community like Pittsburgh.<P>"I can't wait for them to come to me, especially because I am the new kid on the block."<P>A shining moment for Wehmeier occurred late last year. Holocaust survivor and Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel came to Pittsburgh to speak as part of the Three Rivers Lecture Series, of which Bayer was a sponsor.<P>The Wiesel speech almos





<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

