<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<center>
<B><font size=+2>Transportation
</font></B><br>
<b><font size=+1>A Beltway: Advocates Say Build it<br>
abd Businesses Will Come</font></b><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>
<hr>

<P>

Dan Campbell tries to lure business to the suburbs near Greater Pittsburgh International Airport. He says there's always interest, that is until the prospects take one look at a map.<P>Then, forget it.<P>"They like the skilled labor, but then they look at the lack of access and the inability to get people to the jobs," says Campbell, executive director of the 22 West Progress Group Inc. "These companies then discount Pittsburgh."<P>In other words, those jobs go elsewhere instead of coming here.<P>In Part IV of Executive Report's six-month series entitled Resuscitating the Region, ER looks at how transportation offers a window of opportunity to spur regional growth. In previous months, the magazine talked about the importance of entrepreneurship, exporting and education. In coming months, ER also will look at tax reform and tourism.<P>This month: transportation. Is a beltway the road to success?<P>Do We Compete?<P>When a consultant hired by the Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission compared the Pittsburgh region to 16 other metropolitan regions in the East, the findings were sobering.<P>Eleven of those regions were surrounded by beltways, and every single one realized both population and job growth from 1980 until 1990. Among them, Columbus, Ohio, and Baltimore saw employment jump 21 percent, while Indianapolis jumped 18 percent.<P>Five other metropolitan areas with "grid" highway systems all realized job growth even though three of them - Detroit, Cleveland and Buffalo - lost population over the decade. Grid systems consist of parallel series of interstate highways, allowing travelers to easily move to an alternate route if the highway they're traveling on is blocked.<P>Then there was Pittsburgh with its node highway system consisting of the Interstate 376 Parkway for east-west travelers and Interstates 79/279 for north-south travelers. Pittsburgh was the only of the 17 regions studied to lose both jobs and population. <P>"Where the interstate service is good, those places are growing like weeds," says Roger Carrier, the former district engineer for the Pennsylvania Department of Transportation who now is president of Triline Associates, a traffic engineering firm in McMurray.<P>"If we had the right roads here, this place would be in a frenzy [of economic development]," Carrier says.<P>But the region is not growing. And although a beltway sounds like a massive undertaking, it isn't that farfetched a proposition. One link already is in place, and another is on the Turnpike Commission's agenda.<P>The Clock<P>The easiest way to look at a beltway is to picture it as surrounding the face of a clock. And looking at Pittsburgh, one already sees roadway stretching from noon to 3 o'clock in the form of the Pennsylvania Turnpike from Exit 6 in Monroeville to Exit 3 at Cranberry.<P>Another section, covering 6 o'clock to 9 o'clock is the proposed Southern Beltway that would stretch from Route 60 near Pittsburgh International Airport and connect with the Mon-Fayette Expressway near Finleyville in Washington County.<P>Beltway advocates envision another 12-mile leg connecting Cranberry to Pittsburgh International Airport (9 o'clock to noon) and the other final section stretching from the Mon-Fayette Expressway east to the Pennsylvania Turnpike either in Irwin or Monroeville (3 o'clock to 6 o'clock). There is also talk about running the Mon-Fayette Expressway all the way into Pittsburgh.<P>At worst, it would be mucheasier to move around the region. At best, development would occur along the sections of the beltway, beefing up suburban tax bases and creating employment opportunities.<P>Consider what happened along the beltway that surrounds Washington, D.C.: A study by the Metropolitan Washington Council of Governments, commissioned by The Washington Post, shows that in a five-year period from 1979 through 1984, a total of $832.6 million worth of commercial projects were started within roughly a mile of either side of the 66-mile-long beltway. <P>The overall construction during the 1979-84 period translated into about 17.6 million square feet of new office space, retail stores, hotels and educational and medical facilities.<P>Granted, development along a Pittsburgh beltway would never mirror the nation's capital, but what happened in Washington does show how infrastructure improvements can be an economic catalyst.<P>Southern Beltway<P>The section of the would-be beltway closest to construction is the 28-mile section that would bend behind the South Hills, connecting the airport to the proposed Mon-Fayette Expressway. The section stretches from 6 to 9 on the clock face.<P>Planners have narrowed the choices where the road would be built to a corridor along the Washington-Allegheny county line. The question remains: Will it be built? <P>North Strabane Township supervisors approved a resolution in December opposing plans to lay the Southern Beltway across the northern tier of the township.<P>Some residents were so against the road that they told township officials to raise their taxes by 1 mill to fight the road. Other residents offered to make personal contributions to a legal fund.<P>Supervisors in Cecil and Nottingham townships also have passed resolutions condemning plans to have the $630 million road pass through their communities.<P>As with most projects of this size, a fear of property condemnations have driven the opposition to the road.<P>Council meetings and public hearings are peppered with comments about the road "cutting through my home" or "leveling my backyard." But beltway advocates say the reality is that there is a price to pay for saving this region from economic debacle, and some unlucky people won't have a choice in the process.<P>"I have tremendous empathy for those who will be displaced, but we've come to the time when sacrifices have to be made for the good of all," says Larry Simpson, immediate past president of the western Pennsylvania chapter of the National Association of Industrial and Office Properties, a group that strongly supports the beltway concept.<P>"I fully understand the fears of those impacted by the road," adds another beltway advocate, state Sen.   J. Barry Stout, a Democrat whose district covers Greene County and parts of Beaver and Washington counties.<P>"I don't know where we'd be if we did not have the interstate system to move people and goods today," Stout says. "We would be strangled with traffic. I hope at some point in time that people will realize that a beltway is important for the future of this region."<P>Without the beltway, the region is doomed to economic death, advocates say. And the western suburbs of Pittsburgh near the airport are a prime example of why. Currently the townships stretching from the airport into the South Hills are a maze of winding, two-lane roads dotted with no-passing zones and weight-restricted bridges.<P>"If you get behind a coaltruck, you are there all day," says Carrier, the traffic engineer.<P>Property that might be prime for a manufacturing or distribution facility lacks access, probably one of the main reasons the new airport terminal has not been the economic catalyst that many hoped it would be.<P>Paying For It<P>Stout admits that talking about a beltway is one thing; actually funding a series of projects that create a beltway is another story.<P>"You are into a very costly transportation network," the senator says.<P>At presstime, Gov. Tom Ridge proposed a gasoline tax as a means of funding infrastructure improvements, among other things. Beltway advocates, who feared Ridge might steer clear of such a tax to fund highway construction, were somewhat relieved. With legislators up for re-election next year, it was unlikely they would push the gas tax had Ridge not supported it.<P>    It remained unlikely at presstime that the gas tax would generate sufficient funding for all the projects the state would like to begin.<P>   The reality: Stout says there is more work planned than there is money to pay for it.<P>   From Carrier's standpoint, the only way the beltway will become a reality is if the Turnpike Commission undertakes the project as a toll road that will pay for itself over the years.<P>    And highway projects don't happen over night. There are years of planning, public meetings, impact studies and bidding before the first bulldozer ever moves one pile of dirt.<P>That's why, beltway advocates say, the time to move aggressively on such projects is now. The first step is the Southern Beltway.<P>"We have a belief that Pittsburgh can do better," says NAIOP member James Storer, director of development for Mosites Development Co. "We believe western Pennsylvania can do much better.<P>"We have not, in the past, done what we need to do in order to do better as a region."<P>Build it, Storer and other beltway advocates say, and businesses will come.<P><P><P>




<hr>

