<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0496.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0496.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Welcome to the<br>Jungle
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Remember the Boring Pittsburgh Zoo? Those days are <br>long over; The Zoo has Thrived Since Being<br>Privatized, and Director Barbara Baker has big plans</font></b><br>

<i>By Cynthia Bent</i></center>
<hr>

<P>
One day back in the late 1980s, Bob Luffy took his kids to see the Pittsburgh Zoo. He was terribly disappointed with what he found. He told his friend John Burgess about it a little while later - not knowing that Burgess was president of the Board of the Friends of the Zoo.<P>"I said, 'It's dirty, it's run down, it's a shame.' He said, 'Why don't you come on board, get involved?' I said, 'Why not?' " recalls Luffy.<P>At that time, the Friends of the Zoo was only a fundraising arm of the city-run facility. Since then, the changes that have taken place can only be described as revolutionary. The Zoological Society of Pittsburgh Inc. now owns and runs the zoo as a nonprofit corporation - commanding an annual budget of over $6 million.<P>Major renovations have changed the face of the zoo, including the addition of a brand-new Kids Kingdom. Attendance has increased 55 percent, with all-time high reached last year of over 680,000 visitors. Secure funds for the futurehave given the zoo the ability to plan the next 10 years with an end goal of becoming one of the top 10 zoos in the country.<P>And Bob Luffy is now chairman of the Zoological Society board. <P>"It's been a tremendous transition," says Luffy. "There's a world of difference between knocking-on-doors fundraising to an administration with a staff of 80 full-time employees in charge of a $30 million animal collection, with our own finances, marketing, and so on."<P><P>What's New at the Zoo<P>The 10-year strategic plan, in the works for over a year, reveals an ambitious vision of a rapidly changing zoo where visitors will never be bored again. The primary goal is to reach one million visitors per year sometime in the next five years by tapping the regional market. At the forefront is an effort to make the zoo kid-friendly.<P>"I've pushed since the beginning ofmy involvement to make this the biggest and best children-focused zoo in the country," says Luffy, emphasizing the link between families and increased membership. "Nothing else would generate that kind of return on the investment for us, for one thing, and really, the zoo is for kids."<P>With first changes since privatization - Kids Kingdom and the Discovery Pavilion - the rubber hits the road. The first phase, Kids Kingdom, opened last May. A phenomenal hit, Kids Kingdom has outdoor playgrounds, where kids can climb on webs like a spider, swing down a rope like a gibbon or slide down a windy tunnel like an otter. The play areas surround petting corrals, where kangaroos and goats get up close and personal. One might lick you on the face.<P>Part II, the $2.2 million Discovery Pavilion, is slated for unveiling in May 1997 with more upclose experiences in the animal habitats. For instance, visitors will walk through a bat flyway - a 40-foot long tunnel with caves at eitherend - so close to the bats they can feel the breeze of their beating wings. <P>Another tunnel in the exhibit will be underwater - visitors will stroll through a glass tube beneath tanks of freshwater alligators and fish in wildlife-like surroundings. It will feel like being surrounded by a marsh and all its creatures.<P>One other attraction, the Meerkat Village, will showcase what it's like to be a little prairie-dog-like African mammal that burrows underground. Human burrows will run under the village, with pop-up windows for eye-to-eye contact with the animals.<P>Other exhibits will change regularly to keep visitors coming back again and again. Kids can peer through microscopes at an invisible world, and see what a junebug looks like or explore the skeleton of mammals, finding out what makes them tick and roar.<P>The rest of the zoo will gradually undergo a revolution as well. Graphics all over the zoo will be smartened-upboth visually and content-wise to provide education about the animals. Instead of seeing just the animal's name, or maybe even no sign at all, visitors will learn where tigers prowl, what giraffes eat, how many snow leopards are left in the wild and more.<P>This May, the zoo's train ride also gets a major facelift, with the help of faculty and students from the Pittsburgh Art Institute. Professor Alan Assad will enlist the help of students in the school of Industrial Design Technology to make the train ride into a safari education about the world's endangered species. The train will trundle by dioramas of life-like creatures in their wild habitats, like cats peering out of the jungle or wolves playing with their pups.<P>Assad says the school is excited to get their first chance to demonstrate the talents of its students, who study design of amusement parks and museum exhibits just like this one. It's rare, he says, that students get the chance to add projects like this to their portfolios.<P>Then comes the renovation of the AquaZoo. December saw the introduction of a new AquaZoo curator, Jim Prappas, a veteran of Walt Disney World and the Texas State Aquarium. He's jumped in with both feet, revamping and cleaning. A bevy of chambered nautilus, brightly-colored shellfish related to squid, set up shop in late winter. All over, tropical plants, waterfalls and fish have appeared in nooks and crannies. Divers swim through the tanks polishing the glass. Extensive future planning for major changes is now underway, though no solid decisions have been made.<P>Construction will next begin in 1998 for the South America and Asia exhibits. No one's quite sure what that's going to look like, because the American Zoological Association has not assessed the situation yet; the animals brought in will depend on what's available around the country. The most anyone knows is that the exhibit should have both indoor and outdoor components, to try to make as much of the zoo hospitable in wintermonths as possible. And 2001 will see the raising of an animal health and research complex, which won't be open to the public but will push the zoo to the forefront as a national research and health facility in the next century.<P><P>Other Strategies<P>Animal welfare and conservation have evolved into the zoo's primary raison d'etre. The goals in this area are to continue to provide top-notch care for the animals in the collection, and to focus on research and breeding programs for selected endangered or threatened species the staff has singled out for concentration. Two species the zoo has already begun to develop include the African elephant and the orangutan, because of staff expertise in these areas.<P>The five elephants are very young; zoo staff hopes to begin breeding them soon. It won't be long, they hope, before film clips of baby elephants born in Pittsburgh show up at the end of newscasts around the country. Likewise, the zoo aspires to become a breeding and research center for orangs.<P>Then there's educational programming, which is of utmost importance to the zoo's mission and already an area of explosive growth. Under Margaret Markas, curator of education, the program has increased from 454 students in 1990 to 38,000 last year.<P>Markas, a former animal keeper with the zoo, remembers a time when she did both special events and education, before the Education and Administration Complex was built, before there was even a place to hold classes. Now, with an MA in education from Duquesne under her belt, the redirected mission of the zoo to free her and provide resources, and with a five-classroom, 250 seat auditorium at her disposal, she's challenged just to keep up with the demand.<P>Markas runs programs for every age student, from age 3 through 103. The zoo teaches classes, holds workshops for teachers, runs summer camps, overnights, tours, even a cruise on the Gateway Clipper. The Oldsmobile Zoomobile travels throughout the region doing in-school visits. There are lecture series, night safaris and programs in conjunction with the Carnegie, Phipps Conservatory and the University of Pittsburgh, all developed in the last five years.<P>Other goals of the plan include more fundraising, marketing and membership drives. For instance, the zoo has just started group tour sales - parties or business groups can book the zoo for tours, conferences and meetings; while groups meet in the Educational Complex, spouses can tour the zoo with families. The zoo has already generated $259,000 from only eight months of group sales. Zoo Director Barbara Baker notes that 47 percent of Kennywood's business is done in prebooked groups, so the zoo's potential should be huge.<P><P>The Privatization<P>The story of the zoo's privatization is a classic tale of what the private sector at its best can accomplish. The first meeting Luffy attended, the group discussed its search for a new director, who would turn out to be a force that Luffy and others credit with making that change possible. Barbara Baker, a South Carolina native, lured from Riverbanks Zoo in Columbia, started as director in July 1990.<P>Baker says the zoo was at a crossroads when she came, ready for changes. The city had poured $26 million into renovations, and after 10 years of construction, it was time, she says, to take off. But the zoo was hampered by the limitations of being city-run. For instance, the city could never provide marketing for the zoo, so no one knew how it had already changed.<P>The zoo was ready to come to life as a major asset to the community - provided, of course, it could be set on sound financial footing, sheltered from the high and low tides of political maneuvering. Other zoos around the country were moving in the same direction; in1990, 47 percent of zoos were privately administrated already. Now, that number is 56 percent. Privatization was, in the zoo's eyes, a key to the future.<P>It finally became apparent around 1991 that the city needed to spin off some of the drains on its finances, and the board jumped at the chance to take over the zoo. Jeff Stilson, then president, co-chaired a task force with Jim Stalder of Price Waterhouse to push the zoo into privatization. Negotiations for that change took two years.<P>It was a long and difficult road, not least because the mayor's office changed hands just as the deal was ready to be inked. The board had to start all over, convincing the new administration of the wisdom of the deal. <P>Pete Hodgkins, director of the Philadelphia Zoo, which has always been privately administered, made the trip to Pittsburgh to testify before the council on the board's behalf.<P>"They would have the best of bothworlds, private management and some public support," he recalls. "I was strongly in favor of this move for them."<P>In the midst of the negotiations, Stilson asked Luffy to take over as president of the board, wanting to move on to other projects. Luffy asked him how much time the commitment would take.<P>"He said, 'About one hour or two a week.' He lied. A lot." Luffy has nevertheless remained dedicated to the zoo's mission ever since. <P>At about the same time another key to the zoo's future was being forged. The Regional Asset District funding project was in the works, a concept that could provide the zoo, along with a myriad of other public facilities, with stable funds that would mean the difference between stalled development and a bright future.<P>In the end, the zoo got both its wishes. The Regional Asset District Initiative was signed the same day as the privatization deal - December 14, 1993. The zoo had been given its wings; now it had to learn to use them.<P><P><P>New Order<P>The first year after privatization was a busy one. The zoo staff spent 1994 adjusting to the climate change, and preparing for its next big moves, says Baker.<P>Baker brought on board Saul Markowitz, a former director of public relations for CMU's College of Fine Arts who can only be described as "Mr. Energy." Markowitz set about rehabilitating the zoo's dusty image with the energy of the Tazmanian Devil. His team came on board in April 1994 with painfully little time before its busy season (see sidebar, page 18).<P>After revitalizing attendance and getting used to its new wings, the zoo was ready to take on the next phase: the next 10 years.<P>"We needed a master development plan to reflect the Regional AssetDistrict, the membership growth, the momentum we had, to keep it all going and bring in new projects every year," says Luffy. Mark Vernallis, a board member with a background in strategic financial planning for venture capital firms, decided to take on the job.<P>The plan took about six months to nail down. Vernallis traveled around the country with Baker, visiting successful zoos to peek at how they formulated their own strategic plans. His committee then put down into words where they were and where they'd like to go.<P>"The security of the RAD fund made Pittsburgh's plan unique," explains Vernallis. "While other zoos are questioning their survival from year to year, wondering where winds of political change will leave them, we are able to plan to make this zoo an awfully positive asset to the region."<P>A shift in the philosophy behind the zoo's mission was also involved. Over the past quarter century, the focus of zoos has changed from "stamp book" collections, as Baker puts it - having at least one of everything - to a focus on conservation and education, to help keep all species around in their own habitats, in the wild, for all time. As a result, zoos have grown their educational programs into centerpieces of their missions. Pittsburgh was starting in this direction with the addition of the Educational and Administrative Complex in 1993, but needed direction.<P>The Into the Future plan is a study of these assets and challenges, designed to push the zoo to top capability. The specific goal, in order to make the zoo the best asset to the region and to the greater zoological community, is to be recognized as one of the top 10 zoos in the country.<P>It won't be easy. Pittsburgh is, of course, at the mercy of the weather. The terrain is rough and hilly for some. The zoo traditionally has had no focal animal to research or exhibit, something the board identified as a mark of a top zoo. Some of its facilities are outdated, like the AquaZoo. <P>But these are seen as opportunities for improvement, not downers. Some of their challenges - such as the youth of their marketing and educational programs - have already provided those opportunities. <P>"This is not a bookshelf plan," emphasizes Baker. "We live with this document day to day, and refer to it whenever we make a decision. Every so often, the staff sits down, takes a page, and tries to come up with a way to make it happen. I think we're well on our way."<P><P>The Present Zoo<P>Baker and Vernallis did some benchmarking of the Pittsburgh Zoo while traveling around the country researching. Baker says they'd already  succeeded in putting the zoo in the top 20, maybe top 15 facilities in the country. Cracking the top 10 won't be easy.<P>"You pretty much have to knock someone else off the list to be considered top 10, but we believe where we'restarting from is a pretty good platform," says Vernallis. The plan lists some of the zoo's assets: its sound financial base due to the RAD, great new educational facilities and the best children's zoo in the country (on completion), already high attendance (the zoo is currently second in attendance only to the Pirates). Vernallis, and everyone connected with the zoo, whether board member or staff, would list another asset near the top of that list: Baker.<P>"Much of the success we've had can be credited to Barbara, as well as the board," says Luffy. "She's assembled an excellent staff."<P>"I can't see the zoo ever going backwards with Dr. Baker," agrees Markowitz. "She's allowed us to do crazy things. What would most people say if you came to them and said, 'We've got this great idea. It's about a clam?' "<P>"Dr. Baker is a dynamo, with great zoological knowledge and sound business sense," agrees Philadelphia's Hodgkins. "They take their conservation and educational roles seriously, and business too. To meet our lofty goals, we need to stay in business. They're doing all the right things."<P>Baker herself credits the foresight of the board, and the community.<P>"It's been so exciting," she says. "Within two months of privatizing, everyone was calling to see how they could help. We had sponsors calling us."<P>Vernallis says, "Vibrant organizations have an ability to attract people and to accomplish. The zoo is in that phase. There's lots to keep the momentum for a long time."<P>Their motivations may vary; some want to see a pearl for the region, some work for the love of animals or the excitement of their job. All, however, are committed to the zoo with a passion, and all have the ability to work as a team with a precision that almost seems flawless.<P>"Look at the results," says Luffy. "We've got great new projects, a great educational complex already built, we'recertainly known better now than four years ago. Now the zoo is someplace the community is proud of and will go to on a regular basis. There's a lack of restrictions; the staff makes the future of the zoo limitless. I think it will be a top 5 zoo. It will be a real treasure to the Pittsburgh region."<P>"We had to find ways to get people back through those gates again, to pique people's interest in what's happening," says Pittsburgh Zoo Marketing Director Saul Markowitz. His method? Take a shoestring budget and mix marketing, public relations and advertising whenever possible by generating stories with unique advertising.<P>Anyone who was around during "The Clam Campaign" of spring 1994 will surely remember it - the fast-paced, colorful ads bursting onto the screen with wild animal sounds punctuated by periods of quiet blurping noises and a deep-voiced narrator: "Have you seen the Quahog Clam?"<P>"The idea was," says Markowitz, "it got people talking. It was the first time that the zoo had really done anything that was really different." <P>The marketing department since has generated much-needed membership and attendance, and sponsors as well - over $1.1 million in sponsorship support in 1995, including advertising time, and cash donations of over $260,000. Baker points out that privatization was one of the best things to happen for the zoo in the arena of sponsorship.<P>"Some people are leery to give to government-run facilities," Baker says. "They're more comfortable with corporate entities - that the place will be around and not run by politics, that the money will go to what it's supposed to and be used efficiently, and that they will be well recognized and treated."<P>"We couldn't do without sponsors," adds Markowitz. On the zoo bandwagon are companies like AT&T and the Body Shop, sponsors for last winter's ZooLights festival, WTAE, which has produced TV spots for the zoo and sold countless hours of airtime toyet more sponsors, and the Grand Olds Gang, which has been on board since 1994 and recently  donated a $25,000 Zoomobile for educational outreach.<P>Hank Anderson Sr., president of the Grand Olds Gang, couldn't be happier about their relationship with the zoo. He says they'd been looking for a new project to get involved with in the community, and when WTAE proposed the zoo, "It was a no-brainer." <P>"They made a very good impression the first time they walked in the door," he remembers. "I haven't met one person there yet who's not friendly, helpful and capable ... that's very rare these days. They're on the right track, and they're the kind of exciting people we want to be associated with."<P>The relationship has been so productive that the Grand Olds Gang just recommitted for three more years. As far as Anderson is concerned, the zoo improves the community, and the stronger the community, the better for his, and everyone's, business.<P>





