<a href="../zine/0496.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Supplement4.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Running Away From the Field
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>A Once-Small Washington County Track has Become a Regional <br>Entertainment Source- And Thinking Growth<br>Through the Next Decade</font></b><br>

<i>By Pohla Smith</i></center>
<hr>


<P>

Good EVE-ning racing fans!<P>The booming, baritone voice of track announcer Roger Huston rumbles around the clubhouse and grandstand of Ladbroke at the Meadows, the harness racing track located about 15 miles south of Pittsburgh in North Strabane Township, Washington County.<P>The effect is like listening to a foreign film dubbed in Sensurround: Huston's voice rolls over the on-track loud speakers as it's going out on the airwaves via satellite and then back again to dozens of track television monitors that are tuned into the Meadows Racing Network.<P>The reverberations are most intense in areas still filling with people arriving for the live racing card. It's worst in the grandstand, where three-quarters of the 4,500 bleacher seats are empty. <P>But the competing cadences aren't as jarring in the spots already jumping. There's the simulcast areas in the grandstand and lower level, where as many people watch the races on track TV monitors as those who watch live out the windows.  Here Huston's cadences blend into a cacophony of chitchat, bettors' chalktalk and clinking glassware to produce a loud but ignorable dull roar. <P>On an average night, the on-track crowd will number some 1,300, who collectively wager some $92,000 on the live harness races, and spend an average of four bucks each for food and beverages. A nice night for a Pittsburgh area restaurant and nightspot, but hardly the stuff of big business, right?<P>Wrong.<P>The lost-in-time, state-fair atmosphere of horses circling the Meadows' five-eighths-mile limestone track is deceptive. These days, racing at the Meadows is very big business indeed. Certainly bigger than in horse racing's heyday in the 1960s, when the sport was the only legal gambling outside of Vegas. Sure, the crowds at the little track founded by Hall of Fame horseman Del Miller were bigger then.<P>But the action wasn't.<P>    Today,  the Meadows is the hub of the American activities of United Kingdom-based Ladbroke Group PLC, a huge multicontinent conglomerate operating one of the largest racing and gaming companies in the world. In 1994, total operating profit for Ladbroke Group, which also operates Hilton International, was about 315.1 million pounds. That is $491.5 million in U.S. dollars.<P>    More locally, the little track nestled between Route 19 and Interstate 79 is the crown jewel of Ladbroke Racing Pennsylvania. LRP, headquartered in a recently renovated administrative building in the track's stable area, also owns and operates five (soon-to-be six) off-track betting parlors and a burgeoning home-telephone wagering network.<P>But that doesn't mean LRP is standing still.<P>"The key in this business is that every year we have to find the next button to push to make something happen here," says LRP Vice President Michael Jeannot.<P>The focus this year will be home-telephone wagering, and western Pennsylvania will benefit because of it.<P>The Meadows Racing Network carries Huston's booming voice into millions of homes and dozens of simulcast wagering sites across the United States and Canada by satellite and cable TV. Every time Huston's voice booms into a simulcast site in Florida, a track in Nevada or a home in Canada's Maritime Provinces, it is a little bit of free publicity for Washington County and for Pittsburgh. Ladbroke Racing Pennsylvania is fast getting a reputation in the racing and gaming industry as one of the most aggressive, technically up-to-date operations in the nation.<P>Residents of big racing states like New York and California are stunned when they hear that people sitting at home in Squirrel Hill can watch and bet on the races from Belmont Park and Santa Anita, something few of them can do themselves.<P>Ladbroke at The Meadows also will be taking on a higher profile nationally as phone-wagering hub of the new American Championship Harness Series. Plans for the series call for 30 one-hour nationwide telecasts of about 100 races from the United States' top tracks with at-home wagering for the TV viewer through the Meadows. The first telecast is set for July 13 on ESPN2. <P>Together, telephone, off-track and simulcasting are referred to in the U.S. racing business as convenience wagering - a way for racing to take its game to fans who no longer go, or never have gone - to the track.<P>Home betting can be as simple as picking up the telephone to wager off entries in a program or newspaper, using money stashed in a track account. Or, in a couple places outside Pennsylvania, it can be as complex as watching the races on TV while wagering via an interactive remote control. OTBs range from the countertop-only storefronts of New York City to the posh restaurant/sports bar/lounges favored by Ladbroke.<P>Simulcast sites are any place - race tracks, theaters, OTBs - that display the  video simulcasts of live racing from other locales, and accept wagers.<P>Ladbroke Pennsylvania<P>In terms of growth, Ladbroke Racing Pennsylvania is the star of Ladbroke Racing Corp., the U.S. umbrella company. Though headquartered in the Holiday Drive business park in Greentree, Ladbroke Racing Corp., is quite far-flung. It includes  thoroughbred tracks Detroit Race Course and Golden Gate Fields, a card club in San Pablo, Calif., and recently closed Valley Greyhound, a dog track the company is trying to turn over to locals in Texas.<P>The U.S. corporation is a relatively new venture for Ladbroke Group's gaming division, which is best known for the dozens of betting shops and gambling casinos it operates across the United Kingdom, Ireland and Belgium. The firm bought its first American racing properties in the mid-1980s, just in time to take advantage of the proliferation of laws legalizing off-track and simulcast wagering. It purchased the Meadows from Ed Ryan of Ryan Homes and Joe Hardy of 84 Lumber six years ago.<P>In terms of Ladbroke's influence on the region, consider these numbers: In 1995, total handle - or money bet into or through LRP - was more than $314.5 million. That represented more than 7 percent growth over 1994 total handle of $293.5 million. <P>That increase was due primarily to even bigger growth in Call-A-Bet, Ladbroke's name for the telephone wagering system it operates for both live races and imported simulcast signals. Call-A-Bet handle increased from $18.4 million in 1994 to nearly $23 million in 1995 - more than 24 percent - after live programming from the Meadows was expanded to a 12-hour, seven-day-a-week program, including race simulcasts from tracks across the United States.<P>LRP also had substantial revenue growth selling the simulcast signal of its races to other tracks and betting outlets. "Our signal sales totaled $74 million last year, and that was literally $10 million three years ago," Jeannot says. "That's huge."<P>Additional, perhaps even more spectacular growth is likely in 1996. New regulations allow LRP to accept  out-of-state telephone wagers, and LRP's executives have vowed to go after that huge untapped audience of stay-at-home gamblers in a big way. They'll feed the Meadows show to more cable networks and into more homes, perhaps by direct satellite delivery, for more hours a day. A new website on the Internet also will play a major role.<P>"It was easy a year ago to say, 'Well, if people wanted to bet they'd go to OTB. They'd find a way,' " Jeannot says. "But that's not the case. It's distribution, distribution, distribution."<P>Ladbroke Pennsylvania also recently got site approval for the sixth and final OTB parlor it is allowed by state law. The 20,000-square-foot facility planned for a former supermarket in Century Square Plaza, West Mifflin, would be the largest of the chain, which also includes sites in Moon and Harmar townships, Greensburg, New Castle and Johnstown.<P>New Castle, the first and, by total handle, most successful OTB, also is in line for expansion. In addition to adding some jobs, expansion means more tax dollars for Pennsylvania, which gets an average of 2.2 percent of every wager made at the state's tracks. <P>"We paid over $690,000 in state pari-mutuel taxes last year," says Anthony Mediate, director of marketing and communications for Pennsylvania.<P>Local municipalities cannot tax pari-mutuel wagers (the school district around Pocono Downs harness track in eastern Pennsylvania recently tried, but the courts said no). Still, there are many other ways to get in on the action.<P>"We pay mercantile tax, occupational privilege tax, real estate tax, school tax and business privilege taxes," Mediate says.<P>"We pay occupational and real estate taxes to Washington County for Ladbroke at the Meadows and these 40 people up here [staff of LRP].  And for the OTBs, we pay mercantile, occupational, real estate, school and business privilege tax in other counties."<P>Randy Edmonds, general manager of the Meadows, guesses that the track is the second or third largest employer in the county. <P>If you look at the figures the way Pennsylvania's tracks did during the massive lobbying effort to legalize OTB a few years ago, he's probably right.<P>At the height of the racing season, which runs late spring through early fall, the Meadows employs 500 people. Another 500 people work independently in the stable area as trainers, drivers and grooms.<P>An additional 100 people or so provide ancillary services: veterinary care, shoeing, feed, equipment and so on. Add all those together and you get 1,100 people dependent on the Meadows for a living. <P>That puts Ladbroke among the region's top 25 employers.<P>"Ninety to 95 percent of the people working for us live within 15 miles of where they work," Mediate says. "So wherever we have an operation, our employees, directly or indirectly, are impacting those communities. It's the churn effect. It's going through and churning that economy."<P>But the biggest impact on Washington County and greater Pittsburgh may be in the realm of public relations generated every time Huston's voice is heard in another part of North America.<P>The only fly in the ointment could be legalization of riverboat gambling, the most recent rage among states hungry for new revenue and gamblers looking for more action. The incursion of riverboats has meant trouble to competing racetracks in other states.<P>Though casinos and gaming companies have been lobbying hard for riverboat legalization in Pennsylvania, there's been a dramatic slowdown in casino expansion the last couple years. Here in Pennsylvania, the movement has been slowed by opposition in Harrisburg (see Eye on Harrisburg, page 9).<P>But if it does get approved, Ladbroke is confident it could survive the challenge. Thanks in large part to intense lobbying by Ladbroke, the pending bills grant racetracks a riverboat license if riverboat gambling becomes legal in their market. So if one of those bills passes, Ladbroke will expand further.<P>"We're a major Pittsburgh-area employer, a major gaming company, and we've done a good job of telling the state that. If it comes in, we want the legislature to look at us first. And I think we're on favorable ground," says John Swiatek, who oversees government relations as vice president, operations of Ladbroke Racing Corp.<P>"We can utilize it to benefit our existing businesses, to bounce people to and from the riverboat operations to the off-track betting facilities to the racetracks, maybe put an off-track betting facility on a riverboat operation. We think that's what we need to have occur if riverboats do come to Pennsylvania."<P>Ladbroke has gone beyond the "what-if" stage: Swiatek confirmed the company has optioned land it could use for docking. Though he declined to reveal its location, it is believed to be near Three Rivers Stadium on the North Side.<P>"We've done that more defensively," he says. "We feel in order to protect and grow our business we have to have land and be prepared to go forward."<P>If it does, Huston's resonating voice and the rest of Ladbroke racing no doubt will go along.<P>




<hr>

