<a href="../zine/0496.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0496.Supplement5.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>I Don't Have to Go in the Bank
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+>The Banks Know This Tune and Others;<br>If Banking's Not as Convenient as<br>Possible, Customers, Will Sing the Blues</font></b><br>

<i>By Christopher Lawton</i></center>
<hr>


<P>
Patty Kelly doesn't step foot inside a bank. That's why she is a typical banking customer, banking instead at automatic teller machines or by phone.<P>Anything but a trip inside.<P>"With an ATM, I don't have to go inside the bank to do my banking," says Kelly, 33, a Mellon Bank customer. "And I can use it off-hours and on the weekends. Telephone banking enables me to check the status of my accounts whenever I want, any time of day or night."<P>Banks know that. So financial institutions large and small are offering up a  host of traditional and nontraditional services as part of a common strategy to best deliver the widest array of services - or convenience - to consumers like Kelly.<P>Consider the activity at some the region's banks:<P>	Mellon, which was one of the first banks in western Pennsylvania to employ ATM technology, currently offers videoconferences so customers at suburban branch offices can talk to financial counselors in downtown Pittsburgh. It also offers telephone banking.<P>	The other regional giant, PNC, is launching on-line banking and is heavily into telephone banking.<P>	Smaller banks like First        National Bank of Herminie and First Western have branches inside retail stores.<P>"Convenience has always been driven by the customer, but with the rapid pace of new technology, banks today can now offer many services that will make them even more convenient," says Fritz Elmendorf, vice president of the Consumer Bankers Association.<P><P>The Giants<P>It's not surprising that convenience has become all-important in banking. With an increasing number of single-parent and two-earner households, time is tight.<P><P><P>This new age of banking started with automatic teller machines, which allowed customers to deposit and withdraw funds when the bank was closed, or at a location where there was no available branch office. <P>Mellon was an early player in ATM banking and 15 years later has one of the largest ATM networks in the region, serving one of the largest customer bases with over $41 billion in balance sheet assets.<P>"New technology has enabled banks to offer a whole host of options to the customer, in addition to services offered through ATMs, but it remains the bank's responsibility to determine what services are best for its customers," says Paul Beideman, vice president of Retail Financial Services for Mellon Bank.<P>Mellon's interactive video conferencing lets customers connect from any branch or store office to investment experts or a mortgage banking official at another Mellon location.<P>Interactive video also allows Mellon customers to interact with Mellon's planned Financial Centers - libraries offering financial information and access to personal financial investors and business bankers.<P>"These Financial Centers will be strategically located throughout the Mellon system and will also offer walk-in services to customers who wish to take advantage of this type of service," says Beideman. "Inter-active video allows customers to interface with experts from their location, bringing this service to the customer rather than the customer having to make a trip to another location," says Beideman.<P>     Mellon also has Direct 24, full-service bank-by-phone capabilities, 24 hours a day, seven days a week. Using their phone, Mellon customers can establish loans, open new accounts, transfer money between various accounts or seek additional information about other Mellon products.<P>At PNC Bank, similar strategies are progressing just as quickly. One current focus is the Spring launch of on-line banking through which customers will be able to bank from their home computer with software such as Quicken or Microsoft Money.<P>"PNC strongly believes in Internet technology as a vehicle in which to conduct business, and we wanted to give our customers the flexibility to choose their own software," says Judith E. Campbell, a PNC senior vice president. With a few keystrokes from home, PNC PC bankers will easily be able to apply for loans, buy mutual funds and deposit money into CDs and checking and savings accounts.<P>With the formation of the PC banking, PNC is taking their customers' view that convenience is no longer location, but rather time-driven. PNC managers also feel that their investments in many other nontraditional services, such as their downtown telephone banking center, puts them ahead of the competition, at least for now.<P>PNC offers technology services such as telephone banking and telephone bill-paying services; the latter allows the customer to designate merchants to whom the bank may automatically pay bills from the customer's checking account. PNC is also developing a technology that will create a "smart card" for use in all types of customer purchases.<P>For this type of transaction, funds are transferred from the customer's checking account to the smart card for payment of items ranging from airline tickets to chewing gum.<P><P>Tweaking Traditional<P>Not all convenience-oriented measures are high tech. Some are no tech.<P>Mellon's Beideman, for one, touts the overall importance of technology-based services, but in the same breath points out that a balance must be achieved. You can be just as convenient to some customers by simply staying open a little longer.<P>"Institutions must consider the advantages of traditional services such as extended hours of operation and location of branch offices, as well as those consisting of nontraditional technology-based services."<P>Mellon and Integra - being acquired this spring by National City Bank of Cleveland - have long had presences in retail stores, a relatively inexpensive strategy that community banks also have employed.<P>Locally, Mellon started this trend several years ago with the opening of a new branch inside a Giant Eagle supermarket. "Retail stores appeal to customers who don't want to make a special trip to do their banking," says Mellon's Beideman. "Customers can go into a Giant Eagle to do their grocery or other shopping, and stop by the bank to open an account or perform another service. It also affords the supermarket an opportunity to get the Mellon customer's attention who may come into the store to predominantly perform banking services. Any way you look at it, it's a win-win situation."<P>Maria Brady, marketing officer for First National Bank of Herminie, agrees. "Supermarket banking builds upon the principle of the multiple sale, and it increases impulse buying."<P>Two years ago, First National of Herminie opened a retail store in the locally owned Davis grocery store in Greensburg. Like its larger counterparts, First National's retail store branch offers full-service banking, such as the bank's ability to make a car loan or provide home equity financing.<P>Brady suggests that the approach banks take to retail store banking is a little different than its traditional "brick and mortar" counterparts.<P>"In a retail setting, banks can be proactive. That is, they can go out into the aisles of the store, or use the PA system to greet people and tell them what the bank has to offer," says Brady.<P>One reason the smaller banks can open retail store branches is that they are less costly for the bank to open and maintain than traditional branch offices, which usually require several million dollars in investment capital. Retail store branches, in comparison, can be opened for about a quarter of a million dollars. <P>First National has also partnered with Redstone Highlands, a long-term nursing care and residential living community in Greensburg, to offer branch service banking on Redstone's campus.<P>"This venture provides a community service to Redstone's older adults, who want the convenience of face-to-face banking without the inconvenience of having to drive off-campus to the bank," says Brady.<P>"The establishment of First National's branch on our campus has enabled us to use our resources to take better care of our residents - and it's enabled our residents to better manage their care by providing a facility on campus for their banking needs," adds Ron Barrett, president of Redstone Highlands.<P>Other banks are expanding into the retail and nursing home environments or making plans to do so. First Western Bancorp, which has offices in western Pennsylvania and Ohio, recently opened a full-service retail store in New Castle at a Wal-Mart Superstore. PNC Bank is also seriously considering retail store service for its customers and has plans for an opening possibly by the end of 1996. <P>Mellon not only has 66 retail stores throughout Pennsylvania and New Jersey, but operates an office in the South Hills at Friendship Village, a long-term care facility and retirement community.<P>Another small bank, Pittsburgh Home Savings, opened a supermarket-based branch inside a Shop N' Save grocery store, says J. Ardie Dillen, president, Pittsburgh Home Savings Bank. Dillen sees this as a way to pull in $6 million in deposits and make $6 million from loans over the next few years.<P>"There is a real challenge for community banks the size of Pittsburgh Home Savings to compete with the technological services that the larger banks offer," says Dillen.<P>The retention of traditional banking while moving high tech shows there still are those who want banking to have a personal touch, according to Steven R. Sant, vice president for retail banking for First Western.<P> "We still feel that our customers want that element of face-to-face banking. The difference is that the tradition of the branch office has created a more retail-oriented approach to banking," says Sant. And in fact, First Western calls these new branches, like the one in Wal-Mart, "retail stores."<P>"We believe that in addition to the retail store environment, First Western must offer its customers services that meet their needs," added Sant. "That is why we've added a 24-hour customer service line and a 'loan by phone' line, both of which offer added convenience to our customers."  <P>In addition, First Western is considering PC banking and telephone bill-paying technology as possible offerings to their customers. "Even though we're considering new technology, our feeling is that our customers still want to know the person they're dealing with  at the bank one-on-one." <P>Subtle Technology<P>Some of the convenience-oriented technology doesn't even require consumer participation. Last year, First National Bank of Herminie began to offer its customers "image processing."  This service, which relies on optical technology, gives a copy of customers' checks in sequential order rather than sending cancelled checks with the monthly statement.<P>"This service saves time for our customers in two ways," says Brady. "First it eliminates the need for customers to place checks in numerical order before balancing a checkbook, and secondly, it gives customers the ability to call in and check on the status of individual checks, because we now have a permanent record of the customer's checking account." Before image processing, First National would typically have to go through microfilm files to find the check in question.<P>First National's main objective, with all of the services it offers, is  to increase its loan base. They therefore try to offer services that appeal to people in the 25 to 45 age group, those most likely to take out significant loans.<P>Banks all over the country are using various methods to sell their products and compete for customers. According to Fritz Elmendorf at the Consumer Bankers Association, "It's important not only for banks to compete with the widest array of technical services, but important to offer price considerations in the form of lower service charges and fees as well." <P>The CBA cautions, however, that those institutions that don't offer a balance of both traditional and non-traditional services invite disaster.<P>"Nationally, we're seeing a trend away from the traditional branch-based service toward the nontraditional technology-based services," say Elmendorf. "As much as 40 percent of bank customers don't want to have to go inside their bank to perform transactions, and that figure will probably continue to climb."<P>Says Patty Kelly, the Mellon customer: "I like the availability of service I have at my fingertips. It gives me the option to change the way in which I do my banking if I find it's more convenient."<P>Or to change banks, for that matter.<P>





