</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>A Mile Away, But Worlds Apart
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+>Many Firms Like the Lower Rent<br> and Better Parking That's Just Outside<br>Pittsburgh's Central Business District</font></b><br>

<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>
<hr>


<P>
Thomas McKinney's problem was elevators. With ICF Kaiser International employees rotating from team to team for different projects, the employees spent a lot of time at his firm's offices in downtown Pittsburgh riding up and down. <P>The solution for McKinney, group senior vice president for ICF Kaiser, lay across the Monongahela River at Gateway View Plaza. The engineering, construction and consulting services firm will relocate in July, moving its Pittsburgh operation that includes 250 employees from four floors of Four Gateway Center to the new site on West Carson Street.<P>"We've signed a lease to rent 75,000 square feet on one floor in the new facility, which will offer a larger work environment that is more versatile than our current space on four floors," McKinney says.<P>"Our new space will offer great flexibility with respect to space planning and future growth. It also will accommodate more conference and proposal rooms, video conferencing, updated networking, cafeteria and workout center, nearly unlimited <P>storage space and free parking for employees," says McKinney.<P>That's a fairly lengthy list of reasons to move. And ICF Kaiser is not the only company settling in Pittsburgh's fringe real estate markets.<P>The downtown office market remained tight in recent months, so some firms have been content to set up offices on the North Side, Southside or in the Strip District. For one, locating just outside the central business district tends to be cheaper, as much as $3.50 less per square foot for Class A space. <P>"Cost is always a factor in this," says McKinney. "We will see a cost savings in moving out of the central business district. We needed to look for something that is more cost-effective."<P>"There's no question that the fringe areas are considerably lower [in price]," adds Duke Kingsley, executive vice president of real estate firm Grubb & Ellis/Axiom. "And the concessions will benefit the tenant."<P>Space availability also plays into the mix. For instance, the large amount of space at Gateway View Plaza was simply not available for ICF Kaiser downtown. In fact, it has been virtually impossible in recent months for any company to find contiguous blocks of Class A space over 20,000 square feet in the central business district.<P>So they look elsewhere.<P><P>The Fringe Markets<P>It's hopping outside the central business district.<P>Integra Financial, currently set to be acquired by Cleveland-based National City Bank, was an early mover across the rivers. In 1993, it relocated mortgage and data processing operations at space formerly occupied by Sears at Allegheny Center.<P>Last summer, telecommunications giant AT&T consolidated part of its regional operation in 64,000 square feet of space at Station Square's Commerce Court. Wesco, an electrical equipment supplier that spun out of Westinghouse Electric Corp., took 53,500 square feet at the same location.<P>"We've definitely seen an increase in absorption rates for these fringe markets," says Jeffrey Ackerman, vice president of Arnheim & Neely Inc. "This is attractive space for engineering firms or companies that needed space to house back-office operations. It is a very attractive alternative."<P>So much so that at presstime, several credit card companies were looking at the city's fringe markets as a possible location for phone centers, according to Ackerman.<P>The average cost for Class A space in the fringe markets was slightly over $18 per square foot, compared to $21 to $22 in the central business district. Spread that per-foot savings over 30,000 square feet and it adds up.<P>That's primarily why fringe market growth becomes more obvious every day. On the North Side, for instance, the influx of office workers mixes nicely with tourists visiting attractions such as the Warhol Museum and Carnegie Science Center, making sidewalks much more crowded than a decade ago.<P>"It's improving," says Glen Schultz, an architect with Williams Trebilcock  Whitehead, a firm that's been on the North Side since 1959 and in its current space - a nicely renovated turn-of-the-century warehouse just off the Ninth Street Bridge - for 12 years.<P>"With the Warhol Museum, the SMS [Engineering] building and others, there are a lot of people around during the day," Schultz says. "It's a pretty active community. That's really the sense, it's a community."<P>The five-story, $6 million SMS Engineering facility sits across the street from the Warhol Museum near the Seventh Street Bridge, right next to where Alcoa has proposed building its $20 million world headquarters. The new Alcoa building, to be located on a 2-acre riverfront site between the Seventh Street and Ninth Street bridges, will house about 550 headquarters employees. Another 250 Alcoa workers located at Two Allegheny Center, also on the North Side, are staying at that facility. <P>An added plus for the North Side will be $6.5 million in infrastructure improvements the city promised in conjunction with the Alcoa project.<P><P>Back Downtown   <P>There are those who simply cannot leave the central business district, such as the corporate law firms in the city. But that doesn't mean these firms are without flexibility.<P>Even businesses as image-conscious as law firms can consolidate critical, high-profile operations in Class A space while putting some back office operations in less plush, less expensive offices.<P>Buchanan Ingersoll, for instance, realized significant cost savings despite its move to upscale One Oxford Centre. About 320 attorneys, legal secretaries, legal assistants and support staff work at One Oxford, but another 60 back-office personnel work out of offices at 441 Smithfield Street.<P>"In fact," Managing Partner William Newlin says, "on a per-lawyer and cumulative basis, we will pay less rent during the next five years than we have the previous five years."<P>Grubb & Ellis, in its annual forecast on the regional real estate market, predicts new development of Class A space downtown sometime before the end of the year.<P>Last year's major deal, in which Lazarus vacated its store and planned construction of a new facility on Wood Street, tightened an already tight market. Blue Cross is taking most of the Lazarus space, and some office space is being lost at the new Lazarus site.<P>Kingsley says the financing industry is more amenable to funding a project for new Class A space since the market is so tight. And it doesn't hurt that the city is willing to offer incentives for development.<P>One thing is for sure: As the market remains tight, rental rates will slowly climb and concessions will be a thing of the past<P>





