<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Supplement4.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>Regulation
</font><BR>
<font size=+1> Should We Believe Clinton's Promise<br> of a Kindler, Gentler OSHA 
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<P>
<hr>

The people sitting around the hearing room in the Dirksen Senate Office Building liked the sound of the words coming from Joe Dear's mouth. They hoped these words were coming from Dear's heart.<P>Dear, the assistant U.S. secretary of labor and head of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, was telling how the days of over-regulation by OSHA inspectors were long gone. He held up the standard OSHA poster that - by law - must hang in every workplace.<P>"Before, there was a $400 fine if you didn't have this poster hanging," Dear told a group of small business owners from Pennsylvania, who traveled by bus to Washington, D.C.<P>"In one year, we fined 5,000 businesses for not having this poster hanging," Dear told the group. "Not any more. If you don't have it hanging, we just hand you the poster and say, 'Please hang this up.' "<P>Dear's comments are a good sign, considering the chances for significant OSHA reform are growing slimmer; it appears there will not be enough votes in the House of Representatives to override a promised presidential veto. <P>In this election year, the Clinton administration is coddling the labor unions, so the president will stand hard against any reform the unions don't bless. And the unions don't bless much.<P>Milder reform may squeak through, but that would leave it to Dear and OSHA operatives to effectuate any significant changes in an agency that has long been an albatross for businesses large and small.<P>The only reform the White House will support beyond codification of OSHA's Voluntary Protection Program is Dear's plan to provide a defense for employers when trained employees deliberately disobey safety regulations. <P>"I'll meet you halfway," Dear told the small business owners, there in March as part of a lobbying effort organized by SMC/Pennsylvania Small Business. "I don't think we can go after the employee who is trained and properly equipped with safety equipment, yet disobeys safety regulations. What we can do is allow that to be an affirmative defense for the employer if the employer can prove it."<P>Businesses big and small rightfully argue that OSHA's role in the American workplace should be diminished. Today's workplace is much safer than in the past.<P>In a way, it seems the Clinton administration is pushing OSHA in much the same direction Gov. Tom Ridge is pushing the state's environmental regulators. Ridge wants environmental regulators to help employers comply, as opposed to pouncing on them when they don't. Ridge even dumped the old Department of Environmental Resources and replaced it with the Department of Environmental Protection.<P>The problem is this: Some die-hard environmental regulators still practice like they are working for the old DER. They  pounce.<P>We can probably expect the same  at the federal level, from some old-time OSHA regulators. Some will still inspect like they're getting paid a commission on the amount of fines levied against a company.<P>Joe Dear will tell us otherwise, and only years later will we know what truly transpired.<P>As Dear spoke in Washington that day, sitting about 10 yards away was U.S. Sen. Conrad Burn, a good ol' boy Republican from Montana who tells it like it is. Burn turned up his hearing aid so he wouldn't miss anything Dear was saying.<P>Burn's take: "They sure say the damnedest things in an election year, don't they?"<P>


<hr>

