<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><IMG border=0 align=left SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><BR>
<BR><FONT SIZE=+2>Tommy Fell Asleep<BR>But the Rest of Us Must Listen Closely When<BR>Entrepreneurial Opportunities Present Themselves</FONT SIZE>
<font size=+1></font><BR>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b>
<hr>


Tommy fell asleep. Because he is 4 and the meal was taking longer than usual, everyone accepted his lackluster response to the dinner conversation. If the chocolate ice cream didn't arouse him, exploring the creation of a burgeoning new industry certainly wasn't likely to waken the child.<P>The discussion that Tom missed was about the Pittsburgh Tissue Engineering Initiative, a comprehensive strategy to turn tissue growth into business opportunities. Dwindling federal dollars are converting researchers to entrepreneurs. From their fledgling operations at Carnegie Mellon or Pitt  Medical Center laboratories, tissue engineers hope to "privatize" research formerly the domain of the National Institute of Health. <P>Tommy's sleepy response to all of this unfortunately reflects Pittsburgh's typical attitude toward entrepreneurial endeavors. Yawn. A few eyelids may flutter, but generally, our risk-adverse community snores rather than roars. An exception to this rule, the tissue engineering initiative has the potential to create a whole new industry. <P>The mastermind of this effort is a brilliant man whose unassuming nature obscures his intellect, Dr. Peter Johnson, a.k.a. Tommy's dad.<P>After a frustrating year of being a one-man band fueled solely by vision and conviction, Johnson is convinced that Pittsburgh can lead the charge to build a $400-billion-a-year industry. <P>A potential impetus to spur this growth, the tissue engineering initiative is Johnson's brainchild. Through the advancement and commercialization of tissue engineering and related technology, the initiative seeks to pair researchers and academicians with entrepreneurs. With this marriage of business acumen and academic prowess, the PTEI hopes to enable this region to build upon its distinctive competencies in healthcare, specifically, organ transplantation. New companies and new jobs are bound to result.<P>Motivated by the potential for personal financial gain, this type of cooperative economic development is as important as other espoused cooperative efforts. The anticipated return from consolidating the region's economic development agencies pales in comparison to the return this community could realize from the PTEI.<P>Like Tommy, most Pittsburghers fall asleep when big ideas are discussed. They miss the best part of the meal. <P>Wake up and smell the potential. Nurturing the Peter Johnsons of this area is like fanning a spark. Eventually the spark bursts into a flame that emits tremendous energy. <P>Life is too short for us to be so shortsighted.<P>


<hr><BR><BR><BR>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

