<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>The Outside Edge
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>If You Own a Family Business,
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Get Some Advice From Outside the Family</FONT><br>
 <i>By Joseph E.Morando
</b></i>

<HR>


Without a doubt, the single best business decision I've made in the last 30 years."<P> A new strategic alliance with a customer or supplier? A new program of international expansion? How about "C. none of the above." The business decision this real-life family business owner is referring to involves nothing new at all. He simply took advantage of a resource that has been there all along and is required by law - his board of directors.<P>Prior to restructuring, this family business board consisted of the usual suspects - family members, two employees and the corporate attorney. These were people who either were incapable of contributing anything to the business or were knowledgeable contributors to the business already.<P>Most family business boards resemble this company's former board. The structure is popular, because it is convenient and comfortable. When and if the board meets, it does not challenge the CEO/owner's decisions. <P>Without an active outside board, his company is surely missing business opportunities that could enhance its market position.<P>Most business owners I talk to object to an outside board because "nobody knows my business as well as me." This is true, but irrelevant.<P>The board is not another layer of day-to-day management. It is not there to give advice on how to make a widget better or faster. The board's role is to be involved in major decisions and strategic issues and to act as a reviewing body for management decisions.<P>Another common objection to the use of an outside board is a concern over loss of control. This concern is generally unfounded. Although the CEO reports to the board, the board in turn reports to the shareholders.  So a board cannot exert any greater control beyond the controlling shareholders. Ultimately, it is the controlling shareholders who have the final say in any decision.<P>Obviously, if the business owner is not willing to listen to the counsel of the outside board, the board may as well not exist. In the end, however, the typical family business board cannot exert final control.<P>Who should be on the board? An effective board is composed of non-self-interested, risk-taking peers. Directors of effective boards are usually successful business people who have no vested economic interest in the company. A company's specific needs should also be considered in selecting directors. For example, if overseas expansion is under consideration, the obvious choice is an executive whose company has already taken this step. <P>Other family business owners, particularly of larger businesses, often make excellent directors. In addition to the seasoned business advice they can offer, they also understand the importance of the emotional family issues which are unique to mixing family and business.<P>Putting qualified outsiders on the board will also lend critical objectivity.  It is almost impossible for an employee or company attorney to be completely objective, perhaps running the risk of offending their meal ticket.  <P>On the other hand, a qualified outside director has only one reason to be involved - he sincerely wants to help.  Thus, he is willing to look the CEO/owner in the eye and tell him exactly what he thinks. This objectivity is critical in all business matters.<P>It is extremely difficult for a business owner to be objective when evaluating his or her children. It can be gutwrenching to choose one child over another as the ultimate successor. Having a group of independent,   objective directors involved makes     the whole process less stressful for all parties and significantly increases the odds of a sound business judgment being made.<P>Who should not be on the board? Outside advisors such as accountants, attorneys, bankers, etc., who are paid for their advice. It is not necessary to have them as directors. The same is true of employees.<P>Putting in a truly legitimate outside board of directors is a major cultural change for any family business. <P>Most business owners have operated in a secretive and unexamined environment for so long that the thought of opening up to an outside board of directors is scary and uncomfortable. <P>I am not so naive to think that this article alone will make you business owners run out and set up a board. Perhaps you think a board may be beneficial when your successors are at the helm, but not while you are in charge. Most of you will stick with the comfort of the status quo. Just hope your competition does too.<P><P>Joseph E. Morando is a partner with Arthur Andersen in Pittsburgh.<P>

<hr>


<P>


<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

