<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>
</i></b>

<HR>

<H2>Everyone Should Read This Diary</H2><P>Anita Brattina tells a story that probably sounds familiar to quite a few working professionals.<P>"I had a new boss, and my job description was being dismantled a little more every day," Brattina writes in her recently released "Diary of a Small Business Owner" (Amacom, $21.95).<P>"The climate at work had really been getting worse over the last year. I felt less and less control over my department. The idea of running my own company with no bosses, no board of directors and no political gamesmanship was more alluring."<P>The rest was history, so to speak, which Brattina lays out nicely in this first-person account of her evolution: from employee to start-up business owner, and then finally to the point where her Pittsburgh firm - 11-year-old Direct Response Marketing -  eclipsed annual sales of $1 million.<P>By early spring, the book was in its third printing.<P>One reason for the demand: in each chapter, tucked amidst detailed diary entries, are "Lessons Learned." <P>A sampling:<P>l	Lesson No. 17: Rising Above the Basic Need for Money: "Somehow I had to learn that it was okay to make more money than my parents made, more than my friends, more than the sum of our monthly expenses. ... Once I set my sights on growing the business large enough to support a well-paid staff, pension and health benefits, enough money in reserves for slow times, and a paycheck I could be proud of, then the numeric goals changed. It was easier to set my sights on building a company that did $1 million, $5 million, $10 million in gross annual sales."<P>l	Lesson No. 39: Hiring the Next Person in Line: "In more than one instance, I made hasty hiring decisions because we were so understaffed. ... I seemed to hire anyone who fell into my radius within a few days of the position being created. Looking back, I realize that if I had simply forced myself to put an ad in the Sunday newspaper, I probably could have had a choice of more experienced people. But I never thought I had the luxury of time."<P>l	Lesson No. 52: Going National: "The way we got the national accounts still started locally. It was because I called on the local sales office of these national companies and did successful local projects. Then I started talking to the regional manager, national man-ager ... and so on."   <P>Who says you can't learn from  others' mistakes?<h2>More Healthcare:Cost Cuts vs. Health</H2>      <P>Most people have felt the effects of healthcare's move to managed care and the cost-cutting that has gone hand-in-hand.<P>Now this: a recent study says HMOs that steer their patients to cheaper prescription drugs are actually increasing the cost of care in the long run, because some of these people are getting sicker.<P>The study challenges the belief that cheaper medicines, such as generics or older formulations, reduce costs without degrading quality of care.<P>As restrictions on drug choices increase, "researchers found more patient visits to physicians, more emergency room visits and more hospitalizations, all of which would likely lead to an increase in medical costs,'' says the study, conducted by the Institute for Clinical Outcomes Research in Salt Lake City.<P>The message: Researchers argue that health plans must pay more attention to a patient's overall treatment program, not just to the individual components of care, like the cost of drugs. That's funny, we thought coordination was a benefit that plans promised.<P>The study was published in the American Journal of Managed Care. It covered 13,000 members of six health maintenance organizations in various areas of the country, and was paid for by the HMOs and by the National Pharmaceutical Council, which represents drug companies. The HMOs agreed to cooperate only if they could retain anonymity.<P>More than 125 million Americans belong to HMOs or other health plans that require or encourage doctors and patients to use drugs from a preferred list, called a formulary.<P>Health plans can make more money by sharply limiting their formularies to just a handful of drugs in each category, because they can demand big price discounts from the drugmakers for the right to be in the formulary.<P>The researchers say patients covered by plans with the most restrictive formularies used other medical services twice as often as patients with no such restrictions.<P>Patient advocacy groups say the study findings don't surprise them.<H2>I'm Going on Vacation ...to Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania'</H2><P>This month, ER discusses the importance of tourism to the regional economy (see Resuscitating the Region on page 16). <P>And if you think Pittsburgh doesn't rate as a tourist destination, check out the following excerpts from Washington Post travel writer James Yenckel's review of Pittsburgh as a tourist destination:<P>As an avid sightseer, I'm a collector of curiosities - that is, offbeat sights (or sites) that are unique or at least very rare. So I was pleased to discover, early into a recent first-time visit, that the city of Pittsburgh is a treasure trove of the unusual. <P>In pursuit, mostly on foot, I explored its historically rich streets with increasing enthusiasm, acquiring many intriguing additions to my mental collection. <P>To name but a few: <P>l	Cinderella's glass palace, which is the impression I got anyway of the soaring PPG Building - a 40-story glass skyscraper in a modern Gothic style with fairy-tale towers, a lush inside winter garden and a regal courtyard. This is the kind of place that a princess who owes her marriage and throne to a glass slipper would build.   <P>l	The Stephen Foster Memorial, acclaimed - as a brochure puts it - as "the world's only concert hall, museum, research library and archive devoted to an American composer." Foster's cherished melodies are playing while you examine memorabilia from his short but productive life that began in Pittsburgh. <P>l	A permanent exhibit called "Eating" at the Carnegie Science Center, which overlooks the Ohio River. An informative, often humorous examination of international dining habits, it is sponsored by the H.J. Heinz Co. Foundation, an offshoot of the old Pittsburgh firm famous for its ketchup. <P>l	The Monongahela and Duquesne inclines - twin thrill rides from the past. They still do useful duty as public transportation in hoisting riders up the steep green slope of Mt. Washington for panoramic views of the city and its three great rivers - the Allegheny, the Monongahela and the Ohio. <P>Ethnically diverse, Pittsburgh is a city of close-knit neighborhoods - about 90 by one count - where many of the old customs (as well as the bakeries and cafes) still flourish. At the top of the Monongahela Incline, which was an easy walk from my downtown hotel, I stepped out onto Shiloh Street, a quiet little Mt. Washington byway that seemed decades removed from the urban bustle far below. Inside Knell's Bakery [now out of business], I treated myself to a sweet strawberry tart with definite Old European origins. <P>To add to the city's flavor, Pittsburgh enjoys an unusual variety of sophisticated cultural organizations, such as the Carnegie Museum of Art and the Pittsburgh Symphony, a well-respected, much-recorded orchestra. And the city's universities, among them the giant University of Pittsburgh, Carnegie Mellon University and Duquesne University, en-liven the sidewalks and the night life. The current hot spot on the South Side (south of the Monongahela River) is East Carson Street, a turn-of-the-century commercial strip several blocks long lined with funky shops, small bookstores, eateries and pubs.<P>I spent two days in Pittsburgh, and even by hurrying I could not take in all it offers.<h2>'... And Maybe I'll Make a Stop in Fayette County'</h2><P>As we point out in this month's Resuscitating the Region story (page 16), tourism is a recession-proof industry of which we must get our share.<P>Long before the state made its recent push with tourism, Fayette County - the rural, somewhat mountainous county that borders West Virginia - was already building tourism into its strategic plan.<P>It was a wise move, considering Fayette County is home to the Nemacolin Woodlands and Seven Springs resorts, whitewater-rafting hot spot Ohiopyle State Park and Frank Lloyd Wright's architectural masterpiece, Fallingwater.<P>What's lesser known is the county's potential to attract tourists interested in American history. For instance, there's Fort Necessity, where George Washington nearly ruined his military career by surrendering the fort during the French and Indian War. <P>There's also the National Road Heritage Park. The National Road was the first federally funded highway in the United States, and the only one entirely built by the federal government. When completed in 1852 (construction began in 1811), the road ran for over 600 miles from Cumberland , Md., to Vandalia, Ill., and was the first major artery of the great American westward expansion.<P>Fayette County's Heritage Development Plan, prepared by the Fay-Penn Economic Development Council and the Fayette Heritage Committee, projects significant opportunity to develop tour packages that will link heritage sites to lodging, camping, restaurants and other services.<P>With the tourism comes the merchandising opportunities that - combined with promotional materials - keep the visitors coming back.<h2>Creating Interest in Commercial Checking Accounts</h2><P> The Federal Reserve Act prohibits banks from paying interest on what it defines as demand deposit accounts -commonly known as free-access commercial checking accounts. The result? Companies that carry large daily balances in their checking accounts accrue no interest on that money unless they sweep the unused balance into other accounts each business day.<P>In a typical sweep arrangement, idle balances are transferred daily to money market deposit accounts, certificates of deposit, bank mutual funds, trust accounts or commercial paper. The banks charge a fee - sometimes heavy - for the service, which for years was exclusive to big business.<P>And old banking habits die hard. The easy money to be made on commercial checking accounts has kept many banks from making an aggressive move into cash sweeps despite account erosion, some executives say. In recent years, however, banks began feeling more competition from nonbanks that can offer similar services to the small and midsized companies whose yearly revenues range from $2.5 million to $25 million.<P>One suburban Pittsburgh firm, BusinessAmerica/Pittsburgh Metro East, is offering the Commercial Banking Service Link Program, which reduces or eliminates service charges while allowing the customer to accrue interest on the entire account balance, not just the unused balance.<P>"It turns what traditionally has been a cost of doing business into an income generator," says BusinessAmerica principal Rick Rohac, whose office is in Murrysville.<P>Some savvy small business owners have known they can collect interest on the checking accounts and have demanded sweep arrangements from their banks. Many others, however, mistakenly believe their commercial checking accounts are drawing interest, when in reality they're not.<P>Many banks award what are known as earnings credit - a dollar amount that appears on bank statements. To many businesses, it appears as though the dollar amount is real money. In reality, the amount can be used only to offset bank service charges. It never turns into cash for the account holder.<P>A comparison: a firm with an average daily balance of $62,000 would earn about $152 worth of earnings credit monthly, compared to $286 in interest at a rate of 5.5 percent via Service Link. That's $3,434 annually.<P>



