<TITLE> EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Changing Strategies</b> 
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Ridge's Second Budget is Business Friendly,<BR>But Takes a Different Approach From Last Year                

</font><BR>
<i>By Jim Strader
</i>

<HR>

<P>
Tom Ridge made his budget debut with a package of tax cuts for Pennsylvania businesses amounting to more than $280 million.<P>But that was a year ago. This year,  Ridge's encore was awaited eagerly by business. <P>How would it play? Would the governor get a curtain call or the hook? Right now, it's too early to tell. <P>Ridge's latest budget proposal offers a decidedly different approach toward the business community. Gone is the big tax break, replaced with other forms of tax relief and a new look and new name on the marquee at the state commerce agency.<P>Ridge's efforts last year, much applauded by Pennsylvania businesses, also had the effect of quietly eliminating a revenue surplus, which the outgoing Casey administration says amounted to about $400 million. So in his latest budget proposal, presented for legislative and public consideration in February - with a June 30 deadline - Ridge has less to work with in the way of cash. <P>Nevertheless, the administration continues to push its business-friendly agenda in other ways.<P>Topping the list of benefits for business is a $15 million plan to offer a tax credit for job creation. The administration pushes the idea as a no-lose proposition, saying the $1,000 per job tax credit would be available only for new jobs.<P>"Taxpayers won't spend a cent unless there is a family-sustaining job to show for it," the governor says.<P>But critics say the fine print in the proposal - a minimum of 25 new jobs required before a company can claim the first $1,000 tax credit - means it is geared toward bigger operations, and would not help small businesses.<P>Democrats in the House of Representatives, itching to get back in power but still one vote shy of a majority, were quick to jump on the governor's idea, calling it a "tax incentive that isn't an incentive." They assert that the average Pennsylvania business employs 20 workers. Larger companies are downsizing, the Democrats say, while small businesses produce the most jobs and deserve attention from Ridge.<P>Ridge's budget plan contains two other direct tax cuts aimed at businesses. One initiative would reduce the capital stock and franchise tax, and the other would eliminate the computer sales tax on the manufacturing, processing, agricultural and public utility sectors of the economy. <P>And in a move to make an indirect cut in the cost of doing business, Ridge used his budget speech to call on lawmakers to reform the workers' compensation system. <P>"We can no longer pretend that our workers' compensation system is helping our workers," Ridge told the assembled House and Senate members. "Tragically, ironically, the system we designed to help injured workers is now costing healthy workers their jobs."<P>A broader move laid out in Ridge's budget plan is the reorganization of the Department of Commerce, which he wants to convert into a new agency - the Department of Economic and Community Development. The Commerce proposal characterizes Ridge's main economic goals in the coming year. Like the spending proposal, the suggested departmental realignment is subject to legislative approval.<P>The plan involves folding <P>the Department of Community Affairs - long the funnel for the "walking around money'' grants Ridge targets for extinction - into the new department.<P>The governor also proposes a new business resource center and nearly doubled state spending for job training - money for regional "skills centers" to make training and educational programs more accessible. He also proposes  creating a "business retention" team to help spot and solve problems before companies move operations out of Pennsylvania.<P>The Ridge administration started a budget sales job right away, traveling across the state and speaking to groups with a stake in the outcome. And the governor - who speaks highly of <P>competition in corporate settings -found that competition squaring <P>off in the statehouse as budget <P>deliberations began. <P>As with many business propositions, the wide range of special interests chasing limited budget dollars means Ridge's plan is sure to be evaluated as much on its merits as on its politics<P>




