<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>



<P>
<B><I><font size=+2>Rich Engler</font></I></B></center><P>


<HR>
<b>
Name:		Khalid Raheem<BR>
Age:            43<BR>
Lives:          On the North Side of Pittsburgh<br>
Education:      University of Pittsburgh, 1982;<br>
                Public Administration/Psychology<BR>
Last Book Read: Waiting to Exhale<BR>
                by Terri McMillan<BR>
</B>            
<hr>

<P>
"You seem to have a drive-by shooting every day," a British businessman visiting  Pittsburgh commented to former county commissioner Tom Foerster last year. <P>Viewers of the evening news have perhaps noticed how frontloaded with abuse and murder it's become, compared to years ago. Through TV goggles, it really does seem that Pittsburgh has become ridden with crime and violence. <P>But while there's no denying that homicide and violent crime do exist, statistics show their levels have actually decreased in recent years. The National Institute of Justice attributes that in part to a decrease in gang activity - and in Pittsburgh, we can thank the Gang Peace Council for that. <P>It started in 1992 when a group of Muslim men, concerned with the devastating connection between drugs and gangs and the violence sweeping our neighborhoods, decided to confront the problem head on. <P>Khalid Raheem, head of that effort, knows firsthand what it's like to be caught up in gangs and the criminal justice system - and uses his background as a bridge to reach young people now enveloped in gang activity. <P>This month, they hold their annual Gang Peace Summit. Lydia Strohl talked with Raheem about Pittsburgh's gang activity, and how his group is attacking the problem.<P>Executive Report: What is the Gang Peace Council?<P>Khalid Raheem: The Gang Peace Council is a social service agency and social advocacy group dealing not only with gang- and drug-related violence but also the social causes contributing to young people participating in acts of drug- or gang-related violence. <P>ER: How did it start?<P>KR:  A group of Muslim brothers met every week and one problem that kept coming up was gang violence. Some of us having been more familiar with gang culture, some coming through the criminal justice system, we thought it was important to address it. <P>We decided to form a group that would focus on gang- and drug-related violence, working with young black kids in our neighborhoods, educating parents, professionals and people in the communities about gang violence. We started the Gang Peace Council.<P>Initially our membership was  exclusively Muslim. Now we have a very diverse membership of about 500.<P>ER: What did you do first?<P>KR: The most important thing initially was to educate the community. We held a series of Gang Awareness Seminars that I would facilitate. We would invite parents, other community leaders and activists, teachers and administrators. I would talk about the history of the gang culture in America, about gang prevention and intervention, specifically addressing certain groups. For instance, if I was talking to a group of parents, I would point out things they should be looking out for. If their child comes home wearing certain colors, if they look a certain way, have a certain disposition, if their school performance has fallen off drastically, if they're no longer interested in extra-curricular activities, but seem more prone to hang with some newfound friends that you know nothing about. I would talk about the different neighborhood rivalries that gave birth to contemporary gang culture. <P>Keep in mind, this was several years ago, so many people didn't know what it was to see a youngster wearing red flannel, blue flannel or all black, so we had to educate them. We had to teach people to read the walls - what it meant if they saw RIP, with an equal sign with somebody's name, with another equal sign with $500. That someone is not necessarily dead; that's a contract on that person's life for $500.<P>We had a tremendous response. <P>ER: What is the gang situation in Pittsburgh today?<P>KR: Not as bad as other parts of the country. Part of that is that the contemporary gang situation is not very old. We're talking about a culture that really came to the forefront in 1989. Whereas  in some of the major cities -  New York, L.A., Chicago - you're talking about a gang culture that goes back several generations and is deeply rooted.<P>There were Pittsburgh gangs in the '50s and '60s, but the gang culture today is markedly different. Then it was based on neighborhood affiliation. Violence was a fistfight. Guys probably drank an occasional beer, but there was no link between being a gang member and 'hustling,' selling drugs.  <P>The gang culture that we see now, we believe, is a direct result of the socioeconomic conditions that came to bear in the '80s. If you look at the gang migration, they really started to grow in those particular regions where you had economic deprivation. Where parents for the first time found themselves working two or three jobs. If you look at southwestern Pennsylvania, for example, once the steel industry collapsed a lot of economic hardship fell on families and communities, which made them ripe for gang penetration and drug penetration. If people were not as vulnerable, the Crips and Bloods would not have been able to move outside southern California. <P>And to make things even worse, somebody came up with crack cocaine. You can use it yourself, or sell part of it to supplement the income you're making at McDonald's, because you're not making $14 an hour working for U.S. Steel anymore.<P>You now have gangs throughout the city of Pittsburgh, North Side, East End, Greenfield, Homewood, Hazelwood and also the Mon Valley. <P>ER: Do you have any idea of the numbers that are involved?<P>KR:  No. Several hundred consider themselves to be gang members. Thousands more are affiliated with gang culture only because their neighborhood is. They wear gang colors, and are obligated in many ways to support one another. But they are not hard core 'gang bangers,' gang members.<P>ER: How did the gang culture take root in Pittsburgh?<P>KR:  It started in Homewood, as an outgrowth from some gangs that did exist, predicated on old neighborhood rivalries. About 1989, some people from Homewood came into contact with people who knew something about the gang culture, and they in turn brought that information back to Homewood and used it as an opportunity to organize younger boys to facilitate the drug business. I think they saw it as an opportunity to make some quick and fast money. Juveniles could not be prosecuted the same way as adults, so juveniles could be used.<P>Also, it gave these young adults a tremendous sense of power; they would give the teenagers gifts, advice, look out for them. These young drug dealers, future leaders of the New Jack gangs, started undermining parental authority. It opened a floodgate.<P>We have a deeply rooted gang culture here in Pittsburgh. It has not yet become a serious generational gang culture, only because it is so new. <P>ER: Obviously, one key to success is respect. How have you gained that?<P>	KR: Part of it is just being honest. Another part has to do with your willingness to listen, your willingness to connect. And last but not least, it could have something to do with who you are. I'm part of them. Based on my past, coming up through the gang culture, through the criminal justice system, I can relate. What he's going through, I've already been through.<P>ER: What does the gang provide  to these young people?<P>KR: It provides protection. It provides a sense of identity. It can provide an opportunity to make money; illegally, but nevertheless, an opportunity.<P>For some it's a boost in self-esteem, because now they can finally say they belong to something that is respected, that is revered, or that is feared.<P>We do not seek to destroy gangs. The mission of the GPC is to transform the essence of gang culture. To move gang bangers along the road to becoming just gang members, and from gang members to productive human beings. It takes a lot of work.<P> A gang banger is someone who is actively engaged in a lifestyle that is destructive to his family and community, involved with drug using, drug selling, violence, murder, robbery, disrespect of elders, seniors, children.<P>A gang member is someone who has this affiliation because of his neighborhood, because of his past, but is willing to move away from those self-destructive behaviors, look at other options, and make some commitment to change. If we hadn't taken some steps, in 10 or 15 years we'd have a generational situation, where people would grow up not knowing any options but the gang.<P>We do conflict resolution, crisis intervention. We have summits, truces. But we need permanent organizational things that people can look to: for example, businesses that are owned and operated by people from the community, former and current gang members who see owning a business as a viable option to doing robberies and selling drugs. Mentoring programs and rites of passage programs, which provide a viable option to being jumped in, or sexed in, to your neighborhood gang, or having to commit some kind of atrocity, like a drive-by or a mugging, or a burglary to be part of your neighborhood gang, so it doesn't destroy you, or somebody else.<P>ER: Replacing the organizational tenets of the gang culture must be incredibly intensive work.<P>KR: Always. It's very difficult to get kids from rival neighborhoods and gangs to sit down and talk, because they've taken each other through a process of dehumanization. Like two opposing armies who've been brainwashed to not see one another as human beings - that's the same process many gang members go through. The enemy is not a human, so you can shoot, maim, rape or fire bomb them.<P>So we have to bring young people to the table, to recognize we're all human beings, and we have a lot more in common than in difference.<P>ER: It is most often this disregard and sense of lawlessness that the media portrays of the gang member,  implying a disregard for human life in general. Is that an accurate depiction?<P>KR: No. That's a stereotype. Many times, the violent acts commited by gang members are acts of self-defense and retaliation. And often, these acts are done under the influence of drugs and alcohol. I'm not talking about violent acts connected to crimes of property, like robbery. <P>The first gangsters actually came from the Old West - Billy the Kid, the Earp brothers. The first gang to wear bandanas were the Outlaws. We have to break the stereotypes.<P>A young black male can be coming from the gym, coming from school, and because he has a hoodie on, he's tall, he's angular, people say, 'He's a gang member.' He's not a gang member, he's a child. He's on his way to doing all the things teenagers, black or white, do. <P>But it's very difficult to get the media to back off that, because America is profit-driven. If the newspaper or magazine or radio station can sell more advertising by constantly playing on how dangerous it is out there, how hiding in every corner and crevice is the boogie man, black male, Latino male, gang member, then they're going to continue to poke that. <P>I can tell you about white boys that are Crips and Bloods. I can tell you about the Irish Lynch Mob, based in Greenfield, or the Wood's Run Crips, an all-white gang on the North Side across from the penitentiary. I can take you to Hawaii and introduce you to Asian gangs. I can take you to the Native American reservation, the New Jack culture is there. The gang culture now is geared toward youth, whether they're black, brown, red, white or yellow. It even transcends gender; there are girl gang members. It's a class issue.<P>I've never seen so many people in the city of Pittsburgh homeless. I've never seen so many people standing on street corners, begging, who don't have jobs. Elderly people working in Burger King,  who need extra to make it. <P>And now we have generations of young people coming up who see this, and  think, 'Hey - you graduated from high school, you graduated from college, and you're still not making it. What are my chances?' Some of them have decided on a life of crime. It's sad.<P>ER: What do you tell that kid?<P>KR: I tell that person to make a commitment to do what is right, and not what is expedient. I tell that person that for them to do anything other than what is right is to basically emulate the very people that they criticize. <P>When I talk with young African Americans, I ask them why European people enslaved people from Africa. They say, 'The white man didn't like us,' or 'The white man didn't understand us.' And I say, well, that could very well be true, but the bottom line is that at that particular point, slavery was one of the most economically profitable businesses you could get in. So the reason white people sold black people was that they could make tremendous profit.<P>Then I switch it back to them, and say, 'When you decide to sell drugs, most of them are going to people from your own neighborhood. You're basically functioning off of the same logic that the slave master used.' You have to rise above it, make a serious commitment to change, and then  come together and change the forces that created the madness.<P>ER: The work that you do validates the gang culture. That bothers some people. What's your response?<P>KR: First of all, the gang culture is real, whether they want it to be or not. We don't validate the gang culture, but we do validate people's social reality. When I do a home visit, I'm not saying 'Check this out, home boy, it's okay for you to be a Crip.' <P>I come in and try to find out what's going on with that young man, and how we can get him away from that. But in order to get to that point I have to recognize his social reality.<P>I may be called to talk to a group of kids who are about to fight each other. We go to the school. We hold conflict resolution sessions. We get these young men, or women, or both, not to kill each other, at least not on school grounds. They've already identified themselves with the gang culture. The best we can do is intervene so they don't murder each other, so perhaps at some point we can get the transition from gang banger, to gang member, to regular human being. <P>ER: Will the proposed changes in the public schools affect your work?<P>KR: It's going to make our work a lot more difficult. I hope it's modified. If not, we're going to be bringing students together from neighborhoods with serious blood feuds. We are concerned for the safety of the young people, and school personnel. Young people can't be expected to learn if there's always a threat of imminent violence.<P>What I hope to do is to educate the educators. A young person will not listen to you if they're trying to tell you, 'Well, hey, I hurt, because my friend got his brains blown out last night, and I saw it. So I'm acting up at school today. I'm slouching, cussing in class because I hurt.' If you say, 'Go over there and sit down.' It's like 'Your pain is not real for me.' If a teacher is not willing to recognize and validate the pain, they can never steer that child in a positive direction. <P>ER: Does the business community have a role in this?<P>KR: Consider hiring young people from communities that are riddled with gang violence. Don't turn them away because they're from a certain zip code. Don't turn them away because they are black, or male, or wear their hair in a certain style. <P>Last but not least, you can support the Gang Peace Council, either with cash or with other resources.<P>


<hr>

