<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Salut
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>Corked Off at Restaurants That Mark Wine<BR>Up Out of Sight? Try the Carlton Instead
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<p>

<hr>
If you have a grateful heart, show it by directing the bearer to the best wine in town, and pray, let not this highest point of sacred friendship be performed slightly, but go about it with all due deliberation and care, as holy priests to sacrifice.<P>		- John Wilmot<P>Second Earl of Rochester, English poet, in a letter to diplomat <P>Henry Savile in 1673<P><P>he Carlton, in One Mellon Bank Center, the wine list is longer than the menu. About 10 times longer, in fact. And another curious thing: the prices. A bottle of Dominus Meritage  for $52.30. Frog's Leap Merlot, $31.09. Gloria Ferrer Chardonnay, $26.99. What's going on? Savvy restaurateur Kevin Joyce woke up and smelled the sediment.<P>"As restaurateurs, we're always schooled that you have to make certain numbers with the beverage," says Joyce. "But with wine, that doesn't make sense. Because that pushes people into lesser wines in a restaurant. When they're eating great food, that's when you should let them enjoy great wine."<P>So the Carlton marks up every bottle of wine just $10. Exactly. And because he makes the same profit on every bottle, his mission is to look for the best wine in taste and value, not markup-ability.<P>It's a bold move, but his customers love it. And it wasn't his first. <P>Eleven years ago, Kevin Joyce opened up the Carlton - named for the Carlton House Hotel that once stood on the corner of Forbes Avenue and Grant Street - for Levy Restaurants, a Chicago company.<P>Last summer, Joyce, who had risen to a partner in the company, traveling constantly to open new markets for Levy, decided to make a change. He was tired of traveling 37, 38, 39 weeks a year. He didn't spend enough time with his five kids. And he had lost track of his other baby, the Carlton. So he bought it.<P>And he's made a few changes. To complement the 200-wine list, he holds monthly wine dinners, featuring themes or visits from vintners, hand-picked wines and special dishes. The regular menu also changes frequently, depending on what's fresh from purveyors, such as one who sends fish direct from the Atlantic each Friday.<P>"Not everything changes every day, but it allows us to rely on seasonal food and challenges our cooks to stay active," says Joyce. <P>One night, we tried the lobster cod cake with basil beurre blanc for starters. Though thick, it was perfectly cooked, with a gentle, rich flavor. To follow, an endive salad, which was topped with a honey Dijon vinaigrette, balancing its tartness, bleu cheese and walnuts. And, in the dead of winter, ripe tomatoes.<P>Next, we chose swordfish, that night layered with crab, spinach, tomatoes, saffron cream and basil oil. The fillet was perfectly grilled, no flavor overpowered another. But in the veal portobello, the medallions sauteed in a  sundried tomato buerre blanc were tough. The Cabrillo bass was a bit bland, grilled and advertised with tangerine piccata butter - if you don't like heavy sauces, ask for it on the side. This place has a heavy lean toward butter and cream.<P>For lunch, more pastas and salads are added to the menu: The mushroom chicken salad was delicious, featuring sauteed seasonal mushrooms and grilled chicken with greens, red peppers and a sundried tomato vinaigrette. <P>The presentation and the service here are delightful, as is the rich, formal dining space. The coffee was sour, and one dessert - an apple tart - had a tasteless pudding-like base and a lardy, undercooked crust. The chocolate cappuccino torte, however, was food art. <P>A note of caution: Fridays and Saturdays are often packed, as Joyce offers free limos to cultural events. Likewise, hockey nights. Joyce admits that in the rush to put out timely food, it's not always their best product.<P>


<hr><P>


