<a href="../zine/0596.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Sports.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Sayonara</font><br><font size=+1>The Longer it Takes to Pass Workers' Comp <br>Reform, the More Business We Will Lose<br>
</font></B><i>By Henry Lipput</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>
Rob Rost's family has been running St. Charles Refractories since the 1970s. The company itself, located 60 miles north of Pittsburgh, has been in business for over 100 years and manufactures a ceramic that is used to bottom-pour steel. <P>However, this may be the company's last year in Pennsylvania. Rost, the current plant manager for St. Charles, is considering moving the company to Maryland because of the high price of workers' compensation premiums in Pennsylvania.  <P>"We have a facility in Maryland now," says Rost. "We don't make the exact same product, but I know the cost of doing business down there. It's so much cheaper - the savings on  insurance alone would pay for almost the complete move in just five months."<P>Rost is not alone: Business owners throughout Pennsylvania sing a familiar tune when the topic of workers' compensation comes up. Like Rost, they talk about the high premiums. And they complain about  abuse of the system by workers.  <P>"I have a couple of outstanding cases now that are ringing up some serious bills. It keeps adding to our premium," Rost says.   <P> Gov. Tom Ridge is seeking reform that will lower workers' compensation costs for employers while protecting the interests of injured workers. It's an issue  through which Ridge must tread carefully. He has business on one side and the unions and the plaintiffs' attorneys on the other side of the issue.<P>"There is no greater economic development tool - there is no greater investment the commonwealth can make to retain and create jobs - than to reform workers' compensation," says Ridge. The governor's proposals, if enacted, would add to other recent workers' compensation reforms, including the Act 44 legislation passed in 1993 and last year's state-mandated 9.43 percent rate reduction.  <P>Ridge's plan emphasizes five main principles. Keys to it include a timely return to the workforce of those capable of working and the payment of benefits only to legitimately injured workers. He also wants to ensure that benefit payments are commensurate with preinjury earnings so that workers do not earn more while receiving benefits than they did on the job. Another point calls for the reduction of costs associated with litigation and administration of claims. And finally, the governor wants to guarantee that reform savings will be passed through directly to the employers who pay the premium and benefit expenses. <P>Ridge says his principles stem from employers' common complaint that under the current workers' compensation system there are too many obstacles to getting a recovered worker back on the job.<P>Workers' compensation costs are cited as one of the main reasons that businesses leave Pennsylvania and are discouraged from locating here in the first place.  <P>"The governor wants to make sure that people get just payment to replace lost wages when they're hurt, but right now there are some loose factors in the system [so] that people get more than they should," says John Currie,  spokesman for the state Department of Labor and Industry. <P>Cash pay-outs to injured workers are, by law, usually two-thirds of the employee's salary.  According to statistics from the Department of Commerce, Pennsylvania workers' compensation costs are notably higher than elsewhere in the country - including our bordering states. <P>"Workers' compensation definitely costs more in Pennsylvania, in almost all categories, than the six neighboring states," says Currie. "We still have too high medical costs, even though we're cutting them, and our cash payments are still high."<P>But Currie also had some good news: work-related injuries in Pennsylvania have decreased over the last five years, from 158,000 claims in 1990 to 130,093 in 1994. <P>"It's slowly, incrementally going down," he says.  "People are paying more attention to safety, and the     costs are getting so high, the compa-nies and employees are taking more responsibility."  <P>One recent nationwide survey found that businesses in the rest of the country have seen their workers' compensation costs flatten or even decline in the last few years due to workers' compensation cost-containment initiatives, primarily worker safety programs and case management.<P>But this information may come too late to change the fate of St. Charles Refractories. <P> "The state is definitely trying to improve," says Rost, "but I have a problem that's long-existing here, and I see I can move the whole facility down to Maryland and save this much money."  <P>Just one more business saying so long, Pennsylvania. Thanks for the memories.<P>


<hr>

