<HEAD>
<TITLE> Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Law.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Licensed to Sit</font><br><font size=+1>Would Sports Fans in Pittsburgh Pay Extra Money<br>Just for the Right to Buy a Ticket?<br>
</font></B><i>By Bill Modoono</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>

The first reaction of the typical western Pennsylvania sports fan is the natural one: It can't happen here.<P>Oh, sure the concept of Personal Seat Licenses, or PSLs, may be a revenue-producing trend sweeping pro sports across the nation, but it would not work here. Can you imagine paying money simply for the right to buy tickets to the Steelers, Penguins or Pirates? Never happen?<P>Don't be so sure. In fact, some experts argue that if Pittsburgh fans really love their teams, then they should embrace this concept.<P>This much is certain: In sports, the cost of doing business as well as the cost of keeping up with your rivals are ever-increasing. The franchises that stay afloat - both on the field and in terms of money-making - are the ones that are most creative in terms of finding new revenue streams. The old Pittsburgh way - strict fiscal prudence - is not enough these days.<P>The money-maker of choice, in markets large and small, is the new stadium. Baseball teams want to emulate Baltimore's Camden Yards, which has become a mecca for fans in its short existence. Football teams want to emulate Dallas' Texas Stadium, with its corporate sponsorship and theme-park atmosphere, which is altering the experience of going to games.<P>Paying for the stadiums is a different matter. With state and local money tighter and taxpayers and big corporations in less generous moods, pro teams have looked elsewhere for financing. For several National Football League teams, PSLs saved the day.<P>In Charlotte, for instance, the expansion Panthers financed a facility that will open this fall primarily through PSLs. Ninety percent of its 72,500-seat capacity stadium has been bought by fans, who paid from $600 to $5,400 for lifetime rights to purchase season tickets to Panthers' games. In Oakland, the Raiders were lured back to their ancestral home by the promise of revenue generated by the sale of 11-year PSLs that range from $250 to $4,000, depending on the location of the seat.<P>In both cases, Charlotte and Oakland did not have teams, so fans understood that a willingness to purchase PSLs could help them get one. Nashville is doing the same thing to lure the Oilers out of Houston.<P> In Pittsburgh, things won't be as simple. The team most in need of a new stadium is the Pirates, but PSLs have no track record in baseball. "Really it's an untested idea in baseball," says Ethan Green, assistant editor of Team Marketing Report, and an expert on PSLs. "But there is a strong possibility it could work. It depends on the pricing. Actually, it could be more of a value for the fan, because in baseball, they're getting more games."<P>Mark Schneider, chairman of Pittsburgh's Stadium Authority, says the San Francisco Giants are attempting to finance a new stadium through PSLs, but it's too early to say if that will work. He believes the key to a new Pirates stadium lies in finding the right location and then getting strong financial backing from the state.<P>As for the Steelers, Schneider says, "No one's done a PSL in an existing stadium." But, regardless if the Pirates get a new stadium or not, the Steelers have expressed interest in making more money from Three Rivers Stadium. The team's lease expires in 1999 and, as Art Modell recently proved, NFL owners have options.<P>What the Steelers could do, Schneider says, is sell more expensive "club seating" in premium seat locations and give club members access to a private facility - much like the Igloo Club at the Civic Arena - reserved parking and other amenities. The money raised through club seats would not need to be shared with the rest of the league and could be spent on such modern necessities as free agents.<P>If the Pirates get a new stadium, and the Steelers want to reconfigure or expand Three Rivers, it is conceivable that PSLs could be used to pay for it. Green sees PSLs as the "fairest way" to do such things.<P>"I don't look at it as a tax. Really, PSLs take the tax burden off the taxpayers who have nothing to do with the sports teams. With PSLs, the fans of the teams pay to build the stadiums."<P>Actually, a plan similar to PSLs already exists in this market. Pitt, like a number of major colleges, requires scholarship fund donations from fans who want to buy the best seats to basketball and football games.<P>Would fans support pro teams beyond the simple ticket price? Who knows. Just don't say it can't happen.<P>

<hr>

