<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Sports.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>The Firing Line</font><br><font size=+1>Mishandling a Legitimate Employee Termination<br>May Push the Employee to File a Lawsuit<br>
</font></B><i>By Jim Urban</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>

When a Connecticut hospital let go of one of its social work managers a few years back, security guards met the woman at her office and escorted her to the parking lot, leading her past co-workers who stared in disbelief.<P>Her co-workers thought the way the termination was handled was unjust. So did the civil court jury that awarded the employee $105,000 for the emotional distress she suffered as a result of being paraded past friends and co-workers when she was terminated.<P>The Connecticut case is one of several in recent years in which a fired employee has pursued a lawsuit or collected damages over the manner in which he or she was fired.<P>Other examples:<P>l	In New Jersey, middle managers for a major pharmaceutical company fired a sales representative inside a diner, then followed him home and retrieved the employee's company car and drug samples. A jury awarded him $8 million in punitive damages.<P>l	In Minnesota, a fired healthcare worker sued for defamation after his supervisor made him pack his belongings in view of other employees, then escorted the employee to his car. An appeals court overturned a lower court's dismissal of the defamation count, paving the way for the defamation count to proceed to trial.<P>These cases show how fired employees can and will sue over the way they were fired. But more importantly, the cases illustrate how an employer can mishandle an otherwise legal employee termination and motivate the employee to consult an attorney. In the end, the employer may spend thousands of dollars to defend a lawsuit that might not have occurred if the termination was handled properly.<P>"In advising clients on how to terminate employees, I've always told them to do it with fairness and dignity," says attorney John E. Lyncheski, head of the labor and employment law practice at Cohen & Grigsby in Pittsburgh. "I've since added the word 'class.' <P>"If you effectuate a termination with fairness, dignity and class, you are ahead of the game," Lyncheski says.<P>Rarely, Lyncheski and other attorneys say, will an employee sue solely over the way he or she is fired. Quite often, however, it's the way the termination is carried out that motivates the employee to seek legal counsel. <P>"You have to be sensitive to how the employee is going to react, or you are going to spawn a lawsuit," says Clare Gallagher, a partner at Doepken Keevican & Weiss in Pittsburgh.<P><P>Some Common Mistakes<P>A crucial part of an employee termination is explaining the reason for the move. Lyncheski says some employers use the wrong person to handle the termination; perhaps the messenger is someone who tries to cushion the blow for the employee.<P>"The person hedges on the reason, and not communicating a clear message creates suspicion," Lyncheski says.<P>Gallagher echoes that statement.<P>"You must explain to the employee the real reason," Gallagher says. "A lot of times, in attempting to make it easier on the employee, the employer creates mistrust."<P>Another common mistake: employers overconcern themselves with security measures and in the process humiliate the employee, as the Connecticut hospital did. Make no mistake about it, employers have an absolute right to protect their property and have a duty to protect the employees who remain on the job. But at the same time, they must not overdo it.<P>"The really bad examples," Lyncheski says, "are where employers use excessive security or supervisors to escort the employee off the premises."<P>One method of avoiding litigation is to offer the employee compensation in return for the employee's waiver of his or her right to sue the employer. But courts will not enforce such arrangements that are not bargained-for exchanges. In other words, the employee who waives his or her right to sue must get, in return, something beyond that to which they already are entitled.<P>Employees also must have adequate time to review the waiver.<P>Some employers offer outplacement services as a means of helping terminated employees think about the future, instead of dwelling on what has just occurred. Outplacement firms, which assist the employee in finding a new job, usually charge a percentage of what the employee made - commonly 15 percent - if the employee was upper management. Outplacement of lower level employees usually is handled on a flat-fee basis.<P>"We reduce the risk of employee litigation," says Dale Urban, vice president in the Pittsburgh office of Right Associates, an outplacement firm. "That's a high payoff for employers. They are buying insurance against potential higher costs of litigation."<P>

<hr>

