<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Feature.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2></B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+>Kevin McClatchy Mixes the Enthusiasm of a Sports Nut With <br>a Serious Business Demeanor; He's a Good Fit for the Pirates
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>


<P>
<P>It is Saturday afternoon at the Ross Park Mall. A crowd has gathered, in the opening under the escalators, between the Limited and NRM Records, for a fashion show featuring spring wares from the mall shops. For openers, the Pirate Clubhouse models do a turn around the runway, pivoting, as models do, so the entire audience can glimpse their head-to-toe logoed regalia. <P>Then a young man gets up on stage, in a striped Roberto Clemente jersey over baggy jeans, and, slouching a little, does a runway circle. His amble turns into a bit of a scurry as his turn ends. As he nears the mike, he takes off his ballcap in recognition of the applauding audience, revealing a head of dark blonde hair that has clearly been encapsulated all day. He beams at the crowd sheepishly.<P>"I must admit," says Kevin McClatchy, the Pirates new owner, as they quiet, "that was a first for me." <P>Maybe he never did a runway show before, but even before McClatchy, 33, signed off on the Pirates deal on Feb. 14, he's been center stage. His mug has been all over the papers since last fall, when his intent to purchase the team became serious.  Pittsburgh intently watched the pursuit, with its last minute requests, stays and requirements, like die-hard fans in the last inning of a very close game. <P>McClatchy caught every fly, fielded every grounder and rounded every base. Sincere yet firm with the city and the then Pirates owners. Enthusiastic and decisive with the team assembled for the deal. Smart and convincing with potential investors. Graceful with the media. Diplomatic with Major League Baseball.<P>He scored. <P>But it wasn't easy.<P>Batter Up <P>Kevin McClatchy first came to Pittsburgh last summer after hearing from an investment banker of the opportunity to purchase the Pirates. McClatchy, then a resident of Sacramento, Calif., had taken a leave of absence from his family company, McClatchy Newspapers Inc., to further pursue a career in sports ownership. (He already owned a 45 percent interest in the Modesto A's, a minor league baseball team, and for a time pursued acquisition of the Oakland A's, but failed to secure enough dollars to complete the deal.) He came to Pittsburgh on reconnaissance, meeting initially with the mayor and other parties. <P>Nonetheless, McClatchy had thrown his hat in the ring. Then Major League Baseball rejected cable magnate John J. Rigas' bid and, very suddenly, McClatchy became a top contender. <P>"I went back to California, waiting to hear something," McClatchy remembers. "I didn't know things were going to evolve this quickly. I remember getting the call and jumping on a plane to Pittsburgh. After that it seemed like a roller coaster. We had two weeks to raise $40 million. I don't know if we were given two weeks to succeed or to fail, but we were given two weeks."<P>McClatchy pulled together a group that included attorneys from Reed Smith Shaw & McClay, financial advisors from Arthur Andersen and Charles H. Gesner, Jr., of Lehwald, Orosey & Pepe, to get the job done.<P>"It became a team process," says McClatchy. "My role was really to get out and sell the concept to investors to get them to believe in what we were doing, and that it was possible to turn around the franchise." <P>But how to convince local investors of that? He armed himself with financial projections, item-by-item changes showing a turnaround could, in fact, be achieved. <P>"You could generally get the meeting, because [the team has] been such a big part of the city. But you can only pull on people's heartstrings so long. Anybody who's been successful in business wants to know the bottom line. I was convinced it could work. The question was, could we put a substantial enough group together in what appeared to be a short window of time? I wasn't necessarily convinced we could do that."<P>He did make that deadline, partnering with local investors like Tony O'Reilly and the H.J. Heinz Co., Blade Communications and race car owner Chip Ganassi. The pressure, however, was not alleviated but turned up, it seemed: As the weeks progressed, demands from the owners, Major League Baseball and the city drew out the deal. <P>"I have done a lot of deals, but never anything quite like this," acknowledges David L. DeNinno, partner, Reed Smith Shaw & McClay. "The principal complicating element was lack of time. He had to convince the mayor and investors that he had the wherewithal and the business sophistication to pull it off, and convince the bank that he would be able to complete the transaction and operate the team successfully. And he had to deal with a somewhat difficult existing ownership, and convince Major League Baseball to let him become the youngest owner. <P>"Other than that, it was a piece of cake." <P>Mayor Tom Murphy, who had favored Rigas, admits he was not initially impressed with McClatchy. Like many, he feared that because McClatchy was from out of town, his goal was to move the team. <P>"Our first meeting was not particularly good," says Murphy. "He said very little; the people he was with spoke. Then in the fall, the Pirates gave Bart Fisher a week, then Kevin two weeks. It was a way to get rid of them. But we met every day for two weeks for lengthy periods of time. He came by himself, or occasionally with an attorney. We engaged him on complex issues, and he was prepared to make decisions. We ended up very actively working with him. <P>"Early on, it became clear that this was a life decision for him; he wanted this as his career. And if he could make it work in Pittsburgh, he wanted to."<P>Out of the Frying Pan <P>McClatchy says that from the beginning, he really believed the team should stay in Pittsburgh. In fact, that was one of the elements which initially attracted him to the team. <P>"Having looked at the A's and very briefly the Giants, I thought they had better fans here - not a large base, but the fans they had were very dedicated, which is very important when they're your customers," says McClatchy. "There's no question the Pirates should stay here. I grew up a Giants fan, and about five or six years ago, the Giants were talking about moving to St. Pete. I remember, being a fan, it felt like the worst thing, that your team that you had grown up with, was going to move. So I'm not very keen on franchises moving. When you grow up with a team, someone else might own it, but it's your team. I wouldn't want to put the people here through that. And I don't think you have to. I think you can change things."<P>And that's just what he intended. But the hoops continued to pop up. And he continued to jump through them. One challenge came from U.S. Sen. Rick Santorum, who was concerned about reports he had read in the Sacramento Bee, one of the McClatchy Newspapers, that Kevin McClatchy was involved with building a stadium in Sacramento that met minimum Major League requirements. Santorum brought the issue to the attention of the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, sparking a flurry of media attention early this year. He met with McClatchy.<P>"We talked about [the situation],"says Santorum, who's now clearly McClatch-inated. "The most logical team for Sacramento would have been the A's, but there was no way they could support it. He told me all the things I needed to know."<P>McClatchy continued to rise to every challenge. Not enough capital? He secured more. A guarantee on a new ballpark? Okay. But there were less concrete hurdles, too.<P>"Kevin was an outsider," opines Murphy when asked to pinpoint McClatchy's greatest barrier. "In other places, people are not under such scrutiny, but Pittsburgh is very insular. I think it surprised him, the politics of it all. People were encouraging, then would try to cut off his legs."<P>The McClatchy camp continued their roller coaster ride. <P>"There were dark moments," says DeNinno. "A number of times we were close to the breaking point, but Kevin quickly rebounded, through sheer determination and will power." <P>Privately, however, McClatchy wasn't always so certain his bid would make it. Kevin Rios, a close friend of McClatchy's (and keeper of his dog, Bo Jackson, during the deal) says there were definite peaks and valleys. <P>"He'd call and say, 'It's over,' " says Rios, a Sacramento private investigator. "He was frustrated at times - it seemed like each time they asked for a deadline, they changed the rules."<P>But like the Energizer bunny, he kept going and going and going. Then, on Valentine's Day, all parties gave the nod. McClatchy prevailed.<P>"Kevin just refused to let his dream go," says DeNinno. <P>The Pirates were his.<P>The Sporting Life<P>So why would Kevin Soerensen McClatchy, born on Jan. 13, 1963, in Sacramento, Calif., want to put himself through all that for the opportunity to work like hell to save a flailing ball club? Odd as it sounds, it's almost as if the Buccos are McClatchy's Rome: All roads led here.<P>"He was always very athletic, interested in every sport there was - football, basketball, junior tennis, baseball," says Grace Kennan Warnecke, McClatchy's mom. <P>"I'm one of those sports junkies that, before I could read I knew people's batting averages," says McClatchy. "It's funny, because my family are all intellectuals. Sometimes I think I was hatched."<P>The youngest of three children, McClatchy lived with his mother  and his sister, Adair, after his parents were divorced in 1966. He spent weekends and summers with his father, Charles Kenny McClatchy, called C.K., editor of the Sacramento Bee. The Bee, founded by the McClatchy family in 1857, is the flagship of McClatchy Newspapers, which Fortune estimates at $600 million net worth. Now publicly held, McClatchy Newspapers, with Kevin's uncle Jim McClatchy at the helm, publishes 12 newspapers in California, Washington, Alaska and South Carolina.<P>In Sacramento, the McClatchy clan is known for their community spirit, which they are not afraid to take to the extreme, sometimes earning them the label "eccentric." They are benefactors of the arts and champions of the environment. C.K., who died in 1989, was a fiery liberal who ran the Bee with strong presence. An obituary in Time magazine credits C.K., who died jogging at the age of 62, with "infusing his papers with a competitive edge and liberal views."<P>"We spent a lot of time together. He was very intelligent, very caring," says McClatchy, who spent most of his childhood in California, except for a few years in Washington, D.C. <P>Grace, Kevin's mother, attended Radcliffe and is a former freelance photographer. Later, she was a photo editor of "A Day in the Life of the Soviet Union," and founder of the first American-Soviet Youth Symphony. Fluent in Russian, she now works with companies wishing to establish business in the former Soviet Union through her New York-based firm Sovus Business Consultants. That interest comes from her father, George Frost Kennan, a Pulitzer prize and National Book award-winning intellectual. Kennan spent 27 years in the foreign service, including posts as Ambassador to the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia. Credited with seminal ideas in U.S.-Soviet relations, Kennan is author of some 18 books on Russia, diplomacy and nuclear issues. His published personal travel accounts reveal an insightful curiosity in humanity and love of community. And it was he who set the family precedent in baseball: Interned in a German camp for six months during World War II, George Kennan encouraged baseball games among embassy personnel to keep them active and sane. <P>In 1969, McClatchy's mother married architect John Carl Warnecke, and took his name. Warnecke's work, which includes the J.F.K. Memorial in Arlington Cemetery, Logan Airport and the Neiman Marcus and Bergdorf Goodman stores, moved the family to Washington. It was there, in the fifth grade, that McClatchy got his first job - following in his dad's footsteps, so to speak: a paper route. <P>"I did it to get some money. My dad was very cheap, in a positive way. He didn't throw money around. He  had a [small] apartment in a place that wasn't all that great. I remember once I went home and asked my mom if we could send him some money." <P>"Kevin has an entrepreneurial streak. He didn't have to have that paper route, but he got up at 5 a.m. every day. And it wasn't easy, because it was complicated getting paid," says his mother, imparting a warm, deep laugh, which she does often in the conversation. "Kevin would get frustrated and he does have a temper, though he's become much more even-tempered." (On that subject, Mayor  Murphy credited McClatchy, saying that McClatchy kept his temper in check at times when Murphy himself would have become emotional.) <P>It was also in the fifth grade that McClatchy was diagnosed with dyslexia, which seemingly explained his inclination toward sports - dyslexia makes book learning difficult. He often says that toppling dyslexia built the determination he so publicly displayed pursuing the Pirates. It did force him to make what he calls his first step toward growing up - at 14, McClatchy went away to boarding school at Trinity Pawling High School in New York. His mother was getting a divorce from Warnecke, and thought it would be better for McClatchy to be with other kids. More importantly, TP had a special program for dyslexic students.<P>"It was my choice - in eighth grade I was reading at a sixth grade level. It was not good. Sports gave me confidence, but I was not good in school so I cut up a little bit. I was dealing with a fair amount of frustration, and I knew this was my only chance," says McClatchy. At TP, he roomed with Dan Rooney Jr., and came to Pittsburgh for the first time for Thanksgiving at Rooney's home. At the end of McClatchy's freshman year, he received an award for being "outstanding citizen." <P>"He was so proud," recalls his mother. (With the caveat: "Mothers are never the best ones to ask about their children. There's that special bond.") "Before that, he was popular, happy-go-lucky. After that, he showed real leadership. He worked with younger kids, worked with Big Brothers & Big Sisters. But Kevin always had a zillion friends. Just ask him how many weddings he's been in." (fifteen or so.)<P>"He was a quiet kid," says his uncle Jim McClatchy. "But he was always doing something."<P>The Comeback Kid <P>The Pirates aren't the first team McClatchy's brought back. As a student at the University of California at Santa Barbara, he raised money and worked with administration to re-establish their football program, discontinued since 1971 due to lack of support in the Vietnam "anti-establishment" era. <P>"He was instrumental in bringing it back, against a clear lack of support," says Steve Colvin, a fraternity brother of McClatchy's who remains a close friend. "Kevin's very easygoing and jokes around a lot. I mean, he wasn't the guy in the corner with the lampshade on his head, but he has a good sense of humor. Then he has a flip side where he can shift gears and work hard to get things done." <P>McClatchy played cornerback. "I always wanted to be an athlete when I was younger. Then reality comes in, things like speed and leaping ability - I think I knew that then," says McClatchy, who has also been through shoulder and knee surgeries. It wasn't until later that career and sports meshed - during college, McClatchy worked summer jobs like construction in Alaska. ("You could make just ridiculous amounts of money.") After school he spent the prerequisite months as a waiter in a ski resort town, then held jobs as a reporter in Bend, Ore., in sports production for WPLG in Miami and in advertising for the Miami Herald newspaper, where he started off on the phone, taking classified ads.  <P>Until, in 1989, his father died. McClatchy went back to California for a few months, to take care of family business, and ended up staying with McClatchy Newspapers. "I had no plans to do that, but I felt a responsibility," says McClatchy. "I always planned I would go there and work with him. This just moved it up. <P>"Two years before, my best friend was killed in a freak accident. He       was like my brother. That really changed my perspective - I realized things had an end. Then my father  died unexpectedly. His leadership and guidance suddenly weren't there. It was me at that point. It made me grow      up quicker. That was a bad three or four years." <P>At McClatchy Newspapers, which had gone public a month before his father died, Kevin came up through the sales department to become advertising director. In 1992, he helped found the Newspaper Network Co., which consolidates daily newspaper buys nationwide. McClatchy became national sales director, remaining in Sacramento. While the family name was well-known there, McClatchy did not have the kind of face recognition he has here, he says. But he did take on some of the family's civic tradition: McClatchy worked to complete funding and build an amphitheater in Sacramento's underprivileged Oak Park, a project his father had begun, which Kevin dedicated in his father's name. His financial responsibility was also increased, with an inheritance from his father that increased his net worth, which he confirms is currently about $20 million. <P>"I bought a house," says McClatchy, claiming it didn't really affect his lifestyle. "I eventually bought part of a minor league baseball team. And I bought really good seats for the Sacramento Kings [basketball] games."<P>His friends say he was as low profile as it comes, back in Sacramento. Recreation drove the social calendar - to the beach, local sports events, travel to Dodgers and 49ers games, and time at his family house in Lake Tahoe, where he spent summers growing up. <P>"He's a good talker," says Rios, who shared the Kings seats. "He has an awareness of the world, and he's fascinated by other people, especially in high positions. He aspires to be able to speak to people at all levels. He's not a big reader, he learns from talking."<P>"He's an upright guy, modest and decent," says Jim McClatchy, his uncle and former employer. "He doesn't profess to be a scholar, but he is interested in the world. He's got a good group of buddies, he's outgoing, he likes people, likes to have a beer, likes girls."<P>One day he made a spur of the moment call which eventually changed his career direction. <P> "I read about this guy who was buying a single A team and was talking about moving them to Sacramento," recalls McClatchy. "So I called him, out of the blue, and told him I thought he was making a mistake. He invited me out to talk about it."<P>"He just showed up at this meeting. It became clear to me that he was one of the most capable and willing to get this thing going," says Fred Anderson, a Sacramento manufacturer of building materials who jokes that he's spent more than Steve Forbes did on his political bid trying to bring sports to that town. They bought the team, the Modesto A's, and McClatchy became president. McClatchy then took a leave of absence from the Newspaper Network, and the two started the Northern California Sports Development Group to acquire more  franchises.<P>"I thought he was out trying to get a team for Sacramento, and he ended up in Pittsburgh," chuckles Anderson, who's invested in the Pirates as well.<P>"We'll lose him - Major League Baseball has suggested he decrease his involvement with the minor league," Anderson says. "But I have to think that in some ways I'm responsible for getting him involved in baseball. I think that's one of my greatest achievements in sports."<P>A Stand-Up Guy <P>Pittsburgh sure thinks so. At a recent reception for season ticket holders, for which 800 RSVPed and 1,400 attended, people stood in line for three hours waiting for autographs.<P>Days later, on a disgustingly bone-chilling Saturday, there was a line out the door of the Ross Park Mall's Pirate Clubhouse for autographs. McClatchy signed and signed, smiling all the while.<P>"I came over to say thank you," says Judy Stupak, a middle-aged woman with her teenagers in tow. "He saved the Pirates for us. If it wasn't for him, the heritage of baseball, a part of Pittsburgh history and our history, would be gone. My parents took me to games, I took my kids. It kept us close." <P>McClatchy sits and talks with fans until the last one leaves; the staff has to cut them off ("He'd sit there all day if we didn't," says one employee) and hustle him to another event. <P>This willingness to listen is endearing about McClatchy. As is his wide smile, which turns a nice looking but unremarkable white male face into a recognizable personality.<P>"My mother said, 'He's such a nice kid. I wish he was my son,' " says Mike Kelly, Ketchum Public Relations vice president and counsel to the Pirates. "Thanks, Mom." <P>McClatchy's youth is generally seen as an asset, and, in his own words, can be disarming in negotiations. He doesn't hide the fact that he has an aggressive agenda, but that fact does, at times, get overlooked because he's just so darned nice. Potential opponents or critics would do well to remember Mark Sauer's sidestepping upon McClatchy's arrival: McClatchy even took Sauer's office. He may have great dimples, but he's no pushover. <P>"Kevin's down to earth, no hidden agenda. He actively seeks input before he makes decisions," says Kelly. "He's a hell of a guy to do business with, you tell jokes and have fun, and you don't have a fear of offering a differing opinion. He will listen to it." <P>The combination is winning. In two short months, any skepticism once raised about McClatchy's intentions for the team has been dispelled. City Council, once a major critic, named April 8, opening day, 'Kevin McClatchy Day.' It was, appropriately for the Pirates, the day after Easter. McClatchy, however, is modest about it. <P>"I think once people have gotten to meet me, they realize I'm pretty much a regular guy," says McClatchy, his well-cut suit and starched white shirt humanized by scuffed bucks and the paper clip holding the ends of his tie together. "I get tired of seeing 'newspaper heir.' I've worked my whole life. If I sat around and counted money and didn't work, sure, call me an heir. But if I'm putting in 16 to 18 hours of work a day, I think I deserve to be called a business person." "If anyone can tell he's from a prominent background I'd be surprised. He drove an old car in college, and didn't have any more than anyone else, except maybe a nice place to go for holidays," says Colvin, a stock broker in Los Angeles. He and McClatchy have for years talked every day, about sports, mostly. "His priorities were school, family and friends - not necessarily in that order." <P>The family is close, albeit not geographically, but they gather for holidays, get together as often as possible and are wired on e-mail. Charles, McClatchy's older brother, owns and directs two homeless shelters in Sacramento; his sister, Adair, is studying environmental science at San Francisco State. One family base is Princeton, where George Kennan, now 92, lives. Grace Kennan Warnecke came to Pittsburgh for the opener, as did many of Kevin's friends, and has already suggested taking the Pirates to Russia.<P>"I was very surprised when he said he would like to buy the Pirates," says Kevin's mother. "It seemed like an incredibly big step. I lived that with him, though, and by the time he actually bought the team - well, I'm just happy it worked out. I really think he's thinking of making baseball better. It's such a big part of American life. I think Kevin, through all of this, just wants to leave the world a better place, which he gets from both the McClatchys and the Kennans." <P>"You know," says Kevin's mother, "a lot of his sense of community and team spirit comes from sports."<P>Which is getting it back in     spades.<P>Play Ball <P>When the deal was done, McClatchy launched into the Pittsburgh community like a jet-propelled rocket, visiting groups in all corners of the region. "The key to all this is the fans," he says. All fans. <P>One day in March, the fifth graders at Haine Elementary, clad in black and gold, graciously told their guest, Kevin McClatchy, what they know about him. He's 33, single, paid $90 million for the Pirates and needs $150 million for a new stadium. Then it's their turn to ask questions. He listens intently.<P>"Do you have a dog?" Yes, a yellow lab, who was 4 years old on April 25. "What's your favorite color?" Dark blue. "What's your favorite Italian food?" He names a complicated dish, explaining it's black pepper fettuccine with shrimp and duck - maybe kids don't like it.<P>"Where do you live?" In Point Breeze, in Pittsburgh. "What kind of car do you drive?" A jeep, which is good in the snow. "What books do you read?" He likes John Grisham's novels. "What music do you like?" Bruce Springsteen. Of course, the Boss. "Do you like MTV?" Yes, he says, and names a few shows, which they agree are good. <P>"Are you tired of all the meetings you have to go to?" No. He shows them his schedule, runs through a typical day. Radio shows, meetings, appearances, interviews. "Are you signing any new players?" He runs down the latest, explaining that the key is the pitching, and he'd like to see revenue sharing.<P>They have some advice: They've thought up a number of ways to raise money for the new stadium. And 'If you ever feel like buying the Pirates was a mistake, keep your head up.'<P>He smiles, hands out ballcaps and has his picture taken with each one of them, then with the whole class. Above the blackboard is a sign.<P>"In a world full of followers ... Dare to be a leader."<P>





