<a href="../zine/0596.Feature.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<center>
<B><font size=+2>Tourism
</font></B><br>
<b><font size=+1>Are We Getting Our Share<br>
of This Recression-Proof Industry?</font></b><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>
<hr>

<P>

Molly Stahlman was in the midst of her MBA program at Carnegie Mellon when she decided what she wanted to do with her degree upon graduation: She would start a company offering trolley tours of Pittsburgh.<P>That's right: Her business - which provided its first tour last month - depends on people who want to board a motorized trolley and ride around greater Pittsburgh seeing the sights.<P>Sound like a reach? It's not, according to the 27-year-old entrepreneur. And she's not the only person voicing that opinion.<P>The Allegheny Conference on Community Development's Working Together Consortium sees tourism as a means of triggering economic growth in the region.<P>Stahlman is banking on it. Pittsburgh Trolley Tours Inc. is starting out small - only two trolleys right now - but she is projecting growth in coming years. She'll initially cater to private groups, corporations or hospitals and the such that bring people into town for conferences or conventions.<P>"I've found that people do want a really classy tour of Pittsburgh," says Stahlman, who tapped the expertise of several CMU professors when developing her business plan.<P>"There is a rich history here," Stahlman says. "People who don't know Pittsburgh don't have a high opinion of it like we do. So let's show them. Half of it is the packaging. We will be a top packager, give them a really classy tour of Pittsburgh."<P>In Part V of Executive Report's six-month series entitled Resuscitating the Region, ER looks at how tourism offers a window of opportunity to spur regional growth. In previous months, the magazine talked about the importance of entrepreneurship, exporting, education and transportation. Next month, ER will end the series with a look at tax reform as a window of opportunity.<P>This month: Tourism.<P><P>Tourism Economics<P>Statistics show that travel and tourism have long been important parts of the American economy. Dollars spent by tourists produce a ripple effect  felt in every aspect of a community, as well as the overall economy.<P>The plus about tourism - in contrast to other industries - is that it rarely suffers stagnation. Even during recessions, tourism has been a winner. Consider these statistics:<P>u	The American Automobile Association estimates that 47 million people belonged to an automobile club for travel services in 1994, the most recent year for which statistics were available. AAA travel agency sales that year totaled $2 billion, up from a previous high of $1.8 billion the year earlier.<P>u	Also in 1994, travelers spent  $399.6 billion on travel in U.S. destinations, an increase of 5 percent from the previous year. Revenues in the hotel industry increased 7 percent over the previous year.<P>u	In Pennsylvania in 1994, 164,000 people were employed in tourism-related jobs, the ninth most among the 50 states. California was No. 1 with 591,400 tourism-related jobs.<P>u	Travelers spent almost $2.2 billion in 1993 in Allegheny County alone, second only to Philadelphia County at $2.3 billion, according to state statistics.<P>"Attracting visitors is a practice growing throughout the world," says Richard Stafford, executive director of the Allegheny Conference. "If we even just kept our share of this market, we will continue to have dollars. In addition, I buy into the idea that we may do a notch or two better.<P>"This is known as a European city in America," Stafford says. "It's an interesting place for a lot of people to      visit. Because of philanthropy over the years, we have a lot of attractions - The Carnegie and all its branches,       for example."<P>Tourism insiders say their industry is important because it brings wealth into the region, much like the business practice of exporting does. Instead of shipping a product elsewhere and bringing dollars into the region in return, tourists simply spend the dollars here personally.<P>"It's no different than if they bought a $100 widget made here in the region," Stafford says. "We are importing dollars. What you are talking about is jobs."<P>Joseph McGrath, executive director of the Greater Pittsburgh Convention and Visitors Bureau, says about 50 percent of visitors to Pittsburgh are business travelers who come here to visit the likes of USX, Mellon Bank, PNC Bank or other large companies with significant operations here. Another 30 percent are traditional tourists, and 20 percent are conventioneers.<P>The traditional tourists range from actual vacationers, to those attending a special event in the cultural district, to day-trippers who enter the city to shop and eat.<P>The real eye-opener for locals is the actual vacationers. Many do come, and what they see in Pittsburgh is often quite different than what the locals see.<P><P>An Outsider's View<P>Back in mid-1995, Washington Post travel writer James Yenckel spent two days in Pittsburgh and subsequently gushed about it as a tourist destination in an article that appeared not only in the Post but also in the Los Angeles Times and other newspapers nationwide that subscribe to the Washington Post-Los Angeles Times News Service.<P>Yenckel's conclusion: "Given Pittsburgh's rich historical heritage, I probably shouldn't have been surprised by the abundance of fascinating things to see." (For more excerpts of the Pittsburgh travel review, please see Chronicles on page 7).<P>	You'll hear no argument from the Conven-tion and Visitors Bureau's McGrath, who thinks greater Pitts-burgh can better take advantage of the "fascinating things" to which Yenckel referred by doing a better job of "bundling" these various attractions.<P>	"Individual attractions are usually not strong enough to attract someone to a destination," McGrath says. "But if you package the attractions together, there's a better chance that they'll come."<P>	So a younger family may spend part of the day at Sandcastle or Kennywood Park, then head to a Pirates game in the evening. A couple with interest in the arts, meanwhile, may spend the day at The Carnegie in Oakland, the Regional History Center or the Warhol Museum, then take in the symphony that evening.<P>John Herbst, executive director of the Regional History Center, is counting on tourists being a significant part of the center's audience. <P>"Anyone who travels to a place wants to know about where they are," Herbst says. "They'll want to know about Pittsburgh, and the History Center is ready to play that role."<P>The best economic opportunity with tourism lies in conventions, and anyone who has ever attended a convention knows why. Conventioneers tend to be on expense accounts, so they spend more money than the traditional tourists and the business travelers.<P>Geographically, Pittsburgh is a good location for conventions since approximately 40 percent of the U.S. population resides within a 500 mile radius. And the fact that USAir has a hub in Pittsburgh allows many people to take direct flights here. In some instances, USAir may provide special air fares for conventioneers.<P>Now the problem: the state-owned David L. Lawrence Convention Center's relatively small exhibit hall tends to limit its ability to bring in conventions. That's why Pittsburgh Mayor Tom Murphy moved to scrap plans for a $6 million entrance lobby intended to beautify the convention center and use the money instead to buy land to at least double the exhibit hall's size. <P>The Convention and Visitors Bureau's sales department studied 13 cities that are considered to be most competitive with Pittsburgh, including Baltimore, Columbus, Cleveland, Detroit, Indianapolis and Cincinnati. All 13 cities had more gross exhibit space than Pittsburgh, and seven of them had more total hotel rooms within walking distance of the convention center. These factors are weighted heavily by convention planners.<P>The convention center expansion here will beef up both exhibit and meeting room space. The expansion likely will go west toward the Cultural District, with later expansion east toward the Strip District. The expansion was still being studied by a local group at presstime. <P>As for the hotel space, McGrath says there is a glaring need for a large hotel that could add anywhere from 500 to 1,400 hotel rooms in the market. The closer to downtown the better.<P>How urgent is this? Pretty urgent when you consider that conventioneers who don't come here are probably going somewhere else.<P>Just ask Andrew Young, the former mayor of Atlanta, who pushed tourism and to this day credits a third of corporate relocations to Atlanta to people whose initial experience in Atlanta was a visit there for a convention. They came back later, Young says.<P>"It's forced tourism," adds the Convention and Visitors Bureau's McGrath. "You are forced to go to that destination. Then they say, 'It's not bad, maybe I'd come back.' "                        <P>




