<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0596.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Regional History Center
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Letters from Naig</font></b><br>

<i></i></center>
<hr>

<P>
Andrew Carnegie went from rags to riches, literally.<P>The man who would become the biggest name in steel was born in Scotland and got his start as a bobbin boy in a Pittsburgh textile mill at $1.20 a week. Before his death in 1919 at the age of 84, Carnegie would plant the seed that grew to become USX Corp. And with his millions, Carnegie would build the sprawling libraries and museums that bear his name and still attract thousands annually.<P>Yet he remains an enigma.<P>"Carnegie was a very complex guy," says Duquesne University Provost Michael Weber, a historian. "No one has put the finger on him real well. He was without question a business genius. He didn't make steel himself, but he put together all the pieces to make it work, using what would later become common business methods."<P>Carnegie's feats as an investor and steel magnate have been well-chronicled. But until recently, information about Carnegie's early, formative years was somewhat limited. That changed with the opening of the Senator John Heinz Pittsburgh Regional History Center in Pittsburgh's Strip District. Just weeks before opening, the history center became the repository for letters and other Carnegie documents dating back to 1853.<P>USX, the steel and energy giant that evolved from steel holdings Carnegie sold to J.P. Morgan in 1901, gave the regional history center 14 boxes of papers USX had been keeping at a constant temperature in a limestone mine.<P>Prior to USX releasing the documents, only two historians had seen them in the last 40 years.<P>"It is not for me to comment on the value of these historic documents," says USX Chief Executive Thomas J. Usher. "I'll leave that to the historians."<P>So will we, and the early reviews from some paint the letters as classic Carnegie.<P>"I see him as being kind of a contradictory man," says Professor Daniel John Santoro, a University of Pitts-burgh at Johnstown professor who has studied the evolution of the steel industry. <P>"I don't want to say that he talked out of both sides of his mouth, but he was also kind of strapped by the realities that faced him as a businessman. <P>"Take the Homestead steel strike: Carnegie had criticized competitors for not allowing the union in the workplace. He asked why they would deny workers what he and other businessmen claimed as a right. But when it came to his own business, he abandoned that position quite quickly."<P>The Homestead Works near Pittsburgh was one of the largest plants in Carnegie's steel empire. He had acquired it in 1889 with the purchase of the H.C. Frick Coke Company. Along with the plant came Henry Clay Frick himself and the plant's union, the Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers. <P>By 1892, Carnegie and Frick were so worried about falling prices and overcapacity in the steel industry that they sought to cut wages at Homestead, which led the union to go out on strike. At the same time, they hoped to dislodge the Amalgamated as the bargaining unit at the plant. Their plan included bringing Pinkerton security men into the plant, inviting the strikers to return to work, and hiring nonunion labor if they did not respond. Getting wind of the plan, the workers block-aded the works and fought a pitched battle with the Pinkertons in which more than a dozen people were killed. The violence continued for weeks until the governor sent 8,000 troops to Homestead. Only then could the plant reopen with a large complement of nonunion labor. <P>The strike and the battle captured national attention and permanently tarnished Carnegie's reputation as a progressive employer.<P><P>The Letters<P>The letters were penned long before Carnegie ascended to power. The correspondence started in 1853 - when Carnegie was 18 - and lasted four years. Carnegie aggressively chided George "Dod" Lauder, his cousin in Scotland. Lauder's father suggested that the boys debate via mail about the politics of their respective countries.  <P>"One can note the tremendous energy Carnegie had as a youth for this environment that he would exploit when he grew older," says Professor Allan Zeman of Robert Morris College.<P>Carnegie and Dod debated the characteristics of their countries - from governmental structure to social policy - each defending their country's weaknesses and pointing out the strengths. Carnegie touts the superiority of American know-how, even though years later he would use European technology - the Bessemer converter - to build his steel empire.<P>Carnegie signed the letters "Naig." The following are excerpts.<P><P>Defending Federalism<P>Carnegie had only been in the country five years, but studied and embraced the system of federalism, under which some powers were reserved for the states. Europe, for the most part, still toiled under feudalistic rule. Carnegie went right to the point, explaining why federalism works and slipping in a slam against the systems of government present throughout Europe.<P>"Our revolutionary fathers were afraid to create a powerful government. They argued it might be turned into an instrument of oppression as it had in Europe and they thought that the states could legislate for themselves and know their own wants better than any other.<P>"Accordingly you will find a clause in our present constitution to that effect. I send you a copy of it.<P>"I have no doubt you will be surprised at its simplicity and won't believe that such a nation as this composed of  25 million from all the ends of the earth can be governed by such an insignificant looking document. But that's because you have been brought up to think a constitution should have something mysterious about it as it is the case with your own - a thing to be talked about but never seen. Our constitution was made by the people and can be altered, amended or done away with by them whenever they see fit."<P><P>Rubbing It In<P>In a subsequent letter, Carnegie responded to information from Dod about reforms taking place in England. Carnegie inferred that England was following the lead of the United States. Carnegie also writes words he definitely would not write were he alive today: proclaiming the efficiency of American politics.<P>"I can think of no reform which you have that we do not possess. We have all your good traits which are many, with few or none of your bad ones which I must say are neither few nor far between. But we go ahead. We now possess what the working classes of your country look forward to as constituting their political millennium.<P>"Now all these great reforms were gained without threatening to revolutionize. Oh No. Our political engine works so smoothly, no puffing and blowing but everything easy about it. It would amuse you to see our politicians bowing and scraping to their masters, the dear people.<P>"But the best proof of the superiority of our system is seen in the general prosperity and progress of its citizens. Among a multitude of similar instances I will mention the following: We have now in the national treasury nearly $22 million. Our debt is being paid off as fast as it becomes due. Our receipts annually exceed our expenditures. Towns and cities spring up as if by magic. Mind is freed from superstitious reverence for old customs, unawed by gorgeous and unmeaning shows and forms.<P>"This doing of a thing 'because our grandfathers did it' I can assure you is not an American institution. We have little veneration for those rules and principles rendered sacred by the seal of the ancients whether in church or state.<P>"Now we don't look upon Government with any peculiar reverence nor regard it as a science. Our aim is to continually simplify and moderate what little we have got. We regard Government merely as the body through which the Nation acts and think that it should be as absolutely under its control as our body is under our mind. ... The time is near at hand in this country when our president will be considered (as he really is) only the head clerk of our establishment and his cabinet as under managers."<P><P>Foreign Affairs<P>When Dod prodded America for not playing a larger role in the world, the 19-year-old Carnegie responded by telling Dod that America's role is to lead by example instead of imposing its views and beliefs on other countries.<P>	"Great and good men in every nation glory in its prosperity and would lament over its downfall. Our mission as the representative of a new era, as the pioneer of liberty is to serve as an example to other nations to incite them to come up to the true standard, to impel the people to ask and obtain new reforms and go on steadily progressing. For our own sake as well as theirs, we ought not to impair our strength or retard our progress by laying down the ploughshare of peace or the sword of war unless compelled to do so in self-defense."<P><P>On the Defense<P>Dod finally put Carnegie on the defense by chiding Carnegie about America's use of slaves. Carnegie concedes the argument, but says America should not be condemned.<P>"We hate slavery as much as you do and have abolished it as you did as far as we had the power. It is true our southern states urged on by British Demand for cotton, cherish the curse in their bosoms. 'Tis horrible to think of one man trafficking in the flesh of another and to think of the wrongs, crimes, and cruelties committed by and inherent in this institution. Men like ourselves bought and sold in the 19th century. Women and children lashed like cattle. It is sickening to think of. When nations are called upon to render an account of the deeds done in the body, when the recording angel looks upon the workings of this accurst system what think you will be the enquiry? Will he begin at the beginning and say, Whence came this monster? Who is its author? How and by whom was it established? And then we will reply, when we were in the helplessness and innocency of childhood entirely under the guidance of the mother country this system was forced upon us. We think we did our duty. We demonstrated earnestly against it. We made a tax on every negro that entered to discourage it. We solemnly declared that the 13th colony would be shielded from the curse. <P>"Since we became our own masters we have declared the trade to be piracy. State after state has liberated its slaves till now, from being 80 years ago all the victims of this hereditary curse, two-thirds of our population live in states where there is no such thing as slave. This much we have done since we had the power and although the system has spread in the South, in comparison with the population it has been rapidly decreasing and we all know how hard it is for us to uproot bad habits engrafted upon us in youth and especially so when taught from a parental hand."<P><P>A Nation's Destiny<P>Carnegie ponders what would come true - America becoming the world's dominant nation - and how that role would play out. <P>"We are possessors of a mighty nation, a land we think marked out by the finger of destiny to become the greatest among the nations of the earth. Its mission we believe is not only to continue as asylum for the poor and honest of the world, to stand as a vast receptacle of all the oppressed and downtrodden, gathering them under its paternal wing as a hen gathering her chickens and feeding and nourishing the famishing brood, high though such a destiny be, we still look higher. She is chosen to stand forth in the van of every reform calculated to elevate the human race and serve as a burning shining light to others."<P><P>More Politics<P>Carnegie compares politicians to employees. He says they either do what the people want, or find a new job.<P>"In order to attain this position certain [things] must be carried out. We want our machines built in a certain manner. We go to work, advertise for workmen, inform them what we want done and how and when, name the wages, (we pay our workmen) length of service etc., take those we like best and if they enter our employ, insist upon our wishes being carried out in every particular. We must have our way when it is we who bear the burden."<P><P>Dear Andrew Carnegie:<P>You will be pleased to know that after 100 years your legacy to this wonderful city is still legendary. Our children study your contributions to Pittsburgh as a business leader during the early decades of the Industrial Revolution. You will also be pleased, however, to learn that they are equally aware and appreciative of your role as a champion of literacy for all people and as a benefactor of the arts.<P>Libraries across this country bear your name because you above all others recognized the importance of universal literacy and donated huge sums of money to make books of all kinds available for public use. In Pittsburgh today, our local Carnegie libraries are an important partner in the education of the city's youth, providing warm, quiet places for young people to study, conduct research or merely to enjoy a good book. You would be especially proud, I believe, <P>of today's libraries which are promoting a new technology-based literacy that can open new worlds for everyone. "A library outranks any other one thing a community can do to benefit its people," you said. "It is a never failing spring in the desert."<P>You also recognized the importance of the arts to society, and their inextricable link to education and literacy. Today, performing halls around the country bear your name, a testament to your desire to make arts accessible to the public. In Pittsburgh the Carnegie Institute represents perhaps your most visible legacy. As you once said, "The success of library, art gallery, museum and music hall - a noble quartet in an immense building - is one of the chief satisfactions of my life."<P>Your community investments, which totaled $350 million in your lifetime, continue to pay huge dividends today. All of us are the beneficiaries, and we are grateful. We are also hopeful that the spring you tapped in Pittsburgh will never run dry and that generations to come will be able to reap the benefits of your contributions to a literate society and your appreciation of the arts.<P><P>Sincerely,<P>Louise R. Brennen<P>Supt., Pittsburgh Schools<P><P>Dear Mr. Carnegie:<P>What I have always admired the most about you is the hundreds of thousands of jobs you created.<P>You helped raise a golden age of heavy manufacturing. Large corporations like your Carnegie Steel Company dominated the economy in Pittsburgh and across the country. For decades, sons and daughters assumed from early childhood that they would work for the same large industrial concerns that hired their parents.<P>But if you returned to western Pennsylvania today, you might shake your head in amazement. You would see daily reports of large companies making massive layoffs of tens of thousands of employees at a time. You would learn that employment at what are now called Fortune 500 companies is down substantially from the levels of 10 and 15 years ago, despite enormous economic growth nationally.<P>You would see that unemployment is relatively low, and you might ask yourself, "Where is everyone working?"<P>The answer, Mr. Carnegie, is at small businesses.<P>Some are service companies, some manufacturers, some retailers. Some are making and selling things like software and facsimile transmission machines that you could not have imagined possible when you resigned your job at the Pennsylvania Railroad in 1865 to start your first business, the Keystone Bridge Company. Together, these small companies create about 90 percent of all new jobs.<P>Somehow, I doubt you would wring your hands in despair. I have a feeling you would roll up your sleeves and start looking for an underserved market niche. You would think about how you could deliver a better product or service at a lower price faster than your larger competitor. You would figure out how to get into international markets. You would, in short, join the ranks of the small but aggressive entrepreneurs who are the true engine of growth in America in the 1990s!<P><P>Sincerely,<P>Leo R. McDonough<P>President,  SMC<P><P>P.S. Thank you very much for your gift of the Carnegie libraries. You have generously given to the people of this community the precious resource of knowledge and ideas which will endure as long as Pittsburgh itself.<P><P>Dear Mr. Carnegie:<P>Most people remember you as an entrepreneur and business leader. But before you started your first business, Keystone Bridge Company, in 1865, you were an employee.<P>Your success working for other people shows today's workers what most <P>successful business people know: that the best employees make the most successful entrepreneurs.<P><P>Despite a limited education, you rose quickly in every company that employed you, be it a cotton factory, a telegraph office or a railroad. You treated the resources of your employers as if they were your own. You worked tirelessly to get the job done, whatever it was. By aligning your own goals with those of your employers, your employers thrived, and so did you.<P>Industrialization and technology were rapidly changing America. Rather than worry about if new technology would change or end your job, you embraced technological advances, like the Pullman sleeping car, and later as an entrepreneur, the Bessemer process for making steel.<P>You also learned from your employers about how to build and run a        company. You moved up the ranks at the Pennsylvania Railroad, ending up as the head of the western division. You saved some capital and bought shares in the company. With the profits from your investment, you financed your first  enterprise.<P>As a captain of industry, you applied the lessons you learned as an employee, and built one of the greatest industrial concerns the world has ever seen.<P>Yours is the story of the good <P>employee who sees an emerging market opportunity and grabs it. It excited me as a child, and it still excites me. As one of the thousands of employees turned business owners who has used your life as a <P><P>model, I thank you.<P><P>Respectfully yours,<P>Michael L. Bussler<P>Algor Inc.<P><P>Dear Andrew Carnegie:<P>For nearly 100 years, people have celebrated you for building an important industry, endowing public libraries, founding educational institutions and supporting myriad charitable causes. But some have vilified you as one of the major exploiters of labor in your era.<P>You would be surprised at how the pendulum has swung since you were active in business. In your day, labor unions, to the extent they existed at all, were struggling to survive.  Govern-ment laws protected employers against organizing.<P>But since then, a massive body of regulations has emerged to foster union organizing and protect union activity. The percentage of the workforce that is unionized hit a peak of more than 30 percent in the 1950s, and has now leveled off at about 17 percent.<P>As you knew all too well, a union is a third party that positions itself between employees and their employers, and stifles a cooperative working out of problems together. Unions insist upon work rules and inflexible contracts, which make it harder for employers to operate at peak productivity. Unions also can make it harder for employees to pursue the lifestyle they now desire; for example, by making job-sharing and flex time unachievable. Unions have been very slow to respond to the needs of the young, women and minorities, and they often negotiate away the future of younger workers to protect their most senior members.<P>Unionized companies are often at a competitive disadvantage, as seen in a recent strike at one General Motors plant that rocked not just GM, but the economy of much of the Midwest.<P>And the pendulum continues to swing to the side of unions. Our current president, Bill Clinton, is working to pass a law to ban the use of replacement workers. This law would make it much harder to operate during a strike, giving unions enormous negotiating leverage and power. The National Labor Relations Board (which didn't even exist until decades after you retired), has recently begun to swing toward organized labor. Unions are exercising political influence beyond their numbers.<P>Most union leaders have an adversarial mentality forged in the steel mills built by you and your business partners. Yet a team partnership attitude is needed to remain competitive in today's global economy. I believe that if you were alive today, you would understand that attitude and do all you could to provide employees with a fair wage and a good working environment, foster the teamwork approach to employee relations, try to meet the needs of the workforce and comply with the large body of laws and regulations governing employment. You would work to make American industry more competitive in the global economy, despite the efforts to the contrary by organized labor.<P><P><P>John E. Lyncheski <P>Chair, Labor and <P>Employment Group<P>Cohen & Grigsby<P>





