<center><B><font size=+2>The Flex Office
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Some Developers Have Carved Out a <BR>
Niche by Building High-EndFlex Space<BR>
for Use by Office Operations</font></b><br>

<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>
<hr>


<P>Bill Corace's first foray into flex space left him a little worried. Early into the project, the warehouse tenants who Corace figured would line up to get into the space were turning up their noses.<P>As it turned out, the traditional warehouse tenants weren't necessarily concerned about the landscaping and architectural appeal that Corace was including in his project.<P>"I thought my primary tenants would be taken from warehouse space," says Corace, principal of Secon Corp., developer of Abele Business Park in South Fayette Township.<P>"What I found out was that the warehouse tenants were interested in lower rent and were not concerned about aesthetic appeal," Corace says. "Then we switched gears and marketed it to office tenants who pay higher rates but want the better access, storage space, loading docks and other things associated with light industrial. That turned the project around.<P>"I goofed up in such a way that it was much better in the long term," Corace says.<P>Yes it was. Flex space has been around in one form or another for a couple decades. In its original form, a lot of warehouse space or light industrial space was mixed with a small amount of office space. And in many locations here and nationwide, that still holds true. Nationally, the average blend of use is 40 percent office and    60 percent industrial.<P>But Corace and other western Pennsylvania developers - such as Burns & Scalo Real Estate Group - have carved out a niche by developing flex space that caters more to the office user than the warehouse tenant. So image-conscious tenants can combine upscale front-office operations with less plush back-office operations. And with office space tight in both the central business district and the fringe markets, prospective tenants are seriously considering flex as an option.<P>"The demand is increasing," says Jack Donahue, vice president of commercial real estate firm Grubb & Ellis. "The market is getting a lot tighter, and office tenants are considering flex space because the occupancy cost is less than Class A office buildings."<P>Today, Corace has 100,000 square feet of flex space at Abele filled primarily with small firms that on average take up about 3,000 square feet of space. Some use as little as 1,200 square feet, and none use more than 9,000. <P>Corace is breaking ground this spring to add another 60,000 square feet and keep up with market demand.<P>Burns & Scalo Real Estate Group, meanwhile, already has 275,000 square feet of flex space at Bursca Business Park, plus another 100,000 square feet at Southpointe. Both sites are in the Interstate 79 corridor south of Pittsburgh.<P>Burns & Scalo will add more flex space at Southpointe and break ground this year to build a 100,000-square-foot facility in Cranberry Township.<P>"When we first started this, we thought there was going to be a small percent of office use versus a lot of warehouse," says Burns & Scalo principal Jim Scalo. "But the market trend as these products become better located, as the product has matured, is that we are finding it's heavier office use."<P><P>Why Flex? <P>The hot niche product here has been the flex space that's geared more to predominantly office operations.<P>What's it got over traditional office space? For one, an office building is not easily accessible for deliveries and is too expensive - in Pittsburgh, as much as $10 per square foot more than flex space - to use in part for storage or light assembly operations as many firms do. The traditional industrial warehouse, on the other hand, lacks the desired upscale image of an office building.<P>At Burns & Scalo's Southpointe site, Columbia Energy Services has executive offices plus a less plush trader's pit where commodities traders work the phones and watch the ticker board overhead.<P>Not far away, Synergistic Technologies mixes front-office operations in its space with a wide-open light assembly area that's large enough to fit a van inside.<P>At Abele, rust block buildings with cedar siding blend in with the wooded landscape.<P>From the outside, the front of the buildings look upscale and classy. But drive around the back, and there are the loading docks.<P>The tenants who are finding flex space suitable include sales and service operations, home healthcare offices and distribution centers for high tech products such as electronics and computer items.   <P>"In that scenario, this is a guy who wants to blend his rental rates," says Scalo. "He needs an office and needs a shop. By bringing them together, he blends the high office rental rates with the low shop rental rates, into a medium rental rate."<P>In the Pittsburgh market, that medium rental rate usually ranges from $8 to $13, depending upon how much of the space is actually used for office. The more office space, the higher the price.<P>Some tenants are smaller, service-oriented organizations that need high-end space but cannot be in pure office buildings because they require the loading facilities. At the same time, industrial buildings lack the image that these tenants want to project.<P><P>Happy Campers<P>You won't hear the flex developers complaining about their tenants being predominantly office users. Simply stated, the developers get a better return on their investment from office users since the rates are higher when the space is predominantly office.<P>"No matter how these buildings are used, it costs the same to build these buildings," says Jeremy Kronman of Gold & Co. "Take Burns & Scalo, for example. When the space is used for all warehouse, the tenants pay $9 per square foot, versus $13 per square foot for using it all as office. So the more office space, the better the return for the developer."<P>And it doesn't hurt that western Pennsylvania's topography makes it tough to build flex. Developers need to find large tracts of flat land so they can build the long, one-story buildings  typical of flex structures.<P>Insiders say most of the good spaces already are taken,  overpriced or improperly zoned. That tends to limit competition and keep the market tight.<P>The topography of hills and valleys is perhaps the dominant factor. Donahue of Grubb & Ellis says national investors see the western Pennsylva-nia terrain and start looking elsewhere. <P>Could that change? Possibly if the market remains extremely tight, according to Tom Black, a commer- cial real estate analyst with the Washington, D.C.-based Urban Land Institute.<P>"I think national investors tend to view easily supplied markets as being more risky for obvious reasons - there's more competition," Black says. "So in the sense that the Pittsburgh market is tough to supply, national investors may view it as less risky and come in here."<P>And if the high tech industry continues to develop, that would only fuel the demand created by the tight office markets.<P><P>The Office Users<P>When people like Scalo or Corace present their pitch to office users, it's pretty simple and to the point. They hammer away at cost and convenience.<P>In traditional office buildings, tenants split the cost of space used for stairwells, elevator shafts and lobbies. So the tenants are paying for gross square footage over and beyond what they actually use.<P>"When you take the single-story product, you eliminate the cost of unused space," Scalo says. "A lot of customers can take less square feet because they don't pay for the residual waste."<P>"The operating expenses are higher in traditional office buildings," says Donahue of Grubb & Ellis.<P>There are also other benefits, such as parking, which is often plentiful and nearby. And some business parks featuring flex space have other amenities such as walking trails or fitness centers that make these parks pleasant places for people to work.<P>"It's absolutely the product of the future," Scalo says. "This product makes sense, which is why it has had success."<P>




