<center><B><font size=+2>The Summer Term
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Quick and Painless</font></b><br>

<i>By Gretchen McKay</i></center>
<hr>


<P>Taking Classes During the Summer is an Easy Way to Continue One's Professional Education or to Accelerate a Degree Program Already in Progress; For the Schools, It Means Exposure and Dollars<BR><BR>Summer school.<P>It's a concept bound to evoke groans from anyone under the age of 18.<P>But to some Pittsburgh adults, the opportunity to take courses in the summer is anything but a vacation buster. In fact, summer school makes sense, allowing students to continue their professional education, accelerate a degree program already in progress, or play catch up after a particularly demanding spring term. <P>It also enables high school seniors looking to jump-start their college careers and "visiting" students, those home on break from colleges outside of Pittsburgh, to pick up a few extra credits to transfer toward their degrees.<P>Make no mistake: summer sessions can be demanding. Matriculating during the summer usually means learning the same amount of material, and chalking up the same number of contact hours, in a much shorter period (typically over the course of 5 to 6 weeks instead of a semester).<P>And there's no break when it comes to cost.<P>Still,  summer programs are business as usual for most institutions, despite a smaller student body. There may be fewer courses to choose from - fewer students mean fewer tuition dollars - but the schedule of classes is almost always an extension of what's offered during the rest of the year.<P>The exception is upper-level courses, often limited because they may be too difficult to digest in such a short period. Students may also have to get used to new faces, since most schools rely on part-time or adjunct professors - who don't earn benefits - to teach many of the classes.<P>Deciding which courses to offer involves something that Dr. Jo-Ann Sipple, vice president for academic and student affairs at Robert Morris College, calls "magic." Administrators must study patterns of enrollment and course sequences to ensure a "break-even" number of students in each class. They must also determine which courses will be attractive to visiting students, a large percentage of any summer program, as well as what faculty will be available to teach.<P>At Robert Morris, summer students can sign up for most of the school's regular course offerings during a three-week intensive spring session, two five-week sessions or one 11-week evening session.<P>The roster includes everything from accounting, communications and computers to management, marketing and finance. As a result, notes Sipple, those who want to make progress toward their degree can pick up what's required without having to wait for fall term. <P>Community College of Allegheny County, too, offers a "meat and potatoes session" at 13 different locations. The schedule, offered in two six-week sessions and one 10-week session,  comprises a little over 500 classes in nearly a thousand sections.<P>"Summer is a pretty big deal," says Academic Dean Rich Betters, "and an integral part of many degree programs for our students." It's important to visiting students, as well: Up to 38 percent of CCAC's summer clientele are degree-seekers at other institutions.<P>Yet adults aren't CCAC's only customers; it also markets a few special programs for area youth. Their "Come to College" program for children and teens offers a blend of academic, recreational and exploratory classes. In addition, kids can sign up for a summer military camp and a "Come Fly With Us" course exploring careers in aviation.<P>Chatham College, too, seeks the nontraditional student during its three-, five- and seven-week sessions. Nearly one-quarter of its total summer offerings, in fact, are unique to that semester.<P>Here's why: Chatham only opened its campus up to summer school in 1992, and as the new kid on the block, "You have to position yourself as unique in the marketplace," says Shaik Ismail, dean of continuing education.<P>So in addition to more than 50 traditional courses, Chatham students can choose from 10 innovative programs and workshops, such as a mothers-and-daughters program in performing arts, a course in marine and freshwater ecology for high school girls and a Spanish class focusing on health and medical terminology.<P>The college also has a six-week summer day camp, with sports, music and the arts, for children in grades one to nine.<P>Point Park College strives to set itself apart from its competitors by offering several accelerated programs during the summer in addition to the traditional courses in English, science and theater arts. Summer students can "stack" courses by taking two on the same night, earn three credits in three weeks through the Saturday seminar  or take courses "special delivery," which are once a week for ten weeks.<BR>How do colleges go about filling those vacation-time classrooms? Most go the traditional route, advertising in local newspapers, magazines and on radio, and by mailing the schedule of classes to corporations. <P>Others go one step further. Chatham, for example, purchases lists of students with Pittsburgh addresses who attend other schools, then sends them their summer circular; CCAC mails a course brochure to nearly every resident zip code listing in Allegheny  County and places ads in college newspapers within the tristate area.<P>The effort pays off: Though summer programs aren't necessarily cash cows, they do account for a substantial amount of revenue. At Point Park, for example, summer students generate about 10 percent of the tuition revenue for the year, according to James Errett, vice president of finance and administration; at Chatham, summer programs pull in about $500,000 of the college's $14 million budget.<P>"It has to be profitable," says Chatham's Ismail, noting the school must still cool and clean the campus, as well as pay the faculty. "It would be impossible to carry off if we didn't more than break even." <BR><BR>
Special Supplement<BR><BR>Guide to Southwestern Pennsylvania Colleges and Universities<BR><BR>Executive Report is pleased to present this education guide. Included in this alphabetically arranged listing are the colleges and universities in Allegheny, Armstrong, Beaver, Butler, Cambria, Fayette, Greene, Indiana, Lawrence, Somerset, Washington and Westmore-land counties. The guide details admission criteria, academic departments and programs, financial aid information and special nontraditional programs. In each case, upcoming academic programs are listed where available. Figures reflect the 1995-96 academic year. As nd suggestions are welcome.<BR><BR><BR><BR>Allegany Community College <BR>(814) 445-9848<BR>R.D. 5 Box 24C<BR>Somerset, PA 15501-8314<BR>This is a branch campus of the Cumberland, Md.-based Allegany Community College.<BR>Major schools/departments: business, criminal justice, electromechanical, general studies, nursing, finance, computer/data entry<BR>Degrees: A.A., certificates<BR>Admission requirements: application, high school transcripts or equivalency diploma<BR>Tuition: $3,240<BR>Students receiving financial aid: 60%<BR><BR>Butler County Community College <BR>(412) 287-8711<BR>P.O. Box 1203<BR>College Drive<BR>Butler, PA 16003<BR>Butler County Community College was established in 1965.<BR>Major schools/departments: allied health, business, humanities and social sciences, natural science, technology, nursing<BR>Degrees: A.A., A.S., A.A.S.<BR>Admission requirements: vary by program<BR>Undergraduate <BR>enrollment: 3,133<BR>Tuition: $1,200<BR>Students receiving <BR>financial aid: 36%<BR>Number of scholarships available: 80<BR>Corporations that have recruited on campus: 12<BR>Recent academic programs: medical assistant, physical therapist assistant, CAM/ CNC technology, communication arts/graphic design, early childhood education<BR><BR>California University of Pennsylvania <BR>(412) 938-4000<BR>250 University Ave.<BR>California, PA 15419<BR>California 