<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Supplement5.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>Wanted
</font><BR>
<font size=+1> A CEO who Wants to Grow<BR>the Company, Not Downsize it 
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<P>
<hr>

An executive search firm recently studied the trends of its clients and came up with this shocker: The demand is slowly declining for chief executives whose primary concern is the bottom line. <P>Let's hope so. Cost reduction at most companies has hit the wall. The fat is gone. <P>Many of these CEOs battled the bottom line via downsizing. For some, the process became analogous to a jogger going on a crash diet just before a marathon. Consider that runner, trying to get by on less and less while demanding maximum performance from the body. In the end, the body can't function like it should, and the rest of the runners jog on by.<P>In business, it's the competitors -- those lean enough to be efficient, productive and customer-oriented at the same time -- that pass you by. And loading up on carbohydrates won't do you any good by that time. It's too late.<P>It's fine to concentrate on operational efficiency, restructuring and downsizing for a period of time in order to survive. But when the short-term gains have been realized, companies must pursue an agenda of growth and new business development with as much passion. They must, without question,  pursue the long-term future. <P>"If you call a quarterly earning a result, this quarter and next quarter, yes, [companies] are getting the results they want [from downsizing]," says consultant Alan Downs, author of the book "Corporate Executioner" and former counselor of companies that used  downsizing strategies.<P>"[The companies] are trimming expenses and they are seeing profits increase," says Downs. "If you're looking at the long-term -- let's say five years -- in almost every case they're not seeing an increase in profit, they're not seeing a reduction in expenses. They're seeing a decrease in customer service, they're seeing a decrease in productivity."<P>They're also seeing their competitors pass them by as growth strategies are ignored.<P>Downs cites Eastman Kodak as a prime example. Anorexic Kodak has restructured five times since 1985, cutting 12,000 employees in the process. Through all this, revenues have increased only slightly. The same scenario has played out at many other companies, including one I know that recently introduced a new product without having sufficient marketing and sales personnel in place. The new product was a good one, but the target markets knew little about it. <P>Hopefully, that is changing. Christian & Timbers, the same executive search firm that says bottom-line-oriented CEOs are "out" also says there is a demand for CEOs who are customer driven. Giving the customers something they want is definitely a growth strategy.<P>Companies that do not try to please customers by anticipating and fulfilling their unarticulated needs and that do not think differently about competitiveness had better prepare for their next wave of restructuring and downsizing. These companies will become less and less competitive in the future, necessitating yet another downsizing. It eventually becomes a vicious cycle, cutting until there is nothing left.<P>The irony is that yesterday's stars -- the CEOs who attacked the bottom line via downsizing -- are becoming today's laggards. Some will be reluctant to rethink the organization and unwilling to overthrow the very systems that have supported their ascendancy. Their organizations are doomed to failure.<P>Let's hope they check their egos at the door and think about growth. Or they won't have much of a company left in five years.                	     	    <P>


<hr>

