<B><IMG border=0 align=left SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><BR>
<BR><FONT SIZE=+2>Back From the Road<BR>We can Learn From Our Southern Neighbours 
</FONT SIZE>
<font size=+1></font><BR>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b>
<hr>

After 4200 miles over 28 days with stays in 17 different hotels and 100 interviews, I return to Pittsburgh with new insights to the factors contributing to the South's impressive growth. I headed south to study our high-growth neighbors: Atlanta's 100,000 new jobs created last year and South Carolina's $1 billion in new investment lured me to investigate the secrets to their successes. I needed to know whether all that glistens is gold.<P>The Interstate 95 corridor's growth record doesn't just glisten. It shines. Michelin and BMW, two of South Carolina's newest recruits, don't make location decisions casually. Pittsburgh's southern competition is undeniably formidable.<P>Atlanta's burgeoning crime rate, gridlocked traffic and intense pockets of poverty do not deter development -- at least yet. Likewise, South Carolina's abysmal public education system and sleepy pace do not  impede growth. All these communities I visited are fraught with problems as they compete for private investment dollars. Yet, they do compete.<P>The key to success lies in advancing opportunities commensurate with the problems. Those areas that used their problems to foster opportunities ultimately prevailed and prospered.<P>In almost every case, periods of significant hardship became the impetus for change. Crises paved the way for new and unorthodox approaches in economic development.<P>Business as usual became business as unusual, transforming sleepy towns into industrial powers. Business led the charge with help from government. Not vice versa. Politicians played a critical role, but were not the orchestrators of success.<P>In addition, our high-growth neighbors shared other commonalities as well. Most importantly, they saw themselves as connected to the outside world.  A deep water port, a world-class airport or easy access to interstate highways served as the vital connection to the outside world.<P>These communities view themselves from the outside in and are entirely customer-driven in their new business solicitations. Furthermore, their efforts are precise and calculated.<P>Alternatively, Pittsburgh views itself from the inside out. It applies old, but proven solutions to new problems. <P>Our June and July issues will feature a detailed description of the key factors causing the South's stellar performance. This magazine will examine, in particular, key success factors that Pittsburgh can best apply.<P>Crises prevail here. Let's use them to our advantage as agents for change.<P> 



<hr><BR><BR><BR>

