<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Build it
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>Forget About a Baseball-Only Stadium;
</font><br>
<font size=+1>The City Needs a Sports Complex</FONT><br>
 <i>By Jim Mitnick
</b></i>

<HR>

Over the past several years, we have heard much about the need for a new baseball-only stadium, the need to expand the David L. Lawrence Con-vention Center, the need to develop the theater district, expand retail and shopping downtown and develop the riverfronts.<P> Very few disagree that our rivers are one of Pittsburgh's greatest assets, and any development must provide access for the public to enjoy. The expansion of the convention center will increase convention trade shows, hotel occupancy and support restaurants and local business. Additional retail will provide added diversity to downtown and expand one's experience when visiting downtown.<P>But what would happen to us if the Pirates, in five years, moved to a larger market because the team could not afford to be competitive in this market?<P>Consider what would happen if the Penguins no longer had an outstanding team and could not support themselves because of inadequate facilities.  <P>Consider this nightmare: the Steelers moving to Cleveland.<P>As strange as this seems, it can all happen, and then what would become of downtown? People would go downtown for work, then return home. That would be it. Downtown would open at 9 a.m. and close at 5 p.m.<P>There are too many examples of cities that have ignored the aforementioned possibilities. And as Cleveland is finding out with the Browns' proposed move to Baltimore, if you wait too long to act, sometimes it will be too late.<P>Now may be the best time in Pittsburgh's history to consider building a sports complex that would guarantee professional sports in Pittsburgh for the next 50 years and anchor future development in downtown.<P>If a new baseball park is inevitable, then where is the best location?  The options are limited to the land adjacent to Three Rivers Stadium along the Allegheny River, land in the Strip District, an area at the end of Grant Street, a suburban site or perhaps the South Side.<P>The one area that has never been considered is the current location of the Civic Arena. The advantage of such a plan includes its adjacency to downtown, the Port Authority busway, Crosstown Boulevard, light rail transit, utilities, easy access to downtown services including shopping and dining, the convention center, theater district ... the list goes on.<P>What about the Civic Arena? Good question. This all means what many of us have known for a long time: The Civic Arena should be replaced. Let's face facts: The Civic Arena is now 35 years old and no longer meets the criteria for a major sports facility or entertainment center. It pales in comparison to facilities in other cities.  <P>At the same time, Pittsburgh would have the opportunity to fix an eyesore that has existed at 6th Avenue and Grant Street for over a decade. You have USX Tower on one side, One Mellon Center on the other and vacant property in between.<P>Here's the plan: Let's consider including the baseball-only stadium in a new entertainment facility for hockey, basketball, indoor soccer and other sports above the subway station at 6th Avenue and Grant Street between the Crosstown Boulevard and Ross Street.<P>These plans -- although bold -- would still allow for the riverfront        to be used for private development with public access and would permit a hotel to be built at 6th Avenue           and Grant Street to support the downtown business district and the convention center.<P>This also opens up the possibility of renovating Three Rivers Stadium to allow for the reconfiguration of the lower bowl seating for football and    the enjoyment of the fans. Football  was not meant to be played in round stadiums.<P>If this could be accomplished along with other economic development currently planned, our downtown will become a destination point and truly an asset to Pittsburgh and our region. We should give people a reason to come downtown, not to stay away.<P>But this will only happen if planners think long-term. We can't just hurriedly drop a baseball-only stadium in the first convenient site. The Civic Arena is just as much a dinosaur as Three Rivers Stadium. Let's think long-term and develop a plan that addresses several of the city's impending problems at once.                                          n<P>Jim Mitnick is vice president of the Pittsburgh office of contractor Turner Construction Co.<P>


<hr>


<P>


<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

