<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>
</i></b>

<HR>
<b>A Peek At the History Center</b><p>The public won't get its first look at the Pittsburgh Regional History Center until it opens late next month in the Strip District, but ER got an early peek. Here's our advice: Make sure you check out the history center after it opens April 28.<P>The building -- the former Chautauqua Lake Ice Co. building on Smallman Street -- is worth seeing alone. The brick walls are two or three feet thick in some places, and the structure is supported by massive wooden pillars and beams that were brought in from the Northwest when the 160,000-square-foot building was constructed in 1898.<P>They don't build structures like this anymore.<P>"The pillars and beams are spruce," explains John Herbst, executive director of the Historical Society of Western Pennsylvania. "Back then, we didn't have trees here that were this large. We did have a good rail system, so this lumber was brought in from the Northwest by train."<P>Of course, the real attraction will be the exhibits, which will include homes from the region's different eras. The timeline starts with a log home, circa 1780, that is a reproduction of an actual log home built by a Whiskey Rebellion insurgent from Cecil Township, Washington County. From there, the next stop is a 1908 millworker home from Homestead. And finally, a 1952 brick home from West Mifflin.<P>Herbst says actors will welcome visitors to the homes and explain to them the history.<P>The main floor includes a 1940 trolley car that actually rolled into the building on tracks left from when Chautauqua Ice occupied the building. Years ago, trains carrying ice from Lake Chautauqua rolled into the structure for unloading.<P>The main floor is wide open, and Herbst says groups will be able to use it to host receptions or dinner parties. The dinner capacity is 300, but it jumps to 1,000 for cocktail receptions.<P>Upstairs, other attractions include a classroom equipped with a kitchen that Herbst says eventually will be used for ethnic cooking classes.<P>And most importantly, don't miss the business archives, which include letters written by Andrew Carnegie. Other larger collections include business and commercial records from Alcoa, H.J. Heinz, Horne's, J&L Steel, Mellon Bank, Kennywood Park and the Allegheny Conference on Community Development.<P>The history center is named for late U.S. Sen. John Heinz.    <p><b>Workplace Violence: One Study Says it<br>Can Be Prevented</b><p>                 A computer stolen, personal property destroyed, even bomb threats or violence in the office ... the stress of problems at home exploding in the workplace is a manager's worst nightmare. Workplace violence at least causes property damage and stress on the whole office. At its worst, the results can be tragic.<P>And according to one new study, the possibility of violence is very real, but can be prevented if the right steps are taken ahead of time.<P>The University of Southern California's Center for Crisis Manage-ment conducted a study of violence in the workplace, aiming to find  solutions through better management. The study was sponsored by the International Facility Management Association, PepsiCo, Taco Bell and Pizza Hut. <P>Forty-three percent of companies responding to the survey reported at least one violent incident in the last three years, including employee theft, weapons in the workplace, fraud and bomb threats. <P>But the study also found that violence can be avoided with some pro-active measures: One recommendation is to build background checks into hiring. Employee assistance programs also can help lower the chances of violent incidents. For instance, the study found that an effort to identify hotspots and help employees manage stress, drug problems or other personal or work-related problems lowers threats and heightens productivity.<P>It's also important to communicate company strategies or initiatives to employees, rather than leaving them to draw their own conclusions about the future. <P>The study's sponsor, the IFMA,  conducts research and educates businesses on management strategies for human resources, organization and real estate assets, and has branches throughout the U.S. and Canada.     <P><b>More Growth Companies</b><P>In the December issue of ER, we told you that Saxonburg-based II-VI Inc. was the region's No. 1 growth company. II-VI's staggering growth rate of 62.36 percent over the past five years placed it atop the sixth annual list.<P>The Top 10, compiled by Parker/Hunter Inc., gauges public companies on the growth of their earnings per share over five years. What we didn't mention were the names of some other companies with strong growth that did not make the list because of "technicalities."<P>Medrad, for instance, had a five-year growth rate of 20.33 percent, which would have placed it at No. 5 had it not been acquired by Schering AG.<P>And where was Fore Systems? It was among five companies that have shown substantial growth but did not make this year's list because of insufficient history. The others were American Eagle Outfitters, Black Box Corp., Cable Design Technology and General Nutrition Centers. The requirements for consideration are pretty simple:<P>1.	The company must be headquartered in southwestern Pennsylvania.<P>2.	Shares must be publicly traded on the New York Stock Exchange, American Stock Exchange or NASDAQ.<P>3.	The company must have five years of historical earnings per share data available.<P>4.	After excluding all extraordinary gains and charges, a company must have reported earnings in each of the past five years, and estimated 1995 earnings must exceed the prior year's.<P>5.	Those companies with peak earnings prior to 1990 are excluded.<P>6.	The company must show positive revenue growth over the past five years.<P>7.	The five-year growth rate is calculated using the least-square method. The data points are the past five years' earnings per share data and the current year's analyst projection. If an analyst projection is unavailable, we use analysts' consensus data from Zack's Investment.<P>8.	All earnings per share data are for the fiscal year end of each individual company.<P><b>A Shock Jock In The Market</b><P>Howard Stern went on the air on WXDX 106.7 FM in Pittsburgh in November, exposing listeners to the belches and dirty words that have made him the most famous disc jockey in the country. Stern predicted he would be No. 1 in the ratings in Pittsburgh within a year.<P>But was Secret Communications, owner of WXDX, taking a gamble? It slotted Stern opposite Scott Paulsen and Jim Krenn, the region's top-rated morning team at WDVE, which Secret also owns.<P>"Conventional radio wisdom doesn't apply in this hyper-competitive market," says Gene Romano, operations manager for both stations. "Our long-term goal is to have the dominant rock combo in the U.S., and that requires two dominant morning shows. Howard will help the X own new rock in Pittsburgh."<P>During Stern's on-air press conference last year, Stern, who traditionally declares war on the top DJ in each new city by holding a "funeral" for them,  asked about the competition, but was for the most part restrained. No funeral was held for Paulsen and Krenn.<P>"Times have changed for Howard," says Romano. "I don't think that's a major priority for him anymore."<P>Romano's priority is to entrench Secret Communications at the top of the Pittsburgh rock market. Romano says changes in communications law mean that Secret can pursue the goal of controlling the rock segment of the airwaves here. In other words, more advertising dollars would be paid to Secret.<P>Currently WDVE plays rock, while WXDX has an alternative music format. Plans may be in the works to acquire another station pursuant to  new regulations allowing ownership of more than two stations in a market. WXDX will eventually move to 105.9 FM, currently held by WAMO, and boost its wattage from 47,000 to 72,000. WAMO will move to 106.7 FM in a swap that includes a $14 million payment from Secret to WAMO owner Sheridan Broadcasting.<P>Romano says the strategy pitting Stern against Paulsen and Krenn makes long-term sense, and that he has great confidence in Paulsen and Krenn to get better and better. As for Stern? In his first month on the air, he rocketed into third place among 25- to 34-year-olds with an 8.6 share, while Paulsen and Krenn maintained a solid domination with a 21.4 share.                                 n<P>




<hr>

