<HEAD>
<TITLE> ERIndex </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H13ERIndex.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>We Told You So
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Respironics' Strong Month Proves Its Doubters Wrong
</font><BR>
<i>By Doug Thomas
</i></b>

<HR>
Respironics is on a roll.<P>The company capped a phenomenal period of announcements in early 1996 with perhaps the best of them all: The Food & Drug Administration cleared the company to market two new masks designed for use with its airway pressure delivery systems. It was just another affirmation of Respironics' leading position as the world's leading maker of respiratory medical products.<P>Earlier, Respironics had posted record results for its fiscal second quarter, which ended Dec. 31, without sacrificing its investment in research and development. Sales rose 27 percent while earnings increased 30 percent. Gross margins remained strong at       56 percent. Sales in Europe were also higher than analysts had predicted.<P>The FDA also granted Respironics approval to market its Aria CPAP System in the United States. The Aria is the most technologically advanced and patient-friendly device on the market for sleep-apnea sufferers. <P>All of this is vindication for chief executive Dennis Meteny and the rest of the management team, who as recently as last summer were fighting off ridiculous accusations from short-sellers. In these pages in the July issue, we correctly predicted the resurgence of Respironics and its stock price. At the time, the stock price was 13 1/2. It closed in early February at 23 5/8.<P>Around the Index<P>	Performance was mixed among ER Index companies for the month ended Jan. 19, with technology companies and stainless steel producers doing well and with banks and healthcare companies generally performing poorly. Declines of 10 percent or more in General Nutrition, Mylan, Northstar and Tuscarora offset solid performances from Westinghouse, Universal Stainless, Cable Design and Mine Safety, leading to a 1.18 percent decline, slightly worse than the S&P 500's decline of 0.73 percent.<P>Since inception, however, the ER Index has maintained an edge over the S&P 500, returning 33.84 percent to the S&P 500's 32.65 percent.<P>u	One of the newest members to the index, Universal Stainless & Alloy Products, posted an exceptional       13.1 percent gain in the month to        11 7/8. Universal Stainless, headquartered in Bridgeville, is a mini-mill that manufactures and markets semi-      finished specialty steels. <P>For its fourth quarter and full year ended Dec. 31, the company reported dramatic increases in sales and earnings. Net income for the fourth quarter increased to $1.2 million or 24 cents per share, versus a loss of $1.3 million or 44 cents per share a year ago. Sales for the period increased 139 percent to $12.5 million. For the full year, net income reached $2.7 million or            57 cents per share on a 718 percent increase in sales to $46.9 million. The primary driver of this growth is the explosive demand for stainless steel, resulting in in-creased volume and a growing customer base. Many larger competitors who have been unable to meet demand and are unwilling to invest to expand capacity have chosen to outsource production to specialty steel companies like Universal Stainless.<P>u	After a poor performance last month, technology stocks staged a comeback. II-VI Inc. announced results for its second quarter ended Dec. 31, with net income jumping 40 percent to $834,000 or 14 cents per share, on a 34.7 percent gain in revenue to          $7.9 million. Bookings for the quarter increased 56 percent to $10.5 million. Says Francis Kramer, the company's president: "The record bookings for the quarter reflect the ever increasing demand for our products. We have recently completed a major manufacturing expansion program and are poised to meet the challenge."<P>u	Cable Design Technologies continued its strong performance with its second month of double digit increases, appreciating 15.4 percent. Taking full advantage, the company announced on Jan. 23 that it plans to sell an additional 5.7 million shares of stock. It will mark CDT's second secondary offering since the company went public in November 1993. <P>u	Shares of Mellon Bank fell 4.66 percent, after the company announced earnings that fell a penny short of analysts' estimates. Net income for the fourth quarter of $164 million or $1.18 per share came in below the average estimate of $1.19 per share. One factor contributing to the shortfall was an increasing provision for loan losses that reached $35 million.                         n<P>Doug Thomas is vice president of research for Lancaster, Pa.-based Emerald Asset Management.<P>
<P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

