<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>



<P>
<B><I><font size=+2>David Calamosca</font></I></B></center><P>


<HR>
<b>
Name:		David Calamosca<BR>
Age:            41<BR>
Personal:       Wife,Ruth, and two children, Mica, 6, and<br>
                Sarah, 3; lives in Penn Hills<BR>
Education:      B.A., Education and Social Sciences<br>
                University of Pittsburgh, 1978<BR>
Last Vacation:  To Italy, last October<BR>
</B>
<hr>
If you call the number on a jar of Davide pasta sauce you'll likely get David(e)'s wife. For Davide's 18 pastas and eight jarred sauces pass the true litmus test for homemade: They're made in David Calamosca's basement -- outfitted with commercial stirrers, cookers, pasta drying racks and the like -- from fresh ingredients he procures daily through local produce vendors.<P>Still a cottage industry, Davide's business plan is based on sweat and serendipity -- he not only hand makes, but hand delivers his products, which appear in local retail stores from GNC to Food Gallery to Pennsylvania Macaroni Co. But where once he filled 12 quart containers and sold them out of a Coleman cooler, now he's brewing up to 5000 pounds of sauce a day in his basement to fulfill contracts with hotel chains, which put his pasta on menus from Albany to San Francisco.<P>His secret? "Never compromising," says this former teacher and singer of Italian ballads. But it's been a rocky road -- early on, he made sauce exclusively for a developing chain called the Italian Oven, which led to a lawsuit that remains in civil court. Though he wouldn't talk about that dispute, he admits entrepreneurship hasn't been easy. ER's Lydia Strohl talked to Calamosca in his Penn Hills basement.<P>ER: How did this all start?<P>DC: I always tinkered around in the kitchen, since I was a child. About seven years ago, I took public my skills in making Italian food, and people began to embrace it. I only made one red sauce, and I wanted to make it with the highest quality ingredients of any sauce on the market. I think it's still true today: I don't know if people use the amounts I do. They'll say olive oil, but there might be more salt than oil, or they won't say if it's cold press. <P>I got started on a challenge. I was going to go to Nashville. I had been working as a musician for several years -- I do ballads, songs of life -- and I had some contacts there. The man that worked for Mr. Rogers at that time --  the Purple Panda, Lenny Meledandri -- owned a restaurant in New Kensington. He had just come back from Italy, and he said, David, I've never tasted food this good in my life.' We met through Mr. Rogers, who I met when I working at Turner's Dairy, here in Penn Hills. The two of them teamed up and gave me the push to market the sauce that I was making. Otherwise, I was ready to go to Nashville. I had a job lined up at a health club, I had met the guitar player for the Judds.<P>So I didn't go. I stayed and launched the business from nothing, with a Volkswagen Rabbit and Coleman coolers and a stove. I stood on the streets and in supermarkets sampling for several years before it took hold. It was tough.<P>ER: How much sauce were you making when you first started?<P>DC: I bought plastic containers down in the Strip District. I think I bought 50, and I made like two dozen and wondered, Will I ever sell all these?' I went down to the Strip and went to a store and they said they'd try it. I sold 24 pints of sauce, and I was amazed. <P>ER: And how much sauce and pasta are you making now?<P>DC: On certain days we . Otherwise, I was ready to go to Nashville. I had a job lined up at a health club, I had met the guitar player for the Judds.<P>So I didn't go. I stayed and launched the business from nothing, with a Volkswagen Rabbit and Coleman coolers and a stove. I stood on the streets and in supermarkets sampling for several years before it took hold. It was tough.<P>ER: How much sauce were you making when you first started?<P>DC: I bought plastic containers down in the Strip District. I think I bought 50, and I made like two dozen and wondered, Will I ever sell all these?' I went down to the Strip and went to a store and they said they'd try it. I sold 24 pints of sauce, and I was amazed. <P>ER: And how much sauce and pasta are you making now?<P>DC: On certain days we can make close to 5,000 pounds. We have about 18 pastas now, and eight different jarred sauces and six frozen sauces. The frozen are very small, and we're trying to reduce those. We still sell them in Pennsylvania Macaroni because I sampled there for a year. They're good, they're just hard to sell without the marketing.<P>The sauces are variations on a theme. We take the original sauce and add spice, or a little bit of mushrooms. About four years ago we started making pastas too. Very unique pastas, with fresh vegetables added, fresh garlic -- I call them accent pastas. Some of them are multi-grain, which offers nutrition. Some are made with egg whites, for people who don't want the cholesterol. They have to be one of the freshest pastas on the market, because we have such a small inventory. We're always making food.<P>ER: How wide is your distribution network geographically?<P>DC: For our retail trade, mostly in the Pittsburgh area. We first started making our sauce and putting it in plastic containers and freezing it. But we found that people don't generally look for pasta sauces in the freezer. Where I would go and sample, people would remember and come back and buy it. But I have two degenerative disks and it's hard for me to sample every day.<P>We bought a couple of pieces of equipment so that we can jar our sauce and put it out on the shelves with the other sauces. So at least we're in the same neighborhood. But the stores we haven't expanded much. We're still in the Strip District at Pennsylvania Macaroni, Benkovitz, places like the Shadyside Market, Food Gallerys. We sell a certain amount of pasta to basket companies -- Basket of Pittsburgh in the South Hills -- they send things made of Pittsburgh products. Generally we try to cater to the specialty stores. We also draw attention from the health food stores. It's an all-natural product, it fits into the Italian category, we fit into the gourmet arena, so there's three or four main avenues for the sauce. But unfortunately, other than direct sales, I really haven't spent any time or funds on marketing. I think that's why we're sitting in my basement now. <P>     Maybe I was an idealist, but I had hoped that people would read labels more, that people would look at the product itself -- but when you get a sauce that might end up costing 30 percent more than commercial sauces, then you look at it and say, Well, what's the difference?' And people don't have time to look at it and read the label -- some people don't. They're not going to experiment for $3. But the people who have tried it, my goodness.<P>ER: How did you raise money to get the business started?<P>DC: There was no money. A friend of mine had a pizza shop and I was licensed to make the product there. I've never taken a loan for anything. The traditional Italian way is to buy as you can afford. That's the way I did it. My car was paid for. I bought Coleman coolers. I bought the pot. I bought the gas to put in the car and drive around. This house was half this size. It was paid for. This is an old community -- my grandparents lived here, my father came from Italy. We've lived in this community since the '20s. I think I got one loan, for the Ford out there. It's mostly sweat, drive and conviction.<P>I'm glad I did it this way. People said, You can't do it. You'll never sell a sauce. Your ingredients are too expensive. You can't keep up with the volume.' Obviously, you can't provide for all of America, or all of Pittsburgh, out of a basement. I'd like someday to sell it to the whole country, that's my goal, to show people la verita de la cusine Italiana -- the truth of the Italian cuisine.<P>I lived in Italy many years. If you went to Italy and showed them the commercial sauces, they wouldn't know what you were talking about. I've had people come many times and just for jokes we'll open jars of commercial sauces. They'll say, What's that?' And I'll tell them, That's what the Americans call pasta sauce.' And they just laugh, and we eat our homemade sauce, and go on with life.<P>ER: Do you still do all your own face-to-face marketing?<P>DC: Yes. I have Rusty, who's been here about a year, and Janet, who's been here for five years, my mother -- bless her she's 73 -- comes over and helps. We got hit hard in 1991, we lost about 90 percent of our business. My mother and father both came over here -- if it wasn't for family I would not be able to survive. <P>ER: What kind of profit can you make?<P>DC: It's not that big. The gourmet stuff is $2.45 a jar, for 14 ounces. We started selling the pints for $2.75 seven years ago. Now they're $2.45. I haven't raised my prices extravagantly. I buy more, so it costs a little less, but that was seven years ago.<P>It costs me almost $2.00 to make it. I make a whopping 50 cents on the jar, maybe $6.00 on the case. But it's all straight forward, it's legitimate. You can't hide taste. There's no fine print. It's real honest.<P>But let's face it, some people can't afford it. Even if it's a lot better, to raise a family on a 14-ounce jar of gourmet stuff is snobbery.  So in 1995 I came out with a 26-ounce jar that is really good. It is not a compromise. So what if it just has pure olive oil. So what if I put a little water in with the tomatoes. So what if I don't use carrots, I just use onions and garlic, so I don't spend all that time chopping. It's still really good, but it's a Chevy, it's not a Mercedes. <P>The 26-ounce jar sells for about, on average for a good mark-up for a store, about 30 percent. The consumer can get it for $3.49. That's about          50 cents more than the closest competitor. You can get a Classico for about $2.69. <P>But that $3.49 sauce, I promise you, anyone with a scrutinizing palate will love it. For crying out loud it costs $2.99 for a bag of chips. They're getting olive oil, onions, fresh tomatoes -- I still use the best tomatoes in all my sauces. I'm hoping it's going to pull this business to another level.<P>ER: The bulk of your sales is wholesale? What's the percentage?<P>DC: Probably about 70-30. We've been fortunate to pick up a number of hotels. One particular buyer came to us from an international company about three years ago. They have quality people and a master chef. They said, This is the finest sauce we've ever tasted.' I still service them, they're my largest account. There are a number of hotels that use it -- Marriots, Sheratons, Holiday Inns, Don's Bar, New York Palace -- from Key West to Albany. There are a couple of restaurants here that use it too.<P>We have so many calls where people have said, I just want you to know this is the best stuff I've ever had.' <P>ER: How do you let people know that?<P>DC: I don't. I'm a stone age marketer. I don't run coupons or specials. A part of me is prideful in that respect, because I'm thinking of how it was. <P>I was very prideful. It had to be the best. But I've gone from extra virgin to pure olive oil -- that to me was a step down. But by most people's standards -- my gosh, you can buy sauce with  hydrogenated soy bean oil in it. When you're not using it, you got a leak in your radiator?<P>But it's my face on that jar. This is homemade, we're sitting in my home. It's not home-style, it has no lady on the label who probably never existed. It's the truth.<P>I'm a tangible guy. I work with vegetables, with things you can see. This business represents anybody who wants to strike out on their own and do it better, do it with honesty and integrity. It is becoming increasingly difficult, because there is a drunkenness and a stupor that has blinded a lot of us to the truth. I think we're all compromised. The whole country has just sort of said, We don't care any more.'<P>ER: How do you stick to that as your company grows?<P>DC: You end up in your basement, in Penn Hills. You're with your children, you haven't made them orphans. I want to make a difference in the way people eat and the way people think. I'm just getting back to good old American values.<P>The way I expand my product line is just to do something that's good, and to try to do it better than anyone else. Cooking is an art, it goes through you. My seafood sauce is based on my dad's recipe, but it's the way I interpret it. At the level we're at, we're as homemade as -- it would be like if you came in to buy shoes and we took that shoe and built it around your foot. That's how we do things. Four thousand gallons -- do you know what commercial plants make in one day? It's 200 miles wide and 400 miles long just where they grow tomatoes. They produce like 10 million cases of tomatoes in six weeks. I'm like a grain of sand.<P>ER: What are your plans for the future?<P>DC: This is January, we just had two or three feet of snow. I don't know, I guess I'm waiting for a Messiah. <P>One thing is to continue to invest in my employees, give them a good environment, create more products, keep my family together, keep my health. Basically do what I've been doing for seven years. There are probably a lot of people like me. I don't know how many people make Salsa Italiano in their basement. <P>ER: Do you want to always keep it here in your basement?<P>DC: My goodness, no. There are times, before we had improved our ventilation, that you'd smell like garlic all the time. It's been hard. Even if you want to take a day off, people come to your house. It's a quiet little living and it's convenient. But my goodness, I would love to get into another facility. I would like to do that, and to hire someone to do the sales. I'm beat up. I'm burned out. I'm waiting for something beyond my ability to happen.<P>This kind of stuff is what made America. You can be a philosopher, you can be a dreamer, but you have to have a trade. Or else you're just a cream puff. What I would like to see is I do what I do best, that I make the food and someone come along and use it. I just want to make it, and go for my walks in the woods, and go to Italy.   <P>
<P>



