<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Making Mama Proud
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>A Native Pittsburgher Brings Some Unique Flavors Home
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<p>

<hr>
He's been 'round the world twice, worked with  Wolfgang Puck and Robert Carrier, pioneered "spa" cuisine, and fed celebrities like Jack Nicholson and Woody Harrelson. Now, Pittsburgh native Eric Melley is back, to serve his mother.<P>Yes, his mother, Nina, after whom his new restaurant in Highland Park is named. Formerly La Foret, the restaurant was sold to Melley by friends Candace and Michael Uricchio last fall. After a lightning quick facelift, Nina opened in late December. <P>Like a lot of the restaurateurs coming to town, Melley knows how important the little details are. The service is remarkably friendly; the ladies' room boasts real towels, and a self-service concierge desk is in the offing. Melley is contracting with local artists to show work on the walls of Nina's two dining rooms, which will seat about 65. Downstairs is casual, but the upstairs room is elegant, painted in shades of cream and taupe and furnished with the original chairs. <P>But Melley is first and foremost a chef, and the food is Nina's shining star. His "New American" cuisine blends tastes from the world over. <P>The menu reads easily. Rather than spending time coming up with fancy and confusing names, Melley titles appetizers simply potato sandwich, portabello or shrimp.  Entrees include gnocchi, beef, chicken and salmon. In the subtext, however, we find that a potato sandwich is not just a couple of russets on Wonder bread, but "built with smoked salmon, lemon creme fraiche, sevruga caviar and warmed chive sauce." <P>The important thing to note here is that Melley not only creates a dish to sound good on the menu -- his cook staff really delivers. The dishes we tried were cooked to perfection -- no underdone meat, no half-hearted herbing, no afterthought side dishes. They also plan to offer, for $49.96 (in honor of the year), a tasting menu of a minimum of five courses, made with the best and most exotic ingredients available that day. And Melley promises to be rigorous about quality control.<P>"If I'm not here, we're not open,"says Melley, 34, who lives on the restaurant's third floor. <P>For appetizers, we chose the cavatelli, a penne pasta graced with smoky prosciutto chunks and tawny nuggets of pumpkin, creamy goat cheese and a sage sauce. The ingredients were fresh, and the tastes nicely balanced. We also tried the antipasti, which will rotate, but this night consisted of a sweet red pepper and goat cheese spread with crusty baguette, roasted garlic and grilled asparagus with frisse (a green resembling chicory) topped with lemon vinaigrette. Although not remarkable, it was beautifully balanced. The Nina salad is a nice mix of greens with a lemon herb dressing. The dressing is light and conservatively applied, accentuating the differing textures and tastes. <P>For entrees, we chose the salmon, seared to perfection, served on a bed of creamy leeks and surrounded by a port basalmic vinegar sauce. Dots of hand-crafted artichoke gnocci circled the fish -- they were smooth palate cleansers, with a hint of citrus. The beef was the killer, a perfect filet encrusted in pepper, coriander and herbs, also on a bed of creamed leeks. The wine list is quite expansive and reasonable, but is mostly what was left from La Foret's cellar. That will change, but hopefully the innovation and reasonable prices will not.<P>Stick around for dessert. The espresso granite resembles a gourmet sno-cone, shaved ice flavored like the richest coffee ice cream imaginable. We also tried the chocolate macaroon sandwich, a chewy hunk of macaroon enclosing white chocolate and vanilla bean mousse and slices of mango, in a raspberry puree.<P>Melley's talking about another restaurant, and about cooking classes on days the restaurant is closed.<P>Seems he's here to stay. Yea for Nina. Yea for Pittsburgh.                   <P>


<hr><P>


