<HEAD>
<TITLE> EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Weighing In</b> 
</font><br>
<font size=+1>With Foerster Out, Who Will Pull the Strings in Harrisburg?                

</font><BR>
<i>By Jim Strader
</i>

<HR>
In the not-so-olden days, one of the surest ways to get things done in Harrisburg for the Pittsburgh area was to see Tom Foerster.<P>The longtime political potentate had ties to the Capitol forged as far back as his days in the Legislature and tempered over the quarter-century he served as chairman of the Allegheny County Commissioners. Working relationships with governors and fellow Democrats in the General Assembly  helped the region gain needed attention and dollars over the years.<P>But last year's political shakeup changed all that. <P>Oddly, the political demise of Commissioners Tom Foerster and Pete Flaherty was started within their own party. In the spring primary, Democrats ousted Foerster and Flaherty and chose state Sen. Mike Dawida and Colleen Vuono to run in the fall. Voters in the general election finished the job, by giving the commission majority to Republicans by re-electing Larry Dunn and pairing him with Robert Cranmer.<P>Fresh from the Senate, with plenty of Capitol contacts and connections, Dawida seemed poised for Foerster's mantle. Instead, he picked up Dunn's cloak as minority member of the board and Dunn began building his own regime.<P>The unexpected turn of events poses the question: Who gets things done for Pittsburgh in the Capitol?<P>"I think a rising star will be Jack Wagner, though he's still a <P>quasi-freshman senator," says political observer William J. Green. <P>Wagner, a Democrat, succeeded the late Sen. Eugene Scanlon after serving as Pittsburgh City Council president and losing a bid for mayor. Hart, a Republican from the North Hills, heads the Senate Finance Committee.<P>"Given the turnaround, you have to look at people like Jack and Melissa Hart," Green says. <P>As for the state House, Green sees things as "a little more muddled." A slight Republican margin last year forced the ouster of Democrats Bill DeWeese of Greene County and Ivan Itkin of Allegheny County from majority leadership positions. Republican Matthew Ryan of Delaware County replaced DeWeese as speaker. Itkin lost the majority leader's job to John Perzel of Philadelphia. <P>"The seniority has really taken a beating out here on both sides," Green says, also noting the loss of Scanlon, a longtime lawmaker. "DeWeese, I think, still holds up this end of the state and western Pennsylvania fairly well."<P>"You really have a new game here," says political consultant Dennis M. Casey. "You have new troops coming on the field. We've got a new governor in Harrisburg; you've got new county commissioners here."<P>Power brokers of the past, Casey says, built alliances on shared experiences, such as efforts to soften the decline of the steel industry. Today's leaders lack that kind of common history and the authority that comes with it, he says.		<P>"Nobody seems to have yet emerged to be the policy wonk of western Pennsylvania and as I think about it, it's a little bit scary," Casey says. "That relationship just isn't there anymore."<P>Mayor Tom Murphy came to city hall from the statehouse. But  Murphy's tenure has not given him the opportunity to do much with his Harrisburg links, Casey says. <P>"He's sort of exhausted his clout. I think Tom's like a guy who's on a ship that has 18 holes in it and he's busily running around plugging holes. The ship's still afloat, but everybody knows that it's sinking," Casey says.<P>"Murphy has to go to Harrisburg hat in hand now. He's not going up there to bring them something, he's always asking for something."<P>Others from the Pittsburgh area are in key positions in Harrisburg. Tom Corbett, the former U.S. attorney, is now attorney general. Upper Saint Clair's Mike Fisher, the Senate majority whip, hopes to succeed Corbett. <P>And the region can rely on Gov. Tom Ridge, Green maintains, no matter that the governor's home is in Erie and that he spent a dozen years in Congress fighting for the interests of the state's northwest corner.<P>"Gov. Ridge, born in Munhall, is still deferential to western Penn-       sylvania," says Green, who was an aide to the last governor Pittsburgh sent across the Susquehanna, Dick Thornburgh.<P>"There's still a friend in the governor's mansion," Green says.                 <P>
<P>





<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

