<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H17Education.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<center><b><font size =+2>
Really Cooking</font></B><br>
<B><I><font size=+1>As More Families Elect to Eat Out,<br>Culinary Schools Find Their Students in Demand
</font></I></B><br>
<i>By Gretchen McKay</i></center>

<HR>
Amie Ruffner knew what she wanted when she graduated from high school last year: a good job, fast.<P>College? Not quite. She enrolled at the Pennsylvania Institute of Culinary Arts in downtown Pittsburgh.<P>"I didn't want to stay in school too long, and I've always loved to cook," the 18-year-old says. But the biggest draw was the potential for work.<P>"Even a college degree doesn't guarantee a job today," Ruffner says. "But the culinary field is filled with opportunity. People are always going to be eating."<P>Ruffner knows of what she speaks. The future is bright for those considering careers in the culinary field, thanks to the increasing number of two-income families and working mothers who've come to rely on eating out. The U.S. Department of Labor predicts the number of jobs in the food service industry to grow by 30 percent in the next decade, from 9.5 million jobs in 1990 to 12.4 million in 2005.<P>What's more, the demand for professional cooks and chefs will jump by 35 percent during that period, from 602,000 to 879,000 positions. <P>Though it's not a particularly lucrative career at first -- culinary students typically earn between $15,000 to $20,000 their first year out of school -- it holds potential. Top chefs can easily pull in six figures, and motivated young cooks can expect to double their starting salaries within five years. <P>There are five schools in the region that offer degrees in the culinary arts, with programs ranging from 16 months to three years of study and costing between $4,300 and $20,000. Ruffner's school, the Pennsylvania Institute of Culinary Arts, accepts more than 700 students from 36 states each year. They choose between two associate degrees in food service: specialized technology in culinary arts and specialized business in restaurant management. <P>Both accredited tracks take 16 months, or four semesters, to complete. They include a four-month paid "externship" at the end of the program.<P>Restaurant management students also get hands-on experience operating the school's street-front restaurant, Brendan's, on Liberty Avenue.<P>But the real selling point, says PICA vice president Tom Pasternak, is their 100 percent placement record. <P>"We spend time and effort in each and every student, and it pays off," says Pasternak. "Recruiters come back year after year because we train cooks who are able to work hard and know what they're doing."<P>The tuition cost of $18,962 covers books, materials, uniforms and cutlery for the entire program.<P>Only a few blocks away is the International Culinary Academy, which accepts 250 students a year. There, the four-day school week is headed up by executive chef Joseph D. Parrotto Jr. Over the course of the 18-month program, students spend 75 percent of their time in the kitchen lab.<P>They also study the business side of the culinary world, with courses in business math, entrepreneurship and kitchen operations. Both tracks end with a paid externship.<P>ICA boasts a 99 percent placement rate for its graduates, placing cooks and pastry chefs in all of Pittsburgh's top restaurants as well as five-star resorts and restaurants around the country. <P>"We have established a strong reputation because employers know we have well-trained people," says Parrotto. "We do not put students out of this school who can't do the work."<P>ICA's total tuition cost is $15,550, which covers books, materials, uniforms and cutlery. <P>Relatively new on the scene is the Indiana University of Pennsylvania Academy of Culinary Arts, located in Punxsutawney. It accepts between 85 to 100 new students each fall. <P>IUP, which started its culinary arts program in 1990, offers a 16-month, four-semester certificate program under the direction of Chef Albert Wutsch. The 2,250-hour curriculum also emphasizes the business aspect of professional cooking, with courses in management, computers, purchasing, accounting and menu design. Students must complete a paid externship prior to graduation.<P>What sets IUP apart from its competitors, says Wutsch, is the fact that the culinary school is a division of a full university, thereby affording students access to everything on campus. Culinary graduates can transfer 36 credits toward a bachelor of science degree in hotel, restaurant and institutional management.<P>The cost of $14,792 includes textbooks, uniforms and equipment.<P>On a budget? The most affordable culinary programs in the area are those offered through two community colleges: the Community College of Allegheny County and the West- moreland County Community College.  Like the more expensive schools, the community colleges include kitchen training under professional chefs and paid externships at the end of the programs.<P>The main difference is cost: CCAC is $4,300 for the three-year apprentice program and $3,760 for the two-year associate degree program. WCCC is even less expensive, topping out at about $3,000 for its programs.              <P>
<P>



<hr>

