<HEAD>
<TITLE> Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Law.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Protect the Business</font><br><font size=+1>Small Businesses That Tap Foreign Markets Have a<br>Built-in Safewguard When Domestic Markets Go Flat<br>
</font></B><i>By Henry Lipput</center></i><P>


<HR>
When executives at Bricmont Inc. sat down to develop a long-range strategy a few years back, they knew they had strong domestic markets, but still wanted to broaden the company's horizons.<P>Smart move.<P>Small businesses like Bricmont leave themselves vulnerable when they limit the markets in which they can sell their goods and services. It's the proverbial putting all of your eggs in one basket.<P>Bricmont would have none of that.<P>"The domestic market has been fairly good, this [exporting] is really on top of our traditional business," says David C. Gilbert, senior vice president of sales for Bricmont, a construction engineering firm.<P>"We sat down a few years ago and decided to do a strategic plan, and the <P><P>strategic plan really involved a commitment to do more and more offshore work.  Not necessarily because the market was flat at the time, but traditionally, the industries we deal with here are very cyclical.  We wanted <P>to expand our business to help <P>offset some future low point in the U.S. market."<P>Now, only a couple years later, overseas work accounts for about 60 percent of Bricmont's total sales. The Washington County firm specializes in combustion and heat transfer, catering primarily to steel, glass and aluminum producers.<P>The impetus for the current <P>surge of foreign orders was a recent domestic job that involved a new kind of furnace.<P>"The main product we've been successful with offshore, at least to start with, is a tunnel furnace that is a specialized type of furnace that fits into a new process," says Gilbert. <P>The furnace was developed by a German company, but its first purchaser was an American company.  Bricmont got the order to install the new furnace and has used it as a springboard to attract other clients, mostly foreign, who were interested in the new process.<P>"As a result of our involvement we had a very good competitive advantage," says Gilbert.  "People in Mexico wanted to do it, the next thing the people in India wanted to install one, and obviously we were one of the preferred bidders for the furnace then as a result  of our experience in doing the first."<P>Gilbert believes that beginning an overseas marketing effort can be a very <P><P>expensive proposition unless you have something unique to offer. <P>"In our case, we got involved with a new technology that was timed perfectly in the industry and was needed by a lot of the third world countries," he says. "We sort of rode the coattails of new technology."<P>Other companies are less deliberate about exporting. Bally Design of Pittsburgh, for instance, had foreign jobs fall in its lap as a result of previous relationships. Founder Alex Bally, through his employment at Westing-house's Corporate Design Center and teaching at Carnegie Mellon University, has acquired a number of foreign contracts, including one for athletic shoemaker Adidas.<P>"One of my former students, who worked with us, left Bally Design and eventually ended up at Adidas," Bally says.  "He heard that they had tried to design a robot, a testing robot, for soccer shoes and soccer balls, and that they couldn't find anybody who could do it or dared.  He suggested to them Why don't you call those guys in Pittsburgh, they might do it. They'll do anything.'"  	<P>It wasn't a job that Bally sought, but it wasn't one that he was going to turn down.<P>"Our view has been more of going where we're wanted, and where we're needed, and where the projects are, and where we can make a difference.  And if they happen to be overseas, great.  We're not really actively pursuing that in the sense that we have foreign marketing strategies or something like that. But we have a pretty successful track record [with our foreign clients] and they keep coming back.  It seems to have its own momentum."<P>The Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Development Council created international trade development to provide support to local companies that hope to export.  In 1994, the Council surveyed 700 local companies concerning their export activity and found there was a "lack of commitment" on the part of small and medium-sized businesses in the region when it comes to international trade.  Although there are a relatively small number of experienced exporters in the region, the council concluded that a majority of businesses could increase their level of international business fairly easily and, in the process, also help the local economy.<P>The bulk of companies not ready to export were those with less than 50 employees and without the resources to begin an overseas marketing effort.  The council recommends that businesses work together to establish small trading networks as well as mentoring cycles, trade alliances and client tracking systems to help each other to increase the export capabilities of <P>the region.			    <P>
<P>



