<HEAD>
<TITLE> Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Sports.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>No-Complete Covenants</font><br><font size=+1>Did a Pennsylvania Appeals Court<br>Ruling Limit Their Effectiveness?<br>
</font></B><i>By Jim Urban</center></i><P>


<HR>
Shortly after Insulation Corp. of America fired Richard Brobston in 1993, the former ICA general manager ignored a noncompetiton agreement he previously had signed and went to work for a competitor.<P> ICA, in turn, went straight to civil court in an attempt to enforce the no-compete agreement.<P>A Lehigh County judge upheld the contract, which barred Brobston from working for any competitor within 300 miles for three years. But the Superior Court of Pennsylvania had other ideas. On appeal, the court reversed the decision and sided with Brobston in a ruling that some say is bad for employers.<P>"It had long been thought that such agreements were enforceable whether the employee left the company voluntarily or was terminated. That is, until now," says attorney Thomas Madigan of Cohen & Grigsby. <P>In Brobston's appeal, the Superior Court turned the case in his favor because Brobston was fired for the declining or stagnant sales among his accounts. The court reasoned that if Brobston was of little value to ICA, then ICA should have no concern about his working for the competitor.<P>"The employer who fires an employee for failing to perform in a manner that promotes the employer's business interests deems the employee worthless," Superior Court Judge James Kelly wrote for the appeals court panel. "Once such a determination is made by the employer, the need to protect itself from the former employee is diminished by the fact that the employee's worth to the corporation is presumably insignificant."<P>For years, employers have required their technical and sales employees to sign no-compete agreements. Penn-sylvania courts traditionally recognized such agreements as business necessities, enforcing them as long as the employee received something in return for signing and the no-compete prohibitions were reasonable in terms of duration and geographic scope.<P>"In one sense, the [Brobston] ruling gives employees subject to noncompetition agreements job security," says Madigan. "Employers will have to think twice before terminating an employee subject to a noncompetition agreement, letting him or her free to work for a direct competitor."<P>Arthur J. Schwab, a veteran litigator for Buchanan Ingersoll, says the Brobston ruling mirrors those in other states and is not that surprising. <P>"The courts have always applied equitable principles," Schwab says. "It's always been more difficult to enforce no-compete agreements when you terminate an employee without cause, especially for lack of performance."<P><P>Make It Enforceable<P>A key to enforcing no-compete agreements is narrow construction, according to Schwab.<P>"Particular customers, products, particular market segments," says Schwab, "the more narrow the covenant the more apparent it is to the court that the employer has a legitimate, protectable interest."<P>Most employers can start with a standard form, but it should be modified so it is unique for that specific employee, Schwab says.<P>"Don't try to get more than you need," adds Robert McTiernan of Tucker Arensberg. "If you need a period of time to get someone trained and acquainted, that's the amount of time you put in the agreement.<P>"Courts will wonder if you are just trying to burden a future competitor or really protecting your own business interests," McTiernan says.<P>As with any contract, each party must receive something in return for what they're giving up. Pennsylvania courts say mere continued employment is not adequate. Thus, it's wise for employers to include some sort of promotion, bonus or salary increase in consideration of the employee's signature on the no-compete agreement. In the Brobston case, Brobston received a $2,000 raise when he signed the no- compete covenants, and the court said that was adequate.<P><P>The Future<P>Labor attorneys say they see  employers using the no-compete agreements in an increasing variety of industries. And in a way, the increased use is turning these agreements into double-edged swords.<P>While no-compete agreements do protect the employers, they also limit the pool of talent from which employers can hire. There may be four good candidates to fill a position, but all four may have signed no-compete agreements with their employers.<P>So what's the employer who is looking to hire supposed to do?<P>"Anymore, I get almost as many calls from perspective employers     who are trying to hire someone        who is subject to one of these agreements," McTiernan says. "Many are reluctant to challenge an agreement in court. You hire the employee, and         it creates litigation for the employer. You are immediately sued. You incur legal fees.<P>"But one client fought this and won. As it turned out, this was a very good em-ployee for the client and I think the client felt it was well worthwhile in the end."  <P>
<P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

