<HEAD>
<TITLE> Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Law.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Athletes and Restaurants</font><br><font size=+1>Here's One Guy Who Smiled When<br>Rod Woodson Blew Out his Knee<br>
</font></B><i>By Bill Modoono</center></i><P>


<HR>
It's probably safe to say that Bill Dieterle was the only person in Pitts-burgh who could see the bright side when Rod Woodson was felled by a season-ending knee injury early in the 1995 season.<P>OK, he's from Cleve-land, but this was not Browns' love at work. This was strictly business.<P>"When he got hurt, I smiled," Dieterle says. "I knew he had hit a home run for us."<P>"Us" in this instance refers to Woodson's All-Star Grille, which Dieterle, a national restaurant consultant, and Woodson, the Steelers' Pro Bowl cornerback, opened in August. While Woodson's injury limited his availability for the Steelers, it increased his presence at the restaurant.<P>"The key ingredient in this is the active involvement of Rod Woodson," Dieterle says. "I knew his injury would mean he would be around more, and  that would add credibility to the restaurant."<P>Though athletes have been opening restaurants since the time of Babe Ruth, today's public wants more than just a famous name on the napkin. For these star/restaurateurs, credibility in the restaurant business extends to the tenderness of the sirloin.<P>What's happened is the restaurant business has merged with the entertainment business. The best examples of this are the Planet Hollywood restaurants opening around the country, always after splashy soirees fea- turing celebrity owners Arnold Schwarzenegger, Sylvester Stallone and Bruce Willis. You don't go to Planet Hollywood just for a meal; you go to bask in the star power.<P>In Pittsburgh, star athletes such as Woodson are the celebrities. And Woodson's, located near Station Square, entertains immediately. To the left, a gift shop sells NFL jerseys, T-shirts and assorted other items, including the menu, which resembles a game day program. To the right is a video arcade. Scattered throughout are authentic-looking sports uniforms and helmets, and the big screen TVs common in sports bars.<P>It's the kind of place people get a kick just walking around. Many do.<P>It's also a place where people enjoy being during big sports events such as Steelers playoff games. At press time, the restaurant  was on pace to do         $5 million in business during the first full year, well over Dieterle's original estimate of $3.7 million. After Super Bowl Sunday, the ante will certainly have gone up. And while the place does seem to have multiple personalities -- part family restaurant, part tourist attraction, part business lunch and part sports bar -- the combination is working much better than it did for the former Sports Garden.<P>So Woodson's has made it, right? Hardly -- remember that sirloin.<P>Getting exposure -- which most athlete-owned establishments can do quite well -- is only part of the battle, and a small part at that. Ask Mike Ditka, whose restaurant in Chicago closed after a few years. Perhaps the Chicago Tribune said it best: Jocks in the restaurant industry usually do about as well as businessmen would do as linebackers in the NFL.<P>The famous name can pull customers in once, but diners won't return if the prices are high and the food lacking. <P>And it's important to keep the spacious Woodson's filled; any sense of emptiness is just magnified on a slow night. Word gets around quickly in a town like Pittsburgh. It doesn't help that the restaurant business is highly competitive: For most restaurants, a pre-tax profit margin of 4 percent is good.<P>"Restaurants operate under an extremely narrow profit margin," says Wendy Webster of the National Restaurant Association. "It's an extremely labor-intensive industry."<P>So the question is: Will Pittsburgh diners still find Woodson's tasty after the novelty wears off? Woodson would do well to emulate another Steeler defensive back, J.T. Thomas of the Super Bowl teams, who runs the Applebee's franchise in western Pennsylvania. Nobody goes to his restaurants because he's connected to them; they go for the food, price and atmosphere. <P>If the same can someday be said of Woodson's, he will have arrived as a restaurateur.                                           <P><P><P>
<P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

