<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Sports.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H15Health.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>In Clear View<br>
</font></I></B>

<b><font size =+1>Eye Surgeons See More People<br>Who Want 20/20 Vision ... Now</b></font><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
</center><P>


<HR>
Ray Jakomas has worn glasses his entire life. When he was younger, it meant the usual taunts of "four eyes" and "bottle corks." Mildly annoying.<P>But as he became older, his 20/400 vision actually became dangerous: as a construction worker, Jakomas spent most of his time up four stories or  higher, even when weather conditions reduced visibility through his glasses.<P>"When it would rain, I couldn't see for the mist on my eyes," says 53-year-old Jakomas, who wore glasses to work and contact lenses at other times. "It was a pain. Every morning I would get up, and have to put on glasses or contacts before I did anything."<P>Jakomas investigated radial keratotomy, a surgical procedure that corrects nearsightedness by making tiny incisions in the cornea, flattening its surface. (Nearsightedness occurs when the eyeball has too steep of a slope, affecting the way that light hits the back of the eye and making vision blurry.) He refrained from RK after investigation, opting instead to wait for a procedure then under FDA review: photorefractive surgery with the excimer laser. Last fall, PRK was approved. <P>Just weeks later, Jakomas underwent the procedure in one eye (it's recommended to do one at a time). After putting a few numbing drops in his eye, which was held open with a lid speculum, to numb it, Dr. Richard Stout scraped away the top layer of Jakoma's cornea with a metal tool. Then all Jakoma saw was a series of red flashes accompanied by loud crackling zaps. He catches a whiff like burnt hair. <P>The laser, which takes 200 pulses to cut through a human hair, has done its work in just 20 seconds. <P> Jakomas was almost immediately liberated from eyewear -- the post-op eye now has 20/25 vision.<P>Drs. Kondrot/Stout & Associates has had the excimer laser since 1989, as one of five clinical sites chosen by the FDA to investigate PRK. Stout estimates that between PRK, RK and ALK (automated lamellar keratoplasty, for more severe nearsightedness), he's performed about 3,000 refractive surgery procedures in the past 10 years, the majority in the last three.<P>"It's like being a carpenter -- you have to be able to use all the tools in your bag," says Stout. "Certain results are equal in terms of vision. But with higher amounts of nearsightedness,  the RK incision has to come in closer to the pupil. So with [higher amounts] I lean towards doing excimer laser. When patients come in I explain the advantages and disadvantages of each."<P>The industry is hoping that the American public will focus on the advantages. Indeed, refractive surgery is widely seen as a shot in the arm to many ophthalmologists, with decreasing rate structures and managed care eating away at their revenue. Both RK and PRK are elective procedures, and, at $1,000 an eye for RK and $2,000 for PRK, potentially lucrative.<P>But entering the market is not without risk: Summit Technologies, manufacturer of the FDA-approved excimer laser for PRK, estimates at least $1 million in first-year training and equipment costs to get it up and running. The machine alone is $485,000, plus $50,000 in annual maintenance.<P>It is, however, a risk that many are willing to take. Over 60 million Americans are nearsighted and, according to Summit spokeswoman Nancy Duden, analysts at Smith Barney have predicted that in 1996 alone, 200,000 of them will try the surgery. The company had sold 100 lasers at press time, and is spending multimillions on a nationwide ad campaign. They also plan to partner with hospitals nationwide in establishing a chain of 20 to 30 Summit Vision Centers. While none are slated for the Pittsburgh area, the technology will appear here in spades. Eye and Ear Hospital has purchased a laser.  Kondrot/Stout already owns one. St. Francis Medical Center is participating in a joint venture with Cincinnati-based chain LCA-Vision, which is setting up in eight cities. Their laser will be up later this month.<P>But while none of the doctors interviewed predicted a decrease in the price of PRK due to the excess number of local lasers, several did express concern that the procedure would be overly recommended to finance the expensive technology.<P>In fact, some ophthalmologists caution that refractive surgery as a whole has a long way to go before it's recommendable. For one thing, there are no guaranteed results for any of these procedures, which are expensive and rarely covered by insurance. But most importantly, they take perfect eyes, correctable to 20/20 with eyewear, and put them at risk.<P>"In RK, you're cutting 99 percent of the thickness of the cornea, and you always have the cuts. So you can actually rupture the eye if it's hit in the right place, like playing racquetball or tennis," says Jean Hardwick, M.D., a cornea specialist. <P>But Dr. Deepinter Dhaliwhal, chief of refractive surgery at UPMC's Eye and Ear Institute, says that updated techniques and equipment have decreased those risks enormously. The National Eye Institute recently released a study of RK results: A decade after undergoing RK, about 85 percent of 427 patients reported at least 20/40 vision, with few vision-threatening complications.<P>Though long-term results of PRK in this country are as yet unavailable, proponents say results from other countries show PRK to be as consistently successful as RK, or more. But others disagree.<P>"I've talked to ophthalmologists in Greece and Mexico who do PRK, and they say they only get the results they want 50 percent of the time, because the procedure depends on human healing, and that you can't predict," says Hardwick.<P>It's true, some will heal too much: Ray Jakoma, though delighted his nearsightedness has been alleviated, says he's now a touch farsighted -- necessitating his holding documents out away from his eyes to read them. Others will heal too little and require a second operation. And scar tissue resulting from RK can cause poor night vision.<P>Jakoma knows these possiblities. On the day he's scheduled to have the second eye done, he is so nervous that Stout must hold his head firmly to align the laser. There are 10 minutes of preparatory work, then the 20-second operation. Stout slips a bandage contact soaked with antibiotic into Jakoma's eye. Jakoma will come back tomorrow and have that removed, after which he anticipates about a day of discomfort as the eye heals. But that's it.<P>No more wise cracks about bottle corks. No more questions about whether his glasses are bulletproof. No more fumbling around with glasses and contact lenses.<P>"No trouble," Jakoma says. And he walks out of surgery 15 minutes after he arrived, minus the glasses.                       n<P>
<P>

<hr>

