<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>From the Kitchen Table to the Corner Office</B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+>Business Smarts, Raw Ability and a Little Luck Helped <br>FORE Systems Grow From Humble Beginnings to Wall Street Darling
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Richard Bierck</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>
Eric Cooper is sitting in his posh office at FORE Systems, and around him it's business as usual: FORE is acquiring another high tech company. FORE's stock is climbing. FORE is adding new employees daily.<P>And not far away in Marshall Township, construction workers are building the $40 million headquarters campus that will house all FORE operations, along with new, even more posh offices for Cooper and each of his three cofounders: Francois Bitz, Onat Menzilcioglu and Robert Sansom. <P>It wasn't always like this.<P>As a matter of fact, it wasn't like this at all for this $100 million high tech company that perfected the technology that allows people to communicate instantaneously via computers.<P>"The first mailing address was Francois' house," Cooper recalls. "It was the usual thing where we started on a kitchen table."<P>But in just over five years, Cooper and his mates have gone from the home office to the corner office, from the kitchen table to the executive dining room.<P>Many know the story of FORE's current success. This is the story of FORE's early days.<P>It was those early, modest days of FORE Systems that laid the foundation for the success FORE enjoys today. <P>Most notably, FORE's founders -- all researchers from Carnegie Mellon University -- pulled it off without adventure capital, the seed money many businesses use to survive from the concept stage to the stage where the business is established and self- sufficient.<P>FORE took a different route, linking up with the Naval Research Labs at a very fortuitous time. The Defense Department was revising the manner in which it spent its money. It wanted top-quality work at competitive market prices. In return, many contractors -- including FORE -- retained the right to take that same technology commercial. They could even sell it to the Russians if they so desired.<P>FORE'S Bitz, Menzilcioglu, Sansom and Cooper freely admit that if the Navy contract hadn't come along when it did, FORE probably wouldn't be a household word among tech-stock watchers.<P>"Considering that we had no business track record or contacts with traditional funding sources, it would have been very difficult and, I would guess, impossible for us to have gotten started,'' says Cooper, now chairman and CEO of the company.<P>"If we hadn't gotten the contract, we would have had to have a million dollars at an early stage.''<P>That's not an amount of money that is easily raised, as anyone who has tried to raise adventure capital in  western Pennsylvania can attest. But FORE's founders had perfect timing.<P>A Navy Contract<P>The Navy's ultimate goal was to spur private development of a standardized technology rather than a proprietary one that would lock the Navy into a single contractor and hold taxpayers hostage to high rates. And because the Cold War ended, the Defense Department wasn't as concerned as it was in years past about keeping technological advancements secret. <P>"It's the old $800 toilet seat, $600 hammer," Cooper says, looking back. "Everyone knows that the commercial, off-the-shelf versions cost a fraction   of that.<P>"In the computer tech area it was even worse. You'd get these systems the military commissioned, and then they were locked forever into that contractor to supply them. They wanted to get out of that,'' Cooper says. "The military was well into the new way of thinking -- they no longer wanted to be captive to suppliers and buy military-use only technology.<P>"The rationale was that the commercial marketplace would drive economies of scale, price, performance and so on, to allow the government to get a better deal, because they were just  part of a broader market.''<P>The Navy was right, and FORE was among a handful of defense contractors who benefited from the new spending philosophy.<P>Landing the crucial Naval Labs contract wasn't just out of the blue. The FORE four had worked for the labs previously, so their expertise was a known commodity. This, along with a competitive bid, got them the work.<P>Cooper remembers the relief the fledgling firm experienced when FORE got the contract. "It was tremendous. I think that's what gave us personally enough assurance that, yeah, we could quit our day jobs. That was what really assured us that we could make a go of it."<P>It also meant that Bitz got his kitchen table back. As soon as FORE landed the Navy contract, the company leased 1,300 square feet of space on Murray Avenue in Pittsburgh's Squirrel Hill neighborhood and bought used computers and used furniture.<P>It was still humble, but it was a step ahead.<P>FORE's Niche<P>FORE's founders believed the lucrative future of networking lay in developing asynchronous transfer mode, a technology that links together computers and enables them to share information instantaneously.<P>In early 1992, FORE delivered what the Navy had ordered -- a networking device using an ATM switch that allowed computers to share data, video and voice.<P>It was an auspicious delivery. The four scientists, who named their company with an acronym for their first names, were objectively assured that the prototypical networking device was superior to any on the market. <P>FORE's technology ushered in the current networking era -- one in which corporate executives can ship a training video to dozens of employees sitting at their own personal computers and answer digital questions simultaneously, by voice and by shared notations on screen.<P>"ATM is the plumbing that allows this to happen,'' says Cooper.<P>The technology links multiple computers across a building or city or between states, allowing them to interact in multiple media simultaneously and share information that is effectively broadcast from server PCs within the network.<P>"The one thing that stuck in our minds on the initial project ... was the idea of developing a networking solution that would keep up with the high-end desktop computers that engineers and scientists were already using, because even then it was apparent that these were insufficient, and there     didn't seem to be anything in sight to improve the situation,'' says Cooper.<P>Menzilcioglu, FORE's president, believes the technology would have been available soon, even if FORE had never existed, or if the Navy had        not been seeking to spur its private development.<P> "I'm sure this idea, if not through NRL, would have caught on,'' says Menzilcioglu. "Would we have this? I'm not sure;  it's all timing.''<P> FORE's technology hinged on  a network that FORE's founders had developed  in an earlier CMU research project.  Though commercially infeasible -- in part, because it couldn't be standardized -- its essential principles were solid.<P> "Our [original] research goals put us thinking in this general direction,'' says Cooper, who's equipped with         a propeller-head beanie given him      by an investment banker ("We are    high on the geek quotient,'' he likes to say). <P>"Conveniently, the research project was ending. There were a lot of decisions up in the air about what the next phase of the project would be.''<P>At the time, the prevailing networking wind was blowing toward high-performance equipment, so many researchers aspired to develop networking solutions for super-    computers.<P>"This was not really a direction we thought was very interesting. We saw that supercomputers were going to be less and less important in the marketplace than mass-market computers, and that a network aimed at them would be more interesting for us personally,'' Cooper says. "We decided, well, we can take what we've learned and start over again using the idea of ATM. We learned about it because it was discussed in the standards committees being driven by the telecommunications industry.''<P>Applying the technology to networking then was just a concept, one that the four computer scientists began to focus on. "We thought it was applicable there ... and we seemed to be the only ones who did. We had easily a year lead [because of the Navy research], when no one else was trying to do the same thing. <P>"I can remember our biggest concern was, if this is such a great idea, why isn't there anybody else doing it?''<P>At the Pentagon<P>Did the Navy Labs expect FORE to come up with the solution it did, and to prosper subsequently?<P>Hank Dardy, chief computer scientist for the Naval Research Labs in suburban Washington, says there were no certainties, but the odds looked good early on. <P>"The Department of Defense basically looks for good technology. They looked like good technical people, and we took the chance. We hoped that, if the company's good, good technology comes out, and we can buy it instead of a proprietary solution,'' says Dardy.<P>What brought the Navy and the company together in the contract was a common belief that ATM was the best networking solution, assuming that it could be developed.<P>"The Department of Defense had to come to grips with why we couldn't support [image, voice and video] in a single network. ATM's cell size allowed this,'' says Dardy.<P>"This size is slightly larger than what you want for voice and slightly smaller than what you want for data, and it works if you do it right, with the right silicon.''<P>Without the government contract, FORE might have had to resort to venture capitalists for seed funding. This might have meant selling most of the company, and selling it cheap. Instead, in 1992, after FORE was up and running, the company sold 30 percent of its stock to venture capitalists.<P>"Once we developed our first [commercial] prototype, we almost immediately started selling, initially   to research institutions,'' recalls Menzilcioglu. "It happened through word of mouth, through the Internet. We became self-sustaining.<P>"Then venture companies started knocking on our door. We could have not taken the venture money. But we decided it would be better off taking some in case we needed it -- for expansion. Looking back, I can't say I'm sorry, because it gave us enough cushion. And when negotiating with venture capitalists, if you do a deal at a time when you don't need it, you get good terms.''<P>Rapid Growth<P>FORE completed the Navy contract in 1992 and promptly went into production as the first company to ship commercial ATM networking products. The company's owners grew suddenly rich from feeding a hungry market seeking to link multiple personal computers more efficiently. Initially, FORE didn't even have a sales person; orders for the heralded new technology just rolled in. <P>After the company went public in May 1994, the initial offering price doubled within two months and kept rising all year, prompting Fortune to list FORE as the nation's fourth fastest-growing public company in April   1995.<P>In the year ended March 31, 1995, revenues more than tripled, reaching $75.6 million. Profits increased more than two-fold, totaling $7.4 million.<P>Not a bad few years' work for former academicians still in their 30s.<P>Cooper, for one, has easily made the transition from Ph.D. to CEO. And his role grows everyday -- just look at his wardrobe. He dresses casually when he can, often in khakis, sans tie. But the tie creeps around his neck more and more often,  like a corporate vine.<P>"I can chart the growth of the company and the shift in my role by the percentage of time that I spend wearing a tie," Cooper says. "It has definitely increased -- I think I'm up to about three days a week.''<P>His style has more in common with that of the current generation of high tech entrepreneurs than with classic corporate chieftains.<P>In a departure from the traditional executive role, Cooper and other FORE executives individually take groups of line employees to lunch on a regular basis. The employees are chosen by drawing straws.<P>"I do it when I'm in the office on Fridays,'' says Cooper. "It's not with an agenda of accomplishing anything. It's not a lunch meeting. It's a way to forge some communication among people who otherwise might not be having lunch together.''<P>Like many of the software moguls of the Silicon Valley and Redmond, Wash., FORE's originators are young to be officers in a publicly traded company. At 37, Cooper might be viewed as Pittsburgh's answer to Bill Gates -- only Cooper, who lived in the same dormitory with Gates at Harvard, graduated and went on to graduate school at Berkeley. Gates, you'll recall, dropped out of Harvard.<P>FORE's Future<P>Late last year, FORE acquired Alantec, a hardware and software company whose 200 employees will remain at the company's San Jose plant. The merger includes the       conversion of about 12 million outstanding shares of Alantec stock into FORE stock. At the end of 1995, these shares had an estimated value of about $700 million.<P>Though FORE's numbers have been leaner since the spring of 1995 -- the stock grew 59 percent between April 1 and mid-December -- analyst G. Arjavalingam of Needham & Co. in New York sees this as only natural in a market that is no longer exclusive.<P>Yet Arjavalingam, putting FORE's market share at 60 percent, believes the company will dominate ATM networking for at least the next few years.<P>In the face of competition from behemoth Cisco Systems, FORE officers tout the company's distinction of concentrating solely on ATM networking devices. They maintain that this, along with FORE's head start in software, will keep their edge honed.<P>So for now, eating will probably be the only activity at Bitz's kitchen table, the site of FORE's early work. The new headquarters campus will be ready for operation late this year. Wall Street still likes the stock.<P>It's been a meteoric rise that will likely continue. It started with the Navy contract.<P>"We had used furniture, used computers," Cooper says, looking back. "It was very tight, but we were able to break even that first year and were profitable thereafter."<P>And how.                                    <P>

<P>






<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

