</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<center>
<B><font size=+2>Education
</font></B><br>
<b><font size=+1>We Must Have Opportunities for Graduates<br>
While Teaching Youngsters to be Visionary</font></b><br>
<i>By Cynthia Bent</i></center>
<hr>
Michael and Suzanne Lisanti came to Carnegie Mellon's MBA program with the hopes of earning a world-class degree and finding jobs in Pittsburgh. They got the first, but not the second.<P>"We were pretty upset," says Michael, a Pittsburgh native now working in Dayton, Ohio. <P>"We would loved to have stayed," adds Suzanne. "So many of us in my class wanted to stay, but only one or two could. We couldn't get jobs. We would have even taken less money, just to stay."<P>Michael now believes, having worked for a year, that he would sometime like to start his own business. "I'd like to do it in Pittsburgh, but if I started it part-time, it would have to be wherever my main job was." <P>So Pittsburgh loses two young <P>talents, and a possible startup business.<P>In Part III of Executive Report's six-month series entitled Resuscitating the Region, ER focuses on the role of education in the region's revitalization. In the coming months, ER also will look at transportation, tax reform and tour-ism as other windows of opportunity.<P>One way to pump new life into Pittsburgh, experts say, is to focus on the younger people who tend to start businesses. Pittsburgh has all the raw materials -- good schools, great universities, bulldog-like loyalty to the 'burgh -- but something is still missing. Many talented young people never stay long enough to start their businesses.<P>"Only a small fraction, about      15 percent, stay. There are better opportunities elsewhere," says Jack Thorne, who heads the Don Jones Entrepreneurial Center at CMU's business school. He has watched all too many talented grads take flight. "One student who wanted to stay finally had to take a job in Washington, D.C. He's just started his first business there. That could have been here."<P>"This trend continues to drive demographics of the area older," says Don Smith, executive director of the Center for Economic Development, also at CMU.<P>He notes that besides the fact that less young people start less businesses, 20- to 33-year-olds also tend to spend a very high percentage of their income. High-tech markets like computers and electronics are mainly pitched to the young. <P>"The newest, latest, greatest, cutting edge industries and products -- Pittsburgh misses them as the young leave," says Smith. "It's an unsustainable pattern that's been going on anecdotally since the late '70s."<P>Pittsburgh's "brain-drain" has been Tom Canfield's crusade for some time now. Canfield is the president of The Enterprise Corp., whose mission is to aid entrepreneurs. Canfield says that this region lost $6 billion in human resources since the 1980s -- the 103,000 kids who went to school here and then left. Might sound like a drastic number, but others agree with him -- it's a critical problem.<P>Canfield has a plan of his own. "We have to do proactive things to keep them here," he says. "Are there things we can do to get promising people to sink roots? Where you get your first job is probably where you'll get married, buy a house, get a mortgage and stay."<P>Canfield wants to mimic the successful Kaufmann Foundation, based in Kansas City, Mo. That group's mission is to promote entrepreneurial activity by selecting around 20 fellows and providing them with internships for two years with venture capital firms around the country.<P>"The idea here is to identify Pittsburgh Fellows' and in some way offset their high salary requirements, pay for their positions, make it attractive to stay here," says Canfield.<P>He admits the idea might affect a small number of people -- the couple of winners per year. Others who didn't qualify would nevertheless find a network to other businesses.<P>"We look to promote people who can start businesses with a gazelle' potential. If we find a few gazelles, the rabbits and goats happen," Canfield says.<P>But what about home-grown entrepreneurs? Every innovator doesn't necessarily have an MBA. Smith believes that even if more young people stayed after school, western Pennsyl-vania would still have a problem. <P>"The general culture here grew around big business and big unions," he says, "and doesn't encourage risk-taking. Tradition is hard to change."<P>"We have to change the mindset   of kids," agrees Canfield. We have to show them that it's OK to start a    business, to risk."<P><P>It Starts Early<P>There are some who work against that tide of tradition. The Pennsylvania Council on Economic Education is the state branch of EconomicsAmerica, a nonprofit group whose mission "to promote and encourage understanding of fundamental economic concepts through education" has endured in this state for 16 years. <P>The group tries to foster school-children's understanding of how the economy works through games, curriculum, contests and other programs. PCEE trains teachers to use their material by sponsoring seminars, providing materials and setting up partnerships with school systems; the teachers then take that knowledge back to the classrooms and integrate the programs with their own curriculum.<P>Jan Bishop, economics education consultant for PCEE, says their goal is to teach students skills and attitudes that will last them a lifetime, rather than formulas or statistics they will soon forget.<P>One program, Taking Charge, lets teams of students compete in the classroom against each other to see who can run the best pizza stand. Developing advertising, budgeting and product pricing and hiring employees are all part of the challenge.<P>"We did research on the program and were surprised at the results. It showed a significant attitude change, especially in females," says Bishop.<P>Despite the statewide successes of the PCEE, Bishop believes there's a long way to go. She would like to see more schools take advantage of their programs, though she understands the schools are pressed for time and money as it is.<P>"There's a lack of understanding of what economics is. [Teachers] think it's too hard, that you study it in college. That attitude has to change. We try to make them comfortable with the content. But it's an uphill struggle."<P>Junior Achievement is a more familiar organization to many. The 77-year-old organization is most known for its after-school activity where groups of students start a real business and learn how to run it. But JA is involved in the classroom, too, with programs from elementary school on up. In 1989, for the first time, JA reached more than 1 million students nationwide in one year.<P>JA's programs in-class include games like Job Shuffle, in which students learn the education they need for various careers, or Personal Economics, helping kids learn budget-planning and assess their skills. The programs are taught in many cases by volunteer   business consultants. Volunteer participation reached 57,000 in 1994-95. <P>But teaching kids about how to start pizza stands is only part of the solution. Everyone agrees -- including educators themselves -- that our basic education system could do a better job of preparing students for the job market. And everyone who talks about revamping the school systems says that schools need to maintain better connections to the communities they serve.<P>Helen Sobehart, assistant superintendent of Fox Chapel Area School District, is a strident proponent of the link between education and the vitality of our region. She says that you can't divorce the school from the rest of society. They go together.<P>"If the community is filled with gangs, drugs or even just the attitude that it's ok to drink underage, it's going to carry to the school. We need to heighten the communication between the schools and the community so children hear the same message everywhere they go."<P>Sobehart says that we've lost an ability to be physically close to each other, and that has caused the close-knit traditions of community and values to suffer. Her school system is part of a community group, All of Us Care, formed to rebuild this cooperation between schools, parents, businesses and the rest of the community.<P>"It supports what we're trying to do here at school, and then we in turn support our community," she says.<P>Fox Chapel is also involved        with Career and Academic Passport Initiative, an attempt by business and the schools to generate new standards for education and new ways to teach those standards. <P>"Happily, the skills we emphasize are the same as those we are required by the state to teach. The difference is we're doing so now in partnership with business people in the community.  We're making sure students demonstrate skills by real life applications." That may involve the Taking Charge program. Or it may mean an apprenticeship with a local business, giving a student both credit and a paycheck.<P>"Students who had the ability to participate are all very enthusiastic about how much it helped them prepare for college and for work. The problem is, there's no systematic way for schools and businesses to approach each other. It's all based on who knows who," Sobehart says.<P>That systematic way is Jeanne Berdik's crusade. She's the regional manager of the Pennsylvania School to Work Opportunity System, a branch responsible for implementation of the National School to Work Initiative.<P>"Lots of complaining goes on out there about undereducated graduates [on the part of businesses]. It's absolutely valid. But there's no mechanism for doing something constructive about it," says Berdik.<P>She agrees that the approach to reformation has been fragmented, with individual organizations just out "doing their thing." School to Work tries to integrate technical education with academics, and to provide community and work experience connected to schools and training, and a clear path to post-secondary education.<P>The School to Work effort was started nationally about 1993. President Clinton signed into law in May 1994 the legislation to give federal money to states and some localities      to implement these philosophies,      and go by these guidelines to form these partnerships.<P>Berdik explains her role as that of a go-between. She wants to take the goals of the Regional Economic Revitali-zation Initiative drawn up by the Allegheny Conference, and put them into action in the schools. The industries targeted for growth could communicate their needs in terms of work force to the education system.<P>But that's not the last step. "If we have this economic development mechanism giving this information out, we need partners for them to tell it to," Berdik says. That's School-to-Work's next goal: partnerships between the schools and communities to use that wellspring of information.<P>In McKeesport, for example, she has gathered people who were already in partnership from existing apprenticeship programs and expanded to incorporate representatives of labor, employers, teachers, school board members, post-secondary institutions and city government.  They all sit down together, systematically, to design new programs taking the recommendations of our region's industry and mobilize programs around them.<P>"This is still in fantasyland right now," she admits. But already, within the 13 Southwestern Pennsylvania counties she coordinates, there are 19 partnerships formed.<P>So it seems that people are waking up to the fact that there is a problem in our schools, a problem that if remedied, could lift our region out of its sinkhole, but if ignored, could bog down southwestern Pennsylvania's best efforts at revitalization.<P>Also plain to those who study the problem is that this is only one brick in the effort to shore up the region. A favorable environment, they say, also requires reformation of taxes, regulations as well as venture capital.<P>Spinning wheels in endless debate about what to do accomplishes little. New standards for what students should know are useless until they are implemented and supported by the community. We need a concrete plan for specific action, not more standards and "we shoulds" that have no plans, and no power to ensure action. The Pennsylvania School-to-Work Opportunity System could be a real first step.<P>Whether these efforts will come together, or whether they will sift out and remain unconnected, depends on the tenacity of the people working for them, their willingness to communicate and the commitment of our state towards making real changes and listening to the community.<P>"We are at the bottom of the barrel and there are very few examples of those who rose," says Canfield. "There are places that have transformed, but most had huge injections of federal money. I think we have to do it without federal money, because it's not going to come. And we can't just wait, because it's not going to happen."                               n<P><P>
<P>






