<a href="../zine/0396.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Teaching Old Dogs<br>Some New Tricks
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Under Orders From Gov.Ridge, the State's<br>Environmental Regulators Have Changed Their Ways, and<br>Business Like What They See So Far</font></b><br>

<i>By Jim Strader</i></center>
<hr>
When Tom Ridge ran for governor, he campaigned hard against Mark Singel, the lieutenant governor and Democratic nominee who had plans to move up from the office he had occupied for eight years. But Ridge's attacks didn't stop there.<P>The six-term Republican congressman from Erie waged a battle against what he saw as the entrenched institutions of state government, and none personified that more than the dreaded and powerful Department of Environ-mental Resources.<P>In Ridge's eyes, no state agency had a more old-fashioned, unbending, stuck-in-time way of doing things than the DER. Ridge even had a tag line for the DER that he said loud and often.<P>"It's a job-crushing, community-harassing, regulatory nightmare," the governor proclaimed.<P>So Ridge dissolved the DER and created two new agencies with more than just different names. There are different philosophies: Instead of punishing unwitting violators, help them comply, the governor ordered.<P>In the process, the state had to change the habits of dozens of veteran regulators who were DER holdovers, and that would be key. In essence, Ridge was teaching old dogs some new tricks.<P> "The notion we desire is that government should treat citizens it is designed to serve in a manner that is fair, responsible and reasonable, reaching out to them and helping them comply with the law," Ridge says. "It is a notion that government should be a partner in protecting the environment, rather than a police force that is sitting back and waiting for someone to make a mistake and then pouncing on them from a punitive point of view.<P>"Most citizens I know want to be good stewards of the environment," the governor adds. "Treat them accordingly until they show you something different. If you show them what the law is, show them how to comply with the law and then they willfully ignore it or disobey it, then your response has to be swift and uncompromising.<P>"Absent that, we wanted to go   from a policing and punitive mental- ity to more of a collaborative and          compliance-based mentality."<P>It's still early, but so far Ridge has won some high marks for better defining the agency's mission, for implementing policies many in business see as    forward-thinking  and for instilling a new attitude in staffers who for years worked under the old DER mentality: Find the violators and punish them.<P><P>The New Mission<P>Ridge's decision to split the DER was no secret when he laid out the formal proposal after becoming governor. The plan was developed during his three-year campaign -- honed and hammered into shape as he traveled the state. His harangue against the DER struck home with many of those who dealt with the agency, which had a terrible reputation across Pennsylvania and in the Capitol.<P>Lawmakers from all corners of the state readily recite DER horror stories gleaned from constituent complaints. They were the classic examples of bureaucratic nightmares, and the tales seemed to feed on themselves. Ridge seized on the discontent.<P>In dividing the DER -- and establishing in its place the Department of Environmental Protection and the Department of Conservation and Natural Resources -- Ridge earned points with business. The hellish tales of excessive regulation, impenetrable red tape and eternal delay seemed to be amplified when dollars and cents were involved.<P>"I think splitting the agency serves to provide clearer focus," says Pittsburgh attorney Scott Dismukes, a former Environmental Protection Agency attorney who now heads the environmental law group at Doepken Keevican & Weiss. <P>"Essentially, they've narrowed the mission of the department, and I think by narrowing it, you create a more unified purpose," Dismukes says.<P><P>The Point Man<P>Leading the transition was Environmental Protection Secretary James M. Seif, Ridge's choice to head the new agency.<P>Much of the credit for the new outlook at the DEP goes to Seif, who came to state government from an environmental law practice in Philadelphia. A native of Mount Lebanon, Seif served as the EPA regional administrator from 1985-89 and was an aide to former Gov. Dick Thornburgh. He also prosecuted environmental crimes as an assistant U.S. attorney in Pittsburgh.<P>Seif says the transition has been smooth, and the agency's first year         a success. But there's more to come,   Seif says.<P>"As governor, Tom Ridge has set an ambitious goal to fundamentally transform Pennsylvania's environmental programs from a government knows best' philosophy to an approach that encourages private ingenuity to achieve the environmental goals we set," Seif says. "The core mission of protecting our environment will not change.<P>"Our success will be measured by the partnerships we build, by how well we help people understand the benefits of protecting the environment, by the number of people we bring into compliance and by how well we solve real environmental problems," he says.<P>Part of the Ridge administration's purpose for dissolving DER was to eliminate the sometimes divergent objectives of the two parts of the agency, which managed parks and forests in addition to regulating environmental matters. The new arrangement gives regulatory functions to the DEP and puts the parks and forests in the care of Conservation and Natural Resources.<P>The new conservation agency is headed by John C. Oliver III, former president of the Western Pennsylvania Conservancy. Ridge says his goal in setting up the new department was to allow the state's natural resources to receive more attention, without being in the shadow of the rest of the DER.<P><P>Changing Attitude<P>Seif has been a preacher and practitioner of the belief that the department should be user-friendly and work with business and others it serves, not against them. His experience will be a key to making that shift work, Dismukes said.<P>"He's not just of high caliber and on his own merits is a good appointee in any circumstance, but he's not subject to tunnel vision,'' Dismukes says. "He's been on both sides of the fence; he should be a lot wiser both ways. I think that's a unique strength in that appointment."<P>     The secretary also won praise from the business community for surrounding himself with top aides who take a lead-by-example approach to running the DEP.<P>    Many who deal with the agency on a regular basis say there have been noticeable changes in the last year in the way a good number of the DEP's 3,000 employees deal with the public.<P>"They've always been good people to work with here in western Pennsylvania," says attorney Barry Trilling of Pepper Hamilton & Scheetz, who has more than 20 years of environmental law experience. "They're all terrific people, always good to deal with. They were handcuffed, shackled, by policies that emanated from Harrisburg."<P>And, Trilling says, the way Harrisburg operated kept the agency from keeping up with changes going on around them. He cites improvements made by business in pollution control.<P>"There's been a sea change in industry's attitude toward pollution," Trilling says, explaining that most larger companies have come to realize the benefits of being clean and within the law. <P>"It was like having a bulldog on a choker chain," he says. "It's no longer that way. Industry sees that it's in its best interest -- short-term public relations and long-term profits. It's just good capitalism."<P>"What you had in DER was an attitude that industry had never awakened to that," Dismukes adds.<P><P>The Other Side<P>As impressed as Dismukes and others have been with the changes in the last year, the department has not won unwavering praise. Environmen-tal activists see some changes as too sweeping, with too much emphasis on the needs of business and not enough on protection of the environment. Even the business community has some problems with the way things work at the new agency.<P>Although Seif and other top officials at the DEP have demonstrated the way they want the department to operate, there are those DER holdovers in the agency who cling to the old ways, Dismukes says.<P>"You have career professionals that have seen appointees come and go and have substantially invested their professional careers in the department," Dismukes says. "That leads to some internal tensions."<P>Breaking that inertia among bureaucrats, attorneys and others in the agency is a task undone, he          says. But it is one Ridge and Seif are addressing.<P>From the first days of the Ridge administration, the refined mission and shift in attitude at the DEP were accompanied by new policies. The process of applying for environmental permits was placed on a fast track -- and the agency began offering a money-back guarantee to applicants who did not receive an answer on time. At year's end, Seif boasted of a perfect record.<P>The agency started a systematic review of all regulations -- some 11,000 pages -- to find outdated rules and to work toward consistency with federal standards. The DEP promoted negotiation among interested parties as a way to develop new regulations.<P>In the agency's southwestern regional office, department officials conducted an outreach program of quarterly meetings with people and groups affected by DEP policies. Spokeswoman Betsy Mallison says the effort allowed a two-way sharing of information -- benefiting the department and those it met with.<P>The permit process was expedited for the American Video Glass plant adjacent to the Sony television facility in Westmoreland County, she says, marking a change from the past. Sony's environmental guru, Mark Small, has gone out of his way to compliment DEP for its cooperation.<P>Perhaps the most-heralded policy change came in a package of celebrated laws designed to help business clean up and reuse polluted industrial sites.<P>An Alabama company jumped on the new law right away. Vulcan Materials Co., headquartered in Birmingham, is conducting a cleanup of a Neville Island site it used to own. AMG Resources will expand its recycling operation after the abatement of lead and other substances. <P>The laws allow flexibility in such projects, meaning the Neville Island site can be cleaned up to a point consistent with its future industrial use, rather than to a pristine state, says attorney Tim Weston, of the Harrisburg office of Kirkpatrick & Lockhart, who represents Vulcan. <P>"The part of this process that          is substantially different is that the DEP staff is being allowed to think about site risk, rather than reciting some rote: We want it all gone,' " Weston says.<P>The new laws allow the department to take advantage of its people, too, according to Weston. The scientific expertise of DEP officials should be put to use in such situations.  <P>"They went to school for a reason, and they could think that through," Weston says. "It is not an easy process, and some of them are still concerned that they may not make the right decision. In the past, their concern that they might not make the right decision meant that they made no decision."<P><P>Still to Come<P>After the initial shift in direction at the DEP, the new management eased off its push for dramatic change. By the end of the year, the call was for time to allow the changes to work.<P>But it seems likely there is more to come, provided that Congress does not get in the way.<P>"Much remains to be done," Seif says. "Congress and EPA have been wild cards in our efforts to reform state programs, since some federal and state environmental programs are so closely linked. In some cases, the slow rate of change in Washington is holding up our efforts to reform programs in Pennsylvania.<P>"We've had some success in putting the Ridge principles to work," Seif says, looking ahead. "But we've only scratched the surface."                                                   n<P>
<P>






