<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Supplement4.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Marriage is Grand<br>Divorce is One Hundred Grand
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Much is at Stake When Wealthy Individual Get<br>Divorced; Many Corporate Law Firms Have<br>Family Law Capabilities In-House</font></b><br>

<i>By Barbara Youngerman Meyer</i></center>
<hr>
Attorney Jonathan McAnney remembers when the legal community treated divorce cases with a bit of disdain. The divorce cases were there. They were always going to be there.<P>"Divorce was seen as the unwanted stepchild of litigation," says McAnney, of Tucker Arensberg in Pittsburgh.<P>"But divorces today often involve significant amounts of money. That's a major reason  why things have changed."<P>Yes they have: Much is at stake in divorces, especially those involving wealthy individuals -- from physicians with established practices to owners of successful small businesses to corporate executives. Veteran real estate appraiser Bob Gelman tells of one divorce case for which he was flown "in the client's private plane all over the southeastern United States to evaluate his holdings and eventually testify in court."<P>Spouses battle over luxury cars, multiple homes, stock options, personal valuables and sometimes the value of one spouse's professional license.<P>So divorce -- this one-time shabby stepchild -- has quietly become one of the family darlings. Corporate law firms not only accept divorce cases, they have attorneys with expertise, such as Tucker Arensberg's  McAnney,  to handle them.  <P>"These days you see more large and complex estates being split up," says Judge Patrick Tamilia, a veteran Family Court jurist in Allegheny County before ascending to the Superior Court of Pennsylvania. "There's more divorce among the wealthy than before. It's not uncommon these days to see $500,000 and even million-dollar settlements."    <P>Modern Love<P>Statistics show that half of all marriages in the U.S. end in divorce, which cuts across all class and economic lines.<P>"Divorce is easier now," says Tamilia. "With no-fault [divorce] in place, it's easier. People don't stay in a bad or unsatisfying marriage like they used to. Not that staying together was always good. Some marriages should have ended, but we've gone too far the other way."<P>As a result, many larger corporate law firms have taken on divorce litigation out of necessity over the years. Their clients are asking for it, Tamilia says.<P>"These firms don't just deal with contracts, mergers and high finance. They deal with clients who are human beings, and these human beings get involved in domestic problems," Tamilia says.  <P>"These human beings -- high-priced executives whose marriages have fallen apart -- go to their law firm, the one taking care of their business interests, and say Where do I go? Can you help me?'"<P>A '90s divorce, in many cases, carries with it characteristics similar to those of more traditional corporate law cases.<P>For one, McAnney points out that the attorney fees involved in litigating      a complex divorce can resemble fees from an antitrust case.<P>"Look at the money that's involved in the Barry Bonds divorce," McAnney says. "Legal costs in that case have exceeded $1 million."<P>Secondly, McAnney says many divorces have taken on the look of a business matter since pensions, 401(k) plans, and licenses and educational degrees often are pulled into the fray.<P>"Really," says McAnney, "a divorce now is no different than a business <P>dissolution."<P>And that's just the beginning.<P>High profile individuals face media scrutiny in some instances, and such publicity can hurt their business. Others going through divorce find business competitors snooping in their case file.<P>"I had a client who was fairly well-known in Pittsburgh," says veteran attorney Stewart B. Barman, head of family law practice at Buchanan Ingersoll. "He didn't want his competition to know what his business was worth. By settling out of court, he bought some protection.<P>"He paid more upfront, but there would have been a higher price to pay down the road if he'd gone public."<P>No-Fault Divorce     <P>Divorce in Pennsylvania got a lot easier two decades ago, when no-fault divorce became law. Before the reform, divorce cases tended to be bloody. <P>"We wanted to get the acrimony out of divorce proceedings," Tamilia says. "We wanted the focus to be on the actual dissolution. [The earlier] cases were bitter and hard-fought." <P>A contested divorce was almost impossible to obtain. Or the wife was frightened to have her marriage end; it was her lifeline, in many instances. She had no income of her own and, in the old days, there was no alimony.<P>"So people stayed married forever," says David Pollock, head of the Marital Law Group at Reed Smith Shaw & McClay.  <P>Nowadays in Pennsylvania, all real or personal property -- with certain exceptions -- acquired by either husband or wife during their marriage is presumed to be marital property. This means it doesn't matter who holds the property title, whether it's held individually or by both in some form of co-ownership. It is subject to "equitable distribution" upon divorce.<P>"The entire ball game was made anew back in 1980, when the divorce code came into being," says Pollock. "Now we have spousal support and equitable distribution of marital property. Now there's the whole concept of helping the dependent spouse who   hasn't worked outside the home."<P>"Equitable distribution," says Tamilia, "gave women economic justice."  <P>Property that is equitably distributed is not split 50-50, but instead in a manner that is fair to both parties. But consider problems that can emerge.<P>A classic case involved a physician from New Jersey who was supported by his wife during medical school. The court ruled that the wife was entitled to 40 percent of the value of the husband's medical license, a value the court set at $472,000. The wife's cut: $188,000.<P>"If the physician, however, has only been in practice a short time," says McAnney, "his estate really isn't worth all that much.  His income is high, but you have to consider his debts -- the cost of getting into practice. He doesn't have anything he can liquidate to make a cash settlement."<P>Barman takes the scenario a step further: "Let's say someone's suing her doctor husband for divorce, and she wants half of what his business is worth. And let's say it's worth $2 million. But his is a service business. If he drops dead tomorrow, what's the business worth? What's its inherent value?"<P>Regardless, as the New Jersey case showed, "the courts are awarding the money anyway as though the physician's business has an inherent value, a value apart from him," Barman says.<P>The traps of equitable distribution don't stop there. Consider the common example of the family-owned business.<P>"Take a 55- to 60-year-old guy who's been married 25 years and is in charge of a closely held family business," McAnney says. "The wife has worked at home and has no skills, no real job opportunities and the court will be apt to award her a big chunk of his estate.<P>"But it's important she not get a controlling interest in the company," McAnney says. "You don't want your divorced spouse to be a shareholder with you. It will ruin the business, and then what value is there in it?" <P>Alimony can be just as tenuous.<P>"In the past three years, I've seen a gradual change with regard to support for the dependent spouse," says attorney Pat Miller, the Permanent Equitable Distribution Master in the Family Division of Allegheny County Com-mon Pleas Court. "It's gotten more progressive, more liberalized. We've recognized that the law was too harsh."<P>Usually, wives are the recipient, but there are exceptions.<P>"I've had doctor-doctor cases, where he's in research and she's in private practice," says Pollock of Reed Smith. "He's making a lot less money in research and, so, he's going to get the alimony."  <P>Barman, whose past clients include Terry Bradshaw, says the best way to handle property distribution and alimony is to negotiate it instead of leaving it up to the court.<P>"If I could wave a magic wand, I'd never go to court," Barman says. "Once in court, a third party decides my client's fate. Who would want that?"<P>Other Alternatives<P>Another way to address property distribution and alimony is to work it out in advance of the wedding in the form of a prenuptial agreement. <P>Courts, for the most part, will enforce the agreements provided that the party that is wishing to protect its interests has fully disclosed its holdings.<P>In one Massachusetts case, the court upheld a prenuptial even though it was thrust upon the groom by the bride -- an heiress whose annual salary was $540,000 -- only three hours prior to the wedding. The agreement included a detailed schedule of the wife's estate and expected inheritance. The husband unsuccessfully argued that he signed the document under duress.<P>Another way couples try to resolve their differences is through divorce mediators such as Paul Wahrhaftig and partner Sherle Josephs. <P>"We work on constructive problem solving," Wahrhaftig says, "so we can settle out of court. We work to develop a parenting plan. We separate adult issues from those concerning the kids. We give each member of the couple reassurance that the future can be good for them. Each will be taken care of and the children, too. We don't use fighting words that imply anyone is going to be the loser in the deal."<P>Barman and other attorneys perform similar services for their clients, but Wahrhaftig says his firm is different because it works with the couple, not just one side.<P>"We're working with both, working out the nuts and bolts. We helped a couple who both worked in his family-owned business. When they came to us, they were very angry, very hostile toward each other. Today both work in that same family business. At different ends of the building, I have to add, but they can work together. It was good for the company that they both stay."<P>Of course, the happiest ending would be for the divorce rate to fall to zero -- but since that is unlikely to happen any time soon, divorce specialists can expect their phones to keep ringing.     <P>

<P>






