<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Supplement5.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>It's a Buyer's Market Out There
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+>With Memberships Down, Country Clubs are Hotly Pusuing New Members;<br>The Deals Being Offered by Some Clubs are Turning Golfers' Heads</font></b><br>

<i>By Joe Tuscana</i></center>
<hr>

When Congress passed tax legislation for 1994 eliminating the business deduction for club dues, it reinforced a message to businesses that has become common in these budget-cutting times.<P>There are no free lunches.<P>When it comes to conducting business on the golf course, the bill has gone up considerably.<P>The targets of the new tax law include such institutions as private city clubs, airline clubs and other business and entertainment clubs, including golf clubs.<P>Business write-offs for membership dues in country clubs were eliminated completely. Even deductions for the business lunch, which for so long has served as the bargaining table for many deals, have been slashed. The changes have dealt a severe blow to many  businessmen who use these memberships to foster business contacts. Not to mention the facilities they frequented. Consider the Highland Country Club in West View.<P>"At Highland, we had a lot of small businessmen who were members. We lost membership and we lost golf outings. It affected us big time because of our clientele," says Jim Antkiewicz, who worked at Highland Country Club for 12 years before becoming golf pro at the Club at Nevillewood in January.<P>"Our numbers shrank. Some just dropped out while others cut back."<P>The original tax proposal covered all clubs, including such service organizations as the Lions, Moose and Elks. However, the Treasury Department determined that Congress did not intend to alter the tax status of clubs whose main goals are public service and community volunteerism. Mem-bers of those types of clubs may continue deducting membership dues.<P>But the deficit reduction measure, which hopes to raise an additional  $1.1 billion of tax revenue over five years, puts new pressures on golf clubs to attract membership. This constant chipping away of deductions for business expenses that offer an element of personal benefit is motivating many clubs to offer membership specials.<P>While golf clubs have felt the pinch, the new tax laws, coupled with the construction of new courses throughout the area, have sparked a type of membership war. It's a buyer's market out there and golfers looking for an opportunity to join a club have never had a better time to do so.<P>The Highland Country Club has lowered its initiation fee, and has attracted 75 new members in 1995. Highland is not alone -- local clubs are offering a variety of deals.<P>Dues Decrease<P>"What seems to be going on is that country clubs are offering extremely discounted rates on intermediate (non-voting) memberships,'' says Rich Milesky, a 24-year-old law student at Duquesne University and a member of Shannopin Country Club in the North Hills. "Take the club bonds for example. Before, if you were over 35, you had to pay the day before you began your membership. Now, some club offers allow you to pay over a long period of time."<P>While most clubs claim discounted membership offers are not unique --Shannopin has a special to celebrate its 75th anniversary -- these tempting deals have been more plentiful since the tax change.<P>Milesky is a perfect example of the type of golfer clubs want to attract. At 24, his membership in a club could last for decades and his youth makes him more of a candidate to take advantage of a club's other social amenities, such as the pool, tennis courts and dining areas.<P>"Things are definitely different now," says attorney John Lyncheski, 51, a director with the Pittsburgh law firm of Cohen & Grigsby and a longtime member at Chartiers Country Club in Pittsburgh. "Country club memberships have become extremely competitive."<P>Lyncheski, who served as president at Chartiers Country Club from 1992 to 1993 and who has also served on its board, believes two factors have sparked the intense competition for new membership.<P>"One, obviously, is the IRS limits on deductions for entertainment expenses. Two, I think there is a saturation. The Pittsburgh area has more competition for membership."<P>The recent rise in new course development -- Southpointe, Diamond Run, Mystic Rock at Nemacolin Woodlands and the Club at Nevillewood, to name just a few -- has made memberships more plentiful and competition to fill them much more intense.<P>"Ten years ago at Highland, we had a waiting list," says Antkiewicz. "The past year, we were shy of our membership limit."<P>"In 1985 or so, virtually every country club in the Pittsburgh area had a waiting list to get in," Lyncheski adds. "At most clubs now, it's flip-flopped. At some clubs, there are memberships that go wanting. Other clubs have substantially reduced fees. They are targeting younger men because they have the potential to be long-term members. Some offer intermediate memberships to bring in younger members."<P>Many golf clubs have felt an added economic strain because of the social amenities offered. A swimming pool, tennis courts and dining areas require staff, maintenance and increasing costs for upkeep.<P>"Most clubs look for younger men because they tend to socialize more," says Milesky. "Older members tend to eat at the club more but younger members eat there, use the pool and other facilities. That's especially true for a member who has a family."<P>Pay to Play<P>Make no mistake, belonging to a country club is expensive. At a typical club, besides initiation fees, members are charged monthly dues that cover greens fees, plus there are pro shop purchases and food and beverage tabs. Some clubs also charge fees for locker rentals, club storage and capital improvements. These clubs need a strong membership that will spend money. The younger member makes for the best applicant, not only because of his youth but for the potential to develop stronger business ties.<P>"Younger members tend to spend more time there," Milesky says, "because it's a good networking opportunity."<P>The new tax law limited the deductible portions of business meals and entertainment expenses to 50 percent for fraternal clubs, business   clubs, athletic clubs and even airline travel clubs.<P>Under the new tax law, use of a club is monitored on a day-to-day basis to determine business entertaining. That percentage of use is deductible from annual membership dues.  <P>So if a club's dining area is used for a business luncheon, for example, only 50 percent of the cost may be deducted at tax time. While the new tax law has not eliminated the business lunch, it has certainly curtailed it.<P>"Companies are not willing to pay large amounts of money for group outings," says Tim Jugovic, club manager at Shannopin. "Those situations are not going to disappear, however. Their aim is now to smaller groups."<P>A membership-sponsored business function at Shannopin shows up on the billing statement of the member. Before 1994, those expenses could be deducted at tax time. Club members may be able to get around at least part of the deduction changes this way: If a club itemizes a bill into membership and meal portions, the members can still deduct the 50 percent of the meal portion as a business expense. Every little bit helps.<P>Jugovic says that the business-sponsored golf outings still flourish, but on a smaller scale at his club.<P>While construction of new courses may not be affected by this belt-  tightening, a trend to a different style of club has emerged. Courses such as Diamond Run offer a facility that caters specifically to golfers needs. You won't find a swimming pool, tennis courts or a banquet hall.<P>"We wanted a residential community that was tied into a golf course. That was the thought process behind Diamond Run," says Bob Collins, the club pro at the Gary Player signature course in Sewickley. "When they were building it, we tried to get as much up-front membership as possible. I would guess that 70 percent of the people we bring in here join the club. And about 90 percent of the people who live here are golf members or social members."<P>Collins says that while there is property allocated for a swimming pool and tennis courts, neither has been built. But the option remains.<P>"Tennis courts and pools are not profit centers at a club," says Collins. "Those aspects are nice, but they require maintenance. If you check other clubs, dues may be higher because of the upkeep."<P>Jugovic agrees.<P>"Clubs like Shannopin have amenities supplementing the golf activities. There is a lot of overhead to that." Jugovic says it doesn't matter if a group of 60 or 160 dine at the club, the staff numbers are the same. That's why it is critical for clubs to keep membership rosters full.<P>"You have to keep a pipeline open for natural attrition," Jugovic says. "The market is still pretty saturated and there are still more clubs springing up in the area."<P>One of the attractive aspects of a club built in a residential development is the convenience it offers.<P>"Our banquet facility has been a great source of revenue for us," says Maureen Valentine, who is the membership director at the Club at Nevillewood. "We have seating for 225 and our facility is more of a ballroom. The members use our facility for all types of events: weddings, dinners,  bar mitzvahs."<P>Valentine says the key to making a club's amenities profitable is to do it first class.<P>"We have a French chef on staff and offer a wide variety of menus," says Valentine. "Whatever you need, we can provide, whether it be a luncheon or a black-tie affair.<P>"Obviously, the golf club is our most important aspect. The average age of our membership is around 42, and we offer them a lot of events."<P>Valentine says the club has had success working other events into a golf outing.<P>"You still have to entertain," she says. "We have members from the top corporations in Pittsburgh here. Our beautiful golf course -- which is a Jack Nicklaus signature course -- guarantees their undivided attention for four and a half hours. But we also see it        as an opportunity for fine dining    afterwards."<P>Like many clubs in residential developments, the Club at Neville-wood was to exist exclusively for the residents. But the pull for membership has opened it to individuals who live outside the development.<P>"I think the movement is toward joining a club where the course is just magnificent," Valentine says. "That's very important. I think you can see the value in that."<P>The construction of more golf courses and the increasing need for members could leave casualties.<P>Three scenarios appear likely. Some corporations or individuals, who can't really afford to keep a club membership, will use the deduction elimination as an excuse to leave the club.<P>Other businesses that use country club memberships for their employees to entertain customers will see club dues as a cost of doing business -- with or without the deduction.<P>And some clubs, which do not have business or corporate memberships per se, may not be affected, whether business is transacted on the golf course or in the dining room.<P>The deduction elimination could have an unintended effect if club memberships decrease. A luxury tax  approved in the early 1990s on high-dollar items such as luxury boats and cars costing more than $30,000 had a downward effect on employment in those industries.<P>"I think that one of the changes that will occur is that some of the marginal clubs will fall by the wayside," says Lyncheski. "It takes a lot of money to maintain a first-class golf club. It takes a lot of capital improvements to improve your product."<P>Lyncheski believes the newer golf clubs will draw membership away from other clubs.<P>"That means that clubs on the next tier down will have a tough time competing," he says. "I think it will be more expensive to belong to a country club. Ultimately, the financial support of a club falls to the membership. Fees and dues will probably go up."<P>If Lyncheski is right, then the time to take advantage of these reduced fees is now, even if you get stuck with the bill for lunch.			    <P>
<P>






