<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0396.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0396.Supplement4.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0396.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Mulach Compton Awards
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+>Vocational Rehabilitation Center</font></b><br>

<i>By Joe Tuscana</i></center>
<hr>
Those who have met, or even spoken to Joseph Mulach, Jr., cannot easily forget him. The former three-term board chairman of the VRC possesses  vitality, a sense of humor and compassion for humankind -- all of which, over a period of years, contributed to the development of the VRC into the agency it is today.<P>Even now, at 89 years of age, Mulach, if not playing golf or tennis, shares fond stories about his tenure at VRC and the friendships that he formed there.<P>Mulach, who joined the VRC board in 1962 and continues to serve on the board in an advisory capacity, remembers the day a colleague asked him if he would like to fill a current opening on the board.<P>"I said, 'I never heard of the      organization,'" recalls Mulach, who subsequently attended a VRC board meeting to learn about the agency and its  services.<P>During the meeting, says Mulach, a story was told about a consumer whose life had been changed by the VRC. This woman, who had never been able to do anything on her own, was taught life and employment skills and was able to begin working in        the VRC facility. As a result, her mother was able to go off of welfare and obtain a job.<P>"I thought, This is the ideal sort of organization, that can make people feel as though they can contribute and be a part of society,'" says Mulach, adding that the piece about the mother going off of welfare spoke to the businessman in him.<P>In his role as board chairman, Mulach was instrumental in leading a capital campaign that resulted in the relocation of the VRC to its present location on Forbes Avenue.<P>"At the time, VRC was on the fourth floor of this non-fireproof building with one single, rickety elevator," he says. "I envisioned the consumers, many of whom were in wheelchairs, trying to get out and what an absolute disaster it would be."<P>Mulach remarks that he is bothered by some organizations which he feels spend too much time trying to build up an empire.<P>"VRC has never done that," he says. "It always has excellent people involved with it and an excellent staff. It's my favorite organization, and I've been involved with quite a few." <P>This year, two of the companies founded by Mulach are contributing $10,000 toward the sponsorship of VRC's annual Mulach & Compton Awards Ceremony.<P>Steve Thomas, Mulach's son-in-law and the President and CEO of both Mulach Steel Corporation and Mulach Parking Structures Corporation (MPS), states, "This sponsorship is a tribute to the VRC's activity and benefits to the community and to Joe Mulach's being instrumentally involved in it for so many years.<P>"He's continued to support VRC, and the companies that he started have a commitment and obligation to continue that support and the tradition that he established."<P><b>A Message From VRC Board<br>Chairman H.Lee Noble</b><P>The Vocational Rehabilitation Center has long been recognized as a leader in the rehabilitation field.  In the mid-1960s, VRC became the first rehabilitation facility in Pennsylvania and one of the first in the nation to be accredited by the National Commission on Accreditation of Rehabilitation Facilities. Today, VRC is the only Pittsburgh rehabilitation facility accredited in six program areas.<P>VRC achieved another milestone this year when we achieved a 35 percent  placement rate. The national average is 10 percent for similar agencies. VRC is very proud of our success, and we salute the employers in this community for making our success possible.  <P>Each year, more than 200 area businesses turn to VRC for job placement services for dependable and skilled workers. One such person is Margaret Schmitt, an employee of the Western Pennsylvania Caring Foundation and this year's recipient of the Leonard Weitzman Consumer of the Year Award. Margaret's story is an inspiration.<P>VRC recognizes Margaret's employer, the Western Pennsylvania Caring Foundation, for its commitment to hiring people with disabilities.<P>We also are pleased to honor leaders in our community such as Karen Wolk Feinstein and Tony Sanzo for their efforts in improving opportunities for individuals with disabilities.<P>H. Lee Noble is the Vice-President of Bayer Corporation and President of the Polymers Division of Bayer. He has served as the VRC Board Chairman since last September.A Message From <P>Robert J. Mather, <P>President and Chief Executive Officer of the Vocational Rehabilitation Center<P><P>At a recent community event, I was in conversation with the CEO of a local corporation when he asked, upon learning where I worked, "What's at VRC?"<P>I was caught off-guard by the phrasing, "What's at VRC?" The answer to the question lies not in what, but in who is at VRC.<P>The persons with disabilities who become contributing members of society through training and employment, and the staff members who are helping them to rebuild their lives, are the keys to VRC.<P>Perhaps the "what" of VRC was best described in the emblem on the VRC T-shirts and sweatshirts developed this year and worn with a lot of pride by the staff and consumers.  Four simple words -- "What we do works" -- say so much about the daily happenings at VRC.<P>The agency was recently given affirmation that what we are doing is working through the results of several reviews. In an effort to establish continuous improvement practices and become a Total Quality organization, VRC conducted satisfaction surveys of consumers, workshop customers, staff, board members and parents.<P>The resounding response to the reviews was, "Yes, we're pleased with what you're doing. Keep up the good work." Ninety-four percent of our rehabilitation consumers indicated that VRC services met or exceeded their needs.<P>The VRC was also a pilot agency for a management review conducted by the United Way. Again, VRC programs were rated 90 percent or better by United Way volunteers, and VRC's management practices exceeded the norms for approach, implementation and results.<P>The best reassurance comes from the consumers and their families.  The following excerpts are from a letter written to VRC by the mother of Tanguy Richard, a 24-year-old consumer who came to VRC in 1992.  Tanguy Richard was diagnosed with a brain tumor at the age of two. He still has a short-term memory deficit and minor motor difficulties, but is employed in the VRC sheltered workshop.<P>On our first visit to the VRC in 1992, "we were immediately impressed by the dignity of the work environment and the pride and attention shown by all workers under the outstanding vigilance and assistance of staff members.<P>"Tuesday is a special day. From the evening before, we are reminded that this is payday and are repeatedly asked to guess the exact amount of the paycheck. The check will be displayed in the family room for the rest of the week.<P>"Tanguy has built self-confidence ... he feels important and valued in VRC's environment. There is no greater satisfaction for us than listening to Tanguy explaining to our friends and relatives how proud he is of his job and how important it is to him.<P>"I strongly believe that if all our citizens shared the same enthusiasm and work ethic as you and your clients here at VRC, many of our society's current problems would be solved. It is regrettable that the great daily achievements of VRC and other similar institutions never make the headlines."<P>The words of this letter are true testament to what's at VRC and to the rewards experienced by the consumers and the commitment of the VRC staff.<P>We are constantly assisted in our efforts to achieve successes by individuals like Tony Sanzo and Karen Feinstein.  Their dedication to persons with disabilities and their accomplishments in creating a better working environment for them in our community are worthy of much recognition.<P>They are another important piece of  the "who" that makes VRC work.<P><P><b>Mulach Award Given To Karen Wolk Feinstein</b><P>The name of Karen Wolk Feinstein in the Pittsburgh community is synonymous with quality leadership, a no-nonsense style of business management and an energetic zeal for taking on projects that benefit others, most notably special needs populations.<P>For the past five years, as President of the Jewish Healthcare Foundation, Feinstein has overseen the development of and funding of numerous programs ranging from a Jewish residential home to camps for children with disabilities.<P>Feinstein is this year's recipient of the Joseph F. Mulach, Jr. Award, an annual honor presented by the VRC to a person who has significantly improved the quality of life for persons with disabilities. The Mulach Award was established in 1976 to honor former VRC Board Chairman, philanthropist and industrialist Joseph Mulach, Jr. for his determination and commitment to the VRC. <P>Feinstein was chosen as the first President of the Jewish Healthcare Foundation when the organization was created in 1991, following the sale of Montefiore Hospital to Presbyterian University Hospital.<P> The three areas prioritized by the Foundation were healthcare for children at risk, women's health, and the aging and people with chronic conditions.<P>Much work has been done by JHF in trying to develop integrated care systems which strive to connect families with all the resources to which they are entitled.<P>A significant investment by JHF was made in the Facial Anomaly Clinic at the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center. Feinstein describes the clinic, which is for children born with cleft palates and a host of other facial disorders, as being "a model of the kind of care we wish every special needs population could get."<P>From the time children at the clinic are born, they receive comprehensive healthcare services from psychological counseling to special casework to speech therapy, in addition to regular medical care.<P>JHF has done a considerable amount of work with schools to ensure that children with special needs are completely accommodated in the classroom. Feinstein also speaks enthusiastically about the Foundation's involvement with local camps that focus on children with disabilities.<P>"We really look at camping as a very important way for young people with disabilities to start carving out their independence," she says.<P>Feinstein adds that the Foundation "recognizes that when a child lives with a disability, the whole family does. We really need to support the entire unit."<P>A major concern of the Foundation and an area that is still relatively unexplored nationally, says Feinstein, is how to move vulnerable populations with chronic conditions on to managed care without damaging their ties to existing providers. JHF is currently focusing much of its attention on this challenge.<P>Prior to taking control of JHF, Feinstein was a Senior Vice-President at the United Way of Allegheny County.  She currently serves on the board of directors for various community groups, including the United Way, the  Boy Scouts, Integra Trust Company and Shadyside Hospital.<P>Feinstein commented on the historic ties between the VRC and the Jewish population. Years ago, before VRC became an agency, many Jewish communities had their own vocational rehabilitation centers.<P>She also made a connection between persons with disabilities and the Jewish faith, stating, "As a Jewish Healthcare Foundation, we feel a       special affinity for people who suffer discrimination and who, for reasons that aren't worthy, are barred from   participating in the full spectrum of community life."<P>On being chosen for the Mulach Award, Feinstein says, "I'm delighted to be selected, but I feel somewhat unworthy. There are so many heroes when       it comes to the care of people with     disabilities."<P><b>Anthony M. Sanzo Receives James F.Compton<br>Humanitarian Award</b><P>Tony Sanzo relates the story of his 7-year-old daughter Cameron and her friend as one of the best examples of interaction between humans in the ideal world.<P>Cameron's friend has a physical disability. Cameron does not. The physical differences between the two girls have never even come up in conversation during their activities together.  Though they may recognize that the differences exist, they find no need to acknowledge them.<P>Sanzo, the President and Chief Executive Officer of Allegheny General Hospital, has spent the last several years striving to create the same type of coequal environment at AGH, as well as in the community.<P>He is this year's recipient of the James F. Compton Humanitarian Award, which is given to a president, chairman of the board or CEO for his or her efforts, or those of the company, to improve the quality of life for people with disabilities through enhanced employment opportunities.<P>The Compton award was established in 1992 following the board chairman's death. It acknowledges Compton's own desire to honor top executives in the business community for their leadership role in provid-     ing opportunities to people with        disabilities. <P>Sanzo first became more aware of and involved in the efforts for individuals with disabilities about four years ago during the national initiative known as "Forging a New Freedom."<P>Begun by former Reagan press secretary James Brady, who came to Pittsburgh to kick off the initiative here, Forging a New Freedom was an effort, in conjunction with the passing of the Americans with Disabilities Act, to break down the physical, mental and behavioral barriers in the workplace for persons with disabilities.<P>Though Sanzo was clearly approached to participate in the initiative because of his visible role at AGH, the involvement became a much more personal effort on his part and changed the way he thought about quite a few things.<P>He credits Linda Dickerson, Publisher of Executive Report magazine, for teaching him to think           differently about individuals with disabilities.<P>"Linda was the first person who gave me the opportunity to help out with this initiative," says Sanzo. "By her very presence, she taught me how to concentrate on a person's abilities rather than his or her disabilities."<P>Sanzo stated that as a result of Forging a New Freedom, a directory of accessible facilities in Pittsburgh was produced, accessible walkways were increased throughout the city and county, and employers became much more aware of the barriers that exist in the workplace for persons with disabilities. <P>"Nearly every employer in town has made a financial as well as an emotional commitment to this effort," says Sanzo.<P>Allegheny General Hospital was one of the companies which enlisted the help of VRC and other rehabilitation organizations to study the facility and inform the staff of physical and behavioral changes that needed to occur.<P>AGH has continued its involvement with VRC through a number of methods. VRC consumers work in the microfiche records area of the hospital; the facility uses VRC staff as coaches to work with the AGH management to overcome disability-related obstacles and to provide sensitivity training, and the hospital holds workshops for VRC clients which teach employment interviewing skills. <P>A quality improvement team was also developed at AGH, the mission of which was to improve the quality of life for employers and visitors, either with or without disabilities.<P>"While it has always been our mission to teach, to learn and to heal the sick, I don't know that [AGH] ever focused on a segment of the population in the fashion that we have since becoming involved with Forging a New Freedom," says Sanzo.  "Now that we have, I'm not even sure that people know the phrase anymore ... it's become a natural part of what we do."     <P> Sanzo is flattered to have been chosen as the Compton winner and accepts the award with a great deal of pride and humility.<P>"I personally haven't done anything to deserve this award," says  Sanzo, adding, "I'm blessed with being part of an organization that understands its responsibility in this community and functions as a good corporate citizen."<P>Past Compton award recipients are Wesley W. von Schack, Eugene J. Barone and Robert Mehrabian. <P><b>Margaret Schmitt Chosen Leonard Weitzman<br>Consumer of the Year</b><P>Though nearly blind since birth, Margaret Schmitt always knew that she was capable of achieving many things in life, one of those being obtaining a job.<P>But "working a part-time minimum wage job was never a goal," she says.<P>Following periods of attending college, working and returning to college for her degree, Margaret is currently happy with the position she holds at the Western PA Caring Foundation.<P>Schmitt is this year's recipient of the Leonard Weitzman Consumer of the Year Award. The award was established in 1989 in honor of the VRC's former president, who retired after 41 years.<P>The award recognizes the outstanding performance and excellence of a person placed in the workplace by VRC.<P>Following high school, Schmitt attended college for a while, then spent four years working as a rehabilitation assistant at the Pittsburgh Blind Association. Though she enjoyed the work there, she felt the need to move on to other things.<P>Schmitt returned to college and, in 1992, graduated from the University of Pittsburgh with a Bachelor's Degree in Business.<P>Armed with her new degree and an enthusiasm for employment, Schmitt began the search for a job. It was at    this point that she encountered some obstacles.<P>"I spent quite a bit of time looking for work, but had no offers," she recalls.<P>Though entirely honest with potential employers about her blindness, Schmitt feels that her disability was a contributing factor in her lack of job offers.<P>She realized, however, that if a company was hesitant to hire her because she was disabled, it would be less likely to make any other accommodations for her and would not prove to be a good match.<P>Nearly two years after her graduation from college and still unemployed, Schmitt was referred to the VRC by a client at Blindness and Visual Services.<P>She began a job readiness course at the VRC in the winter of 1994 and by May had been hired in a temporary capacity by the Western PA Caring Foundation.<P>Pleased with her performance, the company hired her as a full-time employee six months later.<P>"I don't look at Margaret any differently than I do anyone," says Stacey Bloom, Schmitt's supervisor and the Manager of Administration and Communications at the Caring Foundation.<P>"Her performance has not been hindered because of her disability  it is on a level expected of that position," stated Bloom, adding, "Margaret also has good ideas and suggests different ways of doing things."<P>As a specialty service representative at the Caring Foundation, Schmitt provides telephone customer service to the parents of uninsured children.<P>According to Bloom, Schmitt handles roughly 50 calls per day, each of which may entail answering parents' questions regarding eligibility requirements for the program, explaining the aspects of managed care to them and researching the status of their claims on the computer system.<P>She also processes requests for applications and works closely with many other departments of Blue Cross and Keystone.<P>Schmitt was provided with specialized computer equipment in order for her to perform her job. She recalls that when she first started working and   didn't have all of the proper tools, "VRC worked really hard to get that resolved quickly.  They really went to bat for me."<P>Looking back at her experience with the VRC, Schmitt says she was especially impressed with the contributive approach of the staff there.<P>"Some rehabilitation agencies have a lower expectation or attitude [of their clients] that is a bit condescending," she says, adding, "I never received that from the VRC. They understood where I was coming from and my employment expectations."<P><b>A Message From Timothy Parks</b><P>I am deeply honored to be asked to serve as the Chairman of the Vocational Rehabilitation Center's 1996 Mulach Compton Awards Dinner.<P>The VRC is a very special agency in our community. Its work is directed toward assisting people in the most fundamental way -- through its work in assessment, training, placement    and ongoing support, the VRC moves individuals into meaningful work experiences.<P>The VRC helps individuals challenged with a range of disabilities focus not on those things that cannot be done, but rather on the world of opportunities of the possible. This builds self-esteem, pride and a sense of purpose that underscores that basic human tenet, dignity.<P>The outcome of the work of the VRC is both a sense of meeting our social and moral responsibility as citizens and it is bottom-line, good economic sense.<P>Last year, VRC helped 1,223 people with disabilities. The agency achieved a record as it placed 433 people in jobs in the local community. This number represents a placement rate of 35 percent and well exceeds the national average of 10 percent for similar agencies. <P>The bottom-line economic impact for this group of 433 people is quite impressive. This group will earn more than $5 million in annualized wages.  They will also pay approximately $500,000 in taxes as well as save the taxpayers some $400,000 in public assistance benefits.<P>The VRC works as a partner with many corporations and institutions throughout our region. Each year we honor those individuals who exemplify the highest standards of excellence within this field of services. This year we will honor three exceptional individuals.<P>First, the Mulach Award recipient is Karen Wolk Feinstein, President of the Jewish Healthcare Foundation of Pittsburgh. Karen's leadership and vision have made a significant impact on the services provided to people with disabilities in this community.  <P>Secondly, we are proud to acknowledge the leadership of Anthony Sanzo, our Compton Humanitarian Award honoree. Tony is highly respected in this community as an advocate for people with disabilities.<P>And finally, we recognize a very special individual -- Ms. Margaret Schmitt, who will receive the Leonard Weitzman Consumer of the Year Award. It is this award which symbolizes the real work of VRC. This is the bottom line, an individual who can reach her potential and contribute to the community.<P>Timothy Parks is the President of the Pittsburgh High Technology Council.<P>

<P>






