<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Supplement4.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>Do you Communicate?
</font><BR>
<font size=+1> Your audiences include Employees and Customers;<BR>Make sure they hear your message 
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<P>
<hr>
An administrator at one of the region's higher education institutions was telling me not too long ago how much she loathes management meetings.<P>"You know the kind," she said. "These are the meetings where the person who is doing most of the talking takes a half hour to say what could be said in 10 minutes.<P>"I'd like to reach across the table and say, `Make your point!'" she added. "I just don't have that kind of time to waste. There are more productive ways to spend that time than listening to someone who cannot efficiently communicate their message."<P>Amen.<P>Many people can put together a grammatically correct sentence. But many choose to put together too many grammatically correct sentences. Before you know it, 45 minutes has passed. If you've ever attended a school board or municipal council meeting, you know that politicians have reduced this to an art. Unfortunately, many in the business world today also do the same. <P>Politicians can get away with it. Business people cannot.<P>In today's frenetic and highly competitive work environment, there is increasingly less time for poor communicators. Fellow managers don't want to deal with them. More importantly, clients or customers may find their obtuseness a turnoff. If they know you can't organize your own thoughts, they'll doubt your ability to organize anything, including the work you're doing for them.<P>And that's just scratching the surface.  Communicating is about knowing your audience and precisely how to sway it in your direction. The situations vary from something as private as a management meeting to something as public as a press conference following a disaster involving your business.<P>You have to know when to say nothing, but you also must know when it's time to talk. And you have to know what to say and how to say it. Remember Pepsi's adept handling a few years back of lies about syringes being found in their soda cans? Or USAir Chairman Seth Schofield standing firm after the crash of flight 427? Schofield said if he thought USAir's fleet was unsafe, he'd ground it. One sentence. To the point.<P>Motorola, one of the most forward-thinking companies in the country, tutors high level executives in communications skills as part of its Vice President Institute. The VPI program consists of a five-day seminar consisting of problem-solving and presentations by - among others - Chairman Bob Galvin himself. Follow-up events occur for two years.<P>At Motorola's VPI seminar, an instructor from Northwestern University teaches the VPs how to handle crisis communication. Participants analyze press releases and news programs to determine whether messages were effectively communicated. <P>How do Pittsburgh executives rate? You tell us.<P>Annually at Executive Report, we pick a Corporate Communicator of the Year in conjunction with the Pittsburgh chapter of the Public Relations Society of America's Renaissance Awards.<P>Last year's winner was Duquense University President John E. Murray Jr., a master communicator. This month, we'll pick our corporate communicator of the year for 1996.<P>He or she will be a person whose messages reach the right audiences and align them with his or her perspective. This person will be someone against whom other business people can benchmark and learn.<P>We hope the choice we have to make is a tough one.      <P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

