<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><IMG border=0 align=left SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><BR>
<BR><FONT SIZE=+2>New Year, Old Ideas<BR>Let's Try Something New For a Change 
</FONT SIZE>
<font size=+1></font><BR>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b>
<hr>

The time is New Year's Eve. The setting is the newly renovated Heinz Hall. The players are the world-renowned Pittsburgh Symphony and 2,000 First Night attendees.<P>Surrounded by the melodious tunes of one of the world's greatest orchestras and the energy of a wildly enthusiastic crowd, I pondered the region's fate.  After all, New Year's Eve is the annually appropriate time for contemplating the future. <P>From my perspective, that future is bleak. Despite my attempts to shrug off  my concerns about this region's stagnation, the harsh reality of Pittsburgh's waning competitiveness besieged me.<P>In some ways, it seemed like a  New Year's Eve of old instead. 1996 doesn't promise significant change or improvement. One of this region's competencies is its widely acclaimed cultural assets and performing arts organizations. But our rich cultural base has fostered an abject adherence to tradition: the works of Mozart, Matisse and Shakespeare are inviolate. <P>Communities, by contrast, are not fine works of art. They should change over time. Culture and the high quality of life that it creates is key to successful economic development, but the concomitant tradition that it imposes is repressive. The compulsive need Pittsburgh has to keep things "the way they were" is the region's most formidable enemy. <P>As comforting as our insularity and inherent sense of sameness may be, a region steeped in tradition is doomed to failure in today's globalized world. The New Year's resolution that I propose for the region is to dare to be different. Forget traditional approaches and philosophies - they will ultimately choke this region.<P>Only effective, maybe even brazen,  leadership will offer real hope. But the Pittsburgh region lacks leadership because its cli mate debilitates those who demonstrate leadership skills. New ideas are not welcome. Instead, instant replays of past approaches are equated with leadership.  <P>Andrew Carnegie is not likely to return as the region's savior. As we continue to celebrate his effusive generosity and extraordinary contributions, we must work together feverishly to build our own future. The days of a dozen people in the Duquesne Club determining our destiny are over. The collective effort of communities of individuals will dictate the region's fate.<P>The Pittsburgh region will become impotent in a world economy if we continue to rationalize inactivity and accept the status quo. This year, we must break tradition, depart from the norm and seize the opportunities that globalization presents.<P>
 



<hr><BR><BR><BR>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

