<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Lethal Legislation
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>A Proposed Bill That Will Limit Immigration
</font><br>
<font size=+1>is Bad News for Business</FONT>
 <i>By Lawrence M.Lebowitz
</b></i>

<HR>
A few weeks ago, representatives of more than 50 western Pennsyl-vania businesses met with U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter at our law firm. These business people all told Specter that the immigration bill proposed by Republican U.S. Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming would hurt their companies.<P>The meeting mirrored another later that week between business people and Specter in Philadelphia, and hundreds of other meetings between senators and business leaders nationwide.<P>The meetings have been called by several organizations, including the American Immigration Lawyers Association, to make Congress understand that the Simpson immigration bill will hurt the U.S. economy. Specifically, the Simpson bill would significantly limit the ability of U.S. companies to hire highly skilled foreign workers, including those at the executive and managerial levels.  <P>Laws governing employment-based immigration must effectively serve the dual purpose of helping U.S. employers remain competitive in the increasingly global economy and protecting jobs of U.S. workers. The law as it now stands does this.<P>Simpson's bill, which proposes to help U.S. workers, will actually hurt them. By eliminating this small but central part of the work force, U.S. jobs will be lost.<P>Surveys indicate there are more than 200 foreign companies with operations in western Pennsylvania, em-ploying more than 10,000 people in our region and more than 60,000 nationwide. Estimates based on the more than 100 foreign companies our law firm represents indicate that only 4 percent of these firms' employees are from other countries. But without those 4 percent who are immigrants - managers, technicians, scientists and others with special skills - these businesses and these other thousands of jobs would not exist.<P>The Simpson bill reduces the available employment-based immigration visas by 46 percent, from its current level of 140,000 to 90,000 per year.<P>Simpson wants these jobs to go to Americans. But what will really happen is that the jobs won't be filled at all. As a result, other jobs will be lost.<P>Here are some examples of how employment of a very small number of highly skilled immigrants creates jobs for people in western Pennsylvania:<P>
<LI>	A Pittsburgh-based equipment manufacturer with 50 employees that is developing a technology that the federal government has deemed to be in the national interest needs four Russian engineers who know more about the technology than anyone else in the world. <P>
<LI>	A Japanese conglomerate employing 4,000 people nationwide (200 in Pittsburgh) is directed by 140 immigrants who are transferring a proprietary technology developed in Japan.<P>
<LI>    One of the world's largest companies, with its U.S. headquarters in Pittsburgh, constantly applies technologies developed in one part of the world to the rest of the world. As a result of its ability to import the needed scientists and technocrats, thousands of manufacturing and support jobs are created in the United States.<P>First on Simpson's "hit list" are nonimmigrant, or temporary, visa categories. The legislation reduces the authorized period of stay from six to three years for professionals who obtain visas under what is known as the H-1B status. And the Simpson bill requires all employers who hire foreign professionals under the H-1B visa category to pay a "penalty" to the U.S. government of 5 percent of the employee's yearly income in year one, 7.5 percent in year two and 10 percent in year three. <P>Perhaps most outrageous is the proposal to make employers who "sponsor" a permanent resident pay 105 percent of the "prevailing wage" rate, that is, the average compensation paid to all other similarly situated workers, and also pay a tax of 10 percent of the employee's annual income. <P>Only an outcry from business will defeat the Simpson bill.  The Pitts-burgh business community should join with businesses across the country in making it clear to Congress why the proposed legislation is unnecessary.  <P>Tell your elected officials that   both nonimmigrant and immigrant       workers are instrumental to the success of many businesses. Explain that if    the Simpson legislation becomes law, American business will be unable to obtain highly specialized workers    from abroad who help keep our    country competitive.                               n<P>Lawrence M. Lebowitz, chairman of the Pittsburgh chapter of the American Immigration Lawyers Association, is a director with the Pittsburgh law firm of Cohen & Grigsby.<P><P>



<hr>


<P>


