<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>
</i></b>

<HR>
<H2>Working Like a Dog</h2>When Gail Amshel of Pittsburgh was laid off from her job as a pharmaceutical sales representative a few years ago, she was relieved. The stressful career didn't suit her personality. She decided try something she liked to do. And what she liked to do most was take care of animals.  <P>But turning that love into a career was another matter. Amshel knew how to care for animals. She had volunteered for years at the Pittsburgh Zoo and had raised pets all her life. Then her veterinarian wanted the name of a pet sitter to whom the vet could refer people, so Amshel gave him her phone number. She got six calls in two weeks. She knew she was on to something.<P>Today, Amshel's life is very different from her pharmaceutical sales days, and immensely more rewarding.  After two successful years in the pet sitting business, Amshel has five independent contractors. Despite hair-raising experiences like pet sitting three dive-bombing cockatiels, three 35-pound South American tortoises and an attacking rooster, Amshel feels very lucky. <P>"I am one of the fortunate few who get to make a living doing what I truly love," she says.<P>Amshel had some help early on. The Service Corps of Retired Executives counseled Amshel on how much pet sitting she would need to do to make a living. SCORE also helped her secure liability insurance, and helped her legally hire the independent contractors.<P>"She had the vision," SCORE counselor Horace Miles says, "and I helped her tackle some of the early problems."<P>National trends show that pets are big business, from breeding them to feeding them to Amshel's niche: taking care of pets when the owner is away. <P>In Eugene, Ore., Dan and Trish Cole leased a defunct gas station and opened Suds'Em Yourself, a full-time, self-service dog wash. The Coles provide waist-high dog tubs so customers won't have to bend over, and electric dryers to blow away the wet-dog aroma. The cost is $6 for small, short-hair dogs and $11 for family-sized, long-hair models.<P>The Coles average 20 dogs a day and employ part-time helpers.<P>The pets are even doing the work themselves in some businesses. Many firms now pay $450 to $800 a month to hire guard dogs instead of paying at least $2,000 a month for a security guard.<P>      In other re-gions, firms are renting dogs to women who take them along as protection while they jog or walk for exercise. One example is Project Safe Run, which was started by a rape victim from Oregon. For a  $25 monthly fee, women can call to reserve a dog, then pick it up and run, walk or hike. The service also has been used by senior citizens of both sexes. <P>While running, the dogs wear backpacks that display the Project Safe Run logo. They also carry the runner's keys, wallet, phone numbers and a Pooper-Scooper. Not every dog makes the cut. They must have the smarts to bite on command, but also must demonstrate restraint by refusing any food that is not placed in their bowl at home.                                                   n<h2> Plowing Through</h2>Is your back shot yet? Or - if you own a small business - is your snow removal budget shot yet?<P>A Pittsburgh firm is banking on it.<P>Just in time for the dead of winter, Solotec Corp. came out with its Driv'nPlow, a lightweight, portable snow plow that works with most mid-sized sedans, compact cars and minivans. The company is hoping that people will drop $279.95 for convenience beyond snowblowers.<P>"This is for professional people who really don't have a lot of time to waste," says Thome Matisz of Solotec. "For that matter, the Driv'nPlow really is for anyone who has better things to do with their time than shovel snow."<P>The plow can connect to the wheel wells of a vehicle or just sit on the ground as the vehicle nudges it along.<P>"In most cases, you don't need to hitch it," Matisz says. "The idea is that the consumer can push it with the car, and that's the beauty of this product."<P>Solotec has shipped units from its South Park warehouse to points all over the Northeast and parts of Canada. Locally, Builders Square and Walmart are carrying the plow, and at press time, Matisz expected to soon have it in Sam's Club.<P>Matisz says the plow unit weighs about 43 pounds and will work with any vehicle with a bumper height of 17 inches or less. That means it won't work with most trucks or sport utility vehicles.<P>When not in use, the plow stores in a garage just like a ladder.<P>The Driv'nPlow will not remove ice, but it did push away 17-inch-deep snow in one run this winter.                  n<P>




<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

