<HEAD>
<TITLE> EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Two Outta Three Ain't Good</b> 
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Pennsylvania Business is Still Working for<br>Ridge to make a move on Worker's Compensation                 

</font><BR>
<i>By Jim Strader
</i>

<HR>
Winning two races in the Triple Crown brings a big purse for a thoroughbred. A batting average of .666 is a dream for a major leaguer. And, in the words of Meat Loaf, the singer who made his name his meal ticket, "Two out of three ain't bad."<P>So, after accomplishing two of their top three objectives in Harrisburg last year, why weren't business leaders satisfied?<P>Maybe it's because the missing jewel - after lower taxes and regulatory improvements - is workers' compensation reform.<P>"For the business community, it has continued to be a major issue," says Don Liskay, president of CompServices Inc., a workers' compensation company based in Pittsburgh.<P>"It's vital to the economic growth of Pennsylvania. Workers' compensation costs are significant," Liskay says. "To the extent we can bring those costs in line with other states, we're in a better position to compete."<P>Otherwise, say Liskay and others, companies will look elsewhere for expansion opportunities. And, they add, companies now doing business in Pennsylvania may be tempted to move.<P>Gov. Tom Ridge had cutting the costs of workers' compensation on his agenda when he came into office a year ago. The Republican governor listed it with other objectives - such as lower business taxes and a more user-friendly attitude on the part of state regulators - that he felt would put Pennsylvania in a better position to compete with other states.<P>	But the issue never got to the top of Ridge's list. After early legislative success in setting standards for hearing-loss claims, workers' comp remained in the "to do" column.<P>A couple of things got in the way.<P>Foremost, Ridge pushed hard for an education program based on school choice and taxpayer-funded tuition vouchers (or grants, as Ridge called them). The initiative failed first in June, then a revamped proposal fell apart in December. A lot of time, effort and political capital were spent, to no avail.<P>Some saw Ridge's emphasis on the education plan as a bid for national attention in the year before a presidential election. For a 50-year-old governor who likely has higher political ambitions - though he says repeatedly that he is kept busy being governor - such an achievement could have made him an attractive GOP running mate for the White House.<P>Ridge also owed the Roman Catholic Church for its political backing in his run for governor. Despite Ridge's advocacy of abortion rights, the church was seen by some to be looking the other way on that issue in hopes of a win on tuition vouchers. A governor who is the product of Catholic schools and has children in Catholic schools now is a needed ally for the church.<P>Also keeping workers' compensation legislation from moving was the issue's complexity and the fierce fight promised by the numerous parties with vital interests in its outcome.<P>In addition, the architect of the last major workers' compensation legislation, Earl Baker, resigned from the Senate to pursue a job in the private sector. He was sure to have been a driving force in further reform.<P>"I think that slowed the process. He had a tremendous amount of expertise on this issue and had spent years studying the issue," says Liskay, who also chairs the workers' compensation committee of the Pennsylvania Chamber of Business and Industry. <P>Liskay's organization, the primary lobbying group for business in Harrisburg, signed on in support of a bill introduced late in the 1995 legislative session by Rep. Joseph Gladeck, a Republican from the Philadelphia area.<P>Gladeck's goal is simple: to help businesses cut their costs in workers' compensation coverage and insurance. He promotes his bill as an economic development measure, aimed at keeping Pennsylvania businesses in the state and bringing new business in.<P>"The bottom line for business is the cost, and you really need a system that is fair and equitable and provides an adequate level of benefits for people who are injured on the job," Liskay says. "The original mission of workers' compensation hasn't changed in that regard, but it has become very costly in Pennsylvania and it's time for us to correct it."<P>Although eager to get the issue moving, business leaders are reluctant to gripe too loudly. After all, Ridge and the General Assembly have been kind.<P>"I don't know if you'd characterize it as frustration," Liskay says of the sentiment he perceives. "We believe the commitment is there on the part of the administration."                                  n<P>
<P>





<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

