<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Move Over Jake
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>Siena is What Home Would be Like, if you Had the Time
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<p>

<hr>
Every month when the catalogues and home magazines come, do you let your mind wander to the atmosphere you might create - if you had the time, the money and no kids or dogs? The owners of Siena, a new restaurant that its owners label "culinary art," have indulged those fantasies.<P>Downtown in Market Square, the space Jake's formerly occupied has gotten a comprehensive facelift - and a beautiful one at that. The space has been redecorated in rich shades of amber and ivory, the walls have been sponged with glowing color, and the shades on the unique ceiling window panels sparkle with celestial bodies. Unusually crafted wooden chairs, rather resembling executioner's stocks, distinguish the bar area. Muslin chaircovers and tapestry pillows in jewel tones are touches that make the room both elegant and warm. <P>Which seems to be the theme throughout. The decor, the menu, the service - all professional and exact, yet warm and unintimidating. Contem-porary, but not pretentious.<P>The menu is the same way. The offerings salve those venturing from their regular roosts while pleasing those looking for new cuisine by using familiar ingredients (well, most of them - I'm still not sure I know, or want to know, what forcemeat is) in inventive combinations.<P>The appetizer list includes creations like their beggar's purse, a "blend of goat cheese, herbs and seedless grapes enveloped in phyllo." We tried the grilled salmon flatbread, which is a small flatbread pizza layered with Boursin cheese, salmon and caviar. The result is remarkable, but avoid the caviar if you don't like things fishy. Another delight is the Maine lobster cakes, which are smooth and delicious, served under a towering baked cracker shaped like a trellis.<P>The Siena salad is a potpourri of greens, including radicchio, beet and escarole. The grilled portobella salad tops the same greens with a meaty mushroom, seared and juicy. Both are a meal. Careful, they're liberal with the salad dressing - we chose the balsamic vinaigrette, which was on the oily side.<P>The entree selection goes from chicken to fish to beef, with some more unique offerings, like venison. Vegetarians have a couple of interesting choices, such as wild mushroom ravioli and a casserole of root vegetables. We tried the rack of lamb, which was beautifully grilled but unfortunately paired with a forgettable bread stuffing. The dish was sided with a very nice complement of quinoa, an ancient grain favored by the Maya. The venison medallions were crusted with walnuts and pine nuts, served atop a slice of grilled yam and dotted with cranberry chutney. The venison was farm- raised, which will suit those who like their game more tame than game, but was a little underdone for my tastes, though I ordered it medium rare. Laid out on a huge serving plate, the food is presented beautifully. <P>The food sounds creative and looks beautiful, but falls a little short in preparation. Perhaps, having only opened in November, it's still gelling -for the owners have between them opened enough restaurants to feed the region. Owners Robin Fernandez (a partner in Metropol and Rosebud), Eric Barth (a Texan with 35 restaurants under his belt), Eric Fernandez (Robin's brother, money guy) and Michael Schumacher, (food and beverage guy) bring an array of talent to the restaurant and, together, have designed Siena as a total experience. The wine list is impressive, and they'll open any bottle to sell a glass. Aperitifs, cigars and espresso are offered after dinner. <P>Add the name Siena to the growing list of restaurants upping the ante for local establishments. That's both creatively and financially: Be prepared, or the bill could take your breath away. Dinner for two, including appetizers, salads and entrees, was $140 before adding a tip. You can't do it every day. <P>But you get what you pay for. <P> Siena<BR>430 Market Square<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa.  15222<BR>412/338-0945<BR>Hours: <BR>Lunch, Mon. - Fri., 11:00 to 2:00 p.m.<BR>Dinner, Mon. - Sat., 5 to 11 p.m.<BR>Appetizers and Salads: $4.95 - $14.95<BR>Entrees: $14.95 - $29.95<P>


<hr><P>


<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

