<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>



<P>
<B><I><font size=+2>Helen Hanna Casey</font></I></B></center><P>


<HR>
<b>
Name:		Helen Hanna Casey<BR>
Age:            46<BR>
Personal:       Married, Two Children, Lives in Shadyside<BR>
Education:      B.S., Georgian Court, 1971<BR>
Last Vacation:  In December, To London<BR>
</B>
<hr>
In 1957, Howard and Anne Hanna founded Howard Hanna Real Estate Services, then a small mom-and-pop business serving the East End neighborhoods. Though their three kids, Hoddy, Helen and Annie, all got broker's licenses at age 18, none of them meant to go into real estate. But in the '70s, for one reason or another, all of them ended up in the family business - eventually setting it on the path to what it is today. The region's largest realtor, Howard Hanna Real Estate Services has 22 residential and commercial sales and leasing offices, 750 associates and 10 ancillary companies. Helen Hanna Casey, second of the three children, is now president of residential sales for the company. No middle child underachieving complex here - Casey is overseeing what can only be termed unprecedented growth for the company. She talked to ER's Lydia Strohl about the family empire at their plush new offices in RIDC Park.<P>Executive Report: You grew up in this industry, right?<P>Helen Hanna Casey: My father started this company when I was six. He had been executive director of the Homebuilders' association and he was transferred to Cleveland. My parents had just restored a 170-year-old house. So he commuted. Then he was transferred to Chicago. My grandmother was not well, and my mother didn't want to leave Pittsburgh. So he started his own company.<P>ER: Why real estate?<P>HHC: I'm not sure. There were probably a couple of reasons. In the 1940s in Pittsburgh, you either worked for a major company or you worked for a start-up business. My father went back and got his master's in economics, I'm not sure why. His grandfathers both had family businesses, and my mother's family came from a family business. A good friend of his dad's had a real estate company: That's where he did I guess what you would call his apprenticeship, working for a year before he started his own company.<P>ER: What was the industry like then?<P>HHC: It was very different. We refer today to them as mom-and-pops, one-office companies. Then, everything was a one-office company. We always had a lot of women working for us, but most companies had a lot more men in the sales force. You had one office that specialized in that one area, people didn't cross around town as much. You did a little of everything, different kinds of sales, rentals, notary public, insurance, all kinds of things that we really didn't do. We really specialized in residential, and a little commercial.<P>ER: When did your growth occur?<P>HHC: The real growth mode came in the '70s, for a couple of reasons. My father bought an appraisal business that had a base in the North Hills. Then my brother [Hoddy Hanna, now president] came in and the decision was made that now was the time to expand. Our real growth, and this is unusual about us, started in the city. In other markets where there is a regional broker that is the major broker, most of them started in the suburbs. We followed the migration of our clients. Where our clients moved we moved, so we went to Fox Chapel, Forest Hills/Churchill market, etc.<P>ER: Was a conscious decision then made to have the company become more than a nice living for your family?<P>HHC: I would say that came a little later. Certainly my brother had the advantage, because of my father, to be able to go to other cities to look at other companies, to take courses, to look nationally to see what growth patterns were. We grew tremendously in the '70s, and I would say by the late '70s there was a concerted plan to be the largest regional broker.<P>ER: And you joined the company just after your brother?<P>HHC: It's a little odd. We all got our licenses when we were 18, because when you're a sole proprietor you worry if something happens. My mother never really sold, but she has her license. They wanted the protection, but they didn't want us to get into the business - any of us. My brother worked in the summers during college selling. But my sister and I were also licensed at 18 - and I can remember being a rental agent in a pinch one summer or something - but we didn't come in until after school.<P>Each of us had different plans when we went to school. My brother was to go to law school. I can still remember the night he told my parents he wasn't going. I had planned on going to law school also, and instead worked on my master's in history, then got married, had babies and taught. I joined the company in 1976 - I'm the middle child, but I was the last of the three. My sister Annie [Cestra], get this, got her master's in deaf education. <P>The draw was different for me, probably, than for them. I was teaching in a small private school and came into the industry like a lot of women, with a personal need for more income. My father was saying that what I knew as women in the industry in the '50s and '60s was not the same as women in the '70s, that what we were seeing was young, educated women who were really coming in and making a name for themselves and establishing their own careers. I think for a lot of the women in the '50s it wasn't so much a choice, they had to go make a living because they were widowed or whatever, in a time when not many women worked. And they were not in the mainstream of society because they were working women, I don't think they considered it a career. You worked a couple of hours here, a couple of hours there, sold people from your bridge club, whatever.<P>That changed dramatically in that 20-year span, to something that had more structure.<P>ER: Are women better at sales than men?<P>HHC: No. I think more women are in the business than men, so the numbers are very skewed. This is because of the flexibility, and because women have done very well in it. They can have a very good career and still have a family. That's why people come in, because they want to have flexibility. But it's the flexibility of personality, not just of time, that makes the difference, that makes success. You've got to be able to switch from one thing to another very quickly.<P>  I'm a firm believer that the word salesman is a dirty word in this country. We have tre-mendous numbers of associates that are former nurses or teachers, and they would never have said that they were salespeople, but I don't think you can get a third-grader to learn fractions unless you can sell them on the idea that it has some meaning for their life. You're selling your ideas. <P>ER: You've had a lot to do with training and development since you've been in the company. How has that changed the career?<P>HHC: There's a theory that people used to come into real estate and they would say, "Here's your desk, here's your phone, start calling people."<P>We were never structured quite that way. Through the years my brother and my father had training, but it was not very structured. I formulated that into a structure. I had advantages because I was able to go off and see what other people were doing. There were days I would go places and watch training tapes for 10 hours and decide what was best for us. People wanted more training, more structure. We've always done one-on-one training, and people across the country are always amazed at the time that our management team puts into training. <P>ER: Has the industry changed in the same manner that Howard Hanna has changed?<P>HHC: Multi-office companies in the '70s and '80s really grew. Some survived and some didn't. There have been major changes in that - nationals coming in and buying local firms, franchising, 100-percent concepts - that have come in over the years.<P>The key to our success without question at Howard Hanna is two things: Our ability, because it's privately owned and it's our name on it, to take the chance, to know that we're only putting ourselves at risk when we open a new market area or buy a new company. And number two, the people who are associated with us - people who have been here years - and are part of the Hanna family. <P>ER: Is it difficult to incent people for commitment to a company that is so family-oriented?<P>HHC: In 1979, we had really opened up a whole bunch of offices. And what did we do - we moved our people up and around. My brother hired a consultant - one of our big concerns was nepotism. When I first started in the business, I lived in Highland Park and had two small children, and I worked in the North Hills office. It was tough, but we were afraid that if I worked in our city office everyone would think it was unfair. So I went to the North Hills for six months, then came back to the city office. Then a couple years later this consultant comes in. I wasn't being considered for any management job, my sister had always been back of office, never in the sales force. He wanted to meet with us, and came back telling us, "You're not using your best assets, your family is your asset here." <P>I can remember someone telling me they were going to leave because I was the manager of that office and they could never be manager. I said, "I don't believe that. I'm 30 years old, and if you think I intend to be manager of this office for 40 years, you're nuts." Sure enough, in 18 months I was regional manager. <P>ER: Do you use unique incentives?<P>HHC: It's always hard to tell. We basically have the same kind of program in terms of commission, but we have additional incentives that we think are different because we don't charge off a lot of things to our sales associates. We pay the advertising expenses, etc. A lot of the incentives we think grow business. We have quarterly events, annual trips, profit-sharing that is not affected by anything but their own production. <P>Three years ago, we put our sales associates on a program where they can get a monthly check, called the income advantage. I don't know anyone else in the country that had it at the time; we were in the Wall Street Journal. About 20 companies have it now. It's a tremendous boon to us. The nature of the industry is that you get paid large sums of money at closing. We hope it gives people more security.<P>ER: The company has been on a real growth spurt. How far can you go?<P>HHC: As far as we want. We've  gone into Beaver County and Lawrence County this year, we went into Washington County last year and Butler the year before. It'll be a big growth year in terms of our expansion. We're going to cross the border into other states.<P>We think the opportunities are that a lot of the outlying counties have individual brokers. We see expansion of what a work commute is - 10 years ago in Pittsburgh a half-hour commute was a long time. Today, 45 minutes is not uncommon. We see an expansion of the edge cities. <P>We're lucky to have a diversity of desires here. People want city living - and we're fortunate many of our city neighborhoods never had to be regentrified. New construction will continue to expand. I believe there is a desire for more community feeling. People are no longer just moving to a school district. Families, especially, are more concerned with where the park is, where the library is, what services are available in my neighborhood.<P>ER: Is Pittsburgh still the place where people who visit are astounded at how little a house costs?<P>HHC: That changed, for two reasons, after about 1990. On the East and West Coasts, 50 to 100 percent appreciation a year, so they weren't coming with realistic numbers. There was a leveling off on the East and West Coasts. And all of western Pennsylvania, between 1988 and 1992, had more appreciation than they normally had.<P>ER: So you're planning to stay a regional company?<P>HHC: It depends what "region" is. Without question there are parts of Ohio right now that are part of the future of our region. West Virginia is the future of our region. We can look at what we have mapped out for the next two years, but the region could be far beyond that in three years.                        n<P>
<P>



