<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>An Off Month
</font><br>
<font size=+1>The Technology Stocks Take Some Lumps
</font><BR>
<i>By Doug Thomas
</i></b>

<HR>
What technology stocks giveth, the market hath taken away. FORE Systems, Respironics and II-VI Inc. all lost ground in the month ended Dec.15, which in turn caused the ER Index to slip slightly behind the S&P 500, but only for the month.<P>Since inception in August 1994, our basket of local stocks has risen 35.4 percent, while the S&P index is now up just 33.6 percent. For the month, though, the S&P won hands down, with a 3.99 percent return vs. just 2.7 percent for the ER Index. The exciting part of the story is that many of the companies in the Index, including those mentioned above, are busy positioning themselves for a bright 1996 and beyond.<P>FORE Systems, for instance, made two significant acquisitions that should bolster its leading position in computer networking. FORE purchased Alantec Corp., the San Jose, Ca.-based maker of network switches, which are electronic devices that boost the transmission speed of computer data through local-area computer networks. FORE makes networking equipment based on asynchronous transfer mode, which is faster still. Its acquisition of Alantec should enable FORE to help its customers increase their capacity to send computer data by applying ATM to their local networks.<P>The stock transaction, which is worth approximately $716 million, is expected to be completed in March. The merger, says Eric Cooper, FORE's chairman and CEO, "gives us the opportunity to have it all in our bag."<P>FORE also bought a private company, CellAccess Technology Inc., a Los Gatos, Ca.-based supplier of digital access products used in computer networks. CellAccess will expand FORE's ATM product line and provide a cost-effective way to link LANs and circuit applications such as voice and video in remote offices to wide area networks. CellAccess will cost FORE approximately $45.5 million in stock.<P>Since the beginning of the year, FORE shares have nearly doubled in value.<P><B>Around the Index</B><P><HR>Cable Design announced late in December that it would purchase Northern Telecom Ltd.'s Canadian communication cable and network wiring unit in a deal that could double Cable Design's annual revenue. Cable Design posted revenue of $189 million for its fiscal year, which ended in July. Northern Telecom's projected annual revenue is $190 million.<P>As part of the $90 million deal, Cable Design gets a number of important new products as well as offices in Canada and 800 employees, including salespeople in Europe, the Pacific Rim and Latin America.<P>Cable Design also reported record results for its quarter ended Oct. 31, with sales up 45 percent and net income up 66 percent. The company also effected a 3-for-2 stock split that was effective Dec. 29.<P>Cable Design, which went public in Nov. 1993, has risen nearly              133 percent since August 1994. It jumped more than 28 percent last month alone.<P><HR>Astrotech International reported a superb fourth fiscal quarter, ended Sept. 30, which capped a terrific year for the maker of stor age tank products. Revenue for the quarter increased to $28.9 million from $23.7 million, while earnings per share doubled to 10 cents from 5 cents in the period. For the year, revenues topped $100 million vs. nearly $69 million last year, while operating income was 28 cents vs. 9 cents.<P>The company ended the year    with "substantial improvement in   revenues and profitability," says             S. Kent Rockwell, Astrotech's chairman and CEO.<P><HR>Aluminum Company of America announced in December that it will build a $32.5 million plant in Hungary to make forged aluminum wheels for trucks and buses. The company says demand for its strong and lightweight wheels throughout the world will soon exceed its U.S. production capacity.<P>In other news, ALCOA promoted company veteran Alain Belda to the new position of vice chairman, possibly making him a strong contender to succeed Paul O'Neill as chairman and CEO. Belda was one of two people who previously were being groomed for the position. <P><HR>Doug Thomas is vice president, director of research for Lancaster, Pa.-based Emerald Asset Management.<P>
<P>



