<HEAD>
<TITLE> HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H15Health.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Law.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>Rewards of Research<br>
</font></I></B>

<b><font size =+1>The Region's Research Environment Helps Draw Medical<br>Talent -But Will Decreasing Funding Edge Us Out?</b></font><br>
<i>By Christopher Lawton</i>
</center><P>


<HR>
It used to be that a patient with a brain tumor underwent traumatic and difficult surgery - difficult for both patient and surgeon alike.<P>Not any more, due to a physician who now calls Pittsburgh home.<P>Dr. Takanuri Fukushima, a world- renowned geneticist, was lured away from the University of Southern California by Pittsburgh's Allegheny Singer Research Institute, where he now chairs the Human Genetics department.<P>"One of the more difficult types of surgery involves the extraction of tumors from inside the skull," says Leslie Shuttleworth, vice president of ASRI. "However, with the discovery of new equipment and new techniques, this surgery can now be performed more efficiently and with less pain."<P>Fukushima is just one example of how the Pittsburgh healthcare community, by mixing research with clinical treatment, is attracting top talent. These are special people.<P>"Many people in this country don't understand the complex nature of the research environment," says Dr. Ronald B. Herberman, associate vice chancellor of research, health sciences at the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center. "They don't realize that the research scientist must have a firm understanding of minute details, as well as a complete knowledge of how the research will be delivered at the clinical level."<P>Top researchers are important to a healthcare community not only because of the innovation they bring and the attention this garners - they also  attract funding to the community. Pennsylvania is one of the top five states receiving research grant funds from the National Institutes for Health. <P>Pitt annually receives research grants totaling $650 million. These funds have led directly to innovations such as Dr. Jonas Salk's discovery of the polio vaccine in the 1960s. More recently, Pitt's research efforts led to the discovery of a defective gene that can cause aortic aneurysms. Pitt also pioneered techniques in breast cancer treatment, replacing the radical treatment of mastectomy with the     less disfiguring lumpectomy.  The list goes on.<P>"Advances in research at the Western Psychiatric Hospital led to a technique whereby patients who have a higher likelihood of developing Alzheimers' can be detected much earlier," UPMC's Herberman says.<P>But Herberman and others are concerned, because reasearch funds don't flow in like they used to.<P>"Simply put, research centers, including UPMC, are having to consider sources of nontraditional funding, such as joint ventures with corporations, both medical and nonmedical, and associations with venture capital companies," says Herberman. <P>"Other research institutions that don't have the magnitude of UPMC's research budget and absorb much of their own cost may fare better, but the amount of research will be drastically reduced."<P>Anthony Sanzo, president of Allegheny General Hospital, of which ASRI is the research arm, agrees. "When reimbursements and grants for research decline, so will the amount of research that's conducted. <P>   "It's a catch-22 situation," Sanzo says.<P>  Another factor that hurts academic health centers in their research mission is that they often must absorb the costs of treating high numbers of Medicaid and Medicare patients. And because Pennsylvania has a proportionately higher percentage of elderly who participate in these plans, Pennsylvania academic health centers, including those in Pittsburgh, face severe constraints. <P>But Allegheny Singer Research Institute, which is largely funded by internal revenue sources, has many successes to its name. In addition to Fukushima's previously mentioned research, in 1985 Dr. George McGovern, an ASRI cardiologist, performed the first dynamic cardiomyplasty in the U.S. In this operation,  a flap of muscle is trained to "beat" as a means of assisting a weakened heart, an innovative approach.<P>The United States has the finest healthcare in today's world, due in large part to research innovation. Now research institutions, faced with increasing healthcare cost containment demands, must go one better. <P>They have the heavy responsibility of realistically weighing the benefits of their programs, and then leveraging dollars today to ensure discoveries tomorrow. And if they don't? <P>We all lose.                                     <P>
<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

