<HEAD>
<TITLE> Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>The Employee Handbook<br>
</font></I></B>

<b><font size =+1>Most Businesses Should Have One, But Draft It<br>In a Manner That Will Keep YouOut Of Court</b></font><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
</center><P>


<HR>
When Judith Smith lost her job at a professional services firm in eastern Pennsylvania, she headed to court with the firm's employee handbook tucked firmly under her arm. Her gripe? That though the detailed handbook set salary levels for each employee classification at the firm, her pay fell below the level designated for her job.<P>The federal court ruled that the employer - in developing the handbook - had written itself into a contract for Smith's salary. So "pay up," the court told the firm, finding that Smith was entitled to the difference between the salary level set in the handbook and what she actually was paid.<P>Employee handbooks bring many benefits to employers, but they also can sometimes - as Smith's lawsuit illustrates - leave a window through which the employer may be dragged into court. So while it's prudent to have a handbook, labor attorneys say make sure you do it right.<P>"Draft your employee handbook so that no reasonable person would consider it as having formed a contract," says attorney Sidney Zohn of Buchanan Ingersoll. "What we see are a lot of different approaches by employees as they try to sue employers."<P><B>Why a Handbook?</B><P>	You think your company is too small to need a handbook? Attorney Bob Prorok of Reed Smith Shaw & McClay points to one state law on discrimination that applies to companies with as few as four employees.<P><B>No company may be too small.</B><P>"Everybody should have one because of the benefits handbooks bring," Prorok says. "The size of the company may certainly affect the size of the handbook - smaller companies don't need as complex a setup - but size should not affect whether or not you have one."<P>"I think generally it's a good idea to have an employee handbook," says attorney Joe Vater of Meyer Unkovic & Scott. "There's one caveat: The employee handbook should be done right, be updated and be followed. If your company won't do one of those three things, then you are better off without it."<P>Prorok and Vater both agree that one key benefit of a clearly written handbook is employee satisfaction. If the rules and requirements are in black and white, the employees know what they can and cannot do. They are unlikely to go to a third party, such as a plaintiff's attorney, for interpretation of or advice about their legal rights.<P>The other main benefit of a handbook, provided that it is followed, is its use when employees charge that they've been mistreated.<P>"Part of every wrongful termination lawsuit is the claim 'You terminated me for X reason, but Joe did the same thing and you didn't terminate him,'" Prorok says.<P>"If you have uniform rules and uniformly apply those rules, it really rebuts the claim that one employee was treated differently than another."<P><B>At-Will Employment</B><P>Pennsylvania is an at-will employment state, meaning employers can terminate an employee at any time, for any reason, or for no reason at all. The courts have protected that right, declining in most instances to declare handbook language as having formed a contract. When an employee sued Conrail, for instance, the Superior Court of Pennsylvania rejected the employee's claim that handbook language, combined with performance appraisals, formed a contract. <P>But employers should take assertive steps to keep disputes from even reaching court. And that can mean making sure the employee handbook doesn't leave openings for employees to sue.<P><B>Some Steps Are Simple</B> <P>One is placing in the handbook a disclaimer noting that nothing in the handbook is intended to form a contract, and that the employee remains an employee at will.<P>Some employers even take it one step further, requiring employees to sign a receipt when they receive the handbook, acknowledging that they understand that the procedures contained in the handbook are for informational purposes only and do not constitute a contract. Vater says he tells his clients to have the employees sign the receipt a few days later, after they've had time to review the handbook.<P>Common mistakes include the use of language that could guarantee employment. Zohn says those terms include "grievance procedure, probationary period, tenure or vested."<P>Some employers also use language that may create a mandatory disciplinary procedure with a "just cause" standard. Instead, Zohn says the language should be open-ended.<P>Most importantly, employers should periodically review and update employee handbooks. Management at one company sued by a terminated employee forgot that a handbook even existed. The employee produced it, and it turned the case in the employee's favor.<P>"These handbooks are something nobody thinks about until they're sued," Vater says. "Then they go scrambling and ask, 'What does it say?'"      <BR>
<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

