<a href="../zine/0296.Law.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Employee Retention</font><br><font size=+1>A Little Flexibility Goes a Long Way Toward<br>Keeping the Staff Intact<br>
</font></B><i>By Henry Lipput</center></i><P>


<HR>
Joe Tomko and his wife were expecting their second child, but they weren't expecting this: Early into the pregnancy, Tomko's boss walked up to him and offered a week off with pay upon the birth of the child. Tomko's boss told him to use the paid leave to take care of his wife and new baby.<P>"It is amazing," says Tomko, who works for Pittsburgh graphics design firm A to Z Communications. "I was quite happy, needless to say."<P>So was Goldie Ostrow, co-founder of A to Z, who can personally attest to the return she receives for making such gestures toward deserving employees. For Ostrow, it's been a strategy of success since she went into business close to eight years ago.<P>She went seven years without having an employee quit, a record most small businesses wish they could boast. The ability to retain employees is crucial to efficiency and profitability in small businesses. Businesses with high turnover rates waste time and money recruiting, hiring and training replacements.<P>Ellen Ruddock of Career Dynamics, a business consulting company, says it's important for small businesses to recognize the flexibility they possess and learn how to use it as a mechanism to reward employees.<P>"We know that people go where they are wanted and stay where they are appreciated," Ruddock says. "And flexibility, nowadays especially, is an important part of that picture. We find that more and more employers are moving away from the mindset that the day and the location and the atmosphere for business has to be exactly what it was 20 years ago."<P>Instead, it's more like the atmosphere at A to Z. Dress is casual. Bonuses are handed out to deserving employees. And then there are the gestures such as the one made toward Tomko.<P>Ostrow says she knows she doesn't have the constraints present in a corporate atmosphere, so she's going to take advantage of it.<P>"In comparing what a small business culture can mean to an employee instead of a large corporate culture, I think there's definitely a lot of flexibility in people's scheduling," Ostrow says. "If somebody needs to go to a doctor's appointment, needs to go to a wedding, needs to run out to see their kids in the school play, that's not a problem here.<P>"We can also bonus people very easily at any point in time and without getting permission or filling out forms," Ostrow says.  "If somebody's been working really hard, we can say to them, 'Why don't you take tomorrow off, this project's done, you were great.' We can give somebody a cash incentive when they've really been working hard, at our discretion, any time.  And I think those are the kinds of things that motivate people.  Everything's very performance-driven, people are definitely paid for performance," Ostrow says.  "I think a lot of large businesses pay lip service to that, but can't really see it or act on it the way we can."  <P>     Ruddock has found that many of her client companies are recognizing the need to work around employee concerns.<P>     "They're not only flexible, but there is an awareness of fairness that has to be carried out," Ruddock says. "They will bend over backwards to recognize and award a good performer with some of those needs that employees have. And every employee wants to be able to take care of their family first and achieve personal goals.<P>   "We know that our personal goals drive our business goals. If our employer's keeping us from meeting those personal goals, it's not too long before the resentment builds up. "  <P>Joe Tomko appreciates working for a small company that can address his personal goals and treat him as an individual.  "Occasionally, there will be a need to resolve a personal situation, whether it's a jury duty thing or whether you have to get your car repaired.  You do the work and get the work done, and they're flexible as to allowing you to leave at different hours.  <P>"In big companies, you can't, you're pretty much stuck in a place from nine to five and they really don't know who you are as much. You're a number," he concludes. "And that's what's real attractive about working for a small business."                                  <P>
<P>



