<TITLE> Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H17Education.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<center><b><font size =+2>
Stress Test</font></B><br>
<B><I><font size=+1>Healthcare Reform Hasn't Yet Trickled Down to the<br>Schools that Produce Doctors, Nurses and Technicians
</font></I></B><br>
<i>By Gretchen McKay</i></center>

<HR>

<P>
The numbers coming out of the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center last April weren't encouraging for young people who were hoping to enter the healthcare field. The medical center said it would lay off 400 people and eliminate almost an identical number of positions via attrition.<P>But some other numbers also were raising eyebrows during this period of upheaval at Pitt and other healthcare institutions in the region: A record number of students were applying to the many healthcare-related programs   offered at regional institutions. <P>The message: Upheaval in healthcare hasn't yet trickled down to the schools that train professionals.<P>"Medicine has and always will be an excellent field. There continues to be a great interest in many other health-related careers as well," maintains Dr. Lauren Roth, associate vice chancellor for education/health science at Pitt and vice president for managed care at University of Pittsburgh Medical Center.<P>Applications for UPMC School of Medicine's 150 spots each year, for example, have jumped to more than 7,000, notes Roth. And programs in pharmacy, public health and rehabilitation science - the design and implementation of wheelchairs and other approaches for the disabled - have also continued to grow.<P>Pitt is not alone. Applications continue to rise at Duquesne University as well, and that doesn't surprise Thomas Schaefer, dean of admissions and international affairs.<P>"Though the nature of healthcare is bound to change [due to healthcare reform], the demand will not," says Schaefer. "The fact is, we don't have control over our health, and the needs are still going to be there. They're just going to be met in different ways."<P>The move toward managed care, for example, has pushed many hospitals and other caregivers to downsize  to become more cost-effective and to emphasize more efficient delivery of services. For instance, a physician's assistant may treat common illnesses and injuries instead of an M.D.; a surgical technologist might draw your blood instead of a registered nurse; a nurse may practice in the home, or a pharmacist in a large chain store instead of a neighborhood shop.<P>Many area schools have modified their existing programs to make them more compatible with market demands, or have created new programs altogether.<P>Take Pitt and Duquesne. Both recently expanded their 5-year pharmacy programs by one year to the doctorate level, in order to help their pharmacists to develop better critical thinking skills and more clinical knowledge.<P>"We're not decreasing the number of pharmacists but giving them more responsibility," says Schaefer, who adds  that without the Ph.D., pharmacists could have trouble finding a job in the future. The training is more intense, and the program is longer, but in the end, "they'll be able to do things only doctors could do in the past."<P>Nursing is feeling the change, too. Many of the tasks R.N.s traditionally performed in the past are now being performed by less-expensive technicians and technologists.<P>Nursing students are going after advanced degrees, such as nurse practitioner, nurse midwife or nurse anesthetist, as nurses will be involved in a patient's primary care.<P>And who is training the technicians who will perform traditional nursing tasks? Many of the same schools. Heeding market demands, Carlow College recently started two-year certificate programs in EEG and surgical technology, both anchored in the national certification process, and applications continue to outnumber the available spaces.<P>"Work patterns are changing," explains Carol Senator, Carlow's director of allied health programs. "Services that were once delivered by expensive professional staff are now being delivered by technicians or technologists, because those services cost less."<P>A year ago, Carlow also became one of the first schools in the country to offer formal education in anesthesia technology.<P>Beyond clinical majors, there's the business of healthcare. Robert Morris College has carved out that niche, offering four business-related undergraduate programs in health services management, long-term healthcare management, nursing management and radiological technology.<P>"When baby boomers hit the upper end of the demographic cycle, we'll have upwards of 45 million Americans 65 years or older, and those people will need healthcare services," says Gloria Barry, acting head of the department of health administration and allied services at Robert Morris. <P>"And there will be an even greater need to manage those services that provide what they need," Barry adds.<P>What's the future hold? Probably much of the same, as emerging medical technologies will require all sorts of expertise from the physicians through the nurses and down to the technicians. That means more learning. <P>"Today's technology," says Pitt's Roth, "along with changing market demands, basically devotes people to a course of lifetime learning. "                <P>


