<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>Sony and the Clean Air Act</B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+>The Law is Overly Burdensome on Pennsylvania Businesses<br>But Sony Showed That You Can Still Do A Major Project Here
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>
It was long before any dirt was moved. Long before a contractor was hired. Long before the public even had a hint that Sony Electronics Inc. and Corning Asahi Video Products might jointly build a glass plant across the street from Sony's existing Westmoreland County facility.<P>The plant would be built all right. It was just a question of whether it would be built in Southwestern Pennsylvania. Sony loved the sprawling East Huntingdon Township site, only a few minutes from the New Stanton interchange of the Pennsylvania Turnpike. But before Sony would commit, it had to first cost out one critical factor: the pollution control requirements imposed by the Clean Air Act.<P>The amendments Congress made to the law in 1990 require companies in Pennsylvania and several other states to purchase what are known as emission credits if the companies emit certain pollutants. Companies that don't have credits to offset the amount of pollutants they emit must buy credits from companies that have more credits than they need. In other words, companies in Pennsylvania have to pay to pollute. In the end, it costs them more to do business here that it would in Ohio or West Virginia.<P>"We felt the emission credits would be available," recalls Mark Small, Sony's irector of corporate environmental affairs. "Our feeling was that it could be done. But the obvious next question was 'How can it be done cost-effectively?'<P>"No one really had attempted something like this - at least in this region - so we had to be innovative."<P>Very innovative, it turns out. Sony spent a full year researching available credits, eventually buying some at a bankruptcy auction. According to parties familiar with the project, Sony spent about $3 million to buy all the pollution credits it needed to meet Clean Air Act requirements. It was a figure with which the electronics giant could live, so the word came down: Move ahead with the project in southwestern Pennsylvania. Today, general contractor P.J. Dick Corp. is constructing the shell of the 500,000-square-foot facility that will begin production in the summer of 1997 and employ at least 500.<P>A happy ending? Not necessarily when you look beyond Sony. <P>While Sony's story definitely is one of success, it also illustrates the burden the Clean Air Act places on companies that do business in Pennsylvania. Moreover, it illustrates why many companies won't consider southwestern Pennsylvania as a place to locate a manufacturing facility.<P>"There are companies out there that look at our region but don't seriously consider Pennsylvania because the restrictions are too hard," says Harold Miller, director of the Southwestern Pennsylvania Growth Alliance, which promotes economic growth in the region.<P>"There are other companies out there that we don't even know about because they don't even look here from the beginning," Miller says.<P>The Clean Air Act<P>Take a deep breath. The air isn't so bad, is it?<P>Truth be told, the air quality in our region has gradually improved since the collapse of the steel industry. Nevertheless, amendments to the Clean Air Act - signed into law by former President Bush after much debate and eventual approval in Congress - cost businesses in our region millions every year. Even worse, the law as it stands now pushes both new and existing companies to Ohio or West Virginia, where the federal pollution restrictions under the Clean Air Act are less stringent. Companies don't pay to pollute in Ohio and West Virginia.<P>The message to businesses in our region is simple: Go west - about 35 miles or so until you cross the state line - where the cost of doing business is much less.<P>"The Clean Air Act makes it more difficult to do business," says attorney Harry Klodowski, who brokers the purchase and sale of emissions credits. "I know companies that have sent their plant expansions to Ohio because of it."<P>So does Scott R. Dismukes, a former Environmental Protection Agency attorney who now heads the environmental practice at the Pittsburgh law firm Doepken Keevican & Weiss. It can be more cost-effective for companies to locate in Ohio, Dismukes says. <P>And for this flight of businesses to Ohio, you can thank the state's Congressional delegation, circa 1990. It supported the Clean Air Act amendments despite what corporate heads in Pittsburgh say was obvious: The ramifications of such a bill on Pennsylvania business would be felt for years.<P>Only one Pennsylvania congressman, Republican U.S. Rep. Bud Shuster of Altoona, shouted "Nay" when the House voted on the bill. The rest - including then-U.S. Rep. Tom Ridge of Erie - voted affirmatively.<P>And it passed.<P>Now Ridge, ironically, in his current capacity as governor of Pennsylvania has launched several attacks against the same measures he voted for in 1990. Late last year, for example, Ridge petitioned the Environmental Protection Agency to remove 37 western Pennsylvania counties from the Northeast Ozone Transport Region, an area covering 12 northeastern and mid-Atlantic states that is subject to stringent and costly pollution control requirements.<P>In Ridge's defense, he was among many legislators who early on had criticized the Clean Air Act amendments for the negative effect they would have on business.<P>Three months before Congress sent the bill to the White House for President Bush's signature, Ridge took the House floor on May 23, 1990, and predicted dire consequences for big business.<P>    "We know that people are going to lose their jobs as a direct result of this legislation, and, oh, indeed what a bitter irony that is," Ridge told his House colleagues from the podium, according to the Congressional Record. "The good news for the people is that they are going to have cleaner air to breathe. The bad news is that they probably will have a little more time to enjoy the outdoors, to hunt and fish and generally enjoy this clean air, because they are going to be out of work as a result of this particular piece of legislation."<P>Yet when it came time to really cast a vote for business, Ridge punted.<P>The Law<P>The Clean Air Act is its common name, but the official title of the law is the Clean Air Restoration & Standards Attainment Act. If you think the name is long, try to plow through the actual law. The bill that went to Bush for his signature totaled more than 1,100 pages and was full of bargains hashed out in the back halls of Congress. In defense of the state's Congressional delegation, our elected lawmakers weren't the only ones who fell in line behind the Clean Air Act amendments.<P>The year 1990, after all, was a time when taking steps to preserve the environment was one way politicians survived the next election. <P>"If you were in Congress and were coming up for re-election, would you want to have to defend the fact that you were anti-environment?" says veteran environmental attorney Dan Darragh of Buchanan Ingersoll.<P>"Would the same bill pass with the current Congress?" Darragh adds. "I don't think so."<P>In 1990, the bill was the subject of months of debate, but eventually breezed through both the House and Senate. In the House, the vote was lopsided at 401-25. The Senate vote was 89-10.<P>Ridge and other lawmakers acknowledged the impact on business, estimating the amendments would take about $22 billion annually from the economy. One of the hardest hit areas would be the Northeast - including Pennsylvania - since companies there would have to pay to pollute while their counterparts in Midwest states like Ohio had no similar costs. In the end, lawmakers justified supporting the amendments with the argument that doing nothing to clean up the nation's air would be even more costly as a result of higher health bills and related economic losses.<P>Perhaps then-Senate majority leader George Mitchell, the venerable Democrat from Maine, best summed up the state of mind in Congress:<P>"With the passage of this legislation, we will take a long overdue step to renewing our national commitment to an active, effective and aggressive program of controlling the pollutants that threaten the air we and all Americans breathe," he said immediately after the Senate vote.<P>In a nutshell, the law marked the first overhaul of the federal clean air law in 13 years. It required new pollution controls on automobiles, factories, thousands of businesses and coal-burning power plants. <P>Specific to Pennsylvania, the amendments designated Allegheny, Armstrong, Beaver, Butler, Fayette, Washington and Westmoreland counties as a moderate nonattainment area for ground-level ozone. That designation was based upon high ozone levels the region experienced during the drought of 1988. And with that designation came costly and burden some requirements placed on existing businesses and any new businesses that might consider locating here.<P>Even worse: The amended Clean Air Act placed the region in the Ozone Transport Region, another black list. So even if southwestern Pennsylvania is redesignated as an attainment area under the law, businesses here will continue to face stringent pollution regulations because they are located within the transport region.<P>Consider these requirements: <P>n Outside businesses locating here or existing ones looking to expand must pay to pollute. They purchase emission credits from other companies that have more than they need. The buyer must obtain credits to cover 115 percent of their own emissions. <P>n An existing business in southwestern Pennsylvania is required to install reasonable available control technology, or RACT, on top of other emission controls. The estimated cost is $1,500 per ton of emissions.<P>The Sony Story<P>Money definitely mattered to Sony, but there were other factors in play.<P>The electronics giant liked the work force southwestern Pennsylvania offered and liked the infrastructure already in place. It also liked the prospect of developing dwhat is known as a "Greenfield Site" under environ-<P>mental law. From a business standpoint, attorney Dismukes of Doepken Keevican & Weiss says developing a Greenfield allows Sony to proceed with little risk of later liability for environmental contamination at the site.<P>But from a cost standpoint, the Clean Air Act still loomed large. In fact, there was a point where spending too much to comply with the Clean Air Act would have made the project cost-prohibitive and sent the plant somewhere else, perhaps down Interstate 70 to Wheeling.<P>"The more we spent, the less attractive western Pennsylvania was going to be," says Small, Sony's environmental guru. <P>Sony's emission credit shopping spree took it to U.S. Bankruptcy Court, where credits belonging to the former General Glass plant in Jeannette, Westmoreland County, were on the block. General Electric also showed up, and the two squared off in a bidding war.<P>"That was the first public auction sale of emission credits where people competitively bid," says Klodowski, the emission credits broker.<P>"GE was bidding against Sony for credits GE needed for a plant expansion it was doing in Grove City. GE pushed up the price, but Sony still got its credits pretty cheap. GE ended up buying credits from a power company and paid even less," Klodowski says.<P>Sony bought the rest of the credits needed to meet the 115 percent requirement from Sharon Steel.<P>"No one really has written a book on this, so everything we've done you could really consider precedent," says Sony's Small. "There is information available ... what credits and who has them, but this process is something that cannot be done overnight. For us, it was probably a year-long effort to secure the credits."<P>Most importantly, it was completed within the budget. The time investment paid off.<P>"Obviously, the price that we spent was not enough to make us pick another location," Small says.<P>Ozone Transport Region<P>How bad is our region's air? It's not good, but it's not bad. In fact, had it not been for unseasonably hot, humid periods during some recent summers, the region's air would probably meet the ground-level ozone requirements set by the Clean Air Act. So Miller of the Growth Alliance holds out some hope that the region can soon gain attainment classification.<P>But there's also the distinct possibility that the region's nonattainment classification could be downgraded to "serious nonattainment." During last summer's unrelenting heat, the level of ozone recorded at one monitoring station in the region was the highest it has been since 1988, according to the Allegheny County Health Department. <P>If a downgrade occurs, the 115 percent capacity requirement on new or expanded plants would jump to 120 percent. Regulations that now apply to businesses which produce 100 tons of emissions annually would apply to businesses producing just 50 tons. <P>Then there is the issue of the Ozone Transport Region. Even if the region wins attainment status, it still would be subject to stringent emission standards as part of the Ozone Transport Region. As previously mentioned, Ohio and West Virginia are not in the Ozone Transport Region even though power plants in the Ohio Valley are a source of the pollutants blowing east.<P>"It's a tough thing because a good share of Pennsylvania's pollution does come from out of state," says Shirley Loveless of the Pennsylvania Environ-mental Council. "The unfortunate part is the competitive disadvantage for our state. Businesses in other states that cause a good bit of our air pollution don't have the same costs.<P>"What do we do? We've got some health problems that we know are present even with the standards as they are, so I don't think we want to let the air become more dirty," says Loveless.<P>Some are pushing for the border of the transport region to be moved west and south, leveling the playing field by <P><P>subjecting Ohio and West Virginia to similar requirements. But don't expect cooperation from Congressional delegations in Ohio and West Virginia. They know they have an advantage.<P>In the meantime, people like Miller of the Growth Alliance give Sony and Corning Asahi credit for actually going through with the Westmoreland County project instead of locating the plant in Wheeling or elsewhere. <P>Until the Sony venture, people like Miller had trouble illustrating this region's disadvantage under the Clean Air Act. Now they don't. <P>On the flipside, Sony at the same time is a benchmark for other manufacturers that might consider locating in the region despite the Clean Air Act. Sony found advantages to locating in Westmoreland County and decided to absorb the Clean Air Act costs.<P>"It is a big deal," Sony's Small says of the pollution costs. "But in this specific location, there were too many other benefits. We already were located here, we like the work force and there's great infrastructure here. There were a lot of positives."<P>And the Sony project is a signal, according to Westmoreland County Commissioner Terry Marolt, that large manufacturers can and should consider western Pennsylvania as a possible plant site. He and others agree that there's more to look at than just costs. <P>Will others come? If they do, emission credits are here for the taking.<P>Klodowski, the emissions credits broker, says it's a buyer's market for credits. That probably won't change any time soon, since business development is stagnant. At press time, Klodowski was shopping around emissions credits owned by U.S. Steel and Rockwell International.<P>"The price is soft," Klodowski says. "There are plenty of sellers. Just think if there really were some business development going on here. The market would be tight, the price would go up, and you would have a tough time getting the credits."<P>Let's hope that's our next problem.<P>
<P>






<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

