<center>
<B><font size=+2>Big Market, Big Money
</font></B><br>


<i>By Bill Modoono</i></center>
<hr>
It's just before sunrise on a chilly December Saturday, and Jim Hedge is performing his weekly ritual. <P>Leaving the warmth of his suburban home and family for downtown Pittsburgh, he enters a building  wedged between a jail and a massive vacant lot and heads immediately for its basement, two flights below street level. He can't see the darkness outside; this room has no windows. What it does have is coffee and other people who, like Hedge, have chosen this odd path to enlightenment.<P>Ahead of Hedge is a 12-hour school day, so it's no doubt amusing to him that this form of higher education is often referred to as "convenient." The single father of two teenagers has his own word for it.<P>"It's a commitment to yourself, it really is," says Hedge, a senior in Robert Morris College's Saturday One Day A Week Program.<P>But however daunting that commitment, it is one that the region's thousands of nontraditional college students are willing to make. And you won't hear the colleges and universities complaining. In western Pennsylvania,  where the population is aging and where once-prosperous corporations are downsizing, so-called convenient education is something of a growth area, if not a lifesaver, for higher education.<P>As a result, there's intense competition for nontraditional students, commonly defined as those who are not  full-time undergraduate or graduate students. While traditional students can have a majority of educational needs met by a schedule that runs Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 4 p.m., nontraditionals cannot. Most likely, they are busy working, raising families or both. Unless the education fits their schedules, they cannot partake.<P><B>The New Traditionals</B><P>William Presutti, associate dean of Duquesne's graduate school of business, has a theory about the move to Saturday college: With downsizing and more pressure on employees to work longer and harder, the desire to spend nights at classes is not there.<P>"There's only so much energy that you have," Presutti says. "How long a day can you put in?"<P>Family responsibilities also discourage older students from taking classes at night. The best option many see is a good night's rest, then a whole or half day of classes on Saturday. <P>Starting this winter, the University of Pittsburgh is offering 90 classes on Saturday and plans to increase that number in the years ahead. Pitt has been offering classes on Saturday since 1972, but only recently has it aggressively marketed the Saturday-only concept. This scenario is being played out at most higher education institutions, evolving into a major undertaking and a major source of income.<P>At Robert Morris, for instance, part-time students outnumber full-timers, which makes you wonder why they are still dubbed "nontraditional."<P>"They're the new traditional      students," says Carol Yova, director of continuing education and lifelong learning at Westminster College in New Wilmington.<P>And, where these students were once of interest primarily to business or vocational schools, now they are pursued by all manner of liberal arts colleges and universities. "Universities are looking for ways to supplement their traditional populations," says Dr. Robert Comfort, interim dean of Pitt's College of General Studies.<P>At Pitt, the expanded Saturday College will offer B.A. or B.S. degrees in economics, history, psychology, huma-nities and social sciences. Moreover,to make the full-time Saturday program attractive to people who think weekends are for things other than studying, Pitt allows students to structure their classes so they do not have Saturday afternoon classes for nine of the 15 weeks in a semester. <P><B>Hedging Their Bets</B><P>These students are simply good investments. Jim Hedge is a classic example.<P>Hedge, 38, of Dormont, describes himself as a "lousy" high school student who never had much interest in college. And, since he had little trouble finding work after graduating from Keystone Oaks in 1976, he never thought twice about what he may have missed.<P>It was only after he started advancing in the field of motion control and went to work for Reserve Motion Control and Systems in Bridgeville that he recognized what he calls "the glass-ceiling effect."<P>"I didn't think I was in jeopardy of losing my job, but I also saw I was at the top end as far as I could go without a college degree. I realized I needed an insurance policy."<P> In Hedge's case, as with many nontraditionals, his company not only wanted him to get the education, it was willing to pay for it. <P>  Not surprisingly, with this kind of incentive, plus the addition of maturity, Hedge has become an altogether different student than he was at Keystone Oaks. This past semester, for instance, he just missed the dean's list, scoring a 3.17 cumulative grade point average.<P>Since entering the Saturday program at Robert Morris' Downtown campus in the fall of 1992, Hedge has taken classes in the fall, spring and summer each year; or 41 Saturdays each calendar year. His winter schedule was not atypical:<P><LI>	7:50 a.m. to 10:25, Business Professional Writing<LI> 	10:30 a.m. to 1 p.m., Operating Systems Concepts<LI>  	1-1:25, lunch<LI> 	1:30-4, Supervisory Skills<LI>	4:05-6:45, Management.<P>But Hedge insists the time flies each Saturday. In August, when he gets his degree, he's even considering going for an MBA, albeit after taking time off to rest and recuperate.<P>"Life experience definitely plays a big part in my being able to do the work," Hedge says. "I don't know how traditional students survive."<P>If it seems as if Hedge and other nontraditionalists are receiving some form of compressed education, it is clear the colleges and universities do not look at it that way. Nor do they want the students to see it in that light. For example, Robert Morris is permitting Hedge's class, which does not complete degree requirements until August, to participate in the college's commencement ceremonies in May. It's a symbolic gesture, but it shows that the older students are every bit as important as other Robert Morris graduates.<P>"The degree they earn is not watered down in any way," says Darcy Tannehill, Robert Morris' associate dean of admissions. "It's the exact same degree. They're not relieved of anything."<P>The same holds true at Pitt.<P>"It's a University of Pittsburgh degree," says Pitt's Comfort. "I say to the professors  who teach them, 'What you expect of              your day-time students should carry over to the others.' "<P>But there are, of necessity, differences. "We ask instructors to keep in mind that many of these students can't get to campus during the week," says Tannehill. As a result, library as-   signments may be curtailed. But, she insists, "They've got to do the same amount of work."<P>   According to figures from the National Uni-versity Continuing Education Assoc-iation, students who attend college on a part-time basis account for one-third of all undergraduates. Two-thirds of all students pursuing masters degrees are part-time and 60 percent of all graduate students, inc-luding those in medical school and law school, can be described as "non-traditional." <P>Noah Brown, director of government relations and public affairs for the NUCEA, says that between 1970 and 1993, the number of full-time students in colleges and universities grew 38 percent, while the number of part-time students increased by 128 percent.<P>The reasons behind those numbers are diverse and range from a decline in the number of manufacturing jobs to an increase in the divorce rate. But one reason remains paramount: money.<P>"There has always been a clear correlation between the amount of education you have and the amount of money you earn," Brown says.<P><B>More Tuition Money</B><P>Money - tuition money that is - is a major incentive for colleges to go after the part-time, older student. <P>Westminster's Yova says that while full-time day students outnumber part-time students at Westminster by a 15 to 1 ratio, the growth is coming from the older students. <P>In an attempt to stimulate that growth, schools are offering part-timers scholarships. Part-timers, paying for their education by the course, are not subject to the housing costs and activity fees full-time students must absorb. According to Yova, part-timers can wind up paying about half of what their daytime counterparts pay for the same degree.<P>Pitt's Comfort says going after the older students is smart marketing for reasons beyond enrollment numbers. He says the older market is a logical target, especially in light of the region's stagnant population base.<P>"Allegheny County is not a growing area," Comfort says. "The aging of the population and shrinking of the potential market for undergraduates has created a competition for students that is very, very intense."<P>"You've got to be customer-oriented," says Duquesne's Presutti. "These students have specific needs."<P>Duquesne's answer was the area's first Saturday morning MBA program, which began in September 1994. On the horizon are a number of joint-degree programs that Presutti says "target specific market niches." Among those will be combined degree programs such as MBA/law, MBA/health management and  MBA/environmental sciences.<P>"A university has a lot of resources," Presutti says. "We have to leverage our resources."<P>If that sounds like advertising-executive-speak, that's appropriate: nontraditional students are heavily  targeted in promotional advertising.  At Robert Morris, for instance, over    80 percent of the school's advertising targeted to specific students is aimed at luring nontraditionals.<P><B>Marketing Niches</B><P>At LaRoche College, the emphasis is not on selling the same education that is available at Pitt or Duquesne or Robert Morris, but selling something that is entirely different.<P>"We're not trying to repeat          programs that already exist," says        Dr. Carol Rush, dean of nontraditional and corporate programs at LaRoche, located in McCandless Township. "We're trying to meet needs not already being met."<P>That's why LaRoche offers a  degree in radiography in conjunction with two area hospitals. The school    has gone directly to the business     community to ask business leaders what courses are most needed. LaRoche offers an increasing            number of certificate - rather than degree - programs in skill areas     such as professional writing, working in teams, supervisory skills and    graphic design.<P>"A really critical need, with so many companies downsizing, is for employees to wear a number of different hats, " says Rush. "They need more skills development."<P>Colleges are wise to please         businesses because many finance        the educations of their employees,          who account for a large number            of part-time students. At Saint    Vincent College in Latrobe, for instance, the majors offered to         those attending evening and Saturday classes are primarily business-             oriented: accounting, business management, finance, communications, computing and information sciences and liberal arts.<P>"These areas appeal to those already working," says Elizabeth Balser, director of the career development center at Saint Vincent. "And their companies will pay for those courses."<P><B>Sacrificing Quality?</B><P>The big question surrounding these programs is whether quality is compromised by convenience. In western Pennsylvania, most college administrators insist that is not the case.<P>"Our slogan is 'quality matters,' " says Balser of Saint Vincent. "For the most part, evening and Saturday classes are taught by our regular faculty, the same as our day courses. Some courses require specialists to bring an expertise, such as investors, and they are part-time, but that is true for day classes as well." <P>At Westminster, 99 percent of classes, day, night and weekends, are taught by full-time faculty members. At Pitt, Comfort estimates that 50 percent of business classes are staffed by full-time faculty, as are 40 percent of arts and sciences classes.<P>At Robert Morris, which uses a lot of part-time teachers from the business world anyway, only one-third of evening and weekend faculty is full-time, according to Tannehill.<P>Tannehill says the use of part-time faculty members brings the "best of both worlds" to the classroom. "Those who are out there working bring a practical base into the classroom. And it's good for students to know people in the business world. It creates good ties for employment purposes."<P>An example is Thrift Drug chief legal counsel Joe Bartolacci, who was a CPA before he became an attorney and today still teaches an evening accounting course at Robert Morris.<P>"If you hold [convenient education] to the same standard, same faculty, same courses, and we do," says Edward A. Nicholson, president of Robert Morris, "the result is that the students' ability to learn what you ask them to learn tends to be greater."<P>At most colleges, getting full-     time faculty to teach evenings and weekends is not as difficult as it     might seem. For one thing, there's the enjoyment factor.<P>"To me," says Comfort of Pitt, "the students are the whole reward for doing it. They bring a lot more life and work experience to the classroom and they are actively looking to participate. They have a mature and sensible manner. They're not bumps on a log."<P>Robert Morris' Tannehill says nontraditional students tend to be better in the classroom: "more self-motivated than parentally motivated."<P>While there is no statistical evidence proving that older, nontraditional students do better than their younger, full-time counterparts, there is overwhelming anecdotal evidence that they do. <P>"They're older and more focused," says Brown of the National University Continuing Education Association. "And, they tend to carry a lot fewer credit hours."<P>Perhaps the most surprising development in the rise of convenient education is that an area once seen as an adjunct to the collegiate environment is now seen as something of value to everyone. Attracting such students keeps colleges economically viable in difficult times. Nontraditional students are advancing their careers. And younger students benefit from the experience their older counterparts bring to the classroom.<P>Jim Hedge says even his own children benefit, although they may not realize it right now.<P>"There have been nights when all three of us are sitting at the dinner table doing our homework," he says. "One thing they've learned from seeing me there is they can't use the excuse 'I don't have the time.'<P>"That excuse doesn't work at      our house."<P>
<P>






