<a href="../zine/0296.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Exporting
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>When We Sell Our Products Somewhere Else,<br>We Import Wealth Into Western Pennsylvania</font></b><br>

<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>
<hr>
The way Connie White sees it, Altamira Instruments wouldn't be around today if it hadn't been for the products it sold in Europe and the Far East about four years ago.<P>The U.S. economy was flat. Domestic customers weren't buying. Altamira, the Pittsburgh-based manufacturer of lab equipment, would have been in deep trouble if it had not been selling in foreign markets.<P>"Had it not been for exporting, Altamira would not have survived the U.S. recession," says White, Altamira's vice president.<P>"Exporting was the thing that saved our business."<P>It also will likely be one of the things that helps save this  region from economic disaster.<P>In Part II of Executive Report's six-month series entitled Resuscitating the Region, ER looks at how exporting offers a window of opportunity for companies of all sizes to spur growth. In January, the magazine talked about the importance of entrepreneurship. In coming months, ER also will look at transportation, education, tax reform and tourism as other windows of opportunity.<h3>This Month: Exporting</h3>Pennsylvania is the nation's fifth-largest state, but statistics show the state ranks 11th nationally in exporting. Business leaders say that number is unsatisfactory.<P>In 1994, a Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Development Council report titled Discovering Export Opportunities found an overall lack of commitment to international trade within the region. The SPRDC report said those business that do export actually do very little. It also charged that public ser-<P>vices are available to companies interested in exporting, but seldom are used. And finally, the report said the region is void of an essential "everyone wins" mentality toward international trade. <P><h3>To Export or Not</h3>Millions of businesses - large and small - export their products and services to foreign countries, and millions more could, but don't because they are intimidated by the untried and unknown.<P>In western Pennsylvania, only about 125, or 4 percent, of the businesses capable of exporting are actually export experienced. Another 500 businesses, or 14 percent, are ready to export. That leaves the other 3,000, or 82 percent, who are not ready to export.<P>"There are few experienced exporters in region today. Of those who are export experienced, many are short-term focused," says Rita Pollock, executive director of the Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Development Council, an agency that serves as a focal point for a variety of state and federal programs offering technical, financial and marketing assistance to small and medium-sized businesses in nine southwestern Pennsylvania counties. <P>The SPRDC periodically hosts forums for companies that would like to get into exporting. Pollock says of about 300 to 400 invitations that are mailed out, about 5 to 10 companies show up. And when it's over, usually no more than one or two actually followup with a phone call to the SPRDC.<P>The reasons why compa nies shy away from exporting vary, depending upon to whom you speak. Pollock has a list of excuses that is as long as her arm. Companies cite lack of knowledge, lack of money, lack of staff expertise and time constraints as roadblocks to exporting. Other excuses include excess paperwork, lack of market expertise, fear of losing control and transportation costs.<P>Meanwhile, business people in Hong Kong, Japan and Germany and other leading international traders long have thought of themselves as active participants in a world economy. And more recently, business people in Charlotte, N.C., Columbus, Ohio, and Madison, Wis., are jumping in headlong. That's why business leaders here say our consumers and industry no longer can be insulated by regional and national borders and expect to survive in the global market.<h3>The Altamira Story</h3>Connie White recognized the importance of foreign markets early on. She was not intimidated by paperwork, control or her own lack of knowledge.<P>Good thing for Altamira that she wasn't. The company not only survived the 1991-92 recession, but it also grew sales from $400,000 in 1988 to $2.1 million last year. And the sales are nicely spread across many markets. About 36 percent of sales were in the U.S. last year, along with 48 percent in Europe and 18 percent in the Far East. That compares with 1988, when U.S. sales accounted for 80 percent, with the other 20 percent limited to Europe.<P>The telltale year was 1991, when U.S. sales accounted for only 16 percent. White and her Altamira colleagues already were in Europe and the Far East, which carried the company.<P>"The first thing we did was research markets, listing 20 countries where we could sell. Then we prioritized them," White recalls of Altamira's entrance into foreign markets. "Then we looked for sales agents."<P>Sound easy? White admits, it really wasn't rocket science.<P>To find sales agents, White simply got on the phone and asked other companies that were exporting who they were using. She checked references and moved ahead. Today, Altamira sells in countries such as the Netherlands, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Japan, Germany, Korea and China. <P>The business is there, according to those who already are there.<P>II-VI Inc. of Saxonburg, which headed ER's recent list of Top 10 growth companies (December 1995), sells its laser products to over 2,400 customers in 35 countries, with foreign sales accounting for 47 percent of its revenue in fiscal 1995.<P>Even professional services firms are tapping foreign markets. Environmental engineering firm Chester Environmental, for instance, decided to aggressively pursue international business in the early part of this decade and landed contracts in Taiwan, Mexico, South America and China. The result: Revenue generated from foreign business jumped from $170,000 in fiscal 1992 to $12.07 million in 1994.<h3>The Exporting Push</h3>At presstime, the SPRDC was moving ahead with initiatives aimed at spurring exporting. Among several other measures, the agency wants to develop a formal mentoring cycle through which the experienced exporters would work with less experienced companies.<P>The state has also taken steps, recognizing that statewide only about 20 percent of the manufacturers sell their products overseas. Gov. Tom Ridge appointed a task force to develop the state's export strategy, although a final report was not out at presstime.<P>"We certainly need to sell our goods in the other 49 states, but I   think there are other huge markets    out there internationally," the governor says. "We must have a strategy to      promote exports. We must have a mindset that says export, export, export. There are billions of consumers out there for the widest possible range of products.<P>"We have world class workers who produce world class products in Pennsylvania," Ridge says. "I think we ought to stamp them, "Made in Pennsylvania" and get these products  out the door."                                       n<P>
<P>






