http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0296.Supplement3.html 192.204.56.67 19970115125603 text/html 16389
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:01:12 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:20 GMT
Content-length: 16212
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0296.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0296.Supplement4.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Who's Really Calling the Shots?
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>An ER Special Report: How the Decision-Making Power<br>is swinging From The Doctor to the GuyWho Cuts the Check</font></b><br>

<i>By Lydia Strohl</i></center>
<hr>
Dr. LaDonna Fuge, a family practitioner at Forbes Health System, spent more time than usual away from her patients last December. And she wasn't holiday shopping. <P>"I spent over a dozen hours in discussions with payors about patients," says Fuge, president of Forbes' Independent Physicians Association. "I had a 62-year-old man who had two strokes, and they told me he didn't qualify for rehab. But I didn't feel it was safe enough to take another option [which the HMO ordered].<P>"And some of the contracts include a gag clause, so you are not allowed to say to the press or to the patient that you disagree."<P>Welcome to the wonderful world of managed care. Used to be, the patient and doctor would decide the most effective course of healthcare. But in an effort to cut costs, businesses - in the form of managed care companies and other healthcare insurers - are micromanaging healthcare.<P>Patients and doctors, meanwhile, are questioning the change. And they're not the only ones wondering whether the guys who merely paid the bills in the old system should be managing clinical care in the new? <P>It's just one of the complex issues brought about by healthcare reform. Even though the Clintons' reform fell flat, the industry is going through fast, fundamental change, nationally and locally. And at the core of the change is money. In round one, the dollars were slashed by downsizing, layoffs and the other usual methods of budget streamlining, like group purchasing for volume discounts. It wasn't deep enough. What's needed, insiders say, is a complete change in the philosophy and delivery of healthcare in Pittsburgh.  <h3>A Nonsystem </h3>At the root of the problem is the fact that what we have been calling a healthcare delivery system isn't really a system at all.  <P>"It's all done informally," says William Cross, vice president of health knowledge systems for the Hospital Council of Western Pennsylvania. "What we had, until 1985, was a cost-based reimbursement system where anything was covered. You wouldn't take your car into a shop and say, 'Anything you can find, I'll pay you to fix,' but that was what we had."<P>The most effective way to deliver care, say the experts, is to build integrated systems tying in an entire spectrum of entities to provide a continuum of care. Currently, our system is built around the hospital, where about 40 percent to 60 percent of our healthcare dollars are spent. But at an average of over $1,100 a day, that's the most expensive place to care for the sick. <P>A philosophical shift is also necessary, however, to really shore things up for the long run. Today's system is built around making sick people well. The new system, experts say, must shift to focus on treating that first symptom and treating it the most effective way possible. <P>More fundamentally, it must shift to providing preventive care up front to improve the health of the entire population. That eliminates expensive, critical care down the line. Preventive care, coupled with having the best, most appropriate care available when people require it, will demand coordination of everyone from doctors and hospitals to social service agencies, laboratories, home health agencies and many others.<P>"It's hard to do that in a boutique, cottage industry, which is basically the way healthcare delivery is here in Pittsburgh," says Jim Fritz, president of the Southwest Integrated Delivery Network, an entity currently being set up to provide such a spectrum in the region. "But we won't be successful unless we include the whole continuum of care, with the real focus on the primary care physicians." <P>Though physicians only command 35 percent of healthcare dollars, says Fritz, they control 100 percent of the spending decisions. The new model for healthcare acknowledges this, and makes the primary care physician the gatekeeper.<h3>Calling the Shots</h3>With the advent of managed care and the gatekeeper concept, primary care doctors are in demand. Hospitals, insurers and other networks are scrambling to get them on their team, partnering with them, even buying them -   setting them up in new facilities, promising empowerment and giving them signing bonuses as incentives. For managed care companies to ensure convenient access for their members to the system, companies must consolidate their relationships with primary care doctors, including specialists and pediatricians. <P>"For an insurer, success in the future means growing and retaining market share by providing broad access to networks and primary care," says Gus Georgiadis, executive vice president of primary care delivery systems for Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania, which controls 68 percent of the insured population in Western Pennsylvania.<P>To date, Blue Cross has 1,800 of the 3,300 primary care physicians in its coverage area participating in its Keystone HMO. But it wants more. <P>Eventually, the company hopes to have 500 primary care doctors in some form of this "guaranteed access" model. At year's end, Blue Cross had already partnered with 135 physicians, most of whom will be moving to eight new staff centers being built throughout the area. Blue Cross has $30 million earmarked to build the new centers. <P>"The way healthcare is delivered now is fragmented, not user-friendly," says Georgiadis. "We're attempting to meet the needs of the single mom head-of-household market. They need one-stop shopping. "<P>Sounds great - but who wins when clinical and financial goals collide?<P>"Often, despite the physician wanting to provide certain amounts of care, their hands are tied," says Dr. Richard Harris, an internist and president of the Allegheny County Medical Society. "In an HMO network, restrictions apply to certain procedures. And the physician is restricted to sending patients to the hospitals and doctors in that particular network, as well. I had to look in the [HMO's list of doctors] the other day to pick a specialist for a patient, and pick someone I was not familiar with. But if I didn't, the patient wouldn't get care." <P>Interruption of traditional relationships and referral patterns is only one of the side effects of affiliating with managed care. Many changes are a result of primary care physicians being paid by the HMOs on a capitated basis. So instead of getting paid for the services they perform, they are paid one monthly fee, anywhere from $10 to $15 per patient, to provide all services for that patient. Although specialists' fees are not taken from that, the HMO sets up funds to pay for utilization of other portions of the system. What's left, the doctor and the HMO split. Some doctors say they're waiting to see that actually happen.<P>"Never in 10 years have I gotten anything back," says Dr. Marc Schneiderman, president of Fifth Avenue Medical Associates, a physician group based in Coraopolis. <P>"My overhead is increasing, my income is decreasing. Yet the CEO of [one HMO] made $11 million two years ago. There are huge windfalls being made in managed care, and they're being made on the backs of the physicians and hospitals."<h3>Transitional Losses</h3>"I don't know that finances are the real issue," says Harris. "In California [a market in which capitation is the standard], doctors make more money now [with managed care]. As the capitation system gets more established and people take more risk, they can get more reward." <P>But he acknowledges that the system now, with low or no copays for office visits, encourages people to come to the doctor for minor problems.  <P>Another place the physicians lose, they say, is in administration of care. Paperwork from the many different alliances they must now form to ensure that they can cover a broad spectrum of patients is drowning them. <P>But there are more serious problems, like those hours Fuge spends battling about patient care with the HMOs. She cites another case, in which the HMO approved mental care for a patient, but only through an agency it contracted with. The arrangement required a long commute for the sick woman. In another situation, the payor refused to pay for a hospital stay. <P>"I wasted two months of work to get a few thousand dollars back to the hospital," says Fuge. "I have to feed my family, and it's difficult to look back on the week and realize that an entire day of potential work was lost. And those were three I won. But you don't win them all. It tears at your soul." <P>The payers realize that the systems are not perfect yet. All seem to say that cost-effectiveness and patient-centered care can be compatible - eventually. <P>"We're looking for ways to partner and develop systems of care that share income equally," says Dan Lebish, senior vice president of provider network development and management at HealthAmerica. The payers feel that more direct relationships with doctors, like those being made with buyouts and partnering, will help. <P>But some doctors are skeptical. They feel disinherited when they sell their practice and become an employee rather than a proprietor. <P>"The unstated reason for acquiring primary care physicians' practices is because that's where everything starts, and they will direct patients to other parts of the system," says attorney David Lowe of Cohen & Grigsby, who has overseen many practice sales. "By having the primary care physicians in the delivery system, they have access to a broader patient base and revenue stream." <P>Hospitals and insurers buying practices generally arrive at a selling price and a signing bonus. But Lowe says few will guarantee employment of the physician for over 10 years. Most guarantees are for three to five. <P>"In general, I think physicians would rather keep things as they are - masters of their own destiny," says Lowe. "But they see that they need to create ties with one or more entities to insure their own future." <P>Schneiderman says that hired physicians loose their entrepreneurial spirit, and cites 10 percent to 20 percent drops in physician association membership corresponding to this trend. But depending on the alignment, Schneiderman and others say it is possible for physicians to retain some degree of clinical autonomy in this shifting environment.<h3>Taking the Lead</h3>Organizing into self-governing networks and is one way for doctors to retain a larger portion of clinical autonomy and profits. Fuge believes that networks organized by providers are the only way. "It's the only cost-effective, quality-effective, patient-advocate option that I have seen in 10 years," says Fuge. "I believe as clinicians we have the responsibility to drive the bus. Laying down in front of it isn't going to do any good." <P>The premise of these provider networks, or integrated delivery systems, is that they will organize a full continuum of care and contract with the insurance companies and managed care organizations (payers), or directly with employers. Rather than a capitated fee per patient, they will receive the premium dollars, less a negotiated administrative fee, which the payer keeps. So far, two networks have formed in Pittsburgh, with a third expected. Last summer, the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center formed Tri-State Health System, comprising UPMC, South Hills Health System, Passavant, St. Margaret and Washington hospi-tals. Southwest Integrated Delivery Network aligns Allegheny General Hospital, Sewickley Valley Hospital, Allegheny Valley Hospital, Forbes Health System, St. Clair Hospital and their physician organizations. <P>The networks organize the continuum by researching the best practices and choosing appropriate courses of care by consulting global data bases to find out what's happening elsewhere. <P>The integrity of networks will be based not only on cost-effectiveness, but also on outcomes - by benchmarking the health of members against other populations and whether they become better over time. Such a standard will ensure that quality of care drives the system. The networks not only agree, but believe good outcomes will be a tremendous selling point.<P>"We're moving toward a continuum of care, a product that has to produce something - cost savings or outcomes or whatever - and that means being able to accept some risk, so that if you get a good outcome you are rewarded on that," says SIDN's Fritz. "It's a lot easier to take on risk in large numbers. The system will win." <P>According to Blue Cross' Georgiadis, it is organizing on many of the same premises, empowering physicians by including them in the governance of the system. But Blue Cross will need to sign the provider systems as well - and, with the strong ties to UPMC forged after its coup there last spring, Blue Cross is naturally aligning with Tri-State. And Blue Cross is talking to SIDN.<h3>The Cost of Quality</h3>Patients are worried too. They are worried when their family doctor or certain specialists are not included in their healthcare plan's network. They cannot understand when an HMO tells them a certain avenue of care is unavailable - well, perhaps available, but not covered. In the future, patients will have to take more responsibility for the lifestyle choices they make that affect their health. And, hopefully, plans will build the systems to help patients to do this.<P>"We pay for our healthcare and we should become more knowledgeable about what is possible and have the best plan possible," says Karen Finestein, executive director of the Jewish Healthcare Foundation, a local leader in facilitating healthcare change. "Communities will get the health plans they deserve. They need to put a searchlight on what's happening and get what they need."<P>No one quite knows what's immediately ahead for healthcare here. Western Pennsylvania has 50 percent more hospital beds than it needs. Hospitals are struggling with change, implementing new programs to remain competitive. Their changes will be among the most fundamental.<P>But is the emphasis on cost reduction contradictory to providing quality care? The state is defining its role as the system's hall monitor, even as the insurance plans are shoring up alliances. <P>One thing is clear - the Pittsburgh healthcare industry has a tough road to travel. Opening a presentation about managed care to doctors last December, Schneiderman flashed a slide of Pieter Bruegel's "Triumph of Death," a 1556 painting depicting the plague. <P>"Chaos," Schneiderman remarked. "That's the milieu of Pittsburgh right now in the healthcare arena."             <P>

<P>






