<center><B><font size=+2>Design Dilemma
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>If Your Architect Isn't Listening,<br>You May End Up With Something You Din't Want</font></b><br>

<i>By Shareen Berry</i></center>
<hr>
"My tailor is the only man I know who behaves sensibly. He takes my measurements anew each time he sees me. The rest go on with their old measurements and expect me to fit them."   <P>- George Bernard Shaw<P>Does the latter sound familiar?<P>Some managers have found it to be the case when dealing with an architect. You discuss a project - whether it be new construction or minor renovation - listing both concerns and needs. In the end, the architect has missed the boat. Or as Shaw would say, "The suit doesn't fit."<P>That's why although the process of finding the right architect can be time-consuming, it's a time investment that usually will pay off in the end.<P>"The most critical thing is the selection of someone to help you interpret your vision," says architect Jay Labarthe of the Design Alliance in Pittsburgh. "Often, it is a mystical process. You can rate, analyze and spreadsheet alternative firms to death."<P>Prepare: It helps to be prepared before making initial contact with architectural firms, experts say. Those planning a project should know their desires and ideas. Then, it's time to ask some questions:<P><LI>For what will the structure be used and will there be ample space?<LI>	Has a location been selected, a budget developed and a construction schedule set?<LI>	Do you have the resources for the project?<P>Now it's time to approach the architects. Some businesses have found it helpful to contact other businesses that have gone through similar projects. They often can provide insight on which firms had their acts together and which firms did not.<P>Some businesses also have found construction companies to be good reference resources, since they are the ones working hand-in-hand with architectural firms on various projects over extend periods of time.<P>"The people who know the most about us are the people at the construction companies," Labarthe says. "After all, many of them have worked for us for 20 or 30 years. In most cases, clients only work with us for a year or so."<P>The Interviews: The meeting is crucial because the client can usually get a personal feel for the architects. It's also a chance to carefully evaluate the firm's history and understanding of your needs.<P>"A good architect is an active listener," says Robert Harald Tarasovich of Johnson Schmidt & Associates. "The architect should evaluate the client's needs and recognize that, just as the clients differ, so do their needs."<P>After gathering all of the needed information, experts say it's good to rate the firms based on personal confidence, design ability, technical competence, professional service and cost. Rating the firms will help the client pinpoint the best choice and move ahead with the project.<P>Those who have been through it, however, offer some advice: Keep the lines of communication open with the second choice. You may need the No. 2 choice if discrepancies over price or logistics develop with the top choice.<P>The Design Process: Don't think this is simple. In fact, it is very complex. Many businesses find that out the hard way by trying to handle the design phase of a project in-house.<P>"Many people feel they can do the work themselves," says Ed Pope of Gardner+Pope Architects. "However, they often disregard the fire codes, electrical codes and other codes that are included with an architect's services. If something goes wrong, the blame falls on us. Therefore, we make sure the codes are being followed."<P>In most cases, architects include in their fee the basic services of preliminary design, development and preparation of construction drawings and assistance in negotiations and contact with the contractor.<P>Other services, such as outside consultation, predesign work and analysis work for site preparation may be required to properly implement the project. Those often cost extra or may not even be offered by the architect.<P>In writing the contract, the client can choose to pay for a set of basic services - standard services common in every project - with a second category of additional services costing extra. With another option, the parties designates services needed up front and set a price for them.<P>Sometimes, too little is known about the project to determine the full extent of professional services in advance and proceed to a contractual agreement based on designated services. In this case, experts say it's wise to provide project definition and other predesign services first, with remaining services to be determined later.<P>Ultimately, after much research and examination, the vision begins to take shape. And because of the deliberate selection process, it takes shape the way you wished.<P>"A reasonable size project takes six to 12 months to design," says Labarthe of the Design Alliance. "Then there's 12 months to build and 12 more months for the contractor's warranty. You are hiring the architect not solely for the design, but for 36 months of guidance and assistance throughout the project.<P>"There must be a mutual trust during that time."<P>

<P>






