<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>Militancy Doesn't Work
</font><BR>
<font size=+1> Unions Have A Lot to Learn From<BR>the UAW Debacle at Caterpillar 
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<P>
<hr>
It's been almost four years since a Democratic presidential nominee named Bill Clinton came to Pittsburgh to schmooze with teachers. That's right: teachers, not steelworkers.<P>In this town where for decades steelworkers formed the heart of organized labor, the then-future president shined his shoes and put on his best tie to engage in chitchat about textbooks and mainstreaming at the annual convention of the American Federation of Teachers.<P>There were no flannel shirts. No steel-toed boots. No satin jackets embossed with "Local 1397," the once-large United Steelworkers local that represented 15,000 millworkers in Homestead.<P>Clinton was coddling unionized teachers in July 1992 because they were the strongest arm of organized labor in that election year. The traditional labor unions, which represented a third of the industrial work force when they helped elect Presidents Franklin Roosevelt and Harry Truman, only marginally influenced Clinton's win in 1992. He didn't even mention them in his acceptance speech at the Democratic National Convention.<P>Now it's 1996, and little has changed. The traditional labor unions don't wield the clout they possessed years ago. The United Auto Workers proved that last month. <P>UAW members at eight Caterpillar Inc. plants in four states - including Pennsylvania - ended a 17-month walkout that they originally thought would cripple Caterpillar. Instead, only about 8,700 of more than 14,000 who were eligible to strike stayed on the picket lines. Others crossed the lines or retired. Caterpillar, meanwhile, posted record profits.<P>The UAW finally waived a white flag Dec. 2, ordering strikers back to work under the company's terms. Those Caterpillar workers who stayed out for the duration each lost roughly $37,000 in wages before the strike was crushed.<P>This was the latest blow to labor in a succession of skirmishes in which corporate America has shown that it clearly has the upper hand.<P>The mythical Joe Magarac, a towering, burly steelworker who dipped metal bars in molten steel before bending them into different shapes with his bare hands, must be sick to his washboard stomach. <P>Instead, Magarac should be whispering in the ears of these labor leaders who are trumpeting the so-called new spirit of militancy in the AFL-CIO. Union leaders today would be well advised to learn that their most effective tool is cooperation, not militancy.<P>First off, there's little reason for militancy. This isn't the pre-World War II era when workers were toiling for long hours in unsafe workplaces without benefits. This is the '90s, a time when workplaces are safe and management often empowers employees by involving them in decision-making.<P><P><P> And the benefits offered by many manufacturers go beyond the basic. One manufacturing site in New England has a laundry service. Employees can tote their laundry to work, where the company will launder and fold the clothes for $1 a load.<P>Secondly, unions that think militant tactics will work aren't acknowledging the nature of business today. Want to call a strike? The employer of today can hire new workers from the tremendous pool of underemployed Americans. The employer can also shift production overseas or farm it out to contractors. It can even lure union members across picket lines, just as Caterpillar did.<P>A big union gripe today is over change companies make in the work place to become more efficient. Change may result in the loss of a few union jobs, but at the same time it probably secures hundreds of other union jobs because increasing efficiency makes the company more competitive.<P>Only about 12 percent of private-sector manufacturing jobs are unionized today. By the beginning of the next century, labor experts predict that only 7 percent will be unionized. That's about the same number as at the beginning of the 20th century and a fraction of the 36 percent peak in 1953.<P> These unions that remain must realize that they are a partner in making American business more competitive in the global economy. Militant tactics by unions only do their members a disservice and will make American business less competitive.<P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

