<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><IMG border=0 align=left SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=+2>One Hundred Thousand <BR>New Jobs or Bust 
</FONT SIZE>
<font size=+1></font><BR>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b>
<hr>

The Fortune 1000 enterprise is no longer the vehicle that fuels economic growth or job creation. Of the meager 1,000 new jobs created in this region last year, few, if any, emanated from large companies. <P>Job growth is the exclusive domain of the small and emerging business sector. So when the Working Together Consortium established the region's economic development mantra as "100,000 new jobs," they dramatically increased the importance of the entrepreneurial sector in this economy. <P>Or did they?<P>Generating 100,000 new jobs regionally before the turn of the century is at best a stretch. If current trends prevail, Dick Berner, Mellon Bank chief economist, predicts a net job loss of 1,000 jobs here in 1996, resulting in no net job gain for 1995 and 1996. <P>Though his crystal ball may be cracked, the modest 1995 job gain is accurate. The Working Together Consortium's strategies to achieve the 100,000 new jobs allow for slow job growth initially, followed by a period of rapid expansion, crescendoing to 100,000 new jobs in the year 2000.<P>Since job growth follows entre-preneurial vitality, the region's relatively low entrepreneurial energy choked any new job creation efforts. In 1995, Pennsylvania's new company formation rate fell from 45th to 49th in the nation. Our job growth rate in these new companies fell from 33rd to 38th in the country. Sadly, once again the Development Report Card for the states ranks Pennsylvania dead last in entrepreneurship.  And University of Pittsburgh research ranks this region's entrepreneurial vitality  well below that of the state, making Pittsburgh arguably the worst major metropolitan center in the nation for new business development. The prospect of generating 100,000 newSince job growth follows entre-preneurial vitality, the region's relatively low entrepreneurial energy choked any new job creation efforts. In 1995, Pennsylvania's new company formation rate fell from 45th to 49th in the nation. Our job growth rate in these new companies fell from 33rd to 38th in the country. Sadly, once again the Development Report Card for the states ranks Pennsylvania dead last in entrepreneurship.  And University of Pittsburgh research ranks this region's entrepreneurial vitality  well below that of the state, making Pittsburgh arguably the worst major metropolitan center in the nation for new business development. The prospect of generating 100,000 new jobs in five years greatly diminishes in this unhealthy entrepreneurial climate.<P>Yet, entrepreneurial vitality has not emerged as a top priority among corporate leaders and public officials. The Allegheny Conference on Community Development presented a plan for regional growth and prosperity at its Nov. 16, 1995, annual meeting. Building an entrepreneurial infrastructure hardly featured prominently. Their grand vision anchored on tourism, retail expansion and housing and commercial development.<P>Entrepreneurial activities should feature prominently in any job creation strategy. Relegating entrepreneurship to this also-ran status guarantees this region will never reach its 100,000 new jobs goal. That is cast in stone - a gravestone, in fact.<P>
 



<hr><BR><BR><BR>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

