<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>After the Cuts
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>Downsizing Brought About its Own Demise;
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Now it's Time for Some Growth Strategies</FONT>
 <i>By Charles Reese
</b></i>

<HR>

We see a few companies continuing to scale down their work forces, but it otherwise seems clear that the relentless purging of middle management over the past 15 years has about run its course.<P>Most of us would also agree that the financial results of this approach have been very positive: There have been dramatic gains in profitability.<P>The astute manager, however, should consider a few longer term, contrary patterns that are beginning to emerge. Most notably, as American industries become leaner, meaner and more competitive on world markets, the business environment surrounding those industries changes as a direct consequence. For example, more demands are placed on business resources - particularly human ones - than those resources can comfortably support.<P>On the plus side, alternative markets - previously out of reach - become logical targets of opportunity. In short, downsizing brought about its own demise by reviving the opportunity, and in many instances, the need for growth and growth planning. These are concepts we haven't heard much about in recent years.<P>Now, it is also true that at the time of this writing there are some indications of economic flat spots ahead. Nevertheless, I think most business people would agree that overall, the worm has turned once again - back to growth planning.<P>Even now, a growth-oriented atmosphere seems to be overtaking the survival mentality of the recent past, and quite a few industrial manufacturers can realistically plan for expansion to meet longer term profit opportunities. If that kind of sea change has really arrived, and I think it has, a few assumptions that have become holy writ over the past dozen years must also change. For example:<P> Manpower planning means staying as close to the bone as possible:  Let us all keep in mind that the survival organization everyone has worked so hard to achieve is just that - an inherently temporary group designed to get you through the next year or so. There is precious little flexibility in such organizations and typically one finds large age bracket and skill level gaps.<P> We'll cross the management succession bridge when we get there. We're in no position to do anything else right now:  Those of us in the search profession love this kind of thinking, but is it in your best interest? Right now it probably isn't.<P>There are, of course, many elements involved in expanding to meet a business opportunity, but one seminal issue that inevitably needs early attention is the question of how a company organizes to exploit this challenge. Who will manage all of this tomorrow ... and five years from tomorrow? For example, we all know of a few larger companies, currently doing very well, that don't have a clue where the 10 or more key managers it will need in four years will come from.<P>Fortunately, a few highly decentralized companies, including some of my own clients, have recently recognized a need for some kind of program that will produce enough in-house candidates for expected division general management needs in five years, or perhaps sooner. To do this, several of these companies have, as a matter of policy, begun to seek out several multitalented, promotable people for selected assign ments at officer level.<P>Other types of businesses with larger and more structured, linear organizations, such as big steel and capital equipment, have a tougher problem to solve. Specifically, how do they recruit and integrate the high caliber, partly cross-trained individual into middle management? It's difficult to program further cross-training when larger economies of scale and more complex political environments work against any change in traditional, linear promotion routes - but it can be done.<P>There is also less perceived need for change in most highly linear organizations, but in certain circumstances it may be appropriate because of the cash cow nature of these businesses.<P>Does the solution to either of these organizational problems signal a return to the old Fortune 50 policy of establishing "four guys on the bench" for every position, with a third of management constantly involved in some kind of cross-training? Hardly. <P>The correct policy probably lies a few degrees off the current lean and mean heading. Just add several multi-talented, mid- to higher-level management people with multi-directional promotion routes.                                n<P><P>Charles Reese is principal of Reese Associates, a management consulting and executive selection firm that is based in Wexford.<P>


<hr>


<P>


