<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>
</i></b>

<HR>
<P><b>What,s in a Name? Money</b><p>It's likely that Pittsburgh will have a baseball-only stadium someday soon. The question is: What will we name it? Don't expect Roberto Clemente Field, the moniker chosen by former Mayor Sophie Masloff when she suggested a baseball-only stadium a few years back.<P>It's highly likely that any new stadium will bear a corporate name, much like many venues across the country. <P>"It's still a little early, but my sense is yes," says Mark Schneider, chairman of the City Stadium Authority. "It's a big way to support a team in a small market."<P>Some corporations are willing to pay big bucks to affix their name to a venue. Airlines are one example. Michael Jordan roams the United Center in Chicago. There's also Salt Lake City's Delta Center, home to the NBA's Utah Jazz; Phoenix's America West Arena, the home of the NBA's Suns; and USAir Arena, formerly known as the Capital Centre, in Landover, Md. <P>The Landover deal costs USAir $1 million a year.<P>Insurance companies and banks also are willing to pay for posterity. Fleet Center, the new home of the Boston Bruins and Celtics, is named for Fleet Bank.<P>In 1994, representatives of the Civic Arena and the Stadium Authority put out feelers for sponsors for those venues, but received limited response. <P>"We haven't dropped it," says Penguins vice president Bill Barnes. "We are moving on it very slowly."<P>The asking price remains $1 million a year. The Penguins, who control signs in the Civic Arena, have creatively tapped other revenue sources. Look down, at the steps in the seating areas, and you'll see ads for #1 Cochran Pontiac. Look up, there  are two huge ceiling signs proclaiming USAir as the official airline of the Penguins.<P>"You have to continually look for ways to augment your ticket income," Barnes says. "Signage is one way."<P>Coming soon to the arena: floor graphics in the concourse areas. That's right, advertisements, painted on the floor like rugs.<P>At Three Rivers Stadium, management had hoped to bring in as much as $15 million for 10 years when it considered selling the name rights a few years back. Schneider says the authority slowed efforts as the future of the Pirates remained unresolved during the past year.<P>But with the Pirates situation somewhat resolved, Schneider says the authority will look into it again. <P>So take a guess for the new stadium. Here are our favorites: PNC Park. Mellon Gardens. USX Stadium. Heinz 57 Field.<P><P><b>Scrolling Pittsburgh</b><P>Looking for a gift for that special ex-Pittsburgher? Check out Pittsburgh's new screensaver. Twenty Pittsburgh landscapes move blithely across the computer monitor: Aside from the obligatory Golden Triangle skyscape with hot air balloons, there's the incline, the University of Pittsburgh, the Three Rivers Regatta, St. John's church on the South Side, Station Square, a bear at the Pittsburgh Zoo, the Warhol museum and a sunset barge shot. As a special reminder to those far  away to come visit, there's a shot of the new airport thrown in for      good measure.<P>Even better, New Pittsburgh Publications, which markets the screensaver, will imprint your company logo on it. The screensaver costs $29.95, and quantity discounts are available. For information, call 412/681-8528 or fax 412/681-8531. Or interrupt their screensaver and  e-mail them at URL http://www.pittsburgh.net/NewPghPubl/.<P><b>A Voyage for Corporate Support</B><P>Rear Adm. Bill McGowen is setting sail for downtown Pittsburgh in search of corporate dollars. The retired Navy officer is executive director of Pittsburgh Voyager, an educational program centered around a vessel anchored outside the Carnegie Science Center.<P>Not to be confused with the submarine that also makes its home there, the Voyager is a small gray boat, formerly used by the Navy for training in Annapolis, Md., and San Diego. The Navy donated the vessel in 1993 for use as a floating classroom.<P>On board are science and navigation laboratories, resource materials, computer workstations and related equipment. The boat, equipped with central heating and air conditioning, can be used all year round.<P>Students currently using the vessel range from grades five through 10. The program eventually will be expanded to include kindergarten through grade 12. McGowen hopes to sell corporations on the idea of sponsoring school classes on the outings.<P>"It is an exciting, hands-on education program," says McGowen. "We are looking for additional corporate involvement. We are giving companies in the<P>Pittsburgh area the opportunity to join us in this exhilarating experience.<P>"This is an excellent chance for them to further enhance the educational process and help the future work force of southwestern Pennsylvania."<P>The students spend four to five hours on the boat, learning about nautical and environmental sciences. Some students take a stab at navigating a course for the boat. Others experiment with water quality tests.<P>The vessel accommodates up to 30 students. For more information, call the Pittsburgh Voyager at 412/488-5602.<P><b>Juris Imprudence</b><P>A New Jersey firm got into the habit of discharging nontoxic salt water into a nearby creek. To guard against ecological damage to the stream, Magnesium Elektron Inc. installed a complex monitoring system that allowed it to adjust discharges so no damage would occur to the stream. None did.<P>In fact, some of the discharges actually benefited the stream by providing it with needed organic nutrients.<P>The only problem was that Magnesium Elektron was not following its Clean Water Act permit to the letter, which turned out to be a costly mistake to the tune of $2.6 million.  The federal judge in New Jersey who imposed the fine - the maximum statutory penalty allowed in the case - says not following a permit is a serious violation since self-policing is a crucial part of the Clean Water Act.<P>The court justified the penalty by citing damagethat could have occurred and the importance of strict permit compliance.<P>The case is scary: A company that actually helped the environment was sued and hit with the maximum fine. Attorneys at Reed Smith Shaw & McClay's Pittsburgh office point out two other significant points: The penalty was based on what Magnesium Elektron would have paid to overcomply, and the financial condition of Magnesium Elektron's parent corporation was used to determine the com-pany's ability to pay.                               <P>




<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

