<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Travel.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>



<P>
<B><I><font size=+2>Joseph Piccirilli</font></I></B></center><P>


<HR>
<pre><b>
Name:		Joseph Piccirilli
Age:            32
Personal:       Single, Lives in Moonship
Education:      Moon Hish School, 1981
Last Vacation:  Florida, Four years ago
Last Book Read: The BCCI Scandal
</PRE></B>
<hr>
It was Joe Piccirilli's first full day after closing the purchase of the Pittsburgh Brewing Co.  Pleased as punch  about life, Piccirilli squired this visitor into his office, then abruptly changed gears. "No, no, keep your coat on. I want to take you out to the plant." With all the enthusiasm of Willy Wonka taking kids through the Chocolate Factory, Piccirilli proudly showed off the Pittsburgh Brewing Co.  Smiling workers walked up and shook his hand. He joked with them, addressing them by name and sharing details of the closing of the sale with those who asked. In the conference room, he pointed out the many beers the company has brewed over the years - getting little or no recognition for their origination - including theBoston Beer Co.'s popular Samuel Adams, American beer and the little known Morechamp, produced for a brewer in Nigeria. His goal? To increase Pittsburgh Brewing Co.'s line, geographic reach and, therefore, market share. And to have a lot of fun along the way. Here are excerpts from the conversation ER Executive Life Editor Lydia Strohl had with Piccirilli.<P>Executive Report: Where were you before buying the Pittsburgh Brewing Co. brought you all this notoriety?<P>Joe Piccirilli:  My family had a small trash company, and I remember working since I was 5 or 6 years old. Even through high school, I worked before and after school. I knew that's what I wanted to do after high school. I wanted to go into the business. So I did. <P>My typical work week was about 100 hours a week, seven days a week, and I grew the business eventually to the pointwhere we ended up selling the business [Piccirilli Disposal, a residential and commercial garbage disposal company in Moon Township] in 1993.<P>I'd had 20 years working by then, so I took a year off to see other opportunities. I built a house and then started doing some consulting in the solid waste industry. I would go all over the country aquiring landfills and hauling companies. After a year and a half, I got tired of being on a plane three or four days a week. So I told my attorney, find me something I can go to every day and talk to people. I enjoy people and I had that when I had my own company. <P>We started looking last year, and one of the first things we looked at was City Pride Bakery. And thank God I did my due diligence - I told everybody, you know, I'm not a Harvard graduate, but two and two's not four, and things aren't right. You couldn't tie the books together. So we stepped away from the deal, and at that time I had taken some flak from some people who really wanted me to go through with it, but it wasn't a good situation. And I guess later it was proved that I made a good decision.<P>In the meantime we looked at other opportunities, and did participate in some, but none on the magnitude of the brewery. <P>ER: The purchase process was an involved one. Tell us about it.<P>JP: We went through a process where there were probably 25 different bidders. It was a tough process. Here comes Joe Piccirilli from the garbage business, and what do you know about the beer business? And I says, 'Just about as much as Lou Gerstner knew about IBM and computers.' He really didn't, and when you look at a lot of companies, they're bringing outsiders in who ask what may seem to be immaterial questions, but they're common sense questions. Every business has employees. You understand employees and put yourself on their level and ask, and I do that. I go through the shop and I ask what would you change, what would you like to see. They're on the ground floor, they're in the trenchesevery day. And I've been pretty successful with that philosophy.<P>So I told them that, and they said OK. Then the next hurdle they put you through is the financial criteria. <P>ER: You had capital from the sale of your family business, plus outside investment. What was the total price of the deal?<P>JP: The total purchase price was $30.1 million. You had $17 million in liabilities, your payables and underfunded pension, and $13 million of that was cash. Of which a significant portion was equity dollars. I won't get to the specific numbers, but the majority of the money that came into this deal from my family was personal money. Because of the financial structure of the company, the company   really could not support a high level of debt. If           you overdebted the company you'd probably be             in bankruptcy in another      two years.<P>    ER: Do you think it was a good deal?<P>    JP: I think, looking back at it, that it was an above par deal. The potential is that, number one, wehave great products. Number two is to take this nationally. We know we can make the beers, the quality, and that follows through marketing and distribution. Right now we're the ninth largest brewer in the country. The potential is there.<P>  I started this process in March. The company was still running intact. The employee morale was fantastic, given everything they'd been through. However, the company did suffer because of the marketing, the dollars were pulled away. The equipment that needed to be purchased wasn't, so some of the maintenance got to the point where it needed immediate attention to get productivity levels to where they need to be. And believe it or not, that was it. Pittsburgh is a very loyal place to the producer of Iron City Beer.<P>ER: You mentioned before that for nine years, management had not really gone in and talked to employees?<P>JP: The ownership went from an Australian ownership, where the guy wasn't here, taken over by Heilman. So this plant, instead of being a producer of IC and IC Light, really became a production facility for all the brands under Heilman. And then Michael Carlow. <P>ER: There are a lot of questions about what really happened with Michael Carlow. What's your take?<P>JP:  I think of all the entities that Mike Carlow had - Clark Candy, City Pride, the glass company - by far Pittsburgh Brewing was the most financially sound. And what happened, unfortunately, was that the money pulled from the brewery supported all the other businesses. And eventually, that could only go so far. He pulled out all the cash from the business, cut back the marketing, cut back the maintenance, and some things deteriorated over time, which hurt the company.<P>Sales dropped a little, not much. Production probably increased, as far as contracts with other people, because as Iron City lost market share it was replaced with contract brews for Samuel Adams. <P>ER: And what are you brewing now?<P>JP: Right now, it's solely ourselves and Boston Beer. We probably right now do about 20 types of beer. We developed the J.J. Wainwright, too, for two reasons. Pittsburgh is a very loyal market to Iron City and IC Light. However, we're starting to go national with our products - well, you couldn't take an Iron City to Cleveland. So we set up a different line of J.J. Wainwright products, which fall under the category of Wainwright Brewing. And what we are hoping to achieve is if we take the products nationally, and if we don't penetrate the market with Iron City, we'll start marketing the Wainwright. So either one will go and the other will follow, or vice versa. As you develop the relationships, if someone takes a truckload of beer, what we like to do is say, ok, why don't you take a palette of IC Light. The more different types of beer you have, the better off you are. Right now the hot thing is the microbrewed beers, and probably the largest in the country is Samuel Adams. And we've been doing that for eight years. We know we can doit, we've won awards - so we've really pioneered, without knowing it. And now we want to set the stage and go forward ourselves.<P>ER: Products associated with Iron City and J.J. Wainwright are currently in what markets, and where do you hope to go?<P>JP: Right now they're primarily in Ohio, West Virginia, Pennsylvania. Now we've made some contacts in Kentucky. Virginia, we're moving some beers, and the New England area, Maine, Massachusetts. I'm now aggressively pushing the eastern part of the country, and my strategic plan is by mid next year to go to the Midwest. The way to do that is through continuous market development and research, introducing new products - like next year we're going to come out with a Cranberry, a double Bock, a wheat, a summer ale.<P>ER: How much of this business is innovation? A lot of the names that you hear, the summer ale, wheat beer, Oktoberfest - it seems like everybody has aversion. What's the key to the beer business?<P>JP: I don't think it's so much innovation as marketing and distribution. I think sometimes you back into the innovation by what you want to market. The easiest thing to do is make the beer. You can make the greatest beer in the world, but if it's not marketed properly, it's a lose-lose situation.<P>The key is good advertisement. It's an investment, putting the dollars into the future. Being innovative in the market - like we did the 'Burgh Summer Tour, where the camera crews would show up, the response we got was phenomenal. When we had write in your own commercials, people just loved that because they could star in their own commercial. What I want to do is get the company back to the basics, start going back to some of that marketing and advertising and putting the dollars in it. <P>Relationships with the distributors are very important. They push your product and you have to be able to distinguish why theyshould push yours vs. Samuel Adams, or someone else. And it's the support you give them - point of sale advertising, t-shirts, hats, giveaways. What I'm trying to do is rekindle the relationships with the wholesalers, include them in some of the brewery's decisions  <P>ER: What about foreign markets?<P>JP: Believe it or not, we're working with two foreign companies right now, and we've ironed out some basic venture ideas. We haven't formalized them, because you know how attorneys are, but there are agreements to do bilateral marketing where we'd take x percent of their foreign production and do it domestically and they would take some of our domestic production and do it abroad. <P>We're going to probably look at strategic acquistions within the United States that would make sense for Pittsburgh Brewing. A lot of microbrewers have formulas but they don't have breweries, so they're always at the mercy of a brewery to make their products. [We'd buy] formulas, trademarks, names, and we have the brewing capacity here.<P>Now we do about 950,000 barrels a year. We could probably go to 1.3 million. But you can't buy market share. You have to go in, take the time to form the relationships with the distributors and go from there.<P>ER: How much of the management here continued? Do you think you can do it with the people that were here in the past?<P>JP: All of management continued. But that's a question that goes through my mind. I think a fair comment to make is that really, with Mike Carlow, their hands were tied. No one knew what was going on, and there really wasn't much they could do. Their money was taken away from them, they were riding on pins and needles, vendors calling for money. In three months? It may be a different story. I'm not going to lie to you.<P>They need to know, and I think they do, that I care. I walk through every day. I'm not a person that's sitting around or calling on the cellphone from Hawaii.<P>ER: How do you look at the markets in this industry?<P>JP: I guess you look at marketing as far as trends. If you follow any trend of any product it usually starts on the coast - California, Texas, and works its way to New York or vice versa. Then it starts to penetrate the Midwest. It's pretty similar in a lot of products. Once it gets to the Midwest, it's already out of fashion in New York or California.<P>So we look at the markets and say, where are they now? What percentage could we get and what do we need to do to achieve it? If you look at Rolling Rock, it's made in Latrobe. It was trendy - they're paying $4 for it in the New England area. You couldn't give it away here. It's the mentality.<P>Samuel Adams has been very successful everywhere - that's marketing. The good thing is that the J.J. Wainwright Evil Eye we just came out with already has 70 percent of the market share of Samuel Adams in less than a year. So that means the product's good, to catch on that quicklywithout the promotion and the dollars behind the advertising. Now if we can put the dollars behind that quality and taste, I think we're going to take the product that much further.<P>ER: How's the physical plant here? Do you need a lot of dollars in capitalization?<P>JP: Yeah. And a good portion of that is to automate going forward. Some of that is to make up for the neglect that's happened. We committed a lot of money for the next three years.<P>It's over a million dollars a year. So now you're talking about owners coming in, we're not taking a dime of profit out of here, every dollar's going back. I took a drastic pay cut to come here, but I hope it pays off in the long run.<P>
<P>



<hr>

