<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Travel</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H11ExTravel.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Appearance.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Call of the Wind</FONT></b><BR>
<B><I><font size=+2>The Tiny Central American Country of Costa Rica is and Ecotourist's Dream</font></I><P></b>
<i>By Katherine Brentgel</i>
</center>
<HR>
Don't look too hard for the elusive golden toad in Costa Rica's Monteverde Cloud Forest. Even though Monteverde is the only place in the world to see this brilliantly colored amphibian, sightings are rare. Visitors, however, rarely go away disappointed because this misty reserve offers much more: 400 bird species, 100 types of mammals, 490 kinds of butterflies and 2,500 plant species. <P>In Costa Rica, the Nortoameri-canos can see the jaguar and the ocelot slink through the lush, green rain forest. Tourists can spot brilliant red and emerald quetzals, the sacred bird of the Maya and symbol of freedom. They can hear the booming call of the three-wattled bell bird. Or they can watch sea turtles nest on an undeveloped beach.<P>It's all in Costa Rica, a tiny democratic nation bordered by Nicaragua, Panama, and both the Pacific and Atlantic oceans. <P>Twelve percent of Costa Rica's land is protected in national parks, with another 15 percent in private nature reserves like Monteverde. The park system has long been the well-kept secret of biology students and researchers from around the world - but more and more nonscientific visitors are coming to absorb the natural beauty.<P>"I am happy that ecotourism is flourishing because it brings some substantial return to a country like Costa Rica," says Ray Heithaus, a biology professor at Kenyon College who has researched in Costa Rica and taught students there. <P>Ecotourism is blossoming because of Costa Rica's incredible biological diversity, its extensive amount of protected lands and stable political conditions. In size, Costa Rica is slightly smaller than West Virginia, yet has an amazing variety of protected habitats: lowland forests, high mountain paramos, seaside mangroves, swamps and deciduous dry forests. In fact, the largest area of dry tropical forest left in the New World is in Costa Rica's parks.<P>Originally, 99.8 percent of Costa Rica was forested.  But trees began disappearing at an alarming rate until 1969, when natural resources experts lobbied for the creation of a park system to protect at least some of the remaining forest. The government created the National Parks Service in 1970, to the chagrin of farmers, ranchers and loggers, who believed that they would profit most by clearing the rain forests. The government's task was to prove that conservation and development could go hand-in-hand, using non-destructive activities likeecotourism. Since the government lacked the funds to develop tourist facilities or train park guides, it turned to the private sector. The land had been set aside; it was up to the nature tour companies and developers to provide the tourist services. Conservationists liked the  idea because they thought the private sector would do its best to protect        its investment. <P>It has. And ecotourism is big money for this small country. Ecotour companies have mushroomed all over the country, offering guided tours through national parks and more specialized tours that include bicycling, horseback riding, rafting and kayaking. Most towns have a network of native tour guides willing to show visitors Costa Rica's national heritage. <P>One frontrunner is Costa Rica Expeditions, founded by American Michael Kaye. For about $65 a day, the company offers one-day trips led by a professional naturalist to many of the parks and reserves. Like most of the ecotour companies, Costa Rica Expeditions is headquartered in San Jose, the centrally located capital city.<P>These companies offer many one-day trips as well as more extended packages. A guided tour is probably a good idea for first-time visitors; a knowledgeable guide can help you spot and identify birds and animals. <P>Your most difficult task will be to select which parks to visit. Some parks are accessible as a day trip from San Jose. Others are more remote, but accommodations are available in nearby towns. Some examples of the parks:<P>l	Braulio Carrillo National Park, 20 miles east of San Jose, is a feast of lush green forest, waterfalls and canyons. The main highway from San Jose to the Atlantic coast cuts through this park, so it is possible to drive through this incredible landscape. Three monkey species have been spotted in Braulio Carrillo, as well as tapirs, jaguars, ocelots and kinkajous. It is the closest place to San Jose where the resplendent quetzals can be seen. Many people travel to Braulio Carrillo just to climb Barva Volcano, one of two volcanoes in the park. Jungle Trails and Costa Rica Expeditions offer one-day trips to the volcano.  <P>l	Santa Rosa National Park offers great exposure to a dry tropical forest, one of the most endangered ecosystems in the world. It is in the northwest corner of the country on the Pacific coast, over a four hour drive from San Jose. The undeveloped beaches inside the park are beautiful. During the wet season, leatherback, green and Pacific Ridley turtles nest along Playa Naranjo, a beach that is eight miles from park headquarters. <P>In addition to sea turtles, Santa Rosa is home to spider, capuchin and howler monkeys, armadillos, coatis and over 50 species of bats. Thousands of moth and butterfly species have been identified in the park along with 253 bird species, such as orange-fronted parakeets, trogons and caracaras.<P>Liberia, a 45 minute drive to the northwest, has the closest accommodations to Santa Rosa. The town offers several modern hotels with swimming pools and is a good base for exploring the parks and beaches of the region.<P>On the way back to San Jose, another site worth seeing is Arenal Volcano, active since 1968. The volcano belches huge clouds of smoke, ash and thin streams of lava. Its thundering explosions can be heard for miles. Built in 1987, the Arenal Volcano Observatory is a privately owned nature reserve and a long-term research base for scientists. Through Costa Rica Sun Tours, non-scientific visitors can do a day trip to the observatory for about $65, which includes a guide, transportation to the site and a chance to swim in the thermal waters around the base of the volcano. To see Arenal erupt at night, there is also an overnight package available.   <P>Costa Rica is an easy destination to reach. Travelers would most likely fly to Miami on a domestic flight and then to San Jose on Lacsa, the Costa Rican airline. It's a year-round destination, although the dry season (December to April) is most popular, and hotel reservations can be hard to get during this time. Exploring the national parks requires good hiking shoes, rain gear and insect repellent.<P>A little bit of luck won't hurt, either. You might spot the golden toad. <P><P>Destination: Costa Rica<BR>Location: Central America, between Nicaragua and Panama<BR>Size: Slightly smaller than West Virginia<BR>Climate: Tropical; dry season (December to April); rainy season (May to November)<BR>Terrain: Coastal plains separated by rugged mountains<BR>Natural hazards: Subject to occasional earthquakes; hurricanes along Atlantic coast; frequent flooding of lowlands at onset of rainy season; active volcanoes<BR>Bet you didn't know: Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of Costa Rican exports. Most notable are Costa Rican coffee, bananas and sugar, all of which are shipped to   the United States. Other food     crops include corn, rice, beans      and potatoes.<P>


<hr>

