<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Appearance </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Travel.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrTitleExecApprnce.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

<P><B><font size=+2>Fit In, Don't Blend In</font><br></B>
<font size=+1> Executive Dress These Days Means<br>More Than the Conservative Blue Suit</font><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</I>
</CENTER>


<hr>
Debbie Moses, a PNC trust investment counselor, has a work outfit she loves - a wine-colored gabardine suit, with soft lines and a short skirt. Beth Wainwright, executive director of Leadership Pittsburgh, does too - a black suit, with a tuxedo jacket and a short skirt. And Monica Lake's favorite piece? The wife of Steeler safety Carnell Lake has an Ellen Tracy jacket she's had since 11th grade, navy blue and cropped, with military gold buttons.<P>Though the career regimens of these women vary greatly, their fashion does not. They like tradition, with a twist. And that's okay. Because after years of blue suits, dressing for success is loosening up, for both men and women.<P>While other areas of the country - especially hotbeds of small business - move to truly casual executive dress, retailers and shoppers alike say "classic with a flair" is the modus operandi in Pittsburgh fashion.<P>In searching for a look, Pitts-burghers don't fall too far from the tree. Quality, value and longevity       top the list of desirable features for         a wardrobe item. They want classic style that's just a little bit different in some aspect, whether it's the fabric, the cut or the color. They want to fit in, but not blend in.<P>"Dressing is one of the top marketing tools an individual can use," says Philip Elias, president of Elias/Savion Advertising. "It presents an unspoken persona, and sets the stage for who   you are. It should be solidified by your corporate goals and philosophies. People drive BMWs for the same reason. But you can't bring your BMW into a meeting." <P>"It's very important," adds Wainwright. "How you look is the first thing people notice about you. It's the overture, even if you don't know it, and if you do it right, the next step is easier."<P>"People respond to how you look, whether it's acknowledged or not," agrees Moses, whose shopping strategy includes regular passes through Saks, but also through bargain outlets such as Value City and Loehmanns (now closed). "Plus, if I feel good about how I look, it will probably give me confidence."<P>Gone are the times when every man getting off the elevator has to have on a yellow striped tie. Gone, executives say, are the times when women had to wear dumpy, masculinely tailored suits with little ties, though the odd tale still surfaces of the woman who didn't make partner because she didn't dress the part.<P>"I think, in business, women draw the boundaries tighter than they need to. You can push those boundaries if you do it with taste. It can even enhance your success in a client relationship, because they think you're independent-minded," says Moses. "But if I came in in a leather suit, it wouldn't fly."<P>Just what is appropriate? There's a line drawn - but it's all in the mind. Those that cross it, most likely, have different lines. Ideas about fashion are all over the map. Most people, given the choice, wouldn't dress in runway fashion - too drafty, not practical. And others aren't sure that's fashion at all.<P>"People in Pittsburgh associate the word fashion with trend," says Katherine Barchetti, for 27 years one of the area's most forward and successful retailers. "My frustration is that people think Pittsburgh is not fashionable because it's a conservative city. I don't sell a man a suit that will go out of style before eight years."<P>Barchetti, whose pet peeve is customers who remark that they're buying something "to wear when they go somewhere else," bases her men's clothing business on haberdashery that is classic, with a flair. But she also stalks success by giving her customers service and convenience in buying everything from socks to suits to ties. Her massive database includes the sizes and tastes of all her customers.<P>"I just call them, or they'll call me and tell me what's new," says Don Jones, creative director of Jones Day Advertising. "If you're running low on anything, they'll send it down to you."<P>Jones says that he also shops when he's out of town - mostly because he has more free time. But many women say they shop out of town because, though Pittsburgh's fine for the staples, they have trouble finding that one piece to differentiate them from the crowd here.<P>"It's hard finding good shops," says Lake, whose height of 5 feet 9 inches complicates her search. "I'm from California, and it's so easy to find things there. Here, it's hard." <P>Julie Stark, executive director of the March of Dimes, has the same problem to the other extreme. She's just 5 feet tall. <P>"It's hard to find a smart, sassy look on the rack. If you wear something too big it looks like you borrowed someone's clothes," says Stark, whose favorite piece is an eggplant colored dress with a swing cut. "I think Pittsburgh is a small midwestern town in flair and style, but it is a fashionable place. I go to a lot of black tie events, and you see the whole gamut of fashion there. There are a lot of places to shop."<P>For the most part, Pittsburgh executives seem to think that depending on your taste and how dedicated of a shopper you are, there is a place in Pittsburgh to suit you.<P>"I'm not big on any specific store, I shop mostly at Kaufmann's and Saks. Being downtown I find it easier to pop into different places," says Jody Doherty, former manager of public relations for the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, now aide to Allegheny County Commissioner Larry Dunn. "I'm not hard to please. Pittsburgh has a lot of options."<P>And those options are broadening, at least for women. Many female executives mentioned shopping at Ann Taylor, which continues to expand in the region. And smaller specialty shops continue to crop up, like the new Cajoli, in Aspinwall, and Katherine Barchetti's women's shop in Oxford Centre, which opened in October.<P>"I reordered one line three times in one week," says Barchetti, who had a women's clothing shop in addition to her men's shop years ago, but says she closed it because she didn't have enough time. "It's hard to find enough people to work for me. But the wives of my customers kept asking me 'When are you going to have something for us?' "  <P>Barchetti's women's shop will sell sportswear, suits and accessories. Though not in as wide an array as her men's shop, it will also be based on service. That's a concept more and more women are beginning to value.<P>For years, men have been able to call their tailor for a custom fitting. Now, women can do that too, with a couple of new lines that retail through traveling sales people who travel to your home or office.<P>"I sell to the female executive who is too busy or doesn't want to go shopping," says Theresa Sullivan, a salesperson for Doncaster, a Rutherfordton, N.C., company that sells through home-based consultants. The Doncaster line contains executive and casual components, that can be ordered in a variety of fabrics and colors. Sullivan often is asked into the client's closet, to critique her clothing situation.<P>"I go through her closet and say, 'Get rid of this, this is nice, pitch this,' " says Sullivan. "And they do it. I think they just want someone to be honest with them. How they look is important."<P>Beyond the Clothes: Many Improve Their<P>Physical Appearance via Plastic Surgery<P><P>A little tuck here, a nip there - the potential of plastic surgery has been apparent for years, given the patient has ample cash and level of vanity. Previously, however, the extent of contact that most conservative western Pennsylvanians have had with it has been in the grocery store line, where it's easy to chart the cosmetic alterations of the likes of Cher and Michael Jackson. <P>But that's changing, according to Dr. Theodore Lazzaro of Aesthetique, an aesthetic plastic surgery center in Greensburg. Baby boomers, the generation addicted to health and fitness and image, are reaching the age where there's beginning to be a little something to nip and tuck up. And never ones to be frugal with resources when it comes to something that enhances their lives, they're checking in in style - Aesthetique, a late 1890s coal baron's mansion, on 35 acres outside of Greensburg, has been renovated into an accredited ambulatory surgical facility.<P>"Western Pennsylvania is the most rapidly growing area for cosmetic surgery in the country, because it is the cheapest, and because people are finding out that you don't have to go into the hospital," says Lazzaro. <P>Cosmetic plastic surgery is generally not covered by insurance, except   for breast reductions involving more than three-quarters of a pound from each one.<P>"The majority of people that get aesthetic plastic surgery come from households with less than $30,000 income," Lazzaro says.<P>In 1988, Lazzaro saw 50 to 75 cosmetic surgery patients - last year he estimated 750 or 1,000 cases. One demographic that's increasing is men, who are getting cosmetic procedures in increasing numbers. Lazzaro says that his practice, which was 85 percent women five years ago, is now just 60 to 65 percent women. The procedure he performs most on men is eyelid surgery, then liposculpture for the 'handlebars' of fat that accumulate on male backs. Women most commonly have breast procedures, either augmenting or reducing, and liposculpture for the hips and thighs.<P>Another factor contributing to the increase in his patient load is an influx of cases from outside the area, which accounts for 10 to 15 percent of his cosmetic surgeries. Here, depending on the complexity of the operation, a face-lift costs $4,000 to $6,000. In New York, it's $20,000, says Lazzaro. Aesthetique has a deal with nearby Nemacolin Woodlands, where patients can stay for four nights and be pampered until their follow-up visit for $1,000. Even with airfare, they've made a deal.<P>"As the baby boom population becomes middle aged, these same people who have put an emphasis on fitness are now reaching the age where they don't look as good as they feel," says Lazzaro. Indicative of this is the fact that people are getting these techniques done younger: Ten to 15 years ago, his average face-lift patient was age 55 or 60. Now, patients are in their early 40s, and he's had to modify some of his procedures. <P>Lazzaro tells the story of one patient, a CEO, who went back to work after getting a facelift and his eyelids done. At the board table the next day, he could see everyone looking at him out of the corner of their eyes, so he leveled    with them.<P>"I can see you're looking at how good I look. In case you're wondering, I had a face-lift," said the CEO. "I wouldn't think of coming in with a wrinkled shirt, so why would I come in with a wrinkled face?"<P>
<HR>
