<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Buy Our Stock
</font><br>
<font size=+1>A Spate of Public Offerings is a <BR>
Good Sign for the Regional Economy
</font><BR>
<i>By Doug Thomas
</i></b>

<HR>
Just when you were beginning to worry about the shrinking universe of public companies in the Pittsburgh metropolitan area, here comes a spate of initial public offerings and numerous other signs that the local climate for public companies is becoming more inviting<P>A slew of new offerings have catapulted formerly private companies such as The Carbide/Graphite Group, the Carnegie Group and Italian Oven into public entities. More, like Tollgrade Communications, are on the way. Other companies like the already public Universal Stainless and II-VI Inc. are tapping the public markets again through so-called secondary offerings to raise additional capital to expand, either through capital expenditures or acquisition.<P>Pittsburgh is even participating in a big way in the success of some other nonlocal public companies. For instance, the Boston Beer Co., the brewer of Samuel Adams and one of the recent IPO highflyers, had received approximately 46 percent of its beer through November from Pittsburgh Brewing Co.<P>So fear not. Whether through venture capital, private investment or sweat equity, the marketplace for public companies here is diverse and dynamic. Despite losing its share of corporate headquarters, Pittsburgh's climate for fostering new ideas and new companies is showing promise. Our economic future depends just as much on the growth of small and mid-sized companies - e.g. Cable Design Technologies, FORE Systems and Respironics - as it does on the industrial stalwarts and stellar performers like Alcoa, PPG Industries and Mellon Bank.<P><P><B>Around the Index</B><P>The ER Index continues on a growth path, increasing 3.45 percent, as compared with the S&P 500's gain of 1.41 percent, for the four weeks ended Nov. 10, 1995. Since its inception on Aug. 15, 1994, the index has posted a gain of 31.91 percent as compared with 28.51 percent for the S&P 500. The impressive numbers show that individual investors can do quite nicely by investing in local companies.<P>The month's winners and losers:<P>Pittsburgh-based vitamin and supplement retailer General Nutrition Companies reported better than expected earnings for its third quarter ended Sept. 30. Net income increased to $15.9 million, or 18 cents per share, up from $10.1 million, or 13 cents per share, in the prior period. Revenues for the quarter increased 24 percent to $193 million from $156.4 million. For the month, GNC shares finished up 10.8 percent to 23.<P><LI>	PPG Industries had a record third quarter. Earnings for the period were 85 cents per share on revenues of $1.72 billion, compared with 68 cents per share on $1.58 billion in sales last year. <LI>	Allegheny Ludlum announced stronger than anticipated earnings for its third quarter ended Sept. 30. Profits nearly tripled from one year ago, with net income rising to $30.1 million, or 44 cents a share, from $10.3 million or 14 cents. Revenues increased 42 percent to $373.6 million from $262.3 million on a 14 percent increase in steel shipments. Despite the good news, shares of Allegheny Ludlum finished off 15.63 percent in the month                to 16 7/8.<LI>	Armco announced that equipment failures at its steel mills in Mansfield, Ohio, had a negative impact on third quarter earnings. The company reported a loss from continuing operations of $2.1 million. <LI>	Kennametal announced a 28 percent increase in earnings as net income rose to $13.6 million, or 51 cents a share, compared to $10.7 million, or 40 cents a share, last year. Revenues rose 17 percent to $254 million on higher sales of metal-cutting products in North America and Europe and strong catalog sales. Although the results were positive, earnings came in below analysts' expectations, helping Kennametal shares to drop 12.54 percent to 30 1/2.<LI>	The turkey of the month was American Eagle Outfitters, which announced the resignations of Chief Operating Officer Bob Lynn and Chief Financial Officer Adam Monks Dec. 1, only six weeks after the company disclosed a dynamic turnaround plan to New York analysts.<P>The untimely departures of Lynn and Monks raise questions about whether remaining AEO management can turn around  the company.            n<P>Doug Thomas is vice president, director of research for Lancaster, Pa.-based Emerald Asset Management.<P>
<P>



