<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0296.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Presentation is Everything
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>Koto-Buki Offers a Little Bit of Tokyo<BR>in the Heart of Suburbia
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<p>

<hr>


I remember on several occasions in Tokyo, following some friend or another to a restaurant we just had to try. Inevitably, we'd turn off one of Tokyo's crowded main thoroughfares down a twisting narrow alley, where the traditional one-story wooden shops still stood. My host would go straight for the restaurant, identifying it somehow from a row of identical facades, stooping into what was generally a small one-room eatery.<P>Koto-Buki, a new restaurant serving authentic Japanese cuisine, is deep in the American equivalent of that confusing sameness - plunk in the middle of the residential North Hills. <P>Koto-Buki is in a nondescript building on the edge of some North Park townhouses. Don't let that fool you. Inside, the atmosphere is calming - all light wood, tables and chairs in a streamlined design, splashes of color blocked into the room on strategically hung geometric panels. Tables are simply set: There is a white paper napkin with a set of wooden chopsticks at each place, a ceramic pitcher of soy sauce the only other accoutrement.<P>Until the food comes.<P>Then you realize that everything in the restaurant is a subtly balanced backdrop for the meal. First, a simple salad of iceberg lettuce, with maybe a slice of cucumber or radish, and garnished with a thick ginger dressing, not spicy but gentle and refreshing, in a simple black bowl. <P>Then the appetizers. We chose the assorted sushi platter - the pieces of tuna, fluke, yellowtail and salmon so fresh and so tender it practically melted in our mouths. On the beautiful wooden tray were piles of wasabi and gari. Wasabi is a green horseradish paste that is mixed with deep, dark soy sauce, like nothing available at the grocery, for dipping sushi. A refreshing piece of gari, slivered pickled ginger, follows each bite. We also tried shumai, steamed shrimp dumplings dipped into a light sesame sauce. No alcohol is served, but you can bring it if you like.<P>After the appetizers, we were brought soup with white squares of tofu suspended in it. As it is hard to eat soup with chopsticks, the Japanese drink it straight from the bowl. So did we - it was warm and velvety. <P>Next came the dinner. The shrimp tempura and salmon teriyaki combination comes on a laquered tray. The tempura, batter-dipped and fried vegetables and shrimp, was light - jumbo shrimp, fingers of sweet potato, carrots, zucchini and onion. The salmon teriyaki was grilled crispy and glazed in a smooth peanut and soy sauce. A mold of steamed rice and stir-fried vegetables occupied other compartments. The sukiyaki - boiling broth in which was cooking assorted vegetables, tofu and thinly sliced beef - was served in an iron cauldron. The broth was sweet and distinctive, though our server could not identify the special ingredient.<P>The service here, like everything else, is understated and typically Japanese. In fact, this place is so authentic we've heard of one local doctor who used to travel to Washington, D.C., when craving a good Japanese meal who is now perfectly content to travel out McKnight Road. After our meal, they brought the check - we had to beckon them back for coffee and tea.<P>It was worth persisting. The hot ginger tea is a pungent brew of lemon, lime and ginger juices. The dessert menu is light - try the ginger ice cream (they also have red bean or green tea flavor). Because we'd asked for a fork (utensils available on request), they brought us spoons, so I'm not sure how we'd have been expected to eat it. But regardless of how it got to the taste buds, like everything else we tried, it was simple, elegant and delicious.        n<P><P>
<hr><P>


