<HEAD>
<TITLE> HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H15Health.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>A Big Market<br>
</font></I></B>

<b><font size =+1>Medicare HMOs are Battling for the <br>Region's Elderly Population</b></font><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
</center><P>


<HR>
George Wescott says he wouldn't mind. Jean Feskorn and Olga Kessler say they're confused about it. Lou Boliver and Rudy Benedetti already have enrolled. In an HMO, that is.<P>These days, Medicare-eligible seniors are faced with the same difficult healthcare choices as younger people. HMOs are offering them complete care at one premium - often lower than the supplemental  policies many now hold to cover what Medicare does not.<P>HMOs, eager to grow their ranks to achieve cost-effective economies of scale, see seniors as a big market. About 400,000 seniors live in Greater Pittsburgh, half of whom are covered by former employers that pay all or much of their retirees' supplemental premiums. Employers think HMOs can directly reduce the dollars they spend on retiree healthcare. So they're teaming up to attract seniors - in the process, barraging them with direct mail and meetings in every church, community and senior citizen center available. Seniors are confused.<P>"I'm not sure I did the right thing," says Boliver, a 78-year-old retired manager of employee benefits for People's Natural Gas, who enrolled in U.S. Healthcare when People's parent company CNG offered Medicare HMOs to the 7,000 retirees and their dependents it covers. "I think eventually everyone will be forced into HMOs," Boliver says. "It saves the company money."<P>In traditional supplemental programs, either the retiree or the em- ployer pays a monthly premium. Depending on the program, the retiree pays a deductible and a co-pay on visits; the employer pays what Medicare does not cover on a pay-as-you-go basis. For CNG, that cost had been running about $18 million annually, on top of $50 million in premiums. For retirees who chose an HMO, CNG will pay one monthly premium.  In this case, it was $25 if the enrollee choose Sec-urity Blue, Blue Cross' product, or $8 for U.S. Healthcare's product.<P>Retirees meet some co-pays on visits and prescriptions. CNG offered retirees a $25 monthly subsidy to try  the program. <P>"We're able to do that because of the size of the savings," says Andy Haas, CNG assistant vice president for employee benefits and administrative services. "Their [Blue Cross Medi-Gap] premium is going up to $31 per month, per person next year."<P>How do HMOs save? In addition to monthly premiums, the HMO collects anywhere from $250 to $700 per person from the federal government. By applying economies of scale and managed care methods, they cut costs. <P>"The system creates opportunities for HMOs," says Carl Smollinger, senior vice president of the senior managed care program at Blue Cross. "The highest cost of the system is in-patient care, at $1,000 a day, yet there really are a lot of options that cost less. There are regulations built into Medicare, lots of waste we can cut out with managed care, because we're not bound by the same rules."<P>Though many seniors are concerned with the high cost of healthcare, their top concern is limits on their choice of doctors. The Bolivers' primary care doctor is not part of the U.S. Healthcare network, but the rest of his and his wife's doctors (eye, gynecologist and dermatologist) are. The Bolivers are big believers in preventive care, which the HMO also stresses.<P>"There are advantages to HMO plans for the well elderly, especially in preventive coverage," says Dr. Judith Black, medical director of Gerontology at St. Margaret Memorial Hospital. "But if you have physical limitations, you should look very carefully at the accessibility of the HMO."<P>While the HMOs sing of decreasing expenses to seniors, Black says that not everyone can realize savings. She suggests potential enrollees carefully detail the costs they would incur under each plan, as well as look at the convenience of the providers in the network. She also urges seniors who travel a lot to check their out-of-town coverage. "I'm most concerned about the education process," says Black.<P>CNG has spent about $500,000 marketing the plan to retirees. And through the National Medicare HMO Initiative, developed by benefits consultant Towers Perrin, it is able to offer enrollees coverage when they are traveling through participating HMOs. With 12 percent of its covered retirees enrolled in HMOs to date, the company is anticipating about $3.5 million in savings the first year. The jury's still out on whether retirees will be managed care friendly or not.<P>"It's worth trying," says Boliver. "But if there's a problem, U.S. Healthcare will hear about it. I'm not going to just sit down and let anyone tell me what we need."                        n<P><P><P>
<P>

<hr>

