<HEAD>
<TITLE> Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H17Education.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<center><b><font size =+2>
For Women Only</font></B><br>
<B><I><font size=+1>Four Schools in the Region are Proving That <br>Survival Does Not Mean Going Co-Ed
</font></I></B><br>
<i>By Gretchen McKay</i></center>

<HR>
Like most of her classmates, Tamara Watkins was considering only co-ed colleges as she neared high school graduation in 1991. Then she happened upon a brochure touting the merits of all-women's institutions.<P>"It had some very impressive statistics, especially with regards to females in politics," recalls Watkins, who had almost settled on the University of Michigan. "It really piqued my interest."<P>Small wonder. Watkins found out that a quarter of the women in Congress and a third of the women on Fortune 1000 boards are graduates of women's colleges. It proved a powerful draw to Watkins, who subsequently enrolled at Chatham College in Shadyside, one of the region's four women's colleges.<P>Her decision paid off: The management/political science major drew several job offers before she graduated this past May, and is now a sales representative in the lucrative pharmaceutical industry.<P>"I just blossomed at Chatham," says Watkins. "There were more opportunities to take on leadership roles, and I gained a sense of empowerment. Plus I got a superior education."<P>Attracting students wasn't always easy for women's colleges. They  took a real hit in the late '70s and '80s, plunging from 163 colleges nationwide in 1971 to just 84 in 1991. The four here watched enrollment dip as professionally minded women opted for the region's co-ed universities and colleges.<P>"Everyone associated women's colleges with white gloves, which meant one of two things: That women who go there are wealthy, or they don't expect to work," says Esther Barazzoni, president of Chatham.<P>Women's institutions were also failing to reflect women's increased interest in pursuing careers.<P>"The '80s was the decade where Wall Street and making money was big," says Peter Egan, director of admissions at Seton Hill College, a small Catholic women's liberal arts college in Greensburg. In comparison to their co-ed counterparts, he says,  women's colleges were seen as just finishing schools.<P>But that was then, this is now. According to the Washington, D.C.-based Women's College Coalition, applications to the country's 84 women's colleges have risen by 14 percent since 1991, and enrollments have grown to 105,000 students, nearly 20 percent more than in 1985.<P>That translates to a record number of enrollments at the region's four women's schools - Chatham and Carlow in Pittsburgh, Seton Hill in Greensburg and Wilson College near Harrisburg - which have reengineered to meet the challenge. Their strategy includes offering courses that focus on business, math and science, beefing up mentor programs and internships, and engaging in more vigorous marketing. And all in an atmosphere that fosters self-esteem and encourages women to reach their potential.<P>"At a women's college, there's no glass ceiling," says Seton Hill's Egan. "There's an 'I can do anything' kind of attitude through the whole school."<P>What does a women's college offer that its co-ed counterpart does not? The list is long: freedom from stereotyping, a more sup portive atmosphere, gender equality in sports. The schools also offer smaller class sizes, higher  student/faculty ratios and a profusion of female role models, accustoming female students to the idea of power.<P>"We have an overt commitment to women taking leadership positions by expecting them to do it," says Barazzoni. "And what you expect someone to do has a powerful influence on what they actually do."<P>Still, the business of attracting new students hasn't been easy. Chatham considered going co-ed in 1990 as a way to stay afloat financially. Administrators decided against it, however, when everyone from alumnae to trustees protested. They did decide to enroll men in their five graduate programs, but that was the extent of it. <P>Seton Hill also matriculates males, but only in its School of Visual Arts. Carlow, a Catholic liberal arts college in Oakland, still markets itself as primarily a women's college.<P>As for Chatham, administrators there say they took the "quality route" and beefed up curriculum, which included adding some very highly competitive professional programs at the graduate level. <P>Other women's colleges have taken similar strides to lure students from co-ed schools. There's a renewed emphasis on recruiting, often at an earlier age. Take Seton Hill. The college is going after a younger audience, bringing junior high students onto campus to participate in chemistry lab activities, and taking current students into local grade schools to serve as mentors. <P>"We're encouraging girls to pursue careers in math, science and business, and to think about doing it in the best place, which may be a women's college," says Seton Hill president JoAnn Boyle.<P>The end result? Business is booming.  Enrollment at both Seton Hill and Carlow College has doubled in the past decade. Chatham, which has enjoyed a 25 percent increase in the past three years, went up 28 percent last year, or three times the national average.<P>"We're like Olympic training villages, training women to compete in the world," says Barazzoni. 		      n<P><P>
<P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

