<HEAD>
<TITLE> Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>Computer Quandary</font><br><font size=+1>Consultants can Help When<br>Choosing Computer System<br>
</font></B><i>By Henry Lipput</center></i><P>


<HR>
Richard Miller had plenty of reasons to go hunting for a computer system for his insurance agency. He knew it would make his small business more efficient, but he also knew it would keep him and his colleagues on a level playing field with competitors.<P>"Number one, our competitors were computerized," says Miller, a principal with Miller Wrenshall and Associates Inc. "Number two, in today's marketplace, you have to be able to do more with less when it comes to what your staffing budget would be. If you don't have computers, you're going to perform a lot of the manual tasks that are going to cost you a lot more than if you have a computer."<P>But procuring a computer today is no easy task. With rapidly evolving technology, what is cutting edge today can be obsolete in a few months. What complicates matters is the fact that many small businesses - such as Miller's insurance agency - have limited capital budgets. So some small businesses that want the most bang for their buck are turning to consultants, who can recommend software and advise business owners on how much memory their hard disk should have. And that's only a start. There are       also printers, fax modems, translation programs and other bells and whistles to consider.<P>Some make a business more efficient. Others are of no use, so why pay for them?<P>"Up until six or eight years ago, a computer - to a small business - was a very scary thing," says computer consultant Gerald Rosenthal of Teitelman & Rosenthal. "The cost was high, the learning curve was immensely high and long, and there was always a potential for great disaster. Technology has come a long way. The cost has drastically dropped, and the learning curve has greatly shortened. And there are many, many more products on the market."<P>For most small businesses, a computer can ease the accounting procedure immediately. Computerizing the accounting process - or upgrading it if it already is computerized - can help the business better track accounts receivable, in the end improving cash flow. Another emerging plus is the money computers can save a business in paper costs, which have skyrocketed over the past year.<P>"If a small business wants a computer, first we look over their general bookkeeping and accounting situation to see what level of sophistication they want to be at, and then we simply     recommend some hardware with certain specifications," Rosenthal says. "We know the accounting software on the market and we recommend the software that we think fits them."<P>What some businesses don't realize is that by better tracking accounts receivable, a computer can pay for itself within a year. The problem is that some businesses explore computerization or upgrade an ancient system only as a last resort, when they already are choked by a cash flow crisis.<P>"Most small businesses engage me because their profitability, the strength of the business, is in jeopardy, and there are a number of profitability and conflict issues involved," says another consultant, Marty Feinberg.<P>"If a firm can increase its efficiency by 10 percent, it can double net profit without increasing sales one dime," Feinberg says.  "When I do the diagnosis for the business, one of the things may be that they either need computers or they need to update what they have." <P>Some consultants represent certain lines of software or hardware and will take a commission if you buy the lines they promote. Other consultants work on a fee-only basis and, some say, offer a more objective point of view. For the owner of the business, it's a matter of preference.<P>"Usually, the guys who are good will make recommendations with a range of alternatives," says Feinberg, who works on a fee-only basis. "And they'll even help them shop. I don't like to do for a client what a client can do for himself, but in this case, sometimes guidance is worth paying the price."  <P>Once the purchase is made, the real learning starts. At this point, there also are a slew of consultants who will train employees on software.<P>"We recommend software, then we teach them how to use it, and everything is customized to their business," says consultant Jody Sprinkle, of Software Training Specialists. "It's customized in the way that we train them. We're using their work materials and the way they do business, so that they have a decreased learning curve."<P>Again, beware of consultants who also take commissions from software companies. Their advice may not be impartial, industry insiders say.<P>Small businesses must operate at maximum efficiency to increase profitability. Adding computerization or upgrading existing systems is one way to increase efficiency.                           n<P><P><P>
<P>



<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

