</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>DO OR DIE</B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Can We Resuscitate This Region?<br>Now Is The Time to Turn Things Around
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>
Back in 1977, Michael Bussler founded Algor Inc. with a single computer that his clients paid to use on a time-share basis. Now, two decades later, Algor develops and sells specialized software to design engineers in more than 60 countries, with annual sales approaching $10 million.<P>The software has been used to design and test Nautilus exercise equipment, Black & Decker's "Dustbuster" and B.F. Goodrich tires, among other products. The software also was used to stress test Pittsburgh's Smithfield Street Bridge when it was recently rebuilt.<P>So it's quite evident that the Algor of today is a far cry from Bussler's startup as an engineering service bureau with one computer. Today, Bussler employs about 70 people at Algor headquarters in O'Hara Township, and the company's effect on the regional economy goes well beyond paying salaries to employees.<P>Like other successful entrepre-neurships in the region, Algor is a living lesson in trickle-down economics - western Pennsylvania style. The mere existence of Algor creates business for others in the region. Algor pays a law firm. Algor pays accountants. Algor pays to have its headquarters building cleaned. And Algor donated $1 million to Carnegie Mellon University to help fund a research project.<P>"There's no doubt, we are generating some jobs here," concedes Bussler, himself somewhat of a skeptic on the trickle-down influence of entrepre-neurships like his own.<P>"We certainly are not hurting the local economy, since 98 percent of our income is coming in from somewhere else, and hardly any of it is going elsewhere," Bussler says.<P>Other observers agree.<P>"That's a company that is expanding and creating new wealth," says Thomas N. Canfield, president of The Enterprise Corp., which helps entrepreneurs develop businesses with significant employment opportunities.<P>"[Algor] is selling its products and services outside of this region," Canfield says. "That is money we are importing from the rest of the country and world right here into this region. Because of this wealth, we probably have another little shoe store or pizza parlor.<P>"That's how regions create wealth," Canfield says.<P>Unfortunately, Bussler and other successful entrepreneurs are the minority in our region, where the rate of entrepreneurship is dreadful. What's it mean? The professional services firms - such as law and accounting firms - better expand their geographic reach, because they sure won't grow business here unless they take it away from another firm. The same holds true up and down the food chain that makes up our economy. Security guards have fewer offices to watch. Landscapers have less grass to cut. Lawyers have fewer companies to counsel.<P>"There's only two ways to expand your business," says Mark Miner, media manager for the law firm Buchanan Ingersoll. "You can take market share from someone else in the city or you expand geographically."<P>Because the number of start-ups is stagnant, there's only so much business to go around. For you and me, that's bad news. It puts this region at risk.<P>With this article, Executive Report begins a series of articles entitled Resuscitating the Region. The six-month series will focus on opportunities to spur regional growth. Foremost is this month's topic: entrepreneurship. Through the following five months, ER will also explore education, exporting, tax reform, tourism and transportation as areas of opportunity.<P><P><B>Entrepreneurship</B><P>Perhaps Gov. Tom Ridge sums it up best. The gover nor doesn't expect large corporations to come into Pennsylvania, build manufacturing sites and employ thousands of people. There are too many reasons - such as regulation and taxes - for corporations to locate elsewhere. <P>"I believe Pennsylvania's economy depends on our ability to keep the jobs we have, to help Pennsylvania's companies expand in Pennsylvania and to help convince potential entrepreneurs to take calculated risks, to step forward, to pursue that dream," the governor says. "There is no doubt in my mind that our ability to nurture these people is critical to the state's future."<P>And it appears Ridge is walking the walk instead of just talking the talk. He took a first step toward spurring entrepreneurship early in his administration with a budget measure increasing the amount of net operating losses entrepreneurs can carry forward from previous years, up to $1 million from $500,000. Ridge says he thinks the change will convince some potential entrepreneurs to take the leap and stick out the lean times, knowing they can recoup part of any losses at a later time.<P>Ridge also knocked 1 percent off the corporate net income tax during his first year in office.<P><P><B>Good Reason to Act</B><P>Ridge knew that state statistics on entrepreneurship were horrifying. For instance, the Center for Enterprise Development ranked Pennsylvania dead last nationally in 1994 for "entrepreneurial energy." The rank is the result of  combining three factors: Pennsylvania ranked 45th in the rate of new company formation, 49th for rate of change in the formation rate and 33rd for the rate of job growth in new companies less than four years old. The center did not rank states in 1995, but Canfield, the Enterprise Corp. president, crunched the numbers himself and slotted Pennsylvania last again.<P>It gets worse: Western Pennsyl-vania trails the statewide average in new company formations. A University of Pittsburgh study showed the new company formation rate proceeding about 25 percent slower than the dismal statewide rate. About 3,400 new companies are formed in the region each year, half of where we would be if we reached the national average.<P><P><B>Addressing the Problem</B><P>Many observers see a multipronged problem that starts with the region's tradition. Donald F. Smith Jr., executive director of the Center for Economic Development at Carnegie Mellon University, says many in the region expect big business and big labor to provide them with opportunity, rather than trying to create opportunity themselves. <P>History supports that theory: For decades in western Pennsylvania, a son would go to work in the same facility that employed his father and his father's father. People didn't have to create their own opportunities because Andrew Carnegie and men like him were creating opportunities for them.<P>That thinking must change.<P>"We must get the man on the street to accept the challenge," says Gerald E. McGinnis, chairman of Respironics Inc., the once-entrepre-neurship and now public company that posted 1995 sales of $99.5 million.<P>But the problem goes beyond our region's mindset. Even if this region were entrepreneurial, it still would be starting a few steps behind the rest of the country. Only 15 percent of our population is in the prime entrepre-neurial age range of 25 to 34, compared to other regions that typically have over 20 percent of their population in that group. Furthermore, the region's population is the old-est among the nation's metro-politan areas.<P>"And that isn't because old people move here," Allegheny Ludlum Corp. chairman Richard P. Simmons told a gathering of fellow chief executives a few months back.<P>And then there is the problem of cap-ital to support entrepreneurship. A recently published Enterprise Corp. report showed  a shortage of local adventure capital - the high risk start-up money that will sustain a company and enable it to grow until larger pools of capital can be attracted, such as those provided by venture capital funds. The adventure capital usually comes from individual investors, since venture capital firms rarely invest in companies at their earliest stages. The Enterprise Corp. recommends that up to $4 million in adventure capital should be invested in local start-ups each year.<P>As for venture capital - the money that helps established companies grow - the report showed only     a slight increase in the amount              of venture capital here that is available to invest. And five of 13 Pittsburgh-based funds said they were fully   invested and were not seeking             new investments.<P><B>Solving the Problem</B><P>Not all the news is bad. Our region has several factors in its favor: Its universities and hospitals are nationally recognized. It has strong cultural amenities and a low cost of living. It has a great airport and is centrally located between New York and Chicago. You can also factor in more business friendly initiatives that Ridge likely will push through.<P>So there are reasons to consider starting a business here.<P>And to find entrepreneurs who might start businesses, Canfield wants to clone a program used in Kansas City, Mo., an entrepreneurial hotbed. <P>In 1993, Ewing Marion Kauffman, founder of Marion Pharmaceuticals, which now is industry giant Marion Merrill Dow, left half of his $1.2 billion estate to be used for economic development in greater Kansas City.<P>One effort entails using Kauff-man's money to keep talented people in Kansas City. Canfield wants to do the same thing here, tapping the talent produced each spring by the region's universities.<P>Canfield would call the program Pittsburgh Fellows.<P>"I think it is absolutely critical that we copy this program," he says. "Let's get 50 of these people who are imported here - about ready to graduate - and get them to stay here, sink roots here, buy a house ... maybe have a kid. Once they are here, like all of us, they do not want to leave.<P>"If they stay, maybe we get a couple FORE Systems that in a few years will have 500 employees," Canfield says.<P>Then there's the question of money. Why should private individuals invest in a young business when such high risk is involved? William C. Dunkelberg, chief economist for the National Federation of Independent Business, doesn't look at adventure capital as a risk because, he says, eventually there is a return. He thinks adventure capital should be a priority.<P>"Small firms are in many ways the R&D of the U.S. economy," Dunkel-berg said in a speech last year. "Any individual has the right and the opportunity to start a business. Through this mechanism, new ideas, new ways to do things, new products or new niche markets can be served. Successful projects are rewarded with profits, the source of capital for expansion and the signal for new resources to enter the market in the form of competition.<P>"Experiments that fail may result in bankruptcy or termination, but the resources that were used are not lost to society," Dunkelberg says. "They are repriced and redeployed in yet another entrepreneurial venture. This process is repeated until the resources earn a competitive return, the signal that they are now productively deployed."<P>Stories about companies bootstrapping their way to success are common, but in actuality, are much the exception rather than the rule. Seed money is an absolute necessity in most cases: Just ask entrepreneur Gene Kirila, who has been through the early stages of a business twice.<P>At age 20, Kirila left Youngstown State University and with a friend started Pyramid Enterprise, a company that eventually offered a line of 130 fitness products and generated annual revenues of $8 million. Kirila sold the company in 1993 and now is involved with another venture, Pyramid Plastics, which is opening a 65,000-square-foot manufacturing facility in Greenville that will employ 110 people.<P>"Venture capital is the key element," Kirila says. "There's no question."<P>Through the early part of the 20th century, Pittsburgh was a center of venture capital. The Mellon family, H.C. Frick and other business tycoons invested in all sorts of industries.<P>Today, there are signs of improvement in the region. Most notably, Kevin McClatchy pulled several local investors into his bid for the Pirates. And Dr. Peter Johnson, a University of Pittsburgh plastic surgeon who is pushing for Pittsburgh to be a tissue engineering hub, says doors are opening for him.<P><P><B>At Ground Zero</B><P>Some observers say the solutions aren't as simple as preserving the region's younger population and making seed money readily available. Algor's Bussler, for one, tells how the local economy supported his time-share business until the early '80s, when it dried up and forced him to totally change his business to what it is today. He no longer could rely on the regional economy to support his business.<P>"There has to be a viable economy for entrepreneurs to survive," says Bussler.<P>Tom Croft, executive director of the Steel Valley Authority, agrees, and places partial blame for our dearth of entrepreneurship on the region's policy makers. Croft says it was they who a decade ago gave short shrift to the manufacturing base after the collapse of the steel industry. Since then, Croft says, there's been a shifting economic development focus. <P>"Tourism. Retail. If the game plan keeps changing," Croft asks, "how do we even stay on the field?"<P>The Enterprise Corp.'s Canfield says manufacturing can indeed trigger entrepreneurship, provided the manufacturing base is cemented in growth industries. Unfortunately, our regional manufacturing base is not in growth industries.<P>"Name the top five growth industries in the U.S.," Canfield says. "Then name the companies dominating those markets and the Pittsburgh companies participating in those markets. You find out our current economy is not tied to the things that are generating the huge growth."<P>And that could explain the perception that there is a lack of venture and adventure capital, according to CMU's Smith. He stresses that capital does not necessarily have to come from this region. If ideas are viable - and often that means tied to a growth industry -Smith says the capital will flow in from sources here and elsewhere.<P>At presstime, the Allegheny Conference was moving forward with investment initiatives aimed at creating 100,000 new jobs by the year 2000. The business-sponsored policy organization had raised $40 million from the private sector to revitalize downtown Pittsburgh. But it also targeted restoration of the manufacturing base via technology-oriented manufacturers in five key industries: metalworking; chemicals and plastics; biomedical technologies; information and communication products; and environmental products. The Allegheny Conference wants to develop regional technology parks at sites near downtown and the airport.<P>Triggering entrepreneurship is a complex process, and it won't happen overnight. Crucial steps include keeping young talent here, luring adventure capital and tapping growth industries. And Ridge must make Pennsylvania a good place to do business.<P>Whatever the strategy, the time is now. As Allegheny Ludlum's Simmons told his fellow chief executives a few months back: The region is at risk.<P>"Wouldn't it be awful if we simply said we are too far gone - if we didn't try," Simmons told the group. "This is my home. This is your home. This is the home of a lot of people who say we have a window of opportunity and we are going to grasp it.<P>"We're going to try."                    <P>
<P>






