</center><P>

<center>
<B><font size=+2>Dream or Reality?
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Will the Region Support a Downtown Retail District?<br>Lazarus and thje City are Betting on it</font></b><br>

<i>By Christopher Lawton</i></center>
<hr>
It was only a few days after Lazarus - the retailer that acquired Joseph Horne Co. - had committed to building a new store in downtown Pittsburgh. Mayor Tom Murphy was addressing an investment forum at the Westin William Penn and passed on some insider information: A half-dozen or so other retailers - their attention caught by the Lazarus venture - were calling the city.<P>That was good news for Murphy, who only months earlier was sweat-   ing out the possibility that Lazarus might abandon downtown Pittsburgh altogether.<P>But with Lazarus a done deal, Murphy now has something the city has lacked for years: a legitimate shopping district. And even if the other major retailers don't come, Murphy still has this: Lazarus on one corner, Saks Fifth Avenue on another corner and Kaufmann's on the next block. Plus, there's Burlington Coat Factory and Barnes & Noble bookstore, too. Larrimor's, Brooks Brothers and other specialty shops and restaurants round out the neighborhood. The city thinks more will come.<P>"We want to increase the viability of downtown by increasing the desirability of being downtown," says Robert D. Hurley, one of the mayor's economic development managers. "Once you get Lazarus on Fifth Avenue, a lot of the rest will come."<P><B>Setting the Foundation</B><P>Essentially, the present plans were born 15 months ago when Lazarus told the mayor it wanted to move from the Horne's building near Gateway Center. The building was not only old, it was isolated.<P>"The facility that Lazarus inherited required a lot of deferred maintenance to bring it up to today's merchandising standards," says John Hurley, director of real estate for Lazarus department stores. "We also conducted considerable evaluation of foot traffic patterns at the present location and determined that it was on the edge of the core retail area."<P>Rather than invest in a location that was economically undesirable, Lazarus decided to either move to a new location or pull out of the downtown market. The latter would have been Murphy's worst nightmare.<P>"From the outset, Mayor Murphy made it a priority to find a way to keep Lazarus in a downtown location," says Judy Kelly, the mayor's assistant. "His vision was to adopt the concept of retail anchors in a mall setting, and apply it to the retail district in downtown Pittsburgh."<P>In suburban malls, the large retailers draw the crowds and create the traffic that generates business for smaller retailers. The city was thinking the same way when it shoehorned Lazarus into the corner of Fifth Avenue and Wood Street. Lazarus didn't need much convincing. It also realized that building a new facility there would anchor the downtown retail district, along with Kaufmann's and Saks.<P>"We felt that there was great potential for the redevelopment of Fifth Avenue, particularly between our new location and Kaufmann's," says Lazarus' Hurley. "After careful analysis of foot traffic in the area, we also determined that portions of Wood Street, Smithfield and Forbes Avenue would accordingly benefit from redevelopment. Since this district already had some concentration of higher quality retailers, we felt that their added presence was also beneficial to our plans."<P>Mike Hendrickson, vice president of real estate firm Grubb & Ellis Co., agrees.<P>"With the addition of the Lazarus store, Pittsburgh's retail triangle has an opportunity to solidify itself in the retail marketplace," says Hendrickson. <P>One hitch did remain - the old Lazarus site. Remembering what happened with the closing of the Gimbels department store, which stood vacant for years, the city worked with Lazarus, Blue Cross and Oxford Development to get Blue Cross in the space.<P>The healthcare giant is maintaining its space at its Fifth Avenue Place headquarters and is occupying floors two through six and the mezzanine in the old Lazarus site, now called Penn Avenue Place. Oxford is seeking commercial and/or retail tenants for the ground level of the building.<P>"The building will undergo complete refurbishment so that it can accommodate nearly 600 new downtown employees, 400 of whom are  in completely new jobs," says Steve Leeper, an economic development manager for the city.  <P><B>Back on Wood Street</B><P>The city's work still wasn't nearly done. Crucial to any retail district is parking. The city was instrumental in helping Lazarus finalize plans for a 500-car subterranean parking garage for not only Lazarus' customers but those shopping at other area stores. The proposed garage will offer affordable short-term rates to those customers shopping within the district. <P>"We feel very strongly that for the new Lazarus location to be profitable we have to market this store beyond the downtown office workers," says Lazarus' Hurley. "While the business crowd is important to us, it by no means represents the majority of business that this store needs to remain competitive and profitable." <P>It needs shoppers from the suburbs, and Pittsburgh has one distinct factor that works in its favor in that regard. Unlike many other metropolitan areas, Pittsburgh's highway system funnels traffic toward downtown. In contrast, other cities with beltways channel traffic around, and in many cases, away from downtown.<P>"In many suburbs around the city, it's possible to drive in and out of the downtown area in 10 to 15 minutes," says Kelly, the mayor's aide.<P>But the suburban shoppers will have to want to come downtown in the first place. And that leads to even more work. One need only walk the retail corridor to see what needs to be done.<P>Streets are badly in need of resurfacing. The sidewalks - where they aren't cracked - are often uneven, the surfaces raised several inches from the ground due to weather changes. In other places the individual sidewalk panels don't match one another and are made of different materials. Garbage receptacles and garbage in general are another problem. Many of the receptacles overflow, and those that don't are in such bad shape that they look as if they might crumble at any moment. Everywhere, there seems to be an inordinate amount of litter.<P>The Pittsburgh Downtown Partnership has hired workers to sweep the streets and is in the process of purchasing new garbage containers for the area. That will help cosmetically.<P>On other fronts, the downtown partnership is working with Port Authority Transit to redesign bus routes, and with the city to develop an ordinance that addresses aggressive panhandling  downtown.<P>Errol Frailey, president of the Downtown Partnership, strongly feels that with the positioning of Lazarus at Fifth and Wood, the city has demonstrated a serious commitment to upgrading that area.The city furthered that commitment by the inclusion, in the latest budget, of funds to restore  sidewalks, streets and lighting around the new Lazarus facility.<P>"When you sit in a mall, the furniture in the mall is geared so customers look at stores," says Robert Hurley of the city. "It enhances the quality of the location, and stores want to be there. We want to create an ambiance that lends itself to the same thing."<P>The Downtown Partnership also is working with the city to possibly reroute bus and automobile traffic away from Fifth Avenue.<P>"One of the problems we first addressed was that Fifth Avenue seems to have an inordinate amount of bus traffic considering the narrow width of the street and its sidewalks," says Frailey. "Our objective became to find a way to create a better balance of traffic in the area and possibly use other streets to handle some of the load."<P><B>Elsewhere on Wood Street</B><P>The obvious beneficiaries of this early development are those already in or near the retail corridor who have sweated out the lean times. On one end of Wood Street sits Point Park College. On the other end sits PNC Plaza. Once foot traffic increases in mid town, both stand to benefit.<P>Point Park is part of the redevelopment. The college, along with The Carnegie Library, recently purchased the Bank Center to develop into The Library Center. Located at the corner of Fourth and Wood, and opening sometime in the fall of this year, the Library Center will house the Carnegie's downtown business library, as well as Point Park's entire library collection. In addition, it will house a small theater that will be used to hold public events and lectures.<P>"Located in the retail district, the Library Center will attract library users and generate increased commercial activity," says Jim Hunter, interim president of Point Park College.<P>In the renovation of the Bank Center, Point Park and Carnegie Library were careful to preserve the original architecture of the structure.<P>"We wanted the Library Center to stand as an example of how an older structure can be utilized without sacrificing the building's architectural and historical significance," says Hunter.<P>Some businesses may be pushed out by redevelopment in the retail corridor, but they likely will get new space within the corridor.<P>"In addition, we're offering some low-cost financing incentives to retailers around the new Lazarus store who want to renovate their existing space," says the city's Leeper.<P>The Urban Redevelopment Authority has approved $1 million in renovation funds that can be made available to retailers.<P>The city and the Downtown Partnership maintain that only careful planning and a retail strategy will ensure that other retailers follow. What both the city and Lazarus hope to create is a viable retail district in Pittsburgh that effectively competes with the suburban mall alternatives within a 20-minute radius of the city. Planners offer one promise: The downtown retail corridor will be unique. <P>"We are going to determine what type of restaurant, store or entertainment facilities will be needed to best complement Lazarus and strengthen the position of downtown as a unique retail center," says Frailey of the Downtown Partnership. "We want to create something that's different from the suburban retail centers and from anything that Pittsburgh's had in the past in the downtown area."  <P>Lazarus is a key first step.            <P>
<P>






<hr>

