<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Features.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.Supplement3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>


<center><B><font size=+2>Not Here
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Can a Suburban Community<br>Halt Growth?<br>Cranberry Township is Giving<br>It a Shot</font></b><br>

<i>By Barbara Youngerman Meyer</i></center>
<hr>
There were farms with cows grazing in the meadows, a few small businesses and - within Cranberry's 25 square miles - a total population of about 11,000. <P>So on a typical Friday night, Ebeck could drive through his Butler County community to shop in Wexford without hitting one traffic light. But that trip isn't such a breeze anymore. From 1970 to 1990, Cranberry's population grew 200 percent, to about 33,000. New residences increased 354 percent and, as of 1991, 3.7 million square feet of retail, warehouse or office space was constructed.<P>As for Ebeck's Friday night drives? He has some company on the road. A recent township study shows that by the year 2000, weekly traffic volume will have increased 321 percent to 296,000 cars from the 70,275 counted in 1985. Ebeck doesn't necessarily mind. The more people who pass through Cranberry, the more people who might walk into his office for an eye examination.<P>"I'm in the people business," Ebeck says. "It's been good for my business."<P>But not all residents of Cranberry and neighboring communities are as happy. These communities, which once attracted home buyers because of their rustic charm, now resemble modern suburbia. <P>"Thirty years ago, I moved up here from the North Side [of Pittsburgh]," says Darryl Kirschner, who lives not far from Cranberry in Zelienople. "And where am I going to go now? To Canada?"<P><B>Stop the Growth</B><P>Many Cranberry residents have a collective message for developers who are pushing for more growth: not here.<P>Back in 1992, Cranberry Township held two public meetings to define the problem and listen to what residents had to say <P>"The community made it very clear that we must manage our growth," says township Manager Jerry Andree. "And it's not too late to do it." <P>Until recently, Cranberry had been laboring under an outdated development plan. Some liken it to driving 90 miles per hour in the fast lane, steering via the rearview mirror. Development was governed by regulations adopted in 1977, when it was thought the community would always be occupied by rural or low density residential properties. <P>Without new rules to control growth, developers covered almost 12 square miles with anything and everything. Shopping malls were designed with little regard to eye appeal. Much to the irritation of locals, an 80-acre parcel of land was allowed to become a giant auto auction site. <P>But last April, the zoning laws were changed - and are now the township's weapon against developers.<P>"Zoning is how we're going to make things better," Andree says. "For example, we passed legislation that requires 30 percent of a commercial lot to be devoted to green space. Things must look environmentally pleasing. Therenow have to be landscaped islands in the parking lots. And we won't allow wholesale cutting of hillsides anymore." <P>The new zoning laws control residential as well as commercial growth. New residential restrictions demand a minimum lot size of 1.25 acres, for instance. To further mollify people who believe their rural paradise has taken on the "Monroeville look," as some residents put it, Cranberry is building a second recreational park. However, it will be built on 128 acres now used as a horse farm. Gained will be an area with soccer and baseball fields, a swimming pool, picnic facilities and hiking trails. Gone is another bit of the township's rural character - just what the township cites as its major strength.<P><B>The Other Side</B><P>Although Cranberry has passed legislation to control its growth, there are people who resent being restricted in any way.<P>"And, believe me," says Daniel Santoro, Cranberry's Director of Code Administration, "these people abound. They don't want anyone telling them how they can or cannot develop a piece of land. They consider it an infringement on their inalienable rights." <P>Plus, as Santoro adds, there's big bucks to be made. People can sell off just about any tract of land on Route 19 - the main artery running through Cranberry - for a sizable sum. Some don't care how the developer uses the land after its sold because they move out of the township.<P>And, because there's so much money to be made by developing property in Cranberry, the township is spending a chunk of its budget in court. If the township denies someone the right to develop a site in a certain way, the case ends up being litigated.  A developer will rarely go away quietly just because the township says no. <P>"The trend," says Chris Lochner, manager of Hampton Township in northern Allegheny County, "is to do whatever it takes to get a variance on a zoning regulation. Areas of growth, like Cranberry, are being bombarded by developers who won't be stopped. They go to court and, nine times out of 10, are granted whatever variance they need.<P>"Here in Hampton we tried to stop an amusement park being built in an area of the township that is already heavily congested on weekends. And we lost, despite the fact that we showed exiting roads just couldn't handle the anticipated flow of traffic. 'So what' the judge said to our problem. The law is on the side of whoever wants to develop the land."<P>Hampton does not want to stem all growth. In fact, Lochner admits that the township envies Cranberry to an extent because growth does carry with it many benefits. For one, it enhances the tax base of the municipality and other taxing bodies, such as a school district. It also creates jobs. And as optometrist Elmer Ebeck will tell you, it brings more customers into the businesses already located there.<P>But there's a point when growth goes too far, and Ross Township Commissioner Robert Raida says his community is one example.<P>You want to see the downside of growth firsthand? Raida says take a drive along McKnight Road. <P>"We are doing everything we can to discourage any more growth because we don't like the problems we have," Raida says. "We're spending one-third of our budget for public safety. That's about $3.5 million for police protection and other safety-related services. The more growth you have residentially and commercially, the more crime you have. That's not just true in Ross or Cranberry. It's what happens anywhere." <P>Ross Township discouraged Wal- Mart from building on land located at Babcock and McKnight.<P>"We just made it somewhat difficult for them and they went away," Raida says. "They didn't want the fuss, I guess. But people have the right to develop the land, and it's hard to fight it. Yes, Cranberry is spending a lot of its budget in court and I feel sorry for them. That's a heck of a way to spend your money." <P><B>Legal Fees</B><P>Andree, Cranberry's manager, concedes that the battle is an expensive one. But in the same breath, he says it is one worth fighting if that's what the residents want.<P>"We have successfully defended 95 percent of our cases," Andree says. "Yes, it's expensive to take these people on, but that won't stop us. We have a $5.8 million budget. We can cover any legal costs involved in protecting our community. We will not sign Cranberry's death warrant." <P>Because the township is under pressure to alleviate rather than compound its traffic congestion, it may rezone land surrounding Route 228. A 1 million-square-foot mall proposed for a site in that area might not make it beyond the planning stage if the land is rezoned for office use or multi-family development only. <P>Traffic studies show that a mall would add 22,000 cars a day to Route 228 - a mere two-lane highway where farm tractors often cruise at speeds approaching 15 miles per hour. However, mall developer J.J. Gumberg intends to continue with plans to build. Observers say the project will probably end up smaller than originally proposed, but, there may yet be another mall in Cranberry. Already in place are Cranberry Mall, the Wal-Mart plaza and several smaller shopping strips. <P>Business parks also are popping up here and there. For example, New Castle-based Penn Power is developing a 180-acre site in Cranberry Township. The land formerly belonged to Three Rivers Aluminum Company.<P>"We are always looking for new and innovative ways to build our business and our relationship with the community," says Penn Power spokesman JoeBobbey. <P>The utility company plans on developing the land for use by 15 to 20 small to medium-sized businesses. GMAC already has committed to the site, which is located between the Pennsylvania Turnpike and Route 19. Penn Power is eliminating a sharp bend from an access road to make the property more attractive.<P>"The excellent location - just 20 minutes from Pittsburgh and in the middle of a major U.S. market region - makes it especially appealing to businesses like small manufacturers, suppliers and distributors, and even information technology companies, " says Randal J. Coleman, economic development consultant at Penn Power. "We consider this venture a new model of cooperation between a community, a local electric company and businesses."<P>Penn Power is a subsidiary of Ohio Edison and provides electric service to more than 140,000 customers in Butler, Allegheny, Crawford, Lawrence and Mercer counties.                               <P><B>Natural Growth</B><P>Most of Cranberry's problems are a natural outgrowth of residential development. To escape high property taxes in Allegheny County with less than a 30-minute commute to downtown Pittsburgh, people are moving to Cranberry in droves. Their property tax rate is half that of Allegheny County communities.  Some talk of savings thousands annually.<P>These new residents, says Chamber of Commerce Director Melissa Corbin-Nelson, want easy access to shopping, banking and a quick bite after work with the kids. It seems that, if Cranberry appears overdeveloped, the only place to put any blame is on the residents themselves. <P>Maybe some of the wealthier and older residents didn't get exactly what they wanted in the way of upscale shops and fine dining. But the typical family has most of its daily needs met in Cranberry, says Corbin-Nelson. The schools and pre-schools are good, she says, and the average family has children ranging from infancy to 10 years of age. Headed by adults aged 25 to 40, this family lives in a new three-bedroom house valued between $115,000 and $125,000. <P>Corbin-Nelson says many neighborhoods, like her own, are comprised of out-of-state people. Her neighbors are young and on the move, often changing jobs or transferred from place to place as part of a management training program.<P>Mike Long, a senior merchandising manager for JC Penney, moved to Cranberry with his family two years ago from Parkersburg, W.V.  Before that, he lived in Columbus, Ohio.<P>"What my wife and I like is that there are lots of people here our age, in their mid 30s, with kids the same age as ours. It's easy to make friends," he says. <P>It does take him five minutes just to get out of his housing development in the morning, and he says he doesn't like that very much. Nor is he happy about thepossibility of more shopping malls moving in.<P>"I work down at Ross Park Mall, and so I'm aware of what big shopping malls bring with them. Crime. Auto thefts. Shady characters. No, I wouldn't like to see that here where I live," Long says. But Cranberry was bound to happen sooner or later.<P><B>At the Crossroads</B><P>Henry Nutbrown, district engineer for the Pennsylvania Department of Transportation for 30 years, calls Cranberry "the crossroads of western Pennsylvania."<P>Running through it are Routes 228 and 19 and Interstates 79 and 76, which is the Pennsylvania Turnpike. "So it was inevitable that Cranberry became what it is today," Nutbrown says. <P>Many see the completion of Interstate 279, which links Pittsburgh with I-79 and, thus, with Cranberry, as the prime catalyst for Cranberry's enormous development. But Nutbrown disagrees.  "Construction of I-279 was just the icing on the cake," he says.  "Even before that road was completed in 1989, Cranberry was growing. If any road is primarily responsible, it's I-79. And both I-79 and I-279 are highways that began to be planned at least 30 years ago." <P>But could anyone have predicted 30 years ago what these roads would trigger? They were, according to Nutbrown, initiated as part of an interstate highway system for efficiently mobilizing armies and missiles throughout the country in case of war. On an everyday basis, they are used to mobilize people from home to work. <P>"Right now," says Nutbrown of I-79 and I-279, "the Parkway North has the second highest volume of traffic in the area, with the Parkway West having the highest. I-279 around the North Side gets 100,000 vehicles each day, according to 1995 figures." <P>Penn Dot's figures tell that "there's a lot of growth happening out north. Everywhere north. But what we are considering for Cranberry specifically," Nutbrown says, "is connecting I-279 and the turnpike to cut down on traffic congestion." <P>Nutbrown has heard complaints that this plan would turn Cranberry into a ghost town, but he doesn't think there's a chance of that happening. Cranberry, like most communities north of Pittsburgh - especially those in Butler County - are experiencing a rapid influx of people.<P>And that brings us back to Darryl Kirschner, the Zelienople resident,  who doesn't know if he'll stay around to help fight the growth. He wishes the trees were growing, not the population.  After all, it's the rural setting that attracted him to Butler County from Pittsburgh's North Side a few years back.<P>Not far from Kirschner's home, there are still pockets of wild turkey left in the woods, along with deer and a few bears. <P>"But it just isn't what it used to be," laments Kirschner. "Just in the past few years, all these peoplehave been coming in here and scaring the animals away. I don't know how far north I'm going to have to go this time."              n<P>Once again the group from FORE Systems is breaking ground; this time, literally.<P>To accommodate FORE Systems' continuing growth, the company is currently undertaking the largest commercial building project in Allegheny County in five years. The new headquarters campus will be located north of Pittsburgh, in Marshall Township.<P>"The buildings will be like none that exist in the area," says William Bates, director of facilities for FORE Systems. "We believe the unique new headquarters will contribute to the growing visibility of FORE, while improving recruitment and creating a sense of identity for employees."<P>State, county and local government joined forces in an effort to lock in FORE's headquarters at the Marshall Township location. A low-interest, $10 million loan from Allegheny County's Economic Development Fund provided 25 percent of the necessary funding. Further funding was arranged by Mellon Bank of Pittsburgh.<P>Bates says the buildings are being designed to capture the dynamic, creative spirit of FORE Systems and its unique image in the computer industry. The new facility will be able to accommodate extensive growth.<P>Six years ago, four professors and researchers from Carnegie Mellon University combined their talents to form the company that now is the worldwide leader in the design, development, manufacture and sale of high performance local area networking products based on ATM technology. FORE Systems has since grown to more than 540 employees. <P>FORE offers the most extensive ATM local area network product line available today and has delivered ATM solutions to more than 800 customers, including Fortune 500 companies, telecommunications service providers, government agencies, research institutions and universities.<P><P>Duquesne University promised to provide a unique atmosphere when it affiliated with the former Vincentian High School to form Vincentian Academy-Duquesne University. Six months into the first school year, students in the academy program are conversing in Spanish via electronic mail with Spanish-speaking undergraduates at Duquesne. <P>There are some other unique characteristics of the program. For one, the school year lasts 205 days, 25 more than the traditional 180.<P>Last August, the 27 members of the class of 1999 spent 15 days in  a summer session that counted against the 205 days.<P>"They were very attentive and were interested in their studies and helped each other out. In fact, they came to me on a few occasions saying they wanted more work to do and wanted to do things in addition to those listed in the curriculum," says Derek Whordley, president of VADU and dean of Duquesne's school of education.<P>Students in the academy program attend classes in the same facility as Vincentian High School students, but follow an international baccalaureate program. Duquesne says the program is the first university-affiliated high school tooffer an IB program in the world.<P>The IB diploma is regarded as a mark of excellence by universities around the world. A student who has successfully passed IB exams is admitted as a second year student qualifying for academic scholarships at virtually any college or university.<P>"We have the opportunity to create the most interesting international baccalaureate school in the world," Whordley says. "I think this school can put some goodness in the world of education that wasn't there before."<h2> Butler County's Mainstay: ServiStar</h2>It takes tools to build something. A company known for tools, ServiStar, is helping youngsters build their futures.<P>Headquartered in Butler, Pa., ServiStar's name has been associated with thousands of independent retailers specializing in hardware, lumber, home center, rental, garden and automotive sales. This $1.8 billion member-owned company has stores located in 49 states and 40 countries. In 1995, ServiStar achieved record sales of $1.8 billion, including a record $766 million in lumber/building material.<P>It also continued its Tools for Tomorrow program, under which independent ServiStar retailers support vocational education programs in their respective communities. The retailers lend tools to vo-tech programs for use in instruction or on community projects. They also conduct how-to clinics, offer discounts tovo-tech students and teachers, and donate ServiStar coupon calendars that student groups can sell for fund-raising purposes.<P>Another facet of the program recognizes at the local, state and national levels vo-tech students who set standards of excellence in vocational and academic skills while displaying commitment to their communities. <P>"The 15 million students enrolled in vo-tech programs today represent the backbone of tomorrow's work force," says ServiStar CEO Paul E. Pentz. "ServiStar is pleased to take a proactive role in promoting the importance of quality vocational education and in recognizing students and teachers who achieve success on a daily basis." <h2> Improving Healthcare in Butler County</h2>Instead of merely mimicking the national debate on the delivery of healthcare, Butler County is taking action to improve residents' health.<P>A year and a half ago, the Butler County Community Health Advisory Council was formed with a simple mission: to improve the health of the people of Butler County by measurably reducing incidence of disease and encouraging healthy lifestyles. The group includes 18 members from all geographic and professional reaches of the county and was one of three areas awarded a $15,000 grant from the Voluntary Hospital Association to assess the health of the community.<P>Through this comprehensive survey, the group has identified 13 community health priorities and is now convening task forces of providers and citizens to work in each area. The top three issues in Butler County are heart disease, unintentional injuries and cancer.<P>"We are asking people to bring their expertise and resources to the table," says Stephanie Rathfon, community health facilita tor. "We want to develop action plans for continuum of care in each of these areas, to see how providers can collaborate and coordinate services. We hope to take out duplication in services and fill in the gaps so we have a smooth system."<P>The 10 other identified issue areas include maternal and infant health, immunization and infectious diseases, HIV and sexually transmitted diseases, diabetes, mental health and geriatric services. In those, the group initially plans to increase education and awareness.<P>Rathfon also hopes that the strategy of creating initiatives with existing resources (110 providers, including hospitals, social service agencies and physicians, have been asked to man the task forces) will decrease the need for intensive funding as the project continues. To date, the group has spent $75,000 to amass the information needed to launch the effort - only $15,000 of which was covered by the grant. The rest has been funded by Butler County Memorial Hospital.<P>"We're the sole commu nity provider, and from our perspective, the continued support of the community health assessment is part of our mission. That's why we're here, to improve the health of the community," says Carol Dietrich, chief operating officer of Butler County Memorial. <P>Dietrich sees increasing the community's health as a good investment for the future, not just for the community, but for the hospital. A healthier population uses less healthcare - so resources can be concentrated on the cases requiring intervention. And that bodes well for a future which, in light of healthcare reform, looks to be getting leaner and leaner.<P>
<P>






