<center><B><font size=+2>To Peek or Not?
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>If Employers Monitor Workplace E-Mail,<br>Are They Invading a Worker's Privacy?</font></b><br>

<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>
<hr>
Supervisors at a California bank found something surprising when they randomly checked an employee's electronic mail. Some messages sent and received by the employee disclosed that the employee was moonlighting as a stripper. The bank terminated the employee, who subsequently sued the bank for invasion of privacy.<P>The bank successfully defended  its action, convincing a judge that the e-mail system belonged to the bank and could legitimately be monitored. Nevertheless, the case shows how an  e-mail system can expose employers  to workplace disputes over what           is private, and potentially lead to  costly litigation.<P>"Most employers are being pretty cautious about it," says Robert McTiernan, an attorney with Tucker Arensberg in Pittsburgh. He advises clients to avoid monitoring e-mail unless they believe it is being misused.<P>"It's an issue that also involves employee morale," McTiernan says. "Employers want to build a sense of trust with employees."<P>Today, 90 percent of all companies with more than 1,000 employees use  e-mail. Surveys show there are close to 20 million e-mail users in the United States today, and projections approach 40 million users nationwide by the year 2000. These 40 million e-mail users will be sending an estimated 60 billion messages annually. <P><B>An E-mail Policy</B><P>Attorney Jeffrey A. Van Doren of Cohen & Grigsby in Pittsburgh says a critical step for the employer - whether they intend to monitor or not - is clearly communicating an e-mail policy. Tell the employees up front what they can expect and what is expected of them.<P>"A wide gap exists between what an employer considers its rights to access and what employees deem an invasion of privacy," Van Doren says. "Most employees tend to believe their e-mail, like U.S. Mail, is private. Thus, employees who discover that their employer has been monitoring their  e-mail messages may believe their right to privacy has been violated.<P>"The Fourth Amendment protects privacy from government intrusion and does not normally apply to private employers, but there is a common law right of privacy that may apply," Van Doren says.<P>Invasion of privacy is relatively difficult to prove.  A plaintiff must show that there was an expectation of privacy and that the employer engaged in highly objectionable monitoring. In some states, the plaintiff must also show that the employer disseminated the information or data received from the monitoring.<P>By defining a clear and concise policy up front, the employer can limit the possibility that it will be held liable for invasion of privacy later. Some employers go as far as having employees sign consent forms before they are permitted to use the e-mail system.<P>"The consent forms are great, because you have taken away that expectation of privacy," says Gregory Miller, an attorney with Buchanan Ingersoll in Pittsburgh.<P>As far as a policy is concerned,   the American Law Institute recom-mends including the following as a starting point:<P>1. An e-mail system is company property and should be used for company purposes only.<P>2. Employees should disclose information or messages from an        e-mail system only to authorized employees.<P>3. The company reserves the right to monitor the e-mail system in order to assure that its property is being used for business purposes only.<P>4. Employees do not have a personal privacy right in any matter created, received or sent from an         e-mail system.<P>5. Nothing should be entered into the e-mail system without a good reason.<P>ALI also says an appropriate program for monitoring an employer's system should be disclosed in detail   to employees.<P>The first point - restricting        e-mail use to company purposes - is critical in light of what happened to one company in a recent National Labor Relations Board case. The employer had allowed employees to use e-mail for a variety of matters with little relevance to the business itself. But when the employees started using it to distribute labor union information, the employer stepped in and put a halt to it.<P>When the employees complained to the NLRB, an administrative law judge sided with them. The judge ruled that the employer discrim-inatorily prohibited bargaining unit employees from using the e-mail system for distributing union information. <P>In addition to the points listed above, Van Doren says managers should consider other variables when developing the policy. Is there union representation that could affect acceptance of the policy? Is bargaining necessary before a policy can be implemented for union employees? How will the employees be informed of the policy?<P><B>The Smoking Gun</B><P>Employers should also be aware that e-mail is discoverable during litigation. Some have learned the hard way, including one employer that was sued by a terminated employee. The employer characterized the firing as an economic layoff, but was sunk by an internal e-mail that characterized the employee as a "bitch" and talked of "getting rid" of her.<P>"People use e-mail like it is the phone," says Buchanan Ingersoll's Miller. "They write something, send it, then hit delete. They think it is gone, but it is not. That stuff is all backed up. And it's just deadly."<P>Relatively few employers have      e-mail monitoring policies in place, and there's a split of opinion as to whether e-mail monitoring should be routine. <P>There are times when monitoring is absolutely necessary. An example is when an employee is using the e-mail system to sexually harass a coworker. If the problem is brought to the attention of the employer and the employer allows the harassment to continue, the company could be held liable for subjecting the complaining employee to a hostile work environment.<P>There's also the chance that some employees may use the e-mail system as a means to leak company secrets. In 1992, Borland International sued industry rival Symantec Corp., accusing it of stealing trade secrets. Borland contended that one of its former executives sent confidential trade secrets to Symantec while working for Borland. The executive subsequently took employment with Symantec.<P>Miller says professionals, who many times deal with proprietary information, are more apt to recognize the importance of e-mail monitoring and accept it. In other industries or situations, monitoring might outrage employees.<P>McTiernan, the Tucker Arensberg attorney, says in those instances you must consider the detriment of implying mistrust to employees.<P>"The greater risk is the damage to morale and the effectiveness in the organization," says McTiernan. "You can have e-mail policies, but the advantage to the employer of routine monitoring is limited in comparison to detriment. If something is brought to your attention about misuse of anything in the company, you are certainly allowed to investigate. But monitoring everything on an ongoing basis? That would be a risk."                <h2>About Wilder, Mahood & Crenney</h2>	Wilder, Mahood & Crenney is a small law firm which provides personal individualized services to a limited number of clients in divorce cases and related matters. Since 1978, the lawyers of Wilder, Mahood & Crenney have represented a broad range of business and professional people and their spouses in complex divorce litigation in Pittsburgh and neighboring counties. WM&C limits its practice to matrimonial law, including divorce, support, paternity, property matters and custody at    trial and appellate levels. The firm has developed a method of handling complex divorce cases which  utilizes the collective expertise of  the firm for the benefit of each individual client. Wilder, Mahood & Crenney lawyers are knowledge- able and experienced in all areas of family law.<P>	<P>	Members of the firm teach family law to other lawyers in continuing legal education programs on both the local and national level. The firm is represented on the law faculties of the University of Pittsburgh and Duquesne University as well as the Robert Morris College Paralegal Program. The first Pittsburgh lawyer to be certified as a matrimonial arbitrator by the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers as well as the first Pittsburgh lawyer to be elected a Fellow of the International Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers are members of WM&C.<P>	Members of the firm lecture and write extensively on family law and professional ethics issues for professional publications and periodicals. The treatise, Pennsyl-vania Family Law Practice and Procedure, was authored by a member of the firm. The firm's lawyers hold leadership positions in <LI>the American Bar Association, the <LI>Pennsylvania Bar Association, the <LI>Allegheny County Bar Association and numerous community organizations. <LI>The WM&C paralegal staff is active in the Pittsburgh Paralegal Association.<LI>	WM&C lawyers have been elected Fellows of the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers, the American College of Family Trial Lawyers, the American Bar Foundation and the Pennsylvania Bar Foundation. WM&C has been represented in every edition of the Best Lawyers in America.<P><P>The Lawyers<P>Joanne Ross Wilder<br>James E. Mahood<br>Lynne Nordenberg Crenney<br>Lisa L. DeCecco<br>Susan Fagan-Weber<br>Thomas J. Campbell<br>Ann M. Funge<P><P>The Legal Assistants<br>Belinda L. Hall<br>Shauna A. Morimoto<h2>Legal Services Directory Listing</h2><p>Firms<h2> Frank,Bails, Kirk, Murcko & Toal, P.C.</h2>33rd Floor Gulf Tower, 707 Grant Street<br>Pittsburgh, PA  15219<br>Telephone: (412) 471-3000<br>Fax: (412) 471-7351<P><P>Selected areas of practice: Divorce, pre-nuptial agreements, estate planing, labor & employment law, land use law, real estate tax assessment appeals, innovative public & private financing, workers' compensation, personal injury, general litigation and zoning matters.<h2>Gefsky and Lehman, P.C.</h2><P>Twenty-third Floor<br>One PPG Place<br>Pittsburgh, PA  15222<br>Telephone: (412) 391-2727<br>Fax: (412) 291-1685<P><P>Corporate law firm emphasizing the organization, growth and financing of business ventures; business mergers, acquisitions, sales, joint ventures, and technology arrangements; tax, estate and succession planning; commerical real estate ventures.<h2>Law Offices of Harry F. Klodowski </h2>Harry F. Klodowski, Esq.<br>Linda S. Somerville, Esq.<br>Suite 3321 Grant Building<br>330 Grant Street<br>Pittsburgh, PA  15219<br>Telephone: (412) 281-7997<br>Fax: (412)281-4212<br>Internet: 74651.525 @ Compuserve.com<P><P>Selected Areas of Practice: Environmental law - Property contamination and real estate transactions; site assessment and remediation; air, water and waste permitting and compliance litigation; business law; administrative and civil litigation.<h2>Swensen Perer & Johnson</h2>2710 Two PNC Plaza<br>Pittsburgh, PA  15222<br>Telephone: (412) 281-1970<br>Fax: (412)281-2808<br><P>Swensen Perer & Johnson is a specialezed litigation firm founded in 1980 by Jan C. Swensen and Alan H. Perer. J. Alan Johnson joined the firm in 1990.<P>J. Alan Johnson had previously served as the U.S. Attorney for Western Pennsylvania from 1981-1989. He currently practices the defense of white collar crime cases, including fraud, financial transactions, and regulatory matters. He has also provided discreet and comprehensive internal investigations for various public and non-profit corporations. Mr. Johnson's early involvement in potential criminal investigations has enabled him to obtain excellent results for his clients.<h2>Carpenter Legal Search</h2>One Oxford Centre, Suite 1500<br>301 Grant Street<br>Pittsburgh, PA  15219-1417<br>Telephone: (412) 255-3770<br>Fax: (412) 255-3780<P>Providing legal search and consulting services to corporate legal departments and prominent regional and national firms.  This includes General Counsel, Assistant and Associate General Counsel attorneys, partner and associate level attorneys, law firm mergers and the opening of branch offices.

