<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Supplement2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>A Business Purpose
</font><BR>
<font size=+1> We Must Preserve Our Strong Cultural Amenities 
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<P>


There's a laundry list of reasons why businesses do not want to locate in our region: Clean Air Act regulations, the tax burden, workers' compensation ... the list goes on.
<P>
Are our local businesses trying to add to that list? Maybe so.
<P>
One of our region's strengths is its strong cultural amenities -- from the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra to the various theater offerings. Yet at a time when national funding for the arts is threatened or declining, the arts community here also is running into resistance from the corporate world.
<P>
The days when corporations funded the arts because they felt it was   their civic duty to do so are long over for some corporations. Some have been ravaged by lean times. Others have simply changed their philosophy on giving.
<P>
Call it bad timing. The arts -- perennially on the financial edge -- are facing some of their most challenging years in recent history. Federal funding for the National Endowment for the Arts is expected to decrease from   $97.5 million in fiscal year 1996 to zero in fiscal year 1999. 
<P>
As this magazine pointed out last month, many corporations these days demand something in return for their sponsorship dollars: visibility. That is not necessarily bad, as long as what they demand remains in line with what they give. 
<P>
Unfortunately, the number of large corporations in this region that sponsor the arts has dwindled. Many have simply left the city and taken their sponsorship dollars with them. One example is Gulf Oil, for years a major sponsor of the arts in Pittsburgh.
<P>
Other corporations that remain  in the area are led, in some cases, by CEOs with no connection to the region and with loyalty only to shareholders. They simply de-emphasize their company's philanthropic interests. Some have no interest in sitting on cultural boards. They have limited interest in permitting other members of their management team to become involved in      the arts.
<P>
It gets worse. The arts community reports a disturbing trend among smaller firms that were born here, grew here, but simply have shown little to no interest in supporting the arts. These are the types of firms that will spur growth in the region. These are the firms we need to support the arts.
<P>
What many fail to realize is the importance the arts hold from a business sense. The arts are much more than black-tie events or photos in the society column. They can serve as motivation for companies to want to do business here. They can serve as motivation for qualified employees to want to live and work here. The arts make the community a place where people want to live. Tony Crumbley, who works for the Charlotte 
<P>
Chamber of Commerce and tries to lure businesses to that region, has little good to say about western Pennsylvania. But when pressed, Crumbley lists our strong cultural amenities as a plus. He's right.
<P>
And as former Harvard Business Review editor Rosabeth Moss Kanter pointed out during her September speech in Pittsburgh, "The final deciding factor in whether a company is going to locate its corporate headquarters in a city is the question of whether top management wants to live there."
<P>
Ironically, one of the nation's greatest backers of the arts -- Philip Morris -- is one that repeatedly has come under attack of late because of its tobacco business. Philip Morris. The tobacco giant donate<P>s 1 percent of its domestic pretax earnings annually to charitable causes. Of its total charitable contributions, 30 percent goes to the arts, as compared with an average of 11 percent for U.S. businesses.
<P>
So if the quality of arts in this region falls due to a lack of support, you can add it to the list of reasons for corporations to stay away. Jot it down right under workers' compensation and high taxes.
<P>
Preserving the arts in this region is crucial to economic growth. Come on corporate Pittsburgh -- from high tech to high finance -- ante up. If a shareholder asks what you are doing with profits, tell them you are investing them. You will be.              


<hr>

