<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><FONT SIZE=+2>Women's Work Redefined 
</FONT SIZE><BR>
<font size=+1>It's Time for More Women to Try the Entrepreneurial Route</font>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b><P>



 
In this region, "women's work" is never done because women never do "their work."  
<P>
Nationwide, women are starting businesses at twice the rate of men.  Not here.  Women-owned businesses employ more people in the United States than all of the Fortune 500 companies employ worldwide.  Yet, only     7 percent of local women-owned businesses surveyed in a recently released Duquesne University study reported payrolls totaling over $500,000 in 1994.
<P>
In fact, 41 percent of women-owned businesses in the Pittsburgh area employ no one other than the woman business owner.  A survey of National Association of Women Business Owners members indicates only 16 percent of their members do not employ anyone other than the business owner.  This striking contrast reveals the differing plight of the Pittsburgh woman business owner  versus her counterparts elsewhere.
<P>
A more accurate barometer of business success -- gross sales -- presents an even bleaker picture.  The percentage of women-owned businesses in the Pittsburgh area reporting 1994 earnings less than $250,000 is almost twice the national percentage.  
<P>
Most women blame the discriminatory practices of men for women's also-ran status within the business community. I disagree.
<P>
I believe that women's lack of support for other women and generally myopic perceptions of a woman's role are much more stifling than men's attitudes or actions toward women.  
<P>
Women don't even support other women here when money isn't involved.  Take the ballot box for example.  Pennsylvania ranks 44th out of 50 states in the percentage of women in our state legislature.  And consider the lack of support for commissioner candidate Colleen Vuono. Women's attitudes about themselves become a self fulfilling prophecy in this area.
<P>
Women here must unleash the tremendous latent capacity which lies within themselves. Pittsburgh cannot afford to have over half its population underperforming.  In many ways, the region's future economic vitality depends on women's ability to obliterate the outmoded paradigms establishing their expected levels of substandard performance. Our women are close to last when compared to other women across the country.  If the region is to prosper, women must get their act together.  This is what I call "women's work."


<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

