<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>The True Enemy
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>A Reluctance to Think Regionally
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Is What Really Holds Us Back</FONT>
 <i>By Marc Jampole
</b></i>

<HR>







<P>
It's no secret anymore that western Pennsylvania is in economic  trouble. While nearby cities such as Columbus, Baltimore and Philadelphia are enjoying economic renaissances, the Pittsburgh area continues to        lose jobs, headquarters offices and   businesses. 
<P>Be it at a cocktail party or business meeting or in the news media, when the hand-wringing stops, the blaming begins. And many people condemn the usual culprits -- labor and taxes. Now, as a business owner who pores over spreadsheets late at night, I can say it's always easy to come to the conclusion that if it only paid fewer taxes or paid employees less, the business would be more profitable.
<P>The problem with that kind of thinking for any business is that you could theoretically reduce your expenses to nothing and still make nothing if you have no customers. 
<P>Instead of dreaming of the proverbial free lunch of low taxes and cheap labor, let's look at what we get for our money.
<P>Labor is an easy issue to deal with, because the facts are so striking,  if underreported. All government research indicates that for virtually every job classification, Pittsburgh has lower wage rates than Cleveland, Philadelphia, Raleigh and San Diego, as well as Los Angeles, New York and Washington, D.C. No study has ever indicated that Pittsburgh labor is less productive. In fact, we always point with pride to our work ethic. With so many fine universities and colleges and many more post-secondary training opportunities than Columbus or Cleveland, it's clear that the workforce in western Pennsylvania is usually a bargain for employers.
<P>The issue of taxation is more complicated, because we do have high taxes in Allegheny County. There really is no such thing as a free lunch, so let's ask the question, what kind of lunch are we getting for our tax money?
<P>Here are some "dishes" that our taxes in Allegheny County pay for:
l 	130 municipal governments.
l	More than 40 school districts.
l	Partial or complete funding for more 	than 40 organizations engaged in 		economic development.
<P>Because we are paying for this duplication of administration, there is less money available for things we really need, such as improved mass transit, county-wide 911 service and classroom improvements. This duplication also leads to competition within the region, for example, between school districts for residents and between economic development groups for funding. This duplication of effort and competition for limited funding has hampered Allegheny County since World War II. Meanwhile, across the nation, one metropolitan area after another has embraced regionalism, and thrived. Examples include Baltimore, Columbus, Milwaukee, Charlotte, Minneapolis-St. Paul and Portland, Ore. -- all growing areas about the same size as Pittsburgh or smaller.
<P>For the business owner or executive looking to expand or invest in Allegheny County, the abundance of local entities is confusing and expensive. Take the hypothetical example of a national chain that wants to place stores in three or four locations in Allegheny County. There is no one place to turn for help in determining the best locations, because every one of the economic development groups and municipalities are in it for themselves.
<P>Once locations are selected, the chain will likely have to approach a different zoning board for each location. A handful of residents will likely oppose the development because of the phenomenon of Nimbyism (not in my backyard). There is Nimbyism everywhere, and often opponents of a development come up with good improvements. But because our region is so fragmented, the chain has to negotiate with many groups and municipalities, not one or two, about their site plans. And the Nimbys end up having a greater say in Allegheny County than elsewhere, simply because their voices can speak louder and longer in a municipality of 10,000 or 20,000 than they ever would in a broader region.  
<P>Allegheny County is moving slowly towards taking a more regional approach to our economy. Our regional asset tax has been a good first step. Allegheny County and the city of Pittsburgh are doing much more together, such as training police and collecting delinquent taxes. But these steps are only the beginning of what it will take for Pittsburgh to be able to compete with Columbus or Baltimore in the future.
<P>People naturally fear change, and the fears associated with regionalism, such as losing control and civic iden-tity, are real. 
<P>But we should fear more Pittsburgh becoming the Balkans of America -- a backward, fragmented region with a relatively low standard of living, a declining economy and constant infighting.                                 n
<P>Marc Jampole is president of Jampole Communications Inc., a Pittsburgh public relations agency.

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

<ADDRESS><h5>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <a href="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments or suggestions?</a><br>
&#169  Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
