Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:51:04 GMT
Content-length: 7289
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>
</i></b>
<h2>We Are Here to Stay</h2>
Reporters from the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette called Executive Report twice on Nov. 9, asking Publisher Linda Dickerson and Editor-in-Chief Jim Urban about rumors that the magazine was shutting down.
<P>
Are they true? No. Was management at ER surprised by the rumors? Not at all.
<P>
"We were the subject of similar but equally untrue rumors two years ago," Dickerson explains. "It's a cut-throat tactic used by the publications that compete with us for advertising dollars, and frankly, it troubles me. November is a month when advertisers are deciding how they will spend their money in next year's budget. If our competitors convince advertisers that ER won't be around, that helps our competitors' position. 
<P>
"At ER, we don't unjustifiably attack our competition," Dickerson adds. "We attack the problems facing this region and try to come up with solutions."
<P>
Dickerson, who has been publisher of ER for 14 years and is well entrenched in Pittsburgh's corporate community, says ER has expanded its coverage of business in recent months. She says since Urban took over the editorial department in June, the magazine has added monthly coverage of issues related to healthcare, education and small business while also adding restaurant reviews, travel features, a monthly look at legislative happenings in Harrisburg and a question & answer with a prominent business person. The magazine also was graphically redesigned.
<P>
"Our October issue, with 88 pages, was one of the thickest we've ever published," Dickerson says. "We are projecting growth in a down market."
<P>
ER was investigating the rumors in an effort to determine the source. Patrick 
<P>
Wood, associate publisher, says the magazine will pursue legal action if the source is pinpointed.
<P>
Under common tort law, a corporation has been defamed if a statement made by another tends to prejudice the corporation in the course of business or if the statement deters others from dealing with that corporation. Remedies under tort law include compensation for any lost business.
<P>
"We're not necessarily concerned about money," Wood says. "To us, it's the principle."
<P>
As for the rumors? The most ridiculous version had Dickerson moving to Florida. The publisher is heading south, but only for a few weeks as she benchmarks our region against those that are thriving in the South. Look for a report on her findings in early 1996.
<HR>
<h2>What Color is the Sky in  Your World?</h2>

Blue? Or is it "cornflower"? The trendy color gurus have gotten their hands on our Crayolas, and have turned color into a marketing tool.
<P>
Though for many, purple may be a lot less confusing than "eggplant" or "aubergine," consumers seem to like the trendy names. One paint company that changed the name of its "off-white" paint to "antique silk" doubled its sales, according to Bob Cooper, a principal with Cooper Marketing Group in Oak Park, Ill., in an interview with American Demographics.
<P>
Cooper, who annually asks 5,000 adults their color preferences for an array of products, has grouped consumers into three groups: Color Forwards are willing to go for new and daring colors; Color Prudents wait for a color to come in before they try it, and Color Loyals stick to the tried and true. Marketers, he says, usually target the Color Prudents.
<P>
They are nothing if not predictable. A 1994-95 research study done by the Pantone Color Institute in New Jersey showed that Americans continue to favor blue above all other colors, but that greens are up and coming. Orange is passe. Leatrice Eiseman, Pantone's director, is responsible for many of the names with which colors have been rechristened, and says giving a color a name gives it romance and panache. Guess she'd approve of the "apricot whisper" just rolled on some of our living room walls. It's all ivory to us.

<HR>

<h2>A Growing Epidemic</h2>

Journalists, secretaries, attorneys, computer programmers, cashiers. The list of working Americans who are slowed by repetitive motion injury grows longer every day. The Bureau of Labor Statistics confirms that "cumulative trauma disorders," including carpel tunnel syndrome, are the fastest growing occupational illnesses.
<P>
The numbers are numbing: Statistics show the number of new cumulative trauma or repetitive stress injuries has more than doubled, from 147,000 in 1989 to 302,000 in 1993, the most recent year for which statistics were available. An increasing number of the injuries occur in the white-collar service sector.
<P>
Experts say over 50 percent of the work force will have some sort of repetitive motion injury by the year 2000. Some past claims have run up to $300,000 for employers, pushing total claims past $20 billion annually nationwide.
<P>
For employers, the cost moves well beyond the workers' compensation or disability costs. Injuries erode the bottom line in other ways, such as productivity decreases and increases in the cost of hiring and training additional personnel.
<P>
Despite the increases in injuries, keyboard manufacturers have fared well in products liability lawsuits, including a New York jury's verdict this summer in favor of IBM and NCR. With juries saying the keyboards are not the problem, some employers now are trying harder than ever to determine the cause.
<P>
Some employers are testing a variety of keyboards to find out which is the safest. A recent entry into the market, the DataHand System, reduces repetitive keystroke motion up to 80 percent and finger travel to a fifth of that in a traditional    keyboard.
<P>
American Express Co. went a step further by conducting an ergonomics study, which included offering typing lessons to a control segment of its 150 customer-service representatives.

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

</BODY>
