<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Be the Show
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>Harry G's Mixes Good Food With a Tune
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<p>

<hr>

<P>

How would you like your picture, in lights, at Sixth and Penn? Not all of us will make the marquee at Heinz Hall, but anyone can get their picture on the wall at Harry G's. 
<P>Formerly Bravo Franco's, the restaurant, renovated by owner Harry Guidotti last summer, features a raised bar and an elegant, white-table clothed dining room. Reminiscent of New York meeting places (but a little cleaner), the small restaurant's walls are lined with photos of Guidotti and his patrons among an eclectic mix of prints. His goal is eventually to coat the walls completely with these photos and lose the animated Disney cels and Native American posters. 
<P>"My customers are the stars," says Guidotti. 
And keeping them in mind, the menu is engineered to serve appetites from demure to decadent -- and back again. We started with red roasted   peppers croustini, topped with a dry ricotta. The tastes were nice, but the croustini a little too thin and unremarkable. The wild mushroom soup, on the other hand, was herbally perfect, with a rich broth. 
<P>Following the appetizers, we moved on to salad -- the tomato and fresh mozzarella is good and fresh, with Greek olives and a light sprinkling of olive oil. The house salad is also good and fresh, with a light vinaigrette, nicely herbed and not too oily. 
<P>Harry G's has a big lunch menu, almost duplicated at dinner, but only at lunch you can get a grilled portabella mushroom sandwich. And you should. Rendolent with the flavors of the grill, the mushroom is juicy atop a soft roll, with red peppers. Skip the grilled salad: Though it's a tasty idea to grill a choice of swordfish, chicken, tuna or N.Y. strip steak over Caesar salad, the salad is drowned in oily dressing. The grilled yellow fin tuna wasn't particularly fresh, either. Though the side of bow-tie pasta with feta cheese and chopped tomato is odd to serve with a lunch salad, it was fresh and perfectly cooked.
<P>If you've a great appetite (we took a pregnant woman along), there's a hearty selection of pasta and entrees for lunch. She tried a Triolene of filet mignon: slices of filet coated with fresh herbs, romano and breadcrumbs, then sauteed. It was perfectly cooked and flavorful, a beautiful cut of beef. It was also served with a side of pasta, though a different one than the salad -- penne in runny tomato sauce. (Besides being pregnant, she is also Italian, and gave it the thumbs down.)
<P>The seafood pasta marinara was also in a rather runny sauce, though the tastes were well-balanced. And the seafood, like that in the salad, wasn't the freshest. Harry's new menu will expand the pasta menu to 16 sauces and seven types of pasta.
<P>The desserts were killer rich -- we tried the peanut butter and chocolate mousse cake, strawberry cheesecake and French apple streusel tart. All were delicious -- the cheesecake rich and creamy, the tart cinnamony (they should have served it hot). The mousse was so rich a spoonful would have done -- but of course it didn't. The cappucino was smooth and full, but the house coffee was the watery standard.
<P>Capitalizing on the location,  Harry G's plays up the show theme. During lunch, a piano player steadily tinkles tunes ranging from "The Wind Beneath My Wings" to Snoopy's theme song -- making it definitely not the place for a business-heavy luncheon, unless you're selling pianos. Every night starting at 7:30, Harry G's has cabaret singers, and, after the show, a curtain call menu, which Guidotti says attracts many stars from Heinz Hall and the Benedum Center.
<P>"We want to be the show before the show and the show after the show and the show when there is no show," says Guidotti, who in 1994 retired and sold his local Guidotti Marketing Group. "I like a party and here I can have one every night, and people pay to come."                                                  
<P>
Harry G's
613 Penn Avenue
Pittsburgh, Pa.  15222
412/642-6677

Hours: Monday - Friday, 11 a.m. to   11 p.m.
Saturdays: 4 p.m. to close,
Sundays: 4 p.m. to 9 p.m.

Lunch Prices:
Appetizers, Soups and Salads: $1.75 - $19.99
Main Salads and Sandwiches: $6.95 - $9.95
Pasta and Entrees: $6.95 - $15.95
