<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>



<P>
<B><I><font size=+2>Stephen G.Sheetz</font></I></B></center><P>


<HR>
<pre><b>
Name:		Stephen G.Sheetz
Age:            47
Personal:       Married, wife Nancy; two daughters, Megan and Nikki
                Lives in Altoona
Education:      BA, Penn State University
Last Vacation:  Stone Harbor, N.J., with family in August

</PRE></B>
<P>

<P>
About eight years ago, Steve Sheetz and his family were selling two hot dogs for 99 cents. They were also losing customers at an alarming rate.
<P>
Today, the Sheetz family sells gasoline, made-to-order hoagies and fresh pizza at their 175 convenience stores in four states. Some stores even have drive-thru windows. You need a gallon of milk and some hamburger buns? Don't even get out of the car.
<P>
The result: Sales since 1987 have jumped about 309 percent despite the fact that the number of Sheetz stores has only increased by 12. 
<P>
The Altoona-based company now employs 4,000 people, 3,400 of whom are full-time.
<P>
In October, Steve Sheetz handed over the presidency of the business to nephew Stanton R. Sheetz. Steve moved up to the position of chairman. He spoke with Executive Report Editor-in-Chief Jim Urban.
<P>

<P>
<b>Executive Report: Early in your tenure as president of Sheetz, sales were flat and customers were shopping elsewhere. Describe how you turned the business around.</b>
<P>
<b>Steve Sheetz:</b> We've got about 175 stores and our emphasis during the past seven years has shifted from number of stores to customer satisfaction. I'm sure a lot of people say that, but in 1988 we had 163 units. Today, seven years later, we are at 175, so we have only added 12 net units despite the fact that we've opened about 60 stores. We've sold several stores, replaced a bunch of stores and just flat-out closed several stores.
<P>
That all came about, I think, in about 1987, when our sales went flat and our customer counts were going backwards. We went from 1,400 customers a day to less than 1,300 a day. Our typical response was always to cut expenses, and at some point, we have  to build revenue. Quite honestly, we didn't know how to do that. All we knew how to do was cut expenses.
<P>
<b>ER: So what was the key step?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> We finally went back to base zero. My brother and I went down to Hagerstown, Md., and spent two days talking to customers -- Sheetz customers and non-Sheetz customers. We did about 40 interviews each to find out what the customers wanted. It's very simple -- in the end they wanted location, cleanliness, quality products, fast service and friendly people. From there, we went to all the stores, surveying over 1,000 people, who basically confirmed those top five items. We came back and just redesigned the whole business.
<P>
<b>ER: I guess there were some surprises?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> You talk about location? We thought we had location, but customers told us we didn't have enough parking, enough gas pumps. In terms of cleanliness, it meant much more than we ever thought. The buildings that had more lights appeared to the customer to be cleaner.
<P>
We always thought fast was getting them in and out in 90 seconds or two minutes. It wasn't that at all. They just wanted to make sure the people we had working were attentive to them and weren't talking on the phone or in the back. The customers didn't mind waiting if they knew we were working as hard as we could to service them.
<P>
We really redesigned the whole business. Although we've only added 12 net units from 1988 until now, sales have gone from $171 million to almost $700 million this year. It's really just giving the customers what they want, and putting in mechanisms to make sure we remain in touch with what the customers want.
<P>
<b>ER: You mentioned location. What else did you learn? Where there stores you thought were in prime locations that in actuality were not?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</B> A lot of what the customers told us dealt with capacity issues, and that forced us to close a lot of the stores that didn't have enough capacity,   parking, gas pumps and didn't have enough space to put more in. So what happened was we had an ideal site that didn't have enough square footage. We either had to acquire neighboring property or close. I would say the capacity issue drove the closings more than anything else.
<P>
The other thing that hindered us was the fact that a lot of the early sites were chosen before self-service gas was legal. They were more neighborhood sites. We used to count rooftops. Then it changed to how many cars went by the location.
<P>
The other factor was the buildings we were in. People found them unattractive ... too cramped. All of those things pushed us toward a replacement mode as opposed to a growth mode. We started chasing customers, and the customer counts grew. From the point when we fell to below 1,300 customers a day in a store, we have now grown to 2,500 customers a day. We've just about doubled the number of customers since 1988.
<P>
<b>ER: Most of your family is involved in the business. How does everyone     get along?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> There's a whole bunch of family involved -- five brothers and a nephew. My brother Bob had it early. We bought him out, but he came back in 1986 in the new company. We established a structure in which his son -- my nephew Stan -- became president in October. I moved to chairman. My other brothers Charlie, Joe and Louie are all vice presidents, so there are lots of Sheetzes here.
<P>
We have open arguments, but we all vacation together. We sit down at Christmas dinner together. Last year at Thanksgiving, we had 50 people at my house. Everybody is amazed at how well we get along.
<P>
<b>ER: What about your children and your brothers' children? Are they involved?</b><P>
<b>SS:</b> We had to make a decision last year whether we indeed wanted to bring the next generation in. We figured the six of us get along so well, should we risk it? In the end, we decided to bring them in because we have a lot of talent in the second generation.
<P>
We basically went out and recruited them. Two of them came back this year. One is a Wharton School graduate who came back as director of personnel. The other has an MBA from Vanderbilt and will be a site selector in Pittsburgh.
<P>
<b>ER: Any reason to believe they won't get along?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> Our ideas are basically the same. We go over the same customer information, and people have different opinions, but when we come out of there, we are firmly galvanized around whatever we want to do. 
<P>
<b>ER: You talked earlier about pleasing the customer. Working at Sheetz is not very glamorous. How do you land loyal and hard-working employees who will give the customers what they want?</b> 
<P>
<b>SS:</b> It's not a glamorous job at all. That was one of the problems that we had. We had to change the attitude about the job and make sure that the job was fun. And talking with employees was one of these mechanisms that was part of redesigning the business. We found out that one of their biggest dislikes was working by themselves.
<P>
Part of our new structure was to design a store that was large enough and generated enough volume so     that you never worked by yourself.     We did that. 
<P>
<b>ER: What about attracting new hires?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> We increased staffing to try and build some fun into the job. That was fine for the people we have, but we also had to attract new people to this job that, as you say, is less than glamorous. One way was to offer more money than others in the service industry do, and then we had to advertise that. We had to market ourselves as the place that was paying more.
<P>
All the things we were doing to retain people were great, but we had a problem attracting good people. We even do a better job with management people now because we are out there recruiting them. We had to believe in ourselves that we had a good place to work before that could happen.
<P>
In the mid-1980s, we fell into that same circle that it wasn't a good job, that it wasn't a good place to work. I think we have worked hard to make it a fun place to work. 
<P>
<b>ER: It seems you turned things around when you stopped cutting on the expenditure side. Is that the way it really worked?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> For us, it's a much different business than it was. There still is the convenience store market where there is one person on duty and the store has low overhead. They'll continue to survive, but we've elected to go a different route. Many people say that we are no longer a convenience store. But we don't know what we are if we are not a convenience store. 
<P>
The spectrum of convenience store has really broadened. Right now, we feel really good about where we are headed. We are in a position now where we can open a good many stores. This year, we probably opened about 16. We geared up our real estate department to open 25 to 30 units a year. We don't want to become numbers-driven again, but we feel we can handle more stores.
<P>
We'll do that because we remain in touch with the customers. This year we conducted about 50,000 customer surveys, a minimum of 250 per store. Each store has its own report card. 
<P>
We are pushing farther south, down into Virginia. We are still opening stores in this area, but not probably pushing any farther west. We are pushing east.
<P>
<b>ER: How concerned were you during your down times of the 1980s?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> I was real concerned. I took over as president in 1984. The sales went in 1985. The customer counts went backwards in 1986, and it got worse in 1987. Each time, I cut ex-penses. I cut labor hours. I thought we were hitting bottom in terms of where we could go. We were still profitable, but only because we just kept cutting and cutting. There wasn't much left to cut, and I was deeply concerned about where we were heading.
<P>
That pressure pushed me away from the stores and made the situation worse. It was constant pressure: What am I going to do? I relied on past methods until I really went out and started talking to customers. That simple action of just walking out and talking to people pulled me away from the focus I was in. It revitalized me, and I realized there was a solution out there. We had to spend money, but it was worth it.  
<P>
<b>ER: So you advise others in business to avoid constantly worrying about the expenditure side?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> I was in the downward spiral focus. It's really the principle of assessing where you are now, where you want to be and how you will get there. To objectively assess where you are is the toughest part. I look back at the '80s and realize I didn't really do that until I went out and talked to the customers and employees. Until then, I was really assessing where we were based on my own mind. To me, it's assessing what the customers think about what you are delivering right now, and what the employees feel. Then, how are you going to get there, and that's the tough part -- setting the strategies.
<P>
It was fun when we went out and talked to customers and employees. And it's been fun these past seven years building what the customers and employees want. And we get to make money, too.  
<P>
<b>ER: You've entered some new horizons as far as convenience stores are concerned. Describe some of the new products or services.</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> We are trying Sheetza Pizza, which we will roll out company-wide. Our best response is in markets where there is not a lot of competition. 
<P>
We have several drive-thrus. One in Hollidaysburg in a neighborhood setting is doing extremely well. It is still in the experimental stage, but we are going to move forward with it.
<P>
Some customers thought they could only buy prepared food, but they can also get a gallon of milk through the window. We renamed it Easy Street. We've promoted the fact that you can get anything through the window, and that has really picked up business. That experiment continues. I think it will be successful.
<P>
For us, it means taking the property and being able to access more customers. We are not touching the parking at all. To me, we are getting other customers who want in and    out fast -- the same theory as the card-activated gas pumps.
<P>
Some people say to me, 'You're crazy. You want the people inside.' My response is that if you treat them right outside, they'll come back again another time and come inside.
<P>
<b>ER: Some of your other changes aren't very flashy, are they?</b>
<P>
<b>SS:</b> Some of the new things are not big items. In the '80s, we didn't even have restrooms for customers. As we talked to them about what they wanted, they asked for restrooms. We put in one toilet in a room that locked. They still weren't happy. The door was locked. They weren't sure if someone was in there. So now we have two stalls with the doors unlocked. They told us they had to wait, so now we have three stalls each for the men and women. That's really what it is all about.
<P>
In the old days, I would have said restrooms were too expensive. It costs money to put them in, to pay for paper, to keep them clean. But we kept at it until the customers were content. Otherwise, they aren't coming back. 


<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

<ADDRESS><h5>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <a href="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments or suggestions?</a><br>
&#169  Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
