<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> ERIndex </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H13ERIndex.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Lighting It Up
</font><br>
<font size=+1>FORE Systems Shows Strong Earnings and a Solid <BR>
Strategy for the Future
</font><BR>
<i>By Doug Thomas
</i></b>

<HR>

<P>

Strong earnings are no surprise when its comes to FORE Systems, but the Warrendale company continues to turn heads. FORE, the worldwide leader in local area networking products based on asynchronous transfer mode technology, reported better-than-expected earnings for the second quarter ended   Sept. 30.
<P>
Earnings per share came in at 13 cents, based on revenues of $38.4 million. The earnings were 2 cents above the average analyst estimate of 11 cents per share. We attribute these healthy results to continued strong unit demand for Fore's switch ports and the company's determination to increase profitability.
<P>
The future looks good as FORE teams up with Premisys Communica-tions to sell Premisys' access products as part of a planned line of Fore Systems' ATM access products. Fore hopes the combined effort will facilitate integration of ATM networks.
<P>
Earlier in the month, Fore successfully completed a 4 million share secondary offering that netted approximately $130 million. Proceeds from the offering will be used for general corporate purposes and for the potential purchase of complementary businesses, products or technologies.
<P>
The better-than-expected earnings, the new deal with Premisys and the recent completion of the company's secondary offering propelled Fore shares to a 52-week high of 57 1/4 on Oct. 31, up from 36 1/2 per share on Oct. 13.
<P>
On the subject of stock offerings, Pittsburgh will become the home to yet another public company spinning out of Carnegie Mellon University. The Carnegie Group, a technology company that has been compared to the likes of Fore, develops knowledge-intensive software products that continually adapt as new data is added. The software is custom-designed for clients to integrate advance software technologies -- including knowledge-based systems and advanced graphical user interfaces -- with existing infrastructures.
<P>
Carnegie's current clientele in-cludes the U.S. Army, BellSouth Tele-communications, Ford Motor Co. and Caterpillar Inc. The company is listed on the NASDAQ ex-change under the symbol CGIX. 
<P>

<B>Around the Index</B>
<P>
    For the four weeks ended Oct. 13, the  ER Index was unable to recover from the late September market decline, finishing down 2.24 percent for the month  as compared to a  0.20 percent increase for the S&P 500. Since inception, the ER Index still maintains the lead with a 27.51 percent return, as compared to a return of 26.73 percent for the S&P 500.
<P>
	This month, Westinghouse and Southwest National Corp. replace Black Box and Integra Financial on the ER Index.
<P>
Most of us know the Westinghouse story: It manufactures and sells electronics equipment and components and operates broadcasting and cable television systems. In a move to expand its broadcasting business, Westing-house recently bid to acquire CBS. On Sept. 13, Westinghouse finalized its $7.5 billion loan for the $5.4 billion purchase after signing with a syndicate of 50 banks led by Chemical Bank and J.P. Morgan & Co. The acquisition is slated for completion by the end of 1995. Additionally this month, the company reached a settlement with the Philippine government that ends litigation over safety at the nonoperational Bataan Power Plant built by Westinghouse in 1985. Settlement of the suit lifts the Philippine ban on Westinghouse products and opens a market the company hopes to tap. Shares of Westinghouse ended the month up 1.72 percent to 14 3/4. 
<P>
	Southwest National Corp., headquartered in Greensburg and the parent company of Southwest Bank, reported an earnings-per-share increase of  4.4 percent to 75 cents in the quarter ended Sept. 30. These results reflect the improvement in loan growth and a decrease in net loan charge-offs. Southwest National shares increased slightly to 32 1/4.
<P>
	Another of note was Alcoa, which announced better-than-expected earnings for its third quarter. Profits from operations increased to $231.8 million, or $1.30 per share, on a 27 percent increase in revenue to $3.33 billion. That compares to net income of  $70.1 million, or 39 cents per share,  in the year-earlier quarter. Shares of Alcoa fell 8.63 percent in the  month to 51 5/8

<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research for Emerald Asset Management, tracks the ER Index which is composed of 25 public companies in greater Pittsburgh.</I>

