<HEAD>
<TITLE> EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>Welcome to the Big Leagues</b> 
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Rookie Legislators Get Taste of Political<br>                    Reality During First Year in State Capitol                 

</font><BR>
<i>By Jim Strader
</i>

<HR>

<P>

As rookie players in the old game of Pennsylvania politics, new lawmakers from the Pittsburgh region took to the field in Harrisburg this past year with enthusiasm and an eye on the pennant. But most of the legislators elected in southwestern Pennsylvania last fall are Democrats who entered the game with an unexpected disadvantage: For the first time in a dozen years, Republicans are making the rules.
<P>
For Rep. Harry Readshaw -- who is new not only to the General Assembly but to politics as well -- the lessons started early.
<P>
"You have to get here and become extremely active quickly to adapt and understand the system -- and by the system, I mean Harrisburg," says Readshaw, a Democrat from Pleasant Hills. "When you arrive in Harrisburg, the name of the game is politics and you have to be able to deal with that."
<P>
Dealing with political realities does not mean compromising ideals, explains Readshaw, who says he came to the Capitol without obligations to anyone but his constituents.
<P>
"I'm a third-generation funeral director. My family has been in the business since 1912," Readshaw says.   "I didn't come to Harrisburg for a job; I came to do a job."
<P>
Readshaw's initial legislative effort was a bill to advance the date of Pennsylvania's presidential primary election, to give the state's voters a larger say in choosing the candidates. The bill lingered in committee for months, despite Readshaw's appeals to ruling Republicans to move the legislation. Just prior to summer recess, the bill made it to the House floor and passed.
<P>
"The only thing that annoyed me is that government could act a little quicker than it does," Readshaw says. "It's frustrating that you deal with issues, or you anticipate dealing with issues, and then they are put aside."
<P>
Rep. Christopher Sainato, elected to the state House after 10 years as a congressional aide, looked for small victories in his first year in Harrisburg. The Lawrence County Democrat pushed to have the toll on the Route 60 expressway lowered to fall in line     with the Pennsylvania Turnpike. The higher toll defeats attempts to use the road to foster economic development, Sainato says.
<P>
"As an economically depressed area, we have to try to use all of the tools that we can to try to attract business," he says.
<P>
"The people who need to use it every day can't afford to use it."
<P>
Turnpike officials rejected the idea, and Sainato will try to make the change legislatively. 
<P>
Sainato also supports the development of enterprise zones to encourage businesses to locate in areas like his district, which lost thousands of jobs a decade ago. Other business-friendly efforts undertaken to date, such as the lowering of corporate taxes, are helpful albeit small steps in what needs to be a bipartisan endeavor, he says.
<P>
"I believe that we have to work together, both as Democrats and Republicans, to try to do what's best for Pennsylvania, and my concern is western Pennsylvania," Sainato says.
<P>
The lone new senator from the area is Democrat Jack Wagner, a Pittsburgh city councilman before his election last year. Wagner finds "real joy and a challenge" in addressing the needs of 12 million people, rather than just 350,000 city residents.
<P>
In some areas, Wagner sees the opportunity to influence the national debate on issues such as welfare and education.  With the federal government shifting more responsibility to states, solutions that work in one state can be tried in others, he says.
<P>
The Ridge administration should be commended for encouraging the reuse of polluted industrial sites, Wagner says. That effort and the larger goal of making Pennsylvania more competitive must be supported by all agencies of state government and by local governments around the state,   he says.
<P>
Rep. Don Walko of Pittsburgh finds the Capitol a little bit like Broadway, a stimulating mix of the best and worst the state has to offer, from the occasional rough-and-tumble of politics to the often thoughtful consideration of issues by his colleagues."It's just a wonderful way to discuss issues and feel like you have a meaningful impact on people's lives," he says. "I'm really energized by it."
<P>
As a Democrat, Walko has felt the sting of politics by having one of his bills passed over in favor of a nearly identical GOP measure.
"That's part of the cost of being in the minority," he says.                         



