<HEAD>
<TITLE> Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H17Education.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<center><b><font size =+2>
Searching for Scholars</font></B><br>
<B><I><font size=+1>For State Schools, Attracting Top <br>Students Is a Never-Ending Battle
</font></I></B><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i></center>

<HR>

<P>

Bob Cook wanted his alma mater to offer an atmosphere similar to what his children experienced at the small, private colleges they attended. Luckily for Indiana University of Pennsylvania, Cook also had a few million dollars to throw around.
<P>
The 52-year-old entrepreneur and native of Altoona pledged $3.26 million to IUP, from which he graduated in 1964. The money will be used to create the Robert E. Cook Honors College, a tool the university thinks will help it lure top students out of high schools near and far.
<P>
For schools like IUP, tools such as an honors college are invaluable as the battle for top students wages on. The schools in the state system -- including IUP, Slippery Rock, California, Clarion and Edinboro -- compete with smaller, private schools whose huge endowments allow them to slash tuition costs and offer other incentives.
<P>
"Many of these students are attracted to private institutions," says Drew McGukin, acting associate vice president for academic affairs at California. "The private schools have flexibility with financing. They give these students reduced rates or even tuition waivers."
<P>
So the state schools fight back. California has had an honors program for about 10 years, annually admitting about 25 students whose SAT scores exceeded 1000. The program mixes disciplines, hopefully producing the science majors who also are strong writers and the English majors who are computer-savvy, McGukin says.
<P>
California is currently evaluating the admission criteria so it can include more nontraditional students, such as working parents who return to school, in the honors program.
<P>
The difference between IUP's and California's honors offerings are facilities and size. First-year students will be admitted to IUP's Cook Honors College next September, with full implementation of the college scheduled for the following academic year. Total enrollment will fall between 300 and 400 students, limiting each annual class to no more than 100 students. They will not only share classes, but also living quarters.
<P>
"I sent both my children to small, private colleges," Cook says. "I wanted to duplicate some of their programs at IUP. When I told administrators that, they said, It sounds like an honors college.' "
<P>
Cook is the former chairman and chief executive officer of Systems Center Inc. of Reston, Va., a leading developer of systems software that  supports IBM's Virtual Machine Operating System. He sold the business in 1993 for a reported $185 million.
<P>
The honors college will limit class sizes to 20 and feature selected professors. Each residence hall room will have a computer with access to IUP's library and the Internet. There's other good news: Honors college tuition will be the same as regular admission.
<P>
Cook's donation has been critical to IUP's chase of top students. Some other schools in the state system don't have the dollars to fund honors programs. An example is Slippery Rock, which resorts to other strategies. 
<P>
Slippery Rock added 35 new scholarships this fall. The school's President's Scholarship covers full tuition and targets students who rank first in their class following their junior year in high school. The school also strives to create an intimate learning environment, pushing professors into the classrooms and trimming class sizes.
<P>
"You won't find any larger lecture sections," says Duncan Sargent, director of admissions. "And you'll find faculty with Ph.D. degrees in their area of expertise. Those are academic types of things." 
<P>
The state schools will use whatever they can for an edge over competitors who try to land the same students. The state schools have one other selling point: They all charged $3,224 for the current school year, which, outside of the region's community colleges, is a bargain.                                         


<hr>

