<HEAD>
<TITLE> Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><font size=+2>The Taxman Cometh</font><br><font size=+1>Close a Profitable Year With<br>Strategies That Limit Tax Liability<br>
</font></B><i>By Henry Lipput</center></i><P>


<HR>

<P>

For Dave Herrmann, the best way to celebrate a profitable year at his small business is to limit Uncle Sam's cut. And at the fiscal year-end, that means purchasing equipment and employing other common strategies.
<P>
"We've mostly purchased office equipment: computers, software, printers, copy machines, some office furniture ... things like that," says Herrmann, president of Herrmann Associates, a manufacturer's agent for heating and ventilation equipment.
<P>
"This year coming up -- if we had a good year -- I'm going to use that money to invest in a new phone system."
<P>
Section 179 of the federal tax code allows small businesses to purchase up to $17,500 worth of equipment and receive a current deduction for that amount, instead of having to depreciate the assets over time. Companies can take possession of the equipment and not pay for it until the following year. 
<P>
"We suggest that every small company look at this," says Jeff Wlahofsky of the Pittsburgh accounting firm Schneider Downs. "That's a good planning technique for both a cash-basis and/or an accrual-basis taxpayer. Both of them can buy that equipment and take that deduction." 
<P>
The tax break was written by Congress specifically for small business, and it may become more lucrative since Congress is looking at raising the deductible limit for fixed assets from $17,500 to $37,500 per year. But year-end tax strategies don't stop there.
<P>
Pension plans, profit-sharing plans and 401(k) plans are also good year-end tax planning techniques if an employer is interested in providing these benefits to his employees.
<P>
"You can take a deduction for the amount of money that you're going to fund in that plan, but under the tax rules, you basically have nine and a half months to fund it," Wlahofsky says. "You can set up a plan before the end of the year, accrue the deduction, and then have until the extended due date of a tax return to actually make the payment into the plans.
<P>
"You can set up a plan, provide a benefit to yourself and your employees, and have a lot of time to raise the cash to fund it. In the meantime, you're saving tax dollars."
<P>
Herrmann's business, with a 401(k) profit-sharing plan, is one example. The employees choose how much they want to contribute, and the company kicks in an amount equal to  3 percent of their pay. "We do have the option of kicking additional money    in if we have an exceptional year," Herrmann says.
<P>
Some companies with accrual-basis bookkeeping also limit their tax liability by paying bonuses to their nonshareholder employees. 
<P>
"You can declare a bonus, accrue the deduction, but not pay it until March 15," Wlahofsky says.  "The employee doesn't pick it up in his income until 1996.  It's a win-win situation, but you have to be an accrual-basis taxpayer."
<P>
Tax planning this year will see some changes due to measures pushed through the 1995-96 state budget by Gov. Tom Ridge. The most noticeable change was a reduction of the corporate net income tax to 9.99 percent, retroactive to Jan. 1, 1995. But small businesses received a break in that they now can claim up to $1 million in net operating losses for previous years, up from $500,000. 
<P>
The state also increased the exemption from $75,000 to $100,000 for the capital stock and franchise tax, lessening the tax burden on small businesses.
<P>
"I think any small business should be thinking about tax planning at year-end," Wlahofsky says. "Basically, the rule of thumb is to defer income and accelerate expenses as best you can."  

<hr>

