<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H15Health.gif"><a href="../zine/1295.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>Big Game Fishing<br>
</font></I></B>

<b><font size =+1>A Young Plastic Surgeon Trolls for Economic Development</b></font><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
</center><P>


<HR>

<P>

<P>
Peter Johnson's life mimics his art -- or one of them anyway. A veteran fly fisherman, Johnson sends his line spinning out over the water, hoping to hook a big one. As head of the Pittsburgh Tissue Engineering Initiative, his job is very similar.
<P>
Tissue engineering includes cell culturing, gene therapy, organ transplant and generation -- procedures that allow tissues to be grown outside the body, often from  minute particles of human tissue. Take the example of a child, burned over 98 percent of his body. If the skin had to be harvested from his own body, where would it come from? What if science could manufacture enough skin to cover the wounds from a piece that's one-tenth of 1 percent of body surface area?
<P>
With heady clinical and cost cutting potential, tissue replacement is an estimated $400 billion market.
<P>
Johnson's tissue engineering institute hopes to anchor the industry here in Pittsburgh. So Johnson, who models   his leadership on the Internet, which ignores traditional boundaries to build cooperation, has woven a web of 411 entrepreneurs, funding sources and university researchers in his computer. He meets with people, lists contacts, matches like interests. His objective? To bring one of Pittsburgh's finest and heretofore mostly untapped resources -- the biomedical research that goes  on in its universities -- from the lab to the marketplace.
<P>
Johnson believes it's high time that researchers (and the American economy) start profiting from and perpetuating their own science, instead of relying on federal funding to create technologies that other countries pick up and beat us with. 
<P>
"It became clear to me that tissue growth outside the body and implantation was going to have a major impact on the way we practice surgery, and actually reduce the cost of healthcare," says Johnson.
<P>
Currently, replacement tissues are harvested elsewhere on the body -- operations that are costly in dollars ($28 a minute for operating time, not including surgeon's fees), and taxing to  the patient's health.  These technologies eliminate both. 
<P>
"The problem was, how would you take something that was the scientific equivalent of a moonshot in its complexity, and bring together enough of a critical mass to make headway?" Johnson says.
<P>
Pittsburgh, Johnson thinks, has that critical mass. The labs at Pitt have strength in cell culture and transplantation. At Allegheny General Hospital's Allegheny Singer Research Institute, researchers work on mechanical systems supporting the growth of cells. CMU's dominance in computing, engineering and design completes the equation. In January 1994, these institutions jointly founded the Pittsburgh Tissue Engineering Initiative. 
<P>
"Pittsburgh has these huge piles of talent, but its weakness is we have few companies related to what they are doing, particularly at Pitt," says Johnson. "So we represent a region that is at high risk for losing talent to regions with the proper structure." 
<P>
A year ago, PTEI was endorsed by the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative as one of the five most promising ventures in the region. The Ben Franklin Partnership granted PTEI  $80,000 last year and $100,000 this year for seed grant programs. But the biggest indicator of its success? Since July 1995, five companies have formed or are coming to Pittsburgh from other places, due to Johnson's matchmaking.
<P>
"In every way possible, PTEI facilitated this," says Dr. Paul Kornblith, former director of UPMC/Brain Trauma Center who is president of Precision Therapeutics. His firm is developing a methodology and laboratory to test specific drugs on the cancer cells of patients outside their bodies, so there's no guessing involved with prescribing chemotherapies. PTEI helped access connections for technology transfer, funding, business and marketing training, even lab space. 
<P>
It's not Johnson's goal to spirit talent away from the universities, only to facilitate the technology's transfer to the commercial marketplace -- which can occur with or without the researcher. So he tries to hook entrepreneurs like the San Diego, Calif.-based Tulip Co., which manufactures instrumentation for procedures such as liposuction. They plan to start a company called CellSource in Pittsburgh at the beginning of 1996 to manufacture autologus (which means "from yourself") tissues like fat, collagen and fiber blast, working with scientists here.
<P>
"Pittsburgh has the science and wants the opportunity, and we want to do a co-venture," says John Johnson, president of the Tulip Co., who is particularly interested in manufacturing fat cells as therapy for incontinence, a problem that affects an estimated 18 million people nationwide. John Johnson says the company didn't even look for possible alliances on the West Coast, one of the two current hotbeds of biomed research. The other is the East Coast, where competition, not collaboration, between institutions is the norm. "There's an incredible willingness on the part of Peter Johnson -- he's a real futurist." 
<P>
Does Pittsburgh have the stuff to become the national hub for tissue engineering? "Not only do I think it's possible, but that it will be achieved," John Johnson says. 
<P>
In October of this year, SoloHill Labs, Inc. of Ann Arbor, Mich., also incorporated a wholly owned subsidiary, SoloHill Therapeutics Inc., to work with researchers here. They will be based in Clairton.
<P>
"What I would see happen is that a large cluster of companies could be formed, the way they did it in Silicon Valley, creating such a competitive advantage that the companies all grow," says Peter Johnson.               


<hr>

