</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1295.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1295.Feature.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>The Best</B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Saxonburg's II-VI is No. 1 in ER's<br>6th Annual List of<br>Top 10 Growth Companies
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>

<P>


Some call it Two-Four. Others call it Eye-Eye-Vee-Eye.
<P>
To Carl Johnson, it's always been II-VI Inc. (say Two-Six), his Saxonburg-based company that develops optical and electro-optical components, devices and materials.
<P>
We won't butcher the name, but we are offering a new handle with a different numeral: No. 1.
<P>
II-VI, with a staggering growth rate of 62.36 percent over the past five years, heads Executive Report's sixth annual list of Top 10 growth companies in southwestern Pennsylvania. The Top 10, compiled by Parker/Hunter Inc., gauges public companies on the growth of their earnings per share over five years.
<P>
This year, the battle for No. 1 was no contest, as the growth rate posted by II-VI was nearly double that of    No. 2 Mylan Laboratories, whose growth rate of 33.46 percent was nothing to sneeze at.
<P>
II-VI takes its name from Groups II and VI of the periodic table where the elements zinc, cadmium, sulfur, selenium and tellurium are listed. II-VI uses those elements to make raw materials for its laser-related products. The company went public in October 1987, offering 924,000 shares at $6.50 apiece. The stock peaked in the first quarter of this year at $23.  
<P>
The CEO, Johnson (for more on him, see page 19), already was a stickler for quality. The public offering eight years ago only heightened the push for quality. Since then, II-VI has further entrenched itself as the leader in markets all over the world, 35 countries to be exact. Over 50 percent of its revenues are from overseas.
<P>
"Being a public company has been good for us," says Johnson, who founded II-VI in 1971 at the age of 29. "Before, we could sit back and say we were working for ourselves," Johnson says. "Once you are working for that investing public, everything changes."
<P>
II-VI's stock settled in at around $12 following a secondary offering in October, but the company looks positioned well. Its infrared products are used in high-power carbon dioxide lasers for industrial processing worldwide. Name an industry, chances are workers are using lasers. Garment makers cut fabric with lasers. The food industry uses them to etch dates and product codes in aluminum cans. 
<P>
Last December, II-VI acquired Virgo Optics, a division of Sandoz Chemicals Corp. that manufactures near infrared and visible light products used in industrial, scientific and medical instruments and solid-state yttrium aluminum garnet lasers. Francis J. Kramer, president and chief operating officer of II-VI, says the YAG lasers are likely a growth area through the year 2000. You know all those airbags that become standard on most vehicles in coming years? The airbag sensors and inflators are welded with YAG lasers.
<P>
II-VI will take its YAG products into the markets where it already has established presence. 
<P>
II-VI is also developing and     marketing solid-state x-ray and gamma-ray products for the nuclear radiation detection industry through its eV PRODUCTS division.
<P>
Lasers are popular because they produce cleaner, more intricate cuts than conventional machine tools. They also last longer and adapt more easily to changes in production. 
<P>
<B>The Line on II-VI Inc.</B>
<hr><pre>
Headquarters: Saxonburg
CEO: Carl J. Johnson
Listing: IIVI on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Optical and electro-optical components, devices and materials for precision use in infrared, near infrared, visible and x-ray/gamma-ray instruments and applications.
Five-year growth rate: 62.36 percent</pre>
<P><pre>
<B>No. 2: Mylan Laboratories Inc.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Pittsburgh
CEO: Milan Puskar
Listing: MYL on NYSE
Primary industry: Pharmaceuticals
Five-year growth rate: 33.46 percent</pre>
<P>Always a bridesmaid, never a bride. Mylan Laboratories comes in at No. 2 for the third consecutive year, cementing itself as one of the region's best stock buys despite its inability to crack the top spot.
<P>Give Mylan Labs credit for its consistent growth. And give Mylan Labs credit for being lean and mean. In its last fiscal year ended March 31, Mylan posted net earnings of $121 million on just $396 million in revenues.
<P>It only gets better. This fall, Mylan signed an agreement to acquire UDL Laboratories Inc., a leading supplier of unit dose generic pharmaceuticals to the institutional and long-term care markets. 
<P>"The addition of UDL will enable Mylan to better position itself with a more complete line of both solid and liquid pharmaceuticals in custom packaging for the retail, institutional and managed care markets," says Milan Puskar, chairman, CEO and president of Mylan.  "The addition of UDL to the Mylan Family,' blended with the two previous acquisitions of Dow Hickam Pharmaceuticals and Bertek, is representative of Mylan's strategic plan to continue its evolution into a fully integrated pharmaceutical company." 
Mylan is ranked No. 1 in total number of prescriptions dispensed among branded and generic companies in the United States, based on an IMS prescription audit conducted at the end of June 1995. 
<P><PRE>
<B>No. 3: Kennametal Inc.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Latrobe
CEO: Robert L. McGeehan
Listing: KMT on NYSE
Primary industry: Industrial tools and tooling systems
Five-year growth rate: 33.17 percent</PRE>
<P>

Kennametal is a global leader in the development and manufacturing of industrial tools and tooling systems. About 80 percent of its sales traditionally are to the metalworking industries, with another 15 percent heading to mining and construction markets.
<P>
The Latrobe-based company    posted earnings per share of $2.58 in fiscal 1995, when Kennametal achieved record sales of $984 million, up             23 percent.
<P>
Much of the growth stemmed from Kennametal's alliance with Hertel AG, a German toolmaker in which Kennametal acquired an 81 percent interest in August 1993. Hertel definitely has been a catalyst for Kennametal, which is now entrenched in the European market and strengthening its position in the eastern part of Europe and the Pacific Rim.
<P>
Kennametal president and CEO Robert L. McGeehan says 1996 holds more potential growth. McGeehan says sales of metalcutting products in the United States should benefit from continued expansion of the U.S. economy, additional branch openings at J&L Industrial Supply and Kennametal's strategic marketing alliance with W.W. Grainger, the nation's largest industrial distributor of maintenance, repair and operating supplies. 
<P>
Overseas, sales in Europe and Asia should continue to benefit from the enhanced product offerings and technical expertise of Kennametal and Hertel in those regions. Sales of mining and construction tools should continue to increase from selected opportunities in existing markets and developing opportunities in China and Poland, McGeehan says. 
<P><pre>
<B>No. 4: Respironics Inc.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Murrysville
CEO: Dennis S. Meteny
Listing: RESP on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Patient ventilation products
Five-year growth rate: 27.08 percent</pre>
<P>

Respironics designs, develops, manufactures and sells respiratory medical products for use in the     home, hospitals and emergency care situations.
<P>
The Murrysville-based firm saw sales in fiscal 1995 -- which ended June 30 -- jump 27 percent to         $99.5 million, up from $78.2 million the year earlier. Included with that were        signs that growth was occurring in both established and emerging markets. International sales accounted for 20 percent of the growing sales base.
<P>
Shareholders had reason to smile when Respironics offered a 2-for-1 stock split in March. The good news continued days later when Respironics disclosed it would acquire Vitalog Monitoring Inc., a California-based designer and manufacturer of sleep monitoring and diagnostic equipment.
<P>
The transaction strengthened Respironics' position in the sleep disorder market. Respironics Vice President Robert Crouch says the rapidly increasing awareness of the harmful effects of sleep apnea was "the engine that drove our business in fiscal 1995."
<P>
The year's sales in that market sector rose more than 30 percent from "an already strong base," Crouch says.
<P>Respironics has several new products in the pipeline, slated for launch during fiscal 1996.




<P><pre>
<B>No. 5: Industrial Scientific Corp.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Oakdale
CEO: Kent D. McElhattan
Listing: ISCX on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Products for detecting, measuring and monitoring gases
Five-year growth rate: 18.28 percent</PRE>
<P>

Industrial Scientific designs, manufactures and sells instruments and other technical products for detecting, measuring and monitoring a wide  variety of gases.
<P>
Its earnings through the first half of fiscal 1995 trailed the year earlier, but the company seemed positioned well to resume its growth pattern.
<P>
"Speaking generally, we decided to increase investments in people, equipment and technologies," says Kent D. McElhattan, president and CEO. "These calculated investments have reduced earnings in the short term, but will pay back in the near- and longer-term future. More specifically, staffing levels and project activity in technical research have been increased, resulting in 30 percent more new products in our development stream. 
<P>
"Secondly, field sales staffing was increased by more than 40 percent during the first quarter. This will broaden our base of customers and contribute to developing practical, useful products.  We project increased sales to begin after 8 to 12 months of investment into these new employees."
<P>
Industrial Scientific also purchased Monitor Group Inc., a developer of portable mass spectrometers for analytical determination of gases and liquids. Monitor pioneered and patented extensive developments that reduce the size and cost of mass spectrometers. Industrial Scientific expects sales to begin early next year.
<P>
The domestic demand for portable gas detection instruments will grow annually at a rate of up to 12 percent, and international markets offer opportunities for substantial growth.
<P>
Just this year, Industrial Scientific established a wholly owned sub- sidiary to better serve the Australian and Pacific Rim markets. By late summer, year-to-date international sales        were up 30 percent compared to the previous year.
<P>

<PRE>
<B>No. 6: PPG Industries Inc.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Pittsburgh
CEO: Jerry E. Dempsey
Listing: PPG on NYSE
Primary industry: Industrial coatings, glass, chemicals and finishes
Five-year growth rate: 16.59 percent</PRE>
<P>

PPG Industries, a member of the inaugural Top 10 in 1990, returns to the list after a four-year absence. PPG is a leading producer of industrial and specialty chemicals, coatings and resins, flat and fabricated glass, and continuous-strand fiber glass. 
<P>
A good investment? Standard & Poors thinks so. It praised PPG in August for PPG's enviable dividend record. PPG was included among a list of 58 companies that have paid a cash dividend for at least 50 consecutive years and increased payments annually for the last five years.
<P>
This year's third quarter was business as usual, with PPG's board declaring a dividend of 30 cents per share.
<P>
"PPG's dividends per share have grown by more than 11 percent since April 1994; dividend payments have increased every year since 1972, and dividends have been paid without interruption since 1899," CEO Jerry E. Dempsey says.
<P>
The company also posted record earnings through the first nine months. Net income was $606.4 million, or $2.97 a share, on sales of    $5.34 billion. That compared with 1994 net income of $363.6 million, or $1.71 a share, including a second-quarter after-tax charge of $51.9 million, or 24 cents a share.
<P>
Dempsey credits PPG's performance of late to diversity in the company's portfolio. For evidence, look at the numbers PPG is posting at a time when housing and auto production -- two industries that drive PPG's business -- are soft.
<P>
"We continue to achieve record results despite only modest economic growth," Dempsey says. "We are benefiting from ongoing strategies to capitalize on our broad business mix and geographic diversification." 
<P>
<pre>
<B>No. 7: S&T Bancorp</B>
<HR>
Headquarters: Indiana, Pa.
CEO: Robert D. Duggan
Listing: STBA on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Banking

Five-year growth rate: 15.37 percent</PRE>
<P>

S&T Bancorp repeats on the     Top 10, moving up one spot from No. 8 last year. S&T is a $1.3 billion bank-holding company whose principal subsidiary is S&T Bank, which operates   35 branches in Allegheny, Armstrong, Clearfield, Indiana, Jefferson and Westmoreland counties.
<P>
S&T has shown loan growth at a time when the economy is flat and interest rates have been volatile. Its nonperforming loans total only about 0.23 percent of total loans.
<P>
S&T also has shown a flare for the creative this year as it further cements its position in its regional market. For example, S&T rolled out a 401(k) service that included Fidelity Investors as investment manager and Benefits Services Corp. as record-keeper.  S&T can provide all the necessary components for a 401(k) retirement savings plan to businesses -- even those with as few as 25 employees.
<P>
S&T also partnered with Wal-Mart, placing a seven-day-a-week facility inside the Wal-Mart store in White Township. That S&T Bank branch is the bank's second to be located within a retail store. S&T Bank opened its first branch within a Kittanning supermarket in June 1992.
<P>
"The establishment of a branch within the Wal-Mart Supercenter as part of our branch network will help us to further establish ourselves as the service and convenience leader in the Indiana market area," S&T CEO Robert D. Duggan says.
<P>
<pre>

<B>No. 8: Parkvale Financial Corp.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Monroeville
CEO: Robert J. McCarthy Jr.
Listing: PVSA on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Banking
Five-year growth rate: 14.94 percent</PRE>
<P>

Parkvale Financial Corp. makes the Top 10 for the second consecutive year, after placing No. 6 on last        year's list.
<P>
Parkvale Financial is the parent of Parkvale Savings Bank, which has 28 offices in greater Pittsburgh. At late summer, Parkvale held approximately $900 million in assets.
<P>
The numbers show why Parkvale is repeating on the Top 10: For the fiscal year ended June 30, 1995, net income increased 11.7 percent from $7.2 million or $2.59 per share in 1994 to $8.1 million or $2.93 per share in 1995.
<P>
Stockholders already know how well Parkvale is doing: Parkvale's board declared a 5-for-4 stock split of common stock in September. The stock split, combined with a quarterly dividend of 13 cents per share, increased the cash payout to stockholders by      25 percent.
<P>
The split represents the third stock split in three years with previous 5-for-4 splits paid in October 1994 and October 1993.
<P>
CEO Robert J. McCarthy Jr. says the continuing profitability of Parkvale Savings Bank and the appreciation in the corporation's common stock justified the stock split and the increase in the dividend payment.
<P>
If Parkvale is not acquired, expect the bank to continue strong growth in the wake of Integra's acquisition by National City. Parkvale is positioned well to pick up some business.
<P>
<PRE>
<B>No. 9: First Western Bancorp Inc.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: New Castle
CEO: Thomas J. O'Shane
Listing: FWBI on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Banking
Five-year growth rate: 12.21 percent</PRE>
<P>

First Western Bancorp Inc. makes the Top 10 for the fourth consecutive year, including placing at the No. 9 spot last year. First Western is a multi-bank holding company based in New Castle, Lawrence County.
<P>
First Western is the parent of First Western Bank, N.A., a full-service bank; First Western Bank, F.S.B., a federal savings bank; First Western Trust Services Co., a full-service trust company and Residential Mortgage Co.     of America, a mortgage banking    company. 
<P>
The parent company has quietly acquired branches in new markets, allowing it to boost its total assets and customer base at the same time.
<P>
For the nine months ended Sept. 30, First Western earned $12.5 million or $2.40 per share, up slightly more than 6 percent from last year's nine month totals of $11.8 million or $2.26 per share. Shareholders were rewarded with a 3-for-2 stock split.
<P>
"Our record earnings to-date in 1995 reflect superior loan growth, better control of interest expense in the second and third quarters and continued excellent cost control," says Thomas J. O'Shane, president and CEO of First Western. "We are also very pleased with our sales of traditional banking products in our recently expanded northeastern Ohio market after the first quarter branch purchases." First Western's 42 community banking offices are located in seven Pennsylvania counties (Lawrence, Mercer, Beaver, Erie, Allegheny, Venango and Butler) and two Ohio counties (Ashtabula and Lake).  
<P>
At press time, total assets stood at about $1.66 billion, up 14 percent from the end of 1994.
<P>
<PRE>

<B>No. 10: Matthews International Corp.</B>
<hr>
Headquarters: Pittsburgh
CEO: David M. Kelly
Listing: MATW on NASDAQ
Primary industry: Custom-made I.D. products
Five-year growth rate: 12.17 percent</PRE>
<P>

Matthews International is a first-timer on the Top 10. The Pittsburgh firm designs, manufacturers and markets custom-made identification products.
<P>
The products include cast bronze memorials for use in cemeteries, printing plates and graphic services for the corrugated packaging industry, and marking equipment and consumables for identifying various consumer and industrial products and containers.
<P>
The interesting product is the bronze memorials: It sounds cold, but as long as people continue dying, Matthews will have steady business. 
<P>
The company recently had a change of leadership when David M. Kelly became Matthews' president and CEO Oct. 1. He succeeded the retired William M. Hauber, who remains chairman of the board. Kelly, 52, spent 22 years with Carrier Corp., where he most recently was in charge of worldwide operations for Carrier's Residential and Light Commercial businesses.                                          



