<p>
<hr>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>These Rising Stars Came to the Fore in 1995  
</FONT><br>
<hr>
<P><B><font size =+2>
Dr. Suzanne Ildstad <br>    
 Director of the Division of Cellular Therapeutics<br>
University of Pittsburgh Medical Center<br></font></B>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
</FONT>
<P>

Nestled among the numerous  photos on Dr. Suzanne Ildstad's desk is a microscopic shot of the insulin-    producing cell of a rat, securely implanted in a diabetic mouse.
<P>
Little wonder that Ildstad, director of cellular therapeutics at the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center, framed it. The acceptance of that cell by the mouse represents a milestone in her quest to transplant organs into humans without massive doses of anti-rejection drugs. It signifies that she's winning -- which could mean hope for thousands of patients suffering from diabetes, leukemia or other auto-immune diseases, even AIDS. 
<P>
"For even a perfectly compliant patient who takes the [anti-rejection] medicines every day, which is not easy, the chance of having a [transplanted] kidney function for 10 years is about one in five. And for hearts and lungs it's even less," Ilstad says.
<P>
Researchers have long believed that transplanting part of the donor's immune system to the patient would confer immunity to the donor's organ. 
<P>
"We began to look at what enables the stem cells to take without graft vs. host disease," says Ildstad. What they found, with the aid of an innovative technology called cell sorting, was a facilitator cell, which allows the stem cells to take. Stripping the T-cells out had also removed this cell -- because no one knew it was there. The facilitator cell has enabled many, many mice to have transplants. And this year, Ildstad and her lab team transferred the technique to human patients. The technique also mitigates the highly selective process of matching donors with needy patients.
<P>
"We have now treated five leukemia patients who conventionally have no match, and three of those five have had take of their bone marrow without graft vs. host disease," says Ildstad. 
<P>
     The procedure is also being tested to induce tolerance for liver transplants in six other patients, and the team has been given permission from West Penn Hospital to use it on patients with red blood cell disorders, like sickle cell anemia. With genetic diagnostic techniques, Ildstad hopes that in the future, patients diagnosed with diabetes could have insulin-producing islet cell transplants in the womb, when the bone marrow is developing, to eliminate diabetes.
<P>
One of the most controversial applications is transferring the bone marrow of a baboon, a species which is immune to AIDS, into a human. Cross-species transplantation, another focus of Ildstad's, creates what's called a chimera, from the mythical creature that was, in parts, goat, lion and snake.
<P>
Under intense scrutiny, the FDA last summer approved the operation, which was to be performed Nov. 1. But the patient, 37-year-old Jeff Getty, contracted pneumonia. Ildstad deemed the operation too risky. If cross species transplantation works, it could ease now critical donor shortages. (For caucasians, the chance of finding a suitable match is 30 percent; for people of color, less than 20 percent.)There have been other hitches in her research. Funding from the National Institutes of Health, which has supported the bulk of her research, is being cut. But she says her biggest disappointment is that her team     doesn't perform the clinical portion of their research at UPMC. The operations to date have been done by partnering with the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, in Houston, and the University of California, San Francisco, an arrangement that doesn't allow the team to follow patients daily.
<P>
"Dr. [Thomas E.] Starzl [director of UPMC's Transplantation Institute] has a different philosophy about Chimerism and tolerance, and we found we couldn't pursue our vision,  without his interference. And for that reason, we petitioned the University to be able to do them elsewhere, because other groups were very excited about our findings," says Ildstad.
<P>
Of course, a rising star like Ildstad has options, about which she will      only say that many are anxious to  make her lab the flagship of their   operation. But what a shame it  would be to have her shoot out of  our constellation.   <hr>                              

<P><B><font size =+2>II-VI Co-Founder<br> 
Carl Johnson is High Tech Smart and Business Savvy</font></b><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
<P>

Carl Johnson's early days as a 29-year-old entrepreneur were pretty simple: He had one partner, 13 investors, a head full of knowledge and a crystal ball that he says could only peer a few years into the future. So even though the potential for growth of his high tech business clearly existed, Johnson had no grandiose delusions about his start-up in the Butler County countryside.
<P>
"My crystal ball is good for about three years," Johnson says today at age 53. "I didn't think past three years. I figured if we survived those first three years, we would be OK."
<P>
He was quite right. Johnson's company, Saxonburg-based II-VI (pronounced Two-Six) Inc., grew from its modest beginnings to the present state as a market leader in the manufacturing of laser components and materials. The laser industry is hot today because lasers help users become more efficient. Lasers help a manufacturer, for instance, speed up production while improving precision.  
<P>
So maybe that crystal ball provided more foresight than Johnson lets on.
<P>
Look at the II-VI of today: It employs more than 200 people at its Saxonburg plant and several hundred more around the world. With II-VI products selling in 35 countries, the company is a benchmark for other companies in the region that are trying to tap the global marketplace. In fact, II-VI was overseas long before many other companies of comparable size even thought about foreign markets. II-VI used distributors in Japan in the early '80s. Today, it maintains a       manufacturing facility in Singapore, a direct sales office in Japan and a distributor in Europe.
<P>
And then there's the earnings.      II-VI went public in 1987, and this year is No. 1 in Executive Report's sixth annual listing of Top 10 growth companies (see page 26). At presstime, the jury was still out on the investment community's reception of a secondary stock offering in October, but the company seems positioned well for future growth.
<P>
About 50 percent of II-VI sales come from foreign markets, where the company is entrenched as a market leader in optics for carbon dioxide lasers. Within the past year, II-VI also paid $2.4 million for Virgo Optics, a Sandoz Chemicals subsidiary with expertise in optics for the higher powered yttrium aluminum garnet or YAG lasers. YAG lasers are becoming more popular because power levels are increasing as costs decrease. Johnson's next task is establishing itself in the growing YAG market on par with        II-VI's presence in the carbon dioxide laser market. 
<P>
Looking back, Johnson says it was a combination of the entrepreneurial bug and his research background that pushed him into starting II-VI. He earned his bachelor's degree in electrical engineering from Purdue, added a master's from Massachusetts Institute of Technology and earned his Ph.D. from Illinois. 
<P>
Just prior to II-VI, Johnson was director of research and development for Essex International Inc., an automotive electrical and power distribution products manufacturer. Johnson oversaw three of the company's research groups at Mellon Institute. 
<P>
He considered other positions before starting his own business.       The original start-up capital for II-VI totaled about $125,000. The original location isn't far from the present Saxonburg plant that is currently being expanded by about 30 percent.
<P>
And the trim Johnson, with slicked-back hair, is staying put.           He loves what he does. So when          investment bankers ask him about retiring or selling the company, Johnson laughs.
<P>
"We are having too much fun doing this," Johnson says. "There is enthusiasm. We know we have good opportunities, and we have the ability to step up and seize them." 
<hr>
<P>
<B><font size =+2>Robert Duggan Has<br> 
S&T Bancorp Thriving in a Tumultuous Industry</font></b><br>
<i>By Christopher Lawton</i>
<P>

S&T Bank is a community bank that doesn't really act like one. And some might say that banking industry veteran Robert Duggan, the CEO of S&T's parent corporation, is a banker who doesn't act like one. After all, this guy likes to watch Indy car racing.
<P>
So much for the stuffy banker      stereotypes.
<P>
Duggan, the 62-year-old CEO of Indiana County-based S&T Bancorp, is anything but conservative. He has S&T speeding along during a tumultuous period in the banking industry when mergers and acquisitions are common and competition between the banks that remain is like never before.
<P>
The banking industry is especially interesting in western Pennsylvania, where banks large and small are jockeying for business created by Cleveland-based National City's acquisition of a Pittsburgh staple: Integra Financial. Conventional wisdom says many individuals or businesses from western Pennsylvania who previously dealt with Integra won't let a Cleveland-based bank handle their money.
<P>
If they don't, their choices will be Mellon, PNC or one of the smaller banks -- Duggan's S&T being one. S&T Bank operates 34 offices within the six counties of Allegheny, Armstrong, Clearfield, Indiana, Jefferson and Westmoreland. It offers customers -- both commercial and individual -- the same services that many of the region's larger banks offer. It even offers some new products that some competitors don't offer. 
<P>
One of these is a 401(k) product Duggan rolled out in August for companies with as few as 25 employees. The full-service package offers Fidelity Mutual Funds and provides employees and employers with documentation services, employee education, daily valuation and 24-hour toll-free telephone access. Plan participants also can use the expertise of S&T trust officers to help them design and customize their investment choices.
<P>
"This plan has all of the retirement savings benefits that larger companies have been able to offer their employees," Duggan says. "This can be a cost-effective way for businesses to provide state-of-the-art benefit plans to their employees by letting S&T take care of the day-to-day administration of the plan."
<P>
And S&T has shown innovation on other fronts, such as attracting the individual customers. In that battle, accessibility is a key because the customer's time is limited. S&T has been out front since 1992, when it opened a branch office in a Foodland supermarket in Kittanning. Late this past summer, S&T opened a branch in a new Wal-Mart in Indiana, enabling S&T to reach a multitude of new customers each week while providing greater convenience to existing customers.
<P>
"Wal-Mart has built a superstore, one of their traditional stores that also encompasses a complete grocery store, and right in front of the 38 registers is one of our offices," says Duggan. "This new branch will enable us to provide products and services to people whose banks may be closed when they're out shopping."
<P>
The bank has shown steady growth, repeating this year as one of the region's Top 10 growth companies (see page 29). In 1991, S&T Bancorp acquired nine offices of Vanguard Savings and four offices of Atlantic Financial. In the process, S&T Bancorp saw its assets portfolio jump to close to $1.4 billion dollars.
<P>
"We also began to realize that  we're competing more and more for customers with all the other larger banks such as Mellon and PNC," says Duggan, who joined S&T in 1981 after 21 years with the federal reserve. 
<P>
In October, S&T opened a branch in Greensburg to expand its presence there. 
<P>
Duggan, like many other banking industry executives, isn't sure how the new presence of National City will affect previous Integra customers. But he is quick to point to a recent survey which argues that 60 percent of a bank's customers usually remain with that bank after a merger. If that's true, National City only has to worry about the 40 percent of Integra's previous customers looking for a better way to save and invest their money. And it should probably worry about S&T Bank. 
<hr>
<P>
<B><font size =+2>Jim Hunter Guides Point Park<br>
Through a Crucial Period</font></b><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
<P>

James Oliver Hunter was serving as associate dean at the University of Pittsburgh School of Law back in 1983. His colleague at the school was       Mark Nordenberg, a member of the law school faculty who eventually became dean and now is interim chancellor at Pitt.
<P>
You might also recognize the name of the fellow who was the law school dean and Hunter's boss at Pitt: John E. Murray Jr. Ring a bell?
<P>
A decade later, all three men have coincidentally taken similar paths. Nordenberg is drawing praise from Pitt faculty members while guiding the school through turbulent times as     Pitt trustees search for a successor to     J. Dennis O'Connor.
<P>
Murray left Pitt last decade for Duquesne University, a school he revived from near death and now has strongly positioned for the future.
<P>
Hunter's path has taken him to Point Park College, the downtown school that was staggered this past summer by budget shortfalls and fast-declining enrollment.
<P>
The school saw enrollment drop    8 percent last year, creating a budget deficit that forced Point Park to tap into its endowment.
<P>
Six months later after being named "president for an interim period," it's evident that the savvy Hunter has been anything but a caretaker at Point Park. He stopped the budget bleeding while bringing a personal touch to the 35-year-old college. 
<P>
To stem the enrollment drop, Hunter personally signed letters that were mailed last summer to part-time students who had not re-enrolled at the school. He told them why he was there and why they should return and join him. Many did. 
<P>
He also hand-delivers funding proposals to Pittsburgh foundations, getting in a handshake and smile so his proposal doesn't blend in with the rest.
<P>
It's all about marketing, the same type that has helped Murray succeed at Duquesne.
<P>
"I think the circumstances John Murray faced when he went to Duquesne were more severe than what I faced at Point Park College," Hunter says. "In just a couple years, John was able to help the institution focus on its mission and stabilize the institution. It's the same formula here at Point Park. We have stabilized the institution financially."

<P>But much work still lies ahead. Point Park, like most private schools, is more expensive than state-funded schools. So Hunter must still try to grow enrollment as the less-expensive competitors try to lure away the same prospective students Point Park seeks.
<P>
Hunter says the Ridge administration's commitment to financial aid programs for college students helps his position. He also points to several quality programs -- such as performing arts, journalism and business administration -- on which Point Park can hang its hat.
<P>
The performing arts programs draw students internationally. Perhaps the school's most famous graduate was a journalism major who went show biz: comedian/actor Dennis Miller, a former Saturday Night Live cast member who has hosted HBO comedy specials and played opposite Michael Douglas and Demi Moore in the film "Disclosure." Another Point Park graduate, Melina Kanakaredes, played a recurring role opposite Jimmy Smits last year in ABC's top-rated NYPD Blue.
<P>
Others who passed through Point Park have turned up both in front of the cameras and behind the scenes in Hollywood. 
<P>
"You can't sell from an empty wagon," Hunter says. "The product must be one you believe in. I have found quite a few of those at Point Park. I have the easy job."
<P>
The future holds some other factors that Hunter says will help Point Park grow. Most notably, the former Bank Center, which for years has been a shuttered eyesore on Wood Street, will reopen in 1997 as a library for the college and a new business branch of the venerable Carnegie Library.
<P>
Then there's Lazarus, the department store chain that will anchor a new store one block from Point Park's new library, likely spurring further growth on Wood Street and definitely increasing the traffic flow past the college.
<P>
A search committee has begun work on finding a permanent successor to J. Matthew Simon, and Hunter is likely to end up on the short list of candidates. He already has many faculty members in his corner. At the very least, he will run the college into the fall of this year. His track record shows he'll run it well. <hr>
<P>
<B><font size =+2>Joe Bartolacci Touches<BR> 
All the Bases As Thrift Drug's Chief Legal Counsel</font></B><br>
<i>By Colleen Anna</I>
<P>

It surprised Joe Bartolacci when an executive "headhunter" called him in 1992 to ask if he was interested in interviewing with Thrift Drug for a position as general counsel. After all, guiding the legal strategy for a $1.5 billion company seemed like an unrealistic career goal for someone with the experience of the 32-year-old Bartolacci.
<P>
But Bartolacci got the job.
<P>
Today, he supervises a seven-     person law department. He negotiates acquisitions. He charts strategies that help guard the chain's market share during healthcare's move to managed care. He also chooses outside counsel to handle matters that might end up in litigation. 
<P>
"I focus on strategic priorities," Bartolacci says. "Thrift Drug recently acquired 100 stores in North Carolina. For months, I was totally devoted to negotiating that deal.
<P>
"Much of my time is also spent in strategic meetings on everything from plans for the future to selecting outside counsel."
<P>
Bartolacci has a unique background, which helped him land the Thrift job. He graduated in 1982 with an accounting degree from St. Vincent College in Latrobe and worked as a certified public accountant with Touche Ross (now Deloitte & Touche). Then came law school at the University of Pittsburgh and some years with a downtown firm.
<P>
Bartolacci liked accounting, but law intrigued him because he loved     to debate. At the negotiating table,    that can be a deadly combination: A numbers-cruncher who likes to argue.
<P>
And as chief counsel at Thrift, Bartolacci uses all of his knowledge     of both accounting and law to         develop and implement corporate strategy. Because Thrift Drug is one      of the many companies touched           by the rapidly changing healthcare industry, part of Bartolacci's cor-  porate development strategy includes government relations and lobbying efforts directed to state and federal regulatory agencies and committees and pharmacy boards.
<P>
It's the side of law he rarely saw when he worked for a firm.
<P>
"Working as an in-house counsel allows me to really get to see the full impact of legal actions," Bartolacci says. "As an attorney working for a variety of clients, you are essentially advising and documenting legal transactions. Now, I get to understand the full implications of each legal action. I know the business and I know the people involved. I have an interesting perspective because my client is also my employer."
<P>
Bartolacci was born in Milan, Italy and came to the United States when he was 2 years old. He grew up in New Kensington, and except for living in Shadyside for a brief time, has lived there his entire life.
<P>
His schedule is often very full. In addition to working long hours in the office at RIDC Park, Bartolacci teaches classes at Robert Morris College in downtown Pittsburgh. 
<P>
"I first taught accounting at St. Vincent," Bartolacci says. "Teaching is something I really enjoy doing. I've taught at least one class on legal or tax issues every semester for years. Teaching and law have a lot in common; you have to enjoy telling what you know to an audience," Bartolacci says. 
Bartolacci has a lot to tell.
<HR>
<P>
<B><font size =+2>Bob Cornell has Carved <BR>
Out His Niche With <BR>
Industrial Properties</font></b><br>
<i>By Colleen Anna</I>
<P>

Bob Cornell used to do what he does now, only for someone else. Now he does it for himself and his partners, and life at Pennsylvania Commercial Real Estate is great.
<P>
"Every real estate broker is an entrepreneur at heart," says the            44-year-old Cornell, who with several other brokers left Cushman & Wakefield in 1991 and started Penn-sylvania Commercial Real Estate.
<P>
"You start with nothing and generate sales," Cornell says. "Your success is directly related to your skill in putting the right people with the right properties."
<P>
Though the upheaval caused by top brokers leaving Cushman eventually led to the closing of the Pittsburgh office, Pennsylvania Commercial Real Estate continues to act as the regional representative for the national company. The main difference is that Cornell and his colleagues reap more benefits and have more individual control.  
<P>
And as one of the founding principals of the company, Cornell's deals have played a significant part in building the 4-year-old company into a major player in the regional real estate market. His niche is industrial properties.
<P>
"I understand the industrial real estate market," Cornell says. "I enjoy handling industrial properties. Industrial real estate demands that you focus on making the deal, not convincing someone that the property can be adjusted to meet specific needs."
<P>

<P>
Industrial real estate deals mostly pivot on successfully match-ing existing properties with clients. Since brokers are paid a percentage of property cost, the larger the deal, the better.
<P>
In the last few years, some significant properties have come on the market in the region. These properties have the larger square-footage and the amenities that manufacturers look for, 
<P>
such as loading docks, high ceilings, sprinkler systems and highway access.  Some of Cornell's recent deals include the 500,000 square-foot Peter J. Schmitt property in Youngstown, Ohio, which was recently purchased   by the May Co., the parent company   of Kaufmann's Department Stores. Cornell also brokered the 320,000 square-foot Charley Brothers warehouse in Greensburg, which was recently purchased by Parkway Food Services. 
<P>
Cornell can stay focused on industrial real estate partly because he can rely on the company's other brokers to handle areas outside of his expertise. That focus on industrial real estate has paid off for Cornell for the last three years, and he foresees continued success for at least another two or three years. Pittsburgh has ideal distribution location, located halfway between Chicago and New York. Overnight delivery runs of only 450 miles will reach 50 percent of the North American population.
<P>
"People are finally discovering Pittsburgh as a center for regional distribution," Cornell says. "It helps that the properties are available. We still lose business to places like Columbus, Ohio, and Harrisburg, but that is beginning to change."
<P>
The toughest part of his job, according to Cornell, is that sometimes he is the first to know that plants are closing and that workers will soon be out of their jobs.
<P>
"But I look at it this way. I have the opportunity and the responsibility       to find a new company to replace those jobs."
<HR>

 
                                         
