<B><font size=+2>Commitment to Quality
</font></B><br>
<B><font size =+1>Chamber Honors Firms Striving for World-Class Performance</font></b><br>

<i>By Shareen Berry</i>
<P>

Q-Net, part of the Greater Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce, started an awards program in 1993 to honor companies with methods in place to assure the quality of the goods and/or services they provide.
<P>
Q-Net was founded with the goal of making the Greater Pittsburgh area synonymous with world-class performance through the use of total quality processes.
<P>
The awards are a simplified version of the Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Awards, which have been presented annually by the Commerce Department since 1988. Winners of  the Baldrige and Pennsylvania    Quality Leadership awards are not     eligible for the Greater Pittsburgh  Total Quality Awards.
<P>
The awards competition is open to public or private organizations in Allegheny, Beaver, Butler, Washington and Westmoreland counties. 
<P>
Evaluations were performed by an independent board of examiners composed of public and private sector quality experts. A panel of judges, with experience in quality and business management, made final recommendations. On-site visits were conducted for those who passed the initial screening. 
<P>
The criteria this year included leadership, human resource development and management, management of process quality, and customer focus and satisfaction.
<P>
Although no company received the "highest achievement" award, we did have several repeat winners along with some new faces, including a school district.
<P>
An award presentation took place in November. Here are the companies that were honored:
<pre>
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: Bell Atlantic Network Services -Western Area
Location: Pittsburgh
Primary industry: Communications
Award: Significant Progress</font></i></pre>
<P>
The regulatory climate of the communications world during the past decade has forced a major shift from a monopolistic environment to heated competition.
Bell Atlantic Network Services -     Western Area, which once had a stronghold on the market, had to improve its total quality in order to stay ahead. The company began to monitor its quality in 1989 by initiating the Philip Crosby-based management system. That changed in 1994, when Bell Atlantic Network Services - Western Area switched to a Baldrige-based management program with hopes of even higher quality.
<P>Bell Atlantic is being recognized for significant progress by the Greater Pittsburgh Total Quality Awards.
<P>"Bell Atlantic's purpose in applying for the Greater Pittsburgh Total Quality Award is to gain expert perspective on how we can improve services to our customers," says Tim Richards, Bell Atlantic's vice president for network operations.
<P>The Network Services - Western Area is one of seven districts in the Keystone Region of Bell Atlantic. The region encompasses 984,648 residential lines and 433,036 business lines spanning from downtown Pittsburgh, west to the Ohio state line, north to Sharon, east to Indiana and south to the West Virginia state line.<P> <pre>
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: Development Dimensions International
Location: Bridgeville 
Primary industry: Human resources consulting 
Award: Significant Progress</font></i></pre>
<P>
Development Dimensions Inter-national helps organizations succeed by creating empowered, high-involvement work forces. Its clients number 12,000 worldwide, including 400 of the Fortune 500 companies.
<P>Over the past 26 years, Bridgeville-based DDI has grown to include more than 75 offices and affiliates in 23 countries and over 1,000 employees.
DDI has been able to improve the quality of its services during growth by using a value-driven change process. Its Total Quality Steering Committee -- which is made up of senior executives -- drives the continuous evaluation of all aspects of the firm. 
<P>Tangible results of the quality initiative include increased customer satisfaction and retention, better efficiency and reduced cycle time, high levels of employee satisfaction and outstanding financial and operational results.
DDI is being recognized for significant progress.
<P>"These achievements are the driving force behind DDI's outstanding customer satisfaction, improved processes, innovative products and remarkable corporate and financial growth," says William C. Byham, president and CEO of DDI. 
<P>More than 15 million people have been trained using DDI programs and materials, and DDI estimates that their newly acquired skills have influenced the work lives of more than 20 million employees.
<P><pre>
<I><font size =+1>Honoree: Mine Safety Appliances Co.,
 Safety Products Division
Location: Pittsburgh
Primary industry: Products for worker safety
Award: Significant Progress</font></i></pre>
<P>
Mine Safety Appliances Co. uses state-of-the-art technology to produce the highest quality materials and equipment used to make the workplaces more safe in a variety of industries.
<P>MSA combines this technological production with a program called Quality for a Safer Tomorrow. MSA is being honored for significant progress with its quality initiative.
<P>"Every auditing organization has helped us," says Thomas B. Hotopp, senior vice president and general manager of the safety products division. "We have been through the ISO 9001 and ISO 9002 processes, audits by many of our major customers, including Martin Marietta and others.  Each and every audit experience brings home several points that we recognize as opportunities for improvement." 
MSA designs and manufactures respirators, hard hats, protective clothing, hearing protectors, eye and face protectors, emergency care equipment, and over 4,000 other types of industrial equipment.  Each MSA product  must meet the requirements of individual governing agencies regulating that industry worldwide. 
<P><pre>
<I><font size =+1>Honoree: Green Tree Marriott
Location: Pittsburgh
Primary industry: Lodging/banquet
Award: Significant Progress</font></i></pre>
<P>Over 158,000 guests annually find a home away from home at the newly renovated Green Tree Marriott. Thousands more enter the hotel to dine or attend meetings, weddings or banquets. To ensure future visits from its customers, the hotel instituted a total quality management program to improve the rate of satisfaction.
<P>The hotel is being honored for making significant progress with its TQM program, which was designed   by the Green Tree Marriott's parent company, Pittsburgh-based Interstate Hotel Corp. 
<P>At the Greentree Marriott, management has increased customer satisfaction, improved operational efficiency and profits and increased market share. The TQM program is targeted at the hotel's staff of 360 people. It encourages the employees to increase enthusiasm and morale that, in turn, increases work production.
<P>"We have worked hard on Total Quality Management for a number of years now," says Ted Knighton, general manager. "We have found that the application format has helped us improve our results. " 
Although the Green Tree Marriott accommodates many overnight guests, it also provides service for more than 960 meetings, 70 weddings and  487,000 meals in its two restaurants, two lounges and 25,000 square feet of meeting space.
<P><pre>
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: Precise Technology 
Location: Pittsburgh
Primary industry: Custom injection molding
Award: Significant Progress</font></i></pre>
<P>Precise Technology is a custom injection molder that provides products and services to the packaging, healthcare and consumer markets. Its capabilities include product design, product engineering, mold building, injection molding and contract manufacturing.
<P>The key to its quality initiative is the ability of program team members to closely work with customers and achieve total quality. These program teams have representatives from every Precise function -- from engineering and mold making to production and quality control. The company is being honored for significant progress.
<P>"The experience has taught our organization more about the importance of quality in the workplace," says John Weeks, president and CEO. "By networking with other companies, this enables Precise to explore new ideas and methods that may improve the Precise Quality process." 
<P>Precise's headquarters, located in Pittsburgh, includes 25 corporate personnel, 62 plastic shop employees and 19 mold shop craftsmen. These employees, who average 18 years of service, constantly participate in updated training programs to preserve the corporation's high standards of operation.
<P><pre> 
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: Price Waterhouse
Location: Pittsburgh office
Primary industry: Accounting
Award: Significant Progress</font></i></pre>
<P>With a name like Price Water-house, some might say that quality is a foregone conclusion. But that doesn't stop the reputable Big Six accounting firm from constantly looking for improvement in the services it provides to clients.
<P>The 50,000 members of the Price Waterhouse staff, who work in 450 offices worldwide, accept total quality management as a business strategy for improvement on client consultation and operational strategy.
<P>"Achieving Total Quality is about continually improving," says James C. Stalder, managing partner in Pittsburgh. "We have applied for the Greater Pittsburgh Total Quality Awards each of the past three years. Without question, we have learned that no matter how good we get, there remains almost unlimited opportunity for incremental improvement."
<P>Last year, Price Waterhouse was the first accounting or law firm ever to be recognized by the Greater Pittsburgh Total Quality Awards. It was recognized for "Serious Commitment" to total quality, but moves up this year to "Significant Progress."
<P><pre>
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: Johnson & Higgins of Pa. Inc.
Location: Pittsburgh office
Primary industry: 
Insurance brokerage and benefits consulting
Award: Serious Commitment</font></i></pre>
<P>The insurance market is extremely competitive. Consequently, Johnson & Higgins must make a conscious effort to preserve its dominance among the top companies.
<P>J&H believes the key to success is in knowledgeable, dedicated employees who are able to thrive in the work environment the company provides. It is being honored for its serious commitment to total quality.
<P>"Quality is a never-ending process," says Roy T. Johnson, principal and senior vice president in Pittsburgh. "Johnson & Higgins is the one who reaps the benefits of providing a better quality work environment for all of its teammates."
<P>Johnson & Higgins was established in 1845 in New York.  Over the past 150 years it has opened 260 offices worldwide. As the largest privately held insurance brokerage and benefit consulting firm, it has exceeded $1 billion in revenues, posted five consecutive years of record growth in new business and maintained a solid record of client retention.
<P>J&H's Pittsburgh branch employs 123 people who assist clients in such brokerage and technical services as marketing, administration, loss control, claims management, actuarial consulting, risk management consulting, computerized risk information and employee benefit consulting and administration.
<P><pre> 
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: North Side Distribution Co.
Location: Pittsburgh
Primary Industry: Distribution/supply chain management
Award: Serious Commitment</font></i></pre>
<P>North Side Distribution Co. has a simple concept behind its total quality initiative: "Give the customer the lowest cost and best value."
NSD offers lower transportation rates, reduced administrative and operating costs, less traffic congestion at its centers and inventory management enhancements. It serves the nation's largest fast food chain: McDonald's.
<P>"This award provides important recognition for the work, dedication, and commitment of each North Side Distribution team member," says Edward Schreiber, general manager. "Their quality dedication to improving the work processes and company performance has brought us to a new level of operating excellence."
<P>North Side Distribution, a division of North Side Foods Corp., is an           8-year-old third-party redistribution organization that has managed to quickly grow in size and revenue. Last year alone, sales exceeded $6 million.
NSD works closely with 58 McDonald's vendors to supply the restaurant with paper, dry food, refrigerated food, frozen food and toys. In an effort to increase efficiency, NSD encourages the vendors to consolidate their products into one truck per restaurant. Its hub concept has been copied twice within the McDonald's family of suppliers.
<P>Early in 1992, NSD embarked on a journey toward improved quality by initiating a Crosby-based improvement process. NSD is being honored for a serious commitment to total quality.
<P><pre>
<i><font size =+1>Honoree: Pine-Richland School District
Location: Gibsonia
Primary industry: Education
Award: Serious Commitment</font></i></pre>
<P>The Pine-Richland School District believes that it is imperative to give children the opportunity to grow and flourish in an atmosphere geared towards quality education. The school district organized a Quality Steering Council to guide the district in the correct path toward total quality.
<P>The panel worked with curriculum, instruction, pupil services, management, personnel, support services and finances to form an integral program that offers the best caliber of education to the children. The district is being honored for making a serious commitment to total quality.
<P>"Our staff and community took a great leap of faith when we embarked on our training program and quality team approach to process improvement and problem solving," says George Szymanski, superintendent. 
<P>A two-day training session was developed during the summer of 1994 to help teachers, administrators and support staff to comprehend the importance of quality and process improvement.
<P>The Pine-Richland School District enrolls 2,539 students with enrollment increases each year of 150 students.




