<P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Who is No. 1? Who Knows? </font><br>
<font size =+1>The Significance of Marc Landing the Rite Aid Account Stretches Beyond Billings</font>
<i>By Richard Bierck</i></B>
<HR>
<P>

A full-sized canoe sits outside the office of Cliff Miller, an avid fisherman who also happens to be executive creative director of Ketchum Advertising. Above the canoe, covering a wall, is a huge photograph of a sylvan stretch of the upper Allegheny River.
<P>
Miller's visitors probably aren't completely surprised. They've already passed a Warhol-esque stack of more than a dozen wired televisions that leans like the Tower of Pisa and squawks a programmed stream of media consciousness like the Tower of Babble. Attentive visitors can hear the inane mutterings of that famous adman, Darren Stevens of "Bewitched."
<P>
And that's just the lobby of Ketchum's recently redecorated digs in PPG Place.
<P>
Across the Monongahela River, Marc Advertising is embarking on its own renovation, designed to make its Station Square offices conform with the agency's new team-oriented     structure. There are no canoes or river photos, but there is a diagram    describing Marc's new account       management structure hung proudly on a wall that likely will be torn down in the remodeling. 
<P>
CEO Tony Bucci touts the superiority of the new structure over more traditional setups. But Bucci is even prouder of another recent achievement: After an arduous and costly pitch last summer, Marc clinched the Rite Aid account -- a chunk of business that, according to Bucci, will escalate Marc's billings beyond those of any other agency in the Pittsburgh market.
<P>
After nailing the account in June, Marc promptly heralded itself as moving to the "top spot as the city's largest agency." It called the business of Camp Hill, Pa.-based Rite Aid "the largest ad account currently being handled by any Pittsburgh agency." Read that as a sinister grin aimed across the river at -- you guessed it -- Cliff Miller and his colleagues at venerable Ketchum.
<P>
At Ketchum, word of Marc's Rite Aid coup was about as welcome as a client at a creative brainstorming session. Executives at Ketchum, which for years enjoyed top billings, now insist that other gauges may be more indicative of an agency's size and clout.
<P>
"We've got 250 employees in this building," says Jim Ficco, president of Ketchum Pittsburgh, referring to the Pittsburgh headquarters of Ketchum Communications, a national company with international offices and affiliates. Marc has about 130 employees. Ficco's attitude is clear: We're still the straw that stirs the drink in Pittsburgh's advertising community.
<P>
Arguments aside, the talk of which agency is No. 1 in the Pittsburgh market has seemed to cloud one important footnote to Marc's landing of the Rite Aid account: Bringing a national account of that stature to Pittsburgh sure won't hurt the reputation of the collective creative talent here. That's why competitors were quick to offer pats on the back when Marc landed Rite Aid. Letters offering congratulations flowed in.
<P>
"They were excited for us," Bucci says. "There are very few agencies who could compete for that piece of business, and other agencies were glad to see a local agency bring it into town. There were agencies in other cities competing for it, so its coming here reinforces the level of advertising in Pittsburgh.
<P>
"There were only a few companies we didn't get a letter from,'' Bucci says.
<P>
<h2>The Billings Scoreboard</h2>
Do billings paint a true picture of an agency?
<P>
"Billings tell you absolutely nothing about what an advertising agency is worth," says Paul Alvarez, president, chairman and CEO of Ketchum Communications. "Billings [figures] are a reflection of media spending. But there are so many ways to get paid -- some agencies are paid by straight hourly rates."
<P>
Alvarez's disdain for his industry's tendency to play fast and loose with revenue figures is common -- most of the ad executives interviewed for this article expressed similar sentiments. The fact is, it is impossible to compare figures of volume and profitability with complete confidence. 
<P>
There are a number of reasons for this, the main one being that most, if not all, ad agencies are privately held companies, and they use varying methods to calculate size and revenue. Even when agencies' statements about their billings are accurate, this accuracy is relative. Agencies earn only a fraction of what they say they do, and that's when they're telling the truth.
<P>
Why? Because the industry has a standard practice of inflating revenues more than six-fold. Instead of reporting the actual amount of money that agencies collect from clients, they multiply their gross revenues by 6.667. This figure is known as "capitalized billings."
<P>
Agencies do this disingenuous, across-the-board tinkering to boost their revenues to a more impressive level, reminiscent of 10 to 15 years ago when they got a straight 15 percent commission on the dollar amount of the ads they placed. Since the early 1980s, margins have narrowed nationwide, making life tougher on ad folks.
<P>
With business dwindling, it's more necessary than ever for agencies to wear fiscal platform shoes to look lucrative so they can bag accounts.  Pittsburgh is no exception. It's survival of the fittest.
<P>
"The landscape is littered with agencies that have died," says advertising industry veteran John McGrath, a former media buyer for the nation's largest agency, Leo Burnett Co. of Chicago. McGrath, now a professor of marketing at the University of Pittsburgh at Johnstown, says agencies now live by the motto "Grow or die."
<P>
<h2>Who's on First?</h2>
Far and away the two biggest survivors in the shrinking Pittsburgh market are Marc and Ketchum. A CPA with a lot of time, and the agencies' full cooperation, could calculate which one is bigger in terms of gross revenues, but this would say nothing about profitability or solvency.
<P>
Marc reports 1994 capitalized billings of $80 million. Ketchum Pittsburgh claims $94 million. Aiming to top Ketchum's figure, Marc asserted last summer that the addition of  the Rite Aid account, "estimated to be worth $50 million in annual [capitalized] billings,"  would make Marc "the region's largest ad agency."
<P>
In September, the agency's revised figure for capitalized billings from the Rite Aid account was dropped to $40 million. Therefore, Marc's actual annual gross revenues from the account would be about $6 million, the quotient of $40 million divided by 6.667.
<P>
Though Marc and Ketchum may be close to the same size in capitalized billings, they are distinctly different in many other respects.
<P>
Founded 80 years ago, Ketchum has reigned supreme as the city's single shop of national renown, being the headquarters for Ketchum Commu-nications, the nation's 22nd largest advertising/public relations company. Clients of Ketchum Pittsburgh include PNC Corp. (Ketchum's first), PPG Industries, Eat'n Park, Heinz USA, the Pittsburgh Pirates, Westinghouse and Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania.
<P>
Marc, established in 1955, is   largely a retail agency, with clients including ServiceStar, Long John Silver's, Pearle Vision, DeBartolo Malls, HealthAmerica, the Pittsburgh Zoo and United Way.
<P>
In an interview this fall, Bucci downshifted briefly from the high-gear boasting he was doing last summer.
<P>
"The truth is, it isn't that important externally," Bucci says. "What's important for us, what has been an internal goal for us ... is that we have been growing so well. If we became  No. 1 because Ketchum lost $40 million, that would not be significant."
<P>
Because Ketchum already represents Thrift Drug, it didn't pitch the Rite Aid account. But if Ketchum had, it doubtless could have weathered the high costs involved if it had failed to get the business.
<P>
But if Marc had failed to land the account, the agency might have taken a big hit. In addition to countless hours of staff time spent on creative offerings for the review, Bucci says, Marc spent "well into six figures" on outside services, including production of costly television ads. Quips Bucci:  "You can't cross a ditch half at a time."
<P>
It paid off. Michael J. Foulkes, marketing director for Rite Aid, says Marc was selected over larger agencies for several reasons. 
<P>
"Marc, in terms of their overall package, was by far the best, and they had a strategic approach to our business and our situation," Foulkes says.
<P>
<h2>Swing, Batter</h2>

Although it seems not to have been a factor in winning the Rite Aid business, Marc's resources are basically local. Ketchum counts among their top strengths both national and international presence.
<P>
"Pittsburgh's not being the communications hub of the world means you don't look to Pittsburgh as the place where all the creative advertising standards are set,'' says Alvarez, a Greensburg native.
<P>
Ketchum executives pepper discussions about Ketchum Pittsburgh with references to Ketchum Com-munications' resources, which include offices in Atlanta, Chicago, Los Angeles, Miami, New York, San Francisco and Washington, plus international offices and affiliates.
<P>
But Ketchum Communications has, in some ways, been hampered from effectively pooling far-flung resources because the different offices have often worked independently. Alvarez says that there's an effort afoot to "to try to do a lot more sharing of talent between offices."
<P>
While Marc was retooling itself into client teams -- a scheme in which clients can communicate directly with virtually any member of the team serving them -- Ketchum was making some structural changes of its own. It was changing over from the traditional structure to an account planning approach which, like Marc's new structure, assigns teams to accounts. The account-planning approach is more linear and involves upper management in more matters than the traditional structure.
<P>
Ketchum's reconfiguration evidently sat well with Heinz USA, which awarded accounts for ketchup, steak sauce and its gravy products to Ketchum a year ago after parting company with Leo Burnett.
<P>
"We needed a different kind of agency with different kinds of skills," says Brian Ruder, president of Heinz USA Retail Products Group. "[Burnett] was looking for something like Nike or Nintendo, where you have one idea and advertise the heck out of it. We were looking for more guerrilla marketing for each of our businesses."
<P>

<h2>The Next Tier</h2>

<P>
Ketchum and Marc are not the only games in town, advertising-wise. But most, if not all, of Pittsburgh's other larger agencies are midsized -- a size that McGrath, the Pitt-Johnstown professor, says is a dangerous one.
<P>
"The midsized companies that cannot demonstrate that they're better than small shops will become extinct. Those that survive are the best of the best," says McGrath.
<P>
Some of the larger Pittsburgh agencies that trail Marc and Ketchum in capitalized billings survive by threading specialized expertise into market fissures. Others have undertaken mergers to consolidate the various types of experience needed to land, and maintain, targeted accounts.
<P>
It's a horse race for third place. In close contention are Hallmark-Tassone, whose merged components posted capitalized billings in 1994 totaling about $32 million; the St. George Group, which is reporting the same figure, and Blattner/Brunner, which posted capitalized billings of about $30 million last year.
<P>
A few weeks after the merger that created Hallmark/Tassone Inc. in December 1994, the newly formed company absorbed all six employees of the Van Dine Group. In March, the company added the four members of Point Communications. The result is an agency with about 60 employees, now housed in Gateway Center.
<P>
"This tripled Tassone Stevenson's size, essentially," says Tim Tassone, CEO of Hallmark/Tassone.
<P>
The goal of the merger was to get new business. In the short run, Tassone says, they lost some clients "who felt that we had become too big for them," including C&C Lumber and the Baierl Auto Group. "But since the merger, we've picked up Sani-Dairy of Johnstown and ATI."
<P>
This fall, Hallmark/Tassone signed the Pittsburgh Penguins and WQED.
<P>
Reporting the same amount in 1994 billings, the St. George Group handles highly visible clients such as Kennywood Corp. and the Italian Oven. Recently, the St. George Group has developed a marketing specialty in new product roll-outs -- advertising and testing consumer responses.
<P>
The agency used this technique for a new lens product of PPG Industries' Transitions Group, headquartered in Tampa, Fla. "We started work on it as a product that was being worked on by PPG, and we got in on the initial consumer design and testing,'' says George Garber, president.
<P>
The Transitions account is one of several recent additions that filled the void when Foodland left St. George. "Even with that occurring, we've had slight growth," says Garber.
<P>
Falling slightly behind in the race for third is Blattner/Brunner, with a client roster that includes the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, Ladbroke Racing PA, Phipps Conservatory, Pittsburgh Paints and Mellon Retail Financial Services. The company also represents the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
<P>
The agency was formed in 1978 by CEO Joseph Blattner, who had another agency, and Michael J. Brunner, then one of Blattner's clients. Over the past five years, the agency has sought to increase its profile by plastering its self-moniker, "the killer B's," on billboards depicting two bees.
<P>
Blattner/Brunner has made a substantial investment in computer technology for market research and in developing interactive ad products. "That's the tail that's going to wag the dog," says Blattner.
<P>
Running slightly behind these three companies in reported 1994   capitalized billings, with $28 million,   is Burson-Marsteller Pittsburgh, the local office of Burson-Marsteller   Inter-national (owned by Young & Rubicam Inc.).
<P>
Clients of the Pittsburgh office include Federated Investors, Allegheny General Hospital, Cooper Industries, Gateway Center and, most recently, the Pittsburgh Foundation.
<P>
"We may have local billings of    $28 million, but we utilize worldwide offices extensively," says Laura Gongos, executive vice president and general manager, referring to the umbrella company's network of international offices that make Burson, like Ketchum, well positioned to expand and service clients outside the area. 
<P>
"The business available in Pittsburgh is shrinking and Pittsburgh agencies here are being forced to look outside this market," Gongos says, noting that 60 percent of the Pittsburgh office's business comes from outside the market.
<P>
And, like Ketchum, the agency is large enough, by virtue of its parent company, to avoid competition with small shops for small accounts. Gongos also stresses the resource of Young & Rubicam's massive electronic data base.
<P>
It's a plus. McGrath says that agencies belonging to multinational umbrella companies have the advantage of appealing to Fortune 500 companies seeking access in the expanding global consumer market.
<P>
"Advertising is a mature product, and we're in the mature stage of the life cycle. It's not rocket science anymore to create advertising. It now comes down to market share," he says.
<P>
McGrath says it is midsized agencies, with fewer than 50 employees, that face the ravages of underselling by small shops armed with what has become the nuclear weapon of Mom-and-Pop advertising: graphics software for personal computers. These programs enable the best of small shops and sole practitioners working out of their homes to produce quality work.
<P>
"They're stealing away work," says McGrath. "Many midsized agencies are too big to be efficient or local and too small to be international."
<P>

<h2>Deciding Factor</h2>

In Pittsburgh, 200 to 300 entities call themselves advertising agencies. Some are shops with less than five employees, and many others are individuals working at home and contracting out various services. 
<P>
To protect themselves from the competition from above and below, some firms have developed unusual niches to develop and hold specific clienteles.
<P>
One example is Krome Commu-nications Inc., which reports 1994 capitalized billings of $12 million.
<P>
Krome has a solid base of local clients that evidently prefer to work with an agency of comparable size. These include several community banks, accounting firms and the law firm of Dickie, McCamey & Chilcote.
<P>
Yet Krome competes with the likes of Ketchum, Marc and Burson-Marsteller for corporate business, too. Its corporate clients include Calgon Carbon, Allied Security and Bayer's industrial rubber products group. Krome vice president Bob Neville argues that agencies the size of his offer clients "a more direct relationship."
<P>
Despite what the agencies say is important in the market, clients themselves cast the most important votes each time they choose an agency based on their own business needs.  
<P>

<HR>
