<a href="../zine/1195.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Update.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><p>

<b><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>Blue Cross Executive Helped Shape <BR> Both His Company and the Community</FONT><br><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE><br>
<i></i></B>
<hr>

<P>
Every time the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater faced its next challenge, managing director Steven Libman would pick up the telephone and fill   in Eugene Barone, the long-time chair of the Pittsburgh Ballet's board of directors.
<P>
Every time, Mr. Barone responded as if the world revolved around the  ballet.
<P>
"He made me feel like it was the most important part of his day, even though I knew that it wasn't," Libman says. "I knew when he hung up that he had more important matters, whether it be for Blue Cross or for another board he was on."
<P>
But that was classic Eugene Barone, constantly concerned about others. That's only one of the reasons why Mr. Barone's passing this fall was such a loss for the region he cherished.
<P>
Mr. Barone died suddenly Sept. 22 at his home in Rector, Westmoreland County. He was 61.
<P>
"He was a man of energy, commitment, inspiration and motivation," says William M. Lowry, who succeeded Barone as president and CEO of Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania.
<P>
Mr. Barone joined Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania in 1958 as a sales representative and quickly worked his way up through the company. He was named vice president of marketing in 1972 and became senior vice president in 1980.
<P>
After Mr. Barone became president and chief executive officer of Blue Cross in 1984, the healthcare insurer cemented its dominant position in    the western Pennsylvania marketplace. The company's revenues grew from $1.1 billion annually to $2.4 billion.
<P>
The Blue Cross board of directors elected Barone chairman of the    board, president and chief executive officer in 1992.
<P>
But Barone's hand was felt in more than the business side at Blue Cross. During his tenure, Blue Cross developed a number of successful programs aimed at providing affordable healthcare coverage to economically disadvantaged segments of the community.
<P>
The Caring Program for Children, which provides free healthcare coverage to children of low-income families, and Blue Cross' Special Care program, which provides coverage for the working uninsured, have served as models for other parts of the country. Both programs have been replicated in other parts of the country by a number of Blue Cross and Blue Shield companies.
<P>
In addition to his responsibilities with Blue Cross of Western Pennsyl-vania, Mr. Barone was appointed chairman of the board of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of the National Capital Area, Washington, D.C., in October 1993. He still held that position at the time of his death.
<P>
"He worked hard and motivated others to do the same," Lowry says. "He was generous with his time and was committed seven days a week to the corporation and the community."
<P>
Mr. Barone also was a strong supporter of the arts, evidenced by the five years during which he chaired the Pittsburgh Ballet board. Observers say Mr. Barone truly believed he must give back to the community and encouraged others to do the same.
<P>
"He would use the power of the chair effectively," Libman says. "When he would recruit someone to serve on the board, he would look them in the eye, and you could just sense the passion that he had for the job."
<P>
Mr. Barone was a native of Pittsburgh and earned his bachelor's and master's degrees from the University of Pittsburgh. He remained a passionate fan of University of Pittsburgh athletics, and also served on the school's board of trustees.
<P>Mr. Barone is survived by his wife, Janice; three children: Suzanne Barone of Bethesda, Md., Sandy Barone of Crofton, Md., and Sherry Javens of Monaca; five grandchildren; his mother, Frances Barone, and one sister, Dolores Chiocchi.
<P>
<HR>

<h3>Contributions to the Caring Foundation</h3>

The Barone family has asked that 
those wishing to remember 
Mr. Barone direct contributions to: 
<P>
Western Pennsylvania<BR> 
Caring Foundation<BR>  
500 Wood St. <BR> 
Pittsburgh, Pa. 15222. <p>
The Caring Foundation funds the 
Caring Program for Children.

