<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Feature.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Updates.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Update.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>What's in a Name?</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Corporate Sponsorship Goes Beyond What's in It for Me, <BR>
But That's Certainly Part of It</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i></b>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE>
<HR>
<P>                                                        
It's hard, these days, to find something that's not commercial. Events, venues, interludes -- nothing, it seems, is logo free. The marketers of the world go to work every day and come up with more vehicles to brand with corporate image. 
<P>
Though much accused of being out of step with other areas of the country, Pittsburgh is no exception. The Thrift Drug Classic. IC Light Amphitheater. The Coca-Cola Star Lake Amphitheater. 
<P>
In fact, it might be said it started here: Andrew Carnegie begat a great tradition of philanthropy nationwide. Carnegie Mellon University. The Carnegie Library, Museum of Art, Science Center.  Carnegie, the Town of.
<P>
But in these days of corporate cost cutting and, more critically, in the wake of Pittsburgh's loss of several corporate headquarters, can sponsorship levels remain high?
<P>
Yes and no. Sponsorship, chosen correctly, can still pack amazing bang for the corporate buck. But sponsors, pressed with increasing requests, are becoming choosier. In response, entities seeking sponsorship are having to become more marketing driven, providing measurable results to would-be sponsors. And they're having to drive to more places, because smaller amounts from more corporations now make up the funding pot.
<P>

<h2>Bang for the Bucs</h2>

"We've played a big role in the community since 1889," says Jim Cameron, vice president of sales and marketing for Cameron Coca-Cola, which has named Star Lake Amphitheater after its brand and abundantly supports other local organizations, among them the Pirates and the Steelers. "We don't expect that just because we're involved, [the consumer] will go out and buy 10 cases of Coke. But we hope they will associate that involvement with us."
<P>
Still, Cameron is looking for more than a warm feeling when he chooses a   sponsorship.
<P>
"We look at what kind of visibility it can generate, and how we can take that visibility and translate it into     volume," says Cameron. "We try to make everything have a value, but it does get tough."
<P>
Cameron Coca-Cola, which works with both Steelers and Pirates, is currently running a picture of Steelers linebacker Greg Lloyd, along with a chance to order discounted Steeler merchandise, on the back of their 12-pack packaging. It's a service to Coca-Cola, to Cameron's customers and to the Steelers. The Steelers' Joe Gordon, director of communications, says it's more than a win-win situation.
<P>
"We win at least twice. There's a  visibility benefit, building and enhancing our fan base. We sell merchandise. And we win a third time, because we get the income from licensing and royalties," says Gordon.
<P>
Sports teams make good sense to Cameron, who says the vast majority of product relationships are made before age 18. Coca-Cola's target audience is ages 12 to 24. Due to Pitts-burgh's older demographic, Cameron must also appeal to other age groups. So he uses venues like the Coca-Cola Star Lake Amphitheater, with which the company just signed their second five-year contract to sponsor, and the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.
<P>
"It's such an intangible," says Cameron. "We think the relationship the consumer has with these events  has a lot more credibility than straight    advertising."
<P>

<h2>Great Expectations</h2>

<P>
There are, however, great strides being made on both sides to define this intangible.
"The days of having to prove     neither your worth or your cause are gone," says Deb Magness, spokes-woman for Heinz USA., which gets more than 1,000 requests annually for everything from food donations to dollars. "Even the smallest request now says 'Here's my cause, please send me x dollars, and here's what I'll give you for funding me.' "
<P>
Magness says that's the beauty of Heinz Baby Foods' Miracle Labels for Kids programs, in which hospitals across the country motivate parents to collect labels from baby food jars and bring them to the hospital, which redeems them for six cents each. 
<P>
"It's really helped us assist hospitals, get our messages out and maintain brand loyalty over generations of infants," says Magness. "The hospitals realize they can generate dollars by promoting our product. But they're not just working on our behalf, because they realize they have something to say and they have parents walking through their doors to redeem those labels."
<P>
Since the program's inception 15 years ago, hospitals have collected approximately 60 million labels, for a collective $5 million. 
<P>
"We're willing to write out the check, but the hospital needs to        realize that work goes along with that," says Magness.
<P>
Forced to ante up, organizations are utilizing board members and hiring marketing professionals to help them suit up for the marketing games. 
<P>
"The Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra is 100 years old and I don't go back that far, but I know that Carnegie and Heinz were involved," says Gideon Toeplitz, managing director of the PSO. "They decided Pittsburgh needed a symphony and raised the $2,000 they needed to start it that first year."
<P>
But in the past few years the symphony has had to develop a sophisticated sponsorship program to continue raising the $1.5 million (6.5 percent of their $23 million annual budget), for which they count on the corporate community. 
<P>
"We sit with corporations and say 'We are interested in satisfying your marketing needs.' Not just their phil-anthropic needs, but a deal that gives them visibility in the right time and  place," says Toeplitz. To that end, the symphony can offer any combination of a number of tools -- advertising in the program, direct mail, newspapers or radio, functions before and after the concert,  tickets, printed logos on tickets or ticket envelopes. The program, which Toeplitz says can apply to everyone from Heinz (which just wrote a $150,000 check for sponsorship of the PSO Pops on PBS) to the laundry down the street.
<P>
"We have developed a chart, and they must understand that if they pay for a hamburger they get a hamburger, and if they pay for a steak they get a steak," says Toeplitz. 
<P>
Their efforts have been sophisticated enough to garner a 10 percent increase in corporate funding each       of the past six years, increasing the    pot from $900,000 six years ago to   $1.2 million today. Generating even more will be an in-house closed circuit television system that will broadcast coming attractions and give credit to sponsors over monitors set up throughout the lobbies of Heinz Hall.
<P>
Television in Heinz Hall. Would Andrew Carnegie turn over in his grave?
<P>

<h2>Artist's Ethic?</h2>

<P>
Maybe not. Carnegie, above all else, was a consummate business man.
<P>
"We are in the entertainment business, and therefore are competing with the Steelers, the Pirates and Star Lake for the same dollars," Toeplitz says. "If you are going to sit there and say we are an artistic organization and therefore we shouldn't do that, you will go broke in a hurry. We use the same methods, within good taste. We know how far the lines go and are not close enough to define them."
<P>
Others, however, say the line        has moved.
<P>
"Certain sponsors have products they promote, a car, say, or a candy   bar, that's their livelihood. There was a time when museums had a lot of   trouble parking a [promotional] car in front of the museum. It was worrying. But that's changing," says Phillip M. Johnston, whose full title is the Henry J. Heinz II Director of the Carnegie Museum of Art. "There's a fairly fine line about how to promote or present a work of art, and we have to be sensitive about relationships with artists."
<P>
In 1994, the Carnegie Museum of Art depended on fund raising for $3.7 million of its $6.7 million operating budget, which includes the Andy Warhol Museum. 
<P>
This year, much of the fund raising and programming focus has been on the Carnegie International exhibit, which opens this month. Another Andrew Carnegie legacy, the Inter-national was first staged in 1896 at a cost of $7,000. To ensure its continuation in 1995, the Museum of Art had to raise $1.4 million. A third of that is income from the A.W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust Endowment, and roughly another third is gifts from smaller funders, the Pennsylvania Council of the Arts and the National Endowment for the Arts. But $600,000 of that came from one corporate sponsor, PNC Corp., in "unrestricted funds," that is, cash.
<P>

<h2>Funding Strength</h2>

"We need a strong community to create a strong business environment," says Susan Bohn, executive vice president for corporate development and communications at PNC. "We can't    be myopic. The heart is the people        in the community, and they need       the arts, quality health care and education ... there's a lot to be said for why people gravitate to a community and stay there."
<P>
The link with the Carnegie in its 100th year won't hurt PNC either.
<P>
"This is one of the top three major exhibits of art internationally, and     the top national exhibit," says Bohn.    "It can bring recognition to our headquarters city."
<P>
And, therefore, to PNC Corp. The Museum of Art's Johnston says that research done after the 1989 Impressionism exhibit at the museum showed that about 50 percent of the visitors recognized Ford as the sponsor of the exhibit.
<P>
PNC's commitment goes beyond that $600,000. To make the association, PNC paid Ketchum Advertising to create an advertising campaign. An internal video newsmagazine, also paid for by the bank, will reach 21,000 PNC employees in 30 states. Kiosks with brochures will be set up in the majority of PNC's 137 branches in 11 counties surrounding the Carnegie. And the Carnegie projects in excess of 100,000 visitors.
<P>
"A good corporate sponsor can bring many tools of promotion which we wouldn't have access to," says Johnston. "Through their employees, branches and clients, they can go beyond anything we could buy. And it reaches these people directly -- our promotion is through ads and membership."
<P>
Bohn says the bank knew that its sponsorship couldn't begin and end with money -- they rarely do.
<P>
"It's not enough just to give dollars, but you have to be willing to give time and energy," says Bohn. 
<P>
Corporate sponsorship often takes a number of forms in a company. The larger ones, like PNC and Heinz, have nonprofit foundations to channel  philanthropy. But sponsorships are also taken on by the marketing departments, and by individuals    who bring pet causes to their management. The question becomes how to allocate money.
<P>
"It's a tough call," says Rick Rehak, regional marketing manager for McDonald's. "It often gets down to our experience with similar opportunities. We get a lot of help from across the country; we all pool information."
<P>
McDonald's is involved with the Pirates, the Steelers, the Bills (Buffalo is in Rehak's region) and, nationally, with the NFL. They also support the activities of the Ronald McDonald house, for families of hospitalized children, and are just kicking off a scholarship program with Pitt. And, says Rehak, individual operators are getting involved in their own communities at their own discretion, and with their own cash.
<P>
Still, regionally, says Rehak, the promotions that have longevity and promise are those that can motivate volume, like the associations with sports teams. (McDonald's largest audience is young males.)
<P>

<h2>Heart Strings, or Purse Strings?</h2>

Which is why many nonprofits are packaging themselves with sports teams. And with the increased competition for funds and increasing costs, the sports teams are pushing themselves to bigger and better promotions. The Steelers realized a 30 to 35 percent increase in marketing revenue in the past off-season, according to Gordon, 10 to 12 percent of which was an increase in consumer promotions. The rest was attributable to higher prices the team was able to command after a successful season. But Gordon says that no matter how the Steelers play, sponsors are loyal -- because the fans are.
<P>
Visibility is key. Take, for example, Thrift Drug's sponsorship of the cycling race the Thrift Drug Classic. Five years ago, Thrift paid more than  $350,000 to establish the race and nab title sponsorship, effectively making certain that their name was synonymous with Pittsburgh's international cycling event. 
<P>
"The Thrift Drug Classic offered the opportunity to have the total title sponsorship at ground level," says Bob Dyer, manager of new store marketing and support for Thrift Drug. "And being a health and wellness company, it parallels the company's attributes."
<P>
Dyer says research shows that for every dollar they spend, they get three times that much in public relations, mentions in the media plus the attention of 350,000 spectators. But it's hard to gage.
<P>
"There's nothing tangible that you can put your finger on. It doesn't show up at the register," says Dyer. "We know that we have to get our name out there in front of the competition."
<P>
It is naive to believe that corporations engage in corporate sponsorships just because it's the right thing to do. Dyer acknowledges that were the event not named for the company, they would not be in it.
<P>

<h2>The Buc Stops Here</h2>

Perhaps the one case in which corporate sponsorship comes closest to charity is with the Pittsburgh Pirates. The Pirates have 35 to 40 promotional games a year, making deals with corporations to sponsor giveaways to attract fans to the ballpark. The Pirates make no money on these deals, according to Mark Ferraco, sales manager, broadcasting and promotions, using them to bolster flagging attendance and create excitement. Both the Pirates and the Steelers get only the price of the tickets for the seats in the Stadium boxes -- out of  $53,000 per box the companies pay annually. The rest goes to the stadium authority. The real place corpo-rations support the Bucs is in their ownership.
<P>
"We're in a unique situation because the corporations in this       city show support by owning the     club and funding the losses," says  Steve Greenberg, Pirates' director of marketing.
<P>
Since 1985, a consortium including some of the city's largest companies and three private investors kept the team alive, until its recent proposed buyout by California newspaper heir Kevin McClatchy. Even in the proposed buyout, however, corporations are showing support. The H.J. Heinz Corporation pledged $5 million to McClatchy's effort, $1 million of which is chairman Tony O'Reilly's own money.
<P>
One can only assume Andrew Carnegie would have done the same.     Even in these days of change, being a good corporate citizen is just good business.

<P>
<hr>

