<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<br>
<a href="../zine/1195.Update.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Updates.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.Update.3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align = center><font size=+2>A Tough Sell</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Why Marketing is Crucial to Attracting Business Here
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Matthew Lucia
</i></b>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>

Tony Crumbley earns a living trying to attract business to Charlotte, N.C. Ask him about his competition, and he reels off a list without even approaching the Mason-Dixon Line.
<P>
"Atlanta, Tampa, Jacksonville, Austin, Richmond, Norfolk ... maybe Nashville," says Crumbley, vice president of research for the Charlotte Chamber of Commerce. "I don't think we would include Pittsburgh as a   competitor."
<P>
Not many growth cities do, even though the Pittsburgh region offers several factors that would seem to place it in the same league. For one, Pittsburgh enjoys ideal geographical placement for product distribution. Overnight delivery runs of only 450 miles will reach 50 percent of the North American population.
<P>
The region also boasts a stable work force, which is evidenced by the high percentage of owner-occupied housing. Companies that locate here spend less time and money training workers than they do in cities of comparable size.
<P>
So why the dearth of economic development? Here's one theory: To land a fish, you first have to bait your hook. Some observers say this region does a poor job of marketing itself, that is, attracting fish in the first place. 
<P>
"The result is misconception," says Crumbley. "I always thought Pitts-burgh was a dirty old town. That perception is probably a very common perception.
<P>
"We thought it was the biggest joke in the world when Rand McNally ranked Pittsburgh as America's most liveable city. I later found out, only because I started asking, that Pitts-burgh has gone through a dramatic transition.
<P>
"I know now there is infrastructure in place," Crumbley says. "Strong arts. Strong cultural amenities. Strong parks. The steel industry is gone, but that was the negative thing that made it dirty. You haven't marketed what's really there now. You haven't moved people past the misconception of the dirty old steel town."
<P>
Even Penn's Southwest Asso-      ciation, the arm of the Allegheny Policy Council that is charged with attracting business, acknowledges that its own research shows that the perceptions of Pittsburgh vary dramatically between those already here and those the region would like to attract.
<P>
"Companies recently located and long-term, mainstay companies have fairly consistent and positive views of the region," says Bell Atlantic vice   president Thomas E. Richards, who chairs Penn's Southwest Competitive Study Commission.
<P>
"Companies with the least exposure to and least knowledge of the region provide the most consistent negative evaluations," Richards says.
<h2>To Market or Not</h2>

Much of the burden of attracting new business falls on Penn's Southwest Association. Penn's Southwest president Jay Aldridge favors the personal touch over multimedia bombardment. Penn's Southwest hasn't waged a       traditional marketing campaign in close to a decade. Instead, Aldridge markets the region at trade seminars here and abroad.
<P>
"We limit our advertisements," Aldridge says. "By focusing our energies on the personal, we find a much greater level of reception."
<P>
In personal meetings, Aldridge can attempt to reel candidates in. And to do that, Penn's Southwest often gets help from companies that already are located here.
<P>
"We base the marketing effort on company success stories," says Bell Atlantic's Richards. 
<P>
But others point out that you can't pitch a company that has no interest in listening in the first place. Thus, it's important to position Pittsburgh in a manner that makes people want to listen. And that returns us to the question of traditional marketing. How much? What type? What's the theme? What markets?
<P>

<h2>Another Approach</h2>

Crumbley of the Charlotte Chamber of Commerce says one key to marketing his region is the step before the personal contact - It helps if they come to you. He    doesn't see companies that would perceive Pittsburgh as a dirty town seeking it out as a place to locate.
<P>
"For some companies, it's a quality of life issue," Crumbley says. "We get companies coming to Charlotte from New York not because our labor is cheap, but because people will come to Charlotte to work for them. These companies from New York have trouble attracting workers because people don't want to live and work in New York."
<P>
So one key is positioning Pittsburgh as a place where outsiders would want to be. Ronnie Savion and her colleagues at Elias/Savion Advertising faced a similar challenge in developing a marketing program for the Greater Pittsburgh Convention & Visitors Bureaus (see ads on page 31).
<P>
The goal was to attract convention business and tourists. The campaign promoted the region in newspapers in cities including Baltimore, Buffalo and Cleveland, in national magazines such as Better Homes & Garden and Reader's Digest, and in trade publications such as Travel Weekly and Destination. The campaign also included outdoor billboards.
<P>
The ads were colorful and clean-looking, with messages that Pittsburgh was both an entertaining and relaxing place to live.
<P>
"Our challenge was to totally delete from people's minds what they knew about Pittsburgh," Savion says. "Then once you get them here, their whole mind changes once they come through the Fort Pitt Tunnels."
<P>
Does such a strategy work?
<P>
Ask Brent Fewell, an environmental engineer who works for the downtown law firm Doepken Keevican & Weiss. He had never visited Pittsburgh before he relocated here from North Carolina two years ago.
<P>
"Being from the south," Fewell recalls, "I heard a lot about the steel legacy, what a dirty city Pittsburgh    was at one time and how it had        been somewhat cleaned up.  But I   really had nothing to go on until I came here.
<P>
"My first time into the city was via the Fort Pitt Tunnel," Fewell says. "When I came out on the other side, it was actually breathtaking to see the city. My initial impression was, 'Wow, what a beautiful location.' "
<P>
Savion says it's best to save the skyline for the personal encounters. When used on promotional materials, one city's skyline looks just like the rest.  
<P>
"If I flashed brochures in front of you for Cleveland, Philadelphia and Baltimore, we'd all look alike. It blurs together," Savion says.
<h2>The Future</h2>

It is likely any regional campaign will be delayed until the state develops its new ad campaign.
<P>
That means Aldridge's personal approach to marketing will continue without much enhancement, and that is not necessarily bad.
<P>
"We have attracted over 200 firms to the region," Aldridge says. "We periodically hold roundtable discussions  as a follow-up courtesy to these businesses. By inviting candidate indus-tries to sit in on these discussions, we afford them an opportunity to talk to representatives from firms recently in their position.
<P>
"We expose them to our best form of marketing," Aldridge says, "which is the body of successful firms now operating out of the Pittsburgh area."
<P>
In Aldridge's corner is Con-   gressman Ron Klink, a Democrat from Westmoreland County, who thinks established business executives are the best messengers. But in the same breath, Klink chastises corporate    powers-that-be.
<P>"The responsibility of recruitment lies in the hands of the captains of southwestern Pennsylvania's successful companies," Klink says.  "Not only must a greater effort be made to convince existing companies to stay, but those who are familiar with Pittsburgh's amenities should be blaring trumpets to the corners of the world. It's time for the captains of industry  to speak up."
<P>

<hr>

