<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<br>
<a href="../zine/1195.Update.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H1Updates.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align = center><font size=+2>Westward Flight</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>The Airport Corridor was Tight;  <BR>Now It is Loosening Up
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban
</i></b>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>

Ted Brooks works out of two offices, each an equal distance from his suburban Pittsburgh home. So when clients want to meet with the Tucker Arensberg attorney, he often lets them choose the location: Tucker Arensberg's downtown office in PPG Place or the firm's suburban office along the airport corridor in Moon Township.
<P>
For the clients, the decision often is a no-brainer.
<P>
"Many would rather come to the Moon office," Brooks says. "There is not as much traffic, parking is not hard to find, nor is it as expensive as downtown. It's all about convenience."
<P>
For Brooks and many others, the airport corridor has become a prime place to conduct business. In fact, for a while it was downright difficult to find a substantial amount of office space in the corridor. Of a total 5 million square feet of office space in the airport corridor, only about 400,000 square feet were available at midyear, according to Gold & Co.'s second quarter report. That translated to a vacancy rate of about 8 percent, well below the region-wide vacancy rate of 15.9 percent and substantially lower than vacancy rates for Monroeville (21.7 percent), the North Hills (18.4 percent) and greater downtown Pittsburgh (20.9 percent).
<P>
It's exactly that kind of low vacancy rate that eventually will drive new development in a market. But in the airport corridor, it never quite reached the breaking point. Now it's headed the other way.
<P>
"We were close," says Jeff Schultz, vice president of Grubb & Ellis. "But now, you have a lot of space coming back on the market. It's moving back to a tenant's market. The tenants will be doing the deals they want to do."
<P>
Within several months, Schultz and other realtors see about 550,000 to 600,000 square feet of space hitting the airport corridor market, pushing the vacancy rate up as much as 10 percent to 18 percent. 
<P>
Roadway Package Systems, for example, is moving into its own facility and freeing up about 200,000 square feet. Add in another 100,000 square feet formerly filled by Legent Corp., which was acquired over the summer by Computer Associates. And brokers expect Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania eventually to vacate as much as 140,000 square feet as it consolidates in what is now the Lazurus store in downtown Pittsburgh. 
<P>
The significance for the airport corridor is that it likely will take about three to four years, brokers estimate, for the vacated space to be absorbed.  Lease rates -- now likely to drop a bit in the airport corridor -- at midyear ranged from $22.75 per square foot for prime space to $10.25 at the lower end. 
<P>
As for undeveloped tracts of land, they'll stay undeveloped for now unless potential tenants drive development by expressing willingness to lock themselves into long-term commitments.
<P>
Right now, few tenants are willing to do that, and brokers don't expect the atmosphere to change.
<P>
"You won't see any speculative development," says Jeremy Kronman of Gold & Co.
<P>

<h2>The Undeveloped Property</h2>

Even though speculative development won't occur, brokers say the fact that the market is not demanding development does not mean that undeveloped sites should sit untouched. In fact, steps that are taken now to make the sites more marketable could spur a variety of development in the near future.
<P>
Off the top of his head, Ron Tarquinio of Tarquin Realty can list undeveloped sites totaling 2,000 to 3,000 acres in the airport corridor. He says none of the sites are ready for development, and other brokers agree that there are some big problems with the undeveloped property in the corridor. Most notable is the fact that most property is sorely lacking when it comes to characteristics developers demand: basics like utilities, access and level ground.
<P>
"When the new airport terminal opened, there was so much hype," Tarquinio recalls. "There were people running around, looking at all the sites, without understanding all the principles."
<P>
But most of the better sites are  already developed. And before developers can hang structural steel or pour concrete at the sites that are left, they are looking at a lengthy process in mere site preparation. 
<P>
"There is a difference between having land available and having product available," says John Hoy, regional managing director for the Rubenstein Co., a Philadelphia-based developer. "In the airport corridor, there is lots of land and very little product. When I say product, what I mean is accessible according to national standards. 
<P>
"You can't tell a national firm, 'Take this two-lane road and turn right at Homer's barn," Hoy says. "That's not the kind of directions a national firm will listen to."
<P>
And reaching a potential site is only part of the problem. As Tarquinio points out, developers want sites that are ready for construction. Raw property won't cut the mustard because of the extra costs incurred in moving tons of earth.
<P>
Time plays into the decision, too. Most companies that would construct a large campus facility, for example, don't like to wait the extra six months to a year that it will take to have a raw site ready for construction.
<P>
Bayer is constructing an 80,000-square-foot headquarters in the airport corridor, but the site is Bayer's already established campus facility in Robinson Township. Many amenities are already in place, unlike undeveloped sites.
<P>
"You could be a year away from starting a construction project that will take 18 months to complete," says Schultz of Grubb & Ellis. "It's very difficult for these companies to plan that far ahead, with growth and those types of projections. RPS was an exception."
<P>
Yes, it was.
<P>
On Sept. 6, RPS cut the ribbon at its new 350,000-square-foot facility on a 115-acre hilltop site in Moon Township. The $40 million project included substantial excavation and took about two years to complete. But the tradeoff is that by the end of this year, RPS will have all its corporate  staff under one roof for the first time since 1988.
<P>

<h2>An Airport Corridor Plan</h2>

In addition to being a broker, Tarquin Realty's Tarquinio also serves on the Conference on Real Estate of Southwestern Pennsylvania, a group of real estate-based trade organizations with a common goal to create a regional marketing entity that will help drive economic development. CRE's initial project focuses on the airport corridor, which CRE members believe is decades away from extensive growth.
<P>
"It's going to take a while," says CRE member Elaine Kirsch, a self-employed appraiser. "It will take a lot of effort, both public and private. This is not something that will be done in six months. You are looking at a bunch of potential roadblocks."
<P>
Robert Ady, president of P.H.H. Fantus, the world's largest relocation firm, offered a grim outlook when he visited the region a month before the midfield terminal opened in September 1992. Ady didn't like the existing infrastructure. He didn't like the lack of vision. He didn't like the feuding between municipalities. He didn't like much at all.
<P>
Ady's message: Don't expect the billion-dollar midfield terminal to generate much economic development until things are in order.
<P>
Tarquinio and others believe it all starts with a plan for the airport corridor, where some communities want development and the enhanced tax base that comes with it. Others want to remain the sleepy communities they currently are. 
<P>
No problem, according to Tarquinio. The important thing is to find out who wants what and proceed accordingly.
<P>
"If you don't want any growth, that's fine," he says. "Don't put an interchange in. There is more than enough property elsewhere."
<P>
And once the planning is ironed out, the region can move ahead with adding the basics that developers want -- the interchanges off existing highways and the utility service. Some observers go as far as pushing for a beltway highway system, even though opponents argue a beltway is impossible because of Pittsburgh's terrain.
<P>
"There is a lot of infrastructure that has to happen," says Schultz of Grubb & Ellis.
<P>

<h2>Edge City?</h2>

As edge cities go, the airport corridor definitely qualifies as it currently stands. But don't be misled. As Tarquinio and his CRE colleagues point out, the corridor still has eons to go before it will be fully developed. 
<P>
And slow development has some advantages. For instance, developers of the airport corridor can learn from problems that have crept up in similar regions across the country. Edge cities are nothing new. Over the past 20 years, a large portion of commercial real estate investment and development occurred in the dozens of what ended up being suburban downtowns.
<P>
White Plains, N.Y., and Stamford, Conn., with high-density employment, retail and entertainment centers are prime examples in the Northeast. Both grew out of their close proximity to Manhattan.
<P>
Some other examples are Costa Mesa, Calif., Tysons Corner, Va., and Perimeter Center in Atlanta. They grew because of access to one or more highways, a regional shopping mall and high-end single-family housing. 
<P>
These suburban downtowns were praised for being newer, safer and closer to both executive and worker housing than traditional downtowns. Now, experts say, some suburban downtowns are struggling. Prime corporate tenants are moving out. Office buildings are slipping from Class A to Class B status, no matter what improvements the owners make. 
<P>
What's more, traffic congestion, high costs and crime -- which corporations thought they left downtown  -- migrated to the edge cities.
<P>
The Pittsburgh airport corridor won't have those kinds of worries for years. In fact, it probably won't ever have those kinds of worries unless residential development picks up soon. Residential development is the one thing that's sorely missing in some parts of the airport corridor.
<P>
"We have an edge city without the population, which is very weird," says Kronman of Gold & Co. "We have a ghost edge city."
<P>
The airport corridor's residential market competes with the region's other growth areas, such as Cranberry and Peters townships, but slow residential growth hasn't deterred retailers in the airport corridor. Just look at Sam's Club and Wal-Mart.
<P>
Some even expect retail ventures to drive residential development. Usually, it's the other way around.
<P>
"The expense of excavating land is very high," says Theresa Rooney, who handles retail clients for Gold. "A residential developer does not have the financial wherewithal to move ahead with a project. Sometimes, the big boys have to go first and then the residential will follow."
<P>
There's no argument from Lawrence Simpson, director of marketing for Johnson/Schmidt & Associates, an architectural firm located in Robinson Township that works extensively with retail developers. Simpson also is president of the Pittsburgh chapter of the National Association of Industrial and Office Properties.
<P>
"When these retailers cite facilities, they base it on things such as wealth creation and job generation," Simpson says. "I have to believe that these retail developers know what they are looking for. This development in the airport corridor is an acknowledgement that developers are getting the retail in place in anticipation of future growth."
<P>

<hr>

