<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Update.3.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><FONT SIZE=+2> A Big Loss
</FONT SIZE><BR>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b><P>


<P align=center><font size=+1><b>Gene Barone was the Last of a<br> 
Dying Breed: The CEO Who Cared</b></font>
<HR>

<P>
When the recently retired chairman of Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania passed away in late September, a chapter of this region's history closed. Gene Barone served in an era when the term CEO was synonymous with community and civic leader.
<P>
Not anymore. Today's and tomorrow's CEOs are slaves to their shareholders and sometimes to their customers. Unless their shareholders and customers are almost exclusively the citizens of the community in which their enterprises are located, today's CEOs cannot afford to spend significant time or money to further the community's interest.
<P>
As successful corporations expand both their shareholder and customer bases, in many ways their "community" becomes the world instead of their headquarters city. With ever-advancing communications technologies, CEOs can embrace the world. A decade ago, a CEO's reach was effectively limited to the city or, at best, the region in which his company was located.
<P>
By century's end, all CEOs will be citizens of Planet Earth, rather than the specific cities where their companies are headquartered. Their interests as well as their satellite operations will span the globe. To survive, let alone prosper, today's CEO must develop a globalized perspective. Of necessity, the world will become his oyster!
<P>
Because of the Pittsburgh region's pervasive parochialism, we effectively insulated ourselves from globalization's ever-tightening grip on a corporate leader's resources. We believed erroneously that somehow our CEOs would be different. We hoped that the core value system that distinguishes this area from all others would sustain the corporate leader's absolute commitment to his community. Our logic was flawed. We forgot that most of today's CEOs are not Pittsburghers. They are not imbued with Pittsburgh's notorious community spirit.
<P>
As the community leadership paradigms shifted throughout the nation, Pittsburgh remained on course. But, we haven't cultivated           a cadre of emerging leaders whose interests are vested in the region.       Our corporate leaders in general do not have understudies who are prepared to fill the leadership void when  it evolves. A narrowing pool of     emerging and potential leaders is increasingly evident.
<P>
Gene Barone was one of the few remaining corporate leaders who served both his community and his corporation well. Name a cause. During his 10-year tenure at the helm of Blue Cross, Gene Barone was there providing leadership, ideas and funding. To say goodbye to him was for me to say goodbye to a way of doing business in this region.
<P>
Gene built his career and his company's success on a simple value -- caring. He cared about his business and customers, but he also cared about his employees and his local community. When Gene Barone passed away, Pittsburgh lost its social conscience, but hopefully, it did not lose its capacity to care.
<P>
Like the program he conceived to provide desperately needed health insurance to this region's disadvantaged youth, Gene's life was a "Caring Program." Originating here, the Caring Program spread to 12 other markets throughout the nation.
<P>
Now Pittsburgh needs another caring program. This one should be targeted at opening leadership opportunities and building leadership capacity among those individuals whose vested interest is this community. To rely solely on the leadership models of our past is to guarantee that we will not have a future.
<P>
A community-minded CEO is a rare commodity these days, but community-minded people with leadership potential still proliferate here. Gene was a leader who cared. He proved that socially conscious corporate executives can be extremely successful. He broke the paradigm and established caring as a fundamental core value of effective leadership. Hopefully, this community will follow his example and nurture those, like him, who care.
<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

