<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.Letters.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>Selling the Pirates
</font><BR>
<font size=+1>Is Baseball's Greed Helping to Keep the Pirates in Pittsburgh?
</font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<HR>
<P>
Sometime this fall, it finally dawned on major league baseball's owners that it was in their best interest to do what they can to keep the Pirates right where they are.
<P>
Roadblocks to selling the team disappeared, and just before this magazine went to press, the major league owners gave their preliminary blessing to newspaper heir Kevin McClatchy's bid to buy the Bucs. McClatchy pledged to keep the team in Pittsburgh, provided the city did its part and built a new stadium.
<P>
But even if McClatchy was unsuccessful in closing the deal, and at press time the deal was still tentative, could the Pirates eventually move? I think not.
<P>
Thank Arlen Specter for timely politics, and thank that age-old human characteristic: greed. Those combined factors are helping to keep the Pirates in Pittsburgh
<P>
A little over four years ago, it was Specter - the Republican U.S. senator from Pennsylvania - who attacked the 73-year-old antitrust exemption enjoyed by major league baseball. At that time, Specter slammed owners in baseball and other team sports for their increasing move to cable and pay-per-view television programming. He argued that the pro teams did not deserve antitrust exemptions when they are depriving the public of basic sports viewing.
<P>
Specter renewed his threats to lead a charge against the exemption in late September should the Pirates leave Pittsburgh. 
<P>
"I think it's baseball's obligation to keep the Pirates in Pittsburgh," Specter says. "If they don't, if they're going to run it like any other business, I don't think they have standing to get an antitrust exemption." 
<P>
Right now, the antitrust exemption allows the teams to pool television receipts and to engage in other cooperative business efforts normally prohibited by the antitrust laws. In other words, it allows the owners to make more money than they would without the exemption.
<P>
The last thing the owners want is to lose that exemption. They would lose income. And losing the exemption is not that far-fetched a scenario.
<P>
Let's face facts: The owners don't have much public support right now, and neither do the players due to the strike-shortened 1994 season. Specter, a presidential candidate, would enjoy some nice public relations by leading a measure that decreased income for baseball owners. After all, the players lose, too. The less the owners make, the less the players make. Many baseball fans would love that.
<P>
And that would only be the first bit of financial fallout for the owners if they allow baseball to leave Pittsburgh. In the backs of the owners' minds is league expansion. Outside of McClatchy, the remaining bidders for the Pirates consist of groups that want to move the team to markets that are prime for expansion before the year 2000.
<P>
The owners, who decided last winter to expand the league, will be well served. They will extract an expansion            fee of $150 million or higher from the new teams.  
<P>
Two markets mentioned include northern Virginia and Orlando, Fla., where the Pirates could have been headed if and when McClatchy failed.
<P>
The owners likely could have tacked a transfer fee to any ownership group that tried to move the Pirates, but it would have been nothing approaching the expansion fees they could collect from those markets by awarding them an expansion franchise two or three years from now.
<P>
In the end, McClatchy was the owners' man because he wanted to keep the team here. No hassles. No lawsuits that are the inevitable when a group tries to move a team, but is blocked. Some owners still are stinging from the aborted move of the San Francisco Giants to Tampa in 1993. Florida investors sued the league and used the lawsuits as leverage to land an expansion team.
<P>
In the end, it doesn't make financial sense for the major league owners to permit the Pirates to leave Pittsburgh. Ironically, instead of a lack of money pushing the Pirates out of town, it is money that helped keep the Pirates here.
<P>
So just because Ted Turner pays Rafael Belliard millions to hit his weight and George Steinbren-ner finds some of his best talent in halfway houses, that does not mean that baseball's owners don't know what they are doing.
<P>
It just took them a little while to figure it out in the case of the Pirates.
<P>

<hr>

