<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Letters </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"alt="Home"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"alt="Archives"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H6Letters.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<font size =+2><B> </B></font size>

<h2>Left Out</h2>
I was happy to see your report, "Competing for Cash" (September 1995), on the recent success being enjoyed by Pittsburgh educational institutions, which signals the continued vitality of the Pittsburgh region. Colleges and universities are indeed one of the chief factors in attracting business here, and it's wonderful to see our fellow institutions doing well.
<P>
However, there is a unique success story happening here at Pittsburgh's oldest private institution of higher education (and the country's third  oldest women's college), Chatham College, which your magazine completely missed.
<P>
Chatham's overall fund raising has increased 60 percent over the past two years, an unprecedented feat in our history. Contributions to our Alumnae Fund have increased 127 percent over the same period. Garnering nearly      $1 million in the past 18 months from local foundations for initiatives central to our programs has shown us that Pittsburgh has confidence in Chatham College. We are pleased to note as well that Chatham enrollment increased a robust 10 percent this year, after increasing 28 percent last year (triple the national rate for comparable colleges), another important sign of recent accomplishment.
<P>
Executive Report also failed to consider the percentage of alumni participation in fund raising, which, although not as immediately impressive as raw dollar figures, goes a long way toward predicting the future health of any college or university. Chatham, with a steady 37 percent of alumnae supporting the college through gifts in the past two years, is healthy indeed. This is the same measure by which foundations often decide to contribute larger gifts. By any measure, Chatham is a success story that must not be overlooked.
<h4>Hannah H. Kamin<br>
Chair<br>
Resources Committee<br>
Board of Trustees<br>
Chatham College<br>
</h4>
<HR>
<h2>Clean Air Act</h2>

The Publisher's Note on the ozone issue (September 1995) was well-written and accurate, and I think it will be a major boost to awareness on the ozone issue. It also turns out to be very timely with all of the attention being paid to exceedences and the auto emissions issue, and will help remind everyone that the problem is both more serious and more complex than it might otherwise appear.
<P>
The Department of Environmen-tal Protection is getting ready to seek input on strategies for addressing the ozone "problem." I'm concerned that as a result of the exceedences over the summer, we are going to be portrayed as having a "problem" with ozone, when in fact high ozone levels have only occurred on a small number of days that already were considered unhealthy because of the heat.
<P>
Moreover, in order to address this "problem," it is going to be assumed that utilities, businesses and\or drivers need to do more on a year-round basis, even though we don't have any definitive evidence on how much of the problem is being caused by transported air, whether NOx or VOC reductions will help or hurt, etc.
<P>
We must make sure that the issue is examined in as comprehensive a fashion as possible.
<h4>Harold Miller<BR>
Director<BR>
Southwestern Pennsylvania <BR>
Growth Alliance<BR></h4>
<HR>
<h2>Innovative Schools</h2>

I found Linda Dickerson's comments (August 1995 Publisher's Note) to be very insightful.
<P>
As a practicing superintendent, risk-taking is a way of life. Here at Latrobe, we are in the second of a three-year plan to implement technology as a tool to augment daily instruction. Our teachers selected software based on its alignment with our curriculum. The teachers are receiving comprehensive and sustained staff development in the use of hardware and software. This is a very expensive project, but we believe it is money    well spent. True education reform  must include some individualized instruction.
<P>
I could go into more detail, however I have another purpose for writing: Your comments aroused my   interest in your thoughts about choice and vouchers as promulgated by     Gov. Ridge.
<P>
My personal point of view is that fundamental change in schools must focus on three broad areas.
<OL>
<LI>We must lengthen the school day and increase the number of days students attend school so that we can provide additional time to cover the ever-expanding curriculum offerings.
<LI>Teachers must be given joint planning time to prepare for instruction and to develop performance assessment tasks.
<LI>We need to use technology to help to individualize instruction.
</OL>
With regard to the Governor's proposal, my concern is that it will do little to improve education and will expand the gap between the haves and the have-nots in our society. Further, the Governor's proposal exacerbates the equity funding issue.
<P>
On a larger scale, I, too, am concerned about the broader social implications resulting from the societal pressures. "The breakup of the family unit, a pervasive sense of hopelessness among disadvantaged populations of youth, exponential increases in teen pregnancies, and the emergence of burgeoning youth underclass" are all important problems that are difficult to solve. Without doubt, the status quo will not be an acceptable future course of action.
<h4>William D. Stavisky<br>
Superintendent<BR>
Greater Latrobe School District<BR></h4>


<HR>
