<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Letters.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>A Second Look
</FONT SIZE><br>
<font size=+1>In Hindsight, This Political Advertising Guru Agrees <br>That There is a Need for a New Approach
</font><br>
 <i>By John Brabender
</b></i>

<HR>

<P>
It is November 1994, the day before Election Day. For a political media firm, this is one of the strangest days of the year. After spending six months working nonstop, addicted to caffeine, on a never-ending ride of daily tracking polls, there was absolutely nothing to be done. At this point, tomorrow's outcome could no longer be changed.
<P>
Tomorrow would certainly be a long and tense day. We are the media firm of record for eleven Republican candidates, nine of whom are in races considered a toss-up, including the campaign of Rick Santorum challenging U.S. Sen. Harris Wofford, possibly the most closely watched race in the country.
<P>
About the only thing left to do is return phone calls. There are a number of calls from various members of the press wanting to know where we will be on election night in case they need comment. I tell them I'd comment now: If our candidate wins, it was the result of brilliant advertising. If our candidate loses, it was because we had a poor candidate. Most of them quickly understand that this is simply consultant humor.
<P>
USA Today wants to know if I think James Carville, Harris Wofford's chief consultant, is washed up if Wofford loses. Commenting on the work of another consultant is difficult, particularly when it's possible the consultant will beat you the next day. I call USA Today back and tell them I think Carville is brilliant, and did an excellent job for Wofford. If Santorum wins tomorrow, I'll say what I really think.
<P>
Then I see "the" message. A reporter wants my comment regarding a full-page advertisement that will run in major newspapers across the country tomorrow, written and paid for by Ketchum Communications. In the ad, Ketchum loudly and proudly proclaims that "We Don't Do That Kind of Advertising."
<P>
Evidently, the copy makes clear that Ketchum does not and will not engage in the disgusting practice of political advertising. Furthermore, Ketchum will be leading the fight to save Americans from this relentless assault of vile, false and misleading advertising. 
<P>
It had been a few days since I had the opportunity to spin a good story, and this one is too attractive to pass up. How dare Ketchum attack my colleagues? After spending years honing my skills, taking on some of the most devious political consultants in the world, this would be easy.
<P>
Any good media consultant knows that the best way to spin a story is to change the focus. I must somehow make Ketchum the villain. I could say that if Ketchum had put this much ingenuity and creativeness into their client's work they might not have lost the Digital account. Or maybe I should simply point out Ketchum's hypocrisy in using a negative advertisement to criticize negative advertising. 
<P>
Then it happens. Every hired gun's nightmare. I hesitate. It would have been easy to conclude that it was fatigue from the long months of campaign battle, or simply pre-election jitters. But the truth of the matter is that I hesitate because I know Ketchum is right. For some time I had become increasingly disappointed at the win-at-all-costs, slash-and-burn, take-no-prisoners approach of many in my  profession.
<P>
Most campaigns start on the high road. But too often, when you're two weeks out and the polls show you five points down, what would have been a lie yesterday is easily justified as the truth today. This was best illustrated locally when the Wofford campaign aired a TV commercial with video footage seeming to show Rick Santorum supporting the idea of raising the age for Social Security to 70. Wofford also held a press conference declaring Santorum's plan "a slap in the face at World War II veterans."
<P>
What few knew then was that Wofford's consultants had deceptively edited the video, eliminating a critical part, where Santorum makes it clear that his plan would only affect Social Security recipients 50 years from now. Immediately after Wofford's ad aired,  Santorum dropped in the polls, only to recover when newspapers across the state wrote that the Wofford commercial was false and misleading.
<P>
It is time for a reform of political advertising. It is time voters know with confidence that the content of a political commercial is factually correct. 
<P>
As I sit in my office on election eve, I think it's fair to say that Ketchum is trying to exploit the present situation to receive some favorable ink. But if their efforts help raise the standards of political advertising, I applaud and thank them.                                        
<P>
John Brabender is a principal of Pittsburgh-based Brabender Cox Ad-vertising and Direct Marketing.

<P>

<hr>

