<FONT SIZE=+2><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>

<h2>Property Assessments Revisited</h2>

So you think your real estate taxes are high? How about an assessment of $277,500? That's the latest assessment against the Sewickley home that Pittsburgh Penguins center Mario Lemieux purchased for $1.48 million in 1992.
<P>
Assessments typically amount to a quarter of the home's actual value. The assessment and respective millage rates then determine how much property tax the homeowner pays.
<P>
What's Lemieux paying for? The luxury of 11 bedrooms, eight bathrooms, six fireplaces and a three-car garage, all spread over 1.25 acres, according to Allegheny County assessment records.
<P>Some other assessments of note:
<UL>
<LI>Pirates president Mark Sauer's $920,000 home in Fox Chapel 
is assessed at $165,000. Assessors counted six bedrooms, six baths and a four-car garage, sitting on 6.7 acres. We hope the ceilings are high. Sauer has a 6-foot-7-inch son, Peter, who will play basketball for Stanford this season.
<LI>Steelers coach Bill Cowher also dropped anchor in Fox Chapel, paying $582,500 in 1992 for a four-bedroom home that is assessed at $135,000.
<LI>County Commissioner Tom Foerster still has his modest two-bedroom home in Pittsburgh. County records show no market value, but the assessed value is $17,375.
</UL>
<HR>

<h2>Building Up Cinema</h2>

Andrew Sproule remembers when Pittsburgh Filmmakers worked out of a hole in the wall on Craig Street, paying $70 in monthly rent to the University of Pittsburgh.
<P>
"We were sometimes looked down on because of the space we were in," says Sproule, the Filmmakers' director of public relations. "You never saw rodents, but you couldn't prove they hadn't been there the night before."
<P>
Well, only celluloid rodents would dare defile the Filmmakers' spanky new headquarters on Melwood Street in Oakland. The old digs had half the space of the new   facility, a former laboratory updated with $1 million given by various local foundations. The Filmmakers now boast new technology and spaces that the group hopes will continue to grow its educational programs in film and photography. The programs are linked with the likes of Pitt, Point Park, Carnegie Mellon, Carlow and Duquesne.
<P>
This semester's enrollment has already jumped, to 620 from 550 students last spring. But that's not unusual, according to director of education Brady Lewis, who says that enrollment has grown every year for the past 10 years. The new space, however, will allow the group to expand its class offerings by about 20 percent and add classes in hightech film editing on a newly purchased system.
<P>
"We had this 25-year-old arts organization that contuned to grow even though it was located in seriously distressed buildings," says Charlie Humphrey, executive director. "But our operations were largely self-sufficient: 83 percent of our budget was earned income."
<P>
In a world of arts organizations with their hands out, that looked good to funders, who anted up in style. Filmmakers plans to augment its traditional program at the downtown Fulton Theater with a "more artsy" cinema series in the new 110-seat screening room at the Melwood facility. The public will have their first chance to see the room during the Three Rivers Film Festival at the beginning of this month. Also planned are photography exhibits in an adjacent gallery.
<P>
"This will blow people away," says Sproule. "I believe we'll become as well known for our photography exhibits as for film."

<HR>

<h2>Have Car, Will Travel</h2>

What's your most prized possession? Chances are it is parked in the garage.
<P>
A recent poll showed that 65 percent of Americans would rather forego romance than spend one day of the week without their car. The poll, sponsored by Enterprise Rent-a-Car, queried drivers on the importance of their car in daily life.
<P>
Sixty percent of those polled said they would rather disconnect their telephone than spend one day of the week minus a vehicle. Of the same sampling, 73 percent would skip their morning coffee and 71 percent not watch television for a weekend rather than lose access to the car for one day.
<P>
Enterprise, which has carved out a niche by picking up customers and delivering them to their rental car, estimates that drivers will spend nearly three years of their lives driving for business and personal reasons. More than a third of all drivers hate being without their vehicle so much that they purposely delay needed maintenance, the Enterprise poll showed.
<P>

<HR>

