<a href="../zine/1195.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>Mojo Rising
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>A New Bloomfield Restaurant Combines Neighborhood<BR> Grace With Atypically Classy Food
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>
<HR>
<P>
Bloomfield is an area known for its spirit of community and vibrant main street. You can get a good meal, especially if what you want is a beer and a burger. But gastronomically, Bloomfield hasn't traversed much beyond that.
<P>
Now, there's a new kid classing up Liberty Avenue. Mojo Bay Bar and Bistro may look like the former Santucci's -- where this restaurant opened in July -- but look again. No, don't look at the decor. Look at the menu.
<P>
Start with the smoked salmon soup, served in a hollow loaf of Tuscan bread, piquant with dill. Though over-stocked with potatoes, its flavors are subtle and well combined, as are those of the steamed clams. In a sauce of garlic and white wine, this dish differentiates itself with the addition of spicy Italian sausage, parsley and diced tomatoes.
<P>
One of the house specialties is gourmet pizza, which co-owner Paul Pirollo advises has a beautiful dough. He should know -- he used to work at Abate, home of some of Pittsburgh's best pizza. The Margherita had sliced tomatoes, garlic and cheese, with fresh basil, in fact, fresh everything. And the dough was not thick or thin, just right, crusty and chewy in all the right places. 
<P>
The menu also features a variety of salads and sandwiches -- the fish sandwich, a holdover appropriately named for Ida Santucci, was a tail of cod, batter fried and served on a big, soft hoagie roll. The Portabella burger, a top seller, is a marinated and grilled cap on a whole wheat kaiser with bleu cheese.
<P>
Pastas are the high end of the menu, which tops out at $9.75. The crab linguini teams crab with portabella mushrooms and sun-dried tomatoes, over linguini in garlic and olive oil. The dish was well-rounded, with random, surprise bites of tomatoes and mushrooms. But the king of the table was the spinach ravioli: fresh ravioli stuffed with spinach and ricotta cheese, topped with grated parmesan and broiled with a brown butter sauce. The flavors melt in your mouth. All of the dishes were made of extremely fresh ingredients.
<P>
To accompany the meal, Mojo Bay has a short wine list, extremely palatable both in price and variety. A decent bottle of Rene Barbier, a Spanish table wine, is available for $11. The menu features 13 microbrews and an array of dessert coffees, all for under $4.
<P>
Unfortunately, there is a catch. It's not the food, which is outstanding, creative and due to expand with the planned purchase of a grill. It's not the service, which is friendly, interested and efficient. And it's not the prices, which are downright inexpensive.
<P>
But for now, all of this must be digested in an environment that is reminiscent of a hospital waiting room. Though a former bar, it is sterile and inexpensively furnished, without even the charm of a dive. At best, one might describe it as contemporary, due to a smattering of colorful graphic paintings. Unfortunately, Mojo Bay must retain Santucci's bar crowd to succeed, so the music is loud. We tuned it out with ravioli.
<P>
That's my advice -- get past it. Pirollo has plans. He and co-partners John Scott, also from Abate, and            Dr. Frank Santucci, son of the former owners, have done the obvious on a shoestring budget (they started up with $90,000, $60,000 of which went to buy the building), and that is, cook their hearts out. The menu was designed with Mike Loeffler, of Dingbats in Waterworks Mall. The 42-seat restaurant, with an additional 10 at the bar and a long function room downstairs, has potential. 
<P>
And the management is nothing if not eager. When he noticed that the nurses from nearby hospitals were walking past his $4.95 lunch specials (and I'm telling you, that cod sandwich could choke an alligator), Pirollo lowered them to $3.95. When his mother deemed the desserts too sweet, she made chocolate cake, rum cake and taramisu. When the wine we ordered was not in stock, they brought us a more expensive one at the same cost. Pirollo calls it "bull pen by committee. Everyone has a dish."
<P>
Even the name was decided democratically. "We didn't want anything ethnic, and we couldn't name it after one of us because then the other two would be mad," says Pirollo, who spent 10 years in the restaurant business in California, and wanted a name to evoke that environment. "It just came to me. And it's perfect, because it's vague, so we can be anything we want to be. We're California/Italian, but that's vague too -- pasta with anything you want on it."
<h4>
Mojo Bay Bar and Bistro<BR>
4624 Liberty Ave.<BR>
Pittsburgh, Pa. 15224<BR>
621-5750
<P>
Soups and Appetizers: $3.25-$7.50<BR>
Salads, Sandwiches and Pizzas:<BR>
$1.95-$7.25<BR>
Pastas: $5.75-$9.75
</h4>
<P>

