<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>

<B><I><font size=+2>EDGAR SNYDER</font></I></B></center><P>

<HR>

<pre>
<B>
 Name:		Edgar M. Snyder 		

 Age:		54 		

 Personal:	Married, wife Sandy, three children. 	
		Lives in Squirrel Hill.

 Education:  	Pennsylvania StateUniversity
		University of Pittsburgh School of Law

 Last Vacation:	Aspen, Colorado last July 

 Hobbies: 	Athletics	
</B>
</pre>
<HR>

From his first solo venture, as a lawyer in Duquesne who kept office hours to capitalize on the mill workers' schedules, Edgar Snyder has realized the value of appealing to the needs of his customer. But it wasn't until 1982 that he placed his first ad, to please his wife Sandy, now his marketing guru. Thirteen years later, with tens of thousands of clients lured by his slogan -- "There is no fee unless we get money for you" -- the insurance companies must be wondering why one of their own gave him his first break. 
<P>
Advertising hasn't just changed him from a solo practitioner into  the CEO of a midsized, "quite profitable" company -- it's literally changed the man's life, making handing out autographs as routine as handing out business cards. Executive Report's Lydia Strohl talked to him in his Gulf Tower office.
<P>
<B>Executive Report: How long ago did you start practicing law?</B>
<P>
Edgar Snyder: I passed the bar examination in 1966 and opened an office in 1967. I practiced downtown working for a law firm, and opened up my own general practice in Duquesne, Pa. Duquesne at the time was a thriving steel community, and I used to keep my office open at the times people were coming out of the steel mill. So I was marketing myself with a sign in the window, and a light on, sitting at the door in case anybody needed a lawyer.  
<P>
<B>ER: Why Duquesne?</B>
<P>
ES: At the time, I was married to someone who had grown up in Duquesne, and I knew someone who would give me free office space in their insurance office. Plus, I believed that the best opportunity when I got out of law school to get business was in a community where there were not very many lawyers, and people themselves would not likely know lawyers. People who were hardworking, steel mill workers usually didn't have a lawyer unless they needed one, versus other areas where people had their own lawyers. Then I became a public defender in the late '60s, strictly criminal work. 
<P>
<B>ER: Why did you begin advertising?</B>
<P>
ES: In 1982, my wife Sandy had a marketing company. She said, 'Why don't we advertise you?' I kind of humored her. It started out as a lark. 
<P>
The first year I advertised in the Pittsburgh Press. I put a little ad in that said 'Know your rights.' Within one year I had the largest drunk driving practice in the City of Pittsburgh. I saw how powerful advertising was. We did a lot of experimenting at that time, and when we changed from the front part of the newspaper, which was world news, to the sports page, we doubled our business. I started to become fascinated by marketing. I had no notion we would even get money back enough to pay for the ads.
<P>
I changed the focus of my advertising after a while, from drunk driving to personal injury. For a while I did both, but I began to see that the public was not going to be impressed by my taking both sides, because a sizable portion of all accidents that happen are because of drinking and driving. 
<P>
<B>ER: How has the scope of your marketing effort changed since that time?</B>
<P>
ES: After we realized this was bigger than either one of us had thought it would be, Sandy gave up her advertising agency to work full-time as a marketing director after we got into television in 1986. In the beginning, I had one secretary and one employee. Today, we have 93 employees and 10 part-time people in five offices. So when you say how has this made a difference -- mixing the marketing and the law -- I've gone from being a small, almost solo practitioner to heading up what I consider to be a fairly large company. There is a world of difference.
<P>
Including Sandy, we have six people who are devoted entirely to marketing.  At one time we were in 27 newspapers in western Pennsylvania. We got rid of newspapers, primarily, because it wasn't cost effective. To us, television is so explosive. I had never been to Johnstown. We put an ad on Johnstown TV. I opened up an office. And the rest is history, as they say. It took off after that. We're on 13 TV stations in western Pennsylvania, and we're on all of those stations almost every day of the week, 365 days a year. That takes a lot of money.  We do a lot of other things within the scope of marketing, but certainly that's where a big part of this budget goes. 
<P>
<B>ER: What's your budget for marketing?</B>
<P>
ES: Total budget I think is proprietary, but we're well over a million dollars annually. For the last few years we have been one of the 10 largest TV legal advertisers in the country. But I don't know about those statistics, because they only get their figures from the 75 largest TV markets in America, and a great part of our advertising is not in large markets.  
<P>
<B>ER: What kind of ethical question for you was it to advertise?</B>
<P>
ES: I went from being a respectable lawyer by reputation, to in many ways becoming a pariah. It really got bad when I went on television, because then I really started to affect all of the smaller communities in western Pennsylva-nia economically, because the lawyers in those areas had to compete against my law firm. I never gave it a lot of thought, about doing this. Because, one, there was no question, the Supreme Court said you could do it. Two, it was being done in many other places across America, including Pittsburgh. I wasn't the first lawyer to advertise in Pittsburgh on TV.
<P>
When we decided to go mass media I knew already, on a smaller scale, how lawyers were coming down on me as not being professional, not creating dignity for the profession of law, and I knew that if I couldn't stand the heat I better get out of the kitchen. But that never bothered me, because I felt that what we were doing was not only legally right, but ethically correct, because I've had ethics counsel on every ad I've ever done. And I'm not thin-skinned.  
<P>
The interesting thing is that the only criticism that's ever been leveled in 13 years of advertising has come from other lawyers, not from the public.  
<P>
<B>ER: How was the criticism leveled at you? Have you had any serious confrontations?</B>
<P>
ES: We were denied admission in a county bar association that had never denied admission to anyone. I felt that was personal. Some of the criticism is subtle, and said behind my back. Some of it is overt, as recently as three months ago when I appeared as a guest at a statewide bar association function, and the president of  the organization leveled a personal attack on me in front of 450 people. That was direct. 
<P>
But I believe I know what the real underlying premise of all of this is. The lawyers who criticize me hide under the badge of dignity and professionalism, and what it really is is economic. I think this has been a substantial economic detriment to many, many lawyers in western Pennsylvania. 
<P>
<B>ER: Why is advertising such a dirty word in law?</B>
<P>
ES: Advertising has been a dirty word in law since 1978, when the now-famous case of the Arizona Bar Association vs. Bates was decided by the United States Supreme Court, which said that lawyers could advertise. There is a segment of the lawyer population who believe that lawyers should only be able to get business by word of mouth and reputation. Every lawyer who has to make a living today has to sell their services. But those who are avowed anti-advertising lawyers say it is just not professional.  
<P>
You have to understand something. Every big law firm in this city has marketing people on their staff. It is not marketing that bothers lawyers. It's TV advertising. Talk to your friendly yellow page rep and he'll tell you no one takes more full page ads than lawyers. 
<P>
<B>ER: Why is TV different?</B>
<P>
ES: Because it is so powerful. It goes out to everyone. The average family in America today watches 7.5 hours of television. That means average. The people that hire me probably watch 10 hours or more of television. If you're a lawyer who is trying to get business the old-fashioned way, by word of mouth, and here comes Edgar Snyder every 15 minutes even when you're switching the channels -- plus the fact that we give a message that says there's no fee unless we get money for you -- lawyers who don't advertise say, `We do the same thing; we don't take a fee either.' But the public doesn't know what lawyers do.  Now they don't have to get  a name from somebody. TV helps elect presidents, why shouldn't it help lawyers who want to get business.
<P>
I think it educates the public as a whole. When we first started advertising for personal injury cases, the average person who would call us had been in an accident six weeks before. Whereas today, with the education of 'Call a lawyer before you talk to an insurance company' mentality that's given in TV commercials, very often we get a call the same day as the accident happens. The public over the last 10 to 15 years has been educated as to what their rights are if they receive a personal injury in an accident. I've had many lawyers say to me, in their off-the-record candor, 'You've helped us all get more business.' The pie is larger of people who know they should get a lawyer. But I don't expect any medals.
<P>
<B>ER: Please explain your fee arrangement.</B>
<P>
ES: We don't bill. Personal injury practice is a contingency fee practice, and we don't get any money on any case unless we win it. And then when we win it, we get paid by the insurance company because we work on a contingent fee. If we don't win, we don't get paid anything. The percentages in this office generally range from 33 1/3 percent contingent fee to 40 percent depending upon the type of case.Those that have greater risk, we charge more. 
<P>
<B>ER: What percent of cases do you win?</B>
<P>
ES: We win most of the cases, but I don't want to mislead what that means. We're careful what we accept here. We have cases where the costs are in excess of $30,000 out-of-pocket on one case. I wouldn't want to take too many cases that I didn't believe we were going to win. But we don't win them all. 
<P>
There's always two issues in every case. One, liability: who's at fault. Two, what are the damages. I set the tone for what we should accept and shouldn't accept. If a case has substantial damages and a big liability question we would be much more likely to handle that case than if there was a big liability question and the damages, meaning the injuries, were very small. Because then on an economic basis it wouldn't be worth the risk and reward. We get well in excess of 10,000 calls a year. 
<P>
We're very careful in the area of product liability, whether it be automobiles, or home products. These companies have an inexhaustible supply of resources.
<P>
<B>ER: What percent of your cases actually go to trial?</B>
<P>
ES: I'll give you two statistics. About 22 percent of our cases are litigated in the personal injury field. In worker's compensation and social security you handle these cases before hearing administrators. So if we litigate 22 percent, I would say in the neighborhood of five percent or less actually go through the trial process, not including arbitration.  We find that if your case is reasonable, before it goes to the jury the insurance company will offer a reasonable  amount of money, though it may not be until    you are sitting on the doorstep of the courthouse.
<P>
<B>ER: How much profit is there in this industry?</B>
<P>
ES: I wouldn't want to say how much the company makes. We are very profitable so far, but if I make bad decisions I can see that margin of profitability go from good to bad.
<P>
<B>ER: What do you think of the term 'ambulance-chaser' ?</B>
<P>
ES: If you put an ad on television that the public watches, they have two choices. They can ignore your product, or be interested in your product, talk to you and make a decision to buy your product. What we're doing is not ambulance chasing, but it's a convenient handle that has been placed upon lawyers who are getting business from people who have been in accidents. Literally speaking, most of them are being taken away in ambulances. But they have the free choice. 
<P>
I had someone on a case that we just became involved in, this HOV case, call up a TV station and say, 'Isn't that terrible that Attorney Snyder would have contacted these people at their worst time.'
<P>
One, it would be against the canon of ethics, and if you got caught you would be disbarred. One of the families of the HOV victims contacted us based upon advertising. We filed a lawsuit against PennDOT in that case. It was the first lawsuit that was filed, and I think a very important step was taken to protect the safety of all the people that use the HOV lanes. And, in fact, we filed the lawsuits and right now, signs are going up. And thank God.
<P>
<B>ER: Have you seen the environment change for personal injury law?</B>
<P>
ES: Yes. The window has opened in terms of educating the public. The insurance companies would give you a counter argument, that all we've done is dig up litigation, but I know better. I know on a statistical basis that lawsuits are not up, but I think that representation of people who have been involved in an accident is up. Although I'll give you an interesting statistic -- in this region, I still believe that only 25 to 30 percent of all people who are involved in automobile accidents, who are injured, use a lawyer. So the vast majority of people injured in accidents are still not hiring a lawyer to handle their matter. Compare that to Philadelphia and it will make your hair stand on end, if you have any hair. I don't. It's like 90 percent in Philadelphia.
<P>
<B>ER: How do you feel about insurance companies?</B>
<P>
ES: I love 'em. I can't live without them, in more ways than one. I'm called to give more public speeches to insurance companies than I am from the law. I think they do a very good job. I wish I could model my profitability on the insurance companies. I've told them that if they could do a better job of dealing with the public, they would put a severe kink in the Edgar Snyders of this world.
<P>
<B>ER: What do you think of tort reform?</B>
<P>
ES: Tort reform, as it is now being used by the Newt Gingrich crowd, is one of the cruelest hoaxes that has been perpetrated on the American public. My hats are off to the insurance industry for the hundreds of millions of dollars that they have spent trying to show the American public that there is a problem. I don't think these measures will help. I think they will hurt victims in accidents, and everyone else doesn't have to worry about it until they're the victim. But we represent victims in this law firm, and I call it a hoax.
<P>
<B>ER: How has this change in your career affected you?</B>
<P>
ES: The recognition has been amazing. I cannot go anywhere in western Pennsylvania without being recognized, talked to, asked legal questions -- I have no private life in Pittsburgh. But I accept it because no one has made me do this. I am not a victim. 
<P>
Some of the market research that we have done over the years gives me a higher name recognition than the President of the United States in some areas. It has nothing to do with me being a lawyer, it has to do with me being a celebrity when the definition of celebrity is being on television every day. I'm like a friend of the family. 
<P>
<B>ER: Has it affected your family?</B>
<P>
ES: My ads obviously inspire a certain sense of humor in people in dealing with me because I can count on one hand the times where people have not been nice in public to me over the past 13 years. My children haven't chosen to be public persons and being Edgar Snyder's son or daughter has embarrassed them. They have become mini-celebrities themselves. 
<P>
They're more accepting as they've gotten older. I read that my daughter said she chose to go to school in the West because it was as far away from Pittsburgh as she could go. I think that was a little tongue in cheek. She's now living in Pittsburgh, and if it was that bad she wouldn't have come back.


<hr>

