<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>A Good Bet
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Bank Stocks Look Attractive in Wake<BR> 

of Integra Merger with National City
</font><BR>
<i>By Doug Thomas
</i></b>

<HR>
<P>
And then there were two -- as       in large, locally headquartered    banks -- following the announcement by Integra Financial that it would sell to Cleveland-based National City Corp. for $2.1 billion in stock. The two banks left are household names, Mellon and PNC, neither of which is rumored to be on anyone's short list. But with this wave of consolidation continuing to roll along, it seems almost inevitable, doesn't it? 
<P>
In the meantime, it is likely that the remaining independents stand to gain market share as borrowers and depositors who prefer to do business locally vote with their feet and head not only for banks like Mellon and PNC, but to other strong local institutions including Parkvale Financial, BT Financial, Southwest National, First Western and Laurel Savings. Mellon and Parkvale shares increased 12.5 percent and 13.8 percent respectively in the month on speculation that both could be merger candidates. So far, there is no evidence to support speculation in either case.
<P>
It is not clear yet whether local consumers, who tend to be parochial, will desire to deal with a Cleveland-based bank rather than a local alternative. Investors are probably well advised to buy a basket of the midtier local bank stocks, as they will either continue to perform well in this environment or will be acquired.
<P>

<h2>Around the ER Index </h2>

The ER Index reported an 8 percent gain in the five weeks ended Sept. 15, 1995, as compared to a 5.09 percent gain for the S&P 500. Since inception, the index posts a 30.42 percent gain versus 26.48 percent for the S&P 500. The strong gains continue to be fueled by acquisitions and better-than-expected earnings announcements.<P>
<DL> 
<LI>	Cable Design Technologies announced that it expects earnings in the fiscal fourth quarter ended July 31, 1995 to exceed analysts' estimates by more than 15 percent. The company cited strong business conditions for network systems cable products and other products for the stronger-than-expected earnings. Additionally, in recent weeks the company has announced several acquisitions. CDTC shares closed up 22.3 percent in the month to 31 1/2.
<P>
<LI>Mylan Laborato-ries Inc. an-nounced that it has formed a strategic alliance with VivoRx, Inc., a California-based biotechnology company. The licensing agreement grants Mylan the exclusive rights to market and sell this product in North America. Mylan shares finished up 14.8 percent for  the month to 23 1/4.<P>
<LI>Northstar Health Services says it plans to acquire Penn Vascular Lab PC and Vascusonics PC for an undisclosed amount.  The two affiliated companies, both Pennsylvania-based, will bring to Northstar 17 western Pennsylvania facilities and combined 1994 revenues in excess of $3 million. Shares of Northstar gained 10.8 percent in the month to $9 per share.<P>
<LI>On Sept. 11, Heinz announced a 12.8 percent increase in net income to $174.5 million, or 70 cents a share,      for its first quarter ended Aug. 2. Revenues for the period increased 21 percent to $2.09 billion. More than half of that increase was provided by the purchases of the North American pet food business of Quaker Oats, the All American Gourmet business of Philip Morris' Kraft division and other small acquisitions. Heinz shares climbed 9.7 percent in the month to close at 46 1/2.<P>
<LI>General Nutrition planned to split its common stock 2-for-1 in October. The split was contingent upon shareholder approval to double the number of authorized common shares to        200 million. General Nutrition shares finished up 12 percent in the month     to 44 1/4.<P>
<LI>II-VI Corp., a designer and manufacturer of infrared optical devices used in industrial and military lasers, was the largest gainer of the month, posting a 50.5 percent gain in its share price to 19 3/4. On Aug. 17, the company announced a 151.7 percent increase in net income to $833,000, or 31 cents per share, on a 62 percent increase in revenues to $8.4 million. The company attributed its strong performance to higher sales and lower per-unit costs, resulting mostly from increased production. The company also announced it filed to sell one million new shares of stock, which will be used for general corporate purposes, including working capital, capital expenditures and possible acquisitions.

</DL>
<h4><i>Doug Thomas is vice president of Emerald Asset Management.</i></h4>


