<HEAD>
<TITLE> Eye On Harrisburg </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<p>

<P align=center><B><FONT SIZE=+2>A Different View
</font><BR> 

<FONT SIZE=+1>Taking a High-Tech Look at the Way Tax <BR>Initiatives Affect the Economy
</FONT><BR>

<I>By Jim Strader</I></B>
<HR>  
<P>

Lawmakers trying to reform the state tax system have a new, high-tech tool to use. 
<P>
The innovative approach was suggested by The Pennsylvania Tax Blue-print Project. It includes computer-generated models that are used to evaluate various tax initiatives and their likely impacts on the economy. The project differs from previous efforts at tax reform by starting without a preconceived outcome, but with the goal of creating a mechanism to assess different proposals, says James C. Stalder, president of the Pennsylvania Institute of Certified Public Accountants, which is directing the nonpartisan venture.
<P>
At the heart of the project is the assumption that Pennsylvania's tax policies drive the economy -- either spurring growth or slowing it. The project seeks to move beyond the scope of previous analyses, which Stalder says often concluded with a comparison of tax rates between states, but without a broader view of the tax situation as a whole.
<P>
"Pennsylvania looks terrible in comparison, rate to rate," Stalder concedes, but adds that exemptions and other factors can bring down the net cost to do business in a state.
<P>
"What we want to demonstrate ... is how Pennsylvania stacks up in total," he says. "We're doing ourselves a real injustice by these reports that show Pennsylvania as one of the worst states."
<P>
With the use of state-of-the-art models as guides, policy makers can answer "what if" questions about the tax system, says Stalder, managing partner of the Pittsburgh office of Price Waterhouse LLP. Proposed tax reductions in one area can be examined through the models to determine the effects in other areas, he says. Likewise, broad revisions of the entire tax system can be analyzed.
<P>
Stalder looks at the value of the blueprint this way: "In the real world, how will all this stuff improve the business climate in Pennsylvania, or the tax climate? We're not going to be driven by misconceptions, we're going to be driven by facts."
<P>
Stalder speaks seriously about the practical value of the project, which has garnered support from Gov. Tom Ridge and from legislative leaders on both sides of the political aisle.
<P>
"Our goal is not to produce a glossy report that ends up on the shelf somewhere, but to produce a tool that can be used on a permanent basis whenever tax reform debate surfaces, whether it's next year or five years from now," Stalder says.
<P>
For his part, the governor expressed his desire to wait for the project's "unbiased technical data" before moving ahead with tax reform.
<P>
"It is my hope that we will then have the tools to produce objective  data that will allow us to deal with the       difficult decisions surrounding tax reform," Ridge wrote in a letter backing the effort.
<P>
The Pennsylvania Tax Blueprint Project also sought the input and support of the three certified public accountants in the Legislature, one of whom is Rep. Greg Fajt, a Democrat from Mount Lebanon. Fajt sees value in the effort's goal to provide the means to develop a coherent tax policy for the state, something he says has been lacking. He also thinks the nonpartisan character of the project lends credibility to the work.
<P>
"I think that the CPA profession has tremendous respect, both in the Legislature and in the public at large. They are independent, they are not affiliated," Fajt says. "What they are concerned with is keeping business taxes as low as possible and creating jobs."
<P>
Bipartisan support and the backing of a wide range of groups outside government is essential to the success of the project, Stalder says. Without that involvement and commitment --which Stalder terms a "buy-in'' -- the effort won't be worth as much down the road, he says.
<P>
Early work on the effort included formulating a steering committee and raising about $2.25 million in private funds. Stalder continues to solicit support for the endeavor.
<P>
"The choice is to get on the train, because it's leaving the station, or just sit back and watch this thing unfold. We want people to have a role in helping us establish this process," he says.
<P>
"It's not our objective -- not my objective on this committee -- to create the perfect answer. We're going to provide the legislators with alternatives. They're going to debate them  and society at large is going to decide what's best."
<P>

<hr>

