<HEAD>
<TITLE> Healthbeat </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H15Health.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1195.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>Feeding the Potatoes
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>Hospitals Increasingly Use Advertising to Get <BR>Their Messages Across -- But Do Consumers Care?
</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl
</I></B>

<HR>  

<P>
In the late '80s, when Pittsburgh television viewers started to see hospital ads flicker across their screens,  they might not have thought much about it, unless they were a doctor.
<P>
"At that time we felt the advertisements were misleading, that they suggested the ability to achieve some things that were unrealistic," says        Dr. Lee McCormick, chairman of the board of the Allegheny County Medical Society. "Also, there was very little advertising then, so there was a little bit of "What the heck is going on here?"
<P>
The campaign, for St. Francis' Laser Center, also used print and radio advertising. But it was the television ads that really ruffled feathers. 
<P>
"Television was controversial. It was reaching so many more people -- that was part of the reaction," says Shirley Freyer, director of public affairs for St. Francis. 
<P>
In 1988, Allegheny General Hospital launched an advertising   campaign titled "On the Frontier          of Advanced Specialty Care." Like        St. Francis, AGH realized it had something to say -- and that television was a vehicle with which to do it. Early campaigns from both institutions focused on high technology and specialty care. AGH even launched campaigns on local television stations during the Super Bowl broadcast, an effective way to reach a big audience.  
<P>
Today, healthcare advertising is prevalent, and hospital advertising is on the increase.  
<P> 
"Historically we have not undertaken paid advertising at all," says Nanci Case, director of planning,   marketing and media relations at Children's Hospital. "But, we've seen misperceptions in the market, and      we felt that paid advertising was the only and the best way to get the        message across."
<P>
Research showed that consumers identified Children's Hospital for tertiary care. But when it came to simpler procedures, consumers didn't think of Children's. 
<P>
To whit, the institution recently launched a campaign positioning Children's as a full-service hospital, and focusing on the institution being broader than its Oakland base, with 150 pediatric office affiliates. The campaign is Pittsburgh-based, and estimated to reach 97 percent of the hospital's target audience (women 25 to 49 with children) 10 or more times. 
<P>
University of Pittsburgh Medical Center, too, forayed into advertising for the first time last spring. 
<P>
"For years we did not advertise," says Jane Duffield, director of the UPMC news bureau. "While we were renowned for the procedures like transplants that get quite a bit of media coverage, people didn't realize that they could get routine care here."
<P>
A change in focus is apparent throughout the region, says Pat Jurczak of the Hospital Council of Western Pennsylvania. Previously, she says, advertising focused on specialties. But now it has gone "back to basics."
<P>
"This is a whole new era of contracts," says Jurczak, "and hospitals are starting to ask themselves which managed care companies they will work with, and how they're going to keep costs down. Advertising is a way for   the hospitals to get the word out to   not just patients but to managed care companies, to get the contracts that keep them going."
<P>
Long-time advertiser AGH has changed its tactic, focusing on educating the consumer on this new environment of managed care. Tom Chakurda, vice president of communications for AGH, says that from the start the     hospital's focus has been educating   the consumer. That's why the AGH campaigns omit billboards.
<P>
"There's not enough room to really get our message across in outdoor," says Chakurda. 
<P>
Physicians have mellowed to advertising, in part, because of this focus on education, which McCormick says is helpful to the consumer. Also, the more prevalent advertising becomes, the more comfortable docs get with it. But he is still wary.
<P>
"My concern is that the patient is getting less and less choice about where they can go. So maybe it's fine that     the patient thinks that Metropolitan General is the best hospital in the world. But if his health care plan    doesn't allow him to go to Metropoli-tan General, he won't have a choice," says McCormick.
<P>
Influencing inclusion into networks via patient perception is one goal of the advertising -- but McCormick isn't convinced it will work.
<P>
"They will not necessarily be more willing to include them in their plan," says McCormick. "Insurers have all the bargaining chips, the patients and the dollars, and they will include hospitals for the most part not because of the public perception but because of the deal they can strike."

<p>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

