<HEAD>
<TITLE> Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1195.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"><a href="../zine/1195.Education.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>

<P>
<P align=center><B><FONT SIZE=+2>A Shoestring Budget
</FONT><BR>
<font size=+1>Small Businesses Must Spend Their Limited <BR>Advertising Dollars Wisely
</font><BR>
<I>By Henry Lipput
</I></B>
<HR> 

<P>
Rick Rohac knows firsthand that small businesses, by their very nature, have small advertising budgets. But he also knows that businesses like his own still must reach potential clients and build name recognition.
<P>
Many small businesses that don't try even the simplest advertising         will lose the battle for success before     it starts.
<P>
"What's important for small business people to realize is if they don't have a budget allocated for advertising in their start-up, they shouldn't even start up," says Rohac, president of Business America/Pittsburgh Metro East, a business appraisal/valuation firm that also brokers the sale or purchase of businesses.
<P>
"There are ways of doing it relatively cost-free," Rohac says. "The two ways that I've found most effective are to network as extensively as possible in professional organizations and to canvass, to cold call, to get out and let business owners know that I'm out there with the service that I offer them."
<P>
It's advertising on a shoestring budget, a challenge faced by the majority of small businesses. Strategies can be as simple as a well-planned business card, which in Rohac's case is colorful and double-sided.
<P>
"So when we leave a business card, we're leaving not only our name and phone number, but a pretty good description of what we can do for them," Rohac says.
<P>
Other small businesses may spend more, but usually it's still a limited amount that without proper planning and research will go to waste. Billboards, broadcast commercials and newspaper advertisements are worthless if your target markets don't see or hear them.
<P>
"It really is doing your homework, as to what's out there, what's in the marketplace," says Ron Kaiser, president of the Kaiser Group, a Pittsburgh advertising agency. "It's learning to not only ask questions, but, more importantly, learning to listen to what people are saying, what people want." 
<P>
<h2>And then there's the budget.</h2>

"If you don't have enough money [to fund a traditional advertising campaign], don't spend any of it," Kaiser says. "And then you have to find other ways to attract customers. And those other ways sometimes go back to the old original ways to do it. I don't        care whether you put a person with a sandwich board out walking up and down the street. Or print up a bunch of fliers, and distribute them up and down the street where there are businesses.
<P>
"The small business person needs to be a guerrilla fighter," Kaiser says. "They need to be street-smart. You need to be able to not try to overwhelm a market -- because you don't have the dollars -- but to outsmart it. "
<P>
Being innovative helps. Often, an innovative approach will get the public's attention. One example was the cookies distributed by DoubleTree Hotel when it took over the former Vista International in downtown Pittsburgh. The DoubleTree is part of a national chain, but is independently owned, with a limited budget for promotion in the Pittsburgh market.
<P>
Other small businesses that elect to use traditional TV advertising can limit their costs by trimming production costs and hitting cable channels instead of the traditional networks.
<P>
One of Kaiser's clients, The Law Firm, wanted to have some immediate impact in the market where it phys-ically was located.
<P>
"We made the decision that we would focus our marketing on the northern tier of Allegheny County," says The Law Firm's Leonard Sweeney. "Hence, we used CableAdNet for the North Hills area, which is a pretty big area."
<OP>
"Local mom and pop clients represent 55 to 60 percent of our core business," says Pat Springer, CableAdNet's director of marketing.
<P>
Sweeney says his commercial brought results, even though it was produced on a limited budget.
<P>
"Anybody can throw a bunch of money into this and have    a Cecil B. deMille production," Sweeney says. "The trick is to have one that just looks like it."

<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a> 

