<a href="../zine/1195.SmallBusinessReport.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H17Education.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1195.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+2>The Five-Year Plan
</FONT><BR>
<font size = +1>Finishing College in Four Years <BR>Has Become a Thing of the Past
</font><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></B>

<HR>  

<P>
When Jack Daniel attended college, he blew right through it, attending summer school and finishing his bachelor's degree in less than three years. Today, as the University of Pittsburgh's vice provost, Daniel watches many young students taking five years and sometimes longer to complete their undergraduate work.
<P>
No problem.
<P>
"It is now normative to take more than four years to graduate," Daniel says. "A major reason is economics. A large number of students are working to pay tuition. Also, a large number of students are doing what I call 'stopping out' to gain work experience. Others stop out after they recognize the need to grow or mature a little."
<P>
Only 31 percent of the high school class of 1990 earned undergraduate degrees within four years,  down from 45 percent in 1977, when the National Center for Education Statistics began tracking graduation rates. 
<P>
Don't be misled by those numbers, educators say. Not graduating within four years does not always mean students are wasting time at parties, a view many parents mistakenly adopt. As Daniel notes, some students are gaining work experience, studying abroad or even staying in school an extra year to complete work for a second major or a minor. Others agree.
<P>
"We are finding students who take those options," Robert Morris College President Edward Nicholson says. "They slow down to get the extra minor, for example, as a strategy to enhance their own marketability.
<P>
"My own son, at Notre Dame, had two majors and a minor," Nicholson says. "He had to go two summers."
<P>
In the end, it's employers who benefit from this trend. The pool of entry-level college graduates is more polished and more seasoned, giving employers more value for their payroll dollars. Employers recognize the trend more every day, so they aren't quite as concerned as they used to be about the amount of time prospective employees spent in college.
<P>
"The difference is, we would ask for an explanation," says Michael Roark, a Mellon Bank vice president. "There are a lot of legitimate reasons. Spending more than four years in college is not necessarily a red flag, but it is something we would ask about."
<P>
Some students, especially those who attend more expensive private schools, can't afford to pay tuition for an extra year. Beyond the tuition, a typical student spends an additional $6,500 to $8,000 annually for college expenses, such as housing, meals and transportation. In other words, the five-year plan isn't for everyone. 
<P>
The schools themselves are not interested in collecting the extra  tuition. At Westminster College, 66 percent of students finish in four years. 
<P>
"We have a moral obligation to get these students through in four years,   as long as they are doing their part," says Elizabeth Hines, registrar at Westminster. "If they are flunking and repeating courses, there is little we can do. But it's scary to think that schools would keep a student for more than four years for monetary reasons. Moving them along is the name of     the game."
<P>
In fact, many schools are now working to remove administrative roadblocks that previously prevented students from finishing in four years. In Florida, for example, the board of regents went as far as requiring faculty members to spend more time teaching and advising.
<P>
In western Pennsylvania, schools have developed committees to review curricula and ensure that students get the classes they need to progress toward their degrees. When required courses aren't available, schools are more flexible than ever before in allowing students to substitute another class.
<P>
Community colleges also are being more precise with the articulation agreements they have with four-year schools. The agreements enable students to transfer most of their credits from the community college to the four-year school.
<P>
What's the message? Don't stereotype students who spend more than four years in college.
<P>
"Look at the student's record and see why the student didn't finish in four years," says Pitt's Daniel. "I think employers are going to see more and more students who actually were in good academic standing."

<p>

<hr>

