<a href="../zine/1095.Supplement.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Feature.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=+2> Who Really Pays?</font><br>
<font size =+1>Employers Cut Healthcare Costs By Restricting Employee Options </font size><BR> 
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i></B>
<HR>
<P>



When Maureen Bertonaschi lost her job as a funder at Mellon Bank last May, her family didn't just lose a valuable second income. Maureen, her husband Michael, and their two toddlers, Ryan and Adam, also lost their family doctor.
<P>   
"Our kids have been going to the same pediatrician all their lives," says Michael Bertonaschi, 39, director of financial aid at La Roche College. "So we decided to pay $400 a month to stay on HealthAmerica. We have until May 1996 and then we'll have to make a decision. Our feeling is that we will get the 17-month-old through most of his shots and visits with our pediatrician, and then it will not be as traumatic to change." The Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act, known as COBRA, mandates that employee health coverage must be extended for one year after an employee leaves their job -- but the employee is no longer eligible for the usually lower rates the employer has negotiated. To remain with Health-America, the Bertonaschis will bear a sizable increase in healthcare costs, on a sizably reduced income. 
<P>
This just when they were getting used to seeing their rates go down. 
Yes, down.
<P>
In 1993, the Bertonaschis subscribed to HealthAmerica through La Roche, at a family rate of $295 a month. They then switched their coverage to Mellon Bank's program, which in 1994 offered HealthAmerica at a family rate of $164 a month. In 1995, that coverage dropped to $135 a month. But they can't get back into HealthAmerica through La Roche. 
<P>
"In November 1994, we switched to Select Blue, [a Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania product] which allows people to use either an HMO [health maintenance organization] or indemnity program," says George Zaffuto, director of human resources at La Roche. "Blue Cross said they would not deal with us if we did not eliminate HealthAmerica. We fought with them, and even talked to our attorneys about it, but they also represent Blue Cross and were not comfortable with the situation."
<P>
Welcome to the brave new world of managed care in Pittsburgh. For so long considered the backwoods of managed care, Pittsburgh has of late seen greater acceptance of managed care. Partly responsible is the introduction of point of service products, which are less restrictive than pure HMOs, yet still realize cost control. Consequently, competition among health plans has heated up to a rolling boil: and though, as usual, competition is having a favorable impact on the market, some consumers are finding that they are the proverbial frog, trapped in the pot as the temperature rises. 
<P>
<H2>Over a Barrel</H2>
The upshot in this case was that La Roche capped enrollment into HealthAmerica.<P> 
"Our increases were astronomical, in the teens and twenties, so I said, 'What can we do to control this?' Managed care is virtually the only way left to have some sort of control," says Zaffuto. "[With Select Blue,] our rates went down 23 percent -- and without that reduction, we would have been hard pressed to fund the full amount."
<P>
Blue Cross says that without eliminating the competition, they have no way to predict whether the rates they offer, which are based on the health of the entire employee pool, are sustainable.
<P>
"In healthcare, 10 percent of the people account for 90 percent of the cost," says Dan Holtz, vice president of major accounts at Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania. "When we're deciding what to charge we look at the claims experience of the entire group over time. What causes problems is when you don't know which ones will stay [in our plan]. It's possible that if the healthy people move into the competitive program and we no longer have that to offset [the higher cost of caring for the sicker people], we can't predict the price as well."
<P>
But HealthAmerica doesn't see it that way.
<P>
"That's a bogus reason they trot out for the underlying reason, to protect their market share," says Tom Murray, senior vice president of HealthAmerica. "And the biggest proof I have is that they've done that where we have been losing money on groups -- they're taking back people we've paid to have transplants. Blue Cross is using the same tactic with large, self-funded employers where they take no risk, just administrate the claims. If their worry is adverse risk, then why do they do that in the self-funded market?"
<P>
Zafutto says Select Blue was the logical way to make the switch to complete managed care, because not all of La Roche's approximately 120 covered employees were comfortable with having their choice of doctor or hospital restricted. Select Blue is a point of service program, which allows patients to make the decision of where they receive care each time they need it. They may use the Select Blue network of providers or go outside that network and pay a higher co-payment charge. But the ability to go out of network doesn't help the Bertonaschis, since their pediatrician is on staff at HealthAmerica, and only cares for HealthAmerica subscribers.  
<P>
"We don't even want to think about getting another doctor," says Michael. "We got this big book that listed all the Blue Cross doctors and felt like we didn't even want to deal with it. Some doctors aren't even accepting new patients. We want the convenience and comfort of sticking with our pediatrician."
So they will pay for it. It's evidence that employers aren't the only ones making tough decisions in healthcare. Increasingly, they are passing along those decisions, in the form of provider restrictions and higher contributions, to employees. According to the Employee Benefit Research Institute, in 1993, 61 percent of full-time employees in medium and large firms were asked to make contributions to their health plans -- up from 27 percent in 1979. What's worse, in a healthcare environment crammed by economics into an increasingly one-size-fits-all system, not everyone will be satisfied.
<P>
"This year, it would cost $291 a month for all four of us to go on Select Blue," says Bertonaschi. "And since it's a point-of-service plan, that only covers 80 percent. We think even though we're paying more now [to stay with Health-America], we're better off in the long run."
<P>
La Roche is not alone in their move to managed care to stem healthcare costs. According to a survey by Johnson & Higgins, in 1994, 58 percent of all covered employees of mid-size employers (10-999 employees) participated in managed care, up from 46 percent in 1993. Yet they still saw average total healthcare costs per employee rise 3.4 percent in 1994, to $3,421 from $3,308. This was smaller than 1993's 6.2 percent increase, but hardly comparable to the decrease of 1.1 percent that employers overall experienced in 1994. Clearly, larger companies with more volume can offer deeper choices. But managed care is here to stay. Even in backwoods Pittsburgh.
<P>
"It's just recently, with the January 1, 1995 re-enrollments, that we saw  a great shift [in this market] to managed care," says Maureen Londino, a principal at Buck Consultants. That's when, she says, Blue Cross, which dominates the market, had its product "mature and ready to go. I think the market will continue to evolve, with United Health Care and Metro Health, the merger of Traveller's and Met Life, coming into the market."
<P>
This competitive situation has led to underpricing strategies to grab market share, say experts. Blue Cross makes no bones about the fact that they want to expand. For years the leaders in the traditional indemnity market, the name Blue Cross was synonymous with quality employer-provided health benefits. HealthAmerica came to town 20 years ago with their pure managed care product, which restricted choice to their network of physicians. Employers and employees alike were slow to take notice -- until the double digit healthcare cost inflation of the late '80s hit. Even then, it proved hard to change the mindsets of Pittsburghers, to whom healthcare quality equaled freedom of choice. Three years ago, health insurers began tailoring managed care to the marketplace, and by the end of the year, Blue Cross, with 65 percent of the insured market in western Pennsylvania, will have more than a million subscribers, 200,000 in their Keystone HMO, 100,000 in their PPO, and 700,000 in the POS plan, Select Blue.
<P>
"That's still less than 50 percent," says Blue Cross' Holtz. "We see 1997 as the year managed care will actually grow larger than indemnity enrollment."
<P>
HealthAmerica, with 250,000 subscribers, 170,000 in the HMO and 70,000 in the POS and PPO plans, is Blue Cross' closest competition, offering a deep array of products and services for not just the corporate but also the Medicare, Medicaid and small business markets. Other companies have come into serve special niches: Aetna, for instance, has a strong national network and is particularly attractive to corporate clients with employees throughout the country. US Healthcare, too, is rumored to be making plays for market share.
<P>
"There's a price war going on right now, so we stress to our clients that they don't just look at the first-year costs," says Angela Walker, vice president of employee benefits services for Johnson & Higgins in Pittsburgh. "We go for two- and three-year rate guarantees, because they will undercut the one-year -- it may be lower than the employer paid just in claims. The POS plans are where we're seeing the growth, and they're very competitively priced. Sometimes we shake our heads and wonder why, but it's whatever the carrier is comfortable with -- depending on how big, how high profile, how important the company is to them."
<P>
This is dangerous, says Walker, because if companies switch plans often to take advantage of lower costs, the market's cost for healthcare will go up in the long term. Besides, the lowest price doesn't always indicate the highest quality.
<P>
"Employers are always looking for ways to provide high quality healthcare at a competitive price, and short term, you can always get a lower price," says Londino of Buck Consultants. "But long term, if you can't negotiate better care and outcomes, you are just putting a band-aid on something that needs surgery."
<P>
<h2>Quest for Quality</h2>
Employers choose healthcare plans depending on the needs of the employees and the industry they serve.
<P>
"Cost, quality and access," says   Earl L. McKinley, director of Westing-house's employee service center, when asked how he buys corporate healthcare. "Since we are a multi-industry company, we have to align the benefits program with business strategy. In competitive conditions, we use benefits to attract and retain employees. On the flip side, we may see that we don't need overly generous benefits, if talent is more readily available."
<P>
In years past, employers judged their healthcare coverage by how efficiently its administration ran -- how responsive the carriers were to employees and how quickly claims were paid. Now, with carriers increasingly managing care, quality is taking on a whole new meaning, and buzzwords like 'measuring outcomes' are part of the benefit managers' daily repertoire.
<P>
Why? Because the numbers are increasingly demonstrating that in managed care, quality outcomes demonstrably affect cost. And employers can't afford to ignore that -- in 1993 public and private employers spent $235.6 billion, approximately 6.2 percent of total compensation, on group health insurance, according to an EBRI study. Health insurance is the fastest inflating element of compensation, increasing at an average annual rate of 13.7 percent from 1960 to 1993. Figures show managed care plans have the lowest cost per employee. Nationwide, according to Johnson & Higgins, indemnity plans for midsize employers cost an average of $3,503 per employee, HMOs cost $3,288 and PPOs cost $3,106. POS plans proved to have the lowest cost, $2,939 per employee. 
<P>
"What employers want to know is how much value am I getting for my insurance dollar? How many cardiac patients died or had to be readmitted? What's your C-section rate? How satisfied are your members?" says HealthAmerica's Murray. "If quality is a goal, then cost will follow."
<P>
The issue of quality has become such an important one that the Pittsburgh Business Group on Health, a coalition of 30 local employers, began collecting data on managed care options last year. 
<P>
"We saw a need on the part of business to get good comparative information," says Chris Whipple, executive director, who says their survey duplicates the Health Plan Employer Data and Information Set (HEDIS 3.0) standards set up by the National Committee on Quality Assurance, one of the groups responsible for accrediting health plans. "Pittsburgh is the first region to release verifiable information. Plan to plan, the national report card project is not comparable. This is the first region where it's regionally applicable."
<P>
The results of this year's study are due out at the end of this month. They will cover HMO and PPO plans -- POS plans are not mature enough in this region, requiring five years to get valid results, according to Whipple. Last year's study included responses from Advantage, owned by St. Francis Health System; Aetna; Keystone, the HMO of Blue Cross; HealthAmerica and US Healthcare. Of the five, three (Aetna, HealthAmerica and US Healthcare) were fully accredited by the NCQA, and one (Keystone) had provisional accreditation. (Keystone has since been granted one-year accreditation, a step between provisional and full accreditation.) On the quality indicators like pediatric immunization, mammography and prenatal care, the locals scored at or above the national average.
<P>
Part of the reason may be the watchdogging of the state.
<P>
"I think in most states, even though the health department is given jurisdiction, they don't take a proactive role," says Tom Chepel, director of the bureau of healthcare financing for the Pennsylvania department of health. "But we have a history in Pennsylvania of coming up with the proper regulatory schemes to protect subscribers. The result is tough standards and longer to go through the regulatory stages. I'd like to say that generally the things we are looking for are arrangements that  lead to poor quality care or underservice. Most use capitation, which may lead to undertreatment."
<P>
The state monitors HMOs and PPOs by licensing them, making sure that they have the proper quality and access in place by doing an in-depth review on-site, and a random review of medical records. The health plan must also have an approved system for consumer complaints.
<P>
"We're proud of our consumer grievance system, and believe we have the most detailed set of guidelines on how to operate a grievance system," says Chepel. Since the system was implemented in April 1991, the DOH intervened in 1,920 complaint calls before a formal grievance was filed. Of the 240 grievances formally filed, 45 percent of those settled have been in favor of the member, saving complaintants an estimated $775,000. The most frequent type of grievance appealed involves a member who goes to the emergency room without contacting a primary care physician.
<P>
All this leads, says Chepel, to well-policed systems. "We are one of the first states requiring external quality assessments. They're done one year after licensing and every three years after that, or as necessary. Other states are adopting this. In fact, many employers are requiring accreditation." The state has approved three external assessment organizations that licensees can use for these check ups, which they pay for themselves. One of the approved groups is the NCQA, which runs a separate national accreditation program.
<P>
<h2>An Executive Decision</h2>
Just having manged care in place is not enough -- a case illustrated dramatically by the story of Allegheny County. In 1992, 70 percent of the county's 7,500 employees were enrolled in HMOs, 30 percent in indemnity programs. But all was not rosy.
<P>
"There were a lot of problems," says George Tkach, now executive assistant to Commissioner Pete Flaherty, but then assistant director of benefits. "Our costs were increasing dramatically. We had seven benefit plans with many different levels -- our employees were frankly confused. Our cost for healthcare per employee had increased from $2,760 in 1987 to $4,289 in 1992. Then I read an article in your publication that said the average cost per employee should be around $3,600 per year."
<P>
Unchecked, the county's healthcare bill would have been $32 million in 1993, and Tkach projected that healthcare costs would have reached $43.6 million by 1995. So the county decided to cut the number of carriers to two, and after a bid process chose Blue Cross, which provides both POS and HMO products, and HealthAmerica's HMO. They also did things like bring the carriers on-line, and offer bonuses to employees who opted out of the program.
<P>
"The first year bids came in at $25.8 million, a $4.5 million savings," says Tkach. After an intensive communications blitz advertising the new program to employees, 88 percent are now enrolled in HMOs and nine percent in POS. Only three percent remain in indemnity, all holdovers on union contracts. POS enrollees only opt out of the network 15 percent of the time. "With renewals, this year the program is up to $31 million. But remember, that's not actual cost savings, just savings over the increases we had projected before."
<P>
It's an important point. Though managed care has indeed slowed the rate of increase in healthcare expenditure, cases where the cost of care is actually decreasing are rare and the numbers negligible. Prices are still escalating: According to Johnson & Higgins, though indemnity plans rose the highest (13.6 percent from 1993), HMOs (7.4 percent) and PPOs (1.4 percent) also continued to increase. Some believe that though managed care has taken an initial bite out of healthcare costs, the true dirty work is yet to come.
<P>
"We've seen significant reductions in utilization by union and non-union employees that reflect changes in the plan designs and an effort to prevent unnecessary hospitalization and unnecessarily prolonged stays in the hospital," says Jim Carney, vice president of administration for U.S. Steel and Carnegie Pension Fund. After 10 years of double digit healthcare cost inflation, USX last year experienced no increase, paying out $255 million for medical insurance for 80,000 retirees and 100,000 employees and their dependents. At latest count, 37 percent of non-union and 22 percent of union employees were enrolled in HMOs.
<P>
"But though we've had success on the utilization side, we've had less success on the cost side," says Carney. "I am very concerned that costs are going to escalate again. One reason is government cost shifting -- the government pays less than its fair share for payments so doctors shift the cost to us. There's also this inability to get hospitals to take facilities out. Hospitals are trying to expand here. Pittsburgh hospitals have more helicopters than many third world countries, and that's ridiculous."
<P>
Carney says that because hospital stays are down, hospitals, which have fixed costs, are hiking prices to cover them. Dan O'Malley, a principal with Towers Perrin, agrees, and thinks the day of reckoning for hospitals will come soon, with the shifting of the region's hefty Medicare population into managed care.
<P>
<h2>Let the Games Begin</h2>
With southwestern Pennsylvania on a road without exits to managed care, new companies and new products are infiltrating the market. 
<P>
"Understand that managed care is still in its infancy," says LeMar Myers, chief of the HMO, PPO and POS review division of the Pennsylvania department of insurance. "Indemnity is still sold more than anything else and there are segments of the market that are untapped."
<P>
"For the last seven to eight years, the number of HMOs was fairly constant, there were always about 20 in operation," says Neil Bonhert, vice president of the Hospital Council of Western Pennsylvania. "In the past year, though, there have been a phenomenal number of new applications."
<P>
Of 14 new applications, three HMOs are coming into southwestern Pennsylvania. Jerry Silver, of Best Healthcare, one of the applicants, says they're coming in to tap the Medicaid market, which has abundant potential with coming regulations requiring disbursement of Medicaid via managed care.
<P>
Much of the competition will come from already established corporations. Myers predicts that US Healthcare, which has been putting on a big push in central Pennsylvania by undercutting competitive rates by 20 to 30 percent and pouring money into advertising, will come on strong in the Pittsburgh area too. And then there is Blue Cross' strategy.
<P>
"The competition in this market is very tough, from the standpoint of going after the employer. Blue Cross has a role in every company," says O'Malley of Towers Perrin. But he says that few have taken the bait and decreased employee choice. "In most cases, employers are reacting negatively to the monopolistic tactics of having only one choice. However, in some cases, Blue Cross has convinced them that if they aggregate their healthcare pool they can save, and they have basically bought their way in. It depends on the employer and the timing and their other business challenges."
<P>
Competition is also coming from providers, doctors and hospitals setting up networks. Pennsylvania does not yet have the legislation in place to allow these Physician Hospital Organizations to contract directly with employers to provide healthcare, but Chepel, whose department is studying that question right now, says he is leaning that way. This will lead to increased competition.
<P>
"Some large employer groups have come to the conclusion that HMOs are just middlemen who charge a 15 percent administrative fee and if I contract directly with the PHO it will be more competitive," says Chepel. "But most don't want to compete with the HMOs, they just want to assume more of the risk. They want to manage their own care and increase [their profit] by good medical management. But it may also increase competition because now it takes a lot of resources [for HMOs coming in from the outside] to credential enough doctors and hospitals to build a system. This way, they could just go to three PHOs and get enough."
<P>
Industry experts are split on the question of whether Pittsburgh is ready for direct contracting. In Minneapolis, where healthcare is light-years ahead of this market, a large alliance of business employers is switching from contracting with large HMOs, planning instead to initiate a voucher system that allows employees to shop among competing smaller groups. The groups will provide information on quality, cost and customer service.
<P>
Towers Perrin's O'Malley says that a good average for an administative fee is $25 per employee per month. The insurance department caps administrative fees at 15 percent of the price of the plan. McKinley says Westinghouse, which is self-insured, pays an administrative fee of under 10 percent, and that's too high.
<P>
"Our administrative cost is lower than buying insurance off the shelf, when there's a risk fee involved. We're taking the risk under our belt. If I'm going to spend money on administration, I better see a payback in management," says McKinley. "There is a point of dimishing returns for managed care, but we're not there yet."
<P>
In Meadville, Crawford County Hospital is contracting with 13 employers directly to provide healthcare. But direct contracting would be more difficult for employers like USX and Westinghouse, with employees throughout the market and the nation. A voucher system like the one to be implemented in Minneapolis, however, might solve that. But no one really knows quite what path the local market will take.
<P>
"I think the market is ready for [direct contracting] at this point, because the movement to managed care has been relatively painless -- what was deemed as unacceptable five years ago, to take away the freedom of choice, has been given up," says O'Malley. "Now that we've gone that far, the logical next step is to go to an even smaller network and improve cost control and quality. But there has to be painless implementation and administration."
<P>
This means that these smaller systems, like the recently incorporated Southwest Integrated Delivery Network -- comprised of Allegheny General Hospital, Allegheny Valley Hospital, Forbes Health System, St. Clair Hospital and Sewickley Valley Hospital and their physician organizations -- must acquire the technology and expertise to manage healthcare. The big carriers, who have been working hard to integrate themselves into healthcare, deny the attraction of smaller, manageable networks.
<P>
"If a group of providers can put together a system that does it as well, or for less, we can't prevent this kind of competition," says Steve Birek, vice president of primary care delivery systems for Blue Cross, which is opening medical centers of their own reminiscent of those of HealthAmerica. "But it's not as easy as it looks." 
<P>
"The one-hospital solution is not very realistic. Just look at the topography," says HealthAmerica's Murray. "This is not the kind of community where you can come in and contract with only two or three hospitals -- you better have a pretty big network. I don't think their product will rival ours -- and we have a lot of other choices."
<P>
With lots of strings attached. As Ryan and Adam Bertonaschi may soon find out, choice, for employees  and their families receiving healthcare benefits, will increasingly mean change and sacrifice.
<P>
<HR>

<h2>How Important Is Your HMO's Fiscal Health?</h2>

Sure, your HMO can hook you up with a doctor, provide you with tests, even hospitalize you if you're going under the knife or delivering a baby. But would-be enrollees might want to check on the fiscal health of the HMO before joining, too.
<P>
Especially in the Pittsburgh area. Weiss Ratings Inc., which rates the fiscal security of HMOs nationwide, recommends only doing business with companies they rate a B+ or higher. None of the HMOs here achieved that mark. Should enrollees care? Certainly.
<P>
"Companies that are fiscally balanced and responsible are companies where consumers are more likely to get good care," says Sue Ann Bailey, spokeswoman for Weiss Ratings, Inc., which has just published its second annual report, rating 317 HMOs across the country. "If companies are in fiscal trouble they are less likely to schedule expensive treatments, tests, or refer patients to the care of more expensive specialists."
<P>
Weiss rates the HMOs' fiscal security by establishing a risk-adjusted capital index, a profitability index, a liquidity index and a stability index for each institution and coming up with a letter grade for each.
<P>
The HMOs they rate in the Pittsburgh area are Health America, which received a C, Keystone Health Plan, which received a grade of B-, US Healthcare, which also received a B-, and Aetna, which received a SD+. 
<P>
According to the Weiss report, a B is 'good,' indicating that the company has the resources to deal with a variety of adverse economic conditions, but in the event of a severe financial crisis should be reviewed to assure its fiscal strength. A C is 'fair,' indicating that the company offers fair financial security and is currently stable, but might have difficulties maintaining that stability during an economic downturn. A D is 'weak,' indicating that the company demonstrates significant weaknesses which could negatively affect policyholders and in an unfavorable economic environment, could be magnified. The plus sign is an indication that the company could be upgraded with new data, and the minus sign indicates that new data might downgrade the rating. The S means 'small' -- that the company has capital and surplus of less than $10 million, and is a 'reminder that consumers may want to limit the size of their policy with this company so that the policy's maximum benefits per risk do not exceed one percent of the company's capital and surplus.'
<P>
-- <b>Lydia Strohl</b>
<p>

