<a href="../zine/1095.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Update.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><p>

<b><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>Making Business Decisions </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>Overestimating Your Own Business Expertise Could Send <BR>Your Business Down the Tubes </FONT SIZE></b><br>
<B><i>By Jack Hallman </i></B>
<hr>

<P>

It often starts with an "Aha!" A light bulb goes on and suddenly you see a better way to build that mousetrap, or repackage that widget.  Before you know it, a small business is born. But making a long-term success of a small business requires a lot more than the risk-taking needed to put that innovative idea into motion.
<P>
One small business owner took the plunge and saw booming sales for his product once it hit the market.  It was an entrepreneur's dream -- except that in this case the business was quickly running out of money.  The cash-flow crisis was spurred by the owner's failure to realize that, while his suppliers demanded payment now, he wouldn't be paid for the finished products until 30 to 60 days after delivery.  His lack of experience cost him dearly.
<P>
Many small business owners soon realize that the day-to-day business decisions they must make are not as straightforward as simply selling the product or services.  How do you know what prices to set?  Where to market your products?  Should you expand the business?  If so, when?  How these issues are handled can make or break a small business's bottom line. 
<P>
Inexperienced owners are left to learn how to make such decisions through a process of trial and error, which can end up affecting the business's profit margin.  
<P>
No wonder 80 percent of small businesses in Pennsylvania fail.  And since roughly 95 percent of all businesses in the state are small, and employ over half of the employees in this state alone, failing small businesses can potentially affect the economic health of the region.  
<P>
Small business is a mainstay of our economy, so the importance of training entrepreneurs to handle crucial business decisions cannot be overstated. 
<P>
As a volunteer counselor for small businesses, I've seen this need first hand.  Time and again I've watched small business start-ups fail because of an inexperienced owner's poor decision-making skills.  The reasons can range from poor location, lack of marketing savvy, faulty pricing or a combination of these.  The results can overshadow the quality of a fledgling business's goods or services. 
<P>
Even seasoned small businesses can fall victim to a lack of preparedness.  For example, countless companies have had to close their doors as a result of wrongly assessing an expansion opportunity. An owner's poor judgment about whether or not to open up another location can send the business spiraling downward, even if it was booming when the decision was made. 
<P>
When small businesses approach my group -- the Service Corps of Retired Executives -- we take for granted that, although they may be experts in their products or services, their understanding of what it takes to run a business is limited.  New business owners who come to us must attend a workshop that covers business planning, financing, sources of capital, taxes and insurance, legal forms of organization and business records.
<P>
After an introduction to the important issues and problem-solving, one or more of the retired executives in the group volunteers to work with the entrepreneurs for more individualized help on their specific problems.
<P>
Without the experience of a large organization to back them up, it is relatively common for small business owners to overlook common business strategies, basic as they may be.  
<P>
One owner, for example, came to SCORE complaining of high turnover rates in his small business.  Although his staff had minimal skills, he was wasting valuable time training workers who would leave the organization months later.  The SCORE advisors helped the entrepreneur create employment ads that would attract an employee pool that best matched the type of jobs he had to offer. 
<P>
There are several programs like SCORE designed to give the small business owner free advice on how to avoid the pitfalls common to running a small business.  Entrepreneurs should look  to such programs for help before it's too late.
<P>
The fact is that small business operators must first realize the depth of business knowledge necessary to successfully run their shop.  With that realization, there are places to come for advice on handling those elusive business details because, as they say, that is where the devil is.                           
<P>
<i>Jack Hallman is a counselor with the Pittsburgh chapter of SCORE, a volunteer organization of retired business executives that provides free and confidential advice to small businesses.  SCORE counselors can be reached at (412) 644-5447.</i>

<HR>
<b><P align=center><Font Size=+2>Staying Alive</font><BR><BR><font size=+1>When Disaster Strikes, Keep a Cool Head and Expect Anything</font><BR>
<i>By Rebecca Fenoglietto</I></b><P>

When Morri Miller got the call at 7:30 a.m., he first thought that it was nothing serious. A little bit of water in the building, part of a wall fell -- so what? Call a contractor. Miller was in Cleveland, visiting relatives.
In fact, that little bit of water was more than one million gallons that had burst from a water main located within feet of the foundation of Izzy Miller's Furniture in Carnegie, a two-story structure comprised of three connecting buildings. The pipe had developed a 2-foot hole that allowed the water  -- half of the entire water supply from the nearby tower -- to empty into the store on Aug. 24, 1994.
<P>
"It looked like a bombed out building," Miller says. "The front portion of the building was gone. It looked like Oklahoma City on a smaller scale. Fortunately, no one was injured here."
<P>
According to Miller, the basement had filled instantly, the first floor took on 1 1/2 feet of water. When the front of the building collapsed, everything housed in the second floor was destroyed by the dust. By 11 a.m. the county's Delta Team was on site to stabilize the area, and the Salvation Army was giving out donuts.
<P>
"Oh, this is nice," thought Miller.
<P>
But it would take a lot more than donuts and the Delta Team to overcome the disaster that decimated approximately $750,000 worth of inventory. 
<P>
How do you eat an elephant? One bite at a time.
<P>
For Miller, overcoming this disaster was a matter of following a logical progression of questions that needed to be answered. Miller did so partly because it worked, and partly, he admits, because he was in shock.
<P>
The first question was whether or not to stay in business at all. Had he chosen to close, the building still needed to be repaired. Additionally, Miller, at 58, says that he felt that he was "too young and too poor to retire. It was never really an option."
<P>
The next question, then, was whether Miller's should stay in the location it occupied for nearly 50 years, or relocate. Miller discovered that the expenses of relocating from Carnegie's East Mall Plaza were too great. Thus, Miller resolved to rebuild.
<P>
The next step was to find a place from which to operate while the building was still unusable. 
<P>
With no inventory and no building, Miller Furniture and its staff of approximately 10 (who, says Miller, were all kept on salary throughout the crisis, and who he credits for working together to keep Miller's viable) operated from a bare-bones office across the street from his warehouse. His ads challenged customers: "If you can buy from a picture, you can save lots of money." Miller admits that it was a hard sell, but he nonetheless maintained his business at approximately 60 percent.
<P>
Keeping that line of communication open -- to employees, customer, suppliers and the community --  as Miller did is essential, says Marc Jampole, president of Jampole Communications. He advocates planning beforehand to minimize communications problems during a crisis.     He suggests listing possible disasters, a few simple messages your company always tries to convey -- be it focused on quality, service or price -- and then list all basic audiences. Have in place a basic set of communication procedures. Name a spokesman and a second choice.
<P>
Then, if a crisis occurs, immediately contact your audiences. "Tell them how you're dealing with the crisis in a way that will be beneficial to them," Jampole says. 
<P>
In a situation similar to Miller's, says Jampole, he would have launched a public relations campaign, explaining what happened and how customers would be served in the meantime. "If they had a promotional budget, I would have spent most of it there," he says. Other measures would include a letter to suppliers, prompt, even early payments to vendors to reassure them of your business's viability and even increased community involvement to raise visibility and unite employees.
<P>
One of the first tasks, Miller says, is to gather as much information as possible about insurance proceeds.
<P>
<h2>Cleaning Up</h2>

Insurance helps, but it can't replace the sheer effort it takes to rebuild after a tragedy. Repairing the building was, says Miller, "a Herculean effort." Simply drying out took until December. Nothing much happened until January. Then, crews were busy rebuilding what was down and refurbishing what was intact, work that was financed by Miller's insurance advance. Removing mud, hauling away debris, repainting, rewalling and recarpeting took more than three months to complete.
<P.
Eight months later, in April, Izzy Miller Furniture was back at East Mall Plaza. One year later, there hardly remains any evidence of a flood. There are some barely noticeable watermarks on the wall and, reports Miller, the floors are not level. The second floor and basement both remain under construction and contractors work to support a new foundation. Miller says he hopes to be completely finished by Christmas -- in time for the store's 50th anniversary.
<P>
Looking back, Miller contends  that there was not much he would do differently.
<P>

<H2>Insurance</H2>

Miller carried three types of insurance: building, contents and business interruption, as recommended by insurance agents. 
<P>
Mike McGroarty, president of McGroarty and Bradburn Insurance Inc. in Bridgeville, says that a good business owner's policy would include property insurance that covered the property, its contents and business interruption; and general liability in-surance that would cover bodily injury caused to others. Business interruption includes income loss and expenses. 
<P>
While the business owner policy is essential, McGroarty says that small business owners can plan for the unexpected with other policies: flood, earthquake, mine subsidence, tornado, snow and collapse of building insurance all are available either through commercial companies or through government in-surance programs. None, he says, are as popular as the business owner's policy.
<P>
In hindsight Miller says he's not convinced that anything would have been more helpful than using the thought-process he outlined.  "Normal decision-making, reasonably faced, is more important than having the answers to a few questions that can be costly if they're wrong." 
<P>
Says Miller, quite appropriately, "[When preparing for disasters beforehand], it's best to put your toe in the water, don't leap in." Even if that water has destroyed your business.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B><P align=center><Font Size=+2>Getting Out</font><BR><BR><font size=+1>If You Don't Have a Plan, You are Asking for Trouble</font><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></B><P>

<P>
In running their convenience store empire that spans parts of Pennsylvania and three other states, Steve Sheetz and his brothers face tough business decisions every day. In what regions do they expand? What services do they add? 
<P>
The biggie finally hit the board room of the privately held business last year.
<P>
"We had to make a decision about whether we indeed wanted to bring the next generation in. The six of us get along so well ... do we really want to risk that?" recalls Sheetz, who is company president.
<P>
"In the end? We said Yes.' We have a lot of talent in the second generation, so we basically went out and actively recruited them. We just brought two sons back. One is a Wharton School graduate. He has come back as director of personnel. The other has an MBA from Vanderbilt; he'll be a site selector in Pittsburgh."
<P>
Statistics show that about 90 percent of America's 20 million businesses are family-owned or family-controlled. Yet, less than a third of American businesses actually get passed to the second generation, and only 13 percent are passed to the third generation. Many of the others are sold to outsiders or to employees who in many cases maintain the integrity of the business to the original owner's satisfaction.
<P>
But sadly, many just become wasted assets because the business owner failed to develop an adequate succession plan. In simple terms, a succession plan is a road map for successors or heirs to follow in the event the business owner retires, becomes disabled  or dies.
<P>
About 75 percent of family-owned American businesses are operating without a succession plan, which usually sets out elements including  distribution of business stock and other assets, debt retirement schedules and division of responsibility among successors.
<P>
Part of the process includes estate planning. If an owner dies without having transferred stock ownership, that stock is an asset that can be included in the estate, experts say. It is likely that the value of the stock will exceed the $600,000 lifetime exclusion from estate taxation. In that case, the assets of the business might have to be liquidated to pay the estate taxes. The heir to the business becomes everybody's least favorite relative, Uncle Sam. 
<P>
One way to provide for enough liquidity at the time of the owner's death is life insurance. Adopting lifetime gifting strategies, whereby stock ownership is transferred during the owner's lifetime, is another method. And there are many others. 
<P>
The important point is to have an estate-tax strategy in place before the owner dies, and the earlier the better. The annual amount an individual will pay for a fixed amount of life insurance, for example, increases as a person ages. So it pays to plan early.
<P>
That's the easy part, with some help from qualified planners.
<P>
The decision to involve the second generation is the difficult one and often causes business owners to delay succession planning. Do the kids get the business? Or will it be sold to employees?
<P>
"It's absolutely crazy that for people who are so focused on making their business a success, this is the last thing they think about," says Jon Peters, vice president of Cigna Financial Advisors in Pittsburgh. 
<P>
<P>
Some questions to consider: Are the children qualified? Are they even interested? Sometimes family politics get pretty heated when trying to answer those questions.
<P>
"You almost have to have a clinical psychologist come in and evaluate everyone," Peters says, tongue in cheek. "These are delicate issues. For one, you have to find out whether the children can get along with other people."
<P>
In Sheetz's case, he's confident the second generation will work together as well as the current management team does.  The Sheetz business started in 1952 with one dairy store. Now there are more than 170.
<P>
"Our ideas are basically the same," Sheetz says. "People have different opinions, but we come out galvanized. Different ideas don't hurt, as long          as you come out with one idea in         the end."
<P>
If the second generation doesn't show potential or interest, it's best to evaluate the other options, experts say. But some business owners are so hell-bent on passing a business to children that they neglect to analyze the fate to which they may be dooming the business.
<P.
"Look beyond your heartstrings," advises Raymond H. Buehler Jr., a certified public accountant with the Pittsburgh accounting firm Schneider Downs. "You are facing two systems: the family system and the business   system. You can include family members in the company's wealth, but they do not have to be part of the future management."
<P>

<HR>
