</center><P>



<B><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2>New Kids On The Block</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Out-of-Town Firms Are Stealing Business And the Local Talent</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Earl Bohn</i></b>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Lawyering was a profession still known for its stability in 1974, the year Chuck Brodbeck earned his law degree from Princeton and joined the bar.
In fact, some might say the legal community in Pittsburgh in those days was just plain static.</B>
<P>
"People thought they would join a firm and spend the rest of their careers there. In terms of scale, the older members made the most; your production was not so important as the number of years you'd been with the firm," says Brodbeck, president of Cohen & Grigsby, a Pittsburgh firm with just over 60 attorneys.
<P>
Times change, and law is no exception. In any business where competitive forces take hold, those who produce and contribute to the enterprise will be rewarded or they will move on.
<P>
"In the mid to late 1980s, that began to be recognized," Brodbeck says. "No longer did seniority rule."
<P>
Nor does it today, if the swirl of players on the chessboard is any indication.
<P>
Over the last decade, that near continual movement of lawyers from one firm to another, plus the addition of a number of out-of-town firms, has upped the ante for the western Pennsylvania legal community. In the words of Chuck Brodbeck, "the economics of the practice of law has changed."
<P>
No single development can explain the movement, but without a doubt an evolution is under way. For law firms, it's this simple: Take care of rising stars or risk losing them to a competitor.
<P>
<h2>More Competition</h2>
There can be no doubt that 
the competition is growing. Consider these recent additions to the legal 
community:
<DL>	
<LI>Philadelphia stalwart Pepper Hamilton & Sheetz opened a Pittsburgh office, anchored by three commercial litigation stars from Doepken Keevican & Weiss.
	
<LI>Prominent Pittsburgh attorney Marvin Lieber led a group of corporate tax and healthcare specialists from Klett Lieber Rooney & Schorling to create an independent Pittsburgh firm a year ago. It recently affiliated with Philadelphia's Obermayer Rebmann Maxwell & Hippel.
<LI>Another Philadelphia firm, Marshall Dennehey Warner Coleman & Goggin, assembled a new Pittsburgh office two years ago around the prac-tice of veteran litigator Brennan Hart, formerly of Zimmer Kunz Loughren   & Hart.
<LI>In 1990, the New York labor and employment law specialists of Jackson Lewis Schmitzler & Krupman sent Lynn C. Outwater to open and manage a Pittsburgh office.
<LI>Shortly before that, in January 1989, the megafirm Jones Day Reavis & Pogue dispatched Erie native and Pitt Law School graduate Paul Michael "Mickey" Pohl to Pittsburgh to open an office that will number 45 lawyers when the current crop of outgoing judicial clerks arrive.
</DL>
<P>
Of course, Pittsburgh's major firms have long-established beachheads in Philadelphia, Washington, D.C., and elsewhere. And they, too,   hire the local talent. For example, Pittsburgh's Klett Lieber hired        attorneys away from Pepper Hamilton when Klett Lieber opened its Philadelphia office.
<P>
<h2>Why Here?</h2>

In the eyes of some observers, the people of Pittsburgh and western Pennsylvania have refreshing qualities that would seem to lend a bit more  dignity, if you will, to lawyering in     this region.
<P>
"You have a very strong work ethic in western Pennsylvania. The people are not litigious. They're not out looking for people to sue," says Brennan Hart of Marshall Dennehey. 
<P>
"If they've been injured, they want to be compensated fairly, but they don't look at a lawsuit as a way to supplement their income or retire early, whereas in other parts of the country that's the way it is. You often see that in the big Eastern cities, like Philadelphia, New York and Boston, and in Florida and California. You'll find them to be far more litigious. 
<P>
"That's not the mentality of western Pennsylvania, or of most of Pennsylvania for that matter. This is still a fairly conservative jurisdiction."
<P>
At the same time, Pittsburgh has one of the highest concentrations of lawyers per capita in the nation. The Allegheny County Bar Association is the only one in the country that provides career counseling to lawyers. "And we are probably one of the few bar associations left in the United States that bothers with lawyer placements," says ACBA Executive Director James I. Smith.
<P>
"Up until about the early 1980s, I had as many openings for lawyers as I had applicants," Smith says. "Today, I have 200 people looking for work, and most of them are out of work rather than looking to move from their current position to another one."
<P>
The relatively non-litigious character of western Pennsylvanians seems all the more noteworthy when combined with the region's high concentrations of attorneys.
<P>
"We have probably right now one lawyer for every 100 to 130 residents. Of course, the first city in this category is Washington, D.C., but they count bureaucrats, so I'd have to say Pittsburgh is first," Smith says.
<P>
Considering the rule of thumb that only one out of every five people ever consult an attorney, "it doesn't take a genius to realize there isn't enough work to go around. The established firms are doing well, but it's a real problem for the youngsters coming out today," Smith says.
<P>
And therein lies a major distinction between the market for legal talent, which seems to be weak here due to the oversupply of lawyers, and the market for high-quality legal services, which would seem to be anything but weak if the arrival of out-of-town firms and the continued growth of certain native firms is any indication.
<P>
"Everybody seems to be busy at the firms I know," says George M. Medved, managing partner of the 3-month-old Pittsburgh office of Pepper Hamilton & Sheetz, a 105-year-old Philadelphia firm with 275 lawyers in nine cities.
<P>
But it is more than demand for high-quality legal services that is bringing law firms from other cities into Pittsburgh. Firms also face the increasingly discriminating taste of corporate clients.
<P>
"It used to be, and it still is in some instances, that the general counsel of a large corporation would go to New York and hire the biggest law firms he could find under the perception that he could never be criticized for hiring a named firm from New York," Lieber says.
<P>
"But those firms are very expensive, and don't necessarily get better results."
<P>
Now, corporations are retaining fewer outside law firms at any one time, and the ones they use tend to  be based closer to the company's   headquarters. Lawyers must learn all they can about their clients' businesses and how their in-house law departments function. Clients encourage the learning, but they     don't want to pay for the continual education of one new face after   another flying in from the outside counsel's home office. The result:     The firms set up shop where their clients are located. For some, that means setting up shop in Pittsburgh.
<P>
"In the old days, clients would have one or two lawyers in house,  passing out the work to firms. Now, with the overabundance of talent, clients have built up big talented staffs that they expect you [the outside firm] to work with," says Mickey Pohl of Jones Day. 
<P>
"There has been a fundamental restructuring in the way law firms distribute their services to the premier clients," Pohl says. "It's too easy to put lawyers on a plane and send them to the client. Now they want to have offices where the clients are."
<P>

<h2>The Newcomers</h2>

It pays to have lawyers on staff who know the personality of a city and understand the ins and outs of getting things done. Thus, outside firms looking to open an office will try to lure attorneys who have an established client base and know the legal terrain.
<P>
"Some of the early firms tried bringing in their own lawyers, but fell on their face. Then the firms started getting smart and began hiring locally," says the bar association's Smith. 
<P>
In some cases, attorneys find working in Pittsburgh for a firm that is based in another city to be exactly what they want.
<P>
"A lot of lawyers feel that being a lawyer -- not necessarily a partner -- at a satelite office of a large firm is the best of both worlds. They have the resources of the larger firm, but have a smaller environment where they have more control," says Lori Carpenter, principal of Carpenter Legal Search, a firm that recruits attorneys for law firms.
<P>
Pepper Hamilton had been considering a Pittsburgh office for quite some time because of the number of clients whose legal affairs touched western Pennsylvania. George Medved and his partners Thomas W. Trimm and Barry J. Trilling left the former Doepken Keevican Weiss & Medved to open Pepper Hamilton's new office. They brought some clients with them, and added them to the ones Pepper Hamilton already had in Pittsburgh to form an instantly viable operation.
<P>
"It became a natural event," Medved says. "I wouldn't say we're not open to new clients, but it's not a situation where we came here just to prospect for business."
<P>
The new office has four partners, including former state representative David W. Sweet, whose former legislative district covers parts of Washington County. Sweet concentrates on affairs in Harrisburg. Pepper Hamilton's Pittsburgh office also includes four associate attorneys.
<P>
Medved adds to the expertise in construction law that Pepper Hamilton already had in its Philadelphia office. The specialties of Trimm and Trilling -- environmental law being one -- give the firm reason to anticipate hiring additional lawyers in the next few months. Pepper Hamilton is looking for candidates among small firms and private practitioners, and the amount of business the candidates bring is not necessarily the top criterion.
<P>
"The emphasis is not so much on the business as the quality of the person as a lawyer," Medved says. "Another tangible factor is the ability of the person to fit within the firm's culture."
<P>
Take, for example, veteran Pittsburgh attorney George Yokitis, who now is managing partner of the Pittsburgh office opened one year ago by Schnader Harrison Segal & Lewis of Philadelphia. The 60-year-old Phila-delphia firm prides itself on soundly reasoned litigation by 230 lawyers who include nationally prominent members of the profession.
<P>
Enter Yokitis, who bootstrapped himself out of a tiny coal mining town in southwestern Pennsylvania with a college football scholarship. He used that opportunity to become one of the region's top environmental litigators while retaining personal qualities that endear him to members of the bar.
<P>
"It's an ideal firm if you believe that there's nothing more important  to a lawyer than quality work," Yokitis says. 
<P>
Schnader Harrison opened here on Aug. 1, 1994, with Yokitis and one other partner, Mindy Shreve, who also specializes in environmental litigation. This spring, Phillip Binotto Jr. merged his Washington, Pa., practice with the firm, and brought two other lawyers as new Schnader Harrison associates.
<P>
Lawyers will tell you that not every firm makes quality its top priority. As one veteran of the Allegheny County bar says, "Some firms are more entrepreneurial than others."
<P>

<h2>The Talent</h2>

The notion that the legal services industry today is first and foremost a business runs counter to a die-hard perception of the law as a calling that lifts its practitioners above matters as petty as self enrichment. 
<P>
That rosy perception rides the lips of both law school students when they're endeavoring to be frank and to some senior partners when they're pitching hard to prospective clients. 
<P>
In fact, every day a lawyer somewhere files a petition, argues a brief or jousts with a creditor, a judge or a plaintiff's attorney on behalf of a pro bono client or a client with shallow pockets and a fee payment schedule that stretches over the horizon. Those practitioners know full well that the profit margin on the services being rendered can be, well, gross. 
<P>
And in towns from Erie to Waynesburg, in counties and parishes from New Jersey to Louisiana to Oregon, there can be found career prosecutors willing to avow that their careers are well spent hounding serial rapists, thieves and drunken drivers. Likewise, there are career public defenders who believe society is better because they force prosecutors to prove their cases beyond a reasonable doubt. They stay in the public sector despite the knowledge that their houses could be bigger, their vacations more luxurious and their kids better schooled if they would trade their mantles of respectability for the mantras of the big firms. 
<P>
They content themselves with $850-a-week paychecks. But sooner or later, as they contemplate their tuition loan repayment schedules or their middle ages at a Medieval law department in a moribund corporation or the swelling pension plans of their elderly senior partners, most attorneys must ask themselves, "Couldn't I be making more money?"
<P>
Those who act on the question seem to be gaining ground on those who do not. The movement of lawyers and the arrival of firms from other cities are, as Brodbeck of Cohen & Grigsby sees it, proper functions of the market for legal talent.
<P>
"Midsize firms are going to have substantial difficulty maintaining themselves unless they're specialized, due to the cost of technology and the general economics of law firm practice," Brodbeck says.
<P>
In addition, the mid-1970s aren't so far in the past that the culture of seniority-above-all-else has been erased entirely. Within certain firms, as a consequence, "some departments are supporting many other departments," Brodbeck says.
<P>
Mickey Pohl of Jones Day echoes that sentiment.
<P>
"Pittsburgh is viewed from afar as a town of wonderfully talented lawyers who don't manage themselves well. The older ones take out the money and don't reward the younger associates. The history of this town has been young lawyers spinning off" and forming their own firms, he says.
<P>
"Look at the groups that have gone off on their own. They tend to be the good ones who left the top of their firms."
<P.
Those departures, on occasion, have come as body blows to the firm being left behind by its bright young stars. In one instance not many years ago, a senior partner is said to have broken down in tears upon receiving the news that his best stallions had crashed the gate of the corral.
<P>
"What seems to be happening now, more than ever, firms are being approached by unhappy lawyers who want to move," says Carpenter, the recruiter "These are lawyers in other firms who feel they don't have much control over their situation or compensation. Others looking to move have larger practices but don't have the support of larger offices."
<P>
Among the reasons Jones Day had for opening its Pittsburgh office was that the city's major firms "had a reputation for being excellent lawyers, but a little reluctant to work with in-house lawyers." Even in other states, Pitts-burgh and Philadelphia firms had a reputation for being "good but a little bit arrogant," Pohl said. 
<P>
It's an attitude that can't survive   in today's swirling competition for business.
<P>
"There are more lawyers than the world needs or than there is work to support, so you get turmoil," Pohl    says.
Earl Bohn is a freelance writer based in Ben Avon, Pa.
<P>
<HR>

<P align=center><h2>The New Practice Concentration: Construction Law</h2>

The evolution of the law has been a factor for many lawyers, particularly George Medved, who has carved out a niche in construction law after helping represent the Port Authority of Allegheny County in disputes arising from the construction of the light rail transit system in the 1980s. 
<P>
Other firms also have attorneys who concentrate a portion of their practice on this emerging area        of law. For example, Tucker Arensberg's Gary P. Hunt does a good deal of work in construction cases, which often focus on the costs associated with projects when they are late being finished. 
<P>
"If you're the owner, the delay causes you to lose the revenue you'd make if the operation opened on time. If you're the contractor, the delay requires you to keep personnel and equipment in the field longer than planned," Medved says. "In the early 1980s, there were probably only 15 practitioners in Pittsburgh. Now the county bar association has started a construction law section."
<P>
ACBA Executive Director  James I. Smith chuckles at the recollection of a call he got from lawyers at Babst Calland Clements & Zomnir who specialize in construction law and said the field was expanding so rapidly it deserved to have a special section of its own with the bar association.
<P>
"Back in April, they said, `We're getting big enough that we want to form a committee.' Generally, anybody who can put together 25 or 30 lawyers has really got something. I thought maybe they'd get 40. We advertised for an organizational meeting, and I'll be a son of a gun, right now they've got well over 100."
<P>
The growth, which is not peculiar to Pittsburgh, stands to reason as owners write increasingly detailed performance incentives and delay penalties into their contracts. Even without the trend to tighter parameters on contractor performance, it would be a noteworthy feat to pull off a project like the construction of Pittsburgh's new airport terminal without a lawsuit being filed over something.
<P> <B>-- Earl Bohn</B>

<HR>

<h2>Seven Reasons Why Partners Explore New Employment Opportunities</h2>

<OL>

<LI>The partner feels he or she is not making a fair salary.

<LI>The partner's role in firm decision-making is limited.

<LI>The partner wants more control over the development of the practice.

<LI>The partner is not getting the administrative or associate support needed to build a practice.   

<LI>Many firms still compensate partners on the basis of seniority.  Thus, less senior partners leave for firms that reward a partner for the business he or she generates. 

<LI>Young partners feel some mid-level partners are not pulling their weight. 

<LI>Another firm may be starting a new practice area, offering the young partner immediate power as head of the new group if he or she jumps ship.

</OL>
<P>
<hr>

