<B><P align = center><font size=+2>Our Children </FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>How a Weak Pennsylvania Law Places Children in Day Care Centers in Peril</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban <FILL></i></b>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>

It was the sweltering summer heat that slowly drained life from 4-year-old Alexandra LeVasseur. While under the care of the Creation Station Day Care Center located south of Pittsburgh, Alexandra was left sleeping in a van following a field trip to Pittsburgh. The co-owner of the facility simply forgot about the young girl, who died of heat stroke about 23 hours later.
<P>
State public welfare department workers inspected the Creation Station the next day and found too many children and too few day care counselors. The state had licensed Creation Station to care for 29 children, but counted 33 children during the inspection. The number of counselors fell two short of what the state required.
<P>
The welfare department shut down the center -- obviously deserved in light of what had happened to Alexandra the day before.
<P>
But in many cases, day care center operators across Pennsylvania exceed capacity or violate state-mandated staff-child ratios and receive little more than a reprimand. 
<P>
Don't blame the welfare department. Child care experts say the welfare department is just enforcing the weak, ineffective law that was legislated by Harrisburg lawmakers.
<P>
How weak?
<P>
"I believe there is no incentive for these day care centers to not cut corners," says Martha Isler, who once headed the state's Bureau of Child Development and now is director of the YWCA's Child Care Partnership in Pittsburgh. 
<P>
"It's a minority of day care providers who are abusing the process," Isler says. "But even if it's only, say, 10 percent -- with 350 licensed centers in Allegheny County alone -- 35 could be operating outside the health and safety standards.
<P>
"When you are talking about reducing risk to children, that 10 percent that is not in compliance is an unacceptable percentage," Isler says.
<P>
"I certainly agree that the law needs more teeth," adds Louise Sutton, director of the public welfare department's western region, which covers   23 counties. 
<P>
"The law is an antiquated law," Sutton says. "We do need better enforcement powers."
<P>
And soon. Day care is a booming industry. One recent count showed 3,697 licensed group homes or day care centers in Pennsylvania that care for seven or more children. Another 4,132 registered family day care homes care for four to six children. Expect those numbers to grow hand in hand with the increasing number of working parents and single parents.
<P>
<h2>A Weak Law</h2>
Under the Pennsylvania Public Welfare Code, the welfare department has several options when it finds a day care provider to be skirting laws and regulations.
<P>
A common step for repeat violators is downgrading the center's license to provisional status, which for the most part only puts the center on notice that it is out of compliance.
<P>
In more serious cases, the state can issue a cease and desist order in an effort to close a center, but the center retains the right to appeal, a lengthy process during which the center may remain open.
<P>
Then there is injunctive relief, under which the state seeks a court order to immediately close down the center. Good luck.
<P>
"We had a situation in the dead of winter a few years back," Sutton recalls. "There were infants in a day care center with no heat. They had to keep winter clothing on inside the facility. We asked for injunctive relief to close the center, but a judge denied it."
<P>
The only real power the welfare department has is to effectuate an emergency closure, as it did at Creation Station. But Section 1031 of the Public Welfare Code strictly limits such action to cases where immediate life-threatening danger is evident.
<P>
Complicating matters, the welfare department has to consider two distinct audiences when deciding whether it should even attempt to close down a facility. Along with the operators, the other audience is comprised of working parents who pay to have their children in day care. If a center is closed down, the parents are thrown into sudden hardship, trying to secure another place for Junior to go at 7 a.m. the next morning. It's not an easy task, especially in cases involving single parents.
<P>
As a result, the closures have been reserved for drastic cases, usually following incidents such as the one involving Alexandra LeVasseur. That same week, the Grandmom's House day care center on Pittsburgh's North Side voluntarily closed after a 4-year-old girl under that center's care           was found inside a locked van in         90-plus degree heat outside of a rollerskating rink.
<P>
But most day care centers cited   for overcapacity or staff-child ratio  violations are able to go about busi-ness as usual.
<P>
"There is no negative sanction, whatsoever," Isler says. "The day care providers are merely handed a piece    of paper that tells them to come        into compliance."
<P>
Compared to laws in other states, Pennsylvania's legislation has several shortcomings. Most notably:
<DL>
<LI>The state public welfare department has absolutely no authority to levy fines against licensed providers. Only unlicensed providers can be fined, $300 per day. In           some other states, licensed providers face fines for violating health and     safety regulations such as staff-child ratio violations.
<LI>There are no provisions for the public welfare department to suspend the licenses and temporarily close a facility for serious violations. Isler, Sutton and others believe such a measure, with proper enforcement, would motivate providers to follow the letter of the law.
<P>
North Carolina's law, for instance, allows for both suspensions and fines of up to $1,000 for violations committed by licensed providers.
<P>
"We use it -- not real frequently, but we use it," says Talitha Wright, chief of eastern regulatory services for the North Carolina Division of Child Development.
<P>
"Primarily, it's not a one-time thing," Wright says. "We use it for repeated violations."
<P>
Pennsylvania will use it the same way, if Sutton has her way. Her staff currently is building profiles of day care operators to include a history of past violations. Those centers that routinely have violated staff-child ratios or have been over capacity would be the first to face the penalties.
<P>
"Until a penalty affects their   pocketbook or their business, it won't carry any significance to the licensed providers," Sutton says. "Fines will send a clear message about the importance of the regulations. Fines will tell providers they must protect children in their care. Fines will tell providers the welfare department is serious about enforcement.
<P>
"As for suspensions? Thirty days would be meaningful," Sutton says. "Parents might be able to take a day off if the center is suspended for one day, but what parents can take off 30 days? When parents have to cover 30 days, they would shop elsewhere and that would affect that facility's business."
<P>
For the fines or suspensions to be  effective, child advocates say  inspectors must have the power to levy them on the spot, similar to the power police officers have to issue traffic citations.
<P>
That's one thing lawmakers forgot about in North Carolina, where fining day care centers is a lengthy process filled with plenty of paperwork and bureaucratic review. Sometimes, the cost of collecting a fine in North Carolina exceeds the actual fine, according to Wright.
<P>
"If it were more immediate, it would have more of an impact,"  Wright says.
<P>
<h2>Not So Fast</h2>

Natalie Kaplan considers herself lucky. She runs a large day care center with ample staff to allow her to move people around and compensate when a staffer is off sick.
<P>
"We just had a problem where one of the staff came to work with an eye problem,"  says Kaplan, who runs the Carriage House in Pittsburgh's Squirrel Hill neighborhood. "We had to get    her out because if she has pink eye,    she cannot be near the children. Fortunately, I have a large center. We had to move a person over, but if we didn't have flexibility, we would have been one child over the staff-child ratio.
<P>
"These things happen. I'm sure the licensing agents see some centers that really are not the better centers. They feel frustrated," Kaplan says.
<P>
The problem is, according to Kaplan, that most day care centers do not enjoy the staff flexibility she enjoys, so they are more apt to cut corners when a staffer is out sick. These same centers are operating on shoe string budgets, so a fine levied against them would only further complicate their situation.
<P>
"A lot of day care operators don't have any money. If they get a fine, it's difficult," Kaplan says. "At the same time, I can understand how the licensing agents feel. There are always people out there trying to get away with more than they should. It's a real Catch 22."
<P>
The welfare department's Sutton says her workers understand that anything from illness to bad weather can put a day care center in a temporary staffing bind. She says penalties probably won't be levied is those cases.
<P>
It's the centers that repeatedly cut corners that she is after.
<P>
<h2>The Corner Cutters</h2>

On June 28, a 4-year-old autistic boy drowned in a pool behind a day care center just outside of Wilkes-Barre, Luzerne County. The welfare department determined that the owner of the center, Mable Roper, 63, had been watching 10 children by herself. State law required a second staffer.
<P>
What's more, state licensing agents conducted a sweep of every day care center in Luzerne County in the weeks that followed the drowning. The results were shocking: All but four of the 71 centers were found to be in some sort of violation.
<P>
Or were those numbers so shocking? Many day care centers operate by the book. But at the same time, these recent incidents show that other day care providers are cutting corners.
<P>
And consider this: State welfare regulations require the welfare department to forewarn centers when licensing agents will be conducting their annual inspection.
<P>
"Even when people know we are coming, we can end up with 11 pages of violations," Sutton says. "If they don't know, imagine what would be evident."
<P>
A simple business strategy calls for maximizing revenue while reducing costs. For some day care centers, that means caring for more children than the number permitted under the license. It also means employing as few caregivers as possible, sometimes less than what the state requires.
<P>
Sound familiar? 
<P>
Creation Station, where Alex-andra LeVasseur was left inside the van, had more children than permitted and less staff than required by law. And don't underestimate the graveness of those violations,  experts say.
<P>
"There should be automatic suspensions for violations concerning being over capacity or ignoring the staff-child ratios," Isler says. "These are the most serious violations.
<P>
"The question of how many children can be handled by an adult is well researched. Imagine during an emergency if you are caring for four infants and you have to get them out of a building during a fire. Imagine trying to get six or eight out of a building. What if they are toddlers, running every which direction?"
<P>

<h2>The Legislators' Part</h2>

At presstime, it was unclear whether child advocates would get the changes in the law that they desire. State Sen. Michael Fisher, a Republican from Upper St. Clair, started the ball rolling in August by calling for public hearings to investigate the western Pennsylvania incidents. Fisher says he wants to examine the training of day care workers and regulation and licensing of day care facilities.
<P>
Those in the day care industry complained quietly that Fisher was blindly jumping into the day care foray without really knowing the issues. Fisher himself was noncommittal when queried about how Pennsyl-vania's public welfare law lacks in comparison to other states.
<P>
"I am not a big proponent of new regulation," Fisher says. "But, that's an issue that needs to be looked at. I am not sure that our law, which is directed towards licensing, is adequate. It may not be adequate. It may not be much more than a lot of paperwork. A lot of paperwork does not mean that the facilities are safe. Is it really the level of care that parents want for their kids?"
<P>
In the meantime, the welfare department says it is increasing the number of unannounced visits and stepping up action against the licenses of serious violators. 
<P>

<h2>The Parents' Part</h2>

Even if legislators beef up the law, it still won't be foolproof. Child care experts say parents will have to do their part, which includes picking a good center to begin with and then holding that center to certain standards.
<P>
When Ellen Wein searched for a day care center for her two daughters, Amy and Robin, she treated the task as if her daughters' lives depended on the decision. In fact, they do.
<P>
"I left no stone unturned," says Wein, vice president of Jampole Communications Inc., a Pittsburgh public relations firm.
<P>
"I did the same type of research I would do for a project at work. I scrutinized alternatives. I asked a lot of questions. I inspected on-site, showing up unannounced to see how I was received and to catch daily activities at the center.
<P>
"There were some centers where there would an be adult sitting on a couch, then they would see me coming with an administrator and it would be like someone just turned them on. They all of a sudden would start interacting with the children. That's bad.
<P>
"At other centers, it seemed like the adults outnumbered the children. That's appealing."
<P>
Once Wein weeded the good from the bad, she was left with her finalists, about whom she conducted background checks to make sure they did not have excessive run-ins with the public welfare department. None did.
<P>
Until state licensing agents have more power to regulate centers, parents must be aggressive in investigating and eventually choosing the day care center that cares for their children. It's best to be deliberate in your search, as Wein and others have been.
<P>
"Our selection process was pretty lengthy," says Bob Bailey, a specifications architect for Williams Trebilock Whitehead. Bailey and his wife have a   4-year-old daughter, Elizabeth, in         day care.
<P>
"A lot of it had to do with the atmosphere of the place and the kind of connection you see between the caregivers and the kids," Bailey says. "We visited places where the impression was that the kids were dumped off, the kids were there, and for the caregivers, it was just a job. There was no connection with the kids whatsoever. You can sense it."
<P>
Sandy Lancia, art director for the St. George Group in Pittsburgh, had to find a day care facility after giving birth to twins, Ross and Michelle, about 2 1/2 years ago. She eventually narrowed the choice to three, at which point she also researched the public welfare department's record of violations by the finalists. Like Wein, she too found nothing alarming and eventually used other factors to chose the center where her children now spend their days.
<P>
Unfortunately, surveys show that the majority of parents choose a day care center based on cost and location. Instead, parents should be more concerned about ratios and the quality of caregivers, child care experts say.
<P>
Many centers staff beyond what the state requires, lessening the chance of the staff being outnumbered, as was Creation Station the day Alexandra LeVasseur was left in the hot van.
<P>
"I don't think there is any excuse for not being able to meet the staff-child ratios," says Wein. "Whether it be for safety, for discipline, for learning -- there are all sorts of reasons to have all hands on deck.
<P>
"Some people won't place their children in a day care center because they don't like the way the place looks," Wein adds. "To hell with how the rooms are decorated. If there are more adults than children there, I am willing to pay for that."
<P>
It doesn't stop there, according to the welfare department's Sutton. Parents are in and out of the centers every day, so they are the best to notice potential problems. When that happens, they should pick up the telephone.
<P>
"We have to do a better job of letting parents know what the regulations are so they can help us in the enforcement," Sutton says. "They can call us and let us know if there is insufficient staff. 
<P>
"Changing the law will help, but there is a whole range of things to be addressed to make day care more enforceable, to make the system safe and to protect children in day care."
<P>
Until these changes take place, some day care centers will continue to cut corners. And young children will still be in danger.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<center><h2>A Parent's Checklist for Choosing a Day Care Center</h2></center>

Choosing a day care program for your child is a challenge. When selecting a program, visit at a time of day when children at the center will be active. Morning is a good time. Take your child along and don't hesitate to ask questions. Choose the program with which you feel most comfortable. Remember, convenience and price are not the most important factors. At the same time, don't expect to find everything listed on the checklist below.
<P>
<h2>Things to Check:</h2>
<OL TYPE=I>
<LI><h3>The Staff</h3>
	<UL>
	<LI>Treats children with both respect and patience.
	<LI>Can meet your child's developmental and emotional needs.
	<LI>Is of sufficient number to meet the needs of children.
	<LI>Takes time to discuss your child with you.
	<LI>Has previous experience or training in working with children.
	</UL><P>
<LI><h3>The Facility</h3>
	<UL>
	<LI>Safe indoor and outdoor play areas and equipment.
	<LI>Orderly, clean play areas.
	<LI>Airy rooms.
	<LI>Sanitary bathrooms and diaper changing areas.
	</UL><P>
<LI><h3>Health and Safety</h3>
	<UL>
	<LI>Comfortable temperatures in all seasons.
	<LI>Rounded table corners.
	<LI>Nontoxic play materials.
	<LI>First aid kit.
	<LI>Healthy snacks and meals.
	<LI>Clean kitchen area.
	<LI>Handwashing after toileting and before meals and snacks.
	<LI>Separate cribs for infants and separate cots\mats for others.
	<LI>Cleaning materials, medicines out of children's reach.
	</UL><P>
<LI><h3>The Program</h3>
	<UL>
	<LI>Proper staff-child ratios.
	<LI>Creative play.
	<LI>Plenty of both play and educational materials.
	<LI>Organized program of activities.
	<LI>Supervised rest time.
	<LI>Minimal, supervised TV, if any.
	<LI>Story reading.
	</UL><br>
<LI><h3>General</h3>
	<UL>
	<LI>State license or registration certificate.
	<LI>Rules clearly explained.
	<LI>Good behavior encouraged.
	<LI>Parents visiting.
	<LI>No children "left out."
	<LI>Lots of laughing, caring, sharing.
	</UL>
</OL>
<P>
 
<h3>Ten Questions Parents Should Ask:</h3>
<OL>
<LI>May I drop in anytime?
<LI>May I participate in program planning?
<LI>May I take part in special events and trips?
<LI>What are the fees and what do the fees include?
<LI>Are the caregivers trained in child development?
<LI>What are the hiring procedures?
<LI>May I contact staff references?
<LI>Are there restrictions on who may pick up my child?
<LI>What happens if my child gets sick or injured at the center?
<LI>Is there a parents' group or program?
</OL>
<P>

<h4>Source: Pennsylvania Department of Public Welfare</h4>

<P>

