<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.Update.2.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H3Publish.gif"><a href="../zine/1095.Editorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Politics As Usual? </FONT SIZE>
<i> By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher </i></b><P>


<P>
The job of the politicians should be to combat the myriad problems in today's society. Alarming increases in youth violence, a lack of economic vibrancy, waning job opportunities and a pervasive sense of hopelessness evidence that ours is no longer a civil society. But instead, politicians use sound bites to battle each other. 
<P>
As campaign signs emerge on the landscape and political messages crowd the airwaves, I think of my own brief foray into politics.
<P>
Several days before the primary election, anonymous phone calls in-formed  Republican voters throughout the county that my health was failing.  Major broadcast media received anonymous calls indicating that I was hospitalized and in serious condition. At strategically identified polls, voters, many of them my friends, were pulled aside and told of my failing health. 
<P>
My phones rang repeatedly with calls about my well-being. But aside from the knot that formed in my stomach when I realized the reprehensible behavior that the political system permits, I was perfectly fine. I have had a physical disability since birth, but no serious, ongoing medical problems.
<P>
We are fighting the wrong enemy, destroying our political leaders before they take office. Respect must be re-stored to the practice of politics.
<P>
Fact: People are increasingly apathetic about the political process. Less than half of all adults are registered to vote. Though it was a beautiful day, less than 45% of those registered voted in the last primary election. 
<P>
No wonder. The public has fewer quality choices. Well-qualified people are discouraged by the experience of those who ran before them. They know history repeats itself.
<P>
A more discerning public wouldn't be fooled. Today's public, distanced from the political process by its inanity, must champion progressive approaches and demand integrity. Instead, principled leadership is a rare commodity, because today's politicians exchange their scruples for success. The price of admission to politics is years of stuffing envelopes or playing bingo. If this region needs to get out a bulk mailing in a hurry, trust me, several current leaders can handle the challenge.
<P>
"That's politics," we say, ultimately protecting the absence of humanity and civility in the political process. Conduct which is totally unacceptable elsewhere is condoned under the banner of politics.
<P>
Well, people get what they deserve. As long as the public tolerates abhorrent behavior between aspiring politicians, we will have politics as usual.
<P>

<hr>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>

