<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.Publisher.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H4Editor.gif"><a href="../zine/1095.Letters.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<B><P align=center><font size=+3>Competion</font><BR>
<font size=+2>We Need More Of It, Not Less </font><BR>
<i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>

<HR>
<P>
I once had a newspaper carrier who managed to deliver the Sunday edition just before noon, but well after my coffee was cold and  bagels hard. I wanted to relax and read the paper. Instead, I waited for the carrier to arrive.
<P>
The problem? There was no competition. He delivered when he wanted to deliver. Complaints fell on deaf ears. My other option was to drive to a store and purchase a copy. It's not the most attractive option in the middle of winter, minutes after climbing out of bed. 
<P>
Competition is crucial to our society. Competition allows the consumer to receive top quality goods or services and rewards those who supply those goods or services. 
<P>
For good reason, we talk about competition throughout this month's issue of Executive Report.
<P>
Take the legal community: Out of town firms are opening satellite offices in Pittsburgh. Some are hiring established attorneys who bring with them a Rolodex full of business. Not only is there competition between firms for business, there's also competition between firms for quality attorneys. Some attorneys who feel they are undervalued by their current employer will jump to other firms for more money or power. Good for them.
<P>
Then there's the healthcare community. Our cover shows two football helmets banging against one another. One is symbolic of Blue Cross and the other of HealthAmerica. Both are engaged in a price war right now that is having a trickle-down effect on the consumer.
<P>
This rivalry between Blue Cross and HealthAmerica has become a touchy subject for some. When Executive Report staffers were mulling over illustration ideas for this month's cover, Blue Cross expressed concern that we might depict it as being on the same level as HealthAmerica. Don't let us mislead you. As Lydia Strohl reports in the story that begins on page 24, Blue Cross definitely is the dominant carrier in this region, with a market share approaching 65 percent.
<P>
As for the quality of actual care? We find no reason to stray from a presumption that both Blue Cross and HealthAmerica provide quality healthcare with minimal administrative headaches for the consumer.
<P>
But what if one did not meet the standards set by the consumer? That's a critical question. What choices would the consumer have? Where could the consumer turn for better quality or service? Without ample competition, our options are limited.
<P>
Some observers think Blue Cross will further cement its dominance in this market. I don't think we want one carrier running away with this market. That leaves power resting in one place. Again, that likely would mean fewer options for the consumer.
<P>
Consider what happened last spring at the University of Pittsburgh: The university opted to give Blue Cross an exclusive contract for all of Pitt's healthcare business. Pitt already was fighting stagnant enrollment and stingy state legislators who wanted to minimize funding for the school. Pitt found it could save millions on the expense side of its budget by dealing exclusively with Blue Cross. An added benefit was the amount of business funneled into Pitt Medical Center, which has a PPO joint-venture with Blue Cross.
<P>
The contract angered many of Pitt's 6,500 employees, 76 percent of whom had voted to retain their choice of provider before the deal went through. About 5,000 employees who were enrolled in HealthAmerica were switched to Blue Cross. Many employees complained that they were left with no choices.
<P>
We, as healthcare consumers, should want to retain some of the power that competition gives to us. In the end, competition will not only ensure the quality of our healthcare, but it will also help contain costs.
<P>
This isn't a slam on Blue Cross. I sincerely hope that Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania will remain the thriving entity it already is. But here also is a vote for HealthAmerica, US Healthcare, Aetna and any other health insurer that is trying to make a go of it in the western Pennsylvania market. 
<P>
Competition is good. We need it in this healthcare market.
<P>
Long live the rivalries.
<P>  

<hr>

