<font size =+2><B>Innovative Schools </B></font size><P>
<pre>
Bravo!
<P>
Your editorial on "Don't Fight Innovation in our Schools" is just 
what the doctor ordered.

<h4>				Helen Sobehart
				Fox Chapel School District</h4>
<HR>
Great article!

Know that I will have provided all the superintendents with a copy. 
Thanks for supporting public education.

<h4>				Joseph Lagana
				Executive Director
				Allegheny Intermediate Unit</h4>
<HR>
I very much enjoyed reading your valuable remarks in the August 1995 
Publisher's Note. The thoughts expressed very much echo my own sentiments 
when I have said time and again -- "Everybody wants school improvement but 
no one will allow school change to occur."

<h4>				Joseph C. Dimperio
			 	Superintendent of Schools
		 		West Mifflin Area School District</h4>
<HR>
The message of not fighting change in schools is such an important 
one and it's nice to see these words coming from a wide variety of 
speakers and reaching different audiences.

<h4>				Jane C. Burger
				The Grable Foundation
				Pittsburgh</h4>
<HR>

<B><P align=center><font size=+2>High Priced Higher Education</font></B><P>

Some national official recently observed that the entire curriculum 
of Columbia University would fit on one CD-ROM. I make this observation 
to support Jim Urban's contention that an undergraduate education is 
probably overpriced, particularly in light of the advances in technology 
and the practical quality of the education product in today's exciting 
economy.

<h4>				Leo Petrini
				Agoura Hills, CA</h4>
<HR>
Not only are our college graduates burdened by debt just to pay for 
their college education, but they also accumulate an additional burden 
of credit card debts.

College students today are given credit cards like some people give 
candy to children. It is not unusual to find a college student carrying 
a MasterCard, Visa and a Discover Card, in addition to their retail 
store credit cards.

Unfortunately, they have very little self-control and even less income. 
This combination creates poor habits, and they then develop poor credit 
ratings.

While we are educating our young people as to the burden of student 
loan indebtedness, don't forget to educate them about the equally 
crushing burden of consumer loan indebtedness.

<h4>				Mark Anthony
				Director, Career Services
				Indiana University of Pennsylvania</h4>
<HR>

<b><P align=center><font size=+2>A Vote For Specter</font></b><P>
 
In February 1994, our firm, Compunetix Inc., installed a large 
teleconferencing system as part of the Air Traffic Control System 
Command Center in Herndon, Va. The system was accepted by the Federal 
Aviation Administration on March 26, 1994. The delivery was timed to
coincide with the grand opening of the new FAA facility.

Unfortunately, the contractual instruments had not been made definite 
because of continuing changes in the FAA requirements. Negotiations were 
marred by continuing, frustrating delays. Of course, Compunetix could 
not support the FAA's operations without payments. The FAA's ability 
to support national air traffic was placed into jeopardy.

In April, more than one year after the system acceptance, Compunetix 
brought the situation to the attention of U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter (R.-Pa.).

Sen. Specter immediately went to work. As a result, the acquisition 
department of the FAA recognized the seriousness of the situation 
and focused its resources on this negotiation. The contract was 
executed on July 21, 1995. Projected revenues under this contract 
exceed $7.3 million.

Compunetix expresses its sincere gratitude to Sen. Specter for his 
prompt and intelligent attention to the needs of Compunetix and of 
the FAA. This is one more sign of Sen. Specter's sensitivity to the 
relevance of the high technology industry in Pennsylvania.

<h4>				Giorgio Coraluppi
				President, Compunetix Inc.
				Monroeville</h4>
<HR>

<h2>Get In The Last Word</h2>

So your thoughts won't fit in a letter? Executive Report invites 
members of the business community to express their opinion in our 
monthly feature: The Last Word.

Pick a topic, take a stance and be prvocative. The Last Word appears 
monthly on the last page of the magazine, just inside the back cover. 
If you have an idea, dorp Executive Report Editor-in-Chief Jim Urban 
a note.

<HR>

<h2>PRSA Symposium This Month</h2>

This month, ER will sponsor a Public Relations Society of America 
symposium that will be held in weekly sessions. Three professionals 
will describe projects they worked on related to the week's theme. 
A moderator from ER will lead a question and answer session at the 
end of each case history presentation.

The four programs, each held at Point Park College on a Tuesday 
morning, will cover 
crisis communications,  Oct. 10, 7:30 a.m.; 
marketing communications, Oct. 17, 7:30 a.m.; 
corporate communications, Oct. 24, 7:30 a.m., 
and new horizons in the PR industry, Oct. 31, 7:30 a.m.

</pre>

