<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.Letters.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H5Guest.gif"><a href="../zine/1095.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <b><P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3>The Jungle</FONT SIZE><P>
<P align=center><font size=+2>For Small Business, the Awaiting Beasts Include Litigation, Regulation and Taxation</font><br>
 <i>By Neil F. Fogarty</b></i>
<HR>

<P>
Developing a small business? Welcome to the jungle. 
<P>
In this wilderness ruled by the world's most merciless tigers (litigation, regulation and taxation), small enterprises are amongst the must vulnerable of creatures, while new ventures constitute even weaker prey. Large companies groan, but at least they have the resources to shield themselves. Small and new companies have no such armor.
<P>
Numerous studies have concluded that job growth and economic development are heavily dependent on small businesses. Particularly in our area, a locale scarred by closed mills and limping from layoffs, small business development is vital. As a community, we must find a path that leads to secure and prosperous careers for all families. That's the path to small business development. But, we will fail miserably unless we change the disastrous small business environment. 
<P>
Pennsylvania ranks last in new business development and, within    our state, Pittsburgh ranks near the bottom. The problems hindering small business are obvious.
<P>
Take the litigious tiger. In the United States, a lawsuit is filed every 30 seconds.The average legal fee to defend a business through trial is $50,000. The average legal rate in Pittsburgh is around $200 an hour, and a local attorney was quoted recently as saying that he thought that a fee of $325 an        hour -- plus expenses, of course -- was "reasonably cheap"! In light of these, how can a small business afford to defend itself? Further, many of those who sue a small business are not paying such fees -- instead they are represented by attorneys who squawk, "There is no fee unless we collect for you." Why shouldn't someone seek a million dollar recourse because the coffee was too hot -- the price is right.
<P>
If the first tiger does not get you, the second might: The regulatory tiger never sleeps. A senator recently stated that last year over 65,000 pages of new governmental regulations were printed in the United States. Even if those pages were the size of postage stamps, that's mind-boggling. Considering that regulations are being spewed forth 40 hours a week, 52 weeks a year from one federal government, 50 state governments, numerous territorial governments and more than 50,000 local governments, that horrendous number may be low. Although many assume that these new laws regulate big businesses, because only 2 percent of American businesses are big, most of these actually apply to small firms. To make matters worse (if that's possible), most small businesses don't even know that these new regulations exist until they are hauled into court, issued a fine and discover that the local media has told the world.
<P>
The last tiger may have the sharpest teeth: the insatiable tiger of taxation. At least until this year when Tommy Ridge and his Republican Roughriders stormed the heights of Harrisburg, our state had the highest business taxes in the nation. Various reforms have been and are being instituted, but keep in mind that the populace is being told that these are tax breaks for big business and the rich. It's an old song, but the tune can be catchy. Sadly, the singers often forget that 98% of the businesses that are benefiting from reduced taxes are small businesses, many of which barely make ends meet yet employ good, hard-working people upon whom families depend. No matter how jaunty the jingle, more taxes on cash-starved small businesses won't generate new jobs.
<P>
Our area is blessed with many  jungle-fighting organizations like      the small business development centers, the Service Corps of Retired Executives, Home Business Associ-ation, etc., who undertake a mountain of work armed with hardly anything more than nonprofit, plastic shovels. Nonetheless, they courageously endeavor to help fend off the menacing tigers and protect as many small businesses as they can. These heroic efforts notwithstanding, we desperately need more help. We need everyone to do their share. 
<P>
If nothing else, stop voting for politicians because of party affiliation or name familiarity. Many politicians who have never even run a lemonade stand (much less a small business) are now passing laws that generate more litigation, regulation and taxation. Furthermore, encourage your children to develop the creative energies necessary to start and run small businesses. This country was founded upon entrepreneurial spirit, so encourage it in your daughters and sons. Finally, quit thinking about starting a business of your own -- get out there and do it. It's a risk, but if you try you might succeed, and if you don't, you won't. Keep your overhead low (start it in your home) and do it part-time (keep your day job), but stop procrastinating.
<P>
Some of you may fear failing, but who has really failed? Someone who started a small business who did not succeed, or someone who has a great idea but does nothing?
<P>
<h4>Neil F. Fogarty, an inductee into "Who's Who of American Professionals" because of his advocacy for small business development, is a lecturer of business law at the University of Pittsburgh, author of the book "Starting a Business in Pittsburgh," and managing attorney for the business law firm of Fogarty & Associates.</h4>
<P>

<hr>

