<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.GuestEditorial.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif"><a href="../zine/1095.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<FONT SIZE=+2><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>

<h2>Wedge or Pickle?</h2>

The golf ball rests on the fringe of the 18th green at Oakmont. Tony O'Reilly checks the break, then pulls out his ... pickle putter?
<P>
Well, probably not. But O'Reilly's food conglomerate, Pittsburgh-based H.J. Heinz Co., does have pickle putters for sale. The golf club looks like a regular putter until you reach the head, then it looks like a regular pickle. 
<P>
Heinz tested the marketability of the pickle putter and other Heinz paraphernalia in a kiosk gift shop the company ran at suburban Pittsburgh's Ross Park Mall during August. Vendors handed out pickle pins for free. Customers had to pay for the other merchandise, which ranged from clothing to cookie jars to hats.
<P>
Heinz spokeswoman Deb Magness says the company traditionally has sold merchandise to employees, but has seen an increasing number of queries from the general public about Heinz merchandise.
<P>
Rolling Rock runs a popular gift shop at its brewery in Latrobe. Magness says Heinz has ruled out a similar gift shop at its North Side plant, citing security concerns.
<P>
Heinz planned to have a gift catalog out this fall. Magness says Heinz also will revisit the Ross Park shop in November, just in time for holiday shopping.

<HR>

<h2>So Long Integra</h2>

Integra's announcement that it will sell to Cleveland-based National City Corp., along with a flurry of other such deals, has created speculation that other bank mergers are not far behind.
<P>
Mellon, which at press time was being mentioned as an attractive acquisition candidate, is clearly undervalued. Its retail franchise and asset management/investment services business are among the finest in the nation. If it remains independent, Mellon should benefit enormously from the acquisition of Integra.
<P>
ER Index columnist Doug Thomas notes that Pittsburghers are going to have to be convinced that banking with a Cleveland-based bank is better than Mellon or PNC or any of the other smaller area banks. Banks like Parkvale Financial, Southwest National and BT Financial, stand to pick up market share as a result of the defection of depositors and borrowers who prefer to deal with a local bank. As Gerry Swatsworth, the former chairman and CEO of BT Financial once told Thomas, the smaller banks in western Pennsylvania can prosper quite nicely by living off the crumbs the big banks leave on the table. With Integra set to be replaced by an even bigger out-of-town bank, there should be more crumbs.
<P>
One footnote to the Integra merger: The Chicago Corp., an investment house, in July downgraded from buy to hold its recommendation on Integra Financial Corp.'s stock. The investment house listed several reasons for the downgrade, the first of which was, "Loan demand continues to suffer from sluggish economic growth in western Pennsylvania."
<P>
The significance? It no longer is a secret that this region is stagnating economically. New business development lags behind both the national and statewide rates. Outsiders are noticing.
<P>
Chicago Corp. also expressed concern about the bank's declining margins over the past four quarters. 
<P>
"Unlike many banks, [Integra] has little in the way of loan growth to mitigate the ailing margin," Chicago Corp. wrote. 

<HR>

<h2>Tipping the Scales</h2>

Statistics show that about two-thirds of working Americans land their first jobs in the food service industry, at anything from a hospital cafeteria to the drive-thru window at McDonald's. 
<P>
When and if Congress increases the minimum wage, restaurants and other food service employers likely will be the hardest hit. 
<P>
"In the restaurant industry, the minimum wage enables employers to hire huge numbers of inexperienced workers and teach them the basic skills," says Ralph O. Brennan, president of the National Restaurant Association.  "When you artificially raise the minimum, you make it more expensive for employers to give unproven workers a chance."
<P>
Proponents of an increase argue that most minimum wage earners are heads of households below the poverty line. But the numbers don't show this to be the case. An estimated 80 percent of minimum wage earners do not reside in poverty level households. In fact, half of these households make double the poverty level.  
<P>
"In the food service industry and in many others, entry-level jobs are a way in and a way up," says Brennan, whose statements are supported by statistics.
<P>
In 1980, 12.4 percent of U.S. workers earned minimum wage; today that number is less than 4 percent. Research by Ralph E. Smith and Bruce Varichek of the U.S. Congressional Budget Office published in Industrial and Labor Relations Review shows that about 63 percent of minimum wage workers are promoted to higher-paying positions within their first year, with the median increase being a 20 percent raise.  Forty percent receive their first pay increase within their first four months of employment.  
<P>
Restaurant owners also argue there is not true minimum wage in their industry and many others because of tipping. In addition to restaurants, many minimum wage earners in hotels, hair salons, department stores and taxi companies increase their earnings via tips, bonuses and commissions.
<P>
This additional income is generally neglected by proponents of a minimum wage hike. In fact, some workers choose to remain in minimum wage positions because of the earning potential of tips and the like, restaurant owners say.
<P>     
The proposed 20 percent increase in the minimum wage would mean a potential 20 to 40 percent decrease in the hours of employment available to workers currently paid less than the new, higher minimum. If the government raises the minimum wage, restaurant owners say, it will curtail employment among just those people they're trying to help.

<HR>

<h2>More Than Just Aspirin</h2>

For years, the name Bayer meant aspirin when we had a headache. Now, you can soothe that migraine with some jazz.
<P>
Bayer has been a major player in the compact disc industry since Sony Corp. and Philips Electronics introduced the technology in 1982. Bayer's parent company, Bayer AG in Germany, was one of the original suppliers of polycarbonate, a tough plastic that was critical to the success of CD technology. A laser beam reads tiny pits molded into the surface of the disc.
<P>
Now comes a reminder of Bayer's role in the compact disc industry.  Bayer is sponsoring a compact disc featuring live performances from the Living and Contemporary Jazz Masters Series at Pittsburgh's Manchester Craftsmen's Guild. Featured performers include Stanley Turrentine, Louie Bellson and Ray Brown. The craftsmen's guild is a nonprofit community arts organization that provides cultural and educational opportunities for inner city youth.
<P>
The CD will sell for $20 at National Record Marts in western Pennsylvania, Borders Book Shops in suburban Pittsburgh and the craftsmen's guild. Proceeds will benefit the guild's Jazz Education Program.
<P>
Other sponsors are Sony and Digital Audio Disc Corp., a leading manufacturer of CDs.
<P>
"This is an important collaborative effort by the corporate world, the nonprofit arts community and the individual jazz performers," says guild executive director William E. Strickland Jr. "The CD has traditional to contemporary jazz and everything in between. The music is very, very strong."

<HR>

<h2>Many Happy Returns</h2>

Do the birthday cards you mail to friends and relatives routinely include the word "belated?" If so, Manhattan attorney Kevin Cohen has a solution.
<p>
Cohen, founder and president of Card Club, hopes to capitalize on business people whose lives are so busy that they struggle to find time to purchase and mail birthday cards to friends and relatives who are important to them. Cohen's firm will mail a card for you with a postmark from the state in which you live. Card Club also will use a computer to simulate your handwriting. The cost: $3.50 per card.
<P>	
"I adore my mother and would never fail to acknowledge her special days deliberately, but I just get caught up in my life on the road," says Peter Lane, a trade show consultant who uses Card Club. "By the time I remember her birthday, I'm apologizing profusely and spending $50 on flowers."
<P>
Until recently, Lane's mother, Frances, had gone decades without her son remembering her birthday via a card.
<P>
"I thought I had seen the last one," the mother says.
<P>
New York-based Card Club went national in August after several years of working on a regional basis.

<HR>

<h2>A Better Way to Pay</h2>

You may be clicking on all cylinders at work, but don't expect it to be reflected in your paycheck. Companies here still shy away from basing pay increases on performance.
<P>
In fact, merit increase budgets are at a six-year low, according to a nationwide survey by Towers Perrin of 1,383 U.S. companies. Those surveyed in the Pittsburgh area report merit budgets mirroring the national trend.
<P>
Although many industries have reported strong financial results this year, the trend in employment remains one of tight and ongoing cost control.
<P>
"Viewed in context, holding down salary increases is part of a broader effort to streamline and maintain peak efficiency and profitability regardless of economic conditions," says Antoinette Petrucci, leader of Towers Perrin's employee pay consulting practice in Pittsburgh. "We're seeing a continuing shift in the compensation ... away from merit increases toward variable pay opportunities that offer significant rewards tied to business results and give employers added flexibility to manage costs more carefully."
<P>
Many organizations today are reengineering the way work is done and restructuring their business operations to meet the challenges of growing competition. Companies are finding that traditional pay and performance management systems are poorly suited to new business environments. 
<P>
Traditional systems are designed to pay employees for performing narrowly defined tasks and jobs for a perceived value to the company. While in a competency-based system, employees are managed and rewarded on the basis of teamwork, risk-taking, technical expertise, customer relationship management and innovations, for example. 
<P>
When Towers Perrin surveyed 100 large employers in the Northeast, they found that one in four companies were seriously considering competency-based pay systems for at least some of their employees. For employees, the flexibility and the opportunity of the competency framework is limitless; for employers, this new pay system would prove to be a more effective use of their people resources. Competency-based pay better serves the organization needs in order to achieve its business objectives, experts say.

<HR>

<h2>Take the Week Off</h2>

Are you stingy in handing out vacation time to loyal employees? In the end, it could cost your business productivity or even employees, says Inga Harris, an employee benefit consultant with Hewitt Associates.
<P>
"Service-related paid time off remains an effective way to reward long-service employees," Harris says.
<P>
Americans actually receive less vacation time than employees in many foreign countries, where the government mandates that employees with over one year of service receive certain amounts of vacation.
<P>
Denmark, Austria and Brazil are the most liberal, mandating six weeks of vacation. Denmark, we should note, has a six-day work week.
<P>
Finland, France and Sweden all mandate five weeks of vacation, while Australia, Belgium, the Netherlands and Switzerland mandate four weeks.
<P>
On the telephone to the realtor already? Don't move to Mexico, where the government mandates only six vacation days annually.
<P>
The average vacation allotment in the United States is two weeks, the same as in Japan.
<P>
Will the U.S. average grow? Probably not, since the modern workplace demands maximum productivity and permits little time off. In fact, almost a quarter of people who did vacation over the summer ended up working from the beach, the mountains, their hotel room, their boat or wherever they happened to be.
<P>
Steelcase Workplace Index, a semiannual survey of workplace trends. reports that 23 percent of its 1,000-person sample did work while on vacation. About 4 percent of those who worked while on vacation said they resented having to do it.

<HR>

<h2>Spoils of a Legend</h2>

With forearms like oak trees, Arnold Palmer used golf clubs to carve his legend out of fairways near and far. He has the hardware to prove it, having walked away with championships from the British Open, the U.S. Open and the Masters, to name only a few.
<P>
The Westmoreland Museum of Art in Greensburg has brought together a collection of over 60 trophies Palmer earned during his career. The display, entitled The Art of Winning: Prizes of Palmer, runs through Oct. 29. 
<P>       
The venerable Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews, Scotland, loaned the museum its silver claret jug, the oldest trophy in golf, which has been presented to the winner of the British Open since 1872. Augusta National Golf Club also has provided the original Masters trophy for the exhibition, and the USGA has provided a reproduction of the U.S. Open trophy.
<P>       
And don't forget the trophy Palmer earned when he first emerged on the golf scene, for winning the U.S. Amateur.
The museum hosted a black-tie dinner in September for Palmer, a native of Latrobe who is winding down his career. (Admission for the Palmer exhibit is $5.)

<HR>

<h2>Actions Speak Louder Than Words</h2>

When working face-to-face, body language plays an enormous part in conveying what one thinks and feels. Your mouth may be saying one thing,   but your actions may be saying something else. In the end, it could hurt       your chances of easing a client's concerns, winning new business or receiving a promotion.
<P>
"People who lean forward in a chair to communicate their interest in what's being said may at the same time glance around the room as if bored. That creates suspicion," says Frank Grazian, executive editor of Communication Briefings, a monthly newsletter dedicated to helping improve business communications.
<P>
In order to convey a clearer overall message, Grazian offers some tips on how to improve nonverbal communication. First, one should realize what their body language is saying to others. If you're not certain, ask a friend or a colleague to watch you and give feedback. Even better: Many companies videotape their sales representatives, then play it back for them. On videotape, one sales representative noticed his nervous habit of clicking his pen. From that point on, the salesman used twist pens so he would have nothing to click.
<P>
Another tip: Watch others and notice what they're saying both verbally and nonverbally. Watch nervous habits such as doodling and finger tapping. These mannerisms can imply that the other party is not paying attention.
<P>
Grazian also notes that one should be especially careful when conversing with people from other countries. Some gestures have less than complimentary meanings of which you may be unaware. For example, avoid scratching your chin downward when speaking with a German. This gesture is interpreted as you think what they are saying is garbage.

<HR>

<h2>Economic Development</h2>

"The people of Pittsburgh, they think economic growth in our region is not all that bad. But in effect, everyone around us is growing so much that we are lagging well behind."
<P><h4>Louis L. Testoni<BR>Managing Partner,<BR> Coopers & Lybrand</h4>


<hr>

