<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"><a href="../zine/1095.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>

<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Veal of Approval </B></FONT><BR>
<P align=center><B><font size = +1>Veal Lovers Have Their Pick at This Heinz Hall Neighbor </font><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban </I></B>
<HR>
<P>

The last time I had a veal dish at a Pittsburgh restaurant, I sent it back to the chef with this request: "Please finish cooking the veal." 
<P>
Sadly, the list of restaurants in this region that have mastered veal is a short one. But add to that list one restaurant, The Overture, which recently changed ownership and is hanging its hat on two dishes that veal eaters should love. 
<P>
The Overture sits across the street from Heinz Hall on Sixth Street. The entrees are pricey, averaging around $20, but the portions are generous and the service, attentive, making The Overture a good way to start an evening in the Cultural District.
<P>
The wine list features French and American, with the French wines (Premier Cru, Joseph Drouhin and Pouilly Fuisse, Louis Jadot) averaging in the low $40s. The American wines, primarily from the Sonoma and Napa valleys of California, average in the mid $30s. The domestics include Ferrari Carano Chardonnay and Chalk Hill Estate Cabernet Sauvignon.
<P>
We started with a first course of two house recommendations: a portabello mushroom and blackened gulf shrimp. The portabello mushroom was stuffed with fresh crabmeat, then topped with an imperial sauce that was tasty but not too rich. The crabmeat made the difference. 
<P>
The blackened gulf shrimp were nicely sized, sitting on roasted red bell peppers and topped with a spicy sauce that tasted of mesquite. Having to pick between the shrimp or the portabello mushroom, I would go with the   mushroom. Shrimp lovers, however,     should try the blackened gulf shrimp. It's a nice change from some unimaginative shrimp appetizers.
<P>
The salad was fresh and crisp, although I thought the house dressing, raspberry vin-aigrette, was flat. However, another in my party raved about the same dressing.
<P>
Chef Wayne Heuler brought one of the veal dishes, Veal Christian, with him from the former Fair-child's of Mon-roeville, tweaking the dish a bit along the way. Heuler stuffs the veal with crabmeat and  sautes it in wine before topping it with mushrooms. The veal melted in the mouth, but as with the portabello mushroom, the crabmeat made the difference.
<P>
The other veal entree was Veal Oscar, which is scallopini of veal sauteed and garnished with fresh asparagus and lump crabmeat. A bernaise sauce topped it off. Of the two veal specialties, the Veal Christian was definitely the more tasty. 
<P>
The menu features two other veal dishes: Veal Diablo and Veal & Peppers. Granted, not everyone is a veal eater. For those who don't indulge, other entrees include New York Strip Steak ($25.95), Blackened Yellowfin Tuna ($20.95). 
<P>
For dessert, we went with The Piano, which is bittersweet chocolate molded in the shape of a grand piano and topped with raspberry mousse. Chef Heuler adds fresh raspberries when they're in season. Lucky for us, they were.
<P>
Dinner for two, including a bottle of wine, is going to run around $100, not including the tip.
<P>
The highlight definitely was the Veal Christian. Downtown restaurants constantly fight an uphill battle. A dish that sets them apart from the competition can only help. The Overture has found one with its Veal Christian.

<HR>
<h4>The Overture<br>
212 Sixth Street<br>
Pittsburgh<P>

Weekdays Noon-9:00pm<br>
Saturdays 4:30pm-10:00pm<br>
Closed Sunday<p>

Appetizers $5.95-$6.50<br>
Entrees $16.95-$25.95</h4><p>


