<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.Diner.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H10People.gif"><a href="../zine/1095.ExecutiveTravel.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><P>
<center>
<!--FONT SIZE = +2><B><PEOPLE MAKING NEWS</FONT></B><br>
<B><I>By MERRITT SPIER</I></B></center><P>
<HR>

<pre>

<b>Name:</b> 		Merritt Holland Spier

<b>Age:</B> 		34

<b>Personal:</b> 	Married, husband David, two dogs Bailey & Aiko

<B>Education:</B>  	B.A., Communications, College of Wooster, 1984

<b>Last Vacation:</b> 	Siesta Key, Fla.
</pre>
It's not public broadcasting, but it's not quite Wayne's World either. It's community television, a forum for Pittsburgh residents or nonprofit groups in the city to hit the airwaves with their own television shows. Programming on the station, channel 21 on the Pittsburgh cable system, covers a wide range of topics: art, sports and religion to name a few. Most of it is produced in the PCTV studio on Pittsburgh's North Side.
<P>
Now, PCTV is embarking on a project that will enable users to express themselves via another medium: the Internet. The project carries special importance to the business community because it will enable users such as small business owners and home-based entrepreneurs to set up a home page and e-mail address at minimal cost. More importantly, the city's young people, who might otherwise have no exposure to the evolving technology, also will be able to gain experience using the Internet.
<P>
ER Editor-in-Chief Jim Urban talked with Merritt H. Spier, executive director/general manager of Pittsburgh Community Television Corp., about her work at PCTV and her uphill battle in getting the Internet project off the ground.
<P>
<b>Executive Report: Before we talk about what you want to do, let's talk about what you already are doing. So what happens at PCTV?</b> 
<P>
Merritt Spier:  PCTV is the public access television station for the city of Pittsburgh. We have a staff of about seven people who facilitate and train ordinary citizens and members of city-based nonprofit organizations on how to produce their own television programs that will appear on TCI cable television channel 21.
<P>
We have a fully equipped studio. We have four edit suites, five portable camera units. We only require two free workshops -- orientation and preproduction -- before someone can begin producing a program in our studio. Most people who come in here want to be the host of their own show. They do the writing. They arrange their own guests. Our staff really only runs the technical side of things. Most of my job is fund raising. I'd say about 90 percent of my time is spent in that area.
<P>
<b>ER: And from television you are moving to the Internet?</b>
<P>
MS: Since we are in the business of teaching people how to use television as a medium to communicate, what we want to do is keep up with the times and add the digital medium. We believe the Internet is going to be the communications tool of the future. It already is a communications tool.
<P>
We serve a group in this community that does not have the financial wherewithal to have access to the Internet or a computer or a modem. With our television studio, we already are serving the underprivileged and the small nonprofits, giving them access to tools they would not be able to afford or use. We've come up with a project called the PCTV Public Internet Access Centers. We want to train the people not only to browse the Internet, but to use it as a communications tool. We will teach courses in electronic commerce that really will amount to in-depth training for people who have a home-based business or want to start a small business. If they have a talent they want to advertise, they can put it out on the Internet. We will give everyone a home page and an e-mail address.
<P>
<b>ER: But to get this off the ground, you need money. Please explain the funding process.</b>
<P>
MS: We have a proposal that has been submitted to the foundations for funding. We are asking for $500,000 over three years, which is not a lot of money for doing what we are trying to do. Some other programs are operated by nonprofits. The Carnegie, for example, is providing people with browsing capabilities. We are doing something completely different than that. We not only are allowing users to browse, but we are teaching them to use the Internet like they would use any other tool. They actually are going to create content on the Internet.
<P>
Locally, the foundations have been pretty slow in reacting. A lot of them already have made a large investment in other projects. I am out there trying to explain how this is different. This is a program that will reach out and train people who otherwise would not have access, plus connect all these nonprofits that really need to be talking to each other. That, to me, is very unique and very exciting. It is something completely different than most other Internet programs.
<P>
<b>ER: Community television is funded in part by the cable operator, in      this case TCI. Does that cover most of your costs?</b>
<P>
MS: Not really. When a cable company comes into a city like Pittsburgh, the city council sets up certain requirements. In Pittsburgh, one of the requirements is that people have a voice on cable television. The voice is PCTV. Along with that, TCI since 1981 has been required to provide PCTV with 25 cents per subscriber per month. That equals out to anywhere from $260,000 annually to $290,000 annually. The rest is up to us. We generate some funds through the sale of videotapes and workshops on certain aspects of production. We don't charge for airtime.
<P>
<b>ER: Does the community seize this opportunity?</b>
<P>

MS: We have about 450 active community producers. They can do just about anything they want. We screen everything that goes out just to make sure we don't violate any state, federal or local laws on obscenity. Another thing we watch for is libelous material. Most of the people who do this have full-time jobs and do this in their extra time. They are a very dedicated group.
<P>
You must live in the city or be part of a city-based nonprofit group. So if you live outside the city and belong to a church in the city, you could do something for your church.
<P>
We have people coming in here thinking all kinds of things, and that is the uniqueness of this place. We have a guy right now who produces a music video show featuring local bands. We have a lot of churches using us for religious programming. We also have a lot of people who are suffering from the problems of gang violence. They have turned that around and really, on a grass roots level, have come to PCTV to use the medium as a means of getting children out of these really violent     situations. 
<P>
We have a whole group of producers who really concentrate on bringing kids in and letting them express themselves on camera, whether they dance, sing, read a story or just talk about how violence is affecting them. The children see that there is more to the world than what is around the corner of their house. They are given the opportunity to see themselves on television, which is rewarding and a real morale booster. It helps build self-esteem, which they have very little of. That's been a very good thing -- a very good use of PCTV.
<P>
We also have some people who are artists who then translate their art into video. One guy does all his artwork on slides, then puts it to music and puts it on the station. We once had a guy who did a show called Plunger Fantastik. All it was was a plunger going up against a wall. Every so often a peanut on a string would fall into the shot. The producer wanted it to be a classical piece of filmmaking. He envisioned himself as the Andy Warhol of video.
<p>
Sports wise, we also have a bodybuilding, aerobics program. Most of our general programming evolves around the African American community.
<P>
The Internet project will not be limited to those who live in the city. We will set up the facility right here. The proposal calls for a classroom, a bank of computers with 32 modem ports and classes. We hope, by year three, that this project will be self-sustaining through the workshop fees, through the setup fees and through the monthly Internet fees. Right now, we are planning to charge $30 to set a person up, which will include the home page, an e-mail address and giving them software if they have a home computer. The connection fee will be $6 per month. The workshop fees are not set, but they will remain nominal.
<P>
We are not out to make money. We really are dedicated to serve this group of people who might otherwise not have the opportunity to experience this technology.
<b>ER: How do you protect against abuse of the system?</b>
<P>
MS: We can put in controls where someone has created something and wants to send it out on the Internet. We can have the ability to control what goes out. Like we monitor for obscenity or pornography on the television side, we would do the same thing here.
<P>
<b>ER: Even though the fees remain nominal, there still will be those who cannot afford the cost. How will you serve them?</b>
<P>
MS: We also have a scholarship committee, a group from our board of directors, that will award up to 100 scholarships for the severe financial hardship cases.
<P>
<b>ER: The notion of opening this up to the region, instead of limiting it to the city, sounds good. Will that fly with the city or with TCI?</b>
<P>
MS: If we run into problems with TCI or the city, we will have to rethink that. We still are maintaining the television side of this, which has always been all the city required. We really feel this is like adding another communications tool, adding to the services we already provide. We already train people to communicate one way. We are just training them to communicate another way. 
<P>
<b>ER: Where does the project stand now? What is the time frame for getting it up and running?</b>
<P>
MS: Right now, we need money to get this going. It will take three years. It will take us a year to get the hardware and the software set up. It will take us the second year to get the staff and other training components worked into the system, then test it a little. We'll open it up to some people to see where the kinks in the system are. By year three, we will be going strong.
<P>
<b>ER: Why are you so confident that the public will use the program? Has it been tried elsewhere?</b>
<P>
MS: They've done it in Minneapolis. They started three years ago, and now they are swamped. Our program is modeled after the Minneapolis one.
<P>
If we get swamped, we will just grow, grow, grow. I'm sure it will happen, because there is a need for this.
A producer walked into my office yesterday and asked when the Internet program would begin. I told him it would be a while because we had to get it funded first. He said, 'When can I pay? I have my money. I want to the first one on. I need to be on it.' There is a real pressure from our constituents to get this going.
<P>
I've got people who have been using PCTV for years and come to me in tears because of how this opportunity has changed their lives. Having access to the medium of television has got them out of bad situations they were in, has connected them with people from all over instead of isolating them in their community. It has made them popular and famous in the community where they do live. It has elevated their position in the community. I think this Internet project will do the same thing, only ten fold. 
<P>
It all started when we thought we would put up a computer terminal in the waiting area so people could browse the Internet. But when we started talking to those who use the facility, we realized that if we set the terminal up we would have a line all the way around the block. That's just browsing. That's not even using it. From there we started calling around to other community access facilities to see what they were doing and realized we were three years behind the times.
<P>
<b>ER:What roadblocks have you encountered as you try to fund this project? Are the decision-makers at the foundations tuned in to the importance of using the Internet?</b>
MS: The problem is that it is very hard to convince people that this is happening -- that this Internet stuff is real. I don't know if this is a Pittsburgh thing or what. People have to realize that if they don't use this, they are really going to miss out. The company that is helping us set this project up thinks of the Internet as a utility. If your electric bill is $300, you pay it because you need electricity and you wouldn't conduct business without it. The mindset should be, 'You don't want to think about running your business without paying for Internet service.'
<P>
We have established relationships with a number of foundations that have been very supportive in the past. This is the largest amount of funding we've ever asked for. It also is the most cutting edge.
<b>ER: How do you get past the roadblocks?</b>
MS: We have to educate them about the Internet. We have to explain that this is not a wild animal. We tell them, 'This is going to be coming to your desk, into your life. You might was well understand it. It is extremely beneficial to people we are trying to serve.' It is an educational process. I've been educating people all along since coming to PCTV. The thing about The Carnegie or WQED is that people know what it is. Our story is different: People don't understand what PCTV is. If they think it is public broadcasting, they already give to public broadcasting. I have to educate them and tell them it is something totally different. With this latest project, it is just more education on what the Internet is. And then what we want to do with it and somehow reduce this fear of the unknown.
<P>
<b>ER: Once the education part is complete, what is your message on why the foundations should ultimately fund a project of this type?</b>
<P>
MS: The foundations say they want to improve the life of the community in Pittsburgh. There are a lot of ways to do that besides, for example, funding cultural programming, which 80 percent of the people we serve do not even see. 
<P>
This technology will create the haves and the havenots. PCTV serves the havenots. The only way they are going to get access to technology is if organizations like PCTV and foundations with the heart to understand this can support the kind of thing that we want to do here.
<P>

<hr>

