<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>A Question of Value</font><br>
<font size=+1>Crown American's Writedown Raises<br>
Question About Value of  Other Properties</font><BR>
<i>By Doug Thomas</i></b>

<HR>
<P>

Johnstown-based Crown Amer-ican Realty Trust is attempting to resolve its core strategic problem: access to capital to finance its growth.
<P>
Shares fell 28.7 percent for the month to $9 following the surprise announcement of a 43 percent reduction in dividend to $0.80 per share, while planning to sell non-strategic properties and renovating and expanding core properties. Equity markets have been less than inviting as Crown's shares trade at levels significantly below its August 1993 initial public offering of $17.25 per share. Mean-while, a highly leveraged balance sheet has made debt financing less viable.
<P>
Crown's capital needs are undeniable.  In addition to debt service and dividend distributions, Crown Amer-ican requires capital to finance the renovation of several regional shopping malls for the opening of May Department Stores, and the renovation and expansion of the fire-damaged Logan Valley Mall in Altoona. Management believes that recent moves position the company to generate capital through a reduction of its dividend (approximately $22 million per year), proceeds from property sales (up to $90 million) and potential debt and equity offerings.
<P>
More problems may loom for Crown. In conjunction with its decision to sell two properties, Crown took a $35 million write-down on the value of these assets. Was Crown's balance sheet overstating the market value of other properties? Management appears to have lost a considerable amount of credibility on Wall Street. 
<P>
While it may appear that Crown addressed a short term cash flow problem at the expense of shareholders,  the family of Crown's CEO and President own over 35 percent of Crown's shares.
<P>

<h2>Around the ER Index</h2>

<P>
After two consecutive monthly gains, the ER Index fell 0.97 percent for the five weeks ended August 11, while the S&P for the same period fell 0.23 percent.The ER Index holds its lead at 20.77 percent, with the S&P 500 trailing closely with a 20.35 percent return.
<P>
<DL> 
<LI>Cable Design Technologies posted the largest gain, increasing 25.6 percent after the company ann-ounced that it had purchased Cole-Flex Corporation of West Babylon, N.Y. 
<LI>Also showing significant advances were Northstar Health Services and Parkvale Savings, which gained 14 percent and 12.7 percent respectively, on positive earnings announcements.  
<LI>Astrotech gained 7.4 percent on the announcement of an over 100 percent increase in earnings for its third quarter. Respironics trailed closely behind, appreciating 6.9 percent on record increases in sales and earnings for its fourth quarter ended June 30. 
<LI>In other news, Black Box Corp-oration gained 6.8 percent the month after the company announced a secondary offering from its principal stockholder, Odyssey, which represents approximately 45 percent of the shares owned by Odyssey.
<LI>Heinz shares, finished off 5.31 percent for the month reacting to news that the Heinz family foundations and trusts cut their stake by selling 12.75 million shares for $540 million. The sale served to dampen speculation that Heinz may soon be acquired. 
<LI>Allegheny Ludlum exceeded analyst's estimates in its second quarter, with earnings of $34.5 million or 49 cents per share. The gain was attributed to higher specialty steel prices and robust market demand. 
<LI>Kennametal reported record sales and earnings for the fiscal year ended June 30. Earnings from operations increased 118 percent to $68.3 million, or $2.58 per share. 
<LI>II-VI Corp. reported earnings for its fourth quarter ended June 30, of $833,000 or 31 cents per share as compared to $331,000 or 13 cents in the prior year, on a 62 percent increase in revenues to $8.4 million. Earnings increases were attributed to higher sales and lower per unit costs resulting mostly from increased production. Also in the month, the company declared a two-for-one stock split payable Sept. 7, 1995. 
<LI>American Eagle shares tumbled 8 percent for the month after the company announced that it expects earnings for the year ended July 1995 to come in lower than last year as a result of its aggressive inventory clearance program. The company is preparing to unveil a comprehensive new strategy within the next few weeks.


<HR>

