<HEAD>
<TITLE> Eye On Harrisburg </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.ERIndex.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<p>

<P align=center><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Is Exporting The Answer?</font><BR> 

<FONT SIZE=+1>State Leaders Think A Push In Foreign Countries Will Spur Economic Development In Pennsylvania </FONT><BR>

<I>By Jim Strader</I></B>
<HR>  
<P>

Many Pennsylvania companies are well-established overseas. Heinz, PPG and Hershey are known the world over. But the nation's fifth-largest state ranks 11th in export trade, state commerce department administrators say, leaving plenty of room for improvement.
<P>
That's why boosting the presence of Pennsylvania products in the world market is a strategy being given renewed emphasis by the state. Gov. Tom Ridge notes that fewer than           20 percent of the state's manufacturers sell their products overseas.
<P>
"Pennsylvania's businesses must no longer think of exporting casually, but as a fundamental way of conducting business," the governor says.
<P>
Designed to meet that goal is the Pennsylvania Export Partnership, geared toward small and medium-sized companies. The program awards grants of as much as $2,500 to help companies attend international trade shows and access the export market.
<P>
Pittsburgh Tool Steel Inc., a specialty steel manufacturer based in Monaca, used the grant to visit an exhibition in Cologne, Germany last March. As a result, the Beaver County company's export business has increased from 2-3 percent in 1994 to about 20 percent this year.
<P>
The business generated by the German trade show and a handful of European sales calls made on the same trip sped the company's entrance to the export market, says Frank Cremeens, who took over Pittsburgh Tool Steel in a leveraged buyout early in 1994 with partner Lawrence Megan.
<P>
"When we bought the company, we had exports in mind, but because of the type of product, the real down-hard feeling was that this was four or five years away," Cremeens says.
<P>
Making contacts overseas is only the first step, Cremeens says. Follow-up is the key to keeping foreign customers, who often meet Americans on one-time junkets, more interested in Big Ben than big business.
<P>
"It's no different than being in Pittsburgh and selling to someone in Chicago," says Cremeens, who is planning another trip for this month to meet with current customers and pitch prospects in Germany and Italy.
<P>
The export partnership---known as PEP--- is available to Pennsylvania manufacturers with 500 or fewer employees and sales of $50 million or less.
<P>
The trade grants are geared primarily toward companies making their initial forays into exporting, but the state also looks to help businesses seeking to expand into new countries.
<P>
The program helped Pittsburgh Tool Steel learn how much was available in the export market, Cremeens says.  His firm consulted with the Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Development Council, which administers the program in Pittsburgh. Pittsburgh Tool Steel also visited the Carnegie Library and the University of Pittsburgh's small business development center in preparation for the trip.
<P>
"You don't make the trip because of the PEP program," Cremeens says, noting that the grant money is only worthwhile if time and effort follow. "It does make it a little less painful. It provides the impetus to get off your tail."
<P>
In addition to the SRPDC in Pittsburgh, the Southern Alleghenies Planning and Development Commis-sion in Altoona assist area companies. These agencies, and eight others around Pennsylvania, act as regional export service providers, identifying and recruiting eligible companies to take part in the grant program. They also help with market research to evaluate export potential and readiness. State offices in Toronto, Tokyo, Brussels and Frankfurt act as economic development liaisons for Pennsylvania companies.
<P>
Other export initiatives in the works in Harrisburg include a Governor's Export Task Force, which will plan and oversee the state's export program. Ridge says he plans to lead trade delegations overseas. Commerce Secretary Thomas Hagen has already traveled to Canada and Great Britain on behalf of the state.
<P>
Despite the early success his company has had with exports, Cremeens says it remains only a portion of Pittsburgh Tool Steel's operation. With all the effort in making and maintaining overseas contacts, he says, the foreign customers can't overshadow domestic business.
<P>
"You have to be careful not to ig-nore the main part of your business."
<P>

<hr>

