<HEAD>
<TITLE> Healthbeat </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H15Health.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Supplement.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center><p>
<P align=center><b><FONT SIZE=+3>The Physician Practice </FONT><BR><font size = +2>Does the MD Need an MBA to Run One? </font><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></B>

<HR>  

<P>

As an orthopedic surgeon, Dr. Norman Krause is pretty good with a scalpel. But take him out of the operating room following a hip replacement surgery and you'll find him equally adept at slicing the fat from his office budget.
<P>
"I used to have enormous overhead," says Krause, a solo practitioner. "That was fine when things were fat. Now, it is anything but fine. My practice is like U.S. Steel or any other company. We look at expenses. We are more efficient and cost-conscious. We took the big picture and figured out a way to do it more cost-effectively."
<P>
For Krause and other physicians, it's come down to this simple reality: The days of loosely running a practice are over. The market is demanding cost containment from physicians. That means physicians must control their own operating costs to maintain profit margins. It's especially true for physicians like the 43-year-old Krause, who is too young to retire but is old enough to have an established practice.
<P>
"Running a medical practice now is very much like running any other business," Krause says. 
<P>
Unlike the old days, many physicians now develop and follow annual budgets, paying close attention to every line item. They regularly review their staffing levels and office technology to ensure maximum efficiency. They stay on top of accounts receivable to maintain adequate cash flow. And above all, they focus on keeping the customers satisfied, who now include not only patients, but insurers and their referral networks.
<P>
Krause's practice is a prime example of how times have changed. Krause once operated without a detailed office budget. Now, he develops one annually and follows it. Krause's payroll formerly funded 14 positions in his two offices in Squirrel Hill and Monroeville. He since reduced his payroll to        4 1/2 positions.
<P>
The same cost-containment pressures also influence larger multi-doctor practices, many of which have hired an  experienced healthcare administrator to run the business side of the practice. Take Michael Busch, whose past jobs included chief financial officer at Hershey Medical Center and vice president for finance at West Penn Hospital. He now is executive director of Oakland Neurosurgical Associates, a 10-physician practice group that employs 32 people in six offices in and around Pittsburgh.
<P>
"When it comes to business operations, many physicians really don't have any interest related to issues of human resources, finance or information systems," Busch says. "Think back to the way it was in the middle '70s. There really were no price controls and there were no contractual issues. The marketplace was so attuned to expansion that many physicans just treated patients and sent a bill."
<P>
With Busch tending to strategic planning, hiring, contractual issues and other administrative matters, the Oakland Neurosurgical doctors are free to spend most of their time practicing medicine. The doctors still dabble in the business side, meeting monthly for corporate meetings and participating in an annual two-day retreat focusing on the business side of the practice.
<P>
Other physician groups aren't willing to invest in a seasoned business manager.  Instead, some are tapping the emerging group of consultants, such as Carol McClain, president of Healthcare Business Cents.
<P>
Like Oakland Neurosurgical's Busch, McClain is a healthcare veteran, a registered nurse who once managed a seven-physician practice in suburban Pittsburgh.
<P>
When reviewing a practice from top to bottom, McClain hits 10 areas that she says are critical to success. They range from patient satisfaction to proper budgeting to coding and charges.
<P>
"There are some physicians who are really business savvy," McClain says. "These are people who are involved with the medical societies and other groups. They are much more in tune with what is going on in healthcare. Many are self-taught business people who are doing very well."
<P>
Include Krause, the orthopedic surgeon, in that group. He acquired his business sense at the office. Now, it is the key to survival for him and thousands like him.
<P>
"A lot of physicians in their mid- to late-50s had a period of time in which they did extremely well," says Krause. "They don't like this current atmosphere, but they can afford to ride it out. Other guys just coming out of school never knew what it is like. They may just go work for an HMO.
<P>
"Myself and other colleagues around my age?" Krause says. "We are right in the middle of it."

<p>

<hr>

