<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Golf Getaway</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/1095.Healthbeat.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/H7Special.gif"></a><a href="../zine/1095.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>

</center>
<p>

<P align=center><B><I><FONT SIZE=+2>Business Hall of Fame<br>
Junior Achievement of SouthWest Pennsylvania </FONT></I></B>

<P align=center><B><font size = +2>A SHARED CULTURE </font><BR><I>By Richard White<br>Chairman, 1995 Southwest Pennsylvania Business Hall of Fame </I></B>
<P>
<HR>  

<P>
In this increasingly global economy, we can learn much from other cultures.  From Africa comes the phrase, "it takes an entire community to raise a child."  In large part, we as members of the business community can do our part by showing tomorrow's leaders how "to value free enterprise, understand business and economics, and be 'workforce' ready."
<P>
The distinguished laureates upon whom we bestow membership in the Hall of Fame shine as examples of free enterprise at its best.  They show us that through hard work, perseverance and self-confidence, dreams can come true.  This is no less true for the many fine Junior Achievement volunteers who enter classrooms around western Pennsylvania to share their experiences and enthusiasm with tomorrow's business leaders, workers and customers.   
<P>
Orville Eberly, Eberly Coal and Coke and Gallatin Bank; Thomas A. McConomy, Calgon Carbon; Roy McKnight, Mylan Laboratories; Robert L. Vann, The New Pittsburgh Courier, and Dr. Richard C. Wallace, Pittsburgh Public Schools, will enter the Junior Achievement Southwest Pennsylvania Business Hall of Fame at the awards dinner and induction ceremony which I will host on Wednesday, October 25 at 6:00 p.m.  Present as honored guests will be many JA students from the area.  I also look forward to hosting and honoring this area's past and current business and community leaders, including John E. Connelly, this year's Achieve-ment Award Honoree, as we encourage our future leaders as well.
<P>
It will take more than a dinner awards ceremony to prepare our young people to achieve for tomorrow.  Important as it is to reward past success, the most vital part of JA's work occurs in today's classrooms.  Only by interacting with JA volunteers can our children gain the fullest benefits from a lifetime's business and community experience.  The dedication and time taken to illustrate, firsthand, the value of education and work pay off both immediately and in the future.  The sooner our young people learn how the economy works, the closer we step to the day when the average student seriously ponders the benefits of owning and/or running a business.
<P>
Junior Achievement volunteers run well-designed, time-tested programs that enrich and educate students.  Equally important are the individual business-person's own personality and stories.  Countless volunteers report attitude and career goal changes by students following their participation in JA. These experiences make all of our efforts worthwhile.  Your experiences offer untold possibilities for inspiration, enlightenment and motivation for our young people.  Consider making this investment in tomorrow's economy, as you will never get a more profitable return!
<P>
<HR>
<pre>
<h2>Junior Achievement of Southwest Pennsylvania Inc.</h2>

<h3>1995-96 Board of Directors

Members of the Board</h3>
