Louis L. Testoni, 
	Coopers & Lybrand
Daniel S. Wilson, 
	Eat'n Park Restaurants Inc.
Stuart T. Wise, 
	Comdoc Office Systems

</pre><HR>

In this day and age, athletes, musicians, actors and other celebrities can no longer be held up as models of success and good citizenship. The negative publicity surrounding such pop culture icons as Michael Jackson, Pete Rose, Mike Tyson and of course, O.J. Simpson, has caused the country to question the people whom we hold up to our children as "successful."
<P>
Sometimes the best examples of perseverance, dedication, commitment and ultimately success, however we define it, can be found in the people we know. Our parents, peers and mentors can offer us a wealth of knowledge, experience, guidance and a pattern on which to shape our behavior.
<P>
By going into the classroom and working with students one-on-one, JA volunteers have the opportunity to provide students with a positive and accessible role model. The simplest commitment to a group of students can provide them with a lasting and positive impression.
<P>
A great way students can meet with adults who are positive role models is through Junior Achievement programs. More students than ever will get the opportunity to interact with Junior Achievement volunteers this school year. Each volunteer can benefit the life of each student. "There are many valuable causes to volunteer for," said Dennis Gilfoyle, vice president of marketing for Junior Achievement. "Junior Achievement is not volunteer firefighting or emergency service. But make no mistake, Junior Achievement is saving lives." 
<P>
The K-6 program allows young students in kindergarten through sixth grade to learn about their roles in the economy of the family, community, city and country. Volunteers from the business community visit the classroom to bring students a practical understanding of how free enterprise works in the community and the value of an education.Through hands-on activities, students in the K-6 program learn fundamental business principles and how they can become contributing members of society. These programs lay the foundation for continued learning and success in high school and beyond, according to Junior Achievement Program Manager Romy Banks. "These programs, aside from their scholastic value, get young people thinking about business and setting goals for success." 
<P>
Another JA program, ESIS, allows seventh grade students to see firsthand how staying in school makes sense. Through the Success board game, students learn the long-term benefits of getting their high school diploma. Students also see what the world holds for a high school dropout. They scan the classifieds trying to find a job they would be qualified for as a dropout. "They have to budget for food, rent, transportation, and other expenses based on their supposed income," Banks says. "It's a real eye-opening experience for them."
<P>
Junior Achievement's goal according to S. Lee Strayer, president of Junior Achievement of Southwest Pennsyl-vania, "is to provide a complete and sequential kindergarten-through-twelfth-grade curriculum over the next several years. The only way that can be accomplished is through business and community leaders going into the classroom." 
<P>
Junior Achievement's programs also represent a vital stepping-stone from a student's secondary education to college or directly to the work force.
<P>
The U.S. position in the world economy depends directly on our nation's ability to prepare tomorrow's work force. Business leaders recognize this challenge as they continually search for workers with new and more sophisticated skills. Junior Achievement knows from experience that a key to success is to bring business and community leaders directly into the classroom. Young students in search of positive role models find such volunteers important sources of inspiration. At the same time, the Junior Achievement classroom volunteers transform textbook theory into real-life experiences that greatly aid the learning process. 
<P>
As our children are confronted with challenges at an increasingly young age it is critical that this type of classroom involvement now begins in kindergarten. With the belief that it is never too early to start preparing our nation's youth for their futures, Junior Achievement programs begin in kindergarten and continue through 12th grade. The goal is to help children learn the parallel between success in school and success in the workplace. When our children learn this, it is far easier for them to continue their education through graduation and become contributing members of society.     
<P>
Students learn about their roles as individuals, consumers and workers in environments that extend from their homes to an international marketplace. A variety of activities are included to help each student develop decision-making and work force readiness skills. 
<P>
For further information on how you can get involved with the next generation of business leaders, call Junior Achievement at 1-800-522-6957.

<HR>
<h2>ORVILLE EBERLY</h2>

The amount of gratitude owed to Orville Eberly is enough to keep many individuals and businesses in debt for several years to come. This native of Fayette county held many accomplishments throughout his lifetime; unfortunately many were known only by those who benifited from them. 
<P>
Eberly started on his path to greatness by following in his father's footsteps: straight into the coal industry as a mine electrician. He mastered his trade early on by simultaneously passing examinations for fire boss, assistant mine foreman and mine foreman, with the help of his attending school at night.
<P>
He then went on to hold the position of mine foreman at Allison and later became superintendent of the Old Home Mine of the W.J. Rainey Co. at McClellandtown, which he later purchased in 1933. Three years later he established Eberly Coal and Coke Co. in Uniontown.
<P>
Years of combined experience and interest in the oil and gas business in 1935 led Eberly to the late William E. Snee, an independent oil and gas producer until the time of his death in 1977. As a productive team, they explored and developed the Summit Gas Field near Uniontown and the Accident Field near Deep Creek, Md.
<P>
In 1956, Eberly took another step forward when he headed a group of shareholders who acquired control of Gallatin Bank. Under his guidance as chairman of the board from 1957 until his retirement in 1977, Gallatin Bank matured to its presently distinguished status as the largest bank in this area and one of the largest in the state.
<P>
Besides Eberly's many business fulfillments, he also greatly supported the advancement of youth through educational endeavors. Orville was the key individual in the addition of the Fayette Campus of Pennsylvania State University to the county. The Eberly Foundation was also established in 1965 to provide scholarship assistance to hundreds of students. A classroom building at the campus was named in Eberly's honor in 1977 as a thank you for his active involvement towards the development of our future. 
<P>
Eberly was an eager and accomplished trapshooter in his spare time. He was president of the Pennsylvania State Sportsmen's Association for five years and was named honorary president for life in 1975. A building was dedicated to him in his honor at Shamokin. His trapshooting skills were also noticed by the Amateur Trap-shooters Association and he was inducted into the Amateur Trapshooters Hall of Fame in 1976. His awards in that sport included the Pennsylvania state over-all championship four times, and the Eastern Zone doubles championship and northeastern United States clay pigeon championship, both in 1951.
<P>
Eberly's continued list of honors include being named Man of the Year by the Greater Uniontown Chamber of Commerce in 1971, serving as president of the Board of Trustees of the Uniontown Hospital Association, and as a member of the Fayette County Planning and Zoning Commission, Greater Uniontown Chamber of Commerce, Greater Uniontown Industrial Fund, and Regional Industrial Development Corporation.
<P>
<h2>ROY MCKNIGHT</h2>

Fortitude, integrity and foresight. These three words come to mind when characterizing Roy McKnight, the enterprising CEO of Mylan Labs. Before his death in 1993, McKnight earned the reputation as a dauntless leader who brought a company from mediocrity to greatness within years. 
<P>
McKnight graduated from Princeton University in 1942 with a bachelor of science degree in electrical engineering. In 1947, he founded Woessner-McKnight Company and spent the next 37 years as a manufacturers representative, selling electrical equipment for various companies, including Edwin L. Wiegand Company.
<P>
A decision in 1974 to invest $1,000 marked McKnight's first major interest in Mylan Labs. A year later, McKnight took up an invitation by Mylan's chairman, Mylan Puskar, to  become a board member of Mylan Labs.
<P>
After the tumultuous economy of 1975, Mylan's board, led by McKnight, investigated the operating procedures of the company. Then, on May 13, 1976, the board's executive committee grabbed the company's reins from Mylan's administration. McKnight's role in this restructuring helped elect him as Chairman and CEO of Mylan Labs.
<P>
Under McKnight's leadership, Mylan Labs became one of the nation's largest independent generic drug manufacturers. Mylan has grown from yearly sales of $13 million in 1976 to profits of $70 million by March 31, 1993.
<P>
By the way, the $1,000 McKnight orginally invested in Mylan Labs in 1974 grew to $337,500 at year end 1994. Some call it foresight -- we call it McKnight.
<P>


<h2>THOMAS MCCONOMY</h2>

Thomas A. McConomy was born and raised in Wilmerding, Pa., and he received his B.S. degree in chemical engineering from Carnegie Mellon University. He began his career as a service engineer for Calgon Corporation in 1955, and, during the next 30 years, held positions of increasing responsibility, including manager of Calgon Interamerican in Caracas, Venezuela, from 1970 to 1972 and vice president and general manager of the Activated Carbon Division of Calgon where he was responsible for worldwide production and marketing.
<P>
In 1985, McConomy led a management buyout of the Activated Carbon Division from Merck & Co., Inc. At the time, the new entity, Calgon Carbon Corporation, employed 700 people worldwide and operated manufacturing facilities in the United States, Belgium, and England. Two years later, he took the company public; it is currently listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
<P>
Under McConomy's leadership as President, Chief Executive Officer, and Chairman of the Board, Calgon Carbon increased sales from $125 million to over $300 million, and the number of employees grew to more than 1,500. In 1988, the company aquired Degussa, AG's activated carbon and charcoal production facilities in Germany. In 1990, Calgon Carbon purchased Vara International, an engineering firm specializing in solving air pollution problems with activated   carbon-based systems, and, in 1991, acquired Trans-Pacific Carbon, a reactivation facility in Blue Lake, Calif. In 1992, the company started up a new state-of-the-art activated carbon production facility in Pearlington, Missi. In 1994, McConomy retired as Calgon Carbon's President and Chief Executive Officer. He remains Chairman and a member of the Board of Directors.
<P>
During his career, McConomy has contributed several articles and papers to technical trade journals and conferences. He has also been active in the Pittsburgh community, particularly with organizations and projects which are youth oriented. He is currently Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Carnegie Mellon University. He also holds directorships at PNC Bank, Equitable Resources, and the Pitts-burgh High Technology Council.
<P>
In 1989, McConomy received the "Enterprise Award" from The Pittsburgh Business Times, and in 1990, he was named "Entrepreneur of the Year" by Ernst & Young, Inc. magazine, and Merrill Lynch. In 1992, McConomy was the recipient of "The William Metcalf Award," given by the Engineers Society of Western Pennsylvania for outstanding engineering achievement.
<P>
McConomy was Chairman of Junior Achievement of Southwest Pennsylvania from 1988 to 1990. During his tenure, student enrollment increased from 14,000 to 24,000, and JASWPA received top honors as the best JA company in the nation. He was instrumental in the merger of Junior Achievement chapters in Pittsburgh and Johnstown, Pa., creating the eighth largest program in the nation. In 1991, McConomy received the National Junior Achievement Gold Leadership Award, the organization's top honor for volunteers.
<P>
<h2>RICHARD WALLACE</h2>

(Richard Wallace was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1994, but was unable to personally accept. He, too, will be honored at this year's ceremony.)
<P>
Under the leadership of Dr. Richard C. Wallace Jr., the Pittsburgh Public School system became a model for other cities. Wallace served as superintendent of schools from        1980 to 1992, developing ways to empower teachers and create options for students.
<P>
His most innovative way of helping teachers was a staff training program called PRISM (Pittsburgh Research-Based Instructional Super-visory Model).
<P>
Wallace thought the approach of personnel evaluation to rid the district of incompetent teachers and administrators was shortsighted. "I persuaded the board that they ought to take a constructive approach that would make certain all teachers and administrators understand the nature of effective teaching and leadership. Training, therefore, would precede evaluation," he explains.
<P>
Before teachers and administrators were evaluated, the board of education would make its expectations clear. Then the teachers would have the chance to see role models and practice their skills.
<P>
The Schenley Teacher Center operated from 1983 until 1990 in Schenley High School. There, teachers could take "mini-sabbaticals" to refine their instructional skills, expand subject area knowledge and learn to relate better to students.
<P>
During each quarter, 48 teachers from all 11 high schools would take part in an eight-week program. The teachers would then divide their time between teaching at Schenley High School and working with visiting teachers. When the teachers finished, they participated in follow-up programs led by principals and department chairmen.
<P>
The Schenley Teacher Center was so successful it was followed by the Brookline Elementary Teacher Center in 1985 and the Greenway Middle School Teacher Center in 1988.
<P>
In 1988, the Schenley Teacher Center was given the evaluation utilization award by the American Edu-cational Research Association.
<P>
Another major achievement during Wallace's tenure was the establishment of magnet programs, or specialty schools, which students choose to attend regardless of where they live in the city. The specialities range from high-tech to the arts.
<P>
One such magnet program is the International Studies Academy. It begins by teaching foreign languages in the first grade. A study showed that fifth graders involved in the program were just as fluent as high school students who had taken traditional language courses.
<P>
The school district received other accolades while Wallace was in charge. The Arts Propel program was named the best arts program in the world by Newsweek magazine in December 1991. Taylor Allderdice, the top academic high school, produced between 12 and 20 National Merit semifinalists each year.
<P>
Another program that Wallace receives credit for is the MAP (Monitoring Achievement in Pitts-burgh) program, which links basic skill instruction with a systematic testing program. The program is recognized for helping to raise the average student's achievement score on a standardized test from the national average to the mid-70th percentile.
<P>
<h2>ROBERT L.VANN</h2>

Robert L. Vann sensed the need for Blacks in Pittsburgh to have their own newspaper, so he founded the Pittsburgh Courier in 1910 with some help from associates. The intial press run was 500, with copies of the debut edition selling for 5 cents on a snowy Saturday morning. 
<P>
The paper quickly grew from a modest beginning to its eventual role as the voice for Pittsburgh's Black community. The newspaper became the platform from which Black leaders could speak out for equality.
<P>
Vann played a critical role, becoming the paper's publisher and editor in 1912 and guiding its growth. He combined an effective editorial policy with shrewd business sense. The Courier, under Vann's leadership, earned a reputation for honest reporting.  The Courier came into its own during World War I, leading the charge for complete integration of American life. 
<P>
But beyond Vann's abilities as a newspaper publisher, he also was an accomplished attorney. After attending Waters Normal Institute and Virginia Union University, Vann earned his law degree from the University of Pittsburgh.
<P>
Just as the Courier made rapid strides, so did Vann's other careers: law and politics.
<P>
Vann served as assistant city solicitor for Pittsburgh from 1917 through 1921. He also served as the national director of Negro publicity during the presidential campaigns of GOP candidates Warren Harding, Calvin Coolidge and Herbert Hoover.
<P>
Vann later felt Hoover had betrayed the African American community, so Vann switched political allegiances to the Democrats, taking with him the votes of many African Americans who looked to Vann for guidance.  Vann eventually was named special assistant to the attorney general of the United States. He later was named to President Franklin Roosevelt's Black Cabinet.
<P>
At the time cancer claimed Vann's life in 1940, the Courier was the most widely read Black newspaper in America, with circulation numbering in the hundreds of thousands. The newspaper's influence was felt across the country during World War II, driving for desegregation through the Courier's "Double V" campaign that called for victory at home and abroad. 
<P>
During a period of great difficulty for African Americans, Vann prospered and was a role model of success.
<P> 
<h2>JOHN E.CONNELLY</H2>
<H3>ACHIEVEMENT AWARD</H3>

For 21 years, Junior Achievement of Southwest Pennsylvania has presented its annual Achievement Award to a local corporation's chief executive. These executives are honored for their personal accomplishments and those of their companies -- people and institutions which have done the most for the free enterprise system. The award has traditionally been presented at Junior Achievement's annual meeting; two years ago, however, a new tradition began with the presentation of the award at the annual Business Hall of Fame Dinner. This year's dinner continues the tradition with the event scheduled for Oct. 25, 1995, at the Pittsburgh Hilton & Towers.
<P>
The 1994 Achievement Award winner is John E. Connelly, chairman and chief executive officer of J. Edward Connelly Associates Inc. Connelly served the public as treasurer of the Allegheny County Sanitary Authority, overseeing more than $100 million in public funds directed toward the new sewerage infrastructure and the consequent rehabilitation of our rivers.
<P>
It was in 1958 that he decided to launch his now-famous riverboat excursion service, which is one of the largest such fleets in the nation. His enterprises are now channeled through a dozen companies, including the Gateway Clipper fleet and the Sheraton Inn at Station Square.
<P>
Connelly is most famous for his marketing ventures, including his "Apples for the Students" campaign that helped equip schools with high- tech equipment so students would be prepared for the computer age.
<P>
JA's mission is to inspire and educate young people to value free enterprise. The 1995 Achievement Award winner and his predecessors are symbols of this mission. Past recipients of this award provide an honor roll of some of the top names in business in southwestern Pennsylvania. 
<P>
<H3>Past Achievement Award Winners</H3>
