<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<b><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2> COMPETING FOR CASH </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b><fill></FONT SIZE></b><br>
<B><i>By Richard Bierck</i></B>
<P>

<font size =+2><B><fill></B></font size> 
<h2>The Future of Our Colleges and Universities Depends on the Money They Raise Today</h2>
<P>
Duquesne University used to be a sleepy commuter school, for more than a century providing undergraduate degrees principally for western Pennsylvania residents. The wake- up call finally came in 1988, when the school named John E. Murray Jr. as its president. 
<P> 
Eight years later, enrollment is up, a 43 percent jump over the past six years. The school is adding 45 new majors and constructing a new science school. Other changes include an expanded student union and a new dormitory. 
<P>
 
"The attitude used to be, 'We'd better not try something because we can't afford it,' " says Murray, drawing on a cigarette in his office on the Bluff. "My view is that growth is essential. If we don't want to grow, we should just stay in bed." 
<P>
Instead, Murray is quite the early riser. His vision for the school required cash, so he has become a rainmaker extraordinaire. Despite a fund-raising environment wracked by corporate downsizing, Murray has amassed contributions to fill the Catholic university's coffers, fuel expansion, increase faculty salaries and add programs. 
<P> 
"I don't know how much longer he can keep it up," a Duquesne professor says of Murray's fund-raising prowess. "I just hope he can sustain it." 
<P>
For now, Murray is making it look easy. A former law school dean at the University of Pittsburgh and a nationally recognized expert on contract law, Murray capitalizes on  his connections to the corporate world. Some of those he solicits are former students who now hold positions of power in the corporate world. Others are people who know Murray because of his stature as a contracts expert. 
<P>
Murray slips into corporate boardrooms or executive suites, talks a little business and walks away with a million here, a million there. So much for the sleepy commuter school. 
<P> 
Experts say the ability to raise money is crucial for survival in higher education. 
<P>
"Money raised today is, in fact, a guarantee of the quality of the school's future," said Tim Seiler, director of operations for the fund-raising school at Indiana University's Center on Philanthropy in Indianapolis. 
<P>
Seiler, who teaches the art of rainmaking, says Murray's contacts in the corporate world are invaluable. But he also points to another advantage: Private schools like Duquesne, Seiler says, usually are smaller and have a loyal group of alumni, a definite benefit when it comes to fund raising.  "Alumni who feel that loyalty are more apt to give," Seiler says. 
<P>
Duquesne, in turn, can beef up programs, hire name faculty members, keep class sizes down and improve facilities, offering a more polished image to prospective students. The tangible, immediate results? One, an enrollment jump at Duquesne when other institutions are trying to stem enrollment declines. 
<P>
Pitt, Duquesne's state-funded neighbor that sits a few miles up Forbes Avenue, is one example. Pitt has seen enrollment decline at the same time that state legislators are becoming more stingy with funding dollars. What complicates matters, Seiler says, is that Pitt -- with branch campuses and sprawling graduate schools -- is the opposite of Duquesne. 
<P>
"Some institutions are so large that it is difficult for individuals to feel loyalty," Seiler says. "What complicates the problem at a school like Pitt is that state funding is staying flat or going down, so there is an increased need for fund raising. Often, alumni do not understand this predicament." 
<P>
Pitt administrators cite general fund-raising numbers that exceed totals of recent years, but trouble raising dollars for some specific goals, such as the establishment of an undergrad-uate business school. J. Dennis O'Connor, who joined the university as chancellor in 1991, resigned last spring after falling out of favor with some members of the university's board of trustees. 
<P>
Do Pitt's recent troubles warrant dire consequences for the university's ability to deliver qualified graduates in the immediate future? Hardly. The university has a firm foothold in the academic world, strengthened by a well-regarded undergraduate program and some outstanding graduate and professional schools. Its medical school, for example, has achieved widespread recognition. 
<P>
But if Pitt's current problems continue, particularly its fund-raising malaise, they might ultimately affect the quality and quantity of the graduates it delivers into the work force. 
<P>
<H2>Duquesne's Rising Star</H2> 
<P> 
In April, Duquesne officials stunned competitive counterparts when they announced numbers reflecting some meteoric fund raising. A $100 million drive for capital improvements, begun in 1993, had already brought in $52 million. By July, the total was $57.5 million. 
<P>
Duquesne plans to reach the $100 million mark by 1999, and Murray's confidence, are supported by the success of a drive launched in 1988, the same year Murray became president. The drive set out to raise $25 million, but in the end brought in $75 million. A lot of the money has come from corporate types, and Murray does not deflect the credit. "I'm comfortable with CEOs," he says. His growth of the school is reflected in the quality of student enrolling there, with SAT scores an average 48 points higher now than six years ago. 
<P>
Of course, the growth also is reflected by the number of buildings currently under construction on the uptown campus. One project is the 40,000 square-foot environmental research center. In planning the structure, the university solicited input from environmental scientists in both government and industry. As a result, Murray says, the center will have a practical orientation. "It's one thing to sit in an ivory tower and talk about the programs you're going to have. But we don't do it that way. We go to the people who do it for a living," Murray says. 
<P>
Another focus of fund raising has been the Bayer School of Natural and Environmental Science, which will support a new master's program. Construction began on the school's structure in January, and is expected to be completed this fall. Bayer's pledge: $2 million. 
<P> 
Other goals for the projected $100 million pool include $25 million to support 45 new academic programs, $15 million for scholarship endowments and $10 million to rehabilitate buildings. 
<P> 
<H2>Pitt's Battle </h2> 
By contrast, the development picture at Pitt is static.
<BR>
Lawrence Weber, vice-chancellor for institutional advancement, says general annual campaigns for voluntary support totaled $29 million in 1992, $33 million in 1993 and $32 million in 1994. The high-water mark was $38 million in 1991. In addition, he says, the university has $20 million in outstanding pledges. <P>But the university has fallen flat in its efforts to raise money for some key capital projects.
<P>
Among these is a proposed undergraduate business school, estimated to cost $30 million. Since fund raising for the school isn't progressing, Pitt is studying the idea of using an existing building to save up to $18 million. 
<P>
Pitt officials readily concede that efforts to raise the $30 million, which have yielded little more than $1 million in two years, are in the doldrums. Some faculty members at Pitt have openly questioned whether there is a need for the business school. 
<P>
Also on hold is fund raising for a sports and convocation center. "The state has funded $13 million for it," says Weber. "But we hope to get more. Penn State and Temple University each got $30 million [from the Common-wealth] for comparable structures. We still hope to raise another $20 million." 
<P>
Early last spring, a consultant hired by the university told Pitt administrators something they already knew all too well: The university wasn't ready to proceed with fund-raising drives for such capital projects. The consultant had based this assessment on a finding that there were differences between some trustees and the administration. 
<P>
It's now clear there were differences aplenty between some of the 36 members of the board of trustees and Chancellor O'Connor. One insider said that some of the trustees who had lost faith in O'Connor's leadership abilities were closely tied to big business -- the most likely source of contributions, particularly those that would go towards a business school. 
<P>
O'Connor came to Pitt, a quasi-public institution, from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, a state university, where he had been provost and vice chancellor for academic affairs. UNC-CH is lavishly funded by state legislators (many of whom are graduates of its law school), and the university has a highly productive private fund-raising machine that enjoys the advantage of linking alumni contributions to its nationally ranked athletic teams. 
<P>
As O'Connor's friction with trustees became public last spring, there ensued intimations that he had fallen short of the mark as a rainmaker. 
<P> 
Yet some suggest that trustees are every bit as responsible as the chancellor. <P> 
"My view is that fund raising is a joint activity between the president and key board members. Many of the trustees reflect corporate Pittsburgh, and this would open the doors to rainmaking activity. Needless to say, the board can also close the door," says Ron Cowell, a trustee and state representative from the 34th district in eastern Allegheny County. 
<P> 
Cowell, who wasn't on the board when O'Connor was hired, says the trustees apparently weren't "clear about their expectations" when they hired him. 
<P>
"I think the board has a responsibility to be clear in articulating the type of leadership that it wants; it should be part of the interviewing process," says Cowell. 
<P> 
O'Connor, who has been loath to make any statements concerning his depar-ture, couldn't be reached for comment.
<P>
<h2> The Other Players</h2>
As Pitt has made headlines for O'Connor's short stint and Duquesne, for bringing in cash, Pitt's Oakland neighbor, Carnegie Mellon University, has continued its national renown for having some of the best computer science and engineering programs, and perhaps the best robotics program. Some of the liberal arts graduate programs were ranked in the top 10 of a Newsweek magazine survey earlier this year. 
<P>
CMU isn't currently in a fund-   raising mode -- not publicly anyway. "We're in the early stages of a campaign that won't be announced for another year and a half or so," says Eric Johnson, vice president for development at the 7,000 student school. 
<P>
CMU's last major campaign raised $226 million in five years. Much of this money has gone for capital projects that include the $47 million university center and the $22 million Pernell Performing Arts Center, which will break ground next spring. Also resulting from the campaign were Roberts Engineering Hall, a $17 million home for materials research (including those for data storage) that still is under construction; the planned renovation of undergraduate chemistry labs, to cost $12 million; the Pittsburgh Technology Center, the recently finished $16 million industrial park on the Mon River, and Posner Hall, the graduate school of industrial administration, completed two years ago at a cost of $14 million. 
<P> 
Other local colleges are just gearing up, however. 
<P>
Chatham College is planning its first campaign since the late 1980s, when the college raised more than $10 million. More than $2 million in contributions that came in over the past year are helping the college rewire its campus for the information age, said Mary Kay Poppenberg, a Chatham vice president. Personal computers, including those in residence halls, will have data and voice links with the institution's mainframes. 
<P>
Annual giving at Carlow College has been increasing about 10 percent a year for the past three or four years, and totaled about $400,000 for the year that ended June 30, said the college's president, Sister Grace Ann Geibel. This fall, she says, Carlow will announce a capital campaign for renovations and "enhancing technology. We're now in the quiet solicitation phase." The college is seeking to offer increased computer capacity along with information management courses and more business-oriented writing courses to prepare students for financial careers. 
<P> 
La Roche College, too, is in the midst of a capital campaign. The school has raised more than $19.5 million since 1990, and hopes to reach its goal of $30 million by 1999, says Paul Stabile, vice president for college relations. La Roche has recently completed and opened two new buildings, a $1 million chapel and a $6.8 million fitness and sports center that has enabled the school to establish men's and women's basketball programs to attract more students. Goals include a new academic building estimated to cost $7.2 million. 
<P>
Robert Morris College is in the early stages of a development campaign. It garnered more than $1 million over the past year, says university spokesman Jeff Durosko. Goals for future fund raising include scholarships, new buildings and academic programs. New academic programs will place a stronger emphasis on oral and written communications. 
<P>
Point Park College's several-year drive has brought in $10 million, some of which will go to the college's library center. Planned for the vacant structure that formerly enclosed Bank Center Mall downtown, it will also house the Carnegie Library's downtown and business branches. Interior demolition began over the summer. 
<P> 
In higher education, fund raising today affects what facilities and programs an institution can offer in the future. In the end, it also will affect the number of students who enroll. It is a key to survival.

<HR>
<h2>What Do Employers Want From Future Graduates?</h2> 
Every employer seeks some basic qualities from the college graduates they interview for jobs: an ability to think conceptually, an intellectual reflex for organizing information and basic research skills to find answers quickly. 
<P>
But in today's intensively competitive workplace, there are some additional qualities that are being stressed, to some measure because of the degree to which they are found to be absent in the hordes of applicants. 

<P>
Chief among these is the ability to communicate clearly, succinctly and effectively, both orally and in writing.
<p>
Grant Wirth, a partner at the CPA firm of D.G. Sisterson & Co., believes that graduates could and should be emerging with better verbal skills than what he's seen in many recent applicants. 
<P>
"Communication is a skill that is not emphasized enough," he says. "And I'm not talking about just touchy-feely communication, but the ability to take complex information and dummy it down, make it simple without over-simplifying it. As the amount of information available grows at an exponential rate, I think people will be required more and more to communicate clearly and succinctly to understand narrow technical fields in order to manage them." vVerbal skills are also high on the list of Marc Herman, senior vice president of PNC Bank Corp., who runs the company's new Financial Services Center. Herman likes to say he needs people who can "smile over the phone," but in order for that smile to be recognized on the other end, and for it to produce a smile in the customer, Herman needs employees who can communicate clearly the things they know about PNC's services. 
<P>
"When people call a bank, they're not looking for a banker," Herman says. "They're looking for someone to help them. The employee needs to know banking, and to know how to handle the call in a way that is not intimidating, but knowledgeable and friendly." 
<P>
Richard DeYoung, a partner in the architectural firm of Williams Trebilcock Whitehead, says he, too, is looking for good communicators. "If we have ideas and can't convey them to partners and clients, what good are they?" says DeYoung, adding that he doesn't expect graduating seniors to communicate as effectively as architects who have been on the job a while. "When they come in to interview, some are in a shell, but when you get some of them talking, they're good." 
<P>
If applicants lack some basic written skills, they never get this chance, DeYoung adds. "The first thing they're rejected for is misspellings or resumes that are graphically displeasing." 
<BR>-- Richard Bierck
<HR><h2>CCAC's Kingsmore Sees Light at End of Budget Crunch</h2> 
Just like most other higher education institutions, some of the numbers facing the Community College of Allegheny County are frightening. 
<P>
Enrollment is down, a 6.1-percent drop last spring from the previous year. Additionally, a change in the way the state funds community colleges will cost CCAC about $4 million in funding next budget year. 
<P> 
But before any programs disappear or class sizes suddenly jump at CCAC's four campuses, CCAC President John M. Kingsmore is trying to manage the budget crunch by re-engineering the manner in which the college operates. That means a focus on having the four campuses operate as one college to eliminate redundant tasks that eat up the budget. Other cost-cutting measures include limiting hiring and offering early retirement to veteran employees. Kingsmore also has brought unions representing college employees into the fold with minimal salary increases until the college gets past its budget crunch.
<p>
In the end, Kingsmore hopes the college will avoid a bud get shortfall while maintaining academic integrity. <P>"We are trying to keep our class sizes relatively low," Kingsmore said. "We are keeping our focus on learning and on the students."
<p>
The average CCAC class size is around 25, a number that undoubtedly will jump if the college has to resort to cutting instructional staff. 
<P>
Kingsmore said this school year is a key for CCAC because of the change that is forthcoming. 
<P>
"I am optimistic," Kingsmore says, "but I don't want to downplay the challenge in front of us." 
<P>
CCAC is the state's fourth largest higher education institution, with full-time enrollment of about 22,000 students. Its strongest selling point is its cost in comparison to four-year institutions. Tuition for this school year is $64 per credit, costing a full-time student less than $2,000 per year for credits that is most cases will transfer to the four-year institutions in the region. Students can finish their degrees at a four-year school after completing two years at CCAC. 
<BR> --- Jim Urban<P>
<hr>
