<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Governer Tom Ridge </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<b><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2> GOVERNER TOM RIDGE</FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b><fill></FONT SIZE></b><br>

<P>

<font size =+2><B><fill></B></font size> 
When Gov. Tom Ridge took office in January, many business leaders in Pennsylvania felt new hope that this state would become a more friendly place to do business. In their words, that meant lower business taxes, less regulation and workers' compensation reform, just to name a few items on their wish list.<BR>During the campaign against Democrat Mark Singel, Ridge himself was critical of the business atmosphere in Pennsylvania. A common image in the campaign was a widely played Ridge television commercial in which he stood in a town square espousing the state's pathetic rate of new business starts. 
<P> 
Now, Ridge has been through his first go-round with the state Legislature and has been gearing up for the Legis-lature's return to Harrisburg this fall. <P>While in Pittsburgh this summer, Ridge reflected on his early months in office and what the future holds. 
<P>
<B>ER: Some say your early months have been a huge success. Others aren't as complimentary. What's your appraisal? 
<P>
Ridge:</B> When I ran for this job, I said there were several things we    needed to do in order to change Pennsylvania. We had to make Pennsylvania a job-friendly state. We had to do more to make Pennsylvania competitive. We had to do more to make Pennsylvania's streets safer. We had to do more to change the relationship between government and the  people it serves. 
<P>
We set a very aggressive agenda, I think, to change Pennsylvania. In the first six months, we kept many of those promises we made during the campaign.  We promised we would have a disciplined, focused budget that cut taxes, produced savings for future years and identified priorities with increased funding consistent with Pennsylvania's needs. We did just that. 
<P> 
We cut taxes. We moved an unprecedented amount over to the rainy day fund, and we increased funding for public education and public funding. Promises made. Promises kept. 
<P>
We talked about holding a special session on crime. It was pretty clear the concerns Pennsylvanians had about crime in their streets, neighborhoods and schools. It was a large part of the campaign. We said we would have a special session. Within several days of my swearing-in, we called the Legislature back in. With considerable help from both sides of the aisle, I think we not only got an unprecedented amount of crime-fighting legislation, but finally some legislation that brings long overdue, fundamental changes to the justice system, with a special emphasis on the juvenile justice system, victims' rights and other related matters. In the long term, these measures will prove to be valuable aids to the law enforcement community and will go a long way to improving our ability to fight crime. 
<P> 
<B>ER: There are issues intimately essential to business -- taxes, workers' compensation to name two. What inroads have you made? 
<P>
Ridge:</B> We talked a lot during the campaign about economic development ... about making Pennsylvania job-friendly. For too long, we've had this outward migration of Pennsyl-vania's jobs and Pennsylvania's businesses to other states. What we need to do is understand that we are in competition with other states and that competition is serious. That competition is even more fierce if you look at the competition of the global marketplace. What we need to do in Pennsylvania is peel off some of these layers of government that I think have disadvantaged our workers and our employers. To that end, we accelerated the reduction of the corporate net income tax, we elevated the level of deductions you can take -- losses from one year and carrying them over to the next. We've begun to change the regulatory environment. We put together a Keystone Export Task Force comprised of Pennsylvanians that will help me design a strategy to promote Pennsylvania's goods offshore. 
<P>
We certainly need to sell our goods in the other 49 states, but I think there are other huge markets out there internationally. We must have a strategy to promote exports. We must have a mind-set that says export, export, export. There are billions of potential consumers out there for the widest possible range of products. We have world class workers who produce world class products in Pennsylvania. I think we ought to stamp them 'Made in Pennsylvania' and get them out the door. 
<P>
Another issue critically important to our competitiveness is workers' compensation reform. This is not a special interest issue. It is not a labor vs. management issue. Clearly, we need workers' compensation to help people who get hurt on the job. But again, as we look to the burden on our businesses in a fiercely, fiercely competitive marketplace, we are disadvantaged in this state and we need to bring some changes to the workers' compensation system as well. 
<P>
<B>ER: Exporting is definitely important, but it tends to lead to gradual economic growth, something that might not produce headlines. Will the voters in Homestead and other small communities even notice if your strategy works? 
<P> 
Ridge:</B> I hope so. They will start noticing right away in some of our urban communities. One of the other initiatives we have involves reuse of old industrial sites. There is no better example of a community that needs that kind of initiative than Allegheny County. We have a strong tradition of steelmaking and manufacturing, but we've been looking at these vacated facilities for a long time. 
<P>
As far as exporting is concerned, the long-term implications for Penn-sylvania's workers probably won't be as visible. But I will tell you it is my firm belief that if you reduce those job-crushing corporate taxes, get the regulatory environment under control, make workers' compensation rates more competitive and you promote exports, it will bring a stability to our communities and businesses that we have not seen, and then you build on that stability. I would like to think that in a couple years, once we get everything in place, that Pennsylvania businesses that have been inclined for a variety of reasons to expand outside Pennsylvania, will stay and expand in Pennsylvania. 
<P>
What will the voters notice? The most immediate and visible reflection of the change will occur in the next couple years as we target some of these abandoned industrial sites, clean them up and give incentives to get people back to these sites and get people back to work. 
<P> 
<B>ER: What about small business? What are you doing to help the small businesses? 
<P>
Ridge:</B> The first step in that direction was changing from $500,000 to   $1 million the amount of net operating loss permitted to be carried forward. That helps the small business, the entrepreneur. The focus on exports will really benefit those small- to medium-sized businesses that have never exported before or are increasing exports. Part of that focus is trying to work within the financial community to develop different kinds of financing instruments. Financing is a huge obstacle to any kind of exporting today. 
<P>
Small businesses also are the ones crying out for workers' compensation reform. We want to begin addressing that agenda this fall. Whether we get it accomplished or not remains to be seen, but we are going to put it out there for discussion. 
<P>
<B>ER: You revamped what was the Department of Environmental Re-sources, an agency many businesses loathed in this state. What will the new regulatory environment be like? 
<P>
Ridge:</B> The Department of Environmental Resources was a job-crushing, community-harassing, regulatory nightmare. The notion we desire is that government should treat citizens it is designed to serve in a manner that is fair, responsible and reasonable, reaching out to them and helping them comply with the law. It is a notion that government should be a partner in protecting the environment, rather than a police force that is sitting back and waiting for someone to make a mistake and then pouncing on them from a punitive point of view. 
<P>
Most citizens I know want to be good stewards of the environment. Treat them accordingly until they show you something different. If you show them what the law is, show them how to comply with the law, and then they willfully ignore it or disobey it, then your response has to be swift and uncompromising. But absent that, we wanted to go from a policing and punitive mentality to more of a collaborative and compliance-based mentality. We've changed the DER. It is now the Department of Environmental Protection. We've created a new department to take care of our parks and forests. Clearly Pennsylvania's parks and forests compose one of the finest and largest such systems in the country. This system needs special attention, a place at the cabinet table before the appropriate legislative committees. Thus, we now have the Department of Conservation and Natural Resources. 
<P>
<B>ER: You also tackled education, an issue of interest to business leaders since business needs a qualified work force in the future. Why did you move ahead with your school choice initiative so early in your administration when you knew success was questionable? 
<P>
Ridge:</B> I raised the level of public debate on education by submitting early on the education reform package. Some people questioned the timing, but I will tell you there was never going to be an easy time to promote fundamental reform in a system that has operated pretty much the same way for 15 to 20 years. The education establishment predictably, and I'm not saying this critically, would resist fundamental reform at any time during the Ridge administration. I felt it was important just to raise the issue early in my administration and let people know I am committed to education reform. 
<P>
<B>ER: What should we expect when you take another run at the Legislature this fall with the education reform package? 
<P>Ridge:</B> I have some basic preconditions that I think are integral to the education reform package and must be preserved. I'm sure there also will be some recommendations I may want to graft on to that package. I think we need an education opportunity grant program. You need to create that kind of choice. 
<P>
Education, in my judgment, has been a priority ignored for too long in Pennsylvania. Clearly, we need to challenge and change the system so there is much greater accountability and better delivery of educational services. The consumers of the educational product are the children. I don't think that product is consistent with what the children's parents are paying for. We have an extremely high per capita expenditure on public education in Pennsylvania. There are good schools and good teachers and these good schools and good teachers have little to worry about in the education reform package. In fact, some of the innovations would be attractive to them. We raised the issue and it is not going away. Even if we get this fundamental package of reform passed, there will be other things we want to do down the road. 
<P>
<B>ER: Do you think you can maintain the level of success you have had with the Legislature? 
<P>
Ridge:</B> There is an energy level, a commitment to change Pennsylvania that has just continued to accelerate. I hope we can maintain that energy, maintain that commitment over the next couple of years. Pennsylvanians need it and deserve it. We've got great people and enormous potential in this state that will only be realized when we change the relationship between government and the people it serves.
<P>
